<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-ATLANTA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON TAMES AMS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, Ga. _ With every lap he makes at Atlanta Motor
Speedway, Jeff Gordon is coming to grips with what has become
NASCAR's fastest non-restricted racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon won the 1998 season-ending NAPA 500 on the reconfigured
and repaved 1.54-mile quadoval last November, under conditions
similar to yesterday's dreary and winter-like weather. Gordon
bagged his second victory in four starts this season in the Cracker
Barrel 500 here, out-pitting and then out-running Bobby Labonte and
Mark Martin on a racetrack that finally has begun to develop a
two-groove personality.
</P>
<P>
   AMS earned its lightning-fast reputation during the first event
run after completion of its redesign and repaving in November 1997.
When Geoffrey Bodine ripped off a qualifying lap at 197.957 mph on
Nov. 15 of that year, AMS became the fastest NASCAR track run
without a carburetor restrictor plate.
</P>
<P>
   It also is a track where every brush with a concrete wall sticks
to your ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a track where you have to drive into the corner
without getting all the way out of the gas,'' said Gordon, the
reigning and three-time Cup champion. ``When you get out of the
gas, it unloads the car and makes it loose. That's a hard thing to
do _ your general reaction is to get out of the throttle. I had to
work on some combinations to make me feel more comfortable here.
Because \Rcrew chief\S Ray Evernham was doing everything he could
to make the entry into the corner more comfortable for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally kind of realized it's not the car, it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   Confident his car would stick in the outside lane at race speeds
over 187 mph, Gordon rallied in the last third of the event to
overhaul pole-sitter Labonte and outlast him to the finish line by
2.537 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   And in what has become an Evernham-inspired trademark, Gordon
set up his run to the checkered flag with an 8.2-second pit stop
for right side tires only and fuel on lap 297 under green flag
conditions. When that cycle of pit stops was completed, Gordon had
gotten around Labonte and reassumed the lead on lap 311 of the 325
scheduled en route to his 44th career Cup victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really committed to the bottom \Rof the track\S all day
long,'' said Gordon, driver of the No. 24 DuPont Automotive
Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``But I was just wearing the right
front \Rtire\S out and getting loose and wearing the right rear
out. I saw some other guys that were using the outside lane, and
that was the only way you could make that car last on the long
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little hairy up there a couple of times, but it
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   So well that Gordon led four times for a race-high 109 laps, or
six more than Labonte, who was followed to the line by the Ford
Tauruses of Martin, Jeff Burton and Dale Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Labonte drove a great race,'' said Gordon, one of 10
drivers involved in 25 lead changes before an estimated 85,000
chilled fans. ``He got up there in front of me that last time after
that pit stop \RGordon finally passed Labonte on Lap 304\S, and I
thought we were in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, the defending race champion, said he might have had
more for Gordon if he could have taken on four tires during his
last stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two tires didn't work for me,'' said Labonte, driver of the
No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac Grand Prix. ``I'm not very good
at that anyway. My car was too tight on two tires and I couldn't
get the right line that I needed. I can't ever make two tires work.
I just didn't run the right line for a few laps, and Jeff made up a
lot of time.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
