<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-NIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORNHUSKERS' CENTER HOPING TO STOP NAILON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A snippet on ``SportsCenter'', a couple of
seconds from a game; until four days ago, Venson Hamilton's
impression of Lee Nailon had been formed in such moments.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Hamilton has seen Nailon performing many dastardly
deeds, like banging inside for a layup and seconds later banging
down a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really is a great player,'' Hamilton said. ``He's going to
be a Top 15 pick in the draft. He's strong inside and physical and
yet he'll go outside on you, too. He just has that never-quit,
keep-fighting mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton gets an up-close-and-personal look at Nailon when TCU
(20-10) plays Nebraska (20-12) at 7 tonight in the second round of
the National Invitation Tournament at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   And Nailon gets his first look at Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen him play before,'' Nailon said. ``My
impressions? He's the Big 12 player of the year. That's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The paint will be their stage. The battle will be between
styles.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is the banger, the in-your-face physical presence in
the lane. He says so himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hard worker so I get a lot of rebounds,'' Hamilton said.
``That's how I make my points.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not embarrassed, either. The way he figures it garbage
points are still points.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton averages 15.6 of them a game and almost as many
rebounds (10.2).
</P>
<P>
   ``Rebounding is a key,'' Horned Frogs coach Billy Tubbs said.
``They are an excellent rebounding team. We have to stay on the
boards with Hamilton. We can't let him get going.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be Nailon's job. It is not his only role, though.
</P>
<P>
   Nailon is the riddle, the sometime-banger inside, the
sometime-finesse player. The question is on a given night which
version of Nailon the other team will see.
</P>
<P>
   On nights when he's both, like in TCU's first-round victory
against Kansas State, he's tough to handle. He had 22 points,
including 2 for 2 on 3-pointers, and eight rebounds against the
Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``All year I've been saying I can play outside,'' Nailon said.
``It's an advantage over a lot of guys who guard me because not a
lot of guys can go outside with me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an advantage against Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not my game,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   When Nailon takes his game outside, the Cornhuskers likely will
switch. The chances for mismatches increases with every switch.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton realizes, though, that sooner or later Nailon will
venture back in and the dance will begin again.
</P>
<P>
   It's a match both players look forward to. Nailon has a chance
to prove himself against the Big 12 Player of the Year. Hamilton
has chance to prove himself against a top 15 NBA draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs was quick to say that the game wouldn't be decided by
Hamilton and Nailon. ``It's TCU versus Nebraska last time I
checked,'' Tubbs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably be pretty good,'' Cornhuskers coach Danny Nee
said. ``I mean, you are talking about two very, very good
players.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
