<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-XAVIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN BEATS XAVIER BY SCORING THE LAST 8 POINTS OF THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Trailing by 6 points with 2 minutes 17 seconds
remaining Sunday night, Connecticut rallied to score the last 8
points and outlast eighth-seeded Xavier, 86-84, to advance to the
Round of 16 of the Mideast Regional of the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Two free throws by the freshman forward Tamika Williams with 7.1
seconds left enabled the top-seeded Huskies to prevail after they
had trailed by as many as 10 points in the second half, keeping a
capacity crowd of 10,027 at sold-out Gampel Pavilion on the edge of
their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Williams got her opportunity to win the game after Nikki Kremer,
the outstanding Xavier guard, who had made eight consecutive free
throws and scored a game-high 23 points, missed two foul shots with
38 seconds to go and the score tied at 84-84.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut will meet the winner of Sunday's game between Oregon
and Iowa State in Cincinnati next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Xavier (24-9) pulled ahead by 10 less than four minutes into the
second half on a one-hander by Taru Tuukkanen, a 6-foot-3 sophomore
from Finland, after UConn had drawn within 2.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies (29-4), led by Shea Ralph and Svetlana
Abrosimova, kept chipping away at Xavier and pulled within 3 points
on a drive by Abrosimova. But, as happened so often during this
fast-paced and well-played game, Nicole Levandusky, the Musketeers'
leading scorer, nailed her team's ninth 3-pointer and Katie Griggs
drove the lane to make it 68-60 with 11 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was UConn's turn to shine on defense, with a 12-2 spurt
that tied it at 72-72 on Williams' second straight power goal
underneath with 7:07 left.
</P>
<P>
   But Xavier would not go away, pulling ahead by 80-76 on a
Griggs' 3-pointer, before Jones scored her fifth basket of the half
on a power drive to the hoop to bring the Huskies within 80-78 with
4:45 left.
</P>
<P>
   A jumper by Griggs as the shot clock was winding down increased
that lead to 82-78, after which Kim Hotz got free underneath for a
layup to widen the Musketeers' lead to 6 before Williams scored on
a drive to cut it to 84-80 with 2 minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But then two crucial errors by Xavier _ a pass that went out of
bounds and a backcourt violation _ enabled Connecticut to tie it at
84-84 on another drive by Jones and a layup by Abrosimova.
</P>
<P>
   After Kremer missed her foul shots and Williams made hers,
Xavier had one final attempt. With time running out, Kremer got off
a desperate off-balance 20-footer just before the buzzer. It was
not even close and the Huskies formed a jubilant pile on the court.
</P>
<P>
   That Williams should score the points that lifted the Huskies to
a comeback triumph was only fitting, since she led UConn with 19
points and 9 rebounds and scored 4 of the Huskies' final 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies weren't able to pull away from the Musketeers during
a see-saw first half.
</P>
<P>
   After the senior captain Amy Duran had given Connecticut a 20-17
lead with her second 3-pointer of the first half, Kremer tied it
with her first of three from 3-point range. With UConn turning the
ball over repeatedly _ 14 times in the half _ the Musketeers went
on a 13-4 run to take a 33-24 lead with 6 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Stymied by Xavier's tenacious defensive play, particularly in
the lane, Connecticut went without a basket for six minutes until
the freshman Swin Cash sank a layup with 2:15 remaining after the
visitors had widened their lead to 38-28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
