<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CABBIE GIVES GONZAGA A LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-GONZAGA-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There is a cab driver in Seattle the Gonzaga Bulldogs
would like to thank _ and perhaps kiss, say, 16 times.
</P>
<P>
   The cabbie unknowingly put some lemon juice on the West Coast
Conference champions' Sweet 16 dream.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Bulldogs needed added incentive going into their
second-round NCAA tournament game against nationally ranked
Stanford at KeyArena, but minutes into his cab ride from the Hilton
Hotel to a restaurant Friday night, coach Dan Monson had some ammo
for his pregame talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told us he asked the cab driver about the NCAA
tournament and how it was going,'' Gonzaga forward Casey Calvary
said, ``and (the cabbie) told him the only reason Gonzaga beat
Minnesota was because (the Gophers) had four players suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cab driver didn't know it was our coach in the back
seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson said Sunday the cab driver also said Gonzaga ``will get
killed (Saturday) by Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the kids nobody believed they belonged, and this was
their chance to prove it,'' Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga took a back seat to no one during its rewarding trek
across the Cascades, winding up with a date in the desert. Unsung
but not unheralded by those who have watched them play, the
Bulldogs advanced to the West Region semifinals in Phoenix with an
82-74 victory over the Pacific-10 champion Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   Next up is a Thursday night game at America West Arena against
Florida, which defeated Weber State, 82-74, in overtime Saturday,
capping a sub-regional that drew far more attention than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA didn't assign a No. 1 seed to the Seattle sub-regional,
but some of the best first- and second-round games in the
tournament were played at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   The only tournament scandal _ so far _ was here, too.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours after arriving from Minneapolis, the Big Ten Gophers
were in big trouble. The St. Paul Pioneer Press reported Wednesday
that a former university employee had admitted taking tests and
doing course work for as many as 20 basketball players, including
four _ two starters _ on this Gopher team.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga sent the Gophers home with a season-ending 75-63 loss.
</P>
<P>
   But some, including a certain cab driver, weren't convinced the
Bulldogs could beat Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   No one can say Gonzaga won because the other team didn't have
all of its players. Gonzaga won because of depth and determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to take anything away from Stanford because they
are a great group of guys,'' junior guard Matt Santangelo said,
``but we wanted it more. Desire is what got us this win.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that Santangelo scored a team-high 22 points and
received double-figure scoring help from three teammates _ Richie
Frahm (15), Quentin Hall (14) and Calvary (10).
</P>
<P>
   ``We go 10 deep,'' starting center Jeremy Eaton said. ``Our subs
come in and contribute as much as the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   When Eaton and Calvary got into early foul trouble against the
taller, bulkier Cardinal front line, backups Mark Spink and Axel
Dench came in and pulled down nine rebounds in 31 combined minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga had a surprising 45-33 rebounding edge, just two days
after Stanford hammered Alcorn State on the boards (45-23).
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just a very physical team,'' said Tim Young,
Stanford's 7-foot-2 center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a dream,'' said Spink, a sophomore from
Bellingham. ``You better pinch me because I don't want to wake
up.''
</P>
<P>
   This sub-regional opened eyes all across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest March Madness upset ended Thursday night's
first-round marathon at KeyArena. Harold ``The Show'' Arceneaux
looked like the next coming of M.J. as he scored 36 points in Weber
State's shocking 76-74 win over North Carolina, which hadn't
experienced a one-game-and-out NCAA tournament in nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, the top seed (No. 2), returned all five of its
starters from last season's Final Four team and figured to last at
least until they played No. 1-seed Connecticut in Phoenix in the
West Region finals. But Alcorn State put some doubt in the Cardinal
minds during a closer-than-expected first-round game Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga took it from there.
</P>
<P>
   And so did Florida, though much more quietly, as the SEC Gators
made sure that there was only one glass slipper available for two
Cinderella teams _ Gonzaga and Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Saturday's crowd (15,187) was emotionally drained after
the Gonzaga-Stanford game and did more watching than cheering
during the other quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   Florida finally figured out a way to contain Arceneaux and
squeeked out a win that put it in the Sweet 16 for the first time
since 1994's Final Four Gator team.
</P>
<P>
   Arceneaux, who scored 36 points against North Carolina, had 21
at halftime against Florida and finished with 32 on 12-of-27
shooting in 43 minutes. But he, like the other Wildcats, looked
tired in the OT session.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying and he got tired,'' said Ron Abegglen, coaching
his final game at Weber State. ``But a tired Harold is still a
pretty good player.''
</P>
<P>
   The best in this sub-regional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever nicknamed him `The Show' did him a great disservice
because he's a lot more than that,'' said Gator guard Teddy Dupay,
whose 3-pointer with two minutes remaining in overtime gave Florida
a six-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Show'' and the rest have departed and the NCAA tournament
won't be back for at least five more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have it back,'' said Brian Trent, the tourmanent
manager. ``The little schools played great, the last game went into
overtime and the sun even peeked out a few times. I thought it went
great.''
</P>
<P>
   And one more thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ever find out who that cab driver is, let us now,''
Calvary said. ``We'll invite him to Spokane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0342 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      03-15 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEFT-HANDER ZIMMERMAN HAS A SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ Jordan Zimmerman isn't sure how he came to love
baseball. Some years, he said, his hometown is covered in snow
until June.
</P>
<P>
   All he knows is his passion for the game was so deep he uprooted
himself at age 16 and moved to another country. Otherwise, there's
no way Zimmerman would be where he is now, with an outside chance
of becoming the latest left-handed Mariner reliever from Kelowna,
B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The last one, Paul Spoljaric, was traded this winter, leaving
the M's without an established lefty in the bullpen. The
23-year-old Zimmerman is making his case for the job, and the
Mariners like what they've seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zimmerman has made us sit up and take notice,'' said pitching
coach Stan Williams. ``His slider needs a little work, but
everything else looks good. Good velocity, no fear and he locates
the ball well. Those are all indications he's going to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman pitched a scoreless seventh inning in the Mariners'
8-7 win over the Chicago Cubs Sunday. The M's ideally would like a
more experienced lefty for the bullpen, but Zimmerman will survive
the next round of cuts on Wednesday and manager Lou Piniella said
Zimmerman has an ``outside chance'' of making the club.
</P>
<P>
   That puts Zimmerman in a similar situation as his brother, Jeff,
a 26-year-old right-hander bidding to make the Texas Rangers'
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Jeff have talked frequently this spring, and always
have been close. They spent three years together on the Canadian
junior national team, and when Jeff went to college at Texas
Christian, Jordan moved to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, a 32nd-round junior-college draft pick by the
Mariners in 1995, saw his career nearly end before it began. He
missed his first two professional seasons recovering from back
surgery, and has pitched in just 842/3 innings the past two years
with shoulder problems.
</P>
<P>
   But participating in the instructional league and Arizona Fall
League (where he played on Jeff's team) has Zimmerman ``feeling
like a brand-new person.'' He throws 90 mph with good life at the
end of his pitches, and the health problems have imparted him a
degree of toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm a lot more mentally strong than I should be for my
age, just because of everything I went through,'' Zimmerman said.
``When you have two pretty serious injuries at a young age, you
learn to deal with things and gain a lot of perspective compared to
other people. You realize there's no point in being scared.''
</P>
<P>
   That perspective is evident when Zimmerman speaks of his goals
for 1999. He's pitching in major league exhibition games, but
Zimmerman doesn't have Seattle on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I make the team, great, but I've never even pitched
double-A before and I'm not going to be upset if they send me there
or even lower,'' he said. ``I just want to have a full season,
health-wise. That's all I'm looking forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Right-hander Bill Swift will pitch two innings Wednesday
against Oakland after a successful bullpen session Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Back stiffness has kept Swift from pitching since a two-inning
outing March 7, and Sunday was an important test for the non-roster
veteran, who is vying for a spot in the Mariners' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was hurt, I'd probably be done,'' said Swift, 37.
</P>
<P>
   Swift wore a brace for his back and might need it during games,
but he said it didn't affect him Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   -- Jay Buhner started in left field again Sunday, but he's
headed for his preferred pasture. Buhner will debut in right field
Monday, four days earlier than planned.
</P>
<P>
   But an unconvinced Buhner said, ``I'll believe it when I see it.
I was supposed to play there (Friday), and that got banged. I know
I'll be there Opening Day, put it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Left-hander Butch Henry, who had been scheduled to follow Ken
Cloude Sunday, started instead for the first time this spring.
Henry, who can release himself from his contract if he does not
make the starting rotation, made it clear last week he will not
pitch in relief for the M's and was upset he had yet to make a
spring start.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, he was upset mainly with himself. After allowing a
mammoth three-run homer to Henry Rodriguez in the second inning,
Henry got into another jam by throwing seven straight balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know better than that,'' said Henry, who pitched in only two
games last year before season-ending knee surgery.
``(Concentration) is a very, very big part of my game, because I'm
not overpowering and I do give up hits. It's going to take time for
me to get back in that swing of things to where I'm mentally
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry escaped the second without further damage and pitched a
1-2-3 third.
</P>
<P>
   -- Williams worked in the bullpen Sunday with right-hander Mac
Suzuki, who has allowed six runs on five walks in three innings.
Williams squatted behind the pitcher and extended his arm so it was
even with the back of Suzuki's knee. When Suzuki brought his arm
back, he would try to graze the ball against Williams' open palm in
an effort to make his mechanics more consistent.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have little time to spare with Suzuki, who is out
of options and must clear waivers if the team tries to send him to
the minors. The 23-year-old has the confidence of his pitching
coach. ``I don't worry about Mac,'' Williams said. ``He's going to
be fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0010 </DOCNO>
