<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0345 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-15 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
ZAGS NOT JUST PRIDE OF SPOKANE ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As day dawned Sunday, having slept the sweet sleep of
Big Dance victors, the Gonzaga Bulldogs woke in their Seattle hotel
rooms, getting ready for their flight over the Cascades, across the
desert-like plains of Eastern Washington and back home to Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   You know, Spokane is totally cool.
</P>
<P>
   A river runs through it.
</P>
<P>
   And right in the heart of the city, someone had the smarts to
build a great park, complete with a carousel and a roller-blade
path and benches and grass that people are allowed to sit on.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the park, a giant waterfall crashes down,
giving you a glimpse of nature's power and the way people harnessed
it to make electricity and allow a little city like Spokane to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   In Spokane, there is even a hip little coffee bar where, unlike
Seattle, a double-tall Americano and a scone costs less than one
share of Microsoft or Amazon.com stock.
</P>
<P>
   Spokane is the kind of place where you can walk through town and
think, or ride your bike out into the countryside along gentle
rolling hills, out into the wheat fields.
</P>
<P>
   And right across one of the quaint walking bridges, about
half-mile from the middle of the city, sits the pleasant campus of
Gonzaga, with neat, brick buildings that are in complete keeping
with the image this highly reputable Jesuit college has earned over
the years _ even before John Stockton, who was smart enough to grow
up in Spokane and dream of playing for the Bulldogs, even when no
other kid's dreams tended to include Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   You know, all said, the Zags have had it pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   The world may think of it as John Stockton U., but there is more
to it than that _ not that Gonzaga players mind that kind of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not kid ourselves,'' Gonzaga guard Matt Santangelo said.
``We've created an identity, but he's the best there is.''
</P>
<P>
   With two NCAA wins, in one swift, dramatic, sweet weekend, it
probably just got a whole lot better for Gonzaga. Santangelo is
right. They have created their own identity.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, or maybe appropriately, the greatest basketball victory
in Gonzaga history took place 300 miles from home.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after beating Minnesota in a first-round game in the
1999 NCAA tournament, Gonzaga slapped mighty Stanford from the
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, or maybe appropriately, Gonzaga's big wins came in
Seattle, the kind of place that could give a place like Gonzaga and
Spokane a complex _ although that would be ridiculously wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there is the big city/little city contrast. There is
also the big conference/little conference juxtaposition. The
Bulldogs are the West Coast Conference champs. The Cardinal were
the brutes of the Pac-10. David and Goliath was the theme imposed
on the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   But that David/Goliath thing was wrong. It continues to be
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who saw the damage Gonzaga did to the University of
Washington and Washington State this season, you know this is no
fluke.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars fell first, losing 70-61 in November. Then came the
Huskies, who started the season ranked No. 14 in the polls but who
were headed for a swift, steady fall just as the Zags lit up their
cross-state rivals. Gonzaga beat the Huskies 82-71 and then
proceeded to romp to a 25-6 record and the WCC championship.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, the Zags have been and continue to be too legit to
label ``Cinderella'' or ``underdog,'' even if the national sporting
media _ and even some of the more hoity-toity newspapers in the
``big city'' of Seattle _ can't help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a Cinderella story. We didn't just spring up and
have a good season,'' Gonzaga coach Dan Monson said again Saturday,
minutes after the Zags had beaten Stanford at its own game.
</P>
<P>
   Monson's sentiments were echoed by Stanford coach Mike
Montgomery, who expressed displeasure that Minnesota, hit with a
scandal of alleged academic fraud, did not beat Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery said he knew Gonzaga was the tougher matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, was he right.
</P>
<P>
   And, boy, would it be wrong for anyone to continue to call these
Bulldogs underdogs any more. That became especially true after the
revered Pac-10 was left without a single Sweet 16 entry. That
became especially true in the big city of Seattle, where the
Huskies were all but embarrassed by a great player from Miami of
Ohio whose name they should be able to spell now.
</P>
<P>
   The boys from Gonzaga are headed to Phoenix for the next round,
where Florida might not be able to wear down these Bulldogs, who
are now the pride of not only Spokane, but beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Off we send them, to the Sweet 16, to fulfill our hoop dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs are more fun than a barrel of Todd MacCullochs.
</P>
<P>
   The great state of Washington, the entire Pacific Northwest,
even all western states' fans who usually side with Pac-10 schools
from Seattle to Tucson, we have new 'Dogs to fawn over.
</P>
<P>
   No underdogs. No Cinderellas. No Pac-10 little brothers. No John
Stockton U.
</P>
<P>
   Just the Gonzaga Bulldogs out of Spokane. That will do just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
