<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUG-SWALLOWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN INGESTED 92 BAGS OF HEROIN, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 44-year-old man who fainted and went into
convulsions at La Guardia Airport early Sunday had 92 thumb-size
packets of heroin in his digestive tract, the Port Authority of New
York and New Jersey said.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Arcadio Yepes of Jackson Heights, Queens, was in
critical condition Sunday night at Elmhurst Hospital Center and has
been charged with possession of more than four ounces of the drug,
the police said. He was stricken shortly after arriving on a flight
from Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Edward Silhan of the Port Authority police said that in his
22 years on the force dealing with drug couriers who swallow
packets, he had never heard of a smuggler who had ingested so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see two dozen, three dozen sometimes, but I was totally
amazed at what this guy had,'' Silhan said. ``He must have been
filled from top to bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Yepes had paid cash for a one-way ticket from Medellin,
Colombia, to Miami, where he cleared customs, then caught a
connecting flight to New York, Silhan said. The packets were sealed
with wax, but one of them burst inside his stomach, poisoning him,
the lieutenant said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say that drug-swallowers are an important link
in the Colombia-New York heroin trade and that they are typically
paid about $1,000 per flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
