<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0348 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SUNS-HNS &LR;      03-15 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SUNS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PHOENIX _ Joe Kleine turned to find Charles Barkley. Barkley
doubled back to Kleine. And when the friends met at midcourt,
falling into a tight embrace, Kleine offered a large body to hold
the exhausted Barkley up, an approximation of the defense with
which he had shut him down.
<TEXT>
<P>
   All that was missing from this fitting postgame scene was
Rockets forward Scottie Pippen, perhaps as dejected and frustrated
as he has been in his career. By then, he needed a hug most.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rockets hit a wall _ Kleine served as a fitting symbol
of that, too _ the Suns flew past them for a 104-90 win Sunday
night at America West Arena, breaking the Rockets' three-game
winning streak and Phoenix's four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley credited his friend for his physical and exhausting
defensive effort, and Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich cited the
realities of back-to-back games. But Pippen said the problem runs
deeper _ so much deeper that he said he doesn't know why the
Rockets signed him as a celebrated, cover-boy free agent less than
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty frustrated,'' Pippen said. ``Playing the minutes
I'm playing (40.6 per game, fourth in the NBA), I'm not involved in
the offense. It makes the game not any fun anymore. My next step is
to find why this organization wanted me. I want to sit down and
ask, `What's my position on this ballclub?' If it's just from the
defensive standpoint, if that's the point, then I can feel much
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen said he does not regret his decision to sign with the
Rockets, only that it has come time to adjust the offense to
include him and other perimeter players to a greater extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get everybody involved,'' Pippen said. ``We have to
make the game for everybody. There's nights when things are not
going right. It's time to go to somebody else or try to get
somebody else involved. There needs to be some kind of system where
we all make the defense stay honest. Everybody is looking up and
figuring out how to play us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games like tonight make the game very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen took just five shots Sunday, making two. He finished with
four points, four assists and four rebounds in 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple games, I'm not involved in the offensive
system,'' Pippen said. ``We have to try to get other guys in the
offense. Teams are starting to play what we're doing and having
success with it. We have to go away from that, and (the
adjustments) are not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating right now. I haven't found my comfort zone in
the system here. It's frustrating to be playing the kind of minutes
I'm playing and not be involved in the offense. To go out and lose,
I realize I could have made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets on Sunday went inside to Barkley and Hakeem
Olajuwon, largely because with Suns center Luc Longley out with a
hip pointer, Olajuwon seemed to have the advantage against Cliff
Robinson and Danny Manning, and because Barkley went up against
Kleine for much of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Olajuwon never found the shooting touch he had
enjoyed in the Rockets' winning streak, the system worked for much
of the game. Despite a horrid start in which the Rockets made but
three of their first 20 shots, they rallied in the second quarter
on the strength of their bench.
</P>
<P>
   Using a nine-man rotation, Tomjanovich believed his starters
would be strong enough to finish the game before the wear of
another back-to-back weekend left their shots short and slowed
their defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that would help us big-time,'' Tomjanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   But Tomjanovich said the Suns ``out-energied us'' and was
particularly impressed with Jason Kidd, whose 26 points, 14 assists
and 11 rebounds gave him his 24th career triple double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is such a winner, such a gamer,'' Tomjanovich said.
``He's amazing. He's one of the best competitors I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd took over in the second half. He hit a baseline jumper five
minutes into the half to complete the Suns' comeback from a deficit
that had reached 12 in the second quarter. And though the Rockets
held off the Suns for much of the third quarter, points became
increasingly difficult to come by as Phoenix, and especially Kidd,
began to roll.
</P>
<P>
   With Kleine bumping and pushing him out of the lane, Barkley
made one of six shots during the Suns' run _ each miss coming up
short _ until Phoenix had built a 10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wore me down,'' Barkley said of Kleine. ``I had nothing
left when the game was on the line. He played great defense, and he
made big shots. I was worn down, and he wore me down even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran out of gas in the second half. There was nothing we
could do about it. It's frustrating, because we're better than that
team. It's disappointing to lose to that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd, meanwhile, either scored or set up 12 consecutive Suns
points in the fourth quarter, turning the game into a ``scramble''
that Tomjanovich said the Rockets had to avoid. And when Kidd
posted up, his only time with his back to the basket all game, he
passed to George McLeod for an open 3 and an 84-77 lead with 5:13
left.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns scored on 15 of their last 16 trips down the court,
Kleine completing the win with a jumper that gave him 10 surprising
points off the bench and left the Rockets wondering what had hit
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game you can't really explain,'' Olajuwon said. ``We
had the game under control, and all of a sudden it slips away. It's
the kind of game you look back on and say, `Wow, we should have
won.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had some theories, but he couldn't explain it entirely
himself. He did plan, however, to get some answers, and for more
than just Sunday's loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
