<HEADER>
A0353 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-UPSET-TEX     03-15 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-UPSET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CINDERELLA'S BALL IN NCAA TOURNAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cinderella's pumpkin coach is a little crowded this year.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in NCAA Tournament history, five teams with
double-digit seeds have reached the Sweet 16. Before this season,
three double-digit seeds had survived to the second weekend four
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of uncharted waters for me,'' said Oklahoma coach
Kelvin Sampson, who had been 0-5 in the NCAA Tournament before his
team's two victories in the Midwest Region. ``I normally get up
here to talk about why we won or why we lost, but that's
inappropriate now. We're going to the Sweet 16.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners, the No. 13 seed in the Midwest, are the longest
shot still playing. Miami of Ohio, led by Wally Szczerbiak, is a
No. 10 seed in the Midwest. In the East, No. 12 Southwest Missouri
State and No. 10 Purdue are still playing. And in the West, No. 10
Gonzaga is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a fluke situation for our team,'' Gonzaga coach
Don Monson said. ``Our kids believed they were going to win that
game \Ran 82-74 victory Saturday over second-seeded Stanford\S. ...
We haven't gone into a game this season where our kids didn't think
they were going to win. And that's a really hard mentality to get
in when it says Gonzaga on your jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   The lower-seeded team has won 19 of the 48 games played. The
South is the only region that has followed form; the four top seeds
have all advanced.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma is the only Big 12 Conference team still standing; all
three Western Athletic Conference teams are finished. Defending
champion Kentucky, which disposed of Kansas yesterday in overtime,
is the only Final Four team from last year still playing. The Big
Ten Conference has four teams in the Sweet 16, most for any league.
</P>
<P>
   For the surprise teams, those double-digit seeds, the next step
is the longest. Last year, Valparaiso (No. 13), Washington (No. 11)
and West Virginia (No. 10) all lost regional semifinals. The
lowest-seeded team to win the national championship was No. 8
Villanova in 1985. The lowest seed to reach the Final Four was No.
11 Louisiana State in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri State probably has the toughest assignment,
facing championship favorite Duke in the East Regional semifinals
Friday. The Bears held their two NCAA opponents to a combined 83
points; the Blue Devils, winners of 28 in a row, beat their two
opponents by a combined 82 points.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Alford's team figures to be a huge underdog, but his
players appear to have things in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to take it seriously, be happy that we're
there,'' senior center Danny Moore said. ``We need to be happy that
we've made the Sweet 16, the first time that's ever happened at our
school. Try to win, but if you lose, you've still had a great
year.''
</P>
<P>
   A year, they hope, where midnight has yet to strike.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
