<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FLYERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS LIKE THIS DRAW WITH DESPERATE FLYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Unlike the Lennox Lewis-Evander Holyfield brawl
the night before, this was a good tie.
</P>
<P>
   Led by captain Derian Hatcher, who stood his ground in an
opening-minute fight with Philadelphia Flyers captain Eric Lindros,
the Stars forged a 1-1 tie with the Flyers last night, before
19,656 at the First Union Center and a national television audience
on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   With the tie, the Stars extended the Flyers' winless streak to a
franchise-record 11 games (0-7-4) and handled a scrappy team that
had been berated by its owner and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good point overall,'' said goalie Ed Belfour, who
stopped 26 shots in moving his record to 30-10-9. ``They worked
really hard and you can tell they're desperate for a win.
Fortunately, we played good defensively and held them off the
board.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that was because of Hatcher, who drew the assignment of
checking Lindros, the league's second-leading scorer. While Hatcher
and defensive mate Richard Matvichuk were successful in holding off
Teemu Selanne and Paul Kariya (third and fifth in the league in
scoring) during the Stars' 4-0 victory on Friday, this was clearly
more a battle of man-on-man.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher was asked to basically carry the load for the Stars in
many ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guy was a machine,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said of the
battle of captains. ``He just absolutely loves this type of game.
The nastier, the uglier, the better. He had a field day today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher answered the bell 40 seconds into the game when Lindros
went right after him and challenged him to a fight. The two
heavyweights wrestled for position and each got one or two punches
in before heading off the ice for five minutes in the penalty box.
Hatcher called the fight a draw, but the truth was it showed the
Stars would not be pushed around by the much larger Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what he was doing, he came right at me,'' Hatcher said
of Lindros' attempt to inspire his teammates. ``Tonight,
Philadelphia dragged us into the battle, and we had a chance to
play well or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars played well, and Hatcher was magnificent. He played
just about every second Lindros was on the ice and held him to four
harmless shots. With Lindros' linemate John LeClair out with a hip
injury, the Flyers had little else in the offensive department.
Their second line of Rod Brind'Amour, Jody Hull and Colin Forbes
provided energy. But for the second consecutive game, the Stars
shut down a talented offensive team and proved a league-best 1.99
goals-against average is well-deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, so is the Stars' 42-12-11 record and 95 points _ 19
points better than second-place Colorado in the West and 11 points
better than the Eastern Conference-leading Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had a great year,'' Flyers coach Roger Neilson said.
``A tie against Dallas is a good tie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars took the lead in the second period when they wore down
the Flyers on successive shifts, which resulted in Mike Modano's
30th goal of the season. Modano, Jere Lehtinen and Jamie
Langenbrunner had to scrap for every inch of ice they could get,
and Modano fed Lehtinen in the slot for a great scoring chance.
Flyers goalie John Vanbiesbrouck came up with two saves (Lehtinen
also swiped at a rebound) before Modano waded through a pile of
bodies to slap in the game's first goal at the 3:51 mark of the
second period.
</P>
<P>
   The line of Mike Keane, Grant Marshall and Tony Hrkac helped set
up that goal by wearing down the Flyers on the previous shift. It
was part of a team effort that had Hitchcock relying on all six
defensemen and putting a great deal of responsibility on Keane and
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of good players tonight,'' Hitchcock said, ``a
lot of good players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers bounced back and ended Belfour's bid for a second
consecutive shutout when Brind'Amour made a strong move behind the
net and found Hull cutting to the goal. Hull somehow squeezed a
shot past Belfour at the 16:15 mark of the second period, and that
would be all of the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Flyers (30-21-17) were pleased with their
effort, despite seeing their winless streak extended. And in the
face of criticism from chairman Ed Snider, who said two days
earlier the Flyers had suffered a ``complete mental collapse,'' and
having had a team meeting with general manager Bob Clarke before
the game, the Flyers said they gave a desperate and solid effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great tie,'' Hull said. ``We're playing the best
team in the league and they play well on the road. For a team that
hasn't won in 11, we'll take every point we can get.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
