<HEADLINE>
`CHARACTER' DESCRIBES CHANEY TO A `T` 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The story is a dozen years old and gets some
embellishment each time it's told.
</P>
<P>
   John Chaney is part of a daily pickup game among the athletic
staff. Guarding Chaney is Temple assistant women's basketball coach
Fran O'Hanlon, now the men's coach at Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Like most contests involving Temple basketball and Chaney, this
is a physical confrontation of the highest competitive order.
O'Hanlon, almost three decades younger, is all over Chaney, who was
a first-rate player in the old Eastern League.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney looks and looks. He cannot find an open man. ``Time
out,'' he bellows.
</P>
<P>
   ``TIME OUT?'' says O'Hanlon. ``You can't call time out in a
pickup game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My gym,'' says Chaney, not backing off an inch and revealing
the competitive side of the man who has become, in the words of
Kansas coach Roy Williams, ``truly a legend.''
</P>
<P>
   The legend is winding down his career now. Oh, nothing is
imminent, unless Temple defies the odds, gets past Purdue on Friday
and wins the NCAA championship.
</P>
<P>
   But sooner, rather than later, which, for a man of 67, would
make sense. Unless, of course, you're talking about Chaney, still a
lion even in the winter of a career in which substance has always
meant more than style.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Chaney's latest group of players to talk about his ``tough''
love style, which includes in-your-face 5 a.m. practice sessions
that teach his players more than basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not mentally tough,'' said guard Quincy Wadley,
``you're definitely going to fold. But there's nothing that I
wouldn't do for the man. Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaney feels the same way about his players, about friends who
have hovered around his program ever since he came to Temple 17
years ago after a 10-year stint at Cheyney State in suburban
Philadelphia, where he won a Division 2 national championship in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Chaney seems like Don Quixote tilting at windmills
when he takes on the NCAA over its academic admissions requirements
regarding test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Other times he goes way over the line, as he did when he turned
a postgame press conference after a loss to the University of
Massachusetts into a national incident when he threatened to
``kill'' former UMass coach John Calipari, words that Chaney now
says he deeply regrets.
</P>
<P>
   But that is Chaney: white dress shirt, tie loosened, a pained
expression that increases whenever one of his players does
something needlessly, like commit a turnover.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way he's always been, seeking perfection in a world
filled with imperfections. He was that way back at Cheyney State,
when he did everything from coach, to tape ankles, to make
breakfast for his team. Once he whipped up some eggs, which turned
green because of some imperfections in the cleaning of the frying
pan. No problem, said John-I-Am: he convinced his team that there
was such a thing as green eggs and ham and that wondrous things
could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Some have. This winter, he passed the 600-victory milestone. He
was nominated to the Basketball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   His teams, whether you like them or hate them, generally always
play hard, most notably on defense, where Temple's matchup zone can
frustrate the best of teams into the worst of games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, somebody from Cincinnati asked Chaney what was the
biggest mistake teams make in trying to solve the matchup zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a mystery out of BS,'' said Chaney in a
self-deprecating manner.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, most of it has worked over the years. Players come and
go and Chaney remains, fixed in his ways, irascible, controversial,
always looking for an edge, always seeking perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The players that have gone through the program still come back,
still remember. When Temple's new state-of-the-art arena, the Forum
at The Apollo of Temple, opened in 1997, a group of ex-Owls who had
gone on to the NBA decided to make their own contribution, chipping
in to buy a skybox that Chaney's family can use as often as it
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Those closest to Chaney cannot tell you when he will finally
decide he has had enough. Some say it will come when he keels over
on the bench, others say in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney has endured more than a modicum of tragedy in the past
few years, ranging from the murder of the son of close friend and
Temple alum Bill Cosby to the death of his longtime assistant and
best friend Jim Maloney.
</P>
<P>
   The past few years have aged him, but they have also added more
character to a man who some people swear has cornered the market on
the trait.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, as usual, John Chaney transferred enough of that
character to his players that they played a near-perfect basketball
game in upsetting Cincinnati, 64-54.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
