<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE'S SANCHEZ GETS THE POINT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The only job more challenging than being a point guard
for John Chaney is being a personal lawyer for Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The task is close to thankless. You are working for a man who is
abnormally obsessed with the position, a man who believes that
without a quality point guard life has just about no meaning.
Truly. Now imagine being a young basketball player who not only has
to play a tough position for a completely demanding man, but who
also must learn what to do while living in an alien culture.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, say hello to Juan ``Pepe'' Sanchez, late of
Bahia Blanca, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Temple advanced to the NCAA East Regional semifinals in the
Meadowlands next weekend via a surprising 64-54 conquest of
Cincinnati Sunday at the FleetCenter. Lamont Barnes did a wonderful
job inside with 16 points and eight rebounds. Invaluable sixth man
Quincy Wadley provided 14 desperately needed points off the bench.
But no one was more responsible for Temple's triumphs over Kent and
Cincinnati than the junior point guard, who followed his 15-point,
9-assist, zero-turnover performance against Kent with a 14-point,
seven-rebound display against Cincinnati, not that numbers can ever
convey the value of a good point guard's game.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in Pepe's basketball background adequately prepared him
for being a John Chaney point guard. How could it? There are no
John Chaneys in Argentina, where basketball, while a popular sport,
is regarded as something more of an art form than a science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball in Argentina is happy basketball,'' explains
Sanchez. ``The one who scores the points or makes a fancy pass gets
all the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no point guards, as such, back home. There are guards,
sure, and they have skills. Juan Espil is a very nice player. But
he's not a point guard, because no one wants any.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's score, score, score, score, and then run down the court
and score some more,'' says Temple assistant coach Nate Blackwell,
who likewise played point guard for John Chaney and, unlike many,
actually lived to tell the tale.
</P>
<P>
   John Chaney isn't interested in helter-skelter point guards. He
wants point guards who understand what it means to control tempo
and get the ball to the right people at the right time and who can
control the game from a defensive standpoint. Having a
keep-'em-honest outside shot is a plus, and it certainly helps if
the point guard makes his free throws. Most of all, he wants a
point guard who agrees with the coach that losing the basketball
via a turnover is, as Chaney says, ``like giving all your money to
a bum.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming a point guard for John Chaney is like pledging to the
Frat From Hell. Initiation starts on Day 1 and ends only when you
peel off that cherry-and-white uniform for the final time. ``He's
got to be able to handle the wrath of John Chaney,'' says
Blackwell, who was as classic a Temple point guard as Chaney has
ever had. ``It hasn't been easy for Pepe. There was a communication
problem, and sometimes there still is. But Pepe has really
matured.''
</P>
<P>
   On the court, the 6-foot-1-inch southpaw is a cross between Dave
Wohl and Sarunas Marciulionis. He never loses his dribble, and he
never goes anywhere in a straight line if he can help it. He seems
to be thinking 20 seconds ahead of the play, and he never, ever
panics. His patience on offense is extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   The quintessential Pepe sequence came with the Owls leading,
47-35, with 7:18 remaining. Temple had the basketball out of bounds
underneath its basket. Cincinnati applied strong defensive
pressure, and Pepe called time out. He was handed the ball for a
second time, and, after surveying the situation, he called for
another 20-second timeout. Pepe knew that Coach Chaney would much
prefer that he whip out a Swiss Army knife from underneath his
jersey, slice the basketball in two, and ingest it rather than
throw a questionable inbounds pass.
</P>
<P>
   On his third try, Pepe did get the ball in play. He got it back,
and then dribbled and dribbled and dribbled some more, until he
spied Rasheed Brokenborough making a move out of the right corner.
Pepe slipped him the ball with a backhand pass, and Brokenborough
slashed to the hoop for a nice little running lefty hook. That
would be Temple's final basket of the game. The final 15 points
came on the free throw line, 7 of them supplied by Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   The Pepe Sanchez who arrived at the North Philadelphia campus
two years ago could not have made that play. ``The American game
has a timing to it,'' points out Temple assistant coach Dean
Demopoulos, ``and foreign players have trouble with it, especially
point guards. People who know him from Argentina say the adjustment
he's made has been amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not understand the American game when I got here,''
Sanchez acknowledges. ``You have to give a lot of credit to the
coach. He taught me to be patient and to understand my role. Back
home, there are no roles. You shoot the ball, pass the ball, do
whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sanchez had good inherent defensive ability when he
arrived, he had no concept of the American game in that area,
either. ``He had to learn that you can take a gamble but it must be
a calculated gamble,'' says Blackwell. ``It can't be 50-50. It's
got to be at least 75-25.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple basically has no backup for Pepe Sanchez. The only thing
that gets him out of a Temple game is foul trouble. He got his
third personal with 12:59 remaining, and Chaney was distraught. He
kept him out for the next 2:45. He just couldn't stand it any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pepe is not in the game,'' Chaney explains, ``everything
is wrong. You need somebody in control of the train.''
</P>
<P>
   That little choo-choo is heading to the Sweet 16, and it
wouldn't be going there without Pepe Sanchez. And don't think
they're not grateful. ``It's a two-way street,'' says Demopolous.
``Pepe stuck with us. There were some rocky times for him, but he
hung in there.''
</P>
<P>
   John Chaney tells a million stories, and now he's got another
one. He's got an Argentine point guard. He can tell people he's got
America's greatest Argentine import since Rita Hayworth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
