<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELL ME AGAIN WHO GAINS FROM ORIOLES' CUBAN TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Please tell me again, somebody, why the
Baltimore Orioles going to Havana to play the Cuban national
baseball team is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Explain, if you will, how this is the reincarnation of
``ping-pong diplomacy'' and how Peter Angelos is going to play the
part of Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say it stinks,'' Rangers pitcher Tony Fossas said yesterday.
``If the United States has an embargo against Cuba, how can you go
there and play baseball?''
</P>
<P>
   Lefty reliever Fossas, 41, was born in Cuba and lived there
until age 10. First baseman Rafael Palmeiro, born in Havana, is
equally adamant about not playing.
</P>
<P>
   Their reasons are political, but they are also deeply personal.
</P>
<P>
   They know. They have relatives in Cuba. They send those
relatives money, clothing, tissue paper, toothpaste _ some of the
necessities of life that are in unkindly short supply in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   And now commissioner Bud Selig is sending them baseball players.
</P>
<P>
   A bad idea, born perhaps of noble intentions. But a dangerous
idea nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Before you begin that trite whine about politics and sports not
mixing, let me interrupt you. You don't know Cuba. You probably
have never seen Cuban athletes in action in person or been forced
to mingle with a Cuban delegation at a sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   To these people, sports is politics and politics is sports. The
1959 revolution is a benchmark. To me, they seem incapable of
separating a pennant race from a testimonial to Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pan American Games in Indianapolis, Ind., in 1987, I saw
Cuban boxers leave their spectator seats to go over and pummel an
anti-Castro protester. I saw a Cuban TV interviewer bring a
heavyweight U.S. wrestler, a Cuban defector, to real tears by
peppering him with ``reminders'' about the brothers, sisters,
aunts, cousins and loved ones that he'd never see again.
</P>
<P>
   At the Summer Olympics, Cuban athletes do not often speak to the
non-Cuban media. A question shouted in English invariably draws a
cold stare. Typically, the Cuban delegation sends its coaches to
meet any Olympic post-event interview requirements. Those coaches
are fluent in Castro-ese.
</P>
<P>
   We hear only what they want us to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame the athletes at all,'' Fossas said on a rainy
day in the Rangers' clubhouse. ``You mention the word `programmed.'
When your life is in jeopardy, when you have families leaving a
country in rowboats, leaving a country in tires, living in a system
where everything your family had was stolen, living in a country
where you have no medicine, very little food, and you're expected
to live on $12 a month, and then, because you're an athlete who
maybe has been taken care of a little bit better, you don't say
anything _ how is that not `programmed?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fossas' point is eloquently put. In Cuba, sport is politics.
Athletes are not sportsmen _ they are emissaries who happen to play
sports.
</P>
<P>
   I'll say this for the Orioles: they'd better win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't win down there, they will be a laughingstock to
all Latin American nations,'' Fossas said. ``If they want to be
jokes, go down there with a team of A-ball guys, because those guys
\Rthe Cubans\S are going to be ready to play. You can bet they are
practicing day and night for this. Their whole lives will revolve
around that one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Please tell me again, somebody, what the Orioles have to gain by
this. It can't be the T-shirts, because the Cuban people can't
afford them. It can't be the gate receipts, because the Cuban peso
is only slightly more valuable than Monopoly money.
</P>
<P>
   Selig said, ``If this generates the kind of results we hope it
will, it could well be the start of something. Something
constructive.''
</P>
<P>
   Like, stealing more Cuban baseball players?
</P>
<P>
   Orioles owner Angelos actually told The Washington Post last
week, ``There is no political dimension to this visit.''
</P>
<P>
   If he really said that, his naivete is surpassed only by his
ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba is one neighborhood where the proverbial brotherhood of
sports is out of bounds. There are human rights issues that cannot
be ignored. There are good people _ some of them now American
citizens _ who are going to be terribly offended by the Orioles'
visit.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Castro is alive, it all has a political dimension in
Cuba, amigo. The Orioles are stepping into something that they are
ill-equipped to handle.
</P>
<P>
   They could be making history, all right.
</P>
<P>
   Another victory for the Castro revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody tell me, please, how this one is going to put food in
the Cuban people's mouths.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
