A0361 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CELTICS-PACERS-BO     03-15 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-PACERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS CAN'T KEEP UP THE PACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The game itself was not the problem. If you lived
in San Antonio, Chicago or New York and watched Celtics-Pacers on
NBC Sunday, you definitely wouldn't have channel surfed. You might
have even said to yourself, ``That game was great.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is more likely that you are a New Englander, not a Texan,
Midwesterner or frequent patron of the George Washington Bridge.
And chances are that the Pacers' 99-96 win over the Celtics at
Market Square Arena had you saying things to yourself, with ``great
game'' not among them.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino stood in a hallway and said the Celtics played their
best game of the year. Larry Bird stood in another hallway and said
the Celtics ``manhandled'' his Pacers. ``Boston was hungry today,''
the Legend said. ``They came after us. They were aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   But, again, words were the Celtics' consolation prize. Because
for the fifth consecutive game and seventh time in eight March
games, they couldn't get what they needed. A win.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say they weren't close. Dana Barros took a
3-pointer just before the final buzzer that could have sent the
game into overtime. Paul Pierce (15 points), playing his first game
in five days, followed an old-fashioned 3-point play with a free
throw that put the Celtics up, 94-91, with three minutes to play.
Antoine Walker had a layup blocked by Antonio Davis with 10.8
seconds left. The Celtics trailed, 98-96, at the time, and if the
shot had gone in this might be a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is a remix of a familiar story and familiar
headline. Celtics Lose . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a couple options on that last play, but that was
basically what we wanted,'' Barros said of his stright-on 3-point
attempt, about 25 feet from the hoop. ``But, you know, it shouldn't
even have come to that. We've had leads in games, man. I'm talking
about double-digit leads. And we're not holding on to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is the part of the story where you will be able to
determine which way you lean in the land of NBA politics. You may
be like Barros. You may feel that a 10-point lead (88-78) with 6:39
remaining in a game should result in your team winning. You may
tell yourself that it doesn't make a difference if the game is on
the road or at home; against the one-win Clippers or 15-win Pacers.
A 10-point lead late should be maintained.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you are like others, people who tell you that a young
team will do such things against a veteran team. They tell you that
the Pacers have Reggie Miller, a man who can make a substantial
lead disappear in seconds, as he did many times against the Knicks.
Or, for a more recent reference, Sunday against the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't beat themselves,'' Pitino said of the Pacers. This
is why he said it:
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a 10-point lead, the Celtics watched Rik Smits (28
points) put in a short hook shot. The lead was 8. That's when Kenny
Anderson saw Walker under the hoop, free for a layup. The point
guard laced a terrific pass; the forward missed the layup. Miller
made a jump shot. And then he hit a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Timeout, Celtics. You mentioned a 10-point lead? No such thing.
The lead was 3, 88-85. The Celtics were ahead. And in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Bird talked before the game about how his team worked out
together during the lockout. This bunch is very close. They hang
out together, work out together, and even do a corny pregame
introduction routine together. They don't get down on each other
when they are down by 10 together, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're going to need right now,'' Anderson said.
``We can't allow ourselves to fall apart. We're slumping, we're on
a five-game losing streak. It's easy to start doubting each other
in a situation like this. We can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   After Pierce had given them their 3-point lead, the Celtics
quickly lost it when Travis Best made a wide-open 3-pointer. Smits
followed with an 18-footer, Walker answered with a layup to tie it
at 96, and Smits came back with a 14-footer.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics were done scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Walker got open in the lane with about 12 seconds left and
appeared set for an easy layup. Davis knocked the ball away the
right way: He stopped his man from scoring and the ball wound up in
the hands of a teammate (Best).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great block,'' said Walker, who led the Celtics with
16 points, 8 rebounds, and 6 assists. ``I didn't know where he came
from.''
</P>
<P>
   Best was immediately fouled, but made only one free throw, which
meant the Celtics still had a chance with 5.8 seconds left. Barros
got free and his long shot went up . . . and off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a better team now than we were at the beginning of the
trip,'' Pitino said. He may be right. But there is not one win in
the last five games to support his statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
