<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PURDUE-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PURDUE SHOCKS MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They came into the tournament through a back door, a
10th-seeded team that few people expected to be playing past the
first round and lots of people didn't think should have been part
of the 64-team NCAA field at all.
</P>
<P>
   But the Purdue Boilermakers, who finished 7-9 in the Big Ten and
staggered into the NCAA Tournmament with five losses in their last
six games, reaching the Sweet 16?
</P>
<P>
   Please.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked Purdue forward Brian Cardinal what he would have
said a week ago if he had been told he was going to the Sweet 16.
``I'd want to know where my seat (in the stands) would be,'' said
Cardinal with a laugh following the Boilermakers' improbable but
convincing 73-63 win over No. 2 seed Miami Sunday at the
FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Now Cardinal and the rest of the Boilermakers will have the best
seat in the house Friday night at the Meadowlands when they face
Temple in an East Regional semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have anything to lose,'' said Cardinal, who scored a
game-high 20 points, including a crucial 5-point spurt in the
second half after Miami had made its final push. ``People didn't
think we should have been in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers (21-12) had earned their way into Sunday's game
with a tough 58-54 win over Texas on Friday night. But the
conventional wisdom seemed to be that Miami (23-7), a rising power
in the Big East, would be a little too quick, too athletic for
Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 13 minutes, the sellout FleetCenter crowd of
18,913 saw a game that gave no indication of the final outcome. The
score was tied, 17-17, when Miami forgot how to score, how to
shoot, how to play defense. Pick your negative.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line was that the Hurricanes didn't score a point the
rest of the half, while Purdue went on a 15-0 spree that was more a
slow jog than a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the key to the game,'' said Purdue coach
Gene Keady, who could only watch in amazement as his team pulled
steadily ahead without doing anything spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers sometimes don't give true indications of the course of a
game, but the first-half statistics were a chilling warning for
Hurricane fans. Miami, despite an overwhelming advantage (13-2) in
offensive rebounds, had shot a miserable 6 of 33 (18.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Even more disheartening for the 'Canes was their 3-point
production _ or lack of it. Forward Johnny Hemsley, who had poured
in nine 3-point shots in Miami's 75-54 opening-round victory over
Lafayette, had problems simply getting off a shot from 3-point
land, much less making one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they were going to face-guard Johnny,'' said Miami
coach Leonard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   He had a remedy prepared: Get the ball inside. But that wasn't
working either. ``My biggest surprise was to have 13 offensive
rebounds and shoot only 18 percent,'' said Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Canes knew they were too good a team to put two halves that
bad together in one game.
</P>
<P>
   During intermission, Hamilton told his team not to panic in the
remaining 20 minutes but to speed the pace as much as it could.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind by as many as 16 with 16:30 left, the
'Canes finally got into the tempo they wanted. In a six-minute
stretch they shaved the lead to 5 _ guard Vernon Jennings put in a
layup with 11:06 left to make it 43-38.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of situation that the 'Canes had thrived on all
through a regular season in which they finished second in the Big
East to Connecticut while leading the conference in shooting
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, sensing that perhaps it was finally going to see the
kind of competitive, down-to-the-final-buzzer game that fans at
other NCAA venues around the country had seen, began picking up the
Miami cause a little more.
</P>
<P>
   But in an eight-second span it ended, as Cardinal put in a
21-foot 3-pointer, then converted a layup following a steal by Mike
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the lead was back to 10 and the 'Canes had nothing
left. Or not enough left to overcome the steadiness of Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   Or the quirkiness of Miami, which took twice as many shots as
the Boilermakers, outrebounded them, 45-29, and still lost badly.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain that, Keady said, ``Thirty-seven free throws,
fewer turnovers, and stopping their best players from getting their
normal scoring average.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers did all of that, particularly stopping Hemsley,
who managed to get off only two 3-point shots and didn't make any.
</P>
<P>
   All of that has put the Boilermakers in the Sweet 16, much to
even their own surprise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
