<HEADLINE>
SNOWSTORM PICKS ITS WAY ALONG THE NORTHEAST COAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Kan., Ohio, Mo., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A huge storm that dumped more than a foot of snow
on parts of the Plains states over the weekend reached the East
Sunday and threatened to bring snow to a 75-mile-wide band from
Washington to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Meteorologists said Sunday night, however, that the snow might
just as likely turn out to be rain, depending on the track that the
storm took and air temperatures. ``It's a real tough call,'' said
Paul Knight, a meteorologist at Penn State Weather Communications.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, it was raining in Washington and New York City but
snowing in many places in between. More than an inch of snow had
fallen in Baltimore and Philadelphia by Sunday evening, while areas
of western Maryland had three to six inches of snow.
</P>
<P>
   Another Penn State meteorologist, Joe Koval, said that while he
expected New York City to get a combination of rain and snow, the
suburbs to the west and north could get a substantial amount of
snow.
</P>
<P>
   Koval said that 10 to 12 inches of snow could fall in
Westchester, Rockland, Orange and Putnam Counties as well as up to
6 inches in northern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Koval said heavy snow was expected in higher elevations in
Connecticut and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a bizarre storm,'' Knight said. ``It has gone in a
75-mile band from southern Kansas and northern Oklahoma, across
southern Missouri and up the Ohio River, snowing very hard in
Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight said 22 inches of snow fell over the weekend in parts of
southern Missouri, and The Associated Press reported that hundreds
of travelers spent Saturday night jammed into motels and community
shelters because of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   A 115-mile-long stretch of Interstate 70 from Wakeeney, Kan.,
west to the Colorado state line that had been closed by the storm
was reopened Sunday but remained snow-packed and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 travelers spent the night in Colby, Kan., filling
shelters set up by the Red Cross and the National Guard Armory.
Hundreds more spent the night in Limon, Colo., because I-70 was
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Signs posted at Salina and Hays had warned travelers that no
motel rooms were available in western Kansas. The Comfort Inn in
Colby ran out of rooms but offered lobby floor space to stranded
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the travelers was Joe Day, an amateur boxer heading back
to Houston from a match in Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the breakfast room, laying on the floor watching
tapes of us getting beat up,'' Day said of himself and his
teammates. ``It's real fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
