<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO COMPENSATION FOR EDWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The Patriots will not receive any compensation for the
loss to injury of Robert Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Robert Kraft tried to convince his peers at the annual
owners meeting that New England should get a first-round pick after
the running back was injured in an NFL-sponsored Pro Bowl event
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, the Patriots' first-round pick last year, suffered a
knee injury that appears to be career-ending during a spill in a
rookie beach football game.
</P>
<P>
   However, although the league sympathizes with the Patriots'
tough luck, reportedly there will be no compensation. Instead, the
league is studying a proposal to pay an injured player a full
year's salary if the injury occurs in a league-sponsored event.
That has not been voted on yet.
</P>
<P>
   In other matters, the new Washington Redskins ownership group
will have a hard time getting voted in Monday. The group, headed by
New Yorker Howard Milstein, met with the league's finance committee
Saturday and it did not go well.
</P>
<P>
   The league had informed Milstein more than a week ago that his
financial package was too highly leveraged. He was told to put more
cash into the deal. Milstein reportedly presented a revised deal
Saturday, but it was not what the NFL had suggested. One league
executive said that if the financing wasn't reworked before the
vote, Milstein faced a difficult task getting the necessary 24
votes for approval.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL also put off to Tuesday or Wednesday an announcement on
the awarding of its 32d franchise. Los Angeles will get the nod,
but there will be some strings attached. The NFL will ask that
certain things be accomplished in terms of a new stadium, within a
time limit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
