<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKW-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDS OF PAIN FOR US WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPOO, Finland _ This time, it was Team USA that stood
dejectedly at center ice, forced to watch its rivals celebrate.
This time, the locker-room tears were those of sadness. This time,
it was different yet oh-so-familiar.
</P>
<P>
   The US may have an Olympic hockey gold medal, but Canada is
still No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Just 25 seconds into the third period in Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's final
of the Women's World Championship, with the game tied, 1-1,
Canadian defenseman Hayley Wickenheiser fired a power-play missile
from the blue line that ricocheted off the stick of Danielle
Goyette, sending the puck flying one way as US goaltender Erin
Whitten went another.
</P>
<P>
   Any hope of the US women's national team winning its first world
championship went flying off with that goal. The Americans never
recovered and Canada went on to win, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they got that goal, they really turned it up a notch,''
said US coach Ben Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Turning it up a notch in the gold-medal game of the world
championships is nothing new for Canada, which has won all five
dating back to 1990, each time at the expense of the US. And being
in the net when the Canadians toss their gloves heavenward in joy
at the final buzzer is nothing new to Whitten, either: She has been
the losing goaltender in every gold-medal loss since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's loss was especially painful to Whitten and her
teammates, because the 27-year-old veteran who narrowly missed
making the 1998 Olympic team played heroically, keeping her
struggling teammates in the game until the end with 27 saves.
``This might be the best game against Canada I've seen her play,''
said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Cammi Granato, the team's captain, agreed. ``Erin came in and
played her heart out; we just didn't put the puck in the net,''
said Granato, who has played on every US world championship team
since the tournament began. ``The chances we had, we didn't bury.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams played tentatively in the first period. The closest
the US came to scoring was when Katie King, the left wing from
Salem, N.H., went head-to-head with a defender and landed one on
the roof of the net with 33 seconds left. But Canada was no more
forceful, and the period ended scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Schmidgall, the Minnesota Gopher who led all scorers in
the tournament and was named the top forward, rung up her fifth
goal 9:09 into the second period, giving the US a 1-0 lead when she
came across from right to left and angled the puck around Sami Jo
Small, the Canadian goalie who plays on the men's varsity team at
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   But the lead failed to ignite the sluggish US, and less than
three minutes later Caroline Ouellette evened the score at 1-1
when, during a barrage of shots, she managed to barely sneak the
puck over the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   The period ended ominously for the US when, with 34 seconds
left, left wing Tricia Dunn of Derry, N.H., was called for
cross-checking. Just 25 seconds into the third period, Wickenheiser
teed it up, Goyette bounced it in, and Canada led, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's usually the difference when we play (this team),'' said
Smith. ``It's whose power play is clicking, whose penalty kill is
hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than 2 1/2 minutes after the Wickenheiser-Goyette bomb,
Geraldine Heaney added an unassisted rocket of her own (``I didn't
even see it,'' said Whitten), giving Canada a 3-1 lead and an
immeasurable confidence boost while the US faltered even though its
defense, led by Sue Merz of Greenwich, Conn. (named, with
Schmidgall, to the all-tournament team) and Whitten kept the
Americans close.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't exactly make up for it,'' said Whitten,
struggling to accept a compliment on her play. ``It hurts to have a
silver medal again.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell Team Canada. ``To come out on top is huge for us,''
said Canadian right wing Jayna Hefford. ``I think after the
Olympics, we came back even hungrier. It was a little bit of
revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   And just another in a great long-running series. ``A year ago I
said I didn't want to play a 16th game,'' said Smith, recalling how
the US and Canada went into the gold-medal game in Nagano tied,
7-7, in their Olympic tuneup matches. ``And here we are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
