<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM BUSTING OUT OF RED SOX 'PEN 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ When Red Sox reliever Jim Corsi wanders
through the locker room at City of Palms Park during spring
training, his message is always the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys are always talking to the starters,'' he says. ``You
never want to talk to the guys in the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right, of course, as in the spring the starters finish
early, meet with the media, and go home. Bullpen regulars like
Corsi are lucky to get in an inning of work, and what they do
rarely rates a high five, much less an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it will be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing all right,'' said Corsi when finally asked Sunday
about his progress and that of the rest of the bullpen. ``Everybody
is throwing the ball good. As long as we stay healthy, we'll be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest tasks of the spring is to find a replacement
for Dennis Eckersley, who in the final year of his Hall of Fame
career last season pitched in 50 games, mostly as a setup man, and
had a 4-1 record with a save and a 4.46 ERA in 39 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Another order of business is to get closer Tom ``Flash'' Gordon
on the mound against live opposition for the first time this spring
and get him going.
</P>
<P>
   Then the brass must figure out how to utilize the rest of the
pen in order to get to Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Holdovers for the middle relief/setup role include Corsi, Derek
Lowe, John Wasdin, and lefthander Ron Mahay. On the basis of his
strong showing in Sunday's 8-7 victory over the Cincinnati Reds,
lefthander Mark Guthrie seems a lock. He has the stuff to get
lefthanders and righthanders out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen is looking really good in the early schedule,''
said pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``Corsi is right on schedule,
Wasdin is on schedule, Lowe too. Guthrie has really surprised me.
He's been really sharp. He's a guy with a good program, a good
idea. He knows what he's doing on the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams is quick to say the Sox can no more
``replace'' Eckersley than they can Mo Vaughn. But they're working
on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what we can come up with, depending on how many
pitchers we carry,'' said Williams. ``The roster dictates that. It
depends upon how much protection we need for our regulars. How many
bullpen guys and so-called utility guys we need. The flexibility of
the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be honest and say I'd rather carry 11 (pitchers), but if
they think 12 is the right number, then that's what we carry. One
of the reasons we made some cuts today is that the bullpen has to
pitch more innings. We'd like to see some of these middle guys get
a couple of innings in a game rather than just one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox certainly want to see more of Guthrie, who most recently
pitched out of the Dodgers' bullpen. They like him a lot, and
Kerrigan thinks he can be even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like today,'' said Kerrigan, ``he was trying to improve his
breaking ball and make it a little sharper. He threw a nice one to
Hal Morris in the ninth and had an outstanding split-finger
fastball. He's got real good command, like Corsi.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan pointed out that Corsi was tough last year against
lefthanders (.211). So was Gordon, as lefties hit only .189 against
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'll find any lefthander who can do better
than that,'' he said. ``We think Lowe has matured and shouldn't
have as much trouble this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line is, the Red Sox believe they have several pitchers
who can handle righthanded or lefthanded batters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
