<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RODMAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORM'S TURN NO SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
 ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sitting in pampered luxury Sunday in a FleetCenter
suite, Garry St. Jean, the general manager of the Golden State
Warriors, had a one-word reaction to the news of Dennis Rodman's
temporarily leaving the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   From his loge seat in the same building, man-of-the-people Chris
Wallace, the general manager of the Celtics, had a similar initial
response.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after catching themselves, both men said basically the
same thing: Why should we be surprised?
</P>
<P>
   Rodman was not with the Lakers as they began a six-game/nine-day
road swing Sunday &UR;  &LR; night in Sacramento, and it began
inauspiciously, LA having its 10-game winning streak snapped,
105-101.
</P>
<P>
   He missed Saturday's practice, leaving with two bodyguards and
no explanation. The Lakers only would confirm that Rodman had taken
an indefinite leave of absence for personal reasons that were not
identified.
</P>
<P>
   This was a classic case of ``Be Careful What You Wish For'' for
the Lakers, and it remains to be seen what, if any, impact it will
have on the young, talented, impressionable team. Rodman had been
displaying some bizarre behavior, even by his wild standards, in
the weeks before signing that had to send out red flags. There was
the on-again, off-again, on-again quickie marriage to Carmen
Electra, the split with agent Dwight Manley, the rambling interview
on ESPN, and the X-rated news conference announcing his intention
to sign with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles general manager Jerry West, who never liked the idea
of bringing in Rodman, was laying low Sunday, probably thinking,
``Na, na, na, na, na, told ya' so.'' Rodman's signing was largely
because of the pushing of owner Jerry Buss; even the players who
originally pushed for Rodman grew tired of the soap opera before
his signing. Then, part owner/icon Earvin Johnson said on ``The
Late Show With David Letterman'' that the move would ``move us down
a notch in class'' if it didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, however, that didn't appear to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles had not lost since Rodman arrived on Feb. 20 and
Kurt Rambis succeeded Del Harris, taking that 10-game streak into
their game Sunday night. Rodman was averaging 10.3 rebounds a game
and had given the team much-needed toughness in his nine games. He
missed the second half of Friday's game with the Warriors because
of elbow soreness.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman was 90 minutes late for Saturday's practice at LA
Southwest College, but did speak briefly with Rambis. He stayed for
about 15 minutes, departing with his bodyguards in his white
Mercedes. He also had missed practice a week ago _ he was excused
from that one for personal reasons _ and already had been late to
one practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was part of the pattern in Chicago, too, and they seemed
to do all right,'' noted Wallace. ``As demonstrated by his track
record, it's part of the package you get. Teams have managed to win
despite the distractions, and I'm sure the Lakers factored that
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, however, are not the Bulls. Chicago had a focus
unlike any other team. The Bulls tolerated Rodman, they fought with
management, they even fought with each other. But they knew how to
win _ they had Michael Jordan and no one else did _ and they won.
The Lakers are in no such position, and even were leaning a bit on
Rodman because of his experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really about developing a team chemistry, and you knew
there was a history of volatility there,'' St. Jean said. ``You
knew what you were getting into. But I'll say this: I have no idea
what's going on with Rodman, but if anyone can get him back, it's
Jerry West. I don't know if people outside the business understand
how much he is respected in this league. When he speaks, it's like
E.F. Hutton _ you listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Buss, apparently, is not one of those people. He didn't listen _
and now his team is again in the spotlight, but for all the wrong
reasons. It's his mess to clean up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
