<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING IS EXCELLENT AT SANTA ANITA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Trainer Bob Baffert's Kentucky Derby picture
is clouded by his own success.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, his 3-year-old filly owned by John and Betty
Mabee's Golden Eagle Farms, captured the $250,000 Grade I Santa
Anita Oaks on Sunday, holding off a late rush from stablemate Tout
Charmant to win the 1 1/16-mile race by a neck.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Exploit and Prime Timber, Excellent Meeting, who has
six victories and three seconds in nine starts, could help provide
Baffert with a good shot at winning a third consecutive Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert was in Louisiana on Sunday for the Louisiana Derby.
Another of his hopefuls, General Challenge, finished fifth with
jockey Gary Stevens aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting was coming off a victory in the Grade I Las
Virgenes. Sunday's race, with Kent Desormeaux aboard, likely sets
her up for the April 3 Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Desormeaux must decide whether to stay with Excellent
Meeting or ride Real Quiet, who is scheduled to run the same day in
the Oaklawn Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux wasn't overly concerned with the close outcome in the
Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, if you look at the race, in the last hundred yards,
she (Excellent Meeting) was holding the other filly (Tout Charmant)
at bay,'' he said. ``I hope nobody gets too concerned out there and
that they don't lose any of their love for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's assistant trainer, Eoin Harty, was a little critical
of Desormeaux's ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kent rode this filly the way he rode Real Quiet last
week (in the New Orleans Handicap at the Fairgrounds) _ with a
little too much confidence,'' Harty said. ``He didn't give any
credit to Tout Charmant, and I knew Tout Charmant had improved a
lot since her last race (second in the Las Virgenes).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0122EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0373 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-B     03-15 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY CONCLUSION TO DRAW: A DAMAGING LOW BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Boxing lost Saturday night. So did Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   The final hour of what had been a glorious month for boxing once
again cast a dark shadow over a sport that has shot itself in the
foot so often it's up to its knees in bullet holes because two
judges saw, or claimed to see, something they could not possibly
have seen. They claimed they saw a way for Evander Holyfield to
have retained his two thirds of the heavyweight title. This simply
did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fight was not as lopsided as many are claiming, it
was not a victory or even a draw for Holyfield. Lennox Lewis did
more than retain his third of the title at Madison Square Garden.
He jabbed and occasionally hooked his way to the right to call
himself the undisputed champion, and even those who favored
Holyfield going in could find no way to dispute that coming out.
</P>
<P>
   Although judge Eugenia Williams had Holyfield winning, 115-113,
and Larry O'Connell of Great Britain scored it a 115-115 draw, only
Stanley Christoudoulou seemed to get it right, giving the nod to
Lewis, 116-113. The Globe had Lewis winning, 115-114, with one
round even that in retrospect belonged to Lewis, the second. That
would have made him a 116-114 victor, but regardless how you
tallied the score it always added up to Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The rounds he won he dominated with a long, often pawing jab
that stopped Holyfield from getting inside and some powerful right
hands that hurt him in the fifth round and bothered him at other
times, although never in the way one might have expected. With the
exception of the third _ which Holyfield took by trying to
overwhelm Lewis to make good on a prefight promise of a third-round
knockout _ the rounds that went to Holyfield were ones Lewis lost
more than the three-time heavyweight champion won.
</P>
<P>
   After seven rounds, Lewis led on all three cards and rightfully
so. But then, in Rounds 8 through 11, he unwisely chose to do
little or nothing and paid dearly for it. He lost all four rounds
on the judges' cards, and the Globe's as well, not because
Holyfield suddenly overwhelmed him _ as he had so many other
opponents late in a fight _ but simply because Lewis did little
more than pose.
</P>
<P>
   CompuBox's normally reasonable accounting of a fight's punch
stats seemed to go as far off the mark at that point as the judges'
cards did at the end, for they claimed Lewis threw 57, 57, 48, and
32 punches in those rounds and landed 30, 29, 31, and 25. If he
did, they must have been like the famed ``anchor punch'' Muhammad
Ali claimed to have knocked out Sonny Liston with in Maine, the
punch nobody saw but Liston, because Lewis did little but paw with
his left hand through most of those rounds. While Holyfield was not
effective even then, people need to remember this is boxing, not
fencing. You don't get points for touching your opponent; you get
points for stabbing him.
</P>
<P>
   This Lewis did through the first seven rounds almost at will and
again in the final one, when he came out throwing and controlled
all three minutes at a time when Holyfield needed something big and
was unable to come up with even something small. But Lewis unwisely
set himself up for problems with his approach once he thought he
had the fight under control, and he learned a harsh lesson. In
boxing, nothing is under anyone's control, except maybe promoter
Don King's.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, though, Lewis at least didn't lose his title, which
would have been the case had all three judges not given the final
round to the World Boxing Council champion. Had that not happened,
a mugging would have turned into a Brink's job, as trainer Emanuel
Steward insisted occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am more upset than anyone,'' Lewis's trainer said. ``It
looked like Evander was working as a sparring partner. Except he
got paid $20 million (to Lewis's $9 million). It was not even a
close fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will try to say that's just boxing. No! No! It's
disgusting. Those judges should never be allowed to work again. It
was a plain robbery. There should be a federal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed a bit strong, but there is much bitterness and ill
will between Steward, Holyfield's former trainer, and the World
Boxing Association-International Boxing Federation champion's camp,
so what was more telling were the calmer words of Don Turner,
Holyfield's chief second and true believer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox was only interested in outpointing Evander,'' Turner
said. ``He sacrificed his punching power to become elusive and he
did a good job. I was surprised by that. If there's a rematch,
Evander is smart enough to know he has to fight a different fight.
He has to apply more pressure next time. He's got to put leather on
the guy for the guy to respect him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was definitely close. I thought we won the last four
rounds to win the fight, but I'm not complaining about the
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   I would think not if he had eyes in his head, which apparently
at least one judge didn't. Williams would later claim she saw
Holyfield ``land more blows.'' According to CompuBox's numbers, he
not only didn't do that, he landed fewer total punches than Lewis
landed jabs.
</P>
<P>
   Often in matters of controversy in boxing, it is wise to use the
eye test when all else fails, meaning just look at the two men
after the fight and adjust your thinking if necessary. Lewis came
into the postfight press conference wearing sunglasses in the dark
but otherwise seemed fit. Holyfield came in with a face that looked
like it should have been in granite guarding the top of some
European castle.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's smile was gone. Now he was a gargoyle, his left
cheek cut and swollen, both eyes puffy and half-closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was 65 years old tonight,'' said Lou Duva, Holyfield's
first professional trainer. ``Look at his face. He's dying up
there. I know that kid. He's hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   Today so is boxing.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents of the IBF, WBA and WBC Sunday ordered a rematch
within six months. But who knows what will happen then, as based on
Saturday night neither man is what he claims to be. Holyfield
looked old and far off his game from the opening bell, unable to
figure out how to get inside Lewis's half-foot reach advantage and
land the explosive combinations that long have been his trademark.
He lacked rhythm, timing, quickness, and combination punching, all
signs of aging.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was equally disappointing despite his victory. Although he
controlled the action with his ring generalship, it was harmless
ring generalship, dominance without doing much with it. When he had
Holyfield in big trouble in the fifth round after landing a
crushing right hand that staggered the champion, he did nothing to
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Lennox won big,'' said veteran trainer Angelo
Dundee. ``That was a bum decision. You know, it says in the Bible,
Forgive them for they know not what they do. And those guys didn't
know what in the hell they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Lennox turns me off. He don't give you nothing. He don't
give you 100 percent. He should have destroyed Holyfield.''
</P>
<P>
   He should have because in front of him stood a great fighter
finally spent, his tank empty after a lifetime battling men like
Lewis, bigger, stronger men. Holyfield was a warrior to the end,
but the end it was. Had Lewis tried to make that obvious, there
might be no controversy. But he didn't, so when it was time to say
``and the winner is . . . '' everyone came up losers. Especially
boxing itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
