<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS IN HOLDING PATTERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins woke up Monday morning in sole possession of
eighth place in the Eastern Conference. But not by much.
</P>
<P>
   They have made it easy on themselves at times this year. At
others, they have made it tough.
</P>
<P>
   With 16 games to go in the regular season, the Bruins have a
couple of days off before facing the Conference's fourth-place team
_ the Toronto Maple Leafs _ Wednesday at the new Air Canada Centre.
While the Bruins are holding on to their position by a thread (they
have 68 points to Florida's 67), the fact is, their schedule is
favorable in their quest for a playoff spot. Of the remaining
games, 13 of the 16 are against conference opponents. That may
sound intimidating, but the Bruins are in the position they said
they wanted to be in all along _ in control of their destiny. Are
things desperate? Definitely. But it's always better to be
desperate against teams against whom you can make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend was a rather strange one. Against the Rangers Friday
night, the Bruins were where they wanted to be after two periods _
in a 1-1 tie. Some seven goals later, in a manic third, the Bruins
were fortunate to come out of Madison Square Garden with a 5-4 win.
</P>
<P>
   Against Buffalo Saturday night, the Bruins seemed to have just
enough energy to stave off the Sabres for two periods. But then
that reserve dried up and halfway through the third it was a 3-1
Buffalo lead and the Bruins looked as if they had run out of gas.
It was hard after the Bruins' huge win against the Rangers to
recover from that high.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 4-point game,'' said goalie Byron Dafoe, who is without any
doubt the Bruins' most valuable player this season, ``that was a
pretty devastating loss for the Rangers. I don't know what that
does to their psyche going down the stretch now, but the bottom
line was it uplifted us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not enough to beat the Sabres, but the Sabres have been
unforgiving opponents for the Bruins all year.
</P>
<P>
   The very best news for the Bruins is that their second line,
much maligned early in the year and changed during the season, has
been a contributing factor to their success recently.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Thornton has been absolutely remarkable in his progress,
using his strength, puck-handling savvy, and ultra long reach to
help Anson Carter and Steve Heinze find their spotty scoring touch.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a roller-coaster season for Boston. The Bruins' win
over the Rangers Friday helped them recover from the disappointment
of their loss to New York at home the previous weekend. Then their
loss to Buffalo Saturday mitigated their enthusiasm for having
dealt the Rangers a near death blow on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere was somber last weekend,'' said Carter. ``Now
you see guys with heads up and chests pumped out and feeling good
about themselves. That's important.''
</P>
<P>
   All that after the all-important Friday win. Despite their
happiness at beating the Rangers in the most unconventional and
un-Bruin way possible, Heinze said sometimes you just have to
accept what is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the polar opposite of what we wanted to do, it was
river hockey _ up and down, not enough defense, and just exactly
what we didn't want to do _ but fortunately we came out with a
win,'' said Heinze. ``The positive in that game was we scored a
bunch of goals but the negative was we didn't play anywhere near
what we wanted to defensively. For us to be successful through this
stretch and through the playoffs, it's going to be defense. It's
not going to be opening up the wide-open game.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss to the Sabres, with 16 games left, the Bruins
are still only 5 points out of the seventh spot. Not long ago, the
Bruins would've been thrilled to just hang on to eighth. Even given
Saturday's result, seventh isn't out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the teams above you, and you start to get a little
more positive, like let's chase these guys instead of looking over
your shoulder,'' said Heinze.
</P>
<P>
   The chase continues Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
