<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0380 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-15 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHOENIX _ The NFL expansion committee seems to be feverishly
working on a plan similar to Bob McNair's recent ``win-win''
proposition for getting NFL teams into both Houston and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It's called the Heads We Win, Tails You Lose Proposal.
</P>
<P>
   It's based on the principle of two birds in the bush being worth
more than one in the hand. It's buying the sizzle and tossing the
steak into the alley. It's putting off until tomorrow what could be
done today.
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue is selling it, and a significant
number of NFL owners continue to buy it. It should be McNair's cue
to walk away from Tagliabue's game and start playing by a different
set of rules.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon could have _ should have, by reasonable
standards _ been McNair's day to cash in on a long, well-played
hand of the NFL's expansion game. The last two cards McNair flipped
over on the table for the NFL expansion committee looked like sure
winners.
</P>
<P>
   After months of playing nice, looking owners in the eyes,
answering all the questions and laying out his cards perfectly
while Los Angeles floundered in search of direction, McNair
announced his win-win plan.
</P>
<P>
   He penned letters to at least eight teams that are looking for
better stadium deals. McNair offered to buy controlling interest in
any of those teams if their stadium issues were not resolved and an
expansion team was not awarded to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The win-win plan seemed perfect for the league, because teams
currently hoping for better stadium deals _ San Francisco, Chicago,
Oakland, Philadelphia, Indianapolis, New England, Buffalo and
Phoenix _ could use McNair's offer as leverage in their
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   If only one of those teams' negotiations fell apart, Houston
still could get an NFL team and the league could acquire the
much-coveted Los Angeles market through expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Then late last week, McNair flipped over the apparent clinching
card, a shrewd guarantee that Houston would sell out every home
game for at least five years if a team arrived. It also seemed like
a perfect play for the league, guaranteeing Houston's formidable
television market even if LA viewers greeted expansion with a
collective ho-hum, as some believe they will.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final card McNair could play. It was smart, proper,
impressive and within the rules Tagliabue and the league set. It
should have had McNair raking the chips off the table when the
expansion committee swung open its doors Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, Tagliabue and a contingent of NFL owners continued
to fall for LA's bluff _ that somehow governmental support would
fall in line in Los Angeles and somehow one ownership group would
surface as a leader, even as a third group from Anaheim entered the
fray Sunday by delivering proposals to owners here.
</P>
<P>
   When the brief expansion committee meeting broke up Sunday,
owners emerged from behind the velvet ropes with gray faces and the
company line on their lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in discussions,'' Tampa Bay owner Malcolm Glazer
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible,'' New York Giants owner Wellington Mara
said.
</P>
<P>
   The clear message was that the NFL is prepared to extend the
deadline yet again for Los Angeles, still hoping that it gets its
bid together. One scenario had the deadline extended another 10
months, which would push up against the Jan. 31, 2000, deadline the
Houston group set. Then, if Los Angeles still is not prepared to
trump Houston, the expansion franchise would go to McNair.
</P>
<P>
   But how much longer can McNair sit at the table with all his
cards perfectly laid out, while Tagliabue and the expansion
committee keep pulling aces out of their sleeves and passing them
to LA under the table? How much longer can the Houston Livestock
Show &AMP; Rodeo wait for the new NFL stadium before it scoffs at it
all and takes a chunk of the $195 million in the Houston bid and
refurbishes the Astrodome?
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk the league has (with extending the deadline) is they
could lose Houston and still not have everything settled in Los
Angeles,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners indicated the expansion committee will award the
franchise to Los Angeles this week no matter McNair's apparent
winning hand. Others said they did not expect any decision about
expansion this week.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for McNair to leave this game and stretch his legs.
Walk over to Jim Irsay and talk about the Colts. Visit with New
England's Bob Kraft or Phoenix's Bill Bidwill and make an offer.
</P>
<P>
   McNair certainly is thinking about it and said as much in the
wake of Sunday's foot-dragging by the expansion committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're available,'' he said. ``We can tell (owners), `If you
can't work something out, we'd like to talk to you.' I'm a
businessman. I try to always have options.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair went to Kansas City last October and wowed owners with
his proposal. He later went to the NFL meetings in Miami and did
the same. He is here. The two leaders of the LA cause, Ed Roski and
Michael Ovitz, are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is ready,'' said San Diego owner Alex Spanos, one of
Houston's expansion supporters. ``Houston is there with everything
we need. We don't have to ask Houston for anything. As owners, we
want LA to take the lead, but they haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair has given the NFL a win-win proposal that could put teams
in two of the biggest markets. He has guaranteed sellouts. He has
played by Tagliabue's rules, but Tagliabue keeps changing them.
</P>
<P>
   It's time McNair makes his own and goes shopping for the team he
deserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
