<HEADER>
A0381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAAEASTANALYSIS-     03-15 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEET - AND SOUR - 16 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Perhaps you couldn't tell the players without a
scorecard, but that wouldn't have been nearly sufficient to
identify the winners and losers who emerged from Boston's maiden
venture as a college basketball mecca.
</P>
<P>
   More than two Sweet 16 berths were at stake during the three-day
NCAA East Regional trial at the FleetCenter. Reputations, futures,
and public perceptions also were on the line, and one had to delve
far beyond the box scores for a legitimate retrospective.
</P>
<P>
   Herewith 16 random winners and losers after the weekend festival
on Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   --The FleetCenter wasn't merely a winner; it flat out hit the
jackpot in its bid to establish itself as a viable venue for
national events. Despite rotten weather Friday; doomsday forecasts
for even worse conditions Sunday night; the construction jungle
created by the Big Dig and the hotel being built in front of the
Fleet that turned the North Station area into a navigational
nightmare; and the utter lack of signage around the city
advertising the games, all sessions were sellouts. And not just in
terms of the tickets but the turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly impressive was the crowd for Friday afternoon's
opening session, a legitimate capacity gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just incredible,'' said Big East commissioner Mike
Tranghese, the NCAA basketball representative at the site. ``A lot
of times, you sell the tickets for the afternoon games but you
don't fill the seats.''
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese, an ardent proponent of the Fleet's big-event
potential, was virtually delirious with delight, believing the
weekend's developments can only enhance the arena's candidacy for
future men's regionals and the 2004 women's basketball Final Four,
for which Boston has bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is going to send a strong message to the NCAA,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   --Making Boston's performance even more remarkable were the
aforementioned traffic congestion and construction quagmire,
definite losers. But the hotel should be completed long before the
2004 Final Four, and the Big Dig can't last forever _ can it?
</P>
<P>
   --Perhaps the biggest loser on the court was George Mason
forward George Evans. The Colonial Athletic Association Player of
the Year shot 0 for 6 in a scoreless disaster as George Mason was
decimated, 72-48, by Cincinnati in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   --Temple guard Quincy Wadley was a winner, if for no other
reason than his powers of persuasion. Despite a broken left hand,
he somehow talked autocratic Owls coach John Chaney into letting
him play. After a cameo in Temple's opening 61-54 win over Kent, he
contributed 14 invaluable points off the bench Sunday as the Owls
shocked Boston co-favorite Cincinnati, 64-54.
</P>
<P>
   --Temple's zone defense was a winner. It flummoxed both
overmatched Kent and highly favored Cincinnati, solidifying
Chaney's coaching credentials, not that they needed it.
</P>
<P>
   --College basketball's supposed marksmen were losers, mainly
because just about everybody with the exception of Miami's Johnny
Hemsley (9 for 12 on 3-pointers, 31 points in the first round),
Cincinnati's Kenyon Martin (7 for 9 Sunday), and Purdue's Brian
Cardinal (5 for 7, 4 for 5 on threes Sunday) lost sight of the
basket. It was as if the Curse of Boston Garden had been placed on
the parquet. The nadir had to be the very first half of the
weekend, in which George Mason turned in a 5-for-31 eyesore.
</P>
<P>
   --The underwriters of the eight schools' insurance policies for
cheerleaders must be financial winners. Talk about high-risk
extracurricular activities: During every timeout, at least one
cheerleader per team was launched to about the same altitude as the
average space shuttle, doing midair triple spins for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   --The FleetCenter hot dogs, as toasty as an Alaskan winter
night, were losers, except possibly for gastroenterologists.
</P>
<P>
   --Sartorially, Kent stole the show. The Golden Flashes' golden
ensembles were beautiful to behold, in direct contrast to their
play.
</P>
<P>
   --In the individual fashion category, the award went to
Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins. His black-on-black ensemble,
color-coordinated with his hair, was slickness personified, though
it reflected the look of a Las Vegas lounge singer more than a
Midwestern mentor. And it was the perfect funereal statement after
the Bearcats' second-round nosedive.
</P>
<P>
   --Lafayette's basketball team was a winner even in losing. The
scrappy Leopards, making their first NCAA appearance in 42 years
and seeded 15th and last in Boston, gave this subregional's top
dog, Miami, a scare for one half and turned in a credible effort
despite losing Friday, 76-54.
</P>
<P>
   --Lafayette's royal rooters, the Zoo Crew, were vocal losers.
Their harassment of Hemsley went beyond protocol, and the constant
salute ``Hemsley sucks'' was a model of poor taste. Back to your
cages, Zoo Crew.
</P>
<P>
   --Purdue reserve Cameron Stephens was the most irresisitible
winner _ the underdog who makes good. His last-second jumper beat
Texas, 58-54, Friday in the regional's most dramatic game.
</P>
<P>
   --Conversely, Texas was a loser, killing itself with 22
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   --Purdue coach Gene Keady was a winner. Aside from salvaging a
season pocked by turmoil with the pair of upsets here, he showed
that the term scholar-athlete isn't necessarily lip service. As is
his habit when visiting an unfamiliar city, Keady took his players
on a tour of Boston, paying particular attention to the JFK Library
and the USS Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   --The loser among tourists was Purdue guard Jaraan Carroll. He
was limited in his sightseeing because he took the team nickname,
Boilermakers, a bit too literally. ``I couldn't get around much,''
he said, ``because of a boil on my foot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
