<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0383 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-CINCINNATI-BOS &LR;      03-15 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CINCINNATI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEARCATS NOT SCARY AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They came into the NCAA Tournament as the Only Team
That Beat Duke, but that's not the label that will stick to
Cincinnati after the Bearcats were bounced in the second round for
the third straight year, this time by Temple, 64-54.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read about it coming in _ one and done _ and they were
right,'' said junior college transfer Pete Mickeal, whose teams at
Indian Halls (Iowa) Community College were 76-1, won back-to-back
national championships, and never had a season end as abruptly as
this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about our reputation, but it's hard to live with
losing. Some guys, it means that it hurts for awhile. Not with me.
Every day I'm alive, I live with it, I walk around with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Melvin Levett lived through the previous two
ousters, when Cincinnati lost by a point to Iowa State in the
Midwest Regional in 1997, then was beaten by a buzzer-beating bank
shot by West Virginia last year in the West Regional in Boise,
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Levett said, it was supposed to be different. The
madness wasn't supposed to end until April, with a Final Four date
and possible rematch with Duke in Florida. It wasn't supposed to
end with Levett missing shot after shot over the Temple zone,
especially in the first half, when the Bearcats made just two
baskets in the first 14 minutes while turning the ball over seven
times.
</P>
<P>
   For the game, Levett made just 4 of 13 shots, 2 of 10 from
3-point range, and didn't make his first 3-pointer until there were
five minutes left and Temple had long since beaten back
Cincinnati's one charge into contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came into the gym this morning, we shot for an hour and
I think I missed four shots,'' Levett said. ``Then to go out and
shoot the ball like that in the game . . . That's just typical of
how I've been, on and off the whole season.''
</P>
<P>
   Only twice this season did Cincinnati score fewer points than it
did Sunday, and its 34.7 percent shooting (17 of 49) from the floor
ranked with its worst efforts of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't make shots, we just don't have many perimeter
shooters,'' Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins said. ``If we have open
shots and don't make them, we struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   A telling stat about the Bearcats this season: In games in which
they scored 60 points or more, they were 23-0. In games in which
they were held under 60, they were just 4-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this game was going to be tough,'' Levett said. ``Our
shots were the key, rebounding was the key. We didn't get second or
third shots, while they had five shots on just one possession.''
</P>
<P>
   Huggins's teams are known for their swagger, their belief that
they can intimidate teams into submission. But it became obvious
early that in Temple, the Bearcats were dealing with a team that
feared its own coach (John Chaney) more than anything the
opposition could throw at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let them take the fight to us,'' said Mickeal, who sounded
mystified by the notion. ``The first time down the floor, they
backed it in (a Kevin Lyde layin), and then they did it again (a
Rasheed Brokenborough layup, followed by a short-range jumper by
Lamont Barnes). You can't let a team get that kind of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, after falling behind by as many as 16 (29-13) late in the
first half, Cincinnati drew to within 35-29 on two Mickeal free
throws with 12:59 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we should have jumped on them,'' Levett said.
``They were tired, they were ready to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Temple's Quincy Wadley responded with a 3-pointer from
the left wing, the Bearcats misfired, and the Owls parlayed three
offensive rebounds into a Keaton Sanders layin. Suddenly, the
Temple lead was 11 again, and the Bearcats never drew closer than 7
the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Huggins, who has taken his team to the Final Four once in 10
years, took exception to the idea that this team had underachieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about that,'' he said. ``We're going to take a
week off, take two weeks off, take finals, have a spring break, and
then go back to work like we always do.''
</P>
<P>
   But for senior Levett, there is no more work to be done at
Cincinnati, not on the basketball court. Underachievers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' he said. ``This isn't how it was supposed to
end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
