u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEMPLE-CINCINNATI     03-15 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEMPLE-CINCINNATI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE SPELLS DOOM FOR CINCINNATI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL VEGA 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It had all the makings of a bare-knuckled, schoolyard
brawl.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner was Cincinnati, which had an unmistakeable swagger
and aura of toughness and confidence after the Bearcats
accomplished a feat matched by no other team _ a victory over Duke.
</P>
<P>
   In the other corner was feisty Temple, whose unrelenting matchup
zone defense and opportunistic offense reflected the tenacity of
its beloved coach, John Chaney.
</P>
<P>
   All that was missing from the opening tap was Michael Buffer
bellowing his trademark command, ``LET'S GET READY TO
RUUUUUMMMBLE!''
</P>
<P>
   To be succint: Temple answered the bell, racing to a 21-8 lead
after the first 6:27; Cincinnati did not, converting just 2 of 14
field goal attempts while committing seven of its 16 turnovers in
the first 14:19.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the sixth-seeded Owls (23-10) earned their first
Sweet 16 berth in six years _ and fourth overall under Chaney _
with an old-fashioned schoolyard whuppin' of the third-seeded
Bearcats, 64-54, in Sunday's NCAA East Regional second-round
matchup before a sellout crowd at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Although Temple suffered losses in its two previous NCAA
matchups with Cincinnati at Salt Lake City in 1995 (77-71) and at
Orlando in 1996 (78-65), the Owls gave no indication that they
would back down, let alone buckle at the knees, from yet another
physical confrontation with the Bearcats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you guys were to draw from your own backgrounds, how many
times did you go to the schoolyard and know that dangerous Dan
McGrew was out there with the rest of them guys, ready to take your
ball, kick you in the ass, and send you home?'' Chaney said,
painting quite the metaphorical image. ``It didn't stop you from
going to the playground. You found motives to go out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys would take my ball every day and I'd go back with a
tennis ball. I didn't give a (expletive). It didn't matter to me.
When kids go out and play, they don't worry about what the pundits
or the talkin' heads talk about, they just go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely what Chaney's Owls did. They just went out
and played. Without fear. Without apprehension. They just played
hard. They played tough. And, above all else, the Owls played
intelligently on all fronts by outshooting, outrebounding, and
outhustling Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Temple converted 20 of 45 shots while using a fierce matchup
zone that created 16 turnovers (10 steals) and held the Bearcats to
17-for-49 shooting. Temple won the rebounding battle, too, 32-31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug ourselves a hole that we had a hard time getting out
of,'' said Cincinnati coach Bob Huggins, whose team (27-6) looked
less like the one that beat the Blue Devils and more like the one
that suffered Conference USA losses to Marquette and Saint Louis in
making a second-round NCAA Tournament exit for the third year in a
row. ``Our whole deal coming in was that we had to do a better job
on the glass, both offensive and defensive glass. They beat us on
the offensive glass early. They made shots and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior forward Lamont Barnes led the Owls with 15 points on
5-for-8 shooting, hitting an improbable baseline skyhook in the
second half that extended Temple's 29-18 halftime lead to 31-18,
and grabbing three of his team's 32 rebounds. Junior guard Pepe
Sanchez added 14 points, hitting 9 of 10 from the foul line, and
had 7 rebounds, 4 steals, and 2 assists. Junior guard Quincy Wadley
came off the bench to chip in 14 points, hitting a huge trey in the
second half that enabled Temple to pull away, 38-29, after
Cincinnati pulled within 35-29 on a pair of Pete Mickeal free
throws with 12:59 to go.
</P>
<P>
   With Sanchez, Mark Karcher, and Rasheed Brokenborough each
nursing three fouls apiece, that proved to be the only point during
the game when it got truly dicey for the Owls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like coach always tells us, `Your will is always stronger than
your skill,' '' said Brokenborough. ``They tried to beat us
athletically and weren't using their heads in trying to attack and
beat our zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon Martin led the Bearcats with 16 points and eight rebounds
while guards Melvin Levett and Steve Logan overcame a combined
1-for-7 start to finish with 14 and 13 points, respectively. After
the Owls twice led by 16 (51-35 and 57-41), Cincinnati twice cut it
to 7 (59-52 and 61-54). But Temple, despite making only two field
goals in the final 8:10, won this battle of wills by making 15 of
its last 20 free throws to win going away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't about who's the toughest; it's about who wants to
win,'' Martin said, through eyes reddened by tears. ``It ain't
about who's the toughest. If that was the case, we'd just put on
the gloves and see who's the toughest. But it's not a boxing match,
it's a basketball game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
