<HEADER>
A0385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PURDUE-CARDINAL-B     03-15 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PURDUE-CARDINAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL'S RULE: INTENSITY WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With his high-top black-and-white sneakers, bulky back
knee pads, and gymnasium pallor, Brian Cardinal looks as if he
stepped out of a 1920s daguerrotype of Indiana basketball.
</P>
<P>
   All right, so he grew up in Illinois, dreamed of playing for the
Illini, and we're on the verge of the millennium. Let's not get too
technical. With his throwback look and style to match, this kid was
born to play in the state that is the game's cradle. And Sunday he
showed why as he basically willed 10th-seeded Purdue past second
seed Miami, 73-63, in the NCAA East Regional second round and on to
the Sweet 16 _ a most unlikely destination for a team that came
into the FleetCenter having lost five of its previous six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd told me a week ago I was going to the Sweet 16,''
said the 6-foot-7-inch junior forward, ``I'd want to know where I
was sitting, because I sure didn't think we'd get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal will be on the floor in the East semifinals against
Temple at the Meadowlands Friday in large part because that's where
he spent most of his time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, his statistics stood out: 20 points on 5-for-7
shooting, including 4 for 5 behind the 3-point line; 6 rebounds; 4
steals; and 2 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as anything, it was his kamikaze intensity that
embodied the Boilermakers' scrape-and-burn style, an admittedly
ragged production that did the trick because it harassed normally
cool Miami into a battle in the muck.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal was at the center of virtually every scrum, slipping,
sliding, crawling, brawling for every loose ball, wrestling for
every rebound. In particular, he was on Tim James, the Big East
co-Player of the Year, like a brace _ and not the type the Miami
forward needed for his aching back. James wound up with 19 points
but shot only 7 for 21 and grabbed a mere eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too smooth out there,'' said Cardinal. ``I wear these
goofy-looking knee pads, and I just go out and try to play hard, do
the things guys don't like to do _ take charges, dive for loose
balls, contest for rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to say it was the defense that stopped James (instead
of the bad back), but I don't know. We tried to take him and them
out of doing some things defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't get the misimpression that Cardinal was a mere
spiritual presence. He filled the box score with some vital bursts.
</P>
<P>
   His two 3-pointers keyed a 15-0 Purdue run that ended the first
half, boosted the Boilermaker advantage to 32-17, and, as Cardinal
said, ``put all the pressure on Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, when Miami responded to that pressure to
close within 43-38, Cardinal did his major damage within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had the Hurricanes' Vernon Jennings driven for a scoop
than Cardinal was taking a pass on the wing from Tony Mayfield and
nailing a trey. Seconds after that, Mayfield stole the ball and fed
Cardinal for a layup that restored the double-digit spread, 48-38.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Gene Keady) always talks about how there are going to
be runs during any game, times when things are not going well,''
said Cardinal. ``It was great the way we responded each time. I got
set up for a couple of open looks in the first half, then I was
lucky enough to hit a three and Tony made the great steal in the
second.''
</P>
<P>
   The coup de grace came at the foul line during the interminable
finish, and Cardinal _ whose father was the Illinois basketball
trainer and who figured he was destined for Champaign until Keady
persuaded him to cross state lines _ did his part, hitting six of
eight free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time to savor the victory, though not necessarily to
rest. As Cardinal went to sit at his locker, a television crew
requested that he stay on his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want me to stand?'' said Cardinal. ``You guys are killing
me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the only time he stood still all day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
