<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIAMI-BOS &LR;      03-15 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING BLOWS HURRICANES OFF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ If Sunday was the first time you'd seen the Miami
Hurricanes, you might have wondered why they bothered to reinstate
the basketball program 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd been watching them all season, you must have thought
this was their evil twin.
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Hurricanes _ the top seed to play this weekend
in Boston _ dropped a giant stinkbomb at the FleetCenter, falling,
73-63, to No. 10 seed Purdue. Senior Tim James said the team wanted
to use this weekend's two games to show all of America that it
could play with anyone. In the end, Miami showed it could beat
dreaded Lafayette. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with these rather telling tidbits: Miami never led.
Miami scored 17 points in the first half. Miami took twice as many
shots as Purdue (76-38) and still lost. Miami shot 6 of 33 in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   The 63 points represented the Hurricanes' third-lowest output of
the season. After knocking down 10 treys against Lafayette, they
made only one Sunday, an inconsequential one with 1:37 remaining.
Inside, they missed layup after layup _ coach Leonard Hamilton
counted 17 of them _ which took a little out of them as the game
progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those games where nothing went right,'' Hamilton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point probably came in the final 5:17 of the first
half. Miami, by then already into its bricklaying mode, managed a
7-0 run to tie the game at 17-17. The Hurricanes then pitched a
shutout for the rest of the half while Purdue scored 15 in a row.
Hamilton saw his team turn it over five times in that stretch, made
seven substitutions to no avail, and watched incredulously as his
team misfired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't finish our plays, for some reason,'' James said.
``It's no one's fault. We just didn't do it. We had a bad night.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, proud Purdue coach Gene Keady beamed ``we had nine
shutouts (possessions) in a row at the end of the half.''
</P>
<P>
   By this time, it also was clear that Miami guard Johnny Hemsley
was not going to duplicate his dismantling of Lafayette, against
whom he made 9 of 12 treys Friday. He ended up scoring 13 points,
but had just 5 at the break and only a single field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue's Alan Eldridge played Hemsley airtight all afternoon.
Miami expected that after the Lafayette game. So the game plan was
to drive to the basket and get the ball into the post, where James
had made a comfortable living all season.
</P>
<P>
   But James had no more luck than Hemsley. He was 3 for 9 in the
first half and 7 for 21 in the game. He was hampered by a sore
back, but Hamilton refused to use that, or anything else, as an
excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a situation where your team gets 27 offensive
rebounds and can't put any of them back in,'' the coach said. In
truth, he exaggerated a little; the Hurricanes were credited with
16 second-chance points. But those who saw the game knew exactly
what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the horrible first half, Hamilton felt his team
would respond in the second. They had trailed UConn by 16 and won
that one, hadn't they? And Purdue wasn't UConn. Unfortunately for
Hamilton, Miami wasn't Miami, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes' last chance came after they rallied to within
43-38 with 11:06 left. A minute later, the lead was back to 12 on 7
unanswered Purdue points.
</P>
<P>
   That was it, really. The Miami numbers were much better in the
second half, but it couldn't afford to match baskets with the
Boilermakers. Purdue attempted only 16 shots in the half and didn't
make a field goal in the final 7:34. It didn't matter. Miami had to
foul _ Purdue took 32 of its 37 free throws in the second half, 18
in the final 2:10.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Miami, they made their shots when it mattered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
