<HEADER>
A0387 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN     03-15 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS FALL TO KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Their starting point guard was lost to injury,
their thuggish rebounder is just plain lost and now the Los Angeles
Lakers have a very clear reminder of what losing feels like.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels strange,'' Shaquille O'Neal said Sunday night after a
stunning 105-101 loss to the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis put it more bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate losing. Losing sucks,'' he said . ``I hated losing as a
player, I hate it as a coach. It's a horrible, rotten feeling. This
is a three-hour sleep night for me.''
</P>
<P>
   If the reaction is extreme, it's only because the Lakers hadn't
felt the sting in a while, since Feb. 22. And Rambis hadn't felt
one period since becoming the coach.
</P>
<P>
   But the team's 10-game winning streak, and Rambis' heretofore
perfect 9-0 record, came to a sudden halt in the face of the Kings'
back-breaking fast break, led by rookie point guard phenom Jason
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, better known as ``White Chocolate,'' gave the Lakers a
taste of what they missed _ the team coveted him on draft day _ and
they came away with a decidedly sour taste in their mouths after
watching him score a team-high 21 points, nine in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also led a transition attack the Lakers never matched,
leading to 25 fast-break points for the Kings, who ended a losing
streak to the Lakers at 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the made-over Kings, with Williams, Vlade Divac and
Chris Webber (19 points, 11 rebounds) aren't talented, but they are
the same folks who donated a victory to the Clippers just three
nights earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could have used the defensive intensity of Dennis
Rodman, taking a leave of absence, and Derek Harper (sprained
ankle), against Webber and Williams, but Rambis waved off such
suggestions as ``excuses.'' He pinned the loss on another party.
Himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost because of my inexperience as a head coach,'' he said.
``It was my fault. I wasn't able to deliver the things we needed to
do late in the ballgame. I wasn't able to get the team to do what I
wanted it to do. We didn't execute the plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make myself clear, I guess, to run the plays I wanted
to get done. I didn't use my timeouts to get the players to foul
whenever they had to. And that's my job as a coach to make sure
they understand all that.''
</P>
<P>
   After a mea culpa like that, you'd hate to think what a losing
streak, or a .500 record, would do to the rookie head coach.
Rambis' martyrdom notwithstanding, this game was lost by lax
defense.
</P>
<P>
   With the Kings running at will, Sacramento took a five-point
halftime lead and extended it to 10 by late in the third quarter.
The Lakers cut the deficit to four early in the fourth period, then
succumbed to Sacramento's perimeter shooting. The Kings went on a
15-6 run, sparked by 3-pointers from Vernon Maxwell and Peja
Stojakovic, and six points by Williams, making it 99-86 with 5:56
left to play.
</P>
<P>
   Even a 10-point quarter from Kobe Bryant fell short of bringing
the Lakers back. His late burst of five straight points cut the
deficit to 99-94 and the Lakers eventually got within three. But
they were forced to foul down the stretch and Williams made 3 of 4
free throws to seal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't play hard,'' said O'Neal, who scored a
game-high 33 points and rejected Rambis' mea culpas. The loss, he
said, ``was our fault.''
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, mitigating factors. Without Harper, Derek
Fisher was forced to play 37 minutes, Bryant 43 minutes as he
started at off guard and backed up at point. Glen Rice, hardly
acclimated to the team and playing his second game in 10 months,
played 29 minutes and missed 8 of 12 shots. Rick Fox was pressed
into shooting-guard duty.
</P>
<P>
   It all combined for a less-than-efficient defensive effort. And
a loss that suddenly reminded everyone that changing coaches and
adding All-Stars hasn't made everything perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does leave a nasty taste in your mouth,'' Fox said of the
defeat, ``especially after being so dominant for a while there.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, said O'Neal, ``Ten of 11 games, I'll take that any
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0137EST &QL; 
