<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-HARVARD-RPI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD BOUNCED BY RPI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ The third period often has been Harvard's best,
with its superior conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Against Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute before 3,117 at the
Houston Field House Sunday &UR;  &LR; night in the third game of the Eastern
Collegiate Athletic Conference quarterfinals, the teams were even
at 2 entering the final 20 minutes. So Harvard had a good feeling.
</P>
<P>
   But it was RPI that came up with two goals in the final period,
the first at 6:57 by Doug Shepherd and the other by Brad Tapper at
13:37. That gave the Engineers a 4-2 lead that they held on to, and
they will play St. Lawrence Friday in the semifinals in Lake
Placid, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard-fought series with three very good games,'' said
Harvard coach Ronn Tomassoni, whose team finished with a 14-16-2
record (8-13-2 in the league). ``We kind of shot ourselves in the
foot, with sloppy play in the third period, and it (directly led
to) a couple of goals. We hadn't done that all week long. When you
give a team like RPI chances like that, they can really be
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   RPI, which finished third in the regular season, just wanted to
keep firing in the third period. ``Harvard did a great job of
packing it in around their goalie (Oliver Jonas),'' said RPI coach
Dan Fridgen. ``We had to shoot through three players to get it to
him. Harvard did a real nice job of keeping its turnovers low
throughout the series.''
</P>
<P>
   In getting the lead for RPI (22-11-2, 14-7-2), Shepherd
registered his ninth goal. He was wide open along the right side
and took a slow wrist shot. On the fourth goal Tapper blasted one
from the right side to give the Engineers plenty of comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``RPI didn't beat us with any of their moves, they just got the
bounces,'' said Harvard captain Craig Adams. ``We played
outstanding, though. It was probably the best three games that
we've played all season. It wasn't perfect, but I was happy with
the way we played. We played our system, we were disciplined. Plus,
we held a high-scoring team down in goals. We just didn't take
advantage of the chances we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomassoni was delighted with the effort of his team, which
finished eighth in the regular season. ``Everyone chipped in,
everyone doing the little things,'' he said. ``We were playing like
a team. We came together. We felt pretty good going into the third
period with it tied. RPI probably didn't feel quite as comfortable,
as the team that was favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our opportunities in the third period,'' he added.
``Our guys played hard and played well, showing a lot of heart. You
look at the start of the season (2-8-1) and compare it to the way
we finished (8-4-1 in their last 13).''
</P>
<P>
   Jonas was outstanding in stepping in for J.R. Prestifilippo
(separated shoulder), finishing with 28 saves, 12 in the second
period. ``Oliver hadn't played in a month, and there was quite a
bit of pressure on him,'' Tomassoni said. ``He did an outstanding
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonas didn't want to hear it. ``You lose, so there's no way that
you can be happy,'' the sophomore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKC-BOSTONUNIVERSITY-     03-15 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVIDENCE SENDS BU PACKING 
</HEADLINE>
 UNIVERSITY-PROVIDENCE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ Just when it was beginning to seem Boston
University might regroup and return to the FleetCenter for the
semifinals of the Hockey East playoffs, Providence sent the
Terriers on to spring break instead.
</P>
<P>
   The Friars built a 2-0 lead in the first period and took it from
there to a 5-1 victory Sunday &UR;  &LR; night before 1,832 at Schneider
Arena in the deciding game of their three-game quarterfinal series.
The victory, which completed Providence's 5-1 domination of the
season series with BU, set up a semifinal matchup Friday against
No. 1 seed New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The other semifinal pits Boston College against Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The Friars are in the semifinals for the first time in three
years. For the Terriers (14-20-3), the defeat gave Jack Parker his
second 20-loss season in his 26 years as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   The teams had split 8-2 decisions Friday and Saturday at
Schneider. The Friars (20-16-1) had won the opener with a
third-period spurt, and the Terriers had returned the favor on the
strength of a second-period outburst. Sunday &UR;  &LR; night the Friars took
charge in the first period, building a 13-4 edge in shots.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pooley, who guided the Friars to the championship of Hockey
East in his second season in 1995-96, said he was proud of the way
his defense played. ``Tonight our guys were stoked up,'' he said.
``Give our seniors a lot of credit. They came through tonight,
big-time. We were 3 for 5 on the power play, and I'm sure that's
what Jack will say was their downfall.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Parker, ``Power plays really killed us tonight.
They have the best power play in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his Terriers were 0 for 16 in the series with the man
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   After a wide open stretch during which referee Ned Bunyon let
the teams play freely, the Friars moved to a 1-0 lead when Doug
Sheppard deflected Jason Ialongo's shot past goaltender Michel
Larocque on a power play at 15:58 of the first.
</P>
<P>
   The next time the Friars were on a power play, Jon Cameron
followed two shots by Jon Coe and put the puck in the net at 17:22.
</P>
<P>
   Providence built the lead to 3-0 in the second period when
defenseman Josh MacNevin's shot from just inside the blue line went
in at the 14:42 mark. The Friars had a 12-3 edge in shots in the
period _ they were warming up to face the Wildcats. They beat UNH,
6-1, Nov. 6, then lost a 3-1 decision in Durham the next night, and
were beaten, 4-2, in Durham Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The third period was more of the same, as the Friars extended
their lead. Nick Lent, a junior out of Westwood, Mass., who played
for the Omaha Lancers in the US Hockey League, stole the puck and
went in on a breakaway to register a goal at 11:30.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Lake made it 5-0 at 12:12 to send the crowd into ecstacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Terriers avoided the shutout when defenseman Pat Aufiero's
shot trickled past goaltender Boyd Ballard with just 3:26 remaining
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Laracque finished with 27 saves, Ballard 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran us out of the building,'' said Parker. ``Physically.
Emotionally. Effort-wise. They played unbelievably hard tonight,
and we had no answer for it. We had just four shots in the first
period and two in the second. It was a great disappointment, but it
was because of how hard Providence played.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for Providence, we'd be an over-.500 club and
we'd still be playing. They beat us five out of six times this
season. That's a feather in their cap. They really showed up. They
dominated us, and they dominated us in an area we could not seem to
solve all year. That was power play and penalty kills.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the less-than-stellar season, Parker said, ``We were picked
to be fourth. We ended up fifth. Nobody expected us to win the
Beanpot. We realy improved as the year went on. I think our
freshman class really came along. It was disappointing we reverted
back (Sundya night) to the less-than-competitive nature we showed
at times this year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
