<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE AWAITS EASY-GOING BC
</HEADLINE>
 COLLEGE-TENNESSEE-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The Boston College women's basketball team
was still riding a wave of euphoria Sunday. It was just hours after
the Eagles had defeated Ohio State to advance to the second round
of the NCAA Tournament, and they had a day off until their next
game.
</P>
<P>
   The opponent _ Tennessee _ is not someone they want to spend a
lot of time dwelling on. So after practicing for an hour and a
half, the players headed back to their hotel to have a team meal
and go out to a movie. For one day, they figured, Tennessee could
wait.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, though, comes the moment of truth. The game that
will be on ESPN at 9:30 p.m. pits the eighth-seeded Eagles (22-7)
against the No. 1 seeded Lady Vols (29-2) in the teams' first
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the Yankees, or the UCLA men's basketball team of the
1960s and early '70s, and that's what this Tennessee team is to
women's basketball. The Lady Vols, ranked No. 2 in the nation, are
not simply the defending NCAA champions _ they are the three-time
defending champs. Three of their players _ Chamique Holdsclaw,
Tamika Catchings, and Semeka Randall _ last week were named
All-Americans. The team's average margin of victory this season was
27 points.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any glimmer of hope for BC, it's that Tennessee will
be without Randall, who suffered a severe ankle sprain in
Saturday's 113-54 win over Appalachian State. She's undergoing
icing and physical therapy with the hope of joining the team for
later games.
</P>
<P>
   Randall is Tennessee's third-leading scorer (14 points per game)
behind Holdsclaw (20.9) and Catchings (16.8).
</P>
<P>
   But BC coach Cathy Inglese said that Randall's absence is hardly
a consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to see anybody, rival team or not, get injured,
especially at this time of year, when it's supposed to be the
dessert of the season,'' she said. ``But Tennessee is not a
one-player team. She's a vital part, but they have so many other
key parts and play so well together. Tennessee is a program, it's a
team, it's not one individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Randall in the backcourt, Tennessee coach Pat Summitt
said she'll call on sophomore Kristen Clement to start, and use
junior Niya Butts off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Summitt, who watched BC's win over Ohio State Saturday night,
said she was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to come out and apply pressure to the
guards, or they'll have a field day,'' she said. ``And they do an
excellent job of handling and passing the basketball. Their
high-low game was textbook at times with how they executed and got
the ball inside.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's starting backcourt of Alissa Murphy (22 points) and Brianne
Stepherson (11) accounted for more than half their team's points.
</P>
<P>
   When they take the court Monday night, both BC and Tennessee
will carry with them memories of big games this season. For BC, it
will be upsets of nationally-ranked Notre Dame and Connecticut. But
for Tennessee, it will be losses to Purdue and Louisiana State.
</P>
<P>
   Summitt said her team has to be reminded of those games so the
Lady Vols don't think that they will just roll over their opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've been in that situation twice this year in which
we had slow starts, we got behind, we did not come with the type of
attitude and intensity that was needed,'' Summitt said. ``And if
that happens, we look real average or way below average.''
</P>
<P>
   Summitt also said she realizes that her team can bring out the
best in its opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that BC is thinking, `Hey, we have nothing to
lose, let's play hard, let's play loose, and in the end let's go
and beat Tennessee,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds good to BC senior forward Paula Bacso.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to lose, so we can just relax and play our
game,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
