<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-XAVIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN SURVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ Down by 10 points early in the second half and
by 6 with 2:40 to play, top-seeded Connecticut dug deep to score
the last 8 points of its NCAA Mideast Regional second-round game
against No. 8 seed Xavier, the final 2 coming on a pair of Tamika
Williams free throws with 7.1 seconds left to pull out a pulsating
86-84 victory Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the freshman center/forward from Dayton, Ohio, will be
returning to her home state next weekend when the Huskies (28-4)
take on Iowa State Friday in the Sweet 16 at Cincinnati, but for
most of the second half, it looked as if Xavier would be the team
returning triumphantly to its home city.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's freebies marked the first time the Huskies had led in
the second half _ and since they had taken a 20-17 lead in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Williams stepped to the line after teammate Shea Ralph had
missed an off-balance leaner and Amy Duran kept the ball alive with
a putback that caromed back to Williams. Xavier point guard Nikki
Kremer, who had gone 8 for 8 at the free throw line before missing
a pair of foul shots on her team's previous possession, fouled
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to stay settled,'' said Williams, who led UConn
with 19 points, 11 in the second half, 8 in the final 7:02. ``Coach
(Geno Auriemma) told me (during a timeout) that `You're going to
make one, then you're going to make two. A lot of things were going
through my head. I just took the deep breaths and tried to follow
through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They gained a lot of confidence against us early and we got a
little frustrated,'' said Auriemma. ``I'm just proud of our guys.
That was a pretty gutty performance at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   It all began to unravel for Xavier (24-9) after a Kim Hotz layup
had given the Musketeers the 84-78 lead.
</P>
<P>
   A Williams putback was followed by an Xavier turnover when
Kremer couldn't penetrate the lane. UConn's Asjha Jones countered
with an in-the-paint hoop, then Xavier was called for a backcourt
violation. Svetlana Abrosimova tied the game with a minute to go on
a twisting layup and then Williams was called for the foul as she
tried to tie up Kremer.
</P>
<P>
   Kremer went to the line, missed both, and UConn called time with
28.6 seconds to go as the crowd of 10,027 at Gampel Pavilion went
ballistic, but that was just a prelude for the wild finish that
kept the fans on their feet long after the game had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who led all players with nine rebounds, six on the
offensive glass, credited Ralph and Doran with heads-up plays at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shea had to create something and it was a great effort by Amy
to keep the ball alive,'' said Williams. ``I've never been in a
situation like tonight where I've been on the line with a chance to
win the game for my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Xavier coach Melanie Balcomb, who once coached against UConn
counterpart Auriemma when she was an assistant at Providence, tried
to downplay the significance of the partisan crowd prior to the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went down to Virginia Tech to play in front of 9,700
people, and yeah, we lost,'' said Balcomb, ``but we won 90 percent
of the game (a reference to Xavier's 61-60 defeat). Our players
aren't thinking about the crowd, they are thinking about UConn _ we
play them, not the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Xavier did tune out the crowd for most of the game, but crucial
turnovers and missed free throws ended any hopes of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``UConn turned up the pressure at the end of the game and we did
not execute,'' lamented Balcomb. ``This is a tough way to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The gallant Kremer, a Cincinnati native who had 17 first-half
points, said that ``those free throws will be with me for a while.
But I wanted to be the one to shoot them.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was another Ohioan who made the difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
