<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER TAKES SONICS FOR RIDE PAST CLIPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sonics coach Paul Westphal insisted before Sunday's
game that he saw a different look in Vin Baker's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   When Westphal further contended that his struggling star forward
had found his comfort zone, he probably didn't realize the accuracy
of his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much that Baker had his second straight solid
outing, finishing with 23 points and a game-high eight rebounds
that helped the Sonics defeat the Los Angeles Clippers 108-89 at
KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   It happened to be the first time all season that Baker's
confidence matched his strong play.
</P>
<P>
   According to Baker, his parents had everything to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   Since their arrival in town Friday morning, Baker said he's
found more solace in two days than he's had all of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very close to my parents,'' said Baker, whose mother,
Jean, and father, James, are visiting Seattle for the first time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having them here is kind of helping me relax a little bit. My
mom is cooking and watching NCAA (tournament) games with me. And my
dad is just telling me to pray.''
</P>
<P>
   It's almost too bad the Sonics didn't think of flying out the
Bakers a lot sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Baker and the team believe this is the perfect time
to put past struggles behind them.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (11-9) snapped a two-game home losing streak in
winning their second straight game after losing five in a row. And
the schedule should provide the Sonics with a bit more relief and a
chance to string together several victories.
</P>
<P>
   They host Vancouver tomorrow before visiting Golden State and
Denver this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   This is equally as important a stretch for Baker, who for the
first time this season has two straight solid performances under
his belt. He looked impressive scoring 18 points on 7-of-17
shooting during a win at Chicago last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Vin Baker is all the way back,'' Westphal said. ``He
had a great game against Chicago, and everybody pretty much sensed
that he was going to play like Vin Baker is used to playing. Then
tonight, he backed it up, and it makes a big difference for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker's influence on the game was evident by the Sonics'
fluidness on offense.
</P>
<P>
   With Baker powering to the basket nearly every time he touched
the ball, the Sonics' outside shooters were rewarded with open
looks. As a result, the Sonics shot 56.8 percent _ their best
shooting percentage this season.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton's 28 points and 11 assists paced the Sonics. Dale
Ellis, who started in place of an injured Billy Owens, finished
with 17. All five starters scored in double figure, and Detlef
Schrempf chipped in 12 points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need inside presence,'' Schrempf said. ``Not many teams can
win consistently (shooting) from the outside. Vin is it. He's our
low-post guy. When he plays like he did today, it makes it easier
for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker seemed to have everything working for him. He even made
seven straight free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not worried about making your free throws, you're
a little bit more aggressive offensively. I wasn't worried about
getting in the paint,'' Baker said. ``I kind of wanted to go to the
line. I'm going to look to be aggressive. . . . This was the first
game that I felt like I had everything going.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're down there's only one way out, and that's to be
aggressive. My confidence is back. . . . I don't care if it's the
Clippers or anyone else, there's no one person who can hold me.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their 1-19 record, the Clippers had not been pushovers
the past week. They beat Sacramento for their first victory last
Thursday. Portland needed overtime to dispose of the Clippers on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the fourth quarter that the Sonics managed to
build more than an eight-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics led 77-75 at the start of the final period when they
pulled away for good. Payton scored four quick points, then after
Baker sank a pair of free throws, Hersey Hawkins went to work.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins buried a 3-pointer and followed that with a fastbreak
layup off a steal. The sequence capped an 11-4 run and put the
Sonics ahead 88-79 with 8:41 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics blew the game open with a 25-10 run down the stretch.
The Sonics outscored the Clippers 31-14 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the Sonics' biggest lead was 50-42 a few minutes
before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't nervous,'' Westphal said. ``I felt like it was
a good challenge for us to take the game. . . . It was a nice day
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   By the look on Baker's face, it was a great day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
