</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, March 15.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-CHINA-MILITARY (Undated) _ The revelation that China
appears to have stolen the design of America's most advanced
miniaturized warhead has prompted new debate in Washington over
whether China's small nuclear force could become a far more potent
arsenal that could rekindle the kind of fears that shaped the cold
war. By David E. Sanger and Erik Eckholm. With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MILITARY-REACT (WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's national
security adviser, Sandy Berger, acknowledged Sunday that ``there's
no question'' that China benefited from obtaining the design of
America's most miniaturized nuclear warhead from the Los Alamos
National Laboratory. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Washington) _ American officials expect little
from the latest round of talks over Kosovo. The talks are scheduled
to start in Paris on Monday. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-UNCERTAINTY (Istanbul, Turkey) _ With a national election
approaching, Parliament in open rebellion against the political
establishment, murderous terror attacks being launched against
civilians and the trial of a hated Kurdish guerrilla leader
approaching, Turkey suddenly finds itself facing deep
uncertainties. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ENTREPRENEURS (Beijing) _ Sitting under stirring
photographs of the young Mao Tse-tung, Chen Jinfei relaxes in the
plush 35th-floor offices of his billion dollar corporation and
reflects on the love-hate relationship between China's Communist
government and private businessmen like himself, who have helped
pushed China's economy forward. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-MASSACRES (Shanker Bigha, India) _ A massacre here of farm
workers and their families _ untouchables at the bottom of
Hinduism's hierarchical social order _ was numbingly similar to
dozens of others committed over nearly three decades in the eastern
state of Bihar. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-LAFONTAINE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Oskar Lafontaine, who
threw the German government into turmoil on Thursday by quitting as
both finance minister and as chairman of the ruling political
party, ended three days of silence Sunday with a thinly veiled
attack on Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. By Edward L. Andres.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-OSHA-WHISTLEBLOWERS (Washington) _ After finding that
workers who complain of health and safety hazards are often
dismissed from their jobs, the Clinton administration will soon
propose sweeping new protections for such ``whistleblowers.''
Republicans are receptive to the idea. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TWO-SLAYINGS (New York) _ They did not know each other, but
Amy Watkins and Marvin Watson were both young archetypes of the New
York newcomer. She was the Midwest idealist come to the big city,
he was the striver from Jamaica. Both were stabbed to death in
Brooklyn this year, and while Ms. Watkins' death has attracted
national attention, Watson died anonymously. Yet if both killings
were treated differently, they each touch on fears held deeply by
many New Yorkers, even as crime has fallen in the city. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN-FISH (Conneaut, Ohio) _ Jim Anthony himself is not
exactly sure why he kept a blue pike in his freezer for 37 years,
but now, nearly four decades later, the fish has become the central
clue in a compelling scientific detective story, sleuthing that
some scientists are hoping will lead to an extraordinary result:
the return of an extinct species. By Pam Belluck. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-COMPUTER-INJURY (Undated) _ There is widespread concern
among physicians, physical therapists and ergonomists that a tide
of injury is inevitable as youngsters spend more time on computers,
both at school and at home. By Jane Gross. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-PRISON-REPORT (Undated) _ The Justice Department, in a
report released Sunday, said the number of American adults in
prison has more than doubled over the past 12 years, reaching its
highest level ever last year. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Austin, Texas) _ Rushing to fill in his blank slate
on pressing issues of the day before the presidential campaign
swings into full gear, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas has embarked on
a cram course that could be titled ``What you need to know to run
for president.'' Richard L. Berke with Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   CASPIAN-ARMY (Washington) _ In its search to remain prepared in
today's ever unsettled, rapidly changing world, the Army has a
notion at least of the type of messy international mission its
forces may well have to face in the years ahead: protecting Caspian
Sea oil. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-REFORM (Fort Irwin, Calif.) A decade after the end of the
Cold War and eight years after the heady triumph of Desert Storm,
the units that come to this sprawling desert base take on an
opposing force designed to look like some Warsaw Pact behemoth. It
is an enemy no one expects them to face, in terrain no one expects
them to encounter, with tactics no one is certain will prevail in
the future. Facing that reality, the Army is now moving to change
the way it organizes its units and trains them to fight. By Steven
Lee Myers. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-FED-DEATH (New York) _ When Tabitha Walrond, a
19-year-old welfare recipient, gave birth to her first child, she
did what new mothers rich and poor are urged to do these days: She
breast-fed her baby. But her two-month-old son died in her arms of
malnutrition. And Ms. Walrond is now charged with recklessly
causing the death by failing to nourish her son adequately and by
failing to obtain prompt medical attention when his condition
became dire. By Nina Bernstein. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PARADE-GAYS (New York) _ The first St. Patrick's Day parade
in the Bronx in 70 years has, in the last few days, become
embroiled in the same political turmoil over gay marchers that has
troubled the St. Patrick's Day parade in Manhattan since 1991. By
Katherine E. Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (Moved in ``w'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TERM-LIMIT-ENFORCER (Washington) _ As a Libertarian with
attitude, Paul Jacob is simply not going to let House members
forget their ballyhooed term-limit promises of the Contract With
America class of 1994. By Francis X. Clines. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
