<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTR-WASHCOL-SOUTHEAST-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS STRIVE TO OUTCLASS DEMS ON EDUCATION  
 TOUGH LUCK  
 STATES' RIGHTS (AND WRONGS)  
 DEAN'S LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.C., Ala., La.)  (Eds: This is Southern Exposure, a Southeast-oriented weekly
political notebook from the Washington Bureau of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.) (js) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ed Flex is a hot topic on Capitol Hill these days,
but that isn't the name of a new member of Congress. It is
congressional shorthand for the educational flexibility bill at the
center of a political fight as Democrats and Republicans try to
outdo one another on school issues.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to score points on a subject traditionally dominated by
Democrats, Republicans are aggressively pushing an education
agenda, trying to one-up their rivals on an issue that resonates
with parents. But Democrats will not cede ground willingly as a
recent congressional debate illustrates.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans trumpeted the Education Flexibility Partnership Act,
a bill that would give local school districts greater freedom to
determine how to spend federal education money. They figure that's
a better message to sell to voters than earlier attempts to abolish
the federal Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local schools do more when Washington bureaucracies do less,
and that is what this bill does,'' declared Sen. Connie Mack,
R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many Democrats support the idea of more flexibility
for schools, they're not making it easy for Republicans. In both
the House and Senate, Democrats tried unsuccessfully to broaden the
legislation, proposing, for example, that it provide for the hiring
of 100,000 new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Democrats joined Republicans to pass the initial
version of the bill, but more votes _ and skirmishes _ are likely
before the measure heads to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were clearly frustrated that Democrats didn't just
play along. ``This is a clean bill and it should be kept clean,''
said Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., said a provision for more teachers
was an essential part of any education bill, insisting that her
party only wanted to improve the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH LUCK
</P>
<P>
   Sweepstakes companies may have run out of luck on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Two days of hearings highlighted the misleading promotions
sweepstakes companies often engage in, sending out letters that
strongly suggest to unsuspecting recipients that they have already
won a fortune. The catch? Buy a magazine subscription.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that many consumers wind up with lots more to
read, but less money. And lawmakers said the elderly, who can be
more trusting and starved for attention, are frequently the victims
of such schemes, pouring their life savings into magazine
subscriptions and even traveling to pick up their non-existent
winnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal laws must be strengthened to prevent companies from
sending deceptive mailings, and to alert consumers that purchases
do not increase the likelihood they will win a major prize,'' said
Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   While executives from Publishers Clearing House, Reader's Digest
Association Inc., Time Inc., and American Family Enterprises
defended their practices as legitimate, lawmakers were skeptical
and promised tough new regulation of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   STATES' RIGHTS (AND WRONGS)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans love to talk about letting state and local
governments do their thing without any meddling from the federal
branch.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes an issue that hits close to home with a key GOP
constituency and, suddenly, federal action doesn't seem like such a
bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., recently introduced a bill that would
prohibit individual cities from filing some lawsuits against gun
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Five cities _ Atlanta, Chicago, Miami, New Orleans and
Bridgeport, Conn. - already sued gun manufacturers, arguing they
hold some liability for crimes committed with their weapons. The
National Rifle Association, which supports Barr's bill, believes
those lawsuits infringe on the Second Amendment right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Barr agreed. ``If we stand by idly while law-abiding firearms
manufacturers are systematically bankrupted by abusive legal
tactics, a disastrous precedent will be set,'' said Barr, who
described the lawsuits as a product of a ``unholy alliance''
between lawyers, mayors and anti-gun activists.
</P>
<P>
   DEAN'S LIST
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Republican Bob Livingston didn't just leave
the speaker's chair temporarily vacant; he was also the senior
member of the Louisiana House delegation. Now GOP Rep. Billy Tauzin
will fill that role and he wants the post to be more than simply
ceremonial.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Tauzin, a former Democrat now in his 11th term,
said the wheeling-and-dealing Cajun wants state lawmakers to think
more like a cohesive group and put their collective muscle behind
measures with Louisiana significance. Their first test could be a
proposal to return more offshore oil royalties to states that bear
the impact of the drilling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
