<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 03:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0429 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-SFCHR     03-15 2075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
  
 ANALYSIS: CLINTON PLAN FOR SOCIAL SECURITY MERELY SHUFFLES DEBT  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Seldom has any proposal been more technically
bewildering and tactically effective than President Clinton's plan
to rescue Social Security.
<P>
   Even Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan found himself
flummoxed trying to explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there's been an unfortunate set of _ well, I'll
say bookkeeping going on here, which _ let me see if I can clarify
exactly what is happening ...,'' Greenspan told a House
subcommittee early in March. He finally gave up, directing members
to some charts instead.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the plan looks simple: Clinton would devote 62
percent of the $4.5 trillion budget surplus projected over the next
15 years to help secure the retirement of the 76-million-member
Baby Boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   In one fell swoop, Clinton seems to address a problem that has
bedeviled armies of analysts and politicians for years, while
avoiding every painful or controversial measure _ from raising
payroll taxes to cutting benefits to making a transition to a
funded system _ that most experts thought were unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans found themselves outfoxed yet again, forced to agree
that they, too, want to devote the surpluses to America's favorite
federal program. Their hopes for huge tax cuts were quashed.
</P>
<P>
   But if saving Social Security was this easy, why didn't anyone
think of it before? Through a year of White House forums on Social
Security reform, attended by Clinton himself, nothing resembling
his plan ever came up.
</P>
<P>
   Why? As U.S. Comptroller General David M. Walker bluntly put it
in a report, the Clinton proposal ``does not represent a Social
Security reform plan'' and ``does not have any effect on the
projected cash flow imbalance'' in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Experts widely agree that the plan would not ``save'' Social
Security. Although White House officials say their proposal would
extend its solvency to the middle of the next century _ by adding
an astounding $2.8 trillion to its trust fund _ they concede that
the plan would not extend by even one day the critical date 14
years from now when the program runs short of cash to pay benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The plan adopts such a novel approach that it took budget
experts a while to figure it out, but most agree that it boils down
to an accounting illusion. ``It's not as if it's doing anything
real,'' said Jagadeesh cq  &LR; Gokhale, a Federal Reserve Bank of
Cleveland economist.
</P>
<P>
   At its core, Clinton's plan would devote 62 percent of the huge
budget surpluses to rescue Social Security. As it turns out, the
surpluses are irrelevant to his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president chooses to equate the (money going to Social
Security) to 62 percent of the projected surplus,'' said former
Congressional Budget Office director Rudolph Penner. ``But he could
as easily equate it to 62 percent of the average temperature in
March.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials concede that the plan would credit
Social Security with trillions of new dollars regardless of whether
surpluses materialize.
</P>
<P>
   The illusion of ``saving the surplus for Social Security'' stems
from the long-standing myth of the Social Security trust fund, a
myth that Republicans and Democrats alike have been happy to
propagate since the program began in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security payroll taxes are right now bringing in billions
more dollars than Social Security spends on benefits. That excess
is supposedly held in a ``trust fund'' to pay benefits to future
generations.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, there is nothing in the trust fund except government
debt. Congress has been spending the Social Security surplus for
years, and depositing bonds, or IOUs, in the trust fund. Although
the government will run a surplus this year of $107 billion, it's
actually a $7 billion deficit if excess Social Security money is
taken off the table.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the projected $4.5 trillion surplus will come
from excess Social Security payroll taxes. So when Clinton promises
to devote 62 percent of that surplus to Social Security, he is
simply using Social Security's own money to ``save'' Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those revenues will not be enough to prevent huge
shortfalls when Baby Boomers start retiring, so the administration
plan goes one step further.
</P>
<P>
   The plan takes the money that will accumulate from excess Social
Security payroll taxes _ $2.3 trillion _ and credits that to the
trust fund. It then turns around and says 62 percent of the entire
surplus _ including the Social Security money already counted _
will also be credited to Social Security _ another $2.8 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   But most of that money was already credited to the trust fund
the first time around. Clinton is crediting it again _ which is why
critics accuse Clinton of ``double counting'' the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Social Security trust fund gets a vast pool of
money _ $5.1 trillion in all _ that extends its solvency on paper
from 2033 to 2055.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, most of the 62 percent _ the extra $2.8 trillion
_ appears out of nowhere. By counting Social Security revenues
twice, the Clinton plan winds up with $5.1 trillion for Social
Security and $1.7 trillion for new spending _ a total of $6.8
trillion from a projected surplus of $4.5 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is creating money out of thin air,'' Penner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration budget chief Jack Yew disputed charges of
double-counting, saying Republicans wanted &LR;  to spend Social
Security surpluses on tax cuts. ``Suddenly, what we do is called
double counting,'' Yew said. ``That's a double-standard, not
double-counting.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, White House officials are correct. Congress has
been doing its own version of double counting for years by sending
paper bonds to the trust fund and spending payroll tax revenue for
other things.
</P>
<P>
   However, the administration proposes to take the practice to a
whole new level by crediting phantom money to the Social Security
trust fund to make it appear more solvent.
</P>
<P>
   As for the ``real'' surpluses _ the remaining 38 percent, or
$1.7 trillion _ that are expected outside of Social Security taxes,
Clinton would spend those on Medicare, the military and personal
savings accounts. ``None of the on-budget surplus is devoted to
Social Security, so you can't say you're improving Social
Security'' by using the surplus, said Gokhale, the Cleveland Fed
economist.
</P>
<P>
   The ``new money'' going to Social Security is simply a
bookkeeping credit of additional bonds to the trust fund. Adding
bonds _ which represent debt, or a promise to pay _ to the trust
fund does nothing to change the 2013 date when the hard cash coming
in from Social Security payroll taxes will no longer cover the hard
cash going out as benefit checks.
</P>
<P>
   That shortfall remains; Taxes will cover only about 75 percent
of benefits for future retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds have no real assets behind them, other than the
government's promise to redeem them. They are not cash. They are
debt, and for the government to come up with the cash to pay the
obligation they represent _ Social Security benefits _ it would
have to raise taxes or cut benefits or slash other spending. Those
are the same old ``hard choices'' that have haunted Social Security
all along.
</P>
<P>
   The administration concedes as much in its February budget.
``These (Social Security trust fund) balances are available to
finance future benefit payments ... but only in a bookkeeping
sense,'' the budget says on page 337. ``They do not consist of real
economic assets that can be drawn down in the future to fund
benefits. Instead, they are claims on the Treasury that, when
redeemed, will have to be financed by raising taxes, borrowing from
the public, or reducing benefits or other expenditures. The
existence of large trust fund balances, therefore, does not, by
itself, have any impact on the government's ability to pay
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is by adding trillions of dollars of paper IOUs to this
same trust fund that the administration claims to be shoring up
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the plan would just shuffle debt from one government
account to another, paying off Treasury bonds with one hand and
adding bonds to Social Security's trust fund with the other.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says the purpose of this accounting maneuver
is to ``hide'' some of the cash surplus, since politicians won't
raid anything earmarked for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   That way, the cash coming in will go to pay off the Treasury
debt. Then the nation will be in a better financial position in the
future when it needs to borrow to pay Social Security benefits.
``We're locking the surplus into debt reduction for Social
Security,'' Yew said.
</P>
<P>
   But all this would happen without Clinton's plan. Surpluses will
automatically go to retire government debt, without any new
accounting. Clinton would actually slow debt reduction because his
new spending eats up 38 percent of the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts question whether shuffling debt from the Treasury
to the Social Security trust fund serves any purpose. ``It doesn't
matter where the debt is held,'' Gokhale said. ``It still has to be
serviced.''
</P>
<P>
   All those IOUs sitting in Social Security's trust fund will
eventually come due, and the only way to pay them is to borrow,
raise taxes, cut spending or inflate them away. This is the vexing
core of Social Security's dilemma, and Clinton does not address it.
</P>
<P>
   What do Republicans have to say? Taken by surprise, they at
first just embraced Clinton's popular promise to save 62 percent of
future surpluses for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But that promise is as meaningless as Clinton's. So now the GOP
leadership has agreed to remove Social Security revenues from
surplus calculations and forgo tax cuts. That does nothing to save
Social Security, but it shields Republicans from accusations that
they are raiding the program.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond taking Social Security revenues off the table,
Republicans are afraid to move on actual reform. ``That's about as
far as we've gotten,'' said a Senate GOP aide.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans would like to adopt some form of private
individual accounts, allowing workers to invest a portion, say 2
percent, of their payroll taxes in their own Social Security
retirement accounts. They see this as a way to allow workers to
build wealth and start putting real assets into the system rather
than trust-fund bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Several moderate Democrats support the idea, including Sens. Bob
Kerrey of Nebraska, Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, and John
Breaux of Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Some plans would tap Social Security's surpluses to finance the
accounts. But that would still leave the program with a future cash
shortfall. Painful cost savings would be needed, from raising the
retirement age, to forcing state workers into Social Security, to
lifting the ceiling on income subject to payroll taxes, to reducing
the inflation measure that lifts benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big fault line in the Republican party right now is ...
can you do Social Security reform and not touch benefits ever,''
said Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa. ``Most of the Republicans would like
to say, `We don't want to touch benefits or raise taxes,' but I
don't know how you get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum said Republicans are scared that ``if they walk out and
do anything on benefits, they'll just get hammered.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats generally back Clinton's pain-free extension of the
trust fund's life. But they fear Clinton also may have created a
Trojan Horse for private accounts with two other ideas in his plan:
investing some Social Security money in the stock market and
``USA'' savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   With just this in mind, Republicans have mostly praised
Clinton's plan as a positive step that opens the debate on Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm emphasizing the things we're in sync on,'' said Rep. Jim
Kolbe, R-Ariz. ``He acknowledges there's a problem, acknowledges we
need to do something now and acknowledges that personal accounts
are feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, privatization advocates are counting on the
public never figuring out Clinton's plan. ``The public doesn't
understand the details, other than that the president said it was
OK to invest in the stock market and to have individual accounts,''
said Michael Tanner, head of the Cato Institute's project on Social
Security privatization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
