<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURNETT-BURNETT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Community Activist Offers High-Tech Help
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As one of Silicon Valley's pioneering computer scientists,
former Cisco Systems &UR;  &LR; executive Bob Burnett helped create the vast
network of technology &UR;  &LR; that links the world today.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Burnett is trying to help link networks of humans so that
they can better deal with the world's biggest technological
dilemma, the Year 2000 computer problem, which he also had a hand
in creating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're lucky, this is just going to be a blip,'' said
Burnett, who chairs a volunteer Year 2000 committee that is
advising the Berkeley city manager's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious problem, but it's something we can manage,'' he
said. ``But you have to hold everybody's feet to the fire.
Everybody's got to take it seriously, and there's got to be
critical oversight of every single public services provider.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett, 58, vice president of engineering for networking firm
Cisco from 1988 to 1991, brings a combination of high-tech
expertise and community activism &UR;  &LR; to the Y2K problem. The problem
stems from a programming shortcut that may cause computer systems
to misinterpret the year 2000 as the year 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett is credited with expanding the city of Berkeley's focus
from just fixing city computer systems to developing contingency
plans to deal with potential wider scale disruptions in power,
water and food supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking at the internal issues, but we weren't focused
on the broader issues until Bob approached us,'' said Deputy City
Manager Phil Kamlarz. ``He and his committee opened our eyes.'' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Burnett also has addressed the state Legislature about the need
to upgrade 911 emergency systems to make them Y2K ready and has
spoken to church and community groups to help prepare the city's
low-income, disabled and elderly residents.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Last month, Burnett was a featured speaker at a two-day
Oakland symposium that focused on getting neighborhoods and
communities prepared to help residents weather any Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to host a cable TV call-in show for Berkeley
residents called ``Y2K and Your PC'' scheduled for broadcast at 7
p.m. March 30 on the city's community access channel.
</P>
<P>
   Yet unlike the army of Y2K pundits and consultants who have
sprung from the woodwork lately, Burnett says he's not out to make
a name or a quick buck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a consultant; I don't have a book; I don't have a Web
site,'' Burnett said.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have to. Born in Hollywood, raised in Newport Beach,
educated at Stanford University and able to retire comfortably from
Cisco Systems at age 50, the Berkeley resident already is living
the California dream.
</P>
<P>
   He's a self-described ``Quaker pacifist'' who since his
retirement has devoted his time as a consultant to nonprofit groups
on projects that ``involve spirituality, philanthropy and social
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he chairs a West Berkeley youth center and served
on an Alameda County committee that reviewed ways to convert the
Alameda Naval Air Station for civilian use. He also co-chairs
Responsible Wealth, a group trying to raise awareness among
``wealthy individuals about the growing gap between the rich and
poor around us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett is not a newcomer to trying to fix the Year 2000
problem. And had the world's computer programmers heeded warnings
by Burnett and others in the mid-1960s, the only worry come New
Year's Eve might have been whether there was enough champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, data still was entered into computers on punch cards,
which because of tight space restrictions used only the last two
digits of a year. This assumed that the first two digits would
always be ``19.''
</P>
<P>
   As these programs began to be rewritten in the
computer-mainframe language COBOL in the mid-1960s, Burnett said he
and other members of the worldwide COBOL standards body
unsuccessfully tried to push for expanding the ``year'' field to
four digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other parts of the industry were basically opposed to this''
because it was too time-consuming, said Burnett, who was at the
time a software programmer and manager for computer-maker Burroughs
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said the U.S. Department of Defense, at a time
when the Cold War was hot, was concerned because ``they had this
huge body of code they would have to go in and change.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett went on to work for Stanford Research Institute,
Fairchild Semiconductor Corp. and IBM. He joined Cisco Systems in
1988 just when the company that makes equipment linking computer
networks was starting to take off.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, newer computer programs that replaced older ones
continued using only two-digit year fields.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Burnett got involved in the Year 2000 problem again
when he approached the Berkeley City Council offering his help in
assessing what the city and its residents face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that because of my experience, I know a lot about it
that can be helpful and I'm definitely not panicked about it,'' he
said. ``It's something we really need to take seriously, and I
think we're doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   His committee, which will issue a report to the council next
month, has surveyed the Y2K plans for services like PG&AMP;E, East Bay
Municipal Utilities District and BART.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Burnett said he's encouraged by the progress made by
companies and utilities so far in fixing the Y2K problem. Still, he
remains cautious because he knows from experience that now's not
the time to become complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the experience of doing very large systems
integrations,'' Burnett said. ``And even if everybody works
diligently, almost always there's some strange stuff that happens
because there are so many different parts that have to be
considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett tries to help residents who are panicked about Y2K, but
he says his wife, psychotherapist Kathy Barry, ``is better at
reassuring them than I.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
