<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 BioScope/Tom Abate  
 All-Day Party to Honor the Discovery That Launched Biotech 
 Revolution 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Roughly a thousand people turned out Saturday for an all-day
celebration held at the University of California at Berkeley to
commemorate the scientific discovery that launched the biotech
industry 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1974 that Stanford geneticist Stanley Cohen and UC San
Francisco biochemist Herbert W. Boyer discovered the technique for
snipping a strand of DNA from one organism and pasting it into
another organism. The process gave scientists a new way to create
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the early applications of this discovery was using
bacteria as a factory to grow human insulin for diabetics.
Previously, insulin for diabetes drugs came from pigs.
</P>
<P>
   Since its earliest days, the specter of cutting and splicing the
master code of life has caused both excitement and apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's event was billed as a chance to discuss not just the
scientific but the social, commercial and ethical dimensions of the
biotech revolution with a dozen distinguished speakers including
three Nobel laureates.
</P>
<P>
   The most informing and entertaining part of the day was the
early morning tutorial held by UC Berkeley extension lecturer
Desmond Mascarenhas. The biotech entrepreneur held a three-hour
lecture on the basics of DNA technology for about 400 people.
</P>
<P>
   Mascarenhas explained the Human Genome Project, an effort to map
all the information in human DNA, by comparing DNA to a cassette
tape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Like the tape, DNA is a long strand of information. And just
as a tape contains several songs, DNA is comprised of units, called
genes, that control various bodily processes from digesting food to
determining the color of a baby's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling tape from a cassette in his hand, Mascarenhas noted that
the pauses between songs are invisible to the eye. Yet they are
detectable by the playback head on the tape deck. In simple terms,
the Human Genome Project is trying to detect the start and stop
points of the roughly 100,000 genes in DNA. If scientists can
identify these genetic songs, perhaps they'll be able to do things
like turn off the genes that cause cancer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The audience more than doubled in size for the star-studded
afternoon session, which started with a keynote speech from James
Watson, who earned a 1962 Nobel Prize for his co-discovery of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Watson's speech was a disappointment. He has been one of the
main proponents of the federally funded Human Genome Project and
listeners had every reason to expect that he would explain the
importance of the endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Watson used his pulpit to deliver a rambling commentary
on his career, punctuated by slides picturing his many scientific
cronies.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the panel discussion showed only occasional signs of
life, despite the impressive array of speakers, which included
William Rutter, chairman of Chiron Corp., and Jay Michael Bishop,
chancellor of UCSF.
</P>
<P>
   One question from the audience that created a stir was whether
genetically engineered foods should be labelled as such.
</P>
<P>
   Labeling has been popular in Europe, but in the United States
(outside of Berkeley) it has not been much of an issue. While other
panelists equivocated, Watson delivered a flat no. Labeling, he
said ``caters to the people who cry wolf when there is no proof
that a wolf exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Paul Rabinow, a UC Berkeley sociologist who has studied
the biotech industry, delivered a provocative observation when he
challenged the underpinnings of bioethics. In the past two decades,
said Rabinow, the field of bioethics has arisen to tackle questions
raised by medical and biotech advances _ such as when to pull the
plug on brain-dead patients on respirators, or whether it is proper
to choose the sex of a baby during in vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   All very interesting issues, Rabinow said, particularly to the
lawyers, doctors and hospital administrators who make such
decisions _ not to mention the patients and families involved.
</P>
<P>
   But he suggested that bioethics has evaded other less-glamorous
but more important questions, such as why a society that is
spending billions to map the genome allows millions of people to go
without health insurance or the most rudimentary health care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
