<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-NET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ 
</HEADLINE>
 FILES _ SF CHRON   Web Cams on Campus _ Here's Looking At You, Kid 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Vince ``Vega'' Nicholas unabashedly offers virtual voyeurs a
glimpse into his dorm room at San Francisco State. He alternately
mugs at a Web camera and trades one-liners in an online chat area.
</P>
<P>
   A shameless exhibitionist? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   A self-promoter who was chosen to be a guinea pig for new Web
site  &LR; www.webdorm.com &LR;  that chronicles the lives of selected
college students a la MTV's ``The Real World''? Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Internet meets `The Real World' _ but without the
mandatory gay character,'' said Nicholas, 21, one of two dozen
college students nationwide who were picked to ``star'' on
WebDorm.com, a commercial Web site. ``People always bring up the
concern of being watched 24-7. I've heard the term Big Brother
being tossed around. But I think technology is something that
shouldn't be feared. It's cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 3,000 miles away, at the University of Miami, a freshman
named Diva smiles into the watchful eye of a Web camera. The gabby
Marin County native said she doesn't mind sharing her life with the
World Wide Web 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think they're my best friend, which is both
strange and cool. They ask me to smile and wave at the camera,''
said Diva, 19, who declined to give her full name. ``There are some
weirdos who want to get too friendly, but online chat is as
friendly as I'll get.''
</P>
<P>
   Since February, WebDorm has installed tiny spherical cameras in
dorm rooms across the country that transmit snapshots to its Web
site every 30 seconds. Typically, each participant is photographed
by a single, fixed camera that cannot be turned off. The WebDormers
_ who use aliases such as NeonQueen and Sassy _ chat online with
visitors, post their musings in journals and receive messages in a
``guest book'' area.
</P>
<P>
   WebDorm stems from the growing popularity of Web cameras, as
well as the widespread use of the Internet among the
twentysomething crowd, according to Alex Chriss, the 21-year-old
Marin resident and Tufts University senior who created WebDorm.
</P>
<P>
   His motivation _ besides signing up advertisers _ is to dispel
the stereotype of What he calls the ``lazy, party-animal'' college
coed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Hundreds of would-be WebDormers have filled out e-mail
questionnaires in hopes of being placed under a cyber microscope,
but only a few outgoing individuals have made the grade. Their
motivation isn't money _ the participants aren't paid though they
get to keep the $100 cameras after a semester _ but rather
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it's legal, anything goes,'' Chriss said. ``Someone
may occasionally moon the camera. This isn't scripted. It may be
boring, but sometimes college life can be boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on several days of viewing dorm rooms in California,
Florida, New England and the Great Lakes, &UR;  &LR; somnambulate might be
more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras, which typically are fixed on desks in empty rooms,
offer small, fuzzy pictures with no sound. When WebDormers are
present _ many of the New England students were on spring break
last week _ the chief form of communication is online chats that
consist of inane chatter about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   A typical exchange:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey (fill in the blank), wazzup?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much, bro. I'm hella tired. :-)''
</P>
<P>
   At least the characters from ``Seinfeld'' were funny when they
talked about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that hasn't stopped WebDorm from gaining a cult
following. ``It's somewhere to hang out and talk about college,''
said one self-admitted ``lurker,'' who asked not to be identified.
``I feel like I know them.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly a fourth of all adult cybersurfers in the United States
are college students, according to CollegeClub.com, a portal site
 &LR; in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``This site and the Web in general are natural ways for students
to interact outside the walls of college,'' said Clay Shirky,
professor of new media at Hunter College in New York. ``College
students have plenty of time, and university networks have plenty
of bandwidth.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of Web cameras to record mundane, day-to-day activities
isn't new. Jennifer ( &LR; www.jennicam.com &LR; ), a 22-year-old free-lance
Web site designer, has chosen to be under the virtual surveillance
of four cameras for nearly three years from her Washington, D.C.,
apartment. The site requires a $15 annual subscription to view.
</P>
<P>
   And various campuses, including Stanford University, have Web
cams set up in public locales such as a dorm lounge or cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  WebDorm is taking a slightly different approach, however. It
is presenting a sort of online episodic TV show patterned after
``The Real World,'' which documented the angst-ridden travails of a
group of twentysomethings for several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like watching the show `Friends' and after the episode,
chatting live with Jennifer Aniston or Courtney Cox,'' said Farhan
Memon, co-founder of Yack.com, an online viewing guide in
Emeryville, who has viewed WebDorm. &UR;  &LR; ``The interactive element of
WebDorm makes this more than voyeurism; it is interactive
voyeurism. This transcends normal programming and becomes an
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't so sure. They ar &LR; gue that WebDorm is the type of
navel-gazing, narcissistic Web site that glorifies vanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to the limits of living vicariously; it's the
height of visceral experiences,'' said Elizabeth Ferrarini, author
of ``Confessions of an Infomaniac.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if we see an explosion of pay-for-view
porn sites like these,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It is an alarmist view that San Francisco State's Nicholas
shares, up to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``WebDorm is pretty much built on trust and good people sharing
a service, like eBay,'' Nicholas said. ``Maybe if this gets bigger,
the weirdos and stalkers will come out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, it's cool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PLAY BALL!  &QL; 
The first pitch of the 1999 baseball season is three weeks away,
but purists already have begun poring over player rosters in
anticipation of their rotisserie drafts. Although there are several
excellent fantasy-league sites, we suggest two _
 &LR; fantasy.yahoo.com/baseball/  &LR; and  &LR; www.rotonews.com &LR;  _ to get you
in the swing of things. Both pack a Sosa-esque blast, and they're
free.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SITES OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Because readers responded so enthusiasticly to last week's
Hampster Dance site, here are a few more Monday-morning
brighteners. Check out  &LR; www.en.com/users/felion &LR;   &LR; /funstuff.html
 &LR; and &LR;  www.angelfire.com/id/hern/ &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
