<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 03:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0433 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EGGHEAD-EGGHEAD_SFCHR     03-15 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGGHEAD-EGGHEAD </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Egghead Ads Marry Web, TV Technologies
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
There has been a lot of talk about the marketing potential of
``convergence'' between television and the Internet _ but not much
to show for it. The concept becomes more meaningful today, however,
with the airing on cable channel ZDTV of an apparently ordinary
commercial for computer and software merchant Egghead.com.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second spot, which will promote a monitor and two
computers being sold via Egghead.com's auction site, employs a
melding of Web and TV technologies that allows the ad to be altered
just minutes before airtime.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, Egghead sends product information and images from
its Web site over the Internet to ZDTV, or ZDTV can take the data
directly from Egghead's site. The Web content is converted into a
television-friendly signal and plugged into a template that
resembles the Egghead site. The whole package is then served up as
an ad _ completely bypassing the cumbersome and expensive use of
videotape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  This process, which takes less than five minutes, will allow
Egghead to show the highest customer bid on each product in
mid-auction, &UR;  &LR; a feature that is expected to drive impulse shoppers
to the site in search of that $96 printer or $1,200 laptop.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, created by New York agency Digital Pulp, display a
changing selection of products. Initially the spots will only say
``Bids start $1,'' but after some practice runs, they will show
actual bids.
</P>
<P>
   The technique lets Egghead staff decide at the last minute which
products to peddle in the ad. That's important because demand for
the high-tech gizmos on Egghead's auction can be volatile, moving
up or down appreciably in just a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional TV ads typically take weeks or months to create and
distribute. Even a simple Web banner ad can take up to two weeks to
get out the door, said John Brodeur, Egghead's chief marketing
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that one day, memory (products are) really hot,''
said Brodeur. ``If the prices are going up and we have a lot in
stock, we can let people know they can get a great deal. Or we
might just have a great buy on some off-price IBM desktop computers
that we just purchased that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Being able to off-load new merchandise before taking possession
of it will save Egghead the expense of shipping and storing it,
Brodeur added. Instead, Egghead's supplier often will be able to &LR; 
 &LR; ship purchases directly to the winning bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the absolute ultimate in latitude,'' said Brodeur,
whose site is the Web's ninth-most visited shopping destination,
according to Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Egghead intends to run 12 of these ``live-content'' ads each
day through the end of 1999 _ an unusually long run considering
that ad campaigns normally last just two or three months. The
e-commerce site Onsale has purchased air time for similar ads,
according to ZDTV.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a similar 30-second spot on video would ``easily take
four hours'' of work in an expensive production facility and then
would have to be physically distributed, said Dave Seedall, ZDTV
vice president of engineering and operations, who developed the
live-content process over about a month.
</P>
<P>
   Simply aiming a TV camera at a computer monitor displaying the
Egghead site doesn't work because the images and text don't show up
clearly.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Groft, corporate media director for the San Francisco
advertising agency Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney, said the new technology is
beneficial but limited.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, ZDTV, a 24-hour channel dedicated to computer
news that was launched last year by magazine publisher Ziff-Davis,
reaches only 10 million households, compared with nearly 100
million for a national network.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the technique is best suited for advertising ``a very
targeted product to a very targeted consumer,'' Groft said. ``It
would work best for a limited-time product or excess inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   Ad executive Ed Dilworth sees the live-content ads as an interim
step on the way to true convergence, which is more likely to be
seen on WebTV or direct (satellite) TV rather than a cable operator
like ZDTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it could work in the future is, for example, I'm
watching a basketball game, and while I'm watching, I can click to
order tickets or buy a jersey,'' said Dilworth, chief executive of
San Francisco's Arnold Ingalls Moranville.
</P>
<P>
   ``ZDTV's application sounds interesting, but it's only a step in
the ultimate direction,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
