A0434 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OXYGEN-OXYGEN_SFCHRON     03-15 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OXYGEN-OXYGEN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Project Oxygen May Blow Away Web Speeds
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Neil Tagare is the Don Quixote of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Crisscrossing the globe, the 37-year-old telecommunications
expert is proposing what many consider unfathomable: A $10 billion,
100,000-mile worldwide network that he claims will be up to 5.5
million times faster than the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Internet to flourish, it needs to become as
ubiquitous, fast and reliable as the phone system,'' Tagare said.
``Slow (transmission) speeds are deterring its growth among many
users and companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Project Oxygen ( &LR; www.oxygen.org &LR; ) _ a commercial venture that
hopes to leapfrog the nonprofit Internet2 _ would pump video, sound
and data at neck-snapping speed to users in 78 countries. The
underwater network of fiber-optic cables will traverse the Atlantic
and Pacific oceans by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I call the project Oxygen because, like air, it is something
you have to have to live,'' Tagare said in a phone interview last
week from Bermuda, where Project Oxygen Ltd. is headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   Tagare is pursuing funding from private investors and bank
loans. His small organization has deals with 40 telecom carriers,
including Global Crossing Ltd. of Beverly Hills, who have bought
into the network. Lehman Brothers Inc. is Project Oxygen's
financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most mind-boggling, ambitious online project yet, and
it has exciting possibilities,'' said Greg Wood, spokesman for
Internet2 in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggest Tagare's plan is too mind-blowing and that the
former Nynex executive is flailing at high-tech windmills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things that can go wrong,'' said analyst
Abhi Chaki of Jupiter Communications in New York. ``First, you have
to raise a lot of money and sign landing contracts with about 100
countries. Then, you have to complete undersea construction. Once
you've done all that, you have to keep the network up and running
at a high level.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Dave Howard, chief engineer of Project Oxygen, admits, ``We
have a huge undertaking that encompasses all types of technology,
different companies and various cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the payoff is enormous,'' Howard adds. ``Eventually, every
consumer on the planet will use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Against stiff odds, Tagare created a global network once before.
</P>
<P>
   FLAG (Fiber-Optic Link Around the Globe), completed in 1996,
transmits vast amounts of data over high-speed phone lines directly
from Europe to the Far East. FLAG was the first privately funded
undersea telecom system. With the financial assistance of Nynex and
Tagare's persistence, the $1.6 billion project took seven and a
half years to construct.
</P>
<P>
   Project Oxygen will take nearly as long to build.
</P>
<P>
   Launched in mid-1997, it will undergo several phases before it
is completed in early 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The first stage, linking 20 countries that stretch from the
United States to the United Kingdom and Germany, will be completed
in six months at a hefty price tag of $3 billion. Tagare said he
already has raised $1.8 billion of that from investors, loans and
corporate sponsors such as Lucent, Pacific Telesis, Japan's NEC and
France's Alcatel.
</P>
<P>
   Once the pipeline is in place, the Oxygen organization hopes to
sell space on its network to telecommunications carriers,
corporations, broadcasters and Internet service providers (and
ultimately, consumers). Project Oxygen would be responsible for
maintaining the network.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Oxygen will ``allow anyone _ large corporation, cable
operator, Internet service provider _ to participate in the world's
fastest Internet service,'' Tagare said. ``It is not an exclusive
club for universities and selected companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The subtle dig is at Internet2, a coalition of universities and
high-tech companies formed in late 1996. Last month, it flipped the
switch on a key segment of its private research network that
connects 70 college campuses. The nonprofit organization includes
Stanford University, the University of California at Berkeley and
Harvard University, as well as major corporate sponsors Cisco
Systems, IBM, Qwest Communications and Nortel.
</P>
<P>
   The 13,000-mile Internet2 network is up to 45,000 times faster
than the commercial Web, but it is not available to the public.
Only researchers and employees at the colleges and corporate
sponsors can use it. Consumers eventually will be able to use
cutting-edge applications created on Internet2 but only after they
have been developed and sold by Internet2 members for commercial
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen, Internet2 and a similar project, the government-backed
Next Generation Internet, are modeled after the original Internet _
except they all use fiber-optic circuits instead of standard
telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of OXYGEN15 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
