<HEADER>
A0435 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEVRON-CHEVRON_SFCHR     03-15 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-CHEVRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDCATTING IN 3-D  
 BY REBECCA SMITH 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In a darkened theater at Chevron offices in San Ramon, an oil
geologist raptly watches a 3-D picture glide across a 28-foot
curved screen. The image shows water gradually invading an oil
reservoir deep beneath the earth's surface in Nigeria.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the mid-1960s, Chevron has extracted hundreds of millions
of barrels of ``sweet crude'' from the reservoir. But daily
production has slumped to fewer than 5,000 barrels from 23,000
barrels, as wells have become flooded with water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there's plenty of oil left,'' said Marcia Houghton,
Chevron's reservoir manager for Nigeria. ``The problem is getting
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, using newly developed 3-D visualization technology, her
team is testing whether yields can be boosted by increasing
underground pressure. The plan is to add water-injection wells at
strategic points to push the ``black gold'' to existing wells, much
the way sheepdogs push straggling sheep to a pasture gate.
</P>
<P>
   So far, test results look good. If things go according to plan,
the oil company's investment of less than $10 million for the new
injection wells could net $600 million worth of additional oil in
coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visualization technology lets us optimize the money we
spend,'' said Don Paul, Chevron's vice president of technology.
``It significantly reduces the uncertainty that's an inherent part
of this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Many experts believe that visualization technology represents
the next big breakthrough in oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
   It builds on improvements in seismic mapping, which uses sound
waves to plot the location of liquids, gases and minerals, and weds
it to production data and state-of-the-art graphics software.
</P>
<P>
   Using special projection equipment _ not to mention 3-D glasses
_ the result is a depiction of the total oil reservoir that appears
to float in space and can be tipped to show different perspectives
and manipulated to play out different scenarios. Test wells, for
instance, can be drilled or capped. And faults can be explored to
see how oil flows through them or around them.
</P>
<P>
   The 3-D images allow a team of experts to make decisions about
where and how to drill. End result: fewer wells that produce more
oil, more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The oil industry has been using computer-assisted visualization
tools for at least 20 years with the best computers available. The
motivation is strong because oil wells are expensive, costing
anywhere from $50,000 to several million dollars to drill.
</P>
<P>
   What's new is the ability to put information in a 3-D format and
make the tool available to an interdisciplinary team of experts in
geology, drilling and equipment design.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Richfield was the first oil company to unveil a 3-D
visualization center, in March 1997. During the next 18 months,
Texaco, Chevron and Exxon got their centers up and running.
Chevron's San Ramon theater has been open only a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology will fundamentally change the way we do
exploration, develop reservoirs and even the way we manage our
operations,'' said Geoffrey Dorn, Arco's director of visualization
technology. ``We're applying it to geology first, but it'll
eventually change facilities designs, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry is taking its cues from other capital-intensive
businesses that are pushing the frontiers of 3-D design. The
semiconductor, automotive and aerospace industries, for example,
have used visualization technology to make operating models of
chips, cars and jets. Those models can detect design flaws before
products actually are made, reducing modification costs.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, experts expect the oil industry to use 3-D
technology not just to find oil in unseen places, but to improve
designs for drilling rigs and oil platforms and possibly for
refineries and service stations.
</P>
<P>
   Visualization technology would make sense in any era, but it's
especially important now with oil at half the price it fetched a
year ago. At Chevron, executives are keenly aware that they must
make investment dollars stretch further since earnings fell 39
percent last year. Though prices have risen this month, with
expectations that OPEC will curtail production, cost controls still
are in place.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the industry has taken two approaches to 3-D
visualization.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies, like Chevron, rely on powerful workstations and
wraparound screens in theaters seating 20 to 50 people. Massive
amounts of data are crunched by the workstations to create 3-D
images that can be rotated to provide different perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   The second approach uses ``cave'' technology. Rooms are built
measuring 10- or 12-feet square. The walls, ceiling and floor act
as rear-projection screens. Three or four people can fit
comfortably inside each room, and data can be projected around them
and manipulated to show, for example, how wells might be drilled to
avoid hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Each approach has advantages and disadvantages. The theaters are
best for bringing together interdisciplinary groups of experts as
well as for making presentations to partnering companies. Chevron
spent $1.2 million to build and equip its two theaters. The second
theater is in La Habra (Orange County).
</P>
<P>
   The caves, which can cost $3 million apiece, are more complex.
They use supercomputer technology and are better suited to research
labs, which is why Arco's center is located at its research and
development center in Plano, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The backbone of Chevron's system is IBM RS-6000 workstations.
For the Nigeria test, they've been loaded up with more than 30
years' worth of reservoir performance data and the best seismic
information available.
</P>
<P>
   To handle all the information, the reservoir is broken into
football-field sized cells or blocks. Thousands of bits of data are
loaded up for each field _ and there are 70,000 in all.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron's two theaters were built as part of its
$400-million-a-year budget for information technology. Chevron's
plan is to get more visualization centers deployed around the
company. Eventually, it would like to network them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the way you get value out of advanced
technology is to put it in the hands of people who run the
business, as opposed to putting it in a lab or technology center,''
said Chevron's Paul. ``The key to success is to distribute the
technology and get a wide variety of people interacting with it.''
</P>
<P>
   That means access to the technology is not just limited to
petroleum geologists. People who build facilities and run them also
are expected to test their designs and plans by using the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Industrywide, the continued advances in technology have helped
drive down the costs of oil production during the past 20 years.
Seismic mapping has helped. So has the ability to drill horizontal
wells, or holes that can curve and run sideways.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, Chevron spent $15 to $17 to replace each
barrel of oil it produced. Today, technological improvements mean
that it costs only $5 or so to add a barrel of oil to reserves. And
continued advances in technology are expected to drive costs still
lower.
</P>
<P>
   At Arco, the technology already is saving real money.
</P>
<P>
   Before drilling a new well in the North Sea, a team visited
Dorn's visualization center last year. They quickly discovered that
the planned bore hole appeared likely to nick a water strata,
possibly adulterating the well and squandering a $10 million
investment.
</P>
<P>
   After months of work, a single day in the cave forced them to
make huge design changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better here than in the field, though,'' Dorn said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
