<HEADER>
A0437 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-SFCHRO     03-15 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MEDICARE'S FATE HINGES ON DEAL FOR DRUG COVERAGE  &HT;     By SABIN RUSSELL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not an easy thing, having the fate of the nation's Medicare
program resting in your hands.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that awesome responsibility rests right now, to a remarkable
degree, with Laura D'Andrea Tyson, dean of the Haas School of
Business at the University of California at Berkeley. She has one
of two pivotal votes on the National Bipartisan Commission on the
Future of Medicare, which is mulling recommendations for the
biggest overhaul of the $210 billion program since it began in
1965.
</P>
<P>
   As early as Tuesday, Tyson must vote on a proposal, developed by
commission chairman Sen. John Breaux, D-La., that would eventually
corral most of Medicare's senior citizen beneficiaries into managed
care health plans run by private insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Democratic backers of the current Medicare
program are pushing for an expansion, to add prescription drug
coverage for the one-in-three elderly Americans who cannot afford
it today.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the possibility of a momentous deal. Call it
the Drug Deal of the Century. As a trade-off for privatizing
Medicare, Congress would add a drug benefit that could cost
taxpayers $20 billion a year, improving the program but chewing up
much of the savings.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Tyson and Stuart Altman, a Brandeis University
health economist who is also considered a swing vote, are holding
out for Breaux to add a drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux's proposal now has 10 votes on the 17-member commission.
Rules require 11 votes for approval. So Tyson and Altman are the
focus of an intense lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be the dean of the business school,'' said
Tyson, who served as President Clinton's chief economic adviser
from 1993 to 1996. ``For the last few weeks, this has become a
major issue, trying to decide the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   An endorsement by the panel, which was created by Congress to
deal with Medicare's looming financial problems, would give a
bipartisan stamp of approval to Breaux's plan before it is sent to
a Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   And for Clinton, whose effort to reform health care proved the
biggest policy failure of his first term, the Medicare plan
represents another chance to leave his mark on the nation's health
care system.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux has been trying to hammer together a drug benefit
proposal to win Tyson and Altman over. ``This is very much a work
in progress,'' he told panel members at the last meeting in
February. ``... What I've tried to do is explore every option in an
attempt to find a middle ground.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how Breaux feels about adding drug coverage to
Medicare, he cannot add it without alienating Republican members
such as conservative Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas. The impasse has
delayed the bipartisan commission report, which was expected on
March 1. The commission plans to meet Tuesday in another attempt to
make a decision, and must disband at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Its decision, however, will shape the debate over health care
reform well into the next century. ``It is likely to kick off a
health care debate as big as any we've had in the last five
years,'' said Drew Altman, president of the Menlo Park-based Kaiser
Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing the panel, Altman suggested, may be
insurmountable. ``They have to find how to expand the program, and
cut it back at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Breaux proposal would do to senior citizens what private
employers did to their employees during the past decade _ steer
them into HMOs. Supporters of the plan believe managed care will
dramatically reduce health costs in Medicare, much as it has done
with private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the reform effort is the relentless march of the Baby
Boom generation toward retirement age and the costly medical
problems that accompany it. The population eligible for Medicare is
expected to swell to 76 million by 2030, nearly double the 40
million eligible today.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare trust fund that pays hospital bills is projected to
go bankrupt in 2008 - just before the first Baby Boomers hit
retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare's promise of ever-expanding benefits is not
sustainable fiscally, politically or morally,'' wrote David
Kendall, senior analyst for the Progressive Policy Institute of
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current Medicare system, patients are not limited in
their choice of doctor. Medicare pays most hospital costs and 80
percent of the doctor bills, which are set by the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   In Breaux's version, Medicare will offer a menu of private
health plans to senior citizens, and guarantee payment for up to 88
percent of the average annual cost of the plans. Many of the plans,
typically HMOs, would be priced at or below the average. There
would be little or no premium cost. But seniors would have to pay
the difference if they wanted a more expensive health plan.
</P>
<P>
   If the idea sounds familiar, it is. Clinton's failed health
insurance reform attempted to apply the same model to provide
coverage to every American. The idea is called ``managed
competition,'' a term coined by Stanford Business School professor
Alain Enthoven.
</P>
<P>
   Although not involved in the current debate, he is on a
sabbatical in England, Enthoven called Breaux's plan a sound
proposal that would steer much of the Medicare population into
managed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the best hope we've got,'' said Enthoven during a
visit to Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   But detractors fear that Breaux's plan will turn Medicare into a
two-class system of quality health care for the well-to-do,
substandard care for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a political standpoint, it kills the system,'' said Rep.
Fortney ``Pete'' Stark, D-Hayward, perhaps Medicare's fiercest
protector in Congress. ``Over time, poor people and middle-income
people will be shouldering more of the burden. ... We'll have a
very poorly structured, two-tiered system that leaves the oldest
and frailest and sickest bankrupt. That's where we were 30 years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco physician Dr. Thomas Bodenheimer, of the National
Campaign to Protect, Improve and Expand Medicare, called the Breaux
plan ``a welfare program for the insurance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bodenheimer warns that Medicare beneficiaries who currently
enjoy the right to health care will get instead a voucher that will
buy less and less coverage over time.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also point out that HMOs have already established a
track record in Medicare, with little to show for it. Roughly one
in seven Medicare beneficiaries is signed up with an HMO today, yet
studies suggest the health plans have cost the federal government
money, rather than saved it.
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case on topics as complex as health insurance,
the two sides break on ideological lines. ``This is between people
who believe in the marketplace, versus people who believe in
entitlements,'' said Gail Wilensky, a health policy analyst who
headed the Medicare program during the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   A Breaux plan supporter, Wilensky said the reform effort is a
bid to realign the incentives in the Medicare program toward
cost-effective care. ``The way we try to control spending in the
current Medicare system is through price controls,'' said Wilensky.
To believers, Medicare can benefit from free-market efficiencies in
the same way the airline, energy and communications industries
brought lower costs through deregulation and enhanced competition.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings it back to Berkeley Business School Dean Tyson, the
woman Clinton chose to set his economic agenda. Where does she
stand on the question of market versus price controls?
</P>
<P>
   In the current Medicare system, she said, ``it's the role of
government to establish benefits, establish price and pay bills
around the country. That's an amazing amount of micromanagement.
... It is a very compelling reason for me to think about change.''
</P>
<P>
   She is also worried that the benefits within the Medicare system
will become illusory as pressures increase to reduce costs. ``The
danger is that, although the government says it will continue to
pay for procedures, it will pay less than they cost, and the
services will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, said Tyson, is now ``at odds'' with the private health
care system on which it was based 30 years ago. ``It doesn't
provide drugs, and it is fee-for-service with controlled prices,''
she said. ``Fee-for-service with controlled prices is something the
private sector is aggressively moving away from.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not the words of a die-hard supporter of the old
Medicare system. ``There's no perfect solution,'' Tyson said. ``I
am personally trying to think of it as a set of policy
trade-offs.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if Breaux can deliver the drugs, and that's a
big if, he has a deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
