<HEADLINE>
BC-FINBUDGET-FINANCE _ BUDGET _ SFCHRON  

</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON  Here are the finance stories the San Francisco Chronicle plans to
move for AMs and PMs of Monday, March 15. For questions, please
call Georgie Dennison at 415-777-6055.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CHEVRON _  &LR;  Why visualization technology represents the next
big breakthrough in oil exploration. By Rebecca Smith
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; OXYGEN &LR;  _ Project Oxygen is a commercial venture that hopes to
leapfrog the nonprofit Internet2 it would pump video, sound and
data at neck-snapping speed to users in 78 countries. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; EGGHEAD &LR;  _ There has been a lot of talk about the marketing
potential of &UR;  &LR; ``convergence'' between television and the Internet _
but not much to show for it. The concept becomes more meaningful
today, however, with the airing on cable channel ZDTV of an
apparently ordinary commercial for computer and software merchant
Egghead.com. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NET FILES  &LR; _ Vince ``Vega'' Nicholas unabashedly offers virtual
voyeurs a glimpse into his dorm room at San Francisco State. He
alternately mugs at a Web camera and trades one-liners in an online
chat area. A shameless exhibitionist? Maybe. A self-promoter who
was chosen to be a guinea pig for new Web site  &LR; www.webdorm.com &LR; 
that chronicles the lives of selected college students a la MTV's
``The Real World''? Definitely. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIOSCOPE  &LR; _ Roughly a thousand people turned out Saturday for
an all-day celebration held at the University of California at
Berkeley to commemorate the scientific discovery that launched the
biotech industry 25 years ago. By Tom Abate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BURNETT &LR;  _ As one of Silicon Valley's pioneering computer
scientists, former Cisco Systems &UR;  &LR; executive Bob Burnett helped
create the vast network of technology &UR;  &LR; that links the world today.
Now, Burnett is trying to help link networks of humans so that they
can better deal with the world's biggest technological dilemma, the
Year 2000 computer problem, which he also had a hand in creating.
By Benny Evangelista
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
