<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0502 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CADILLAC-RACING-REV     03-15 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CADILLAC-RACING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLD ONTO YOUR CAP TAKING THE CADDY FOR A SPIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Mention Cadillac, and the images that spring to mind
are pretty sedate: Midwestern grandfathers tooling down suburban
roads, perhaps, or chauffeurs in caps holding rear doors open for
wealthy widows carrying sculpted poodles out of Fifth Avenue
co-ops.
</P>
<P>
   These are precisely the images Cadillac is trying to change. The
result has been a series of offbeat _ and sometimes off-key _
efforts to build a new, sprier reputation for Cadillac. The latest:
Cadillac is building a race car to compete next year at Le Mans,
the venerable French race in which entrants try to drive as many
times around a track as possible in 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Fire-engine red is a popular color for race cars, but Cadillac
will stick to its heritage by painting its entry a shimmery
platinum hue. Still, some compromises are being made. To defray the
cost, Cadillac will allow other sponsors to put their logos on the
car, although Cadillac will insist that they not be gaudy. And
while the rules at Le Mans require that the race cars have two
seats, the Cadillac entry will definitely not include a chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that Le Mans cars must fit two people, but they fit
side by side, not one in the back seat,'' said John F. Smith,
Cadillac's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac's corporate parent, General Motors, believes the move
makes sense. After largely ignoring the overseas market for luxury
cars for nearly a century, GM has decided it must fight back
against BMW, Mercedes, Lexus and other rivals by invading their
home markets. GM is trying to establish Cadillac as a global brand,
and while prosperous Americans may not pay much attention to events
like the Indianapolis 500, affluent car buyers in Japan and Europe
do tend to watch car races.
</P>
<P>
   Auto racing enthusiasts were nonetheless amused that Cadillac
chose to trumpet its race car plans with an announcement that
began, ``50 years later, Cadillac returns to Le Mans.'' Unlike many
automakers, Cadillac does not have a racing tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Two Cadillacs did compete at Le Mans in 1950, and did remarkably
well, beating cars from racing giants like MG, Jaguar and Ferrari.
But both Cadillacs were entered by a wealthy businessman, not by
the manufacturer. For many years, auto racing ``was something the
standard of the world just didn't do,'' said Robert Casey, an auto
historian. ``They didn't need to; they had the North American
market nailed down.'' Cadillac anointed itself as the standard of
the world after winning a much-contested trophy for automotive
design from Britain's Royal Automobile Club in 1908, and has
periodically used the slogan since then in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Many other auto manufacturers have genuine racing traditions.
Henry Ford raised the money to start Ford Motor Co. by building a
low, rakish car that won an important car race near Detroit in
1902. Ford did not actually drive the car, instead hiring a
daredevil bicyclist, Barney Oldfield, who learned to drive in the
week before the race.
</P>
<P>
   In 1904, with his company struggling against dozens of other
tiny automakers, Ford took a hand-built car out onto the fissured
ice of a lake near Detroit and personally drove it faster than
anyone had ever driven: a little over 91 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's feat was never officially recognized as a record. Land
speed records are calculated from a driver's average speed in two
runs across the same terrain with the second run in the opposite
direction to eliminate wind as a factor. Ford, having barely made
it across the rough ice in his first run, never went back. ``He
didn't care; it was worth it for the advertising,'' Casey said.
``He figured if you go faster than anyone else, you have the
record.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Honda has built its reputation for good-quality
cars and high-technology engines on its many years of racing
experience. Working in Honda's racing division is still essential
to executive success at the Japanese automaker, where the new V6
engine in the Honda Accord was designed by Katsumi Ichida, an
engineer whose previous assignment involved building race car
engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in it to develop the people, the engineers,'' said
Thomas Elliott, Honda's executive vice president of North American
auto operations.
</P>
<P>
   Engines win and lose car races, and Cadillac believes that its
V8 Northstar, which has gotten good reviews from experts, can be
the reliable, high-performance engine it needs to compete at Le
Mans. But the engine will undergo so many modifications for racing
that it will become unrecognizable even to some mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   The Cadillac race car looks a little like a graying Batmobile,
judging from drawings released last week. But in a bid to enhance
future sales, GM designed the car to resemble the Cadillac Evoq, a
prototype coupe that Cadillac is displaying at auto shows this year
and is likely to begin selling in several years. The Evoq and the
race car are painted in a new platinum-colored paint that seems to
change from light to dark and back again depending on the
illumination and the angle from which it is viewed.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac needs all the help it can get. Lincoln nearly outsold
it in the United States last year for the first time in more than
half a century. And some of Cadillac's attempts to change its image
have been failures.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac tried two years ago to woo professional women in their
40s by running television advertisements showing model Cindy
Crawford wearing knee-high boots and a tight, leather mini-dress as
she drove a new Cadillac past the stone walls of a castle. Adweek
described her outfit as a ``Wilma Flintstone-as-dominatrix
get-up,'' and the ads were soon pulled.
</P>
<P>
   But expanding Cadillac's tiny business overseas will be a fresh
start for an aging brand, and Cadillac hopes racing will help it
get off to a fast start abroad. While Americans may have strong
ideas about what a Cadillac is, Smith said, ``Europe and Japan are
a clean sheet of paper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
