to honor its orders on the day before Christmas? And what sort of
society was it that accepted this ghastly contretemps with such
equanimity that not a voice was raised?
</P>
<P>
   A society, it seemed, that was anything but settled. For the
first image was startlingly ``un-German.'' It suggested, if
anything, a flakiness that Germans tend to associate with societies
south of the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   The second image, however, seemed quintessentially German, that
of a society terrified of disorder, wary of disruption; a people
still asking itself, at some subliminal level: ``Can we ever be
trusted again?''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it seems, that is Germany today, a place pulled
between two poles. This polarity challenges the new government of
the Social Democratic chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder. His Cabinet
ministers are very much of Germany's Latin-leaning, postwar
generation, with their houses in Tuscany, their taste for olive oil
rather than lard, for wine rather than beer, for bear hugs rather
than formal handshakes. Theirs is a Germany that is less formal,
more multicultural, more forward-looking and, yes, less reliable in
the sense that it is no longer content with its postwar role as
economic giant and political pygmy.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, an older Germany persists: that of
deep-seated angst, of tremendous formality, of people who will not
cross even empty streets if the pedestrian light is red, of
handshakes of such bone-crushing harshness they speak of
estrangement rather than closeness. A Germany of obedience to
authority, of rigidity and order and Herr-This and Frau-That and
strictly no first names.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Germany for which a voice raised threatens disorder,
and Schroeder's proposed reform offering German citizenship to many
foreigners is a potent threat to be resisted with vigor.
</P>
<P>
   I was recently directed from an airport bus to the rear door of
a Boeing 737 on a flight from Munich. Due to a misunderstanding,
the door was closed. We waited on the stairs in the cold winter
air. Minutes passed. Nobody was prepared to knock on the door.
Nobody was ready to raise a voice. Disconcerted paralysis
prevailed. This, I thought, is still a society that values order
above freedom.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But a few weeks later, I find myself with Joschka Fischer, the
foreign minister from the environmentalist Green Party, a former
1960s revolutionary, watching his face twist into a wry grin as he
considers his delicious destiny: moving the Foreign Ministry later
this year into Hitler's former Reichsbank in Berlin, a place where
East Germany's Communist leader, Erich Honecker, also held court.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer's is a Germany confident that history's lessons have
been learned, one that assumes the past but is not consumed by it,
one that feels it has earned the freedom to be bolder. A society
prepared to take the risk of moving its capital from Bonn back to
Berlin, the city where Bismarck's Reich ended in the humiliation of
World War I defeat and the punishment of Versailles, where the
Weimar Republic ended with Hitler, and where Hitler ended with
ruin. ``No devil lurks in Berlin,'' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Between these often contradictory images _ of caution and
risk-taking _ Germany now makes its way. It is today a place that
tends to shatter preconceptions. Take the autobahn system: the
stock images that arise are of magnificent highways full of
flashing BMW's and Mercedes and Porsches roaring along without a
speed limit to encumber them.
</P>
<P>
   Try this instead: a labyrinth of roadworks filled with cars
crawling along in 30-mile-long bottlenecks or breaking suddenly
from high speeds to negotiate diversions consisting of impossibly
narrow lanes. Of the 7,085 miles of autobahn in Germany, about
one-tenth is currently in the midst of construction or repairs. In
other words, it is rare to drive more than 10 miles without
encountering some sort of obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   What this reflects above all, of course, is the fact that
unification is still a work in progress 10 years after the fall of
the Berlin Wall; much remains to be done to connect the country and
make it whole. Germany, in short, is in the midst of change more
dramatic than in any other west European country.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff Olins, a London-based public relations agency, recently
put on a show in Berlin on the ``rebranding'' of Germany. Nations,
it seems, must also be brands today, capable of selling themselves
aggressively. The Berlin show was an exercise akin to the agency's
``rebranding'' of Tony Blair's Britain as a mecca of hip fashion
rather than the home of quaint old fogies. In the case of Germany,
too, the results were interesting.
</P>
<P>
   There was a postage stamp featuring model Claudia Schiffer. A
redesigned flag of red, yellow and blue _ all primary colors _
rather than the current black, gold and red (``Black is simply
negative,'' said Paul Vinogradoff of Wolff Olins). A photograph of
a pot of Nivea cream (Nivea is a German invention), with the
provocative caption, ``So smooth it must be French.'' Images of the
annual Berlin Love Parade, now the largest street party in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show that Germany can now present itself as a
place where diversity is celebrated, where people are loosening up,
where efficiency is anything but the whole story,'' Vinogradoff
said. The ``safe,'' ``conformist,'' ``perfectionist'' Germany of
today could, with the right encouragement, give way to a ``free,''
``flexible,'' ``relaxed'' and ``spontaneous'' place.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Some sort of transition is evidently under way. Germany
is already a place where you can no longer count on your turkey,
even if people are not yet ready to holler about it. We, by the
way, settled for goose.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
