<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0517 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLUMN-TEEPEN-COX     03-15 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-TEEPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: U.S. policy fails to adjust to changes in Iran
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now we have to hope the Clinton administration, still dully
treating Cuba as if the Cold War never ended, will somehow begin
fine-tuning our Iranian policy to take advantage of, and help
reinforce, the remarkable shift toward moderation there.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it. The opening has been growing steadily since
reformer Mohammed Khatami was elected Iran's president in 1997, but
the best the State Department has been able to muster as a response
has been to doubt the genuineness and durability of the change
rather than pooh-poohing it outright.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Iran's recent, first-ever local elections under the
Islamic revolution's 1979 constitution, Khatami supporters cleaned
the clocks of conservative opponents, winning 12 of crucial
Tehran's 15 council seats and about 70 percent of the votes
nationally. No hardliners won, and women were elected in 20 cities,
one of many accumulating indications that the revolution's early,
hyper-Islamist misogynism is waning.
</P>
<P>
   And all this despite the fact that the Islamic medievalists who
dominate religious offices and much of the bureaucracy had
disqualified some 50 pro-Khatami candidates. Indeed, liberal
clerics, journalists and others earlier purged by the hardliners
were able to return to the political game via the local elections _
a pointed electoral rebuke to the revolutionary mossbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Liberal'' is a relative term in Iran. Khatami and his allies
have no intention of cancelling the revolution or of unhitching
mosque and state, but they've set out an ambitious agenda even so.
The formers are softening the revolution's sharper social edges,
working to institutionalize democratic processes and trying to ease
Iran back into international respectability by disavowing the
revolution's past support for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is right not to get giddy. The conservative
ayatollahs retain potential blocking power. It is not clear
Khatami's theoretical disavowal of terrorism has in fact ended
Iran's role as haven and provocateur.
</P>
<P>
   But surely the State Department can work up something more
useful than rote skepticism. There's an opportunity here to help
turn Iran away from international mischief and perhaps even revive
its traditional role as a counterweight to adjacent Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintonites' record for flexibility is not encouraging. They
continue, for instance, acting toward Cuba as if it were still a
Soviet cat's-paw, instead of being, as it is, merely the shabby and
politically discredited fiefdom of an aged autocrat.
</P>
<P>
   As with Cuba, so with Iran. If unwilling yet to make any major
changes in our own standoffishness, Washington at least could stop
blocking the efforts of our own allies to knit both nations up into
working networks of trade and diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   As Iran's local elections neared, the United States publicly
wished for outcomes that would support Khatami but privately worked
to frustrate Khatami's attempts to increase trade with Europe, in
effect economically starving political reform. To say there's some
tension in those positions is to put it mildly.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
