<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0521 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TA     03-15 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) 
 The Week in Review  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't Look Too Far
</P>
<P>
   Those unschooled in the nuances of presidential candidates'
announcements and exploratory committees may picture experts
huddled around a table deliberating whether their candidate should
take the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiling his 10-member exploratory panel last week, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush said he was ``grateful they will take time to help
me make this decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush exploratory committee has no immediate plans to
meet. What's to explore? The governor himself said he would back
out only if his candidacy were greeted with ``a large thud.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole did not disclose her committee members' names
last week because there aren't any. ``That's a legalism,''
explained Mrs. Dole's senior strategist, Kieran Mahoney.
</P>
<P>
   By registering an exploratory committee with the Federal
Election Commission, contenders can begin collecting money for
travel and early organizational efforts. But it is not required;
candidates could just as easily create full-fledged campaign
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Why do many hopefuls maintain the fiction that they are
exploring when there is little doubt of their intentions? If their
campaigns collapse early, they can make a graceful exit, saying
that _ technically _ they were never in the race. And why announce
in one grand event if you can build the drama?
</P>
<P>
   As one Federal Election Commission official put it, ``A lot of
this is going through the hoops just for the political mileage.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD L. BERKE
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Seuss He's Not
</P>
<P>
   It took only hours for William Ivey, chairman of the National
Endowment for the Arts, to decide about a $15,000 grant the agency
had authorized for a small Texas publisher to translate an unusual
children's book.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``The Story of Colors,'' was written by Subcomandante
Marcos, the leader of the Zapatista rebels in southern Mexico. The
inside flap shows him in full military regalia.
</P>
<P>
   Ivey took over in mid-1998 after the agency narrowly survived
attempts by House Republicans to extinguish it. Less than a day
after a reporter's phone call brought the book to his attention,
Ivey canceled the grant.
</P>
<P>
   Although the book had passed through a yearlong review process,
Ivey used his powers to reject the grant by fiat because he was
worried that some federal funds might make their way to the rebel
group. ``I looked at the movement of money internationally and saw
our inability to know what the ultimate destination might be,''
Ivey said.
</P>
<P>
   The move was a shock to Bobby Byrd, a poet and editor who runs
the Cinco Puntos Press in El Paso, Texas, with his wife and
daughter. Byrd said there was no chance Subcomandante Marcos would
receive any federal money because he had waived his rights to
income from the book.
</P>
<P>
   The book, first published by a small Mexican press in 1997, is a
folk tale about mythical gods who created colors to liven up a dull
gray universe. The Lannan Foundation in Santa Fe, N.M., said it
would donate funds to Byrd's press to make up for the lost grant.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JULIA PRESTON
</P>
<P>
   This Old House: Fallingapart
</P>
<P>
   Fallingwater, the Frank Lloyd Wright masterpiece, ``represents
all the aspirations of the 20th century,'' says Lynda Waggoner, the
house's director. Unfortunately, it can also serve as a tidy
metaphor for a century that, for all its glories, has, well, had
its problems.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, for all his towering vision, was notorious for
neglecting the basics _ like designing roofs that wouldn't leak.
When Fallingwater was being built in western Pennsylvania six
decades ago, the contractor suggested more steel reinforcing for
those dramatic slabs hovering above the waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   But no one _ no one _ was allowed to tell the great architect
what to do, and Wright threatened to walk off the project. The
contractor quietly doubled the reinforcing anyway _ ``the building
probably would not be standing today'' if he hadn't, Ms. Waggoner
said. But even that wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   For Fallingwater is _ oh, it's no use resisting the tailormade
wordplay _ slowly falling into the water. The contractor was right:
The concrete is gradually bending, with one corner of the house 7
inches lower than it should be. The exterior is now adorned with
distinctly un-Wright-like steel beams to keep the whole thing from
collapsing. These will stay until there's a permanent solution.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   NATO Expands East to Poland, Hungary and Czech Republic
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War receded a bit farther following a ceremony in
Independence, Mo., in which Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic
became the first former Soviet-bloc nations to formally join NATO.
At the gathering at the Harry S. Truman Presidential Library,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told the foreign ministers of
the three nations, ``You are truly allies, you are truly home.''
</P>
<P>
   The ministers said their countries saw membership in the
alliance as an assurance of security and a return to their rightful
place in Europe. The enlargement of NATO from 16 to 19 members has
been one of the Clinton administration's top foreign policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Tours Central America
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton journeyed to Central America on a mission of
mercy and regret. In Nicaragua and Honduras, he viewed the damage
from last fall's Hurricane Mitch and promised to do what he could
to pry loose $1 billion in reconstruction aid from Congress. He
also said he would try to ease the plight of thousands of Central
Americans who illegally migrated to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Guatemala, Clinton apologized for the U.S. support of the
nation's military rulers during their 36-year war against Marxist
insurgents and Mayan Indians, which left an estimated 200,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN M. BRODER
</P>
<P>
   Curbs on Antibiotics in Feed
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration is revising its guidelines for
approving and monitoring antibiotics for animals, fearing that the
routine use of antibiotics in livestock feed to promote growth may
threaten human health by fostering bacteria that no drug can kill.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is acting now because the nation is especially
vulnerable: No new classes of antibiotics will be marketed in the
near future, and doctors fear that if bacteria overwhelm existing
drugs, more patients will succumb to untreatable infections.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0080 </DOCNO>
