</P>
<P>
   In Guatemala, Clinton apologized for the U.S. support of the
nation's military rulers during their 36-year war against Marxist
insurgents and Mayan Indians, which left an estimated 200,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN M. BRODER
</P>
<P>
   Curbs on Antibiotics in Feed
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration is revising its guidelines for
approving and monitoring antibiotics for animals, fearing that the
routine use of antibiotics in livestock feed to promote growth may
threaten human health by fostering bacteria that no drug can kill.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA is acting now because the nation is especially
vulnerable: No new classes of antibiotics will be marketed in the
near future, and doctors fear that if bacteria overwhelm existing
drugs, more patients will succumb to untreatable infections.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DENISE GRADY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty on Kosovo Plan
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a second round of Kosovo peace talks, scheduled to
start in Paris on Monday progress looked as elusive as ever. The
Clinton administration tried all week to persuade the ethnic
Albanians to sign on to the peace plan, which grants autonomy to
Kosovo for a three-year period with 28,000 NATO-led troops as
overseers. But the Kosovo Liberation Army, concerned about having
to disarm, kept debating, not signing.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Richard Holbrooke returned to Washington from a visit
to President Slobodan Milosevic, of Yugoslavia, without any
concessions. In Kosovo, fighting flared. With increased numbers of
Serb forces deployed in the Serbian province and the ethnic
Albanians poised for combat, the outlook appeared grim.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JANE PERLEZ
</P>
<P>
   Arab Named Miss Israel
</P>
<P>
   If beauty pageants are reflections of anything particularly
deep, then the Miss Israel pageant broke a barrier of sorts. The
woman chosen to represent Israel in the Miss World competition is,
for the first time, Arab.
</P>
<P>
   Rana Raslan, 21, refused to read too much into her selection,
saying she had been chosen in the contest as ``a beauty queen, not
a political queen.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little controversy over her selection in the Jewish
homeland. In the Arab community, however, some did look askance:
Muslims fundamentalists did not approve of the pageant's bathing
suit competition.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DEBORAH SONTAG
</P>
<P>
   NCAA Rule Is Voided
</P>
<P>
   A federal court in Philadelphia discarded the National
Collegiate Athletic Association's minimum test score requirement
for athletic scholarships. The court found that the requirement
``has an unjustified disparate impact against African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a significant comment on the debate over cultural bias in
standardized test. For the moment, the NCAA has no clear standard
for scholarship eligibility, and has asked for a stay of the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOE DRAPE
</P>
<P>
   Intel Settles Antitrust Suit
</P>
<P>
   Intel Corp. settled an antitrust case brought by the government
just before the trial was to begin, agreeing not to force computer
manufacturers that need crucial technical information about the
company's microprocessor chips to surrender rival technology.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers said they were pleased by the settlement but
were continuing a broader antitrust investigation of Intel.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEPHEN LABATON
</P>
<P>
   RJR Nabisco, R.I.P.
</P>
<P>
   Crumbling under the strain of debt and the specter of fresh
lawsuits over smoking, RJR Nabisco said it would separate its food
and tobacco businesses and sell its international tobacco division.
The company's biggest shareholder, Carl Icahn, said he would wage a
proxy fight to get RJR to spin off its Nabisco holdings instead of
the domestic tobacco operations, as the company proposed.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CONSTANCE L. HAYS
</P>
<P>
   Verdicts in French AIDS Case
</P>
<P>
   Former French Prime Minister Laurent Fabius and a member of his
Cabinet were acquitted of charges of criminal manslaughter and
negligence in the deaths of hundreds of transfusion patients who
contracted AIDS from contaminated blood in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Fabius, now speaker of the lower house of Parliament, and
Georgina Dufoix, minister of social affairs in Fabius' Socialist
government, acted as fast as they could to make testing of blood
supplies for the AIDS virus mandatory from Aug. 1, 1985, a special
high court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Edmond Herve, health minister at the time, was convicted of two
cases of negligence, but was given no sentence. The court said he
should have ordered the recall of previously untested blood when
the risk of potential contamination first became known, rather than
let it be used for several more months.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CRAIG R. WHITNEY
</P>
<P>
   Crayola Changes Stripes
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a few simple strokes can hint at the sweep of history
_ strokes of a crayon, say. Only twice in 96 years had Crayola
changed a color's name, rechristening ``Prussian blue'' as
``midnight blue'' in 1958 because people had lost track of exactly
what Prussia was, and changing ``flesh'' to ``peach'' in 1962,
recognizing that flesh is a many-colored thing.
</P>
<P>
   Now it will relabel ``indian red'' to wipe out any associations
with American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The new name? Ideas are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid and Pain Relief
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid officials have reminded doctors and hospitals that they
must not demand cash payments for anesthesia services from poor
women in labor.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Richardson, the national director of the Medicaid program,
said the government had received reports of some anesthesiologists
demanding such payments for epidural injections to relieve pain in
childbirth. Medicaid provides health insurance for low-income
families and pays for more than one-third of the nation's births.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBERT PEAR
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
