<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0528 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN17-CO     03-15 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Waiting to get to the waiting room
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, March 17, 1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is anything I dread more than going to the doctor's
office, it's calling the doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   It is a terrifying undertaking. Often, I sit around and plan how
I am going to respond to any number of hurdles presented to me on
the other end of the phone line.
</P>
<P>
   The most common is the doctor's office receptionist who answers,
rapidly says ``Hold, please,'' and then does not return, if at all,
for about 7 to 10 minutes while I listen to elevator music.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the doctor's offices where, after waiting on hold
for a while, you get a voice mail identifying someone as the
``appointments secretary,'' but she is not presently in; please
leave your name and number and (maybe) she'll call back.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, once connected to a living person, the most
intimidating question I'm asked is: ``Are you a first-time
patient?''
</P>
<P>
   If I answer affirmatively, I will not be able to get an
appointment with the doctor for at least three months, as there is
some sort of fraternal hazing period within the medical profession
that dictates new patients be put in a holding pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my nose is bleeding,'' I plead, ``It's been bleeding off
and an on for a week. Can't you give me something earlier than May
10?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry sir, but that's the earliest date we have for a new
patient. Perhaps you ought to go to the emergency room.''
</P>
<P>
   That much blood there isn't.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know who trains doctors' office personnel, and often
wonder what my own wife was like when she worked in a doctor's
office for 12 years. I know how she reacts to things I say at
times, so I'd hate to ever hear her ask if I'm a new patient.
</P>
<P>
   It likely boils down to a case of good guy, bad guy _ the
physician instructing his staff to protect him or her at all times,
to keep _ simultaneously _ six patients in six tiny patient rooms,
to obtain blood oaths in writing that all costs will be paid by
Medicare, private insurers or the estates of the patients, and to
leave Wednesday afternoon open for golf.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when you eventually get to see the doctor and complain
about how difficult it was to get an appointment, or how much
resistance there was by office staff to having your blood drawn
without first seeing the doctor, he or she promises to talk with
staff to see that such mistreatment does not occur.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, never happens, was never intended to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a splurge of trying to visit doctors for any
number of reasons, I spent a good part of my time on the phone _
waiting, arguing, begging, giving my life history and trying to
sound like a patient patient, which I was not.
</P>
<P>
   Before the doctor's telephonic guardian even asked the nature of
my illness or need, she wanted to know my insurance benefits. On
one call, I was told that the doctor could not see me because his
group did not work with my insurance company. It took me a while to
convince her that putting the whole thing on my MasterCard would be
just fine and that I would deal with the insurance people later.
</P>
<P>
   People paying up front sometimes bewilders doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three doctors with whom I tried to make appointments last
week for diverse afflictions, I successfully received booking
before the summer solstice for two of them. On the third, I simply
gave up when I heard the doctor's guardian flipping page after page
in her calendar.
</P>
<P>
   From the number of flips, it was beginning to sound like July.
And I wasn't even a first-time patient there.
</P>
<P>
   It makes you wonder (and tremble): What would it be like if we
had socialized medicine?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
