<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0531 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-KUBRICK-INTERVIEW-R     03-15 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-KUBRICK-INTERVIEW-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY KUBRICK: THE QUOTABLE RECLUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (editors: also see DIMAGGIO-INTERVIEW-REVIEW. The Times is running
the two pieces together under a single headline, ``The Silent
Celebrity and the Quotable Recluse.'')  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The interview setting _ Sunday morning in a sprawling, empty
movie studio outside London _ was sepulchral, as vast and quiet as
Hal the computer's trans-galactic homicide scene in ``2001: A Space
Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   And the reclusive film director Stanley Kubrick was formidable,
indeed, when he finally entered a dimly lit office to be
interviewed, brandishing his wariness of celebrity before the lone
questioner.
</P>
<P>
   But the master director proved a charming hermit. Kubrick was
quotably forthcoming 12 years ago once common ground was found in
the only other thing the transplanted New Yorker allowed himself to
watch during the final, manic editing process of making a film _
the latest football Giants videotapes sent from home.
</P>
<P>
   _ By FRANCIS X. CLINES
</P>
<P>
   _ Kubrick seemed particularly taken by the ads that accompanied
the telecasts, finding them to be a source of serendipitous
inspiration:
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen those Michelob commercials? They're just
boy-girl, night-fun, leading up to pouring the beer, all in 30
seconds, beautifully edited and photographed. Economy of statement
is not something that films are noted for.''
</P>
<P>
   _ He smiled in establishing a fine plebeian mood, a belief in
the common-man audience, as he talked of making movies and scouring
all manner of fiction and nonfiction in his endless search for
fresh epiphany:
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts with being excited by a story and finally it's
telling the story on the screen. ... It's the most difficult thing.
A good story is a miraculous discovery. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``That first impression is the most precious thing you've got,
you can never have it again _ the yardstick for any judgment that
you have as you get deeper and deeper into the work.''
</P>
<P>
   _ His love of it all became clear:
</P>
<P>
   ``Making a movie is a process of going into smaller and smaller
detail and finally winding up in the minutiae of how does a
footstep sound on the sound track when you're remixing the film.
...
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes from the most wonderful literary atmosphere to
desperation. It can be as crude as standing up and writing on the
back of an envelope when someone's just said something and it's 4
o'clock with the winter sun fading. You've got to shoot it and
you're trying to exploit something that's just come up. It's like a
quarterback calling an automatic play when he sees the defense he's
up against.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kubrick had trust in the ``more democratic intelligence'' of
the public versus the critics, especially after ``2001'':
</P>
<P>
   ``People who didn't have the responsibility of having to explain
it or formulate clear statements about it two hours after they saw
the film weren't troubled.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Making a movie is like chess:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a series of steps that you take one at a time, and it's
balancing resources against the problem, which in chess is time and
in movies is time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   _ To direct a movie is to protect a single idea:
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of the story the first time you read it is the
absolutely critical yardstick. I remember what I felt about the
book, I remember what I felt in writing the script, and then I try
to keep that alive in the very inappropriate circumstances that
exist on a film set where you've got a hundred people standing
around and nothing but particular problems, still trying to sustain
a subjective sense of what it is emotionally _ as well as what it
is that pleases you.''
</P>
<P>
   _ He found mortality-defying joy in each film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The structure making a movie imposes on your life when you're
doing it again feels like it felt each time before. So there is a
kind of wonderful suggestive timelessness about the structure. I'm
doing exactly the same as I was doing when I was 18 and making my
first movie. It frees you from any other sense of time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 0953EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
