<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0541 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-DOGS-POLITICS-REVIE     03-15 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DOGS-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL ANIMALS: GROWLING OVER DOGS' RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In cities and towns across the nation, a chorus of politically
influential voices cries out in unison: Woof!
</P>
<P>
   From leash laws to legislation to curb dangerous animals to
regulations limiting the number of dogs per household, canine
questions have become the new hot button of local politics. In New
York City, an effort to curb leashlessness escalated this month as
armed police were brought into what had been a Parks Department
offensive; 450 summonses have been issued in the last two weeks.
Dog owners compare themselves to Jews under Hitler, while the parks
commissioner snarls about ``dog terrorists.'' The city will soon
pass out cell phones to volunteers to snitch on leash violators.
</P>
<P>
   Emotions are equally pitched in Avon, Conn., where dog owners
are in revolt over not being able to let dogs run freely in a large
park. In Boston, pooper-scooper laws are a flashpoint. In Venice
Beach, Calif., a ban on dogs on the boardwalk is the issue. In St.
Petersburg, Fla., it is the process of determining which dogs are
too vicious to live. In Cheektowaga, N.Y., pooch lovers seethe at
the legal limit of three dogs per household. In Annapolis, Md., and
Highland Park, Mich., owners are infuriated over bans on pit bulls.
</P>
<P>
   In Minneapolis, Seattle, San Francisco and scores more cities,
people scream for more dog space in city parks. In Santa Fe, N.M.,
last year, a resident filed a $2 million suit against the city,
charging ``Gestapo-style'' enforcement of the leash law.
</P>
<P>
   Dog politics is decidedly local: State laws have little to say
about regulating Rover, and Washington almost nothing. The fight is
over local regulations, and it occurs in city, town and village
councils. But, according to the March issue of Governing, which
tracks trends in local government, the fights have all too much in
common.
</P>
<P>
   ``A seemingly innocuous proposal is quickly followed by a
response stunningly disproportionate to its weightiness in the
public policy arena,'' it said. ``If you thought taxes were the
only issue that made voters' blood boil, then you haven't had a dog
issue appear on the public agenda lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the high-pitched emotions and the sharp polarization,
participants often liken dog issues to abortion. ``There is no
middle ground,'' said Fred Marquis, administrator of Pinellas
County, Fla., where the heated discussion has been over how to
determine if a dog is dangerous and worthy of being impounded. ``As
with abortion, people are either totally opposed or totally
supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Lea Benjamin, a former dog trainer who now writes novels
about a detective who is accompanied by a pit bull, agreed:
``There's no way you can have a calm discussion about this with
anybody. It's like talking about religion. At the end of 10 hours,
nobody's mind is going to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversies are not fueled by an increase in dogs.
Although the American Pet Products Manufacturers Association
expects an increase in a census it is now preparing, the estimated
number of dogs in the country two years ago, 54.6 million, was
virtually the same as in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed, according to James Weverka, president of the
National Animal Control Association, is that dogs in recent years
have gotten larger, are more likely to be guard dogs and tend to be
confined in smaller spaces by working people who spend less time
with them. Upshot: dogs that seem more threatening roam limited
public spaces, whose owners are more likely to treat them
indulgently.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Weverka _ who serves as animal control manager in
Lincoln, Neb., where a dog catcher was recently beaten by an irate
owner _ says the view of dogs has changed fundamentally from the
time when they were prized for herding or hunting. The increase in
the number of people living alone, including older people whose
children have left the roost, may be a factor. ``There's now a
feeling that dogs are members of the family,'' he said. ``A member
of the family would never bite or attack.''
</P>
<P>
   The love people feel for their furry best friends is suggested
by the stuff the 28.5 million dog owners buy their pets as
Christmas presents. A new apartment tower being built in
Manhattan's Tribeca neighborhood will offer a ``doggie bar,'' with
water and treats for pups, and ``doghouse room service,'' providing
milk, bottled water and gourmet dog food. The feeling is almost
parental: Ms. Benjamin says that in 20 years as a dog trainer, she
routinely addressed owners as mommy or daddy, and was never
corrected. But to psychiatrists the attachments may be deeper
still.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kenneth Skodnek, chairman of the psychiatry and psychology
department at Nassau County Medical Center in East Meadow, N.Y.,
suggested that dog owners perceive their pets as an extension of
themselves. ``They take everything the pet does or doesn't do very
personally,'' he said. ``If the pet is criticized, they feel
criticized.'' But he said it may be more than even that. ``Pet
owners allow their pets to do things they wouldn't do themselves,''
he said. ``The pet gives them a chance to feel free.''
</P>
<P>
   Such feelings add ferocity and flair to the dog owners'
presentations. At an Avon, Conn., town meeting last summer, more
than 400 showed up with leashes around their necks. They called a
plan to bar dogs from running free in 230-acre Fisher Meadows Park
a crime against nature, and vowed disobedience. But the ban was
supported in a September referendum. Now, Phil Schenck, the town
manager, wants to bring the warring groups together, perhaps to
find some smaller park area where dogs can go at certain times.
``You need to take the emotion out of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the ban are clearly in the majority, Schenck said.
Similarly, the New York City Parks Department says that user
surveys of parks favored by dog users show that most people in the
parks do not come with dogs; it adds that mail is running more than
3-to-1 in favor of its crackdown. In particular, people are irked
that dog owners berate low-paid park rangers, often minorities, as
Nazis, give them names like Eva Braun and exultantly unleash their
dogs after an enforcer goes around the corner. A typical letter:
``I have yet to see a dog owner take anything other than a position
of righteous indignation when someone objected.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate question, perhaps, is what is a dog? Under English
common law, dogs were considered valueless, mere providers of
pleasure as opposed to livestock, which were considered property.
But thinkers from Homer to Freud have invested canines with deeper
importance _ in the same vein as today's dog defenders.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's ultimate aim is not to eliminate pooches but
persuade people to look down on leash-law violators _ just as
people now complain about smokers in restaurants. ``Unleashed dogs
are violating human rights,'' said Parks Commissioner Henry Stern,
owner of Boomer the (leashed) Wonder Dog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
