<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0542 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-WHITE-HOUSE-PSYCH-R     03-15 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-WHITE-HOUSE-PSYCH-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONDERING A WHITE HOUSE SHRINK 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID WALLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the Monica Lewinsky scandal, people are
wondering what can be done to prevent such a mess from ever
occurring again. For one thing, both major parties are poised to
eliminate, or at least eviscerate, the Office of the Independent
Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But how about an Office of the Independent  &UR; Counselor &LR;  instead?
Some experts suggest that to address the problem of people in the
White House who can't control their darker impulses, the country
needs a shrink on call for Chief Executives, their families and top
aides.
</P>
<P>
   The point was underscored by George Stephanopoulos' revelation
in a new memoir last week that he received psychiatric help and
mood-elevating medication to treat anxiety and depression while
Clinton spin doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mental and emotional health treatment is the last political
taboo,'' said Stephanopoulos. ``That was one of the reasons I
resisted seeking help, for fear it would get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Stephanopoulos exhibited classic avoidance behavior when
asked if he would lobby for an Executive Shrink. The White House
also declined to comment on the notion _ even though the Clinton
administration has championed greater access to mental health care
for all Americans, and the president himself has sought counseling
for his problems from clergymen.
</P>
<P>
   Does the notion of an on-call White House shrink seem all that
crazy, in light of the burdens of the presidency and today's
confessional culture?
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to psycho-biographers to ponder whether a White House
psychiatrist could have helped President Clinton curb
self-destructive tendencies. Or if a shrink could have alleviated
President Richard M. Nixon's palpable paranoia, or soothed a
war-haunted President Lyndon B. Johnson. But Fred Greenstein, a
former president of the International Society for the Study of
Political Psychology, considers the presidency too important to be
deprived of immediate psychological support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather have someone who is untreated with his finger
on the button or someone who had some place to vent?'' asked
Greenstein, adding a line from Hamlet: `` `Madness in great ones
must not unwatched go.'''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gilbert, a professor of politics at Northeastern
University and author of ``The Mortal Presidency: Illness and
Anguish in the White House'' (1992), seconds Greenstein's opinion.
He says the White House medical office _ already staffed by five
full-time doctors _ could easily include a psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``As attitudes towards mental dysfunction change, presidents
might find mental health specialists in the White House
increasingly useful,'' writes Gilbert. ``They would be able to
receive treatment for psychological distress in a routine way, and
the country might be spared an emotionally disabled or impaired
chief executive.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear not. Even now, if a president were to suddenly suffer a
severe breakdown, a helicopter filled with security-cleared
psychiatrists would likely land on the White House lawn faster than
you could say, ``So tell me, how long have you been feeling this
way?''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy White House Press Secretary Amy Weiss said the president
can already avail himself of a number of specialists, including a
psychiatrist, at Bethesda Naval Hospital, where presidents undergo
annual physical exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should receive the same type of medical care
that everybody else receives,'' said Dr. Lawrence Mohr, a White
House physician during the Reagan, Bush and Clinton
administrations. Nevertheless, Mohr expressed apprehension about
turning the White House ``into a hospital,'' and saw no reason to
hire a full-time presidential psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did former President Gerald R. Ford. ``I don't see the need
for someone in that discipline being assigned specifically to the
White House medical office,'' said Ford. ``I think I was normal. I
think I am still normal. If I had any problem along that line
develop, the White House can acquire the best almost
instantaneously.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether presidents should undergo a mandatory
psychological exam as part of their annual physical, former
President Jimmy Carter replied: ``No, you don't have a mandatory
requirement in the law to check a president for athlete's foot.''
But he added, ``I believe that mental illness should be considered
with the same import as physical illness.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an unfulfilled wish. Despite Clinton's plea during his
last State of the Union Address that ``no American should ever be
afraid to address'' mental illness, and despite the public's
embrace of ``Analyze This,'' the new mobster-in-therapy hit, there
is considerable doubt over whether Americans are ready to accept a
president on the couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that it may be fine for a mafia boss to have
self-doubts, but not presidents of the United States,'' said Andrew
Kohut, director of the Pew Center for the People and the Press.
``The public wants presidents to steer straight ahead and not look
back, not over-think his hang-ups. The ghost of Thomas Eagleton
still haunts us.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Eagleton was the Democratic senator from Missouri who was
dumped from George McGovern's 1972 presidential ticket over the
disclosure that he had been hospitalized for depression and
received electro-shock therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagleton experience notwithstanding, some say a president
who owned up to psychotherapy might be able to engender public
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than call it a mental health problem, I would couch it
in familial terms,'' suggested Henry Sheinkopf, a Democratic
political consultant. ``If you say my president has a problem that
required counseling because he wanted to protect his family and
children, that's much more palatable. Still, the idea of their
leaders needing help is tough for many Americans to tolerate.''
</P>
<P>
   And it worries Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska. ``The signal to the
world that the American president, the leader of the free world, is
having to get advice as to his mental condition might destabilize a
lot of things, including stock markets and negotiations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zbigniew Brzezinski, Carter's national security adviser, said
there would have to be precautions against a
free-associator-in-chief divulging secrets. ``The psychiatrist
would also probably have to sign a document obligating him to raise
an alarm if he detected serious problems that could affect the
president's ability to govern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if White House doctors judge the president incapable of
performing his duties, they can alert the vice president, who can
then invoke the 25th Amendment. It gives the vice president, backed
by a majority of the Cabinet, the power to remove a disabled
president from office.
</P>
<P>
   Brzezinski, however, said the practical concerns of leadership
could render a White House psychiatrist pretty useless. ``My guess
is that these therapists would be sitting there for four years and
never see the president,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Justin Frank, a Washington, D.C., psychiatrist, who
volunteered in an interview to be the first First Shrink, admits
that the doctor-president relationship might be challenging. ``A
therapist would have to be flexible about makeup sessions,'' said
Frank.
</P>
<P>
   And would the president have the right to know whether his ally
by the 50-minute hour were a Democrat or a Republican?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' said Frank, ``but I would have the right not to tell
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
