<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     03-15 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 21)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BLACK AND BLUE &LR;  By Anna Quindlen. Dell, $7.50. The heroine of
this novel is a Brooklyn nurse who packs up her 10-year-old son and
flees her abusive husband, reinventing herself in Florida and
waiting anxiously for her past to catch up with her. ``Quindlen
understands thrillers, and her story is well constructed,
beautifully paced,'' Maggie Paley wrote in The New York Times Book
Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONSILIENCE: THE UNITY OF KNOWLEDGE &LR;  By Edward O. Wilson.
Vintage, $14. The renowned sociobiologist argues that consilience _
a grand union of knowledge bound by a set of universal laws _ has
been achieved in the natural sciences but needs to be extended to
the humanities and social sciences. Such a vast interweaving of
disciplines is urgently needed, he maintains, to solve global
problems like the destruction of the environment. ``Wilson's book
sweeps across vast areas of learning in lucid, unpretentious, often
eloquent prose,'' Daniel J. Kevles wrote last year. It is ``an
arresting exposition of Wilson's religion of science and a kind of
sermon ... intended to assist in the reform of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALIENS OF AFFECTION: STORIES &LR;  By Padgett Powell. Owl/Holt, $14.
These tales are populated by lively eccentrics and losers who cast
off the bland conformity of contemporary Southern life. ``In all of
the stories there is the good humor and humane intelligence that
make Powell's work so appealing,'' A.O. Scott wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE ONE BEST WAY: FREDERICK WINSLOW TAYLOR AND THE ENIGMA OF
EFFICIENCY &LR;  By Robert Kanigel. Penguin, $17.95. Frederick Winslow
Taylor (1856-1915) helped to reshape industry by arguing that the
key to increased productivity is not raw muscle alone but knowledge
gained by painstaking inspection and measurement and then properly
applied. ``Kanigel's richly detailed biography ... shows how much
drama there was in the mundane when Taylor was making it the stuff
of a new `science' of efficiency,'' George F. Will wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAR: A DRAMA OF THE AMERICAN WORKPLACE &LR;  By Mary Walton. Norton,
$17. This is an account of the radical redesign of the Ford Taurus
for the 1996 model year and a critical analysis of Ford's corporate
culture. ``This is the rare business book that is a page turner,''
Keith Bradsher wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAPA HEMINGWAY: A PERSONAL MEMOIR &LR;  By A.E. Hotchner. Carroll &AMP;
Graf, $13.95. The author was a close friend during the last 14
years of Ernest Hemingway's life, and his admiring account is
filled with gossip, anecdotes and observations of Hemingway's daily
routines, from his obsessive work habits to his fondness for
alcohol sponge baths. ``Part Boswell, part Euripides, Hotchner has
written a greatly detailed and very loving book,'' Vance Bourjaily
wrote in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HEMINGWAY WOMEN &LR;  By Bernice Kert. Norton, $16.95. This book
focuses on the writer's complex relationships with his four wives
and his domineering mother, Grace. The author reserves ``her
highest praise for the women Hemingway hated the most _ especially
his mother,'' Aaron Latham wrote in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HOUSE GUN &LR;  By Nadine Gordimer. Penguin, $12.95. In
post-apartheid South Africa, a liberal white couple are stunned
when their son kills another white man in a crime of passion and
chooses a black lawyer for his defense. Last year the reviewer Jack
Miles called this an ``elegantly conceived, flawlessly executed
novel'' about race, violence and spiritual turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LAST APOCALYPSE: EUROPE AT THE YEAR 1000 A.D. &LR;  By James
Reston Jr. Anchor/Doubleday, $14.95. A.D. 999 was a decisive, if
bloody, year in European history, one in which the continent
finally began to gain ground in its long wars against Viking,
Moorish and Magyar invaders, and Christianity overwhelmed the
forces of paganism. ``Reston constructs a colorful and dramatic
story,'' David Walton wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BARNEY'S VERSION &LR;  By Mordecai Richler. Washington Square/Pocket
Books, $14. Barney Panovsky is a cranky, aging Jewish Canadian who
puts his failing memory to the test when he sets out to refute the
mean things written about him in a rival's autobiography. Barney's
memoir, stretching back to 1950s Paris and covering three marriages
and his best friend's death, manages to offend just about everyone
involved. In 1997 James Shapiro called Richler ``a gifted stylist,
with a great ear for parody and comic dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued  &UR; THE APPRENTICESHIP OF DUDDY
KRAVITZ &LR;  ($14), an earlier novel featuring another of the author's
Jewish anti-heroes, an enterprising hustler who claws his way up
from the mean streets of Montreal. ``The total effect is as brash
and blatant as a sports car rally _ and as suggestive of power,''
Florence Crowther wrote in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GRANDMOTHER'S TALE: AND SELECTED STORIES &LR;  By R.K. Narayan.
Ecco, $16. These stories exploring small-town Brahmin society in
southern India are marked by simple narratives, sharply drawn
characters and a Hindu humanism. In 1994 the reviewer Shashi
Tharoor called the author ``a consummate teller of timeless tales,
a meticulous recorder of the ironies of human life ... India's
answer to Jane Austen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
