<HEADER>
A0581 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEN-AFFLECK-IN-FORCES     03-15 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEN-AFFLECK-IN-FORCES-OF-NATURE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORCE OF ATTRACTION: BEN AFFLECK TRIES HIS HAND AT ROMANTIC
COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Ben Affleck with Sandra Bullock in a
scene from ``Forces of Nature.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF and SHEP MORGAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    He isn't even 27 yet, and Ben Affleck has already won an Academy
Award, become an international celebrity and had a much-publicized
romance with one of Hollywood's hottest actresses.
 &HT;    You can call him an overnight success if you like _ Affleck
won't mind.
 &HT;    ``You get lucky,'' he says. ``You just have to hang onto the
hope that it's going to work out for you at some point. If you
actually considered the odds of becoming successful in Hollywood,
it would become too depressing and demoralizing. You have to
understand it has as much to do with good fortune as it does with
talent and hard work.''
 &HT;    Well, talent doesn't hurt. Affleck was a triple threat in 1997,
when he proved himself as a leading man in Kevin Smith's quirky
independent film ``Chasing Amy,'' then shone as a supporting actor
in the box-office smash ``Good Will Hunting.''
 &HT;    And, oh yes, he and ``Good Will'' co-star Matt Damon also took
home an Oscar for best original screenplay.
 &HT;    The next year wasn't bad, either _ 1998 brought a featured role
in the blockbuster ``Armageddon'' and another eye-catching
supporting turn, this time in the Oscar-nominated ``Shakespeare in
Love.'' It was a part he'd accepted primarily to be close to his
girlfriend Gwyneth Paltrow, the lovely _ and also Oscar-nominated _
star of the Elizabethan-era romance.
 &HT;    Those two years are a tough act to follow, but Affleck will do
his best, starting with ``Forces of Nature,'' a romantic comedy
co-starring Sandra Bullock and opening nationwide on March 19.
 &HT;    Affleck, who was typecast as a tough guy in early roles in films
such as ``Dazed and Confused'' (1993) and ``Mall Rats'' (1996), is
looking forward to his role as a conservative, buttoned-down New
Yorker who, on his way to his wedding in Georgia, encounters a
series of delays and an eccentric, free-spirited young woman
(Bullock) who makes him rethink his life.
 &HT;    ``I'm actually a very firm and devout believer in happily ever
after,'' the actor says. ``I think that's the noblest of all human
endeavors. When you get to the everyday challenge of sharing your
life with somebody, I think the whole is greater than the sum of
the parts.
 &HT;    ``It takes compromise and sacrifice,'' he adds. ``But the ideal
world is where you wake up with the same person every day and feel
lucky to be there, because you support one another.''
 &HT;    Any hopes he had of achieving that goal with Paltrow apparently
were dashed when the couple's much-publicized romance ended
abruptly earlier this year. At least it seemed to end _ but Affleck
and Paltrow were sitting together at the Golden Globe Awards in
January, and he later made a surprise appearance when she
guest-hosted ``Saturday Night Live.''
 &HT;    Affleck won't shed any light on his current status with Paltrow,
but he doesn't mind talking about their ``Saturday Night Live''
duet.
 &HT;    ``So much scurrilous stuff had been written about us that I
thought it would a way to poke fun at the whole aspect of people
caught in the bind of having to lead public lives while trying to
hide their private lives,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``It's like everybody was chasing us, to the point where we felt
like a pair of bizarre little hamsters running on a wheel,'' the
actor says. ``How would you like it if your romances got reported
in the media? I put hexes on those writers. I send them a little
voodoo curse.''
 &HT;    The reality, he admits, is that there's little he can do about
the media's fascination with his love life.
 &HT;    ``It's hard to have a sense of humor, but you have to accept it
and roll your eyes,'' he says. ``You can't win except by being
yourself, and you can't just stay at home alone and worry about it
_ that's no fun.''
 &HT;    Affleck sighs.
 &HT;    ``They had me dating Calista Flockhart,'' he says bemusedly. ``I
think I met her once, at the Golden Globes two years ago. I have no
idea where that came from.
 &HT;    ``Some of the things that are written about me are so bizarre
that I just have to laugh,'' he adds. ``There was a story that I
went and bought every condom in a Wisconsin 7-Eleven. I have never
even been in Wisconsin.
 &HT;    ``But the best part,'' he says with a laugh, ``was that Trojan
sent me a gift basket full of, like, thousands of condoms with a
note that said, `Now you only have to go to 7-Eleven for beer.'''
 &HT;    Anyone wondering about Affleck and Bullock should look
elsewhere. Paltrow was a frequent visitor to the set _ her mother,
Blythe Danner, even has a role in the film _ and, anyway, Affleck
insists that it's far from inevitable that an actor fall in love
with his leading lady.
 &HT;    ``In real life,'' he says, ``you're really looking for another
person that goes beyond the kind of one-line image that the media
has created for them.''
 &HT;    Affleck gives his own image a new twist in ``Force of Nature,''
when he is forced into doing an impromptu striptease in a bar. Yes,
he drops his pants _ it was his shirt that he kept on, actually.
 &HT;    ``There's a reason,'' the actor explains. ``I have tattoos on my
shoulders, and if I had taken my shirt off they would have had to
cover them with makeup, because they wouldn't have fit my
character. That's a laborious process which I went through on
another film, and I'll do anything to avoid it.
 &HT;    ``But I worked hard on my moves when I was stripping,'' he adds
with a grin. ``I was hedging my bets, thinking maybe I could
develop a second career. I'm always ready to pick up another
trade.''
 &HT;    While Affleck is obviously kidding, he doesn't deny that there
were times early in his Hollywood career when he couldn't help
wondering about other lines of work.
 &HT;    ``I remember auditioning for `Beverly Hills 90210' when I really
needed money,'' he says. ``I had never watched the series, and I
kind of did what I thought was a very subtle reading. Even though
it was a romantic part, I didn't want it to be a cliche.
 &HT;    ``The next day the producers called my agent and told them how
terrible I was,'' he recalls. ``They basically said, `Your guy had
so little energy we could hardly hear him. I guarantee you he will
never appear on `Beverly Hills 90210!'
 &HT;    ``And my agent was screaming at me, `Who do you think you are,
Marlon Brando? You were auditioning for a teen series!'''
 &HT;    Chances are that Affleck could get on the show nowadays at the
drop of a hat, given the teen following he's acquired since playing
the guy who got the girl (Liv Tyler) and risked his life to save
the world in ``Armageddon.'' But the actor remains ambivalent about
his image as a hunk.
 &HT;    ``I think it's a mistake to get caught up in how the media is
categorizing you,'' he says. ``It's easy to become a canvas on
which the audience and the media paint their own fantasies. All you
can do as an actor is to try and be your best, without trying to
live up to what you think people want you to be.
 &HT;    ``The upside,'' Affleck adds, ``is that you get a kick out of
being successful, which is a rarity for any actor who's had to
struggle. You get perks and opportunities that you never knew
existed.
 &HT;    ``The downside is that you not only give up your privacy, you're
known for who people think you are from what they see up there on
the big screen. And that means they don't really know you at all.''
 c.1999 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeanne Wolf and Shep Morgan are Hollywood-based free-lance
writers.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
