<HEADER>
A0582 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERT-CARLYLE-IN-RAV     03-15 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERT-CARLYLE-IN-RAVENOUS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOT FREE: ROBERT CARLYLE HAS GONE HOLLYWOOD, AND HE'S HAVING A
BALL 
</HEADLINE>
  Includes a color slide of Robert Carlyle in a scene from
``Ravenous.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    No wonder so many people want to kill James Bond.
 &HT;    Take Robert Carlyle, the Scottish actor who will play the
villain in the latest Bond installment, ``The World is Not
Enough.''
 &HT;    As Bond, Pierce Brosnan drives a cool Aston-Martin car with all
the latest accessories, including the newest ``Bond girl,'' Denise
Richards. Between stunts, he finds time to down yet another martini
_ shaken, naturally, but not stirred.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, Carlyle's character is actually dying even before the
film starts. With a bullet lodged in his brain, he's utterly
ruthless because he has literally nothing to lose.
 &HT;    ``Look, I don't really want to dominate James' world. I just
want to blow it up,'' Carlyle says with a maniacal laugh. ``I'm a
total destructo!''
 &HT;    If the star of the down-and-dirty British films
``Trainspotting'' (1996) and ``The Full Monty'' (1997) seems out of
place in the jet-set world of James Bond, he's equally incongruous
in Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel, where he's visiting briefly to
meet the press for his new film, ``Ravenous.''
 &HT;    The 38-year-old actor walks in still yawning and rubbing his
head _ which is almost completely bald for his Bond duties. Still,
he looks fit and handsome in jeans and a black Hugo Boss suit
jacket.
 &HT;    It's shortly after breakfast _ which is just as well, because
``Ravenous,'' which co-stars Guy Pearce, Jeffrey Jones, Jeremy
Davies and David Arquette, deals with the not-exactly-appetizing
subject of cannibalism.
 &HT;    Set in 1847 America, it concerns a group of settlers who, on
their way west, are forced to take shelter in an isolated cave. One
thing leads to another, and ... well, let's just say that Carlyle's
character develops a whole new culinary philosophy.
 &HT;    Even after ``Trainspotting'' and ``The Full Monty,'' this is
material which is, to put it mildly, noncommercial.
 &HT;    ``I don't consider the life consequences, career consequences or
other people's sensibilities when I choose a role,'' Carlyle says
calmly. ``I don't think it's my job to worry about these matters.
Some actors do, of course, but I don't want to build a whole career
on how I think people will perceive my every move.''
 &HT;    Which is good, because ``Ravenous'' is sure to be controversial.
Even the cast was caught up in debate, the actor recalls, with
daily discussions on and off the set about cannibalism and the
inescapable question, ``Would you if you had to?''
 &HT;    ``The subject is infinitely fascinating,'' Carlyle says. ``I
think, without a doubt, I'd do it. What I believe in is the
survival instinct, which is the most powerful emotion we have _
you're always going to try to keep your nose above the water.''
 &HT;    His next three films, all due this year, are on more
conventional themes. They include ``Plunkett and MacLeane,'' a
period film about two highwaymen, with Liv Tyler co-starring. Then
comes ``The World Is Not Enough,'' followed by the big-screen
adaptation of Frank McCourt's best-selling memoir, ``Angela's
Ashes,'' directed by Alan Parker and co-starring Oscar nominee
Emily Watson.
 &HT;    Carlyle has only recently completed filming ``Angela's Ashes''
on location in Dublin, which movie magic turned into the grim
Limerick of McCourt's youth.
 &HT;    ``Every single morning, I had dirt applied all over my body,''
the actor recalls, grimacing. ``It was disgusting. We actually had
a pot on the set called `Standard Grime.' They would take out this
bucket and slop it all over you. It really messed up your skin.''
 &HT;    It was an anything-but-glamorous development in a career that
has already offered a fair number of unexpected twists for the
Glasgow-born son of two house painters, who originally planned to
follow in their footsteps.
 &HT;    ``I was 24 years old and working as a house painter,'' he
recalls. ``But then a friend of mine gave me a copy of `The
Crucible.' When I read this great work, I thought, `How fantastic
to be able to talk to the world about important issues!'
 &HT;    ``It seemed like a beautiful way to make a living.''
 &HT;    Talking to the world was one thing, but doing it in a Scottish
accent was another. Even in drama school he had to fight against
pressure to homogenize his speech.
 &HT;    ``Early on,'' he recalls, ``a professor said to me, `You'll
never work because you refuse to change your accent.'''
 &HT;    Actually, however, Carlyle has worked steadily, usually as
morally challenged characters in grittily realistic British films
and television shows.
 &HT;    After reaching more or less the extreme as ``Trainspotting's''
repellent thug Begbie, a guy who delighted in ``glassing'' _
shoving people's faces through glass windows or doors _ Carlyle was
looking for a more human, sympathetic role. He found it in ``The
Full Monty'' as Gaz, an unemployed, divorced father who finally
resorts to joining his similarly downsized mates in staging a strip
show.
 &HT;    ``To me that film is still about gender politics,'' he says.
``It's about men suddenly having to look at themselves in the way
that men have been looking at women for years.''
 &HT;    And about women looking at them, which is a lingering sensitive
point. The final scene of the film involves an audience of hundreds
of women whooping and cheering the blue-collar strippers. Audiences
for the film saw it only from behind, but the women on the set
actually saw ... well, the fuller Monty.
 &HT;    ``Filming that strip scene was the most terrifying thing in my
whole life,'' Carlyle says, looking like he might blush even now.
``I would never do it again, no matter how much money was involved.
 &HT;    ``We didn't have on that little sock that most men use in nude
scene,'' he says, stammering. ``Consequently I felt so exposed.
Plus there were 300 women out in the audience watching us.''
 &HT;    Fortunately, he adds with a laugh, they weren't equipped with
cameras.
 &HT;    ``Thank God they didn't have them,'' he says. ``I would faint if
I saw those pictures on the Internet.''
 &HT;    The international success of ``The Full Monty'' made him at
least a modest-scale movie star, a development which he never
expected.
 &HT;    ``It stuns me,'' he admits. ``If I would have predicted that
one, I probably would also be giving you lottery numbers today.''
 &HT;    He insists that celebrity hasn't affected his life, which is
focused on his wife Anna, a makeup artist.
 &HT;    ``We don't have an entourage,'' he says. ``I don't live that
way. My wife doesn't want a fur coat, and we already have a house.
So our lives haven't changed on that level.
 &HT;    ``Obviously, the one thing you are never prepared for as an
actor is a precious little thing called choice,'' Carlyle adds.
``That's the biggest thing in my life _ I never believed that there
would come a day when I could choose what work I wanted to do. It's
amazing. But it's also a pressure _ once you have choice, you don't
want to lose it.''
 &HT;    Part of his reason for choosing to be a Bond baddie was to offer
an homage to his personal hero.
 &HT;    ``I used to go see the James Bond films with my father in the
early '60s and '70s, when Sean Connery was playing Bond,'' he
recalls. ``To me, he was the only Scottish actor. He was the only
one who worked, and he sounded like me. So that link between
Connery and Bond and acting and Scots was fundamental for me.''
 &HT;    Last year he finally met Connery in person.
 &HT;    ``He is my hero,'' Carlyle says, ``so I didn't say much. I could
just stammer out how much I appreciated his work and he said,
`That's nice, son.' Those three words were enough inspiration for
me.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
