<HEADER>
A0584 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEVE-MARTIN-IN-THE-O     03-15 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEVE-MARTIN-IN-THE-OUT-OF-TOWNERS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE MARTIN: STILL WILD BUT NOT AS CRAZY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Steve Martin with Goldie Hawn in a scene
from ``The Out-of-Towners.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Steve Martin and Goldie Hawn can't help being funny together.
 &HT;    Case study: Hawn has just finished chatting with a group of
journalists at Los Angeles' Four Seasons Hotel, and Martin is on
deck. They're there to promote their second film together, ``The
Out-of-Towners,'' a remake of the 1970 Jack Lemmon-Sandy Dennis
comedy.
 &HT;    As Hawn rises to leave and Martin appears in the doorway, a
journalist asks Hawn who designed her outfit.
 &HT;    The actress scrunches her face.
 &HT;    ``I don't know,'' she says.
 &HT;    Martin is happy to help out, loping forward to tug on the collar
of Hawn's sweater and examine its label.
 &HT;    ``It's a Marnie,'' he says.
 &HT;    And the skirt? Martin, clearly enjoying himself, heads south to
inspect another label.
 &HT;    ``Your pantyhose are by ... '' he says jokingly, then reads the
skirt label aloud: ``Handmade, hand wash in cold ... ''
 &HT;    Everyone laughs, Hawn included, and then the actress heads out
and leaves the stage to Martin, a funnyman who these days is funny
only when he wants to be.
 &HT;    ``The Out-of-Towners'' is one of those times. Opening nationwide
on April 2, it casts Martin and Hawn _ who first teamed for
``Housesitter'' (1992) _ as a long-married Ohio couple confronting
empty-nest syndrome. Their answer is a trip to New York in quest of
a restored spark to their marriage, but the journey quickly
deteriorates into a barrage of muggings, arrests, drug-induced
strange behavior and frustrating encounters with a haughty hotel
manager (John Cleese).
 &HT;    The idea for the remake came from Paramount Pictures chief
Sherry Lansing, recalls Martin, who says he loved the original
film.
 &HT;    ``Sherry Lansing had the idea, and I felt that the
antidisestablishmentarianism of the situation ... '' he stops as
reporters' pens clatter in dismay, then laughs.
 &HT;    ``No, it was Sherry's idea,'' he says more conventionally. ``It
sounded good. Then I got a little cold feet, but Goldie convinced
me. She said, `I think this movie is really about something
important. I think it's about what happens when the kids are grown
_ how does a couple that's been busy for 19 years get back together
and what are they going to do?'
 &HT;    ``I thought that was a good topic,'' he says, ``and the script
started developing in that specific direction.''
 &HT;    On the set, the actor reports, he and Hawn _ both veteran
comedians whose work has turned more serious of late _ relished the
give-and-take of an out-and-out comedy.
 &HT;    ``We make each other laugh,'' he says. ``That gives you a lot of
encouragement. A lot of things were boldly ad-libbed, and they
worked.
 &HT;    ``We both came up in television,'' Martin adds, ``and there's a
great quickness and expediency about television. We're both
expedient, and we both know that to worry something to death kills
it. So we'd say, `Let's just try it. Let's just do it.'''
 &HT;    There was a time when Martin made a movie or two every year.
These days he turns up onscreen less often, and when he does it's
less likely to be in a zany, highly commercial comedy than in a
smaller drama such as ``The Spanish Prisoner'' (1998) or something
he himself wrote, such as the upcoming ``Bowfinger.''
 &HT;    ``I was talking with a friend the other day,'' he says, ``and we
said that the problem today is that the only success is a total
success. We don't take pride in artistic success or a medium
success _ Hollywood only views success as total success.''
 &HT;    Besides, he's becoming more and more active offscreen,
particularly as a writer. A turning point was ``Picasso at the
Lapin Agile'' (1995), the highly acclaimed stage play that explored
the creative and scientific processes.
 &HT;    ``In a weird way I think the writing has helped my acting,'' he
says. ``When you do the same thing over and over you get better,
but you also get disconnected from it. Writing is very direct _
it's you and the paper, and it's coming out of your heart.
 &HT;    ``When I wrote the play I thought, `Why can't I write a
screenplay in the same spirit as I wrote the play?''' he recalls.
``I didn't care about anything, and I didn't think anybody was even
going to see `Picasso.'
 &HT;    ``So I gave it a shot with `Bowfinger.'''
 &HT;    Directed by Frank Oz _ who put Martin through his paces in
``Little Shop of Horrors'' (1986), ``Dirty Rotten Scoundrels''
(1988) and ``Housesitter'' _ ``Bowfinger'' stars Martin and Eddie
Murphy, and will reach theaters this summer.
 &HT;    ``It's about a loser movie producer who tries to get a movie
made with a big star who refuses to do it,'' says Martin, who plays
the producer to Murphy's actor. ``We decide to make the movie
anyway, with him in it, but without telling him.
 &HT;    ``Eddie is so talented it makes me sick.''
 &HT;    Being a screenwriter _ which he has been since ``Roxanne''
(1987) _ is only one of Martin's accomplishments. In a career which
has had more than its share of ups and downs, he's passed through
myriad incarnations as a magician, a stand-up comedian, a comedy
writer for hire, a frequent guest host of ``Saturday Night Live,''
a stage and screen actor, a playwright and a short-story author, to
name only the high points.
 &HT;    But it was his years as a stand-up comic which set the stage for
everything else. Martin regularly sold out 20,000-seat arenas in
his heyday as the ``wild and crazy guy'' who kept a fish in his
pocket and walked about the stage with an arrow through his head.
 &HT;    The wild and crazy guy made Martin famous, the first stand-up
comic to achieve rock-star levels of success. But eventually he
abandoned the fish, the arrow and the stand-up routine altogether.
And while there are certain aspects of that persona in the goofy
physical comedy of ``The Out-of-Towners,'' he says he's never
really looked back.
 &HT;    ``I don't miss it,'' he says. ``Ever. It's a very hard thing to
do. It's hard because you stake everything on every show, and they
can't all be great.
 &HT;    ``So many things can be wrong,'' he adds. ``The audience or you
or the microphone. Those great shows stand out, which means the
rest of them were not that good.''
 &HT;    At 53, with little concern about box-office numbers or star
perks and with the confidence of an actor who can afford to age _
since his livelihood was never predicated on movie-star looks or
sex appeal _ Martin can pretty much do what he wants when he wants.
 &HT;    It's an enviable position, and one that is rare in Hollywood,
especially for women.
 &HT;    ``It's much harder for women, even young actresses,'' he says.
``If you're known at 22 for being a sexy girl, then at 28 there's
the next sexy girl, unless you've established something.
 &HT;    ``That's the accomplishment of Goldie and Diane Keaton, but
especially Goldie,'' he says. ``She was the young, sexy girl, but
she transcended it through, I think, being the kind of person she
is. Goldie's talented _ really smart, astute and direct.''
 &HT;    As for himself, Martin says he's perfectly at ease with growing
older. The shock of white hair that made him look older when he was
in his late 20s now lets him merely look his age.
 &HT;    He also feels more comfortable with himself, personally and
professionally, he adds.
 &HT;    ``It's better,'' he says, hunting for words. ``Through time,
people respect you. People are not just using you. They're
awestruck sometimes.''
 &HT;    And then he smiles.
 &HT;    ``They're more polite than in the old days, when people would
come up to me and say `Be funny!'''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
