<HEADER>
A0588 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-     03-15 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEHIND-THE-SCENES-ON-LAW-&AMP;-ORDER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `LAW' OF INCREASING RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Steven Hill, Angie Harmon and Sam
Waterston in a scene from ``Law &AMP; Order.'' 
 By SIMON HOUPT  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Robert Altman's movie ``The Player'' (1992), Peter Gallagher
plays a movie-studio executive who suggests eliminating writers
from the creative process.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he argues, it's easy to come up with stories _ simply
pick any article out of a newspaper. He demonstrates by reading a
random headline: ``Further Bond Losses Push Dow Down 7.15
Percent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Connery as Bond,'' a sycophantic sidekick chimes in.
</P>
<P>
   It was satire then, but one of the most successful shows on
television has turned the idea of ``ripped from the headlines''
plots into a weekly triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order'' has enjoyed nine seasons of escalating success
on the strength of real crime stories transformed into compelling,
compact and morally complex dramas. Recently renewed for its 10th
season, the series will celebrate its 200th episode in May and
shows no signs of slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   What's its secret?
</P>
<P>
   ``More narrative in 45 minutes than most people get from four or
five feature films,'' says Sam Waterston, who is in his fifth
season as Assistant District Attorney Jack McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories don't condescend to the audience,'' the actor
adds, ``and you get a new perspective on stuff that's in the news.
I think it helps people to think about current events.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Orbach is ideally qualified to assess the show's appeal:
In his seventh season as the languid Detective Lennie Briscoe,
Orbach has been prowling the ``Law &AMP; Order'' set longer than any
other principal-cast member except Steven Hill (District Attorney
Adam Schiff). He sees the show in terms of the classical Japanese
theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone said to me recently, `It's like kabuki,''' Orbach
says. ``It has a very structured form. You know you're going to see
a mystery solved in the first half, then the trial and the
resolution by the end of it. It's a nice, neat package, and I think
people get hooked on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so. ``Law &AMP; Order'' is one of the few shows on
television _ ``Seinfeld'' and ``Hill Street Blues'' also come to
mind _ to beat back early threats of cancellation and blossom into
hits. In addition to its Wednesday-night slot on NBC, the show
plays in reruns on A&AMP;E where, despite airing four times a day, it
has actually increased its audience since launching on cable in
fall 1994.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of popularity breeds security in a show's staff, which
may help explain the strong sense of jovial camaraderie on the
Manhattan sound stage where the show is filmed.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent Friday-afternoon shoot, half the principal cast
was laughing like high-school students on the last day of class. S.
Epatha Merkerson and Angie Harmon (Lt. Anita Van Buren and
Assistant District Attorney Abbie Carmichael) were enthusiastically
singing off-key Neil Sedaka tunes for Waterston and the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that, as soon as the director called ``Action,'' the
trio would slide into a dour grilling of a murder suspect in the
show's familiar, drab-green interrogation room. Never mind that,
week after week, the three _ along with Orbach, Hill and Benjamin
Bratt (Detective Ray Curtis) _ adopt a bewildered melancholy for
their roles. Despite it all, the cast and crew call themselves
``the family,'' a label that says everything about the cheery
nature of their relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see each other there's smiles, there's hugs, there's
kisses,'' Merkerson says. ``They genuinely love me and I genuinely
love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon, in her first season on the show, has particular praise
for the veteran Waterston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's brilliant,'' she says. ``I'm a perfectionist, and he's
taught me so much. I usually learn something from Sam at least once
a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, one of the show's strengths has been the
parity among its cast _ no one actor has stood above the other
members of the ensemble or pulled focus away from the show itself.
Heavyweight actors such as Michael Moriarty and Paul Sorvino have
come and gone, along with six other principals, but ``Law &AMP; Order''
keeps on keeping on.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this ensemble quality has made the show a tough sell.
Without a single marquee star like, say, Jennifer Aniston from
``Friends,'' viewers take longer to warm to a series. It has thus
been an unintentional, though hardly unwelcome, experience for
``Law &AMP; Order'' to find itself benefiting from the tabloid hoopla
over Bratt's relationship with Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all love Ben,'' Merkerson says, sounding like an approving
older sister. ``The attention tickles me, because he really is a
great guy, so whatever press he gets, as long as it's positive, I
think it's great for the show and it's great for him. He's one of
the good guys.''
</P>
<P>
   During a break in filming, Orbach agrees. But he also has a
partial explanation for Bratt's appeal, offered in a conspiratorial
whisper.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ben first came on the show,'' he says, ``I said, `Get him
to take his shirt off once. Let's see him in his strapped T-shirt
once, so the ladies will know what's under the suit. I want them to
see that this guy is like Schwarzenegger!'''
</P>
<P>
   Later, on location in Brooklyn, Bratt hears about this and
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that hysterical,'' he says, almost embarrassed. ``On
most levels the attention is a bother, mostly because my personal
life truly is no one else's business.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I understand the curiosity it holds for people,'' he
admits, ``because I, like most other people from time to time,
enjoy my little bits of gossip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just when it's focused on me, it's a bit more
irritating,'' he finishes with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   That attention is at its most immediate when ``Law &AMP; Order''
goes on location, which it does for roughly four of each episode's
eight shooting days. Though the Texas-born Harmon could do without
the subfreezing winter shoots, she adds that she loves the
opportunity to get onto the streets where the shows are actually
set.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing better than us working on the court steps,''
she says, ``and the real assistant DAs and the real cops walk by
and say, `Way to go, Harmon!'''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone even notices them, though. After all, this is New
York, where people tend to be blase about even such things as
television shoots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry and Ben had a scene once where they were shooting
outside, and they thought they had closed off the block,''
Merkerson recalls. ``But somebody got through. The guy whisked
between them as they were doing the scene. They just looked at each
other and continued on with the scene, and that was the take that
was used.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth season that Bratt and Orbach have been paired
onscreen, but no one knows how long the team will continue. Bratt
has talked about leaving for other projects _ he and his brother
Peter produced ``Follow Me Home,'' an award-winning film that
played at the Sundance Film Festival two years ago _ and the show
changes principal actors on a fairly regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cast changes have kept it interesting for the audience,''
Orbach says. ``People get fired, they move, they have a baby or
they get transferred, you know? It's kind of like life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Simon Houpt is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
