<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONNERLY16-COX     03-15 1585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONNERLY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Connerly: Race has no place in government
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ward Connerly has been called everything from a
traitor to his race to a courageous champion of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, a Sacramento, Calif., businessman, is the architect of
affirmative action bans in California and Washington state. As
chairman of the American Civil Rights Coalition, he is on a mission
to add more states to the list.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly traces his interest in ending affirmative action to
1994, a year after he was appointed to the University of California
System's Board of Regents. Two constituents, Jerry and Helen Cook,
convinced him that their son, James, had been denied admission to
the University of California-San Diego medical school because he
was white. Connerly said he found that the school was giving too
much weight to race in an effort to make the school racially
diverse.
</P>
<P>
   With support from then-Gov. Pete Wilson, Connerly persuaded the
regents in 1995 to end racial considerations in admissions and then
pursued a ballot proposition. In November 1996, the state's voters
endorsed his efforts and ended affirmative action programs. Two
years later, Washington voters followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who gives his age as ``59 going on 80,'' was in Austin
last week to support the Campaign for a Colorblind America, which
is backing legislation to end racial and gender considerations in
Texas, including in state hiring and contracting. Affirmative
action is no longer used in Texas colleges because of a federal
appeals court ruling in what is known as the Hopwood case.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly spoke with American-Statesman reporter Mary Ann Roser.
An edited text of his remarks follows:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you believe we have attained a colorblind society?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't care whether we have a colorblind society; I want my
government to be colorblind.
</P>
<P>
   When you see the blindfolded woman holding the scales of
justice, it's saying, ``Government is colorblind.'' I don't think
we will ever become a colorblind society by practicing race
consciousness. It just imbeds race more into our culture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But as you know, affirmative action was started to remedy a
history of discrimination against blacks. They went through slavery
and haven't been in the middle class that long.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't live in the past. I live right now. I see all of the
success stories of black people and the accomplishments many have
made, mostly on their own. And I see a society that is for the most
part improving. More is to be gained building on the positive
rather than building on a negative paradigm. That negative paradigm
is saying to blacks, ``You can't do it on your own without help
from the white people.''
</P>
<P>
   That fosters the very prejudice people start off with _ that
blacks aren't smart. We then take that prejudice and perpetuate it.
. . . We're better off sometimes to give people tough love. I'm
finding that Asians and Latinos are assimilating into American
life, and blacks are the last to do it. . . . I blame it on black
families.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why are you interested in what happens in other states, and
what is your ultimate goal?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the Congress or the Supreme Court would act, my interest
would cease to exist. But the Congress will not act on this issue .
. . because the Jesse Jacksons of the world and the NAACP will
protest and call people racists. Despite what the president said
about wanting to have a dialogue on race, when the rubber hits the
road, these organizations that want to defend race-based
affirmative action don't want to have a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   What I'm trying to do is keep the ball rolling until the Supreme
Court says whether Bakke is the law of the land. (The 1978 Supreme
Court's Bakke decision said race could be among an array of factors
considered in university admissions but not the sole factor.)
Saying race should be among the factors is like saying you're a
little bit pregnant. . . . There's no such thing as race being one
of many factors. They're taking this as a loophole and driving Mack
trucks through it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the extent of your campaign?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would like to get two or three more critical states to
embrace initiatives like Proposition 209 in California and
Initiative 200 in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Texas one of them?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, Texas doesn't have the initiative process. I'm looking at
Nebraska, Oregon, Colorado, Michigan and Florida . . . iven the
situation in California and Texas, if we're able to get Florida, we
would have a large segment of society living under a race-free
system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand Florida Gov. Jeb Bush wasn't very welcoming.
</P>
<P>
   A: He met with me, but he doesn't want to pursue an initiative,
and I understand why. He's put together a coalition based on race.
When you put together a rainbow coalition, you don't want someone
like Ward Connerly coming in and upsetting the apple cart. He was
concerned about how black legislators would react. . . . One black
legislator said, quote, he should take his little butt back to
California and leave it there, unquote. It was the same thing they
said about civil rights workers in Selma. As a national taxpayer, I
think I have a legitimate right to participate in the deliberations
of that state.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many people believe blacks and Latinos score below whites and
Asians on achievement tests because they are not getting an
adequate education in K through 12. Should they be excluded from
the best universities when they can graduate and succeed there?
</P>
<P>
   A: No one's excluding anyone. We're saying these are the rules
of the game. We're not basing decisions on racial or ethnic
characteristics. There are middle-class blacks who are going to
suburban schools and getting preferences to go to college.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you using test scores as the standard of who should get
into an elite school?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not saying test scores are the sole measures, but GPA and
SAT scores are reliable, and I don't think there's any cultural
bias. Whatever standard you use, apply it equally. I do not accept
that some schools are inferior to others, and therefore, we should
only give black people, Latinos and Native Americans some kind of
break across the board. There are Asians and low-income whites
going there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think there is no discrimination against minority
groups?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's discrimination against fat people, and there's
discrimination against gays, too, and none of it's justified. The
solution to ending discrimination is eradicating the prejudice. The
prejudice is that blacks cannot succeed without a preference.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you do about teachers who have lower expectations of
minority students, and those students, in turn, get lower test
scores and grades?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm told the same thing about poor white trash. The problem
to me is not one that has a racial genesis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you ever benefited from affirmative action?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think I may have been appointed to the Board of Regents
because the governor was trying to diversify the board. But I must
remind you, regents serve 12-year sentences, unpaid, and if that's
a benefit, God help me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's prestigious.
</P>
<P>
   A: It might be prestigious, but if someone walks up to you in
the airport and threatens you, you can stick that prestige in your
ear.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do you feel compelled to be in this fight?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've always believed in integration and taking people at
their merits. I'm in an interracial marriage. My wife is Irish. In
this nation, checking these boxes (on census forms, etc.) is
something I abhor. I believe the day has to come when the American
people will say to their government: ``Stop it. We don't want you
classifying us by race.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You don't like to be called an African American. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: I wasn't born in Africa, I haven't been there, and I'm not
going there. I think someone who was born in Africa and becomes an
American citizen is an African American. I'm an American citizen
and am partly of African descent, about an eighth or so. I have
more Irish blood and more Native American blood. Why should I
follow the one rule that says one drop of black blood makes you
black? African American is a social term. It is a politically
correct term. I simply refuse to use that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you feel uncomfortable in your skin?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not at all. If I could choose to have a color, it would be
this. I know you mean no harm, but I really resent that if I take
the position that affirmative action is wrong, I am somehow engaged
in self-loathing, as some of my detractors say. We should be able
to take political positions without someone ascribing psychological
conditions to us. I'm very comfortable in my skin color, but I
don't believe we should have these categories.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you feel lonely when you're confronted by other blacks?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lonely, yes, because they are American citizens and they
don't understand what I'm about.
</P>
<P>
   I was on the ``Chris Rock Show,'' and he asked me, ``Why are you
doing this?'' I told him, and he said: ``You're probably right.
It's just hard for black people to come to terms with it.'' I'm not
doing this to take anything away from black people or Latinos. I'm
doing this because I want black people to become self-reliant and
not stand on the outside looking in. The fruits of American
democracy are there for us to pick off the tree. The day is come
for us to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
