<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: David vs. Goliath in indoor soccer
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I've spent many weekends sitting on cold metal
bleachers at soccer games with icy, gale-force winds blowing in my
face, bemoaning that none of my sons chose to play basketball or
swim _ you know, cozy indoor sports.
</P>
<P>
   So you'd think I'd be thrilled when our youngest son had the
chance to play indoor soccer this winter. It's a wonderful
opportunity between the fall and spring seasons to put another
10,000 miles on our SUV _ soccer utility vehicle _ traveling to
Dallas for all the games.
</P>
<P>
   We passed on the opportunity. We did agree, though, that our son
could be a substitute player if needed. He was needed.
</P>
<P>
   With the team seriously depleted by spring break trips, our son
got called in for the last weekend of games to determine the season
championship. So there we were, sitting in a nice,
climate-controlled environment with restrooms, a concession stand
and pro shop. I warmed to the sport right away, despite the
constantly blaring rap music.
</P>
<P>
   As best I can tell, indoor soccer is a blend of ``regular''
soccer, ice hockey and roller derby. The artificial-turf field is
encircled by a wall about 4 feet tall, topped with netting that
also covers the ceiling. As in hockey, the pace is fast and
relentless and the boards are a key part of the game _ just ask any
kid who gets bounced off of them.
</P>
<P>
   Our guys handled the first team easily, surging ahead quickly
and staying there. The second game _ which was for the season
championship _ proved more difficult, for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious was that at least two of the players on the
opposing team of 11- and 12-year-olds were nearly 6 feet tall,
close to 170 pounds and had facial hair. Now, as the mother of
three sons, I understand how fickle hormones can be during puberty.
They can sneak up on a guy between his morning Pop Tart and his
afternoon Bagel Bites and leave him 6 inches taller with a voice
suddenly hitting octaves known only to Swiss yodelers.
Nevertheless, these boys were huge.
</P>
<P>
   I hurriedly conferred with fellow parents and was assured that
all birth certificates had been carefully checked and that these
were not, as I had first assumed, 17-year-olds who had been held
back.
</P>
<P>
   Despite valiant play by our team, we lost that final game
resoundingly, 6-2. But then, in a complicated system I only
understood later, we suddenly had 3 more minutes on the clock and
the scoreboard was back to 0-0. With that 6-2 victory, the other
team had tied us for first place on points tallied throughout the
season. The championship was to be decided in six minutes of
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The team that scores first wins _ sudden death, and when I saw
that my baby was paired against one of those behemoths, I thought
it might be just that.
</P>
<P>
   It was a classic David and Goliath matchup. My son's head came
almost to his opponent's chest _ almost. He was outweighed by
probably 90 pounds. My heart sprang to my throat and stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   With about two minutes left in the game, speed and lesser size
came to this David's advantage as he sped past the lumbering giant,
kicked the ball through his towering legs (I'm not sure, but I
think he may have run through the guy's legs, too), picked up the
ricochet off the boards and slingshot it into the corner of the
goal.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd _ and our team _ went wild! It was one of those rare
moments you cherish after spending endless hours at soccer games
and practices for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Life doesn't often hand us such nice endings, when the
scoreboard is set back to 0-0 and more time is added to the clock.
But it sure is sweet when it does.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
