<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: System rage: A hard kick to high tech
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Lane
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Every newspaper's oral lore includes at
least one story about an overwrought reporter throwing a
typewriter. Maybe out a window. Maybe at an editor.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has changed that. Even the most sedentary editors
have time to run before you can heave a monitor at them. Throwing a
computer out a window is hard to do spontaneously. It takes heavy
lifting.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't stop people from trying.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey by a Massachusetts-based computer-network consulting
firm, 83 percent of computer network managers complained that
enraged users smashed their computers.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard was the most-cited victim, according to Concord
Communications' ``Network Rage Survey.'' Nineteen percent of
network managers reported keyboards smashed on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   This is understandable. Keyboards are just right to grasp on
either side and crack squarely in half on a desk's edge. Their
cords, however, make them hard to throw. If you have it together
enough to unplug a standard, six-pin DIN connector, you probably
are too self-possessed to throw the thing out a window.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike typewriters, which are heavy enough to break through
glass for maximum dramatic effect. A keyboard rebounds helplessly
off the pane while everyone watches and you feel stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Or so people tell me.
</P>
<P>
   Second place in the survey was a tie with 17 percent of network
managers reporting either shattered monitors and beaten mice.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad that some people will take out their anger on a
helpless little mouse. But it is neat to twirl them menacingly over
your head.
</P>
<P>
   Or so people tell me.
</P>
<P>
   Monitor violence is more understandable. Where blocked writers
used to stare at a blank piece of paper until their eyes lost
focus, they now stare at a Super VGA monitor until their eyes lose
focus. Huge progress.
</P>
<P>
   A monitor bears the additional burden of being the bearer of bad
news. That's where error messages flash.
</P>
<P>
   ``A system error has occurred. Please reload. All your work will
be converted into stray electrons that will evaporate like a summer
rain _ OK?''
</P>
<P>
   There is something devilish about being forced to click buttons
that say ``OK,'' when things are not remotely OK.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of paper is you can fight it. Wad it into tight
balls. Throw it against walls. Set it ablaze in extreme instances.
Monitors have a way of exploding when you try to do those things.
</P>
<P>
   Or so people tell me.
</P>
<P>
   A small but significant minority of those surveyed _ 4 percent _
said their system users kicked computer hard drives hard to death.
</P>
<P>
   This is made possible by vertical CPU cases that stand on the
floor. A person used to be forced to climb on a chair to administer
a good, swift kick to a hard drive. You can destroy amounts of data
undreamed of 10 years ago and without undue exertion. This, too, is
great progress.
</P>
<P>
   The computer managers surveyed also volunteered horror stories
about computer users who became enraged on seeing the message
``push any key'' and not finding a key marked ``any.''
</P>
<P>
   Another told of a user who fumed when her e-mail wouldn't go
through even though she included a zip code.
</P>
<P>
   Another told of a user who when told to ``insert next disk'' did
so _ on top of the other two already stuck in the drive.
</P>
<P>
   Will Calmas, a Boston-based workplace psychologist, analyzed the
survey and says this wreckage is an all-too predictable symptom of
worker isolation. Companies will spend millions on new computers,
he observed, but fail to invest in the people who work them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have other outlets for getting out their
frustration,'' he said. Cubicle dwellers don't know where to
complain and are embarrassed to ask questions. They are left angry,
untrained and alone with a frustrating box. The result: People push
the ``reset'' button _ hard, with their wingtips.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests businesses should either pay attention to the
people at the keyboards or develop a keyboard that can bounce off a
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Rageproof hardware could become all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
