</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The origin of fables
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Payton is 13 and he has a problem. ``I'm
short, Ms. Schuett,'' he complained one day after class. I didn't
tell him I'd already noticed that. ``I'm never going to grow any
more because I smoked some cigarettes when I was 8. It was my
cousin's idea. He's short too.''
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to watch this year's Academy Awards because I'm a
shoo-in to take home the Oscar for Best Straight Face on a Middle
School Teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payton,'' I begin, talking behind my hand so I can grab my
face in case it threatens to stretch into a big grin, ``I'm not
condoning smoking. It's a lousy habit. But I really don't think a
few cigarettes have stunted your growth. If your cousin is short
too, it's probably a genetic thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw,'' Payton drawls, as he studies his knuckles like they're
a biology project, ``it's cigarettes. I know it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he serious, I ask myself, or is he scamming me because he's
forgotten his gym clothes and doesn't want to go to third period? I
ask him. He looks shocked so I drop it.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few weeks the Feel Good Department (Guidance
Office) has been stuffing teachers' mailboxes with reams of
touchy-feely stuff designed to make educators more sensitive to the
problems (real and imagined) of our youthful charges.
Thoughtlessly, I filed mine right away in the recycling box,
figuring I'd cut out the middle man. That's the part where I stack
them in the IN box and pretend I'm going to get around to reading
them one day when I don't have 85 essays to grade. I'm thinking
maybe I should have saved some because my next suggestion falls
flat. ``Payton, maybe you should talk to the guidance counselor.''
For good measure I throw in a little psycho-babble. ``How do you
feel about that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``NO WAY,'' is his immediate and emphatic response. When I ask
why, he looks at me as though I'd just fallen off the tail end of
the turnip truck and explains. ``He's tall. How can he know what
it's like being me? I figured you'd understand because you're short
too.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not exactly flattered, but I am committed, so I blurt out
the first thing that comes to mind. ``Mickey Rooney is short.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton stares blankly and asks if he goes to school here. No
point in trying to explain, it's a generation(s) gap thing.
Instead, I tell him a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a sophomore in high school, there was a really cool
junior guy who played varsity basketball. We called him Boo Boo.''
Payton interrupts wanting to know if Boo Boo was tall. ``Real
tall,'' I tell him. ``At least 6 feet.'' Payton moans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In September of my junior year, this little pipsqueak shows up
in the halls. It turns out he's Boo Boo's younger brother. So guess
what we nicknamed him?''
</P>
<P>
   Payton cares less so I tell him anyway. ``Poo Poo.'' No
response. ``You know, because he was such a little ... fellow?''
Still nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``About once a week, some wiseguy would stuff Poo Poo in a
locker, slam the door and go to class, leaving Poo Poo to bang on
the door until a teacher came to check out the racket and called
the janitor to let him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boo Boo, being tall and a great basketball player, had more
girls than he could get around to. Poo Poo couldn't even get a date
for the Saturday sock hop. Then a funny thing happened between Poo
Poo's sophomore and junior years. He grew 6 inches over the
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton perks up. ``In one summer? Wow! How tall was he then?''
</P>
<P>
   ``About five-three.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So, did he grow another 6 inches the next summer and play
basketball and get girls?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I answer artfully, ``but now he's a CPA and has lots of
money and is married to the prettiest girl in his class. I saw them
a couple of years ago at a reunion.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton cocks his head to one side in disbelief and asks: ``Ms.
Schuett, is that true? You swear?'' I ask him if a teacher would
lie. He thanks me and leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Now I understand the origin of fables. Aesop must have been a
middle school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Address mail to
320 W. Madison, Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email to:
eschuett(AT)nwonline.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0650 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN16-C     03-15 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gender gap still a wage gap into next millennium
 &HT;    By Marilyn Geewax
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many more girls are heading off to college these days that
women's pay is sure to surge in the 21st century. And that growing
earning power could trigger the biggest changes in family structure
since men left the cave to hunt. Women with fat paychecks may
become the key breadwinners of the next century or even choose to
skip marriage entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Such predictions seem reasonable, given demographic trends. In
1950, fewer than one college student in four was female. Today
nearly six college seniors in 10 are women. The U.S. Department of
Education projects that by 2008, women will outnumber men in
college, 9.2 million to 6.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   But before we start conjuring up images of Lucy and Ethel
heading off to the office while Ricky and Fred tie on aprons at
home, take a closer look at what is really happening. Professors
will tell you that a huge pay gap is indeed about to open up, but
not in favor of females. Men are the ones on the verge of a big pay
raise, while most women are on track to take lower-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   How can that be? If women are going to college in greater
numbers, today's wage data would suggest they are going to make
lots of money. The U.S. Census Bureau says that in 1997, the latest
year for which statistics are available, the average salary for a
college graduate was $40,478 a year, while high school graduates
earned only $22,895 a year. So if more women than men are going to
college, it would follow that in the next century we can expect to
see women paid better than men.
</P>
<P>
   But that assumption could turn out to be dead wrong. In fact,
the end of the 20th century may well be the high-water mark for
women's wages _ currently 76 percent of what men make _ because the
economy increasingly is rewarding people with high-tech skills, not
broad-based knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   In a technology-oriented economy, the people earning hefty
salaries are not the English majors with years of formal education
but rather the Web designers, computer programmers and auto repair
technicians with the know-how to control advanced equipment.
</P>
<P>
   And by a huge margin, the people entering these high-tech jobs
are male.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are not going into those areas (that involve) math and
technology,'' said Norma Kent, spokeswoman for American Association
of Community Colleges. She notes that at two-year colleges, 58
percent of the students are female. However, although women
dominate in overall numbers, few are choosing the fields that offer
high pay.
</P>
<P>
   Kent said the problem is not that women don't take tough
courses; many succeed in difficult science classes in nursing and
other medical fields. But women are reluctant to enter the
male-dominated area of information technology. ``I don't believe
they lack the intellect to do the work,'' she said. ``I think it's
just cultural.''
</P>
<P>
   That is, girls are not encouraged to immerse themselves in new
technologies, she said, noting that most children's computer games
involve good guys blowing up bad guys. Boys quickly get the hint
that the computer is designed to amuse, well, guys; girls feel left
out. When boys decide to skip the four-year college experience to
start training with high-tech equipment, they may be making a smart
financial move.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the cost of tuition at the typical two-year
community college is about $1,500 a year. That means an 18-year-old
can spend $3,000 to get trained in computer programming, machining
or air-conditioning repair. At age 20, he might well get a
``signing bonus'' to take a job that pays $30,000 a year. With
overtime pay, men not yet old enough to drink legally can be making
$40,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with the fortunes of a young woman seeking a
four-year degree at a liberal arts college. By the time she is 22,
she may have piled up tens of thousands of dollars in debt, and her
starting pay as an elementary school teacher will average about
$25,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Even women who gain admission to the nation's Ivy League
colleges may have limited earning power compared with their male
counterparts who skip college to go straight to work in the rapidly
expanding high-tech world. The U.S. Department of Labor projects
that employment in computer and data-processing services will grow
108 percent between 1996 and 2006, making it the nation's fastest
growing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Although about 65 percent of all 18-year-olds do go on to get
some form of higher education, teachers report that the motto
``learn less, earn more'' is increasingly resonating with boys who
can leap directly into good, computer-related jobs with companies
such as Cisco Systems or Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Young men are often only too glad to pass on the poetry and rush
straight toward the stock options. Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates is
their role model; he dropped out of college to start a company that
has built his personal wealth to roughly $80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all young women go to college to prepare for a
low-paying career. Women are filling up half the classroom seats in
many law and medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   But these traditionally lucrative professions often can't
compare with the rewards of computer-related jobs. A recent report
by Newsweek magazine listed the fastest-growing jobs. The top three
were database manager, computer engineer and systems analyst. The
three positions with the highest pay were chief information
officer, wireless engineer and software development manager.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the courses they are taking today in high school, few
young women will be prepared to enter those high-paying,
fast-growing jobs. In a recent study, the American Association of
University Women found that females made up only 17 percent of the
students taking advanced-placement computer science tests in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   But if women aren't entering the high-tech world, what will
happen in other arenas? If more bright young men skip college to
avoid those tiresome English classes, will they be failing to
prepare themselves for management?
</P>
<P>
   Again, Gates may be the role model. Though the Harvard dropout
is extremely smart about software, his recent court appearances on
videotape in an anti-trust suit suggest he might have benefited
from more English and drama classes. Microsoft's interests might
have been better served by having a more well-rounded chairman to
speak for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the next century will produce a strange kind of power
sharing between men and women, with men controlling the technology
and well-educated women taking important positions as lawmakers,
judges, physicians and corporate board members. ``I think more
women will gravitate toward politics,'' Sandy Bernard, president of
the university women's association, predicted.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps men will be so busy making money, they won't much
care who's minding Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
