<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0651 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN16-     03-15 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Study urges aid for businesses owned by people of
color
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Minority business enterprise, taken as a whole, is no
small business anymore. And the time has come when it needs to
advance beyond the civil rights stage and into the real world of
business.
</P>
<P>
   That's the thrust of a new study commissioned by the Minority
Business Development Agency, a federal government branch that
watches and provides some services to businesses owned and operated
by African-Americans, Latinos and others.
</P>
<P>
   A whole family of policies and programs designed to help
minority business is predicated on the thought these enterprises
need shelter in some cases, or special aid in others, to start,
gain footing and become self-sustaining. The federal interest in
this matter is based on the thought minority-owned businesses are
good for urban communities, create broader opportunities and help
provide employment.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Milken Institute of Santa Monica, Calif., finds
businesses owned and operated by African-American, Hispanic, Asian
and Native American entrepreneurs now amount to some $205 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they are growing at twice the rate of all U.S. firms,
and they seem destined to climb steeply because of growing
populations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These communities are gaining new importance as both producers
and consumers of products and services,'' said the report. ``In
addition, many minority communities are located in key population
centers such as New York, Los Angeles, Chicago ... .''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growth of these businesses, minority businesses have
suffered chronically from insufficient capital, both to operate and
to expand.
</P>
<P>
   This can be remedied, the report said, not by larger government
programs but by reorganizing how the businesses are financed.
</P>
<P>
   The study, titled ``Mainstreaming Minority Business,'' advocates
a pooling of public and private funds for business development
among minorities, and developing secondary markets for the funding
as we do for housing _ thereby generating a larger capital pool.
</P>
<P>
   Another key recommendation is to develop more businesslike ways
to grade applications for lending so the paperwork moves faster and
decisions are better based.
</P>
<P>
   Courtland Cox, director of MBDA, praised the recommendations and
said they raise hopes of better access to capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ideas are not new, just novel as envisioned to help
minority enterprises,'' Cox said. He said most of the
recommendations could be implemented with changes in regulations
and should not require major new legislation.
</P>
<P>
   George Andrews, president of Capitol City Bank, which is
expanding in Atlanta, said the program ``looks promising.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending upon how they implement the program, it could help
to provide more capital for community development, and that would
really be important,'' said Andrews. ``It could also help community
banks remain strong as an alternative to other banks.''
</P>
<P>
   William Stanley, of Stanley Love Stanley architects in Atlanta,
said the greater access to capital will be welcome but added,
``Just as important as capital is an improvement in procedures that
can speed up paperwork, so that businesses can respond better to
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank, one of the country's largest players in
small-business loans, declined to comment specifically on the
proposals. It said it will follow the changes with interest.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mark Williams, an Atlanta spokesman for the company,
said that it invites people to examine the work it is doing here
and elsewhere in financing minority businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Greater capital flow would be especially helpful, of course, for
construction enterprises and many high-tech businesses that tend to
depend heavily on capital.
</P>
<P>
   Said the report: ``To sustain growth, minority businesses need
greater access to supplies of capital at all critical stages of
business development, including equity and seed capital, mezzanine
debt and senior debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the specific proposals:
</P>
<P>
   _ Develop secure Collateralized Loan Obligations from a pool of
minority business loans and establish Special-Purpose Vehicles,
ideally through an existing government agency, to implement a
secondary market for CLOs to fill financing gaps.
</P>
<P>
   _ The SPVs would administer pools of small-business loans
purchased from lending institutions and would promote credit
enhancement through a reserve fund that insures the loan pools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish industrywide efficiencies in the small-business
lending market through development of standardization in credit
scoring, standardized loan documentation and borrower education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deregulation of SBA programs so steps can be taken to create
incentives for equity investment and participation in minority
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the overhaul of regulations could take a year or two,
but some changes could start sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The complete report can be seen on the Milken Institute Web site
at http://www.milken-inst.org under ``What's New.''
</P>
<P>
   Links to that site will be available soon on the government site
at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.mbda.gov
</P>
<P>
   E-mail:holsen(at)mindspring.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
