<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0652 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELLPHONE-BDAY16-COX     03-15 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONE-BDAY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    15-year love affair with the cell phone sure to continue
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a way it crept up on us, this love for the pocket
phones you see dangling from belt loops, strapped to waists or
tucked discreetly into vest pockets and purses. The cell phone,
which turns 15 this year, has displaced lots of calls that once
were made on desk phones.
</P>
<P>
   Another fallout has been noticed and appreciated by all frequent
travelers at airports. Many pay phones are unoccupied in the busy
passageways. No need to scramble for coins or stand in lines,
because so many people are carrying their own phones.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the wireless generation.
</P>
<P>
   Personal chatter by phone has become unimaginably convenient,
and been accepted swiftly, since its introduction in 1984 when
BellSouth and others started their service. But what does that say
about the old phone and the various ways we approach telephoning?
What changes can we expect in the future?
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that when it comes to communication, change
is not new. It is today's pace that is revolutionary. Consider
this: The phone was invented in 1876 and Bell Telephone Co. started
a year later, but it was 1929 before President Hoover had a phone
installed in his office. Previously presidents had to step into a
booth outside the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Now, soccer moms and dads watch sons and daughters play in the
sunlit afternoons _ still in touch with their offices or homes by
way of the cell phone, whose new array of batteries allows
continuous operation for days, not hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that more than 30 percent of my talking on phones
takes place in the car, on my cell phone,'' said WillIam Stanley,
architect of the new Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that it is the perfect way to return phone calls, and I
do it hands-free by working on a speaker. The only problem is you
can't take notes.''
</P>
<P>
   You just know, however, that right around the corner is a system
for dictating on tape notes even as you speak by way of wireless
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, whose architecture business is international, says he
uses his cell phone almost exclusively in Africa, where he has many
projects and where the land-line phone service is not well
developed.
</P>
<P>
   David Kettler, a BellSouth vice president who specializes in
technological advances, says at least two things are happening in
phone evolution right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a saying in the business that narrowband, such as
conversation, is moving toward wireless, and broadband, such as
Internet connection and data transmission, is moving toward wired
communication,'' Kettler said.
</P>
<P>
   This could mean that everyday phone use, such as chatting with
friends or reporting in to the office, could continue to flow
toward the hand-held devices such as cell phones. And the present
trend toward wired cable modems and similar devices connected to
the phone lines will be used for big volumes of information.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not so simple. The wireless industry has some of the
sharpest technical minds in the world at work on ways to move
volumes of information by way of wireless networks. As the
economics begins to balance the prices between wired and wireless
communication, prevailing styles may drive even bigger increases in
the use of hand-held and other wireless communicators.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if people, especially business people, have some concerns
about privacy in cell phone conversations, Kettler said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, even though digital technology has made it harder for
people to intercept conversations between wireless phones, that
technology is not seen as matching the security of wired phones.
But steps are being taken to increase security, through encryption
and other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem of ``dead spots'' and other gaps in cell phone
service is also being addressed through a continuous upgrading of
wireless networks, Kettler said. The expansion of cell phone
service areas, and the introduction of systems that minimize
roaming charges, make wireless phone service more handy and more
affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Our preference for cell phones is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by the handy nature of wireless phones, and the improving
efficiency of the batteries that make operation more convenient,
wireless subscribers grew from 3.5 million in 1990 to 24 million in
1995. Today's estimates approach 69 million. The Yankee Group, the
Boston-based research organization, predicts 141 million
subscribers by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   For all we know, improving technology and falling prices could
accelerate the already steep climb.
</P>
<P>
   Kettler says the new advances will not necessarily be in phones
but in the networks that connect the phones. For instance, very
soon, he said, we may have phones that combine the low expense of
the portable phone used around the house, with the power and reach
of the cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have networks that track your use of the phone,'' he
said, ``so that when you use it in the house you are charged the
same rate as the regular house wired phone, but when you leave the
house with it the network will charge a low wireless rate around
the neighborhood, and a higher one as you range around the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are already developing wireless networks within
the house so that phones and computers can communicate within the
home.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another alternative to the ordinary phone is the Internet
phone, where a caller could dial up through the computer and reach
a person on the other end of a phone line, or on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed in that form of telephoning, Kettler said, ways must
be found for completing the calls between areas as the signal moves
over various kinds of networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't easy, but it is being done,'' he said, ``and that
form of telephoning will be a factor in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the growth in wireless communication, snail mail
and the traditional phone are the only ways to reach more than 90
percent of households around the country. At last count some 94
percent of households had phones.
</P>
<P>
   According to Frost and Sullivan, a consulting firm, of the
nearly 99 million households in the United States, more than 18
million already have more than one phone line.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, households now average 2.5 phone lines, and the
consultants say that by next year upper-income families could
average five lines to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
