<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0659 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-SCIENCEPROJECTS1     03-15 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SCIENCEPROJECTS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Web can help harried parents with science projects
 &HT;    By Jennifer Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each spring, I dread the month of March, because March brings
with it the Science Fair project, which can turn the knees of a
strong, normally capable parent into jelly, especially one with
multiple children, which usually means multiple projects.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for me and other Science Fair-impaired parents, there's
the Internet, which can be the starting point to a more meaningful
project, or least some good ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Using a search engine such as Yahoo! or Excite and the words
``science fair project,'' or on America Online, ``Science Fair
Central,'' you can quickly find a wealth of resources.
</P>
<P>
   At http://www.eduzone.com
</P>
<P>
   /Tips/Science/SHOWTIP2.HTM, there's a site with the catchy title
``No More Clay Volcanoes: Your 1999 Science Fair.'' It gives a
straightforward, text-only step-by-step guide, which can make a
handy reference guide as your budding scientist selects and puts
together a project. Not surprisingly, the site's author notes that
the most successful projects are those in which a student is
genuinely interested. This site is part of a larger site called
Room 103, which answers science and technology questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Ultimate Science Fair Project is a giant umbrella site that
includes multiple pages with ideas, idea links and writing hints.
The idea generation page (http://www.isd77.k12.mn
</P>
<P>
   .us/resources/cf/ideas.html) includes a worksheet that poses
questions with suggested topics to insert in the blanks that help
get a student's mind thinking properly about how to select a
project. Below is an example taken from the page:
</P>
<P>
   _ What is the effect of on ?
</P>
<P>
   detergentgermination of seeds
</P>
<P>
   temperaturethe volume of air
</P>
<P>
   _ How/to what extent does the affect ?
</P>
<P>
   humiditygrowth of fungi
</P>
<P>
   color of a materialits absorption of heat
</P>
<P>
   The Internet can also be used to compile a non-Internet resource
list. The names of several science publications as well other
resources can be found at
http://www.ipl.org/youth/projectguide/mags. Hyperlinks on the page
will take you to the online version of the publication.
</P>
<P>
   The research resources listed on this page, such as the
dictionary, are good, but may be difficult for young children to
navigate. And in the case of NASA, the recommended thesaurus costs
money. The MerriamWebster site (http://www.m-w.com
</P>
<P>
   /dictionary.htm), while offering less depth in the definitions,
is free and easier to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   And as we discovered, digital information takes many forms. We
now take extra care when feeding one subject of my son's project.
For on the Internet, we discovered a handy fact _ African bullfrogs
will gladly bite, and eat, the fingers of the hand that feeds them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
