</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERUSER-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Videoconferencing easy enough on PC
 &HT;    By Gerry Yandel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I haven't really dabbled in videoconferencing online since,
well, the first time I ever tried dabbling in it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in mid-1997, I bought a $99 (after rebate) card that
had inputs for cable TV, radio antennas and a camcorder or VCR.
</P>
<P>
   So I jumped online and grabbed a freeware version of CU-Seeme, a
videoconferencing program developed by Cornell University (CU, get
it?). I planned to hook up my camera and do a little virtual
chatting.
</P>
<P>
   After installing the program, I hooked into a reflector _ the
server where CU-Seeme users log in _ run by NASA, and I opened a
small window with a long and static shot of three guys in ties
talking about astrophysics.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged but bored, I tried another reflector. I logged in and
``called'' another nickname by clicking his icon.
</P>
<P>
   I was greeted by a grainy, black-and-white,
choppy-but-unmistakably-live image of a nude male torso.
</P>
<P>
   That was all I needed to send me scurrying to the tranquil
island of ``Myst.''
</P>
<P>
   I never did get around to hooking up my camcorder ... until now.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine in Atlanta, who is anti-technologically
inclined, was lamenting the cost of long-distance when she called
her son, who lives in Boulder, Colo. She didn't believe me at first
when I told her she could call him for 35 cents and see him while
she spoke to him simply by buying a Quickcam and downloading some
free software.
</P>
<P>
   (Actually, she didn't quite understand the words ``software,''
``download'' or ``Quickcam,'' but I was able to convince her
anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   The Quickcam _ plus a cheapo microphone for transmitting sound _
cost $96, and it installed by connecting to a parallel port.
</P>
<P>
   The next step was to download Microsoft Netmeeting, a
full-fledged freeware videoconferencing program, and she was all
set.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, parallel ports are not good conduits for digital
video. The picture from the Quickcam leaves a lot to be desired,
and it's useless for any kind of frame grabbing or video digitizing
beyond making really bad, fuzzy screen savers.
</P>
<P>
   But for Net videoconferencing, it's more than adequate. (Not to
mention a much cheaper solution over time than those 10-10
long-distance deals.)
</P>
<P>
   I also decided to try out my camcorder and card for comparison.
The results were striking.
</P>
<P>
   The card I bought was a Video Highway Xtreme, and it has inputs
for TV, VCR, coaxial, cable, composite video, S-video and AM/FM
radio antennas. To use a digital video card as I did, you'll need a
camcorder or some other video source.
</P>
<P>
   Not counting the time it took to install the card initially,
which went relatively painlessly as far as video drivers go, I had
my camcorder broadcasting in less time than it took to set up the
Quickcam.
</P>
<P>
   Netmeeting and CU-Seeme work in similar ways, a model based on
the Internet chatting network IRC: A person logs into a server _
called reflectors for CU-Seeme and isl servers for Netmeeting _
that transmit sound, video and/or text. Anyone logged in can ``call
up'' anyone else by clicking their icons. Calls can be accepted,
declined, blocked, ignored or conducted in private.
</P>
<P>
   You can contact people directly across the Net for a
``person-to-person'' connection with a program like ICQ, or, in the
case of Netmeeting, across different isl servers.
</P>
<P>
   (The reason I use Netmeeting: It's free, and I knew the
Microserfs would make it optimized to run on Win 95/98.)
</P>
<P>
   There are also several shareware programs _ such as VDOphone,
CU-Seeme and Intel Intercast _ to try out.
</P>
<P>
   One important caveat regarding testing different programs: Video
drivers and associated files go to the very heart of your operating
system, and chaos can result when switching between driver sets,
video capture devices, etc.
</P>
<P>
   An old version of Intel Internet phone scotched my settings for
CU-Seeme and Netmeeting ... even after removing the Intel program
and restoring my previous system.ini file. If you are wary of
messing with your system's device manager or the system registry,
pick one program and stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, be prepared for what transpires on the public
servers. Your family chat could very well be listed next to a user
nicknamed Naked in Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   Some related web sites:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.rocketcharged.com/cu-seeme/reflectors.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.netmeet.net/ilslist.htm
</P>
<P>
   http://www.gvcnet.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.aimslab.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.wpine.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.microsoft.com/netmeeting/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.vdo.net
</P>
<P>
   On Usenet: news:comp.dcomp.videoconf
</P>
<P>
   Have a question about software, hardware or the Internet you'd
like to see addressed? E-mail: pcajc(at)yahoo.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
