<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Junk e-mail a way of life, but you have a few defenses
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'll never forget the thrill I felt when I opened my first
e-mail. Maybe it's strange to feel nostalgic about something that
is theoretically as neutral as computer bytes. But turns out that
Marshall McLuhan was wrong as far as I'm concerned. The message is
the message, and it's the content that matters, not how it arrives.
</P>
<P>
   I still love e-mail when it comes from a friend. But so much of
it is true junk, and I delete that unread. Nowadays the junk
outnumbers the good mail.
</P>
<P>
   Readers often write me, thinking I have some secret method of
shielding them from the invasion that arrives daily in the mailbox
when they log on. Truth is, I can't stop it from coming to my own
mailbox, and if I could come up with a good method of doing that, I
would be a saner man.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few ways to control junk mail, but some of them are
counterintuitive.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you probably have received unsolicited e-mail that
has a helpful note at the bottom offering to remove you from the
mailing list if you'll just ask for that to be done. Sometimes this
is a sincere offer from an ethical merchant. Other times it is a
trick to authenticate your e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   In some mass mailings, the whole notion is to get you to
respond. Once you've responded, your e-mail address commands a
premium price among the e-mail list peddlers. You've just raised
your hand and said, in effect: Yes, I'm here, and the address
works.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a person to do?
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, there isn't a heck of a lot you can do to protect
yourself against the really unethical mailers. These people care
only about profiting from your name. But there are a few steps you
can take to diminish the amount of junk that arrives. Here's a
start:
</P>
<P>
   _ Check with your Internet provider and ask if it offers any
system for filtering out junk mail. These junk mail filters use
various schemes, but most look for the addresses of known junk
mailers. If it's offered, use it. These systems won't eliminate the
junk but will reduce its volume.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you leave public messages on the Internet, you can avoid
using your real address. Some people change the return address on
their account to fool automatic software that harvests e-mail
addresses from postings in almost the same way thresher machines
harvest grain on the farm. For instance, if your real e-mail
address is bhusted(at)ajc.com, it can be changed to
bhusted(at)spamfilter.ajc.com. People who understand e-mail will
figure out what you're doing, but the automatic software will be
fooled and any mail sent to you will go astray. (The downside of
this method is that many Internet users whom you might legitimately
want to hear from also will be fooled, so I don't recommend it
unless you understand that you might also miss some real mail this
way.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Unless you just can't stand it, avoid registering at Web sites
for free gifts and informational mailings offered by some sites.
That puts your e-mail address in the basket to be swapped, sold and
abused.
</P>
<P>
   _ Write your Internet provider and ask that it take any steps it
can to protect you from junk e-mail. While there aren't many things
the provider can do to help at this stage, it's good to register
your indignation since you are something truly valuable to them: a
customer. A groundswell of disapproval will register if the ISPs
has to decide whether to seek or back legislation to control junk
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, keep your sense of humor about all this (I cannot
always obey my own advice, by the way). Just as the paper variety
of junk mail will continue to arrive in your mailbox at home, junk
e-mail is a fact of life. Open an e-mail account, and it will come.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com. Bill appreciates hearing from you but
cannot respond to all e-mail. Personal home page:
http://www.mindspring.com/(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
