<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author sees opportunity in Y2K bug
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not everyone is a ``Chicken Little'' when it comes to the
Millennium Bug. Take John F. Mauldin, who has written a book called
``How to Profit From the Y2K Recession.'' Mauldin is an investment
analyst and self-proclaimed Y2K expert.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, he advocates taking financial advantage of any
disruption, profiting off the hysteria of others. The book is
published by St. Martins Press and retails for the suggested price
of $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Here's a new computer CD game designed for Atlanta, where the
love of Civil War history runs high. In ``North vs. South,''
players re-enact some of the important battles of the Civil War.
You'll find Bull Run, Gaines' Mill, Cedar Mountain, Antietam,
Gettysburg and the Wilderness. This turn-based game lets you
command everything from a corps to a brigade. You can choose
whether to play from the North or South side. The game, published
by Interactive Magic, is available only for PCs with systems
Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   You've shot deer, driven race cars and flown fighter jets. Now
you can ride a bucking bull on your computer. That's right, the
latest simulation software emulates the rodeo. It's called
``Extreme Bullrider'' and is published by Activision. With this
game, you can choose to be one of 20 different riders, select one
of 10 different bulls and pick one of six arenas. There are also 10
different bullfighting clowns to choose from. ``Extreme Bullrider''
is available only for PCs with systems Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   It's back. Byte magazine, closed for a redesign, has returned _
at least on the Internet. The new version offers a comprehensive
Web page. You'll find it at http://www.byte
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur astronomers take note. There's a wonderful site on the
Web to explore your interest in the planets. It's called Virtual
Solar System and is posted by National Geographic. There's lots of
cool stuff, including a fly-by tour of the sun and each planet.
You'll find this site at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.nationalgeographic.com
</P>
<P>
   /solarsystem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
