<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0671 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-TOOLS16-COX     03-15 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calendar Creator apace with the times
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems like Calendar Creator has been around as long as there
have been computers to run it, and I doubt its popularity has ever
waned. Making personalized calendars is one of those things
computers do exceedingly well, and most people can use such
calendars.
</P>
<P>
   Calendar Creator is published now by Broderbund, and just came
out in Version 6. I would have to say its power and versatility
have outpaced its ease of use.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating, useful and even educational program; but
it's unnecessarily difficult to use. Just for an example, there are
several different properties boxes accessed both by right-clicking
or via pull-down menus. This is confusing.
</P>
<P>
   If you just want to make a calendar to keep your appointments
and print it out month by month or week by week, this is pretty
easy. If you poke around a little, you'll find a raft of pre-set
events you can add, from French Saints Days to Japanese holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Since Japan may yet rule the world, it's good to know that under
their calendar, Sept. 15 is Respect for the Aged Day.
</P>
<P>
   You can type in your own events or just use a color code to
remind you of, for instance, your regular haircut appointment or
your semiannual visit to the soothsayer.
</P>
<P>
   Calendars can be printed out in a lot of different ways, and of
course you can add pictures to them. The program comes with a
selection of nice pictures for this purpose. Most usefully, you can
print a calendar in Instabook form for carrying in a purse or a
briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   There is a feature for synchronizing a PalmPilot with the
Calendar in the PC, and Calendar Creator makes a move toward
becoming a personal information manager with an address book.
Entering information into it is rather cumbersome, with a lot of
unnecessary pop-up data entry boxes.
</P>
<P>
   You can have the calendar remind you, by way of a
memory-resident scheduler, of upcoming events. Also, in a neat
little trick, if you enter, let's say, Oct. 3 as your momma's 73rd
birthday, then next year it will automatically change the notation
on that date to show it is her 74th. One assumes, of course,
Calendar Creator is solidly Y2K compatible.
</P>
<P>
   As in most programs these days that make any kind of graphic
presentation, you can do it from scratch or you can use one of many
built-in templates. There are lots of fancy fonts. You can make a
clean, easily grasped calendar, or you can make one virtually
illegible. Computers are very democratic this way.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, this is a most useful and complete program, and
with a little persistence you can cut through its confusion and use
it to help with a lot of tasks. It costs about $60.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
