<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     03-15 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, March 15, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ENCEPHALITIS (San Francisco) _ Dozens of cases of encephalitis
are being examined in depth at the California Department of Health
Services, where a project funded in part by the federal Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention is trying to find causes for the
many cases of encephalitis that defy explanation. By ULYSSES
TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   JETS-WARMING (San Francisco) _ An explosion in commercial air
traffic may be triggering formation of high-altitude clouds that
trap heat and could worsen global warming. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING (Modesto, Calif.) _ After exhaustive searches and
investigations, FBI officials said they have no hard evidence of
what happened to a trio of sightseers or the red Pontiac they were
driving. By ERIC McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   CAL-ADMISSIONS (San Francisco) _ This week the regents of the
University of California are set to vote on a plan to make the top
4 percent at every California high school eligible for the
university in an effort to draw more students from rural and
inner-city areas. By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COSMETIC-SURGEON (San Francisco) _ Dr. Alan Gaynor, a San
Francisco dermatologist nationally known for his glib guest
appearances on TV talk shows, has been placed on five years
probation by the Medical Board of California, in part for the
half-blinding of a woman who suffered a needle stab to the eye in
his office. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-CORPORATIONS (San Francisco) _ Traditional corporations
should emulate the informality, flat organizational structures and
quick decision-making prowess of Silicon Valley companies if they
plan to succeed in the future. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-INSTITUTE (San Francisco) _ The Wine Institute has morphed
from a relatively sedate trade group hosting wine tastings and
endorsing cookbooks into a sophisticated public policy and lobbying
organization. Some 430 dues-paying commercial wineries _ out of a
statewide total of 740 _ belong to the Wine Institute. By DAVID
ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS (Undated) _ It's been 22 years since the first ``Star
Wars'' film, 19 years since the second and a mere 16 since the
third. Now it's two months until the fourth. But the new 2
1/2-minute trailer for the prequel isn't revealing much about what
awaits us. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS-JUNKIE (Undated) _ The full title is ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' but most fans call it EP1 or TPM.
When the flick finally hits the big screen on May 19, it might as
well be Y2K. You thought the mania was bad in 1977, when moviegoers
lined up by the block to see the original ``Star Wars.'' That was
nothing. Twenty-two years has given my generation plenty of time to
anticipate TPM. It's bigger than the Second Coming of Christ _ it's
the Fourth Coming of Vader. By JASON LLOREN.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS-TOYS (Undated) _ In May, the merchandising and food
promotion blitz for the long- awaited new ``Star Wars'' movie,
``Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' is scheduled to begin. A
battalion of toy action figures and space crafts related to the
movie will go on sale May 3, about three weeks before ``Phantom''
opens nationwide. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ELIA-KAZAN (San Francisco) _ Next Sunday, Elia Kazan, 89 years
old, famous worldwide as a distinguished director of theater and
film, will walk to the podium at Dorothy Chandler Pavilion in Los
Angeles to receive an honorary Oscar. This may turn out to be the
most divisive and troublesome moment in the Academy's history
because Elia Kazan is also known worldwide as the stool pigeon who
sold out his colleagues before the House Committee on Un-American
Activities (popularly known as HUAC) in 1952. By NANCY SCOTT.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CORKSCREWS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The first patent for a corkscrew was
taken out in 1795 by the Rev. Samuel Henshall in Oxford, England.
Since then, there have been hundreds, and for some people, a
corkscrew is as personal as a fountain pen. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ADVENTURE-TRAVEL (San Francisco) _ Helga Hahneiser vacationed in
Cambodia while the murderous Khmer Rouge still roamed the country,
went sightseeing in Lebanon near Hezbollah guerrilla headquarters
and visited Zaire while leader Mobutu Sese Seko was railing against
whites. This year, Hahneiser is heading to Libya. Hahneiser is one
of a growing number of people seeking rare sights and unusual
experiences on their vacations.In the tourism business, it is known
as ``adventure travel.'' By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-URUGUAY (Salto, Uruguay) _ A riot of scents greets
visitors to the Uruguayan town of Salto, which is laid out in a
grid with a mix of architectural styles _ 19th-century,
neo-classical, stone-columned municipal buildings and boxy
flat-roofed stores and houses. Eucalyptus trees and jasmine vines
perfume the daytime air, and we inhale the aroma of grilled freshly
slaughtered beef and lamb as we drive to our Art Deco hotel. By
LINDA TRISCHITTA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Phoenix) _ The National Football League will lift its
ban on embattled 49ers co-owner Eddie DeBartolo after the 1999-2000
football season, sources said. Three sources close to DeBartolo and
the club, and two officials of another team familiar with league
deliberations, say DeBartolo must also pay an unspecified fine
first. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Wow, has San Francisco changed
since Joe, Dom and Vince DiMaggio were lads? There are too many
ways to count, but one street scene tells the tale. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For sharing some of what he saw
during his five years in Bill Clinton's inner circle, George
Stephanopoulos is being called a weasel and a Judas. Maybe worst of
all, long-time Clinton haters (people Stephanopoulos presumably
can't stand) are crowing, ``Welcome aboard! What took you so
long?'' By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Constitution appears to
mean that no one can take your property except through a legal
process involving a finding of guilt. But don't kid yourself. Today
these words all too often ring hollow as the federal government,
the states, counties and cities across the land avail themselves of
the opportunity to sequester private property. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   CLACK-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Arlene Perez left the care of her
children to others while she was adrift in the white storm of
cocaine and heroin abuse and a whirlwind of partying. But in the
end, it was the love for the children she'd abandoned that pulled
her back to sobriety's shore. By CARY CLACK.
</P>
<P>
   FLORES-COLUMN (San Antonio) _ Forty years after the arrival of
Barbie, Mattel is understanding the influence the doll can have on
little girls. At last, the company is putting money toward issues
where Barbie's image could be a greater force: supporting programs
that teach girls about technology, money and finance, math and
science, life skills and career planning. By VERONICA FLORES.
</P>
<P>
   EINSTEIN-RECALLED (New York) _ It was April 1954, and I had come
to see Albert Einstein at his home in Princeton, N.J., to ask if he
would accept an achievement award from Lord &AMP; Taylor. And would he
make an acceptance address at a luncheon at the Waldorf? By REA
LUBAR DUNCAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
