<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0679 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-QNA16-COX     03-15 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-QNA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hillary has time to set up camp in N.Y.
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How can Hillary Rodham Clinton run for senator of New York?
She lives in Washington, D.C. Can anybody run for senator of New
York, no matter where they live?
</P>
<P>
   A: Run? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Constitution says you must be a resident of the state
``when elected.'' In New York, according to Lee Daghlian of the New
York Board of Elections, there is no law outlining what ``be a
resident'' means. Move in with a friend, buy a condo, whatever.
Guess New York voters will decide that individually.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Daghlian says he is asked this question dozens of times a
day recently.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Help me find a license plate frame that says ``Swedish
Driver'' with a Swedish flag.
</P>
<P>
   A: The license plate frames are sold by Anderson Butik in
Kansas. Call (800) 782-4132 to order. For bumper stickers such as
``Happiness is Being Swedish,'' contact the Wooden Spoon at (972)
424-6867. Q: I purchased a Gund teddy bear with a music box for my
granddaughter. It has quit working. We bought it while on vacation
in Wyoming, so I can't take it back to the store. I have been
unable to find a phone number for Gund. Can you help? It is her
favorite bear!
</P>
<P>
   A: Contact consumer services at (732) 248-1500 or by mail at
GUND Inc., Attn: Consumer Services, 1 Runyons Lane, P.O. Box 852,
Edison, N.J. 08817 or by e-mail at ask-gund(at)gund.com for repair
or replacement. Gund has been in the bear business for 101 years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Somebody thought it would be clever to sign me up for about
30 various magazine subscriptions. Nothing against Martha Stewart,
but I'm just not real interested in her publication. Nor do I want
Seventeen, Quiltmaker,etc. If I simply ignore the bills, will I get
bad credit? Do I have to spend time and money mailing
cancellations?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, time and a few postage stamps. Contact each publisher
and explain you did not order the subscriptions and are canceling.
If you call, make a log of the date and the person with whom you
spoke; if you write, copy the letter. If the magazines continue to
arrive after repeated attempts to cancel, call the U.S. Postal
Inspection Service. It may take a few months to get this
straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: To the best of my memory, there was a law passed in the 1950s
that made it illegal to put a refrigerator not in use outdoors
without removing its doors to prevent children from playing inside
and being suffocated. Is this correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Refrigerator Safety Act of 1956 requires that
refrigerators be manufactured to open from the inside. The industry
moved from latch closures to magnetic ones in response to this act.
The law is not retroactive so does not apply to refrigerators made
before 1956.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ken Giles of the Consumer Products Safety
Commission, abandoned refrigerators should either have the door
removed, be chained shut or have the opening blocked. A child's
safety is at stake. Q: On Paul Harvey'sradio program recently there
was a story about a 1943 penny sold at auction for $84,000. I was
going through an old coin collection and found one of the pennies.
It is a 1943 penny without a mint mark. Could you find out what it
is worth?
</P>
<P>
   A: Do you have a magnet? If the penny is attracted to the
magnet, it is steel and may be worth as much as 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Rare coin dealer Larry Spencesays during World War II copper was
needed for the war effort. In 1943 most pennies were made of steel.
But a few (blank, S or D) were made of copper. These are worth big
bucks today.
</P>
<P>
   To compound matters, wacky jokers occasionally plate 1943 steel
pennies with copper and try to pass them off as rare. Also many
1943 steel pennies have turned black and owners think they are
copper.
</P>
<P>
   If your penny passes the magnet test, take it to a reputable
dealer who will have it authenticated by the American Numismatic
Association.Then get ready to hear, ``Going, going ... gone!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whom do I contact to buy an episode of Alfred Hitchcock
Presents?It aired about 40 to 45 years ago and starred Joseph
Cotten.Anyone who saw it could never forget it!
</P>
<P>
   A: Not a lot to go on. I found three episodes by the master of
suspense casting Joseph Cotten: ``Dead Weight'' (1959),
``Together'' (1958) and ``Breakdown'' (1955). I hope it was
``Breakdown,'' which is available from Movies Unlimited at (800)
523-0823.
</P>
<P>
   Have a laser disc player? Reel.com sells compendiums of
``Hitchcock Presents `` by special order on laser disc. Call (888)
707-7335.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am trying to get crayon off my son's carpet since he
decided to write all over it. I have tried different cleaners and
it comes off a little but is still pretty visible. We are selling
our house in about six months and I really don't want to invest in
new carpet. I was wondering if you know of some solution or maybe a
home remedy.
</P>
<P>
   A: Dana, Dana, go to the source _ Binney &AMP; Smith,makers of
Crayola crayons.
</P>
<P>
   Scrape the excess crayon with a dull knife. Spray with WD-40
(yes, the lubricant). Let stand, then work the stain with a
stiff-bristle brush and wipe with paper towels. Respray with WD-40
and apply a small amount of dishwashing detergent on the area. Work
in with the brush and wipe with a damp sponge. If stain persists,
repeat.
</P>
<P>
   No time? Try good old Energine cleaning fluid.
</P>
<P>
   For more Binney &AMP; Smith tips, call (800) CRAYOLA.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife and I will be on a Caribbean cruise, setting sail on
the 28th. I would like information on long-term vehicle parking
while we are on the cruise. I tried e-mailing Carnival Cruise
Linesand my mail is always returned. I need information as to the
facilities available and rates. We sail from New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   A: Carnival Cruise Lines customer service, at (800)
327-9501,said you will be leaving from the Julia Street Cruise
Terminal. Parking is available at 1 Julia St., berth No. 2,for $7
per day (rate subject to change). This info is also available by
e-mail at reservations(at)carnival.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I grew up in Chicago and attended many Blackhawk-- hockey
games where Wayne Messmersang the most amazing national anthem. The
crowd would go crazy from start to finish. It sent chills down my
spine, especially during the Gulf War. I have been trying to locate
a CD or audio tape of this and have been unsuccessful. Does it
exist?
</P>
<P>
   A: Messmer's rendition of the anthem tears eyes, lumps throats
and raises the spirits of the rabble. A founding partner of the IHL
champion Chicago Wolves,Messmer was the Blackhawks' soloist for 13
seasons. This amazing talent was shot in the throat by a robber in
1994 and muses a guardian angel may have been looking out for his
vocal cords.
</P>
<P>
   Send $15 to WPM Productions, P.O. Box 578598, Chicago, Ill.
60657to purchase ``The Anthem: Live at Chicago Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you help us identify music on an Audi commercial? The car
drives through a puddle, sending a sheet of water onto the
sidewalk, passing over people. The closing sequence scans a bridal
party. The music is a beautiful women's chorale, singing a
cappella. Want that music!
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Tolegnala and Todora,''by the Mystere de Voix
Bulgares,according to Doug Clark,Audi spokesman. The spot, called
``Heart,'' was produced by a North Carolina ad agency. This is a
special mix of the Bulgarian choir's work. The choir has recorded
extensively. Enjoy!
</P>
<P>
   Upshot/Update/Uproar: The Walters/Lewinsky infomercial/interview
has spawned more than conversation. The lipstick on ``those lips''
_ Monica's, not Barbara's _ is by Club Monaco.The shade? Glaze. The
base? Nude lip pencil. Club Monaco stores are sold out and the
expected shipments are, too. Want to try and snag a tube of Glaze
for yourself or as a gag gift? Call a Club Monaco store at (212)
533-8930or (310) 657-1818and beg.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com
or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
