<HEADER>
A0685 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-WOLFF-QNA16-COX     03-15 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-WOLFF-QNA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author of `Burn Rate' started a firestorm
 &HT;    By Tim Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Michael Wolff tried to get an Internet business
going way back in the early years of the World Wide Web. It was
1996, and he was in a new medium.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote about his adventures in dealing with venture
capitalists, media barons, old and new, and other Internet gold
seekers in a book, ``Burn Rate: How I Survived the Gold Rush Years
on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Burn rate is the term for how much money a startup goes through
in excess of its income. It seems to be the hallmark of an Internet
business.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Wolff is a journalist who writes about the Internet for
New York magazine and other publications. He was in Austin as a
keynote speaker at the South by Southwest Interactive Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin American-Statesman spoke with Wolff last week. Here
is an edited transcript:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are the gold rush years on the Internet over?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are very much still going on. The gold is just
apparently pouring out of those hills.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The people you dealt with didn't seem to have a good idea of
why they wanted to be on the Net or what to do there. They just
thought that's where they should be.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a very fair statement. The same thing still holds
true. People still haven't figured out where it's going, but they
are still trying.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why can't anyone grab hold of the Net and what's going on
there?
</P>
<P>
   A: We are in this period where every nine months, everything
changes. Every phase of this business from online services to push
technology to whatever is the flavor of the moment. Now it's
e-commerce. That will change.
</P>
<P>
   No model, no real business solution has lasted more than nine
months. The more logical way to look at that is that e-commerce
will peter out in a given number of months. To be replaced by
something else.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, how do you make money on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know the answer to that. No one knows the answer to
that. This is the major question. What are the benefits of the
Internet? How do you protect, at the very least, your downside?
That we can't even begin to imagine how big the upside will be.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did you write the book?
</P>
<P>
   A: This book was for me very much two things. I wanted to tell a
story that was very compelling and that a lot of people were
experiencing. I also wrote the book because these guys that I dealt
with were bums. They deserved the harsh light of day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was their reaction?
</P>
<P>
   A: The people I wrote about were furious. It was beyond fury;
they were murderous. It never really occurred to most of the people
in the book that someone would really set down the conversations
they had in business meetings. It just had never happened to them.
Maybe it had never happened to anyone before.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you feel reliving all that as you wrote?
</P>
<P>
   A: For one thing, I guess I was taken about how funny this was.
When I was going through it, it didn't seem funny. It was all
extraordinarily painful. In hindsight, though, it was pretty funny.
No one knew what they were doing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will your keynote be about?
</P>
<P>
   A: The experiences I recount in the book. About writing the
book. About what it's like to really record a piece of this very
odd history that we've all been experiencing. And I'll make some
predictions about what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Such as?
</P>
<P>
   A: One of the predictions I've been making recently is that
there will be a time when the Internet goes away. It really becomes
transparent. It is part of every business. Every transaction and
part of all aspects of everybody's life. Therefore we don't notice
it anymore. Amazon.com becomes part of the books business. AOL
becomes part of the media.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
