<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURES-BJT16-COX     03-15 1628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Tuesday, March 16,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET-PTECH 0312 -- PCs with the new Pentium III chip from
Intel are on shelves now. These new machines are the fastest yet,
reasonably priced and _ based on early reports _ relatively
bug-free. Just don't buy one. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FACT BOX -- Facts about the new Pentium III chip.
</P>
<P>
   TECH BRIEFS -- Sports teams have had their own Web sites since
the Internet became popular. Now individual players are taking the
cue. For example, San Antonio Spurs second-year power forward Tim
Duncan has launched http://www.slamduncan.com, known as The
Official Tim Duncan Website. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY -- As soon as they're available in your neighborhood
_ and if you have the money to spare _ get a cable modem and use it
to connect to the Internet. That's what I did a week ago. It made a
big difference, but maybe not in the ways you'd expect. (Husted,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE LIFE -- This year's hot technology trend is compelling
content from media players such as newspapers, magazines,
television networks and cable companies. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET NOTES -- One of the most popular instruments for
amateur musicians is the guitar. As it turns out, the Web is a
terrific resource for would-be guitar players. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet PTECH page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONE-BDAY _ In a way it crept up on us, this love for the
pocket phones you see dangling from belt loops, strapped to waists
or tucked discreetly into vest pockets and purses. The cell phone,
which turns 15 this year, has displaced lots of calls that once
were made on desk phones. Continuing improvements in service and
lower prices assure the public's love affair will grow ever more
meaningful. (Holsendolph, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
GRAPHIC ILLUSTRATION. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ For many people, the answers are in the stars.
Forget horoscopes and the Academy Awards and go outside tonight and
look up. Those little sparkling points of light _ the stars _ and
those larger lights that do not twinkle _ the planets _ have
provided answers and beauty since the first humans walked the
Earth. To learn about them and enjoy them, you'll find many useful
resources on the Internet. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SCIENCEPROJECTS _ I dread the month of March. It's the
Science Fair project, which can turn the knees of a strong,
normally capable parent into jelly, especially one with multiple
children, which usually means multiple projects. Using a search
engine such as Yahoo! or Excite and the words ``science fair
project,'' or on America Online, ``Science Fair Central,'' you can
quickly find a wealth of resources. (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ It has been a long time coming but apparently well
worth the wait. At least that is the initial review on the Internet
about 3Com's new Mac software for its PalmPilot line of handheld
computers. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCHER _ The portal site snap.com creates a non-profit area
devoted to the Holocaust to tie in with NBC's showing of
Schindler's List Sunday night. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POWERUSER-COLUMN I haven't really dabbled in videoconferencing
online since, well, the first time I ever tried dabbling in it.
After installing the equipment and the program, I hooked into a
reflector _ the server where CU-Seeme users log-in _ and was
greeted by a grainy, black-and-white, choppy-but-unmistakably-live
image of a nudemale torso. That was all I needed to send me
scurrying to the tranquil island of ``Myst.'' I never did get
around to hooking up my camcorder ... until now. (Yandel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ Readers often write me, thinking that I have some
secret method of shielding them from the invasion that arrives
daily in the mailbox when they log on. There are ways to control
junk mail. And some of them are counter-intuitive. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-KIDS _ The Fairy Tale activity center wasn't magical for
Laura Thompson, our 11-year-old software reviewer. She stopped just
short of calling the CD-ROM program boring and confessed that it
didn't hold her attention for very long. (Davis, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA _ Not everyone is a ``Chicken Little'' when it comes
to the Millennium bug. Take John F. Mauldin, who has written a book
called, ``How to profit from the Y2K Recession.'' Mauldin is an
investment analyst and self-proclaimed Y2K expert. And in his book
he advocates taking financial advantage of any disruption from the
Millennium bug. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ A St. Louis company has come up with the software
program for the ultimate control freak. PreNeed funeral planning
software lets you make your own funeral arrangements, from choosing
a funeral director to picking the hue of your headstone. The
program, which retails for $39, is billed as the first funeral
planning product for the PC. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ It seems like Calendar Creator has been around as
long as there have been computers to run it, and I doubt it's
popularity has ever waned. Calendar Creater is published now by
Broderbund, and just came out in Version 6. I would have to say its
power and versatility have outpaced its ease of use. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-ANTENNA _ One of the limitations of satellite television
service is that satellite services don't carry local channels. Your
satellite system delivers all kinds of movies, sports and special
interest programming, but if you want to watch your local news,
you're out of luck. TERK Technologies of Commack, N.Y., sells a
line of antennas that solve that problem by attaching directly to
your 18-inch satellite dish and add the local signal to the wiring
you already have for the satellite. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-PRIVACY _ As the Internet blooms, even the most
technophobic among us deals daily with logins, passwords and the
ever-present issue of privacy. But as network technology gets away
from the desktop and the keyboard, a whole new set of privacy
options arise. How will you protect your smart cards, digital
assistants and home networks? (Gallaga, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-WOLFF-QNA _ Michael Wolff tried to get an Internet business
going way back in the early years of the World Wide Web. He wrote
about his adventures in dealing with venture capitalists, media
barons, old and new, and other Internet gold seekers in a book,
``Burn Rate: How I Survived the Gold Rush Years on the Internet.''
Here's a Q&AMP;A. (Green, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ Pulitzer winner Michael Skube's weekly lifestyle
commentary. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   NFK-CHECKITOUT _ A brief on a new web site, TV show or event for
kids. (Cox News Service) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-NEWSFLASH _ Three or four briefs of world and national news,
written for kids to understand. (Cox News Service) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NFK-FEATURE _ A q&AMP;A with 17-year-old Britney Spears, whose debut
album has been No. 1 for four week. (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMERQ&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumer Q&AMP;A. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) (l, a) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   SXSW-BOBWILLS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As SXSW gets ready to celebrate
new and old music, Bob Wills is still the king in Texas, musicians
say. Even though rock killed his career (despite his claim that he
was rock before Elvis and before it was dubbed that), he was
posthumously inducted Monday (March 15) into the Rock and Roll Hall
of Fame. What does Texas swing have to do with rock 'n' roll?
Wills' daughter lives here, Austin's Asleep atthe Wheel is his
never-ending tribute band and Austinites Al Escovedo and JD Gilmore
recently contributed to a new Wills tribute album featuring a bunch
of punk rockers. Is Bob Wills still the king? And why? (McLeese,
Austin American-Statesman). 40. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
