u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS &LR;      03-15 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL CHAPTER IN STORIED SAGA OF BRAHMIN BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG AND CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The announcement that BankBoston Corp. will be acquired
culminates a storied 215-year history for an institution started by
Yankee merchants and shipowners.
</P>
<P>
   America's first independent bank, which has agreed to be
purchased by Fleet Financial Group, was a sleepy Brahmin
institution for much of its first century. Yet in modern times,
BankBoston produced some innovations that made it stand out among
regional banks: establishing a beachhead in Latin America and
becoming an influential, behind-the-scenes player in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Known as The Massachusetts Bank, it was started in 1784 with
$255,500 in capital to provide loans, bank notes, and deposit
services to Boston business owners who wanted their own institution
instead of depending on British banks.
</P>
<P>
   Following some of its customers in the wool and coffee trade,
BankBoston opened operations in Argentina and Brazil in the early
1900s. Today, Latin America accounts for 20 percent of the bank's
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the bank's flirtation with the silver screen. In
the 1930s, financial institutions were reluctant to lend to
Hollywood studios or to bankroll movies.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Serge Semenenko, who had landed a job at the bank despite
a flamboyant persona and a lack of pedigreed Yankees on his family
tree. Semenenko, a senior executive, was the bank's Hollywood
connection. Like his stuffy peers, he loved yachts. But unlike
them, he insisted on crewing his boats with chorus girls, putting
many a Hub bluenose out of joint. His Hollywood deals made so much
money for the bank that all was forgiven. In the 1950s, Semenenko
helped the bank buy a roughly 30 percent stake in Warner Brothers
Studio.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1930s, BankBoston emerged as the region's premier bank,
eclipsing Shawmut Bank of Boston. And as the nation headed into
World War II, BankBoston was the 10th largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1980s, however, banking was being transformed by
changes in federal law that accelerated the pace of consolidation.
By 1984, BankBoston had slipped to 20th place among the nation's
largest banks.
</P>
<P>
   Social changes had occurred as well. No longer was the bank the
exclusive club of well-heeled Ivy Leaguers. First a Southerner,
William L. Brown, was brought in to run the place. And, later, Ira
Stepanian, the son of an Armenian immigrant who sold cigars, took
over as chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other local banks, BankBoston was hurt by the collapse
in the real estate market in the late 1980s. It reported a $395
million loss in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Such losses meant the bank had to implement huge layoffs. Not
long afterward, in 1991, Bank of Boston stock hit an all-time low
of $3 a share. On Friday, its shares closed at just under $47, a
figure made more impressive by the fact that the stock split in
June.
</P>
<P>
   For much of this century, BankBoston was known as an institution
that specialized in serving large commercial customers. Among other
things, it was noted for nurturing Raytheon Co.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the few regional banks with a substantial overseas
presence, BankBoston has experienced its share of international
volatility.
</P>
<P>
   For more than seven decades, it has operated in Latin America,
opening an office in Buenos Aires in 1917. It has strong operations
in Brazil _ a country whose economic uncertainties have affected
the bank's recent financial results.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston also spent 37 years in Cuba, where it had six
branches before Fidel Castro suspended operations in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the early 1990s, Bank of Boston chose to expand
deeper into consumer banking and small-business lending, largely
through the purchases of smaller banks, including BayBanks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BankBoston's headquarters were undergoing a major
transformation. The US banking industry faced increased competition
for customers and loans by other institutions, such as mortgage
companies and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s, it had become clear that BankBoston either had
to grow by acquiring a rival bank or run the risk of being acquired
itself, possibly by a giant bank from outside the region. When
Fleet acquired Shawmut National Corp. in 1995, its position as the
largest bank in the region was fortified.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Stepanian seemed reluctant to make a deal that could take
the bank to the next level. So the bank's board of directors
pressured him to resign and turned to Charles K. ``Chad'' Gifford,
who promptly engineered the acquisition of BayBanks in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage of New England's second and third-largest banks
pushed BankBoston to new prominence. In the process, the bank,
which had been known as Bank of Boston, dropped the ``of'' from its
name and became known as BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, BankBoston acquired Robertson Stephens, a San
Francisco-based investment firm that enables the bank to underwrite
the public stock offerings of technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gifford seems on the verge of making the biggest deal of his
career by selling his institution to Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   What will that mean? One possible scenario is that a bank with a
storied history will see its name disappear into the history books.
And Gifford will likely be remembered as a man who didn't sell his
bank to an outsider but to a hometown rival.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a certain irony in the purchase of BankBoston. A
Boston Globe story in 1984 noted that BankBoston was such a redoubt
of Brahmins that it didn't hire its first Irish-American employees
until World War II. Now it will be acquired by Fleet, headed by
prominent Irish-American businessman J. Terrence Murray.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
