<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR BELIEVES ADVISER GAVE SOME BAD ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 38, and until October 1997 I had my entire IRA of
$100,000 invested in Fidelity funds, with 40 percent in Magellan,
30 percent in Blue Chip Stock, and 30 percent in Low-Priced Stock
funds. An American Express/IDS financial adviser told me I was not
following the proper asset allocation rules and said I would be
better off in the long run if I took his advice. So I transferred
the entire balance, putting 8 percent in IDS Strategy Aggressive
Growth, 17 percent in IDS Research Opportunities, 10 percent in IDS
Global Bond, 27 percent in IDS Growth, 8 percent in IDS Extra
Income, 11 percent in IDS Emerging Markets, 11 percent in IDS Small
Company Index, and 8 percent in IDS International funds. All
positions are in Class B shares. I recently did some research and
realized that most of these funds are not performing well relative
to their peers. Did I make a mistake? I don't like the fact that he
is only investing in IDS funds. I want to go back to my old way of
investing, which was to depend on Morningstar reports to help me
pick the funds myself. Should I go it alone?
</P>
<P>
   L.N., Boxford, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. Your feeling that the portfolio as a whole has performed
relatively poorly is justified. But the question is: How much do
you want to pay to dig yourself out of this problem?
</P>
<P>
   Since you bought Class B shares, you will face redemption fees
if you sold at this point. So you might want to consider which
funds are performing the best, and which alternative IDS funds you
might transfer into without penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Let's begin, though, with a discussion of asset allocation. I
believe asset allocation is a moving target, and what is a
well-allocated portfolio for a 38-year-old is quite unsuitable for
a 68-year-old, and vice versa. Given that this is all retirement
money, your two bond funds are inappropriate at this stage.
</P>
<P>
   As I calculate your current portfolio, it works out to 52
percent in traditional growth vehicles (Strategy Aggressive,
Research Opportunities, and Growth), 19 percent international
(International and Emerging Markets), 18 percent in fixed-income
(Global Bond and Extra Income), and 11 percent small cap. I have no
problem with the growth segment, but I find the international
position a bit too large and too risky.
</P>
<P>
   I would consolidate the two international positions into IDS
International. At some point you might want to risk money on
emerging markets, but the time isn't now.
</P>
<P>
   I would move the money that's in IDS Strategy Aggressive to IDS
New Dimensions, which is the group's only fund rated five stars by
Morningstar). And I would leave the Growth and Research
Opportunities positions as is.
</P>
<P>
   As for the remaining 29 percent, I would bite my tongue and
withdraw, despite the exit fees. I would then go to Vanguard and
divide the money evenly between Vanguard Small-Cap Index and
Vanguard Specialized Health Care funds.
</P>
<P>
   Why swap one small-cap index fund for another, especially if it
will cost you a redemption fee? Look at the 18.31 percent 52-week
loss for IDS Small-Cap Index fund as reported by Lipper Analytical
Services as of Feb. 25, and then compare it with the 14.23 percent
loss for Vanguard Small-Cap Index for the same period, and you have
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   As for future IRA contributions, you would probably do better by
following your former practice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Correction: I recenlty incorrectly calculated the effects of
retaining a CD as an alternative to paying off a $59,000 7.125
percent mortgage for J.J. of Sharon, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   In my calculations, I omitted a critical step _ subtracting the
taxes that would be due on the money earned by a 6.13 percent
$59,000 CD, a matter of $1,012.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the difference between the cost of the interest of $4,203
a year and the after-tax return from the CD accounts, plus the tax
benefit from the deductibility of the interest payments ($3,781),
is $422.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
