<SLUG> BC-FLEET-DECADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STUNNING DECADE CAPS 200 YEARS OF SLEEPY GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON AND KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It is one measure of an astonishing decade of deal
making by Fleet Financial Group: Of the 10 biggest banks in New
England in 1987, Fleet will own eight of them once it acquires
BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston is the biggest prize of them all for Fleet, which has
long had its eye on its cross-town rival. The $16 billion proposed
deal with BankBoston, announced Sunday, caps a string of
acquisitions in which Fleet has grown from a Rhode Island-chartered
bank to a powerful competitor on the national _ and now
international _ stage.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's savvy isn't obvious to many, said L. William Seidman,
who was once the nation's chief bank regulator.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about the best banks, very few people mention
Fleet,'' he said. But, he added, Fleet was quietly ``doing things
one small piece at a time. They weren't in an exciting area, and
they didn't make any blockbuster deals.''
</P>
<P>
   If the acquisition of BankBoston is completed, Fleet, under
chief executive officer J. Terrence Murray, would become the
nation's eighth-largest banking company.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's scorching trail of acquisitions ranges from a 1986
takeover of tiny Hartford Merrill Bankshares in Bangor, Maine, to
two larger deals in rapid succession _ Shawmut National Corp. and
NatWest Bancorp. _ that doubled Fleet's size in a single year.
</P>
<P>
   Of banks that ranked in the top 10 in New England a decade ago,
only State Street Corp., US Trust, and Fleet have remained
independent. The rest were acquired by either Fleet or BankBoston,
and if the pending deal is approved, they will be combined into one
company: Fleet Boston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet says its lineage reaches back to 1791, when merchant John
Brown formed Providence Bank to help underwrite the expansion of
American manufacturing. By 1954, Fleet had merged with another
Rhode Island bank to become Industrial National Bank, which a
young, scrappy Terry Murray would join in the 1960s. By the end of
that decade, the bank _ now called Industrial Bancorp _ had become
one of the first US bank holding firms listed on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The company signaled its intention to make sweeping changes in
1982, when it hired consultants to develop a new name that conveyed
a more sophisticated image. They chose Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murray has had a very clear vision for his company since the
early 1980s,'' said Nancy Bush, senior vice president of Ryan, Beck
&AMP; Co. in Livingston, N.J. He was ``interrupted by the real estate
debacle in the late 1980s,'' Bush said, ``but in the midst of all
this, he has known where he wanted to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, another deal set the stage for expansion throughout New
England. In its first bank acquisition outside Rhode Island, Fleet
agreed to acquire First Connecticut Bancorp of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   After sweeping deregulation of banking threw open the doors to
interstate banking in the mid-1980s, Fleet expanded its franchise
across New England. That led to purchases of smaller Maine and
Connecticut banks and creation of one of the nation's top 20
lenders.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's deals grew in size. In 1988, Fleet Financial merged with
New York-based Norstar Bancorp, transforming the newly named
Fleet/Norstar Financial Group into a $25 billion bank. By 1990,
Fleet was 14th in US bank rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Fleet's blockbuster deals was its 1991 acquisition of
the failed Bank of New England, then the region's second-biggest
banking company. Fleet bid aggressively, in partnership with the
savvy Wall Street investment firm Kohlberg Kravis &AMP; Roberts. The
deal gave Fleet a huge presence in Massachusetts _ and showed it
could outbid the premier bank in Boston, then called Bank of Boston
Corp. It would not be the last time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Fleet purchased Massachusetts' largest savings bank,
NBB Bancorp, for $437 million.
</P>
<P>
   As it has grown, Fleet also acquired a reputation for being
tough _ some would say cold-hearted. In 1994, the company launched
a program _ called Fleet Focus _ to slash costs and cut more than
3,000 jobs in the name of efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Fleet again moved aggressively to block BankBoston from
another attempted merger _ this time with Shawmut National Corp.
After merger talks between BankBoston and Shawmut fell apart, Fleet
stepped in and acquired Shawmut for $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In acquiring Shawmut, Fleet inherited a number of high-profile
sports franchises in Boston _ getting its name on the new Boston
Garden and becoming banker to the Boston Celtics and the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet established itself as a true Boston institution when it
moved its headquarters to Boston from Providence after acquiring
Shawmut. It soon had $80 billion in financial muscle behind it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Fleet acquired New Jersey-based Natwest, expanding its
reach south to New Jersey and bulking up Natwest's upstart New York
operations. The combination of Fleet, Shawmut, and Natwest put it
in league with other super-regional US banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
