<SLUG> BC-FLEET-DIVEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT CHALLENGE: GETTING THE DEAL PAST THE GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The combination of Fleet Financial Group and
BankBoston Corp. will create an 800-pound gorilla in New England
banking.
</P>
<P>
   The gorilla, however, will have to lose some weight before the
deal is done.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks now operate about 1,500 branches throughout the
Northeast, with deposits of about $110 billion. Sources familiar
with the negotiations said the combined entity will have to sell
about $13 billion worth of deposits to other banks to satisfy
regulators. The regulatory concern is a basic one: The government
doesn't want one bank dominating the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The management of these companies are not pursuing this deal
with the intention of the Feds blocking it,'' said Gerard Cassidy,
a bank analyst with Tucker Anthony. Cassidy, as well as other bank
specialists, expressed confidence that a good-size sale would allow
the merger to pass regulatory muster.
</P>
<P>
   If history is a guide, the merging banks will sell off deposits
and branches in areas where their combined market share is above
the level regulators are willing to tolerate. The banks will also
have to sell loans, including thousands of commercial loans. By the
time the deal is concluded, a large number of local bank customers
will wake up to find they are doing business with a new bank.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators have a complicated index that measures market
share and sets limits on what percentage of the market one bank may
control. Analysts Sunday speculated that sell-offs would be
necessary in Providence, Hartford, and around Boston, where the
overlap between the two banks is greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Under Massachusetts law, no bank may control more than 30
percent of deposits statewide. At the moment the two banks have an
estimated $40 billion in deposits, or nearly 40 percent of the
statewide total, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Danielson, a bank consultant based in Rockville, Md.,
estimated the banks would have to sell $8 billion to $10 billion
worth of deposits in Greater Boston alone. ``That's going to be a
big bite for some other banks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just who will get those deposits was a matter of considerable
speculation Sunday. Under one scenario, some large national bank
could buy the deposits as a way of establishing a foothold in New
England. The names mentioned most often were First Union Corp. and
BankAmerica Corp., both of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Danielson said, however, that Fleet would probably do anything
it could to prevent another big bank from entering New England. He
said it was more likely that Fleet would sell deposits to smaller,
local competitors such as Citizens Financial Group, based in
Providence; UST Corp. in Boston; or People's Heritage Financial
Group of Portland, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gallagher, a New Hampshire lawyer who handles banking
matters, agreed any sales are likely to be local ones. ``This could
be a chance for some medium-sized banks to expand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is quite a bit of precedent for such divestitures. In
1996, after it purchased BayBanks Inc., BankBoston sold a large
number of branches to UST Corp., a deal that allowed the smaller
bank to beef up its presence. In that case regulators insisted the
sale be made to one bank that could become a legitimate competitor
in the Boston market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The antitrust guys will dictate who the winner is here,'' said
one local banker Sunday, who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   When Fleet bought Shawmut National Corp. in 1995 it spun off
some Rhode Island branches into a new bank called the Bank of Rhode
Island. A Fleet sell-off to seal the deal with BankBoston would be
far greater in size than any of those previous deals, analysts
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0872 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-ONBUSINESS-COLU     03-15 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITES JOIN IN UNCERTAIN UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- They are talked about on a first-name basis in every
part of town, the last of Boston's banking giants. Terry and Chad.
Intensely competitive and occasionally combative, they exchanged
public smiles that were hard to really believe.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Financial Group's blockbuster agreement to acquire
BankBoston Corp. is very much a story of Fleet chief Terry Murray
and BankBoston chief executive Chad Gifford. They were the people
who made the deal happen, but Murray and Gifford also personify
corporate cultures that are miles apart and may prove hard to
blend.
</P>
<P>
   Murray built Fleet and its culture from the ground up:
hard-nosed and sometimes ruthless. But more than anything else,
they are opportunistic and creative. Murray and Fleet were thinking
outside the box years before the concept ever filtered into the
banking world.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford spent most of his career inside BankBoston, where a
culture was firmly in place long before his arrival. Powerful and
patrician, with deep Yankee roots, it had a blue-chip reputation
but slow reflexes that were becoming a dangerous limitation in
modern banking. Gifford, by the time he took over as chief
executive in 1995, tried to balance BankBoston's heritage with a
faster pace. Results were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   About town, Gifford and BankBoston seemed at home in the civic
role of an important city institution, almost hammy at times.
Murray and Fleet made their appearances, but seem much more
interested in sticking to business. That was what they were there
to do.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, Sunday's news was a gracious compromise on the
important issues. But was it?
</P>
<P>
   The new name promoted Sunday, Fleet Boston Corp., is a blend of
their corporate identities (memo to Chad: Remember when you told
Bill Crozier his merger would result in BayBanks of Boston? Not for
long, after the ``consultants'' worked it over.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the magnanimous arrangement for Murray to step
down in two years and let Gifford run the firm (another memo to
Chad: Don't forget that BankAmerica chief David Coulter had the
same kind of deal with NationsBank and was pushed out within a
year).
</P>
<P>
   The question remains today: Can these guys get along and can
their companies be put together without punches flying?
</P>
<P>
   Murray started his business career at a small and obscure bank,
Industrial National Bank, after a Providence competitor, Rhode
Island Hospital Trust, turned him down for a job. As the story
goes, the bad news at RIHT came from Clarence Gifford, Chad's
father and the head of Hospital Trust for nine years (no hard
feelings: Murray sent flowers to Clarence Gifford when he was
recently hospitalized).
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to overstate the preeminance of what was called Bank
of Boston in those early days. It ruled New England like no other
banking company: the biggest, the most profitable, and
unquestionably the best. That is what makes the deal announced
Sunday the leading and perhaps ultimate triumph of the Fleet
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial National had changed its name to Fleet before it
struck a series of innovative deals that would build the bank into
a giant. Murray bought Norstar Bancorp of Albany, N.Y., in 1988 and
agreed to give up the top job temporarily. In the dawn of
interstate banking, New England institutions trembled at the
prospect of buyers from New York too big to fend off. No one had
ever considered going the other way, buying a bank outside the
region.
</P>
<P>
   When the failed Bank of New England Corp. was put up for
auction, BankAmerica Corp. and Bank of Boston Corp. rustled up
offers.
</P>
<P>
   The third bidder, Murray, understood the desperation of
regulators to inject outside capital into a staggered banking
system and found a way to engage them. He brought the famous
private investment firm Kolhberg Kravis &AMP; Roberts to the table as
his money partner and scored the coup that truly put Fleet on the
map.
</P>
<P>
   Later still, Murray stepped in the moment merger negotiations
between BankBoston and Shawmut National Corp.'s Joel Alvord
faltered. What was nearly a big victory turned into a grating
setback for BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the events that helped propel Gifford into the top
job at BankBoston, succeeding Ira Stepanian. Right or wrong, the
perception of BankBoston was becoming one of an institution that
was stuck in the mud. Serious suitors called on BankBoston but
those deals fell apart too.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford made his mark quickly by striking a deal to acquire
BayBanks Inc., an important purchase that improved the company's
retail business.
</P>
<P>
   But other moves, like the purchase of investment banking firm
Robertson Stephens Inc., proved to be too expensive to justify, at
least in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter, at least through much of 1998. BankBoston's
strong Latin American business was a story that drove the company's
stock to new heights. But the stock slumped when the world's
emerging markets, including Brazil, took a tumble. BankBoston was
becoming dangerously vulnerable to an unwanted takeover bid.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to join Fleet instead is surely the biggest of
Gifford's career. But making it work, and ending up on top of
Boston's surviving banking giant, is still a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   Count Sunday as a victory for the culture of Terry Murray and
Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
