A0926 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-STADIUM-SCAM-ECON     03-15 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-STADIUM-SCAM-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO WE REALLY NEED NEW STADIUMS?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: San Diego, Denver, Pittsburgh, Indianapolis)   (This excellent 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 13 March 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO, CALIF. _ Three years ago, it seemed that opponents of
huge sports stadiums had won. Such stadiums, they argued, did not
bring economic salvation to cities. The taxpayers believed them,
and in city after city referendums proposing new stadiums were
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tide has turned. Voters in San Diego, Denver and, most
recently, Pittsburgh have all approved new stadiums, to be paid for
largely with public money.
</P>
<P>
   Why the change of heart? After all, even the smoothest
politician hesitates to justify handouts to profitable sports
monopolies owned by millionaires. And nobody has refuted the
blizzard of studies showing that such stadiums have considerably
less economic impact than their supporters suggest.
</P>
<P>
   One such study, by Andrew Zimbalist and Roger Noll, economists
at Smith College and Stanford respectively, in the 1997 ``Brookings
Review,'' showed that Baltimore got only $3 million a year net, in
new jobs and extra tax revenues, from its $200 million Camden Yards
baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the promoters' patter has got better. In the past, the
critics argued that, at the very least, stadium projects needed to
include more than stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   If they did not offer broader benefits to city-dwellers, they
were doing no more, in effect, than transferring wealth from
taxpayers to sports-franchise owners. Enterprising stadium backers
have taken this criticism to heart. Now they promise to spread the
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the problems remain. Take the new $411 million ballpark for
the San Diego Padres, which was approved in a referendum in
November. The project's promoters _ chief among them the city's
mayor, Susan Golding _ argue that the ballpark is merely one piece
of a billion-dollar downtown rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 26 blocks of the city's core will be refurbished
with 600,000 square feet of office space, 150,000 square feet of
retail space and 850 new hotel rooms, as well as the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   This is a complex project, one that requires cooperation among
lots of private and public organizations, and it has already missed
some of its early deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Understandable, no doubt; but at least some of the financing
comes from revenues that are projected to pour into the city's
coffers from a tax on new hotel rooms. These hotels, of course, are
not yet built.
</P>
<P>
   The city also estimates that hotel-room tax revenues will grow
by 8 percent a year, a level reached only in the present boom.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it seems to be expecting an office-space bonanza of
the sort that caused many American cities to come a cropper in the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   More problems are on display in the Pittsburgh project. In
January Pennsylvania's legislature approved a $650 million increase
in the state's debt ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   This is enough to float a bond issue from which $320 million is
earmarked to subsidize four new professional sports stadiums; the
rest is aimed at a hodgepodge of other projects, such as building
an aquarium in Erie and a convention center in Altoona.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters maintain that there are tight financial controls on
project overruns, and call the additional expenditures in
Pittsburgh the economic link that has been missing in past
projects.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the financial controls are lax, and call the
extra money pork-barrel politics _ obvious (and successful)
attempts to buy votes for initiatives that were otherwise unpopular
with Pennsylvania's voters.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Zimbalist of Smith College, a frequent critic of stadium
subsidies, draws an analogy between the complex, interlocking
Pittsburgh projects and omnibus trade bills, and suggests that
voters need what many presidents covet, a line-item veto.
</P>
<P>
   In all these projects, a fundamental question remains. Will the
net revenues be positive? In other words, will success hurt the
city's existing retailers, or will people come from elsewhere to
swell the total number of money-spenders?
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 paper by Mark Rosentraub, an economist at Indiana
University, argued that stadium-driven downtown developments, such
as one he studied in Indianapolis, had little economic benefit _ so
little, in fact, that Indianapolis would probably have done better
to spend its money on something else.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the latest variations on the stadium game have managed to
divide the opposition. Back in 1996, George Will, a conservative
columnist, wrote a scathing column criticizing stadium subsidies as
corporate welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Last autumn, there was Will in the pages of San Diego's Union
Tribune making an exception for the San Diego Padres (of which he
is a director).
</P>
<P>
   Even economists have been caught in the cross fire. Rosentraub
has written a consulting report that supports the
stadium-cum-downtown-development project in San Diego, despite his
earlier study arguing that such developments did no good.
</P>
<P>
   Team owners in Pittsburgh, Denver and San Diego are
understandably elated. After all, despite the cities' claims of
tight budgets, wealthy owners have still gained access to the
public purse while other needy institutions go wanting.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the critics should have been more careful in saying what
they wished for. Having been asked to make more wide-ranging
economic promises, stadium supporters have obligingly delivered _
with riskier projects and even more nebulous benefits. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 850-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer,
she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
