<HEADLINE>
LOVE GIVES TROUBLED MOTHER A FRESH START 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A joyful noise fills this home in late afternoon.
It's the music of Arlene Perez's children at play, their voices a
symphony of yelling, laughing and crying. It's the sweetest sound
to the 28-year-old mother of four; a sound she's just getting
familiar with because, she admits, until now, she wasn't much of a
mother to them.
</P>
<P>
   She left their care to others while she was adrift in the white
storm of cocaine and heroin abuse and a whirlwind of partying. But
in the end, it was her love for the children she'd abandoned that
pulled her back to the shore of sobriety.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, because of her drug problem and neglect, Child
Protective Services (CPS) took custody of Perez's children. In
September 1998, they were returned to her and on Feb. 4, CPS
dismissed custody of them, meaning Perez has sole custody of the
children, are ages 13, 3, 2 and 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the transformation of her life, she's an example of the power
of redemption and the gift of a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of glad CPS got involved and took my children,''
Perez said. ``Because I think if they didn't, I'd probably still be
on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   CPS got involved in August 1996 when her third child, a boy, was
born addicted to cocaine. After his birth, Perez began using
heroin. She stole the drugs from her husband, a drug dealer, who
was the father of her three youngest children.
</P>
<P>
   She failed at treatment programs. Her parents were raising her
children and she'd go months without checking on them, preferring
the blizzard of her addiction to the shelter of her family.
</P>
<P>
   It was when the state took custody that she stepped out of her
drug-induced fog. The murder of her husband last March made her see
even clearer. ``I started thinking, I lost my husband, I lost my
kids. I needed to do something,'' she remembers. ``My main focus
was my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   She's been sober for two years and works as a home health-care
provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's done a wonderful job,'' said Lupe Salas, Perez' CPS
caseworker. ``She chose to make the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally impressed is Associate Judge Peter Sakai who presided
over Perez's case. ``She's a reminder to all of us that people have
the ability to change and do right,'' Sakai said. ``Especially for
her children.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the changes is getting closer to her oldest child. The
seventh-grader spent a year in the Children's Shelter and in a
foster home. ``It was bad,'' the 13-year-old said. ``I didn't get
to see or talk to nobody. I was mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she respects her mother. ``I'm proud of the way she is
because she fought for her kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez's partying days are over, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to sleep at 9 'o clock,'' she said as her teen-ager
winces.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is actively involved in her daughter's education and
attends all parent-teacher conferences.
</P>
<P>
   She believes her evolution from a drugged-out and neglectful
mother to a caring and attentive one is testament to people's
ability to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can change if they put their minds to it,'' she said.
``I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Of children, all children, she said: ``They need love and for
you to take care of them. They need 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   She pauses and listens to the joyful noise outside. ``Children
need their parents. Nobody can love children more than their
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
