r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-15 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM BARBIE: FASHIONABLE AND REALISTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ You wouldn't know Barbie was hitting middle age
were it not for the hoopla last week over her official 40th
birthday. She doesn't look a day over 18 and the doll's most
popular model miraculously has retained impossible 38-18-34
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a hint Mattel is starting to understand the
influence it can have on little girls. No, there aren't any big
changes coming down the pike for Barbie. Fantasy is still her
thing. Mattel, the company that manufactures the doll, instead is
putting money toward issues where Barbie's image could be a greater
force: supporting programs that teach girls about technology, money
and finance, math and science, life skills and career planning, the
media and sports.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel is donating $1.5 million to Girls Inc., the organization
that formerly was the Girls Club of America. One of their
collaborative efforts includes developing a Web site with stories
of successful women that both groups hope will enrich girls.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution is significant but Mattel still misses the mark
as Barbie remains little more than a glamour doll. When I railed on
Barbie more than a year ago, a few female readers complained that I
was bashing the dreams of little girls. Not so. I merely wanted
Mattel to give girls something more substantive to dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Most little girls probably don't clamor for Barbies that
symbolize anything more than a glamorous fantasy world. That is,
after all, the doll's principal attraction, as the readers pointed
out. But Mattel has seen fit to give girls a meatier dream with
their Soccer and WNBA Barbies. There's even a NASCAR Barbie!
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, the company introduced Barbies that had more
active lifestyles. The official Barbie Internet site notes that the
doll took on more athletic roles. She also made a breakthrough as a
``credit-card carrying executive.'' In the 1990s, Barbie even was a
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Why not president? For that matter, why not Barbie, the chief
executive?
</P>
<P>
   The Barbie Web site includes a section that allows a buyer to
design her own doll. You can give the doll a name, select her look,
even her personality.
</P>
<P>
   Mine would be the ``You-Go-Girl'' Barbie and she'd look like
this: (Mattel, take notes.)
</P>
<P>
   I'd opt for the Barbie model with the athletic body. It's closer
to, ahem, reality.
</P>
<P>
   She would wear a fresh-looking suit, nothing too severe. And she
wouldn't wear those gravity-defying, bunion-busting heels the
Mattel designers are so fond of. My Barbie would wear fashionable,
but comfortable, shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Her personality? Assertive and fair, thoughtful and empathetic.
Above all, confident.
</P>
<P>
   No, this is no Masquerade Gala or Hollywood Legends Barbie. This
Barbie is a real-world dream to which little girls can aspire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
