<HEADLINE>
CORKSCREWS COME IN MANY VINTAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Early wines in ancient Egypt and Rome were stored
in animal skins, wooden barrels and earthenware jars. Sometimes
hides were used to cover jar openings, and even large pieces of
cork.
</P>
<P>
   As bottles grew longer and stored horizontally for aging wine,
they had tighter corking, which required compression of the cork.
This also made them harder to extract. As a result, the bottle
screw was born in late 17th-century England, and some of them
survive.
</P>
<P>
   The first patent for a corkscrew was taken out in 1795 by the
Rev. Samuel Henshall in Oxford, England. Since then, there have
been hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   It evolved from the worm or screw on a ramrod, or cleaning rod,
that functioned as a method to remove a gun's charge from firearms.
Go to any household or wine store and you'll find a variety of
corkscrews from under $5 to more than $130 for a gourmet type that
both removes and replaces the cork in the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   But for some, corkscrews are as personal as a fountain pen,
where you never let anyone else write with your nib.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s the auction house Sotheby's re-released its
coffee-table book ``Collectible Corkscrews.'' There are literally
thousands of variations out there.
</P>
<P>
   Yves Rousset-Rouard, owner of the Domaine de la Citadelle winery
in Menerbes, France, has a collection of more than 1,700 corkscrews
in his museum.
</P>
<P>
   A corkscrew comprises a shaft and helix (spiral), or worm.
Usually the helix goes just so far down into the cork before
halting. At this point it can also turn the cork in the bottle's
neck, thus loosening it and making it easier to extract.
</P>
<P>
   Some corkscrews require the strength of Arnold Schwarzenegger to
use, while others make removing a wine cork as simple as taking a
cotton ball out of the top of a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Corkscrews use levers, gears and screws. Some feature
combinations of the aforementioned, as well as a knife for cutting
the foil seal and a brush for cleaning the cork and sediment away
from the mouth of the bottle. They come table size and pocket size.
</P>
<P>
   Materials are also as diverse as the mechanism itself. The
handles of antique corkscrews have been made from porcelain, gold,
bone, horn, ivory or silver.
</P>
<P>
   Before you throw out that old corkscrew in favor of a new
high-tech model, know that since the 1970s, corkscrews have become
collectible items in their own right. People often have one or more
corkscrews. It can take a while to find one that you personally
like to use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
