r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-WARS-JUNKIE-HNS &LR;      03-15 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-JUNKIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EMPIRE STRIKES BACK WITH NEW ERA OF CONSUMERISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JASON LLOREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The full title is ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace,'' but most fans call it EP1 or TPM. When the flick
finally hits the big screen on May 19, it might as well be Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   You thought the mania was bad in 1977, when moviegoers lined up
by the block to see the original ``Star Wars.'' That was nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years has given my generation plenty of time to
anticipate TPM. It's bigger than the Second Coming of Christ _ it's
the Fourth Coming of Vader.
</P>
<P>
   Fanaticism will grow exponentially as the opening approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Campers will crowd theater parking lots. Credit card sales will
surge as people scarf up movie tickets days in advance. Fans will
swamp toy stores to snag the newest action figures.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts, jackets, anything slapped with a ``Star Wars'' logo
will pile up on shelves. Collectors will stock up on multiple
copies of mint-condition memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not immune to any of this, especially the merchandising.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Star Wars'' premiered in 1977, I became a 7-year-old Jedi
zombie. I managed to convince my dad I needed every new Kenner
action figure or toy vehicle. Collector cards, bed sheets _ you
name it, I had those, too.
</P>
<P>
   A baby boomer co-worker once told me how he had to have a Davy
Crockett coonskin cap because the other boys did. For me, and for
my friends, the light saber was our coonskin cap. On Halloween, my
pal Tim Partain dressed up like Luke Skywalker and had a customized
saber consisting of a flashlight and a long glass tube. I'm still
jealous.
</P>
<P>
   But the light saber just whetted my appetite. I bought ``Star
Wars'' stuff like it was junk food. I owned dozens of action
figures, which I kept at the ready next to my bed in a cardboard
box. I had the battery-operated Stormtrooper Blaster with folding
rifle stock. My favorite item: a multilevel Death Star set,
complete with exploding laser cannon, tractor beam tower and even a
garbage compactor room (to re-enact that crushing-wall scene).
</P>
<P>
   When ``The Empire Strikes Back'' hit the theaters, the Force
continued to feed my frenzy. I bought the Hoth Battle Playset. I
was about 10, so scrounging the six or seven bucks to buy it was
tough.
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``Return of the Jedi'' came out in 1983, I had eased
up a bit. I was about to enter high school and set my sights on
more important matters: girls and cars. I put the toys and my inner
sci-fi geek in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   There they stayed until the digitally enhanced ``Star Wars''
trilogy was released a few years ago. Out came Luke, Leia and the
rest of the bunch. I found myself back on the sidewalk, lining up,
waiting for hours to relive that magic. Eventually, the dark side
of the Force drew me in: I started to buy up more toys.
</P>
<P>
   This time they were much better _ the craftsmanship had
improved, the detail was finer and, hey, even the large Han Solo
action figure looked like Harrison Ford. They were also more
expensive. My wallet began to leak.
</P>
<P>
   I gobbled up the goods one at a time: Luke Skywalker, Princess
Leia and R2D2 action figures, at about $6 a pop. Then the
variations: Luke with the cut-off hand a la ``Empire,'' Darth Vader
with removable helmet, the 9-inch Luke with real clothing (Hey, now
he can date Barbie!).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I couldn't pass up getting a saber. Several ads in
the back of sci-fi magazines were selling unofficial all-metal
replicas that looked exactly like the ones Obi-Wan and Vader wield.
Some of these cost $250.
</P>
<P>
   I resisted and settled for the licensed kiddie, all-plastic
version, which was extendible, lighted up at a push of the button,
and hummed as it moved, in the films. I bought one in Vader red,
another in Luke green: about $30 for the pair.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to upgrade. The Millennium Falcon with blinking
lights, rotating laser turrets and sound effects, and the
four-legged AT-AT _ that set me back about $120. I forked over
another $40 for the ``Star Wars'' edition of Monopoly, then shelled
out $20 for the Vader coin bank that lights up his red saber and
plays his ``Imperial March'' theme song. Another $70 and I owned a
copy of Luke's beige jacket from ``Empire.''
</P>
<P>
   After acquiring maybe 50 action figures and countless other new
items, I was forced to cut back _ my cash flow and storage space
couldn't keep pace with the flood of new stuff. Nowadays I pick up
an action figure every month or so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad I slowed down when did. I recently picked up the latest
``Star Wars Insider'' magazine, the official fans' rag, and found
an ad for a life-sized R2D2 and C3PO (with light-up parts), for
$7,000 and $7,500, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   I'll stick to my $5 5-inch versions, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we now have the Internet, the latest pusher to feed
my addiction. I stumbled onto the on-line ``Star Wars''
marketplace, Mos Espa, at www.mosespa.com (conveniently linked from
the official www.starwars.com). With just a few clicks, I placed a
pre-order for the long-awaited Lego TIE Fighter &AMP; Y-Wing Fighter
set ($55), and snagged a deal on a Luke doll in Hoth Gear (half
off, for just $15).
</P>
<P>
   As long as they make it this simple, I'm never gonna quit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
