<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0947 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      03-15 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP ATTEMPTS BROAD APPEAL TO PRESERVE HOUSE MARGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clinging to the slimmest House majority in 45
years, Republican leaders are waging a crucial struggle to avoid a
do-nothing image that could threaten their tenuous grip on power in
the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   With only six votes needed to shift the balance of power between
the parties, House GOP leaders have broken with former speaker Newt
Gingrich's strategy and are reaching out across the Democratic
spectrum _ from conservative lawmakers to organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican goal remains far from fulfilled, and with the
GOP's slender majority, any one of a panoply of House factions
could tilt the outcome of the most important debates in the 106th
Congress. Moderate Republicans, conservative Democrats, and a range
of interparty interest groups all see the potential to exert their
power.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who unexpectedly lost five seats in the 1998
elections, outnumber Democrats by only 222-211, with an additional
seat held by an independent. Another seat is vacant after the
recent retirement of the former speaker-designate, Robert L.
Livingston, a Louisiana Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in fat city,'' said Representative Sherwood L. Boehlert
of New York, a senior member of a coalition of moderate
Republicans. ``This could be our moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Some moderate and conservative Democrats feel equally empowered.
Regularly invited by Speaker J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois to lobby
for their legislative priorities, several Democrats issued an
appraisal of the speaker's leadership that is likely to clash with
their party's election plans to portray House Republicans as
partisan extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speaker is really interested in being inclusive,'' said
Representative Tim Roemer, an Indiana Democrat who has met twice
with Hastert on budget and education issues. ``He has reached out
to moderate and conservative Democrats in a genuine way.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the House has yet to take up the most contentious
issues on the GOP agenda, the stakes in the struggle are enormous.
After deferring major action last year on issues such as Social
Security and health care, Republican leaders are dogged by polls
that show the public yearns for Congress to shed its image as an
investigative body that has focused on President Clinton at the
expense of vital legislative business.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastert, burdened with the thinnest majority since Speaker
Joseph Martin, a Massachusetts Republican, presided over the 83d
Congress in 1954, is given little chance, even among his
supporters, of posting major achievements in the run-up to the 2000
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers said the GOP's slender majority increases the
need for Republican leaders to focus on a centrist agenda that
could foster a possible bipartisan consensus. But Hastert faces a
number of obstacles, ranging from powerful competing interests
within the GOP ranks and lingering acrimony between the parties
over the impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be extraordinarily difficult for Denny Hastert
to hold this group together,'' said Representative Charles F. Bass,
a New Hampshire Republican who is a potential swing vote on social
issues. ``We're not going to change the world in 1999 and 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP moderates already have forced Republican leaders to abandon
one of their top priorities, a 10 percent across-the-board
income-tax cut. The moderate group of 40 to 50 Republicans also has
warned GOP leaders that it will fight plans to finance tax cuts by
cutting some domestic programs substantially.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that our influence has expanded,''
Boehlert said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Republican leaders may have to settle for modest
accomplishments, such as a minor tax cut, a measure granting local
communities greater control of federal education funds, and
incremental progress in protecting patients' rights and making
health insurance more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, finding common ground is pivotal to House Republicans,
who have lost seats in each election since the GOP seized control
of Congress in 1994. If they lose six or more seats in 2000, they
will return to the minority status they had endured since they last
lost power in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the risks, Republican leaders have gone to unusual
lengths to prevent surprise legislative setbacks, even appealing to
GOP lawmakers to inform them if they plan to miss a vote for any
reason.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders, forsaking Gingrich's more confrontational approach,
also have taken the rare step of holding a series of meetings with
one of their most powerful foes, organized labor. Although union
leaders have shown little interest in supporting the Republican
agenda, the meetings reflect a strategy that Livingston espoused
last year before he abandoned his prospective speakership following
revelations of his extramarital affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have slim margins, you can't do everything you
want,'' Livingston said. ``With a margin of only six votes, I'm
going to have to work with people who don't believe the same way I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has tried to create a conciliatory climate in part by
scheduling a bipartisan retreat next weekend in Hershey, Pa. But
leaders in both parties have struggled to sell rank-and-file
members on the notion of sacrificing a weekend at home to bond with
their political adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Edward J. Markey, a Massachusetts Democrat, said
divisions between the parties run too deep to address in a weekend
getaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not yet dealt with the underlying pathology that
affects this institution,'' Markey said. ``That will require
lancing the boil of bitterness and acrimony that characterizes the
relationship between Republicans and Democrats. It needs to happen
here, day by day, not in Hershey.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans such as Boehlert also see little merit in
approaching the retreat as the gateway to a happier, more
productive House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intentions are very sincere, but the results inevitably
are very short-lived,'' he said. ``We can talk all we want about
the Red Sox and the Yankees and Roger Clemens, but what good is it
if we come back on Monday and everyone starts blasting each other
again?''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the divisions, Clinton's quest to diminish the taint of his
impeachment with a major legislative achievement might contribute
to bipartisan action. Both parties also want to demonstrate a
desire to address the nation's problems, which could provide more
impetus for consensus.
</P>
<P>
   But the polarizing force of a pivotal election looms. ``If
everything works out,'' Roemer said, ``we could have a few months
or so of bipartisanship, but then it could all blow up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
