<HEADER>
A0949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCKINNEY-SPEAKS-ART-2     03-15 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKINNEY-SPEAKS-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GENE MCKINNEY, A LIFETIME OF DUTY TURNED UPSIDE DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WIL HAYGOOD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   MANASSAS, Va. _ When the end came, on a winter's day, in the
klieg lights of a galloping sex scandal, the Army left him for
dead, Gene McKinney says.
</P>
<P>
   It was a thousand times worse than friendly fire, he says,
because no one tried to stop the bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I equate this to a battlefield,'' the former sergeant major of
the Army said in an interview, his first in the year since his
court martial on sex charges ended in acquittal on all but one
count. ``You ask me to go out on a battlefield and perform a
mission and I get wounded and get left out there.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, still deeply wounded, is now preparing to fire back
with an explosive legal claim of his own: that military prosecutors
concealed evidence and covered up lies by some of the witnesses
against him, women soldiers who accused him of sexual
improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   But back then, during the court martial ordeal, all he could
think about was the nearly 100 years of combined military service
McKinney men had given to Uncle Sam. He and his brothers saw
soldiers swooping up Route 90, which runs through their hometown of
Monticello, Fla., during the Cuban Missile Crisis, when Fidel
Castro and the Russians were scaring everyone.
</P>
<P>
   That sold the McKinneys on the service. They'd raise rifles,
too. They'd crunch through the weeds of Vietnam, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then it came down to the scandal, the gnawing mess of it all.
His daddy down there in Florida, out on the sun porch, cursing the
military, losing faith. It came down to his sister Essie swearing
she'd never send one of her boys into the military. It came down to
James, his twin brother, leaving the military after three decades,
saying blood was thicker than his love of the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Gene McKinney says his woes grew out of his style of leadership,
the way he'd open his heart and soul and home to soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural for me to help people who need help,'' he said.
``Mom would not allow us to have an evil spirit in ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Army prosecutors, however, said Gene McKinney had a touch of
evil. They said he was a sexual predator. They gave him credit,
sure enough, for being charming. But they also said he was
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   It was a year ago today that McKinney, now retired as the Army's
highest-ranking noncommissioned officer, emerged relatively
victorious from a court martial that saw him acquitted of a
sweeping set of sexual harassment charges that included adultery.
But he was convicted on a single obstruction count.
</P>
<P>
   The six-week trial at Virginia's Fort Belvoir sent slivers of
raw emotion out across the country. And there were those who felt
that the old witches' brew _ race and sex _ was at work again.
McKinney is black; five of his six accusers are white.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six women, five have gone on with their military careers;
one resigned before the court martial began. The waters of Army v.
McKinney remain muddied, the accusations still ricochet as the case
proceeds on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The suddenness of McKinney's fall obscured the astonishing
trajectory of his Army career. Long before the hourglass stopped on
Feb. 10, 1997 _ the day McKinney was suspended from the Army _ his
was no ordinary soldier's life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, a Negro teen and his twin brother left the Deep South.
They took what Elizabeth and Henry McKinney could give them _ the
country upbringing, the family dignity, ``a sense of right and
wrong,'' says Gene McKinney _ and joined the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Pulled on Army khakis.
</P>
<P>
   Laced up Army boots.
</P>
<P>
   And, amid thousands and thousands of other soldiers, became Army
stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would say, `Watch the McKinney boys.' That's how we
were referred to: `the McKinney boys,' '' said James McKinney, the
identical twin who, in a touch of the surreal, stepped in as
interim sergeant major of the Army when the earth began to crack
beneath the shiny shoes of the man who looked just like him.
</P>
<P>
   Gene McKinney had an office at the Pentagon. He had a good wife
in Wilhemina. Met her in Florida when they were just children.
Their only son, Zuberi, was away at college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you my job,'' McKinney is saying. It's early
morning and he's seated on a sofa in his Manassas home. The voice
is deep, rich. ``My job was to represent every enlisted person in
the Army _ over a million people when you talk about the National
Guard, the Reserves. My job was to go out and talk _ to do more
listening than talking . . . I briefed the secretary of the Army. I
would testify before Congress. I traveled with the secretary of
defense every three months.''
</P>
<P>
   He knew a soldier's sweat, the hundred little agonies that can
nag any soldier. He'd been a grunt himself.
</P>
<P>
   Once he marched into a roach-infested dining hall and closed it.
His soldiers _ as sergeant major they were all his soldiers _ were
complaining about the food.
</P>
<P>
   Too many soldiers, he'd tell the brass, lived in crime-infested
areas, lived in homes with mice scooting across the kitchen floor.
``Living paycheck to paycheck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He loved, more than anything, rising from his office, hopping a
plane, going to a training field. He loved getting his shoes muddy,
marching right up to a foxhole, looking down at a startled soldier,
then stopping the soldier from getting up out of the foxhole to
greet him. ``I'd say, `No, no, let me come down to you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His door was always open. That's what he'd tell soldiers.
``Busloads of soldiers would come up to my house. They would say,
`Sergeant Major, can we take a picture with you?' Back in their
hometown, that's bragging rights for them. They'd go home and say,
`Guess what? We went to the sergeant major house and he let us in.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Women soldiers would phone him at home as often as men. They'd
be seeking advice, words of comfort. ``It became a way of life,''
said Wilhemina, his wife. ``It was nothing unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we both admired about each other,'' said James McKinney,
himself breaking his yearlong silence on the scandal, ``is we took
care of our people. Those that needed a kick in the butt, we kicked
in the butt. Those that needed our arms put around them, we did
that. I even sometimes loaned my soldiers money. I let them borrow
my car.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Of course, it was illegal to do that,'' Gene added. ``But there
are two types of leaders. One who does things right. And one who
does the right thing. One . . . follows the rules all the time. The
other does what is right to help the family of a soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to be very well known for honoring our commitment to
our soldiers,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we used to do when we got young black
lieutenants in,'' Gene said, ``is we'd pull them aside and tell
them things to be aware of: You can't be in parties anymore. Can't
walk around like you're at some toga party. Because once they nick
you, it's over with.''
</P>
<P>
   In November of 1996, one of the most explosive sex scandals in
the history of the United States military erupted at the Aberdeen
Proving Ground military installation near Baltimore. Accusations of
forced sex with young female enlistees stunned the command. There
would be courts martial and prison sentences. The US military was
staring down the barrel of a sexual apocalypse.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 4, three months after the Aberdeen scandal, Gene
McKinney was accused by a former aide of having tried to coerce her
into having sex. Six days later he was suspended. ``I went back to
my office,'' he recalled. ``Told my soldiers. They started
crying.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
