<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JETS-WARMING-HNS &LR;      03-15 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JETS-WARMING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOARING JET TRAFFIC LINKED TO GLOBAL WARMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Virginia, Maryland, California)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An explosion in commercial air traffic may be
triggering formation of high-altitude clouds that trap heat and
could worsen global warming.
</P>
<P>
   And the problem could grow: Global aircraft emissions should
increase sixfold by the time today's college students are ready for
retirement, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The menace comes in a beautiful form, the cirrus clouds that
resemble silver, windblown beards and float at 20,000- to
50,000-feet.
</P>
<P>
   The jets emit tiny particles that serve as ``condensation
nuclei.'' High-altitude water vapor collects on these particles,
crystallizes, and forms the icy clouds. Research shows that some
contrails expand into huge, natural-looking cirrus clouds that
cover thousands of square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have long known that cirrus clouds usually block the
escape of Earth's infrared radiation, heating the planet. Increased
cirrus cover might, therefore, hasten global warming.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, researchers began intensely studying the
possible threat of jet-bred cirrus clouds, and now, just as they're
beginning to gather useful data, Congress is eliminating the
project as of Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working furiously trying to turn (the cancellation)
around,'' said Don Anderson, scientific leader of the program, the
Atmospheric Effects of Aviation Project at NASA's Goddard Space
Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The program was budgeted for $7 million in the current fiscal
year, which ends Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're scrambling trying to find other funding,'' said Patrick
Minnis, a NASA atmospheric scientist who is a leading figure in
contrails research. So far, that quest has been unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the researchers say the scientific data are becoming
ominous:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cirrus cloud cover has increased an average of 5 percent over
three National Weather Service stations in Northern California
since 1971, said Minnis, who is based at NASA's Langley Research
Center in Hampton, Va.
</P>
<P>
   _ The nation as a whole has experienced about a 5 percent
increase in cirrus cloud cover since 1971, Minnis' data show.
</P>
<P>
   _ Very clear evidence exists of increased cirrus cloudiness over
the Northeastern United States, which swarms with air traffic,
since the early 1980s, French researcher Olivier Boucher reported
in the Jan. 7 issue of the British journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
   By analyzing cloud observations made from 1982 to 1991 by
observers at U.S. weather stations, Boucher found ``a clear
signal'' of increased cirrus cloudiness over the Northeast United
States. ``Over the Western United States, the signal is not so
clear,'' he said in response to an e-mail query.
</P>
<P>
   If the contrail risk is real, it could lead to warmer weather in
regions where air travel is high.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, important early findings were uncovered by NASA's
SUCCESS project (Subsonic Aircraft: Contrail and Cloud Effects
Special Study). In the project, scientists used aircraft to form
contrails, then studied them close up.
</P>
<P>
   They flew through the contrails to capture and analyze their
content of ``aerosols,'' which are very small particles on which
ice crystals might form, producing cirrus clouds.
</P>
<P>
   They also formed contrails into easily noticeable shapes, ovals,
and tracked them by satellites for long periods.
</P>
<P>
   Cirrus clouds typically form between 20,000 and 50,000 feet
above sea level. The wispier cirrus clouds form close to the
50,000- foot range, while the more overcast cirrus _ broad, dense
sheets called cirrostratus _ form at around 20,000 feet.
Contrail-bred cirrostratus are the biggest worry, because they
cover the largest area of sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We documented several cases where contrails evolved into
things that looked like natural cirrus,'' said Eric Jensen, a
specialist on cloud microphysics at NASA's Ames Research Center in
Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of global aircraft emissions is expected to increase
by up to six times by 2050. Passenger miles in air travel soared in
the United States alone to 605 million in 1997 from 404 million in
1987, according to the Air Transport Association in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The link between aviation and the increase in cirrus clouds is
``not an absolute truth,'' Anderson said, but some researchers
believe the data ``strongly suggest that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
