<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0953 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCKINNEY-SPEAKS-2ND &LR;  &UR;      03-15 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKINNEY-SPEAKS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 MANASSAS, Va.: ... started crying.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time the grounds at his military base had thawed from
winter, five more women had come forward claiming sexual harassment
by McKinney. The Army launched an exhaustive investigation, and
upon its completion, announced that there was sufficient evidence
to proceed with a court martial.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney denied all charges. He says he was a victim of the
convulsions that followed Aberdeen.
</P>
<P>
   Husband and wife sequestered themselves. A stoic Gene McKinney
told his family members down in Florida that it would all blow
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Gene thought the cavalry was coming to save him,''
said Essie Rollins, his sister.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, the world wanted to know, ``Who's Gene
McKinney?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The home was at 905 4th Street in Monticello, near Florida's
northern border. ``Just a little two-room shack, to tell you the
truth,'' Elizabeth McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth raised the kids and sweated in the kitchen. Henry
sweated in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   It was inching toward noon on Nov. 3, 1950, when Elizabeth
McKinney summoned her midwife. Later that day she delivered two
boys. James arrived first, and 30 minutes later Gene. It was a
difficult birth. They were breech babies, born feet first.
Elizabeth's daddy looked down over them. ``They'll be special
boys,'' he said. ``They'll be brave.''
</P>
<P>
   The twins were dutiful children. ``They worked in the fields,''
their father said. ``They worked in watermelon patches. They saved
their money and bought their own school clothes. Never had to worry
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   They graduated from high school in 1968. James McKinney signed
up for the Army right away. Gene wanted a taste of the world. He
went north. Detroit was far enough.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, smoke got in his eyes. ``They were killing people,''
Gene McKinney said of the Detroit riots. ``I used to tell people,
`I can get paid for doing this.' So I joined the Army.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, he was fingering his orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked God to give me a sign he'd come back,'' Elizabeth
McKinney said of the day when her son Gene told her he was on his
way overseas.
</P>
<P>
   A violent thunderstorm woke her from sleep just before he left.
``That was my sign. I knew he'd be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   He landed in Vietnam with the 173d Airborne. ``A lot of blacks
in that unit,'' Gene McKinney said. ``A lot of blacks in Vietnam,
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Marching through jungle, seeing what wasn't there in the inky
nights, breathing bad dreams and death, sleeping with eyes open,
everything about living and dying started to blur.
</P>
<P>
   Gene McKinney celebrated his 19th birthday hauling grenades and
looking over his shoulder for Charley and under his feet for booby
traps.
</P>
<P>
   He returned home to Florida in 1971. Best job he could find was
installing air conditioners. He hated it. And so, 38 days out, Gene
McKinney marched right back into the Army.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Benning in 1971 Gene McKinney was named Soldier of the
Year. He stayed four years in Germany. Wonderful reviews and
promotions followed.
</P>
<P>
   As Gene was promoted, James was never far behind. ``There was no
one else out there,'' James said, ``who I thought could compete
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   On leave, the McKinney sons returned home to Florida. They'd
slip their mother some money. ``Build you a new bathroom, Momma,''
Gene told her.
</P>
<P>
   Essie would sit at the dinner table and listen to Gene and James
talk about the Army, the racial harmony. ``I didn't think they were
living in reality,'' Essie said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rumors had started that the McKinney brothers were sergeant
major of the Army material.
</P>
<P>
   It's all the same Army _ enlisted and officers _ but it's a
different river for each. Officers have clubs, make policy, hang
among themselves. You come into the Army off the streets, a buck
private, like Gene and James McKinney, you might not have any grand
dreams. You might just wish to be a solid soldier.
</P>
<P>
   But if you did have dreams, you might set your sights on the
position of sergeant major of the Army. That's the highest an
enlisted man can go. It'd take a hundred little miracles. It might
even take a mother's belief in thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   In July of 1995, Gene McKinney became the 10th sergeant major of
the United States Army.
</P>
<P>
   James and Henry Jr., another brother, made Gene's ceremony in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Florida boys.
</P>
<P>
   Henry was beside himself.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left Germany, Henry Jr. pulled Gene aside. Just some
brotherly advice. ``We talked about women, about the need to never
be one-on-one with a woman now, to always be seen in a crowd.
Things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did with those women was no different than what I did
with male soldiers,'' McKinney said. ``One female said she was at
my house. Said we had sex on my couch in the sun room. Had she ever
been in my house? Well, she came by my house to make assignments
for my trips. Anytime a soldier rings my doorbell _ male or female
_ they get invited in.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you say, `Gene, why would you invite soldiers into your
home?' . . . Can you imagine the most senior guy in the Army
denying soldiers the right to know how he lives?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never touched any of them in any kind of manner other than a
handshake,'' McKinney said of his accusers. ``I may have had my
hands on Brenda's shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was always as a show of support, like comforting
her,'' Wilhemina said.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, the first black sergeant major of the Army, refused to
blame race for his downfall. But it seeped out into the open soon
enough.
</P>
<P>
   A black retired general asked McKinney to meet him in a park,
for a talk. The general begged McKinney to take a plea bargain,
said the court martial was bad for Army morale, that it was harming
black soldiers. Then the general started weeping.
</P>
<P>
   No such show of sympathy, however, came from Togo West, the
secretary of the Army.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `I reported to Togo West, a black man. He put his tail between
his butt and ran,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen ``Not guilty'' verdicts echoed through the courtroom.
The sole guilty conviction, on an obstruction count, concerned a
phone call McKinney had made to one of his accusers.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Barnes, lawyer for Brenda Hoster, McKinney's first
accuser, says the Army chose to prosecute the case with
well-meaning _ but inexperienced _ prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Army very reluctantly brought this to
prosecution,'' said Barnes, a Denver-based attorney who works with
women who have military discrimination claims. ``We never asked for
any criminal charge. We just asked the Army to treat it like other
sex harassment cases. But given his prominence, they couldn't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes says she still fervently believes in McKinney's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney's lawyer, Charles Gittins, says he thinks he can prove
the case against the sergeant major was built on untruthful
testimony by key witnesses. As part of McKinney's appeal, Gittins
is pressing a freedom of information claim for documents he said
were illegally concealed from the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In private interviews with Army prosecutors, witnesses were
cross-examined and caught in lies and still sent to the witness
stand,'' Gittins said. ``When Army prosecutors violate the law to
obtain a conviction, they need to be held accountable. Since the
Army won't do it, I'm going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Army prosecutors, citing McKinney's appeal, refuse to comment on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gene and Wilhemina McKinney live in a fine home in
Manassas. They've only got each other now. Zuberi died from
injuries suffered in a car accident three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gene McKinney hasn't hung one Army picture on the wall. He says
he won't. Let it all die. Let it all go away.
</P>
<P>
   He's only 48 years old. He's job hunting. He might get into
communications work.
</P>
<P>
   Some mornings he goes for walks. There are woods in back of his
home. He loves it when it's raining out. He says it reminds him of
marching across Army fields, going to meet his soldiers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
