<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0954 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRANT-IMAGE-BOS &LR;      03-15 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-IMAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE MELTING POT TO THE JACKPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time Joe DiMaggio took the field in Yankee Stadium, a
shy, 22-year-old boy-hero who spoke with his bat, Frank Sinatra, a
year younger, had already talked his way across the river from
Hoboken and was crooning for the big bands, ambition glinting off
his toothy smile.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades that followed _ indeed, for all of mid-century
America _ Sinatra and DiMaggio shared an important credential: They
were among the first celebrities minted in urban, immigrant
America, and thus were competing role models for neighborhood boys
with downtown dreams.
</P>
<P>
   They existed in parallel universes, and sent out sharply
opposing messages.
</P>
<P>
   Now that they are both gone, the sheer power of their images
attests to something bigger than baseball and more enduring than
gold records. It is the strength of celebrity, the ability to lead
by gesture, and the enormous influence that accrues to those with
charisma.
</P>
<P>
   ``If DiMaggio was the good boy, Sinatra was the bad boy,''
explained historian Thomas O'Connor. ``Sinatra was tough. Rumors
had it he was tied in with the mob. That was part of his appeal.
There was surface polish, but, underneath, the almost sinister
element of suppressed violence. . . . DiMaggio was soft-spoken,
polite. If he wasn't the kids' model of appeal, he probably was for
their mothers.''
</P>
<P>
   The aspirations of millions seemed to exist in the vast distance
between them. For the sons of immigrants looking for a stake in
America, they were two fables, two choices, two models for success.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra wore his class resentments on his gold cufflinks. His
triumph was that of the street kid who achieved power without
dimming the crude force of his personality. As a singer he was
famous for his enunciation, but between songs, he spoke with a
thick, almost thuggish, Jersey accent. It advertised his ascent in
the world, reminding listeners exactly where he came from and where
he had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio was a born ballplayer, a natural, and thus represented
success without politics: His was the triumph of God-given talent
in America's emerging meritocracy. Like many heroes, he sprang from
nowhere _ actually, the fishing village of Martinez, Calif., near
San Francisco _ and was propelled by unseen strength. He never
pushed his way onstage; even while patrolling centerfield in 10
World Series, he hardly seemed to work up a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   When his baseball feats elevated him in New York social circles,
he exuded a gentlemanly grace; his manners were pristine, almost
virginal. He was, in the parlance of the times, ``well brought
up.'' His mother and father, who had nine children, taught him that
modesty and respect were calling cards in any society.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a story about Joe DiMaggio that I saw in a magazine
that once said, `Joe DiMaggio, unlike other Italians, doesn't put
oil in his hair, he slicks it back with water,' '' said former
Boston City Councilor Lawrence DiCara. ``I never forgot that.''
</P>
<P>
   By showing restraint, DiMaggio projected strength of character.
He was twice divorced, and estranged from his only son, but
nonetheless famous for his romantic fidelity. His kindness to his
troubled ex-wife Marilyn Monroe, who was exploited by almost every
other man in her life, burnished his legend. The single rose he
would place beside her grave for long after her death was an
enduring symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``DiMaggio basically swore off women after Marilyn Monroe,''
whom he divorced, after a marriage of less than a year, when he was
39, noted DiCara, ``so he and Sinatra were just very different
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if DiMaggio signaled the importance of resisting one's
appetites to achieve a deeper moral satisfaction, Sinatra urged
indulgence as the reward for success. Though he maintained
turbulent, but loving, relationships with his three children,
ex-wives, and an entourage of male buddies, he seemed to relish
promiscuity, discarding ``dames'' like burned-out cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Even as his drinking buddy Dean Martin wilted beside him,
Sinatra defied dissipation: He acknowledged no dark side in his
good life.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Sinatra's unvarnished confidence and DiMaggio's easy
grace were carefully crafted images that, well into later life,
they struggled to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   When photographers were around, the elderly DiMaggio would
frantically discard his drink; he seemed to believe that legends
should not indulge themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sinatra, by contrast, ordered up album covers of himself
dragging on cigarettes and sipping highball glasses long after
smoking and drinking had lost their glamour; he was still swinging
in the age of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Yet both defied the usual degradation of celebrities in their
twilight years, the threadbare look of self-delusion. Sinatra and
DiMaggio understood they were icons, and that their kind of magic
didn't fade; death would only enhance their profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Writing the morning after DiMaggio's death Monday, Philadelphia
Inquirer sportswriter Bill Lyon, like millions of men who grew up
in the 1930s and '40s, recalled his first ballgame. ``More than a
half-century later, this is what I remember: The outfield grass _
it was perfect and took my breath away. And my grandfather, the
gentlest man I've ever known, whispering the instruction in my ear.
`Watch the centerfielder. See how he carries himself. It is very
important, how a man carries himself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Peter S. Canellos is the Globe's assistant managing editor for
local news.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
