<SLUG> BC-BOOK-IDENTITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FORMER LESBIAN, A NEW IDENTITY WITH NO NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
APPLES AND ORANGES 
My Journey Through Sexual Identity 
By Jan Clausen 
Houghton Mifflin, 253 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Throughout most of history, identity was, and still is in most
of the world, something one is born with and cannot change. One is
a Serb or a Tutsi, a peasant or a noble, a man or a woman. Only in
the West in modern times, and perhaps nowhere else as much as in
America, identity is just the reverse: It is something one seeks,
chooses, adopts, and this adoption is always momentous. Americans
have the glorious freedom to decide who and what they are, but
sometimes we see, as most poignantly in this remarkable memoir,
what a painful and difficult passage this freedom requires.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon-born Jan Clausen is a novelist, poet, left/liberal
activist, and teacher of writing and literature at New York's New
School. For many years she was also a confirmed, committed, and
activist lesbian with a long-term committed partnership complete
with child (her partner's biological daughter). Though she had had
male lovers in her youth, her life in a Portland commune in the
early 1970s (she was born in 1950) exposed her to women as lovers,
and she became openly lesbian some time after she moved to New York
in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Settled in Brooklyn, she began a life of writing, demonstrating,
and activism on behalf of social justice, especially for women,
very much in the context of a discrete sisterhood, a lesbian
community, a world in which her identity was clear and her sense of
belonging unquestioned, least of all by herself. With her longtime
partner, Leslie Kaplow (a made-up name), she was in no doubt about
who she was and with whom she belonged.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1987, until she unexpectedly fell in love with a man.
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with Kaplow had become troubled. Heavily
involved with the American movement in support of the Sandinista
revolution, Clausen went to Nicaragua on a fact-finding trip. The
group she traveled with included an activist lawyer named Benjamin
(no last name is given), who was born in Grenada and educated in
Britain. He became intensely interested in her, and to her
surprise, she was also attracted to him. When they returned to New
York, while Kaplow was away, Clausen and Benjamin became sexually
involved, with explosive consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstantial outcome was simple enough: Kaplow was
outraged, Clausen moved out, and she began a committed,
home-sharing relationship with Benjamin that still exists. Nothing
unusual _ happens all the time. But because the new lover was a
man, for Clausen the emotional and social consequences were
unusually painful and complicated. Though some lesbian friends were
understanding and supportive of her choice and change of life, she
drew rage and ostracism from many others, and experienced the loss
of her settled identity within the sisterhood.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision to permit her own desire, she writes, ``required
giving up that sense of being among the elect that my lesbian
feminist identity furnished in return for its exorbitant demands on
my sense of political duty. . . . I was struck by how often
lesbians inquired what I planned to call myself, almost as though
the absence of a name for my condition were more upsetting than my
actual behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   When she granted permission for one of her lesbian poems to
appear in a gay anthology, the editor, a friend who had accepted
her new situation, ``soon was harshly reproved by a self-appointed
member of the identity police who thought I'd forfeited my rights
to any further association with dyke culture.''
</P>
<P>
   However, after she published an article in 1990 about her
experience, ``My Interesting Condition,'' in Out/
</P>
<P>
   Look magazine, she received besides outraged letters some from
women who had had similar experiences, who had unexpectedly found
themselves in a new closet. ``Apparently,'' she writes, ``ours had
become the latest edition of the love that dare not speak its
name.''
</P>
<P>
   She is no less committed to social justice than she ever was,
and does not reject or denounce her former life or loves. But she
does reject the premise that in order to make the world a better
place, one has to buy into, wholly, a complete
sexual/social/political identity. ``Beyond identity categories,''
she writes, ``we all face the puzzle of how best to foster justice
in a complicated world in which `shared oppression' is less than
ever a simple mechanical binding force.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a deeply and sometimes tortuously introspective book.
Clausen is a gifted writer, with impressive eloquence and clarity,
even though her ideas are sometimes wrought with the sort of poetic
idiom that requires careful, slow reading. Many of her sentences
are of Jamesian length, with parenthetical asides that give the
sentences themselves an aspect of self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Though she is sure of who she is and where she stands, her
position no longer represents a definition out of a catalog. ``Now
I want a life,'' she writes, ``that can't be paraphrased _ my own,
with all its imperfections and surprises. Its lack of romantic
certainty. Its failure, precisely, to be some other story, to be
justified by anything external to itself.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, she wants to be that other American curiosity:
an individual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
