<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-DATABASES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PURSUIT OF CROOKS, DNA COUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts _ now the only state now unable to collect blood
samples from inmates to go into a statewide DNA database _ is
falling behind the rest of the nation in an area of law enforcement
that, say some experts, could dramatically reduce violent crime and
make serial rape non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   The court-ordered ban on DNA collection here has put
Massachusetts well behind states such as Florida, where the state
has a DNA database of some 55,000 people convicted of any of six
serious crimes. State officials there have been able to identify
100 suspects in serious crimes that investigators never would have
considered unless their DNA matched that at a crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Bureau of Investigation last year launched a
nationwide DNA database system, known as CODIS, that allows state
and local law enforcement agencies to exchange and compare DNA
offender profiles and crime scene profiles electronically.
</P>
<P>
   But while Massachusetts can request that a sample from a crime
scene be run against the national database, it cannot submit its
offenders' DNA for matches.
</P>
<P>
   Why the restrictions? Massachusetts is home to the nation's only
successful legal challenge to a DNA collection law. Superior Court
Judge Isaac Borenstein ruled last summer that the Bay State's
program _ which would take blood samples from inmates convicted of
one of 33 serious crimes as well as those on parole or probation _
was a violation of the Fourth Amendment and the state constitution
because it was an unlawful search, one without probable cause.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Supreme Judicial Court heard arguments
on whether to uphold Borenstein's ruling. A decision could come
anytime, but most likely not until summer.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether collecting DNA samples and using them in a
database is like 21st century fingerprinting _ a legitimate tool
used to help solve violent crimes _ or whether it represents a
government-sanctioned invasion of privacy against inmates, even
when there is no specific evidence linking them to any unsolved
crime.
</P>
<P>
   While that debate is being aired in the courts, there is little
dispute over DNA's effectiveness fighting crime. ``It will greatly
cut down on the number of crimes . . . people commit,'' says Walter
Rowe, a forensic sciences professor at George Washington
University. In many of the cases, it was highly unlikely law
enforcment would have identified the individual involved without
the DNA database.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Danny Keith Hooks, who last September was
convicted of killing five women in Oklahoma in 1992. The only lead
investigators had was some blood at the scene. The DNA in the blood
went into the DNA database and in 1997 California officials matched
it to that of Hooks, a prisoner who had been convicted of rape in
California and who, before being released in 1995, had been forced
to give a DNA sample. Once identified, Hooks was arrested and
returned to Oklahoma to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider the case of Gerald Parker, whose identification was
California's first so-called ``cold hit.'' Officials found that the
DNA database linked Parker, a convicted murderer, to the 1979
murders of a woman and her baby in Orange County. As a result,
Kevin Lee Green _ who had served 17 years for the murders _ was set
free.
</P>
<P>
   DNA matching has even proved useful even here in Massachusetts
where _ despite the court ban _ samples can still be collected from
people who authorities have reason to believe commited a crime.
Thus, when Edmund Burke was arrested for the murder 75-year-old
Irene Kennedy in a Walpole park in December, and bite marks found
on the victim matched his dental charts, he was forced to give a
DNA sample. It worked to his advantage: samples taken from saliva
on the victim did not match Burke's and he was freed.
</P>
<P>
   If the state was able to build a large database _ about 1,100
samples were taken from prisoners when the DNA database law was
enacted, but an injunction issued over a year ago halted the
practice _ it is conceivable that it might one day contain a match
to the saliva left on Kennedy's body.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, however, say that while DNA can be a useful law
enforcement tool _ and suspects with ``probable cause'' should be
forced to give samples _ the Massachusetts law is poorly written,
encompasses too many types of crime, and could permit the samples
to be used for research, not just identification.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts ought to start over'' and rewrite the law, says
Dr. Paul Billings, a medical geneticist and director of the Council
for Responsible Genetics.
</P>
<P>
   If the SJC upholds Borenstein's ruling against the current law,
then Massachusetts could fall even further behind the rest of the
nation. Earlier this month, at the request of Attorney General
Janet Reno, the National Commission on the Future of DNA Evidence
began considering whether authorities should take samples from
indivudals at the time of arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will need to consider if it is constitutional, to what
extent it might be an unlawful search and seizure, and we need to
look at fingerprinting for some guidance,'' says Christopher H.
Asplen, executive director of the National Commission on the Future
of DNA Evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next class of consideration is the societal privacy
issues. Do we want to do it? What needs to be done to make it a
pure private system? Is the benefit to society worth the cost of
perceived infringement of society?
</P>
<P>
   ``And the third category, from a practical standpoint, is what
does this mean? The big database issue right now is, nationally we
have backlog of more than 450,000 samples. There are more than
450,000 blood samples or swabs (taken from inside the mouth) that
sit untested and not put into the database.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem was the rush by state legislatures,
including Massachusetts, to enact DNA database legislation to
ensure that they continued to receive federal funding for law
enforcement. State labs were not prepared for the immediate
avalanche of samples.
</P>
<P>
   Asplen said if nothing is done to speed up data entry _ such as
hiring private labs to do much more of the work (which could
increase the liklihood of abuses of the data for research) _ it
will take between four and six years to enter all the existing
samples, as well as new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have a guy convicted of one of the enumerated crimes,
convicted, say, of rape, and his blood is drawn on release, but it
sits in storage for two years and he re-offends,'' says Asplen.
``Let's say you get a good sample from the crime scene, it is
entered into the database and nothing happens. Now, if he does it
again, when you get to victim number two, that would have been a
completely preventable crime. The guy would have been stopped after
the first one. We are in a position where we will have to say to
the victim, we are sorry this guy got to you, or your daughter,
because of the backlog.''
</P>
<P>
   Further compounding the backlog, the FBI system uses a DNA
analysis method that provides less information than the one now
favored. So much of the data entered under the initial system must
be redone.
</P>
<P>
   Despite concerns about privacy and constitutionality, taking
samples at the time of arrest is gaining supporters around the
country. It's already done in Louisiana, and in New York police
commissioner Howard Safir created a furor late last year when he
suggested doing the same thing in an effort to continue to bring
down the city's crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   There is no data to suggest that DNA databases act as a
deterrent to crime _ other than to get a criminal off the streets,
so he can't repeat his offense _ but their effectiveness as a tool
in investigations is considerable. Even in Massachusetts, where the
offender database is so limited, the separate data base collected
from crime scenes provided evidence linking five murder-rapes in
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate continues here, supporters point to the example of
England, which has the oldest and largest DNA database in the
world. There are some 475,000 profiles in the database in England
and around 700 matches are made each week, with, on average, a 40
percent chance a stain found at a crime scene will match a name in
the database.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science is there, if you can maintain the integrity of the
database,'' says Essex County District Attorney Kevin Burke, who
turned to DNA analysis to find who raped a comatose woman in a
Lawrence nursing home. ``It makes all the sense in the world,
especially with sexual offenders. If you did nothing but limit it
those convicted of sexual offenses, you would be doing the
Commonwealth a big favor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
