<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY IS SALT BAD FOR SOME PEOPLE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Why after a holiday dinner of baked ham am I so thirsty a few
hours later?
</P>
<P>
   Why is salt so bad for some people?
</P>
<P>
   C.P., Concord, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. For something once so rare that Roman soldiers were paid in
units of salt, giving us the word salary, salt's gotten a pretty
bad reputation recently. The fact is, salt is not only good for
you, it's absolutely vital for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salt does two things in the body. It helps us keep the right
water levels inside our cells, and out in our bloodstream,'' says
Dr. Robert Stanton, Chief of Nephrology (the study of the kidney)
at The Joslin Diabetes Center. ``Cells somehow know how big they
want to be, and our body knows what blood pressure it wants. Salt
helps us maintain both.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt is one of several kinds of particles that float around in
our bodies' fluids. If the concentration of those particles in our
bloodstream is the same as in the fluid inside our cells,
everything is fine. But when the particle concentration, known as
osmolarity, is higher on one side or the other, the extra particles
act like little magnets that pull water molecules toward them.
</P>
<P>
   When the osmolarity is higher out in the blood, for example,
salt particles pull water out of the cells and into the bloodstream
through the permeable cell membrane. If the cells lose enough water
they shrivel up and die. (Drinking salt water kills you by
dehydrating your brain cells. That's why saltwater-drinking
shipwrecked sailors go mad before they die.)
</P>
<P>
   Our cells can recognize internal and external osmolarity. When a
ham dinner raises the concentration of salt particles in the
bloodstream, the cells sense that the extra salt outside is pulling
some of its water away. They fight back. They produce organic
particles with names like taurine and betaine that hold onto water
and keep it from leaving. They also send chemical signals to the
brain that say ``Hey, the blood is too salty for us! We're drying
out! Water things down out there and get the salt levels down, will
ya?'' That signal makes us thirsty.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking fluid gets the osmolarity _ salt concentration _ in the
blood back to what the cells prefer. (Bartenders may not realize it
but they're actually serving those free salty snacks to alter your
osmolarity.)
</P>
<P>
   High blood osmolarity also triggers the brain to release an
anti-diuretic hormone. We urinate less. The body holds onto liquid,
and gradually salt concentration in the bloodstream drops back to
normal levels, about eight grams per liter. (Sea water is about
three times as salty.)
</P>
<P>
   But let's say instead of eating a salty meal, you are exercising
and sweating. You're losing water and salt. The loss of all that
water drops your blood pressure, which sends signals to the brain
that make you want to drink to replace the missing fluid. ``But
you'd better drink sweat, or something chemically like it,'' Dr.
Stanton warns. ``Something with salt in it.''
</P>
<P>
   If you only drink water, you're watering down your blood
osmolarity.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually things get saltier inside the cells. The extra salt
particles inside the cells draw water out of the bloodstream and
begin to swell. Since they don't like that either, they signal the
brain that the blood stream needs salt.
</P>
<P>
   We don't rush to find the closest bag of potato chips. Instead,
the brain tells the kidney, our body's filtration plant, to get rid
of water, but hold onto salt. Within an hour, this can start to
raise the salt concentration in the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   By influencing how much water stays inside our cells, and how
much stays in the bloodstream, salt is vital for controlling
healthy cell size and blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   If we have all these sensitive systems for regulating the right
amount of salt, why do some scientists say salt is bad for us?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us are more salt-sensitive, some are less,'' Dr.
Stanton says. ``Some of us have differing abilities to dilate our
blood vessels and regulate our blood pressure. Some of us have
differences in our hormone systems, which affect how well we can
respond to changes in salt levels.''
</P>
<P>
   So is salt the bad guy some think?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no smoking gun that's popped out,'' Dr. Stanton says.
``Some studies show salt contributes to essential hypertension,
which is high blood pressure without any secondary causes. Some
studies show it doesn't. The best thing is try higher or lower salt
levels on yourself, cautiously, and see how it affects your own
blood pressure and find the level that's right for you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
