<HEADLINE>
WHY HOUND STEPHANOPOULOS FOR HIS MEA CULPA? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For sharing some of what he saw during his five
years in Bill Clinton's inner circle, George Stephanopoulos is
being called a weasel and a Judas.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe worst of all, while his former friends and colleagues ask,
``Et tu, Brute?'' longtime Clinton haters (people Stephanopoulos
presumably can't stand) are crowing, ``Welcome aboard! What took
you so long?''
</P>
<P>
   The former White House aide is hardly the first defector from
the Clinton administration. But with his book, ``All Too Human: A
Political Education,'' Stephanopoulos has become the most public
and detailed of the disgruntled alums. Until Hillary Rodham Clinton
or James Carville decide to spill their guts, he likely will own
the award for falling the furthest out of love.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply smitten with the Democratic presidential candidate in
1991, Stephanopoulos giddily jumped onto ``the Clinton roller
coaster,'' rode into the White House and stayed there until the
president's reelection in 1996. Now he says he knows that his
former boss is a bigger liar than he ever dreamed and, though he
has been ``a good president,'' he doesn't think the country should
ever have elected him.
</P>
<P>
   As so often happens when a once-trusted intimate breaks rank and
hangs dirty laundry on the public line, many folks seem more
concerned with Stephanopoulos' ``betrayal'' or ``bad timing'' than
with his actual revelations. Condemnation runs from the blanket to
the remarkably petty.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kennedy and Johnson aide Richard Goodwin groused:
``Who is George Stephanopoulos but another kid on the make? ... Who
would care about (him) if not for Clinton?''
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end of the scale, Philadelphia Daily News
columnist Sandy Grady felt compelled to cheap-shot Stephanopoulos
for his choice of anti-depressant: ``Zoloft (the celebrity pill
that doesn't seem to help Mike Tyson's rage).''
</P>
<P>
   What causes a person to do a 180 on someone he or she once
adored?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's a matter of growing up and seeking revenge for
what is perceived of as a ``Mommy Dearest'' childhood. Sometimes
it's retaliation for being personally screwed over. (Mia Farrow and
Claire Bloom's dismembering of their famous exes come to mind.)
Sometimes it's a classic shedding of scales from the eyes, often
made easier by a stay in prison, as so many of Nixon's minions
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   In Stephanopoulos' case, the motive _ along with a $2.75 million
book advance, of course _ appears to be a kind of cathartic purge.
He isn't just disgusted with Clinton for having feet, legs and
maybe a soul of clay; he's disgusted with himself for being such a
sucker for the guy.
</P>
<P>
   For all the unattractive vignettes that Stephanopoulos has
shared of late about Clinton, he beats on himself pretty good, too.
Whether he admits to the unmacho act of bursting into tears after a
confrontation with the first lady or refers to himself as an
``enabler'' of Clinton's habitual mendacity, Stephanopoulos seems
less a cocky, self-righteous avenger than a man chanting ``mea
culpa'' and dutifully smacking himself with a cat o'nine tails.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most common criticism of Stephanopoulos has been his
timing: Why didn't he honor the unwritten code of political
aide-olotry and wait until Clinton was at least out of office?
</P>
<P>
   Why on Earth should he have waited? Out of gratitude because
Clinton plucked him from obscurity and rewarded his hard work with
a high-profile staff position?
</P>
<P>
   Out of allegiance to the noble end that he and departed staffers
like Dee Dee Myers, Robert Reich and Mike McCurry must once have
believed justified any means?
</P>
<P>
   Because his former boss has set such a potent example of
trustworthiness and straight shooting among his inner circle?
</P>
<P>
   Because negative revelations will threaten the pristine image of
``The Presidency'' that eight or nine Americans might still harbor?
</P>
<P>
   Those who would condemn Stephanopoulos ought to remember a
couple of things.
</P>
<P>
   Genuine loyalty is like faith: You can't buy or coerce it. You
have to build, maintain and guard it so that it can be relied on
when the sun disappears and the going gets brutal.
</P>
<P>
   Even in modern politics, you get what you sow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
