<HEADLINE>
BLACK HOLE IS HOME FOR OLD TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. _ Nothing on Edward Grothus's property is
radioactive, but all of it is nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   The parking lot of his aptly named Black Hole warehouse looks
like a post-nuclear junkyard _ as if the atomic bomb had been
dropped on the very laboratories where it was first developed.
</P>
<P>
   There are fireproof, waterproof, no doubt blastproof, filing
cabinets. There are computer desks and office chairs and exercise
bicycles for scientists who had so much highly classified material
to read that they couldn't pedal outdoors. Inside is even worse,
17,000 square feet of alphabetized castoffs, from alarms to motors
and meters to xyz plotters, whatever those are.
</P>
<P>
   All of it was bought for pennies on the dollar from Los Alamos
National Laboratory, where computers considered cutting edge on
Jan. 1 are past their prime by Dec. 31. And all of it is for sale.
The cheapest item, a tiny electrical component called a resistor,
goes for one cent. The crogenic dewar, a large thingamajig for
storing liquid nitrogen, tops the price list at $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's stuff is out this year, so they get rid of it,''
said Grothus, 75, a former machinist who put in 20 years at the
lab. ``So I made a business out of buying last year's technology
and finding homes for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his customers, he said, are colleges and universities
worldwide. Set designers have made their way to the Black Hole,
whose merchandise has appeared as props in ``Silkwood,'' ``The
Manhattan Project,'' and other movies. Collectors looking for a
'50s-style drafting table or the perfect high-voltage vacuum relay
have found them here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like the city of Los Alamos, which this year celebrates its 50th
anniversary, Grothus has been filling the Black Hole for half a
century. The Iowa native moved to the Jemez Mountains 35 miles
northwest of Santa Fe in 1949, drawn like thousands of others by
the chance to help make H-bomb history. Ten years later, while
keeping his day job measuring the hydrodynamics of nuclear
implosions, he realized that there was profit to be made from
another kind of nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more artifacts than the Bradbury Museum downtown,''
said Grothus, opening a door into a room filled with the choicest
collectibles. ``I have the real museum. All this time I've been
stashing away the artifacts of the nuclear age.''
</P>
<P>
   To put the years in perspective, Grothus mentioned that when he
started at the Lab, as it's known around the one-company town, the
bombs being built were as big as Volkswagens. By the time he quit,
a half-dozen could fit on his desk. But by then, he wanted nothing
to do with nuclear proliferation. Even before a Lab employee was
fired last week on suspicion of selling nuclear secrets to the
Chinese, Grothus had decided that the entire operation was ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Grothus prides himself on being an outspoken antinuke
activist, making him something of a rarity, if not a pariah, in a
city where almost every other adult is connected to the Lab. To
mark the anniversaries of the two bombs dropped on Japan, he holds
a demonstration at the pond in the center of town every Aug. 6 and
9. He also jokes that every Sunday, he holds an ``anticritical
mass'' in a former church he owns nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost all my faith in the schemes and dreams of nuclear
weapons and nuclear power,'' said Grothus, who wears a button on
his flannel shirt asking people to speak up because he is hard of
hearing. ``First, only a madman would use a bomb, because what
would he gain? Second, nuclear plants have waste, and there's no
good place to put it. And the power plant itself has a limited
lifetime. Where are we supposed to put that when we're done with
it?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grothus, of course, is happy to take the safe stuff himself,
although the Lab recently began using an Albuquerque auction house
to sell equipment it no longer wants. All that's left for him to
buy nowadays is used office furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Grothus said he expects to be around to hassle pronuclear
administrations for years to come. Turning on a Geiger counter, he
noted that the low click-clicks indicated everyday background
radiation. It's not dangerous, he said. Then he said he used to
handle depleted uranium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lab raised thousands of generations of mice, proving a
little radiation is good for you,'' Grothus said. ``So I'm shooting
for 110 because of what I've handled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
