<HEADLINE>
PRESCRIPTIONS: A MEDICAL DRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Mrs. G.L. died last month in a central Massachusetts
nursing home, attendants gathered her unused stockpile of
prescription medicines _ $142.30 worth, nearly all still sealed in
sterile bubble-packs _ and literally flushed it down the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   It happens every day in nursing homes across the nation.
Millions of dollars' worth of costly medication goes down the drain
daily. By one estimate, the waste in Massachusetts exceeds $27,000
a day, $10 million a year. Nobody really knows for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thrown away antibiotic pills worth $75 apiece,'' says
Francoise Levesque, a Whitinsville nurse who is trying to change
the current throwaway system and allow unused prescription drugs to
be recycled.
</P>
<P>
   The trillion-dollar-a-year US health system is notorious for its
inequities. But the contrast between waste and want couldn't be
more stark than it is right now, as thousands of Bay State elders
struggle to pay escalating pharmacy bills with sharply reduced
assistance from HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Other coverage plans, they're finding, are either restricted to
the poorest elders or are financially out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross-Blue Shield officials agree that's the reason why
consumer inquiries about its Medex Gold unlimited drug coverage _
the annual open enrollment period ends on March 31 _ are up only
five to seven percent this year, despite the fact that 60,000 HMO
``senior plan'' subscribers lost similar coverage on January 1.
</P>
<P>
   The annual premium for Blue Cross-Blue Shield's Medex Gold Went
up March 15 from $3,126 to $3,435. Not surprisingly, the number of
elders buying nongroup Medex Gold coverage dropped by 20 percent
between 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So while nursing homes routinely throw away medicine worth
thousands of dollars, Bernice Speliotis of Lynn is struggling to
pay her monthly $400 prescription costs on a pharmacy allowance
from Tufts Health Plan's Secure Horizons, her HMO, of $41.67 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Some elders who have never touched a gun are wondering if they
should join the National Rifle Association so they might qualify
for a new medigap drug plan from Allianz Life Insurance Co. that
costs $2,664 a year, which is available to NRA members.
</P>
<P>
   And Victor Pelletier, an 88-year-old Marlborough, Mass. man, is
watching his Visa bill swell with pharmacy charges no longer
covered by Fallon Community Health Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fallon used to pay part of it but now I have to pay out of my
own pocket,'' he says, referring to $4,000 in annual drug costs for
himself and his wife Lucille. ``I can't afford to keep up with
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pelletiers' $22,000-a-year income is just $300 above the
eligibility limit for a makeshift, one-year assistance program for
low-income elders put into place this year when Fallon and other
Massachusetts HMOs abruptly cancelled unlimited drug coverage. Such
programs take only income into account, not pharmacy bills or other
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, Massachusetts HMOs were compelled to offer such
generous pharmacy benefits. But the HMOs cancelled unlimited drug
coverage in January after Congress and a federal judge overturned
the state law.
</P>
<P>
   While terminating unlimited drug coverage, the HMOs extended
modest new pharmacy benefits to all 180,000 Medicare beneficiaries
enrolled in senior plans, only about one-third of whom had paid
$840 to $1,000 a year for the now-defunct full drug benefits. HMOs
point out that the new zero-premium drug benefits makes most of
their senior plan members better off than they were, elder
advocates and state officials say they're being overwhelmed by
people in urgent need.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $600 to $800 a year that HMOs allow doesn't begin to cover
many people's medication needs,'' reports Jackie Anthony, a nurse
at East Boston Neighborhood Health Center who works fulltime to
help the most desperate patients qualify for drug manufacturers'
little-known drug giveaway programs. ``People can't afford these
medications.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the SHINE program, a state counselling service whose
name stands for Serving Health Information Needs of Elders, have
quadrupled since January. ``Some of our centers are serving more
people in one month than they did in all of last year,'' says
Marion Aspinall, a SHINE program manager.
</P>
<P>
   SHINE counsellors around the state say they can search out
partway solutions for some elders. One such partial-success story
illustrates the hit-or-miss nature of the current patchwork. An
anonymous man volunteered last Friday to help Constance Rubin of
Framingham with her crushing $2,840-a-month medication bills after
he saw a television report on her plight.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly any way to deal with the larger problem. But the
alternatives are spotty, at least until Beacon Hill lawmakers craft
whatever reforms are possible at the state level while Congress
begins the lengthy debate about adding some drug coverage to the
financially shaky Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   That task is daunting. State legislators, who will consider at
least seven reform proposals at a March 30 Statehouse hearing, are
still uncertain how ambitious they'll dare to be. ``It's hard to
say exactly where it will come out,'' says state Senator Mark
Montigny, a New Bedford Democrat who heads the powerful Senate Ways
and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the prospects are even murkier. A 17-member
special commission on Medicare reform is reportedly near deadlock,
and a key issue is whether to add drug benefits to the program.
</P>
<P>
   While the politicians grapple with the issue, advocates can only
steer elders with low incomes to little-known sources of help, such
as the state's under-used Senior Pharmacy program, or last-resort
drug company giveaway plans. The Senior Pharmacy plan, funded with
$30 million in state tobacco tax money, offers up to $750 a year in
support, but only to those with incomes under 150 percent of the
poverty level ($12,078 for singles, $16,290 for couples).
</P>
<P>
   Senior Pharmacy rules out assistance for anyone with any other
drug coverage, however inadequate. But state officials said last
week that elders who have a current Senior Pharmacy card may use
it, even if they now qualify for the HMOs' new capped drug coverage
that began January 1. And in July, when current Senior Pharmacy
cards expire, ``our expectation is that current members will be
able to reenroll,'' said Derrek Shulman, a spokesman for the
Executive Office of Elder Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many elders' incomes are too high to qualify them
for Senior Pharmacy, Medicaid, or other existing programs _ but not
high enough to afford comprehensive medigap policies or thousands
of dollars in annual pharmacy bills. Even five years ago, before a
spate of new drugs inflated pharmacy costs sharply, US elders with
incomes under $16,104 ($21,720 for couples) were spending
one-quarter of their income on out-of-pocket medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, patients, doctors, nurses, social workers, and
advocates can look forward to more scrambling _ and maybe to such
creative partial solutions as a way to recapture those pills now
going down nursing home toilets, although that too is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run around to our medicine cabinets'' for free samples,
says Mary Abate, a patient advocate at East Boston Neighborhood
Health Center, where staffers even dig into their own pockets for
emergency pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could name a half-dozen people, and I'm sure there are many
more, who say, `I'm only taking one pill a day instead of two and I
cut that one in half.' I beg them not to do that,'' Abate says.
``Just the other day one woman said to me, `I beg you to help me.'
It tears me apart that people have to beg for medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard A. Knox's e-mail address is knox(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
