<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0968 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-15 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAHEEN'S SENSIBLE APPROACH TO N.H.'S SCHOOL FUNDING CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. -- New Hampshire Governor Jeanne Shaheen was
patiently explaining her sensible proposal to reform public school
funding the other day when a fellow of libertarian bent asked if
``none of the above'' could be a choice for voters should they get
the issue in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where have you been?'' the governor shot back with more
amazement than pique. ``That is not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, in a policy conundrum that has national
attention, that is both accurate and inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that because of last year's state Supreme Court
decision declaring unconstitutional the property tax-based method
of paying for schools, doing nothing is incompatible with getting
right with the law. But it's also true that schemes are being
floated to evade the state's duty in whole or in part, in deference
to New Hampshire's infamous tax theology. That theology is clashing
with a deeper commitment to the state's future, in which education
is center-stage. And the clash has created a golden opportunity for
centrist leaders like Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the cliche rules that the devil is in the details of
major policy proposals. In her case, it's the virtue. Ever since
the court decision last year that New Hampshire's nearly complete
reliance on the property tax creates disparities among cities and
towns that illegally mock any pretense of equal opportunity,
Shaheen has tried to offer solutions that correct the inequity
without breaking the state's tradition and her campaign pledges to
go without sales and income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   As the court's April 1 deadline for compliance nears, the only
viable alternative to the governor's proposal of a mixture of new
revenue sources turns out to be an income tax. And, amazingly, that
is what barely slipped past the the lower house of the Legislature
this month via Democratic and moderate Republican votes.
</P>
<P>
   It was the subject of local and national astonishment, but the
reaction missed the point that as legislation, Shaheen will veto
it, which makes its passage by the newly Democratic state senate
doubtful and irrelvant.
</P>
<P>
   However, as one alternative that rises to the Supreme Court's
challenge, the income tax more than qualifies as a choice for the
voters in a referendum, which Shaheen would like to arrange to
decide this momentous question. For the moment, the big question is
whether the court will permit the people to make that judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The other alternative, if the judges permit, would be Shaheen's,
which seeks to spread the mild pain around the state without
dipping directly into workers' paychecks. To date, what the
governor has done is show that this can be done fairly _ no mean
feat.
</P>
<P>
   As Shaheen notes, what is required by the court's decision is
the replacement by state funds of the current reliance on widely
disparate local property tax revenues for education _ not extra
spending per se. Using a commission's expertise, the money needed
to finance adequate schooling was found to be slightly less than
$900 million, or about 4550 per pupil. And since the state is
already spending roughly $100 million on education, that leaves
nearly $800 million to be raised.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot of money, almost as much as the amount of purely
state money now in the overall New Hampshire budget. But Shaheen
shows it can be done in ways that would have less impact on working
families than direct income taxes. Half, for example, would come
from a statewide property tax of $6 per thousand in assessed value
that would actually slash taxes for people and businesses in more
than 80 percent of the state's communities. Even many Republicans
are for this.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy appears to flow from three ideas that
legitimately raise concerns, except when compared to the
alternative:
</P>
<P>
   --$145 million from putting nearly 3,800 slot machines at the
state's four racetracks. From the reaction in some hyperventilated
quarters, you'd think Shaheen wanted a casino in every garage.
</P>
<P>
   --$91 million from replacing existing business levies with a
single tax based on value. It's efficient (as several other states
have discovered), permits a higher threshhold for taxation that
exempts thousands more small businesses, and its net burden is
considerably reduced by the property tax savings.
</P>
<P>
   --$73 million from the addition of a capital-gains tax to the
existing 5 percent levies on interest and dividends. But with
higher personal, elderly, and disabled exemptions, it will be
possible to raise the earnings threshhold for all three taxes
signficantly, which will be deductible on federal returns, with
sales of primary residences totally exempt.
</P>
<P>
   You could argue that an income tax is simpler, but you would
have trouble arguing it is more fair. What is undeniable is that
these are the responsible choices and the people deserve the
ultimate power.
</P>
<P>
   As for the right, they can continue to erect roadblocks and
offer nonsolutions. But the remarkable history of Shaheen's success
teaches that they will do so at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
