<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-15 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 LOCAL POLITICS, LOCAL CARES
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is conventional wisdom: At century's end, Americans have
soured on politics. In our brokers, we place our trust. In the
market, we secure our future.
</P>
<P>
   But someone forgot to tell Becky Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   In her kitchen on a recent weekday morning, a half-dozen jittery
candidates were discussing campaign strategy. In her sunroom, a
dozen animated strangers were stuffing prestamped envelopes.
</P>
<P>
   Around her dining room table, women were bent over voter
registration lists, addressing postcards to their neighbors to
solicit support for would-be members of the School Committee, the
Library Board, the Recreation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In the living room, a frenetic campaign manager had a cell phone
to his ear and a pen in his hand, hustling an endorsement from the
local state rep for one of the candidates on his slate.
</P>
<P>
   This is political activism, suburban style.
</P>
<P>
   Washington may be dulled by postimpeachment malaise. New
Hampshire may be numbed by ever earlier prepresidential primary
visitors. But, in community after community where voters will
assemble in Town Meeting this month and next to make decisions
about everything from library construction to tree maintenance,
there is no shortage of political energy.
</P>
<P>
   In one suburb west of Boston, Becky Epstein's home has served
for weeks as campaign central for several of the 15 candidates
vying for six open seats on various boards in town.
</P>
<P>
   People _ women, mostly _ sat on the floor around the coffee
table in her family room, pasting address labels on campaign fliers
with a dispatch that would be the envy of most assembly lines.
</P>
<P>
   Epstein did not know many of her house guests, but she knew why
all of them were there: the need to build new classrooms in a
well-regarded public school system that is beginning to strain at
the seams. Electing like-minded neighbors to related committees in
town could mean the difference between a son or a daughter learning
to read alongside 20 classmates instead of 30.
</P>
<P>
   Try mobilizing a similarly motivated campaign staff around
NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   The political cynicism that has characterized Washington in the
wake of l'affaire Lewinsky is, in large measure, a Beltway
phenomenon. The public's disgust with the president's recklessness
and its even greater dismay with the partisan reaction of the
Republican Congress has not caused the much-heralded death of
politics in America.
</P>
<P>
   At home, in our communities, we are still turning to politics as
the single most effective tool to bind us in common cause. Should
we build a new library or expand the old? Should we rely on private
concerns to provide recreational facilities for our teenagers or
construct public community centers? Should we restrict development
to preserve open space or build critically needed low-cost housing
units instead? Should we raise taxes to build a new school or use
modular classrooms until the baby boomlet passes through?
</P>
<P>
   That every woman in Becky Epstein's home kept one eye on her
watch was a measure of how personal she considered the political
stakes in one town's election. It was an early release day at the
elementary schools. The minivans and Range Rovers would be backing
out of Becky's driveway by noon, campaign workers transformed back
into mothers, deserting her kitchen for their own to prepare lunch
for the returning grade school hordes.
</P>
<P>
   The women would be back the next morning and the next, writing
campaign ads, soliciting contributions, building signs, and
delivering them to neighbors willing to stake them on their front
lawns.
</P>
<P>
   It was deceptively sunny on Election Day. Campaign veterans
turned up for their one- and two-hour shifts as sign holders at
polling places, supermarkets, and the town dump in down parkas, fur
hats, woolen mittens, and fleece-lined boots.
</P>
<P>
   At Precinct F, the pros cringed at the sight of a bare-headed
political novice in patent-leather flats and thin gloves, frozen
despite the coffee being dispensed regularly by other volunteers
from the back of Land Cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your first political campaign?'' they sighed. ``First rule of
sign-holding: mittens, not gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 29 percent of the town's 15,400 registered voters cast
ballots that day. But that's up from 24 percent in the last
townwide election two years ago. It just might be that Becky
Epstein's kitchen campaign operation accounts for the increase. And
all her candidates won.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
