<SLUG> BC-TV-RESCUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RESCUE' NEEDS MORE THAN AN IV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RESCUE 77 
Starring: Marjorie Monaghan, Christian Kane, Victor Browne, Richard
Roundtree 
On: WB 
Time: Premieres Monday, then moves to Tuesdays at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rescue 77'' is the latest pretty-people series from Aaron
Spelling, producer of hits like ``Melrose Place'' and ``Beverly
Hills 90210'' and misses like ``Malibu Shores'' and ``Sunset
Beach.'' Without any melodramatic sizzle, camp splash, or engaging
medical drama, ``Rescue 77'' promises to land in the misses pile
with a big fat thud.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to reinvent the 1970s action series ``Emergency''
for the 1990s, tracking the daily life-saving adventures of a team
of paramedics in LA. The three young do-gooders of ``Rescue 77''
are the quirky and handsome Wick Lobo, the heroic and handsome
Michael Bell, and the emotional and pretty Kathryn Ryan. Looked
down upon by the firefighters with whom they share the fire
station, they are defensive about their role in emergency response
and like to go off on self-righteous tirades ending with ``We
always come.''
</P>
<P>
   The trio sleep in the same room at the fire station, which may
come in handy for Michael and Kathryn, who may have a budding
attraction. Kathryn is the most interesting character, just back
from a nervous breakdown after a disaster involving the death of
children.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene typical of the show's shoddy scripting, the station
captain has Ryan read her own psychological history out loud,
obviously for the sake of the viewer. He needn't have bothered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1414EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-WARREN-2TAKES-B     03-15 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WARREN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIANE WARREN KNOWS THE SCORE FOR REALSONGS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Includes Warren Hit List sidebar)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The coffee-stained Baldwin piano, on which Diane
Warren writes her many hits, sits in a cramped room that she calls
``the Cave.'' Cassette tapes are stacked everywhere. Tattered
curtains cover the windows. It looks like a disheveled college
dorm, rather than what it really is: the epicenter of a
multimillion-dollar empire that has forged hits for Aerosmith,
Celine Dion, Toni Braxton, Brandy, Cher, Gloria Estefan, and others
too numerous to mention.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a magic in here,'' says Warren, an engaging workaholic
who spends 12 to 14 hours six days a week in the Cave, cranking out
hits that have earned her every accolade _ and some backlash _ from
a music community that views her as the queen of radio pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diane is America's top songwriter _ wonderfully talented,
creatively inspired, and endearingly neurotic,'' says Clive Davis,
president of Arista Records, for which she wrote a No. 1 hit,
``Unbreak My Heart,'' sung by Toni Braxton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diane is beyond neurotic,'' says Tommy Mottola, president of
Sony Records, for which she wrote ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing''
for Aerosmith. And he means this as a compliment: ``She's the kind
of person who, after she plays you a song, will still play it five
more times. And when you tell her it's going to be a No. 1 smash,
she'll say, `But do you really love it? Do you want to hear it
again?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Warren first pitched ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing'' to Mottola
over the phone. The two of them speak four to five times a week to
discuss what she's writing at her music-publishing company,
Realsongs, which she operates from an eighth-floor office on Sunset
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked the song and put it on hold,'' says Mottola. Then the
opportunity to land it on the ``Armageddon'' soundtrack emerged,
and Mottola thought of various artists who might record it, before
settling on Aerosmith. The song became Aerosmith's first No. 1 hit
and was nominated for a Grammy for song of the year (losing to ``My
Heart Will Go On'' from ``Titanic''), plus just received an Oscar
nomination for best song in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she tailored the song for Aerosmith, Warren answers no.
``I like to write the song first. I don't like to tie it to
anyone,'' says the 42-year-old California native. ``It's the idea
that if you build it, they will come. Someone will make it their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened with the Aerosmith hit. ``Steven Tyler
really made the song his own,'' she says, noting that he was in
tears after recording it.
</P>
<P>
   So it comes as a surprise when she hears that Tyler, during a
recent backstage press conference at the Grammys, said that
Aerosmith didn't plan to do any more of her songs. ``We've already
sold out enough,'' Tyler said, illustrating the backlash that
Warren has sometimes faced in being America's most mainstream,
pop-ballad songwriter. While many extol her talent, other critics
label her songs schmaltz.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not new. That was happening 10 years ago,'' says
Warren, whose first hit was ``Solitaire,'' for Laura Branigan, in
1981, followed by ``Rhythm of the Night,'' for DeBarge. ``I prefer
someone to like what I do if they're going to record it. I don't
want anyone to be forced to sing one of my songs.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Aerosmith: ``If selling out is having the greatest hit of
your career, and selling out more concerts than ever, then that's a
strange thing for him to say. I don't mean to go off, but I'm just
reacting. I would think that people should be more appreciative.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler, who is known for sometimes blurting things out, did admit
that Warren's tune ``was the right song for the right movie at the
right time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand where Steven's frustration comes from,'' says
Warren. ``I understand that it's probably weird for him. It's their
first No. 1 record, and it probably got more attention than they
wanted it to. But it's a fact that it's their biggest hit, though
people out there in the world don't really care who wrote it. Most
fans probably think Aerosmith wrote it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Healthy bank account &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warren adds that Tyler's bank account was no doubt helped by the
song. And she doesn't have to add that so was hers. A worldwide hit
can, for the writer, generate $2 million to $3 million in record
royalties and radio, TV, and live performance fees. And Warren has
had many of them, including ``Because You Loved Me,'' for Celine
Dion (from the ``Up Close and Personal'' soundtrack), ``How Do I
Live,'' for both Trisha Yearwood and LeAnn Rimes, and the latest,
``Have You Ever,'' for Brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Since Warren controls all of her own publishing, her efforts
have made Realsongs the most successful female-owned business in
the music industry, according to The Los Angeles Times. Her company
occupies an entire floor of a high-rise building, and she's
assisted by a staff of 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being successful means I'm good at what I do,'' says Warren,
who may be eccentric but is driven to excel. ``I've always wanted
to be successful. I've always wanted people to hear my songs. I
don't write in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Diane is unfairly maligned sometimes by people with snobbish
attitudes,'' says Roy Lott, president of Capitol Records. ``She's a
classic pop-radio songwriter whose lyrics impact regular folks.''
</P>
<P>
   As for any elitist critics taking shots at her, Mottola says,
``Good, I hope they continue to do that and she gives us more
songs. This is a hit-driven business _ and Diane Warren writes
hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren grew up in Van Nuys, Calif., wanting to be a songwriter
from as early as she can remember. ``I was also a rebel,' she says.
``I got kicked out of some schools. I never liked school very much.
I went to four years of college, but I never graduated. My dad said
he'd support me financially if I went to college. I just took film
classes and watched movies while I sat in the back writing lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had only one music-theory class in my life _ one little
semester, which I didn't pay much attention to,'' she adds. ``I'm
basically self-taught. I taught myself piano and guitar.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, she studied the Beatles and Motown artists,
especially Stevie Wonder. ``I had older sisters in the house and
they always had records. And I'd always see who wrote the records.
I was fascinated by the person writing the songs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
