<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0982 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-WARREN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     03-15 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WARREN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LOS ANGELES: ... the songs.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's also fascinated by hard work. The only time she takes off
is on Sundays, when she leaves her home in the Hollywood Hills to
go to her Malibu condo and walk the beach. Otherwise, she's working
(``I'd go crazy if I took much time off'') and confesses that she's
sacrificed a social life in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I can focus on is songwriting,'' says Warren,
who also wrote three songs for Whitney Houston's new album, another
two for Deborah Cox's new disc, and one for Kiss's upcoming
soundtrack to the film ``Detroit Rock City,'' two for Latin star
Ricky Martin's next album, and an undetermined number for 'N Sync's
next CD.
</P>
<P>
   Her reach is extraordinary, since she's notched hits on the pop,
country, R&AMP;B, adult-contemporary, and Latin charts. ``I've also
done stuff on CeCe Winans's record and Jennifer Holliday's gospel
record,'' Warren says. ``And I was up for a Dove award (for gospel)
a few years ago for something I did with Michael W. Smith. I was
probably the only Jew in the place.''
</P>
<P>
   As for technique, she writes one song at a time and typically
writes melody and lyrics simultaneously, rather than one or the
other first. Some songs take a long time _ she took two weeks on
just a single verse for ``Rhythm of the Night'' _ but others, like
``Because You Loved Me,'' for Dion, went quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A song has a life of its own. It's going to take as long as it
takes. There's no set time,'' she says. ``Sometimes they're
stubborn little creatures.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, she excuses herself from the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird. I'm restless. I'm getting restless right now,''
she concludes. ``I'm writing a song that's really cool and part of
me wants to be in there finishing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DIANE WARREN'S HIT LIST: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --``Unbreak My Heart,'' for Toni Braxton. No. 1 for 11 weeks on
Billboard's Hot 100 singles chart. Grammy Award winner for female
pop vocal performance in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   --``Because You Loved Me,'' for Celine Dion. No. 1 for six weeks
on Billboard's Hot 100 singles chart and No. 1 adult contemporary.
Grammy Award winner for best song written for a motion picture
(``Up Close and Personal'') in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   --``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing,'' for Aerosmith. No. 1 on Hot
100. Grammy nomination for song of the year and best song written
for a motion picture (``Armaggedon'') in 1999. An Academy Award
nomination for best song, and No. 1 country single for Marc
Chesnuttin 1999.
</P>
<P>
   --``Have You Ever,'' for Brandy. No. 1 Hot 100 single in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   --``How Do I Live,'' covered separately by LeAnn Rimes and
Trisha Yearwood. No. 1 country hit for Rimes. Grammy Award winner
for female country vocal performance for Yearwood in 1998. Both
acts received Grammy nominations for the same song.
</P>
<P>
   --``Just to Hear You Say You Love Me,'' for Faith Hill and Tim
McGraw. Top 5 country single in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   --``For You I Will,'' for Monica (from the movie ``Space Jam'').
No. 4 on Hot 100 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   --``Nothing's Gonna Stop Us Now,'' for Starship. No. 1 Hot 100
single. Academy Award nomination for best original song (from
``Mannequin'') in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   --``Rhythm of the Night,'' for DeBarge. No. 3 Hot 100, No. 1 R&AMP;B
hit. Golden Globe nomination for best original song (from the film
``The Last Dragon'') in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   --``If I Could Turn Back Time,'' for Cher. No. 1 adult
contemporary song, No. 3 Hot 100 in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   --``Blame It on the Rain,'' for Milli Vanilli. No. 1 Hot 100
single in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   --``Look Away,'' for Chicago. No. 1 Hot 100 single in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Among her other hits: ``If You Asked Me To,'' for Celine Dion;
``When the Night Comes,'' for Joe Cocker; ``Who Will You Run To,''
for Heart; ``Missing You Now,'' for Michael Bolton.
</P>
