<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0988 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-KUBRICK-BOS &LR;      03-15 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-KUBRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROL FREAK KUBRICK LEFT A REMARKABLE BODY OF WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley Kubrick's life ended with an ironic neatness that I like
to think would have made the old controlmeister smile. He lived
just long enough to ship off to Hollywood the finally completed
print of his long-gestating and several-times-reshot ``Eyes Wide
Shut.'' We'll see it July 16, and we can decide then whether it's
of a piece with the rest of his films. Kubrick wasn't prolific. He
made only 13 full-length films in 45 years. More than 10 years have
elapsed since his penultimate one, ``Full Metal Jacket.'' But
although they contain only one out-and-out masterpiece, ``The
Shining,'' Kubrick's films form a singular and remarkable body of
work.
</P>
<P>
   His major films remind us, in an age blinded by the notion of
success, of winners and losers, that in art you can fail, as I
believe most of Kubrick's films did, and nevertheless achieve
greatness. Although he was celebrated as a great stylist, it was
style, too much technical fussing, that detracted from Kubrick's
films. What makes them great is the size and span of his overriding
and obsessively continuing theme, a view that violence, and the
irrationality that breeds it, are intrinsic to our makeup. He
expressed it in film after film, image after image.
</P>
<P>
   Literally and figuratively, his films assert, we are meat
eaters, not that far out of the caves, despite our hardware. It is
a vision he bracketed grandly in ``2001: A Space Odyssey,''
beginning the film with a scene featuring a bone being tossed in
the air by prehistoric men, ending it with mankind having extended
its killer instinct into its tools, namely the murderous computer,
HAL. In ``Full Metal Jacket,'' he strikingly crystallized mankind's
schizoid tug when he suddenly filled a frame with Marine Corps
grunt Matthew Modine wearing a peace button on his flak jacket and
a helmet with ``Born to Kill'' lettered on it.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick has never been a friend of the military. His
breakthrough film, ``Paths of Glory,'' starring Kirk Douglas,
attacked military pathology and coverups, making the point that
French soldiers in World War I were as likely to die from the
stupidity of their own officers as from German bullets. Its sheer
intensity and conviction make it a riveting antiwar film to this
day. After replacing Anthony Mann as director of Douglas's
large-scale but largely conventional Roman slave-rebellion epic
``Spartacus,'' Kubrick made his sulfurous comedy of nuclear
holocaust, ``Dr. Strangelove.''
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb,''
it forever etched on our collective consciousness the image of Slim
Pickens as America's ultimate cowboy of war, riding the bomb to
Armageddon, tall in the saddle and high on the suicidal jingoistic
rush of it all. As the violence persisted throughout Kubrick's
films, the insanity attached to it emerged ever more clearly.
Kubrick was too innately American, which is to say too innately
puritanical, to be comfortable with the sexual subversiveness in
Vladimir Nabokov's ``Lolita,'' but its distanced aesthetic at least
stayed out of the way of the flamboyant performances that carried
it.
</P>
<P>
   In ``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' Kubrick got away with
ponderousness because of the way the film asked you to give
yourself over to the psychedelic effects and floaty atmosphere that
turned it into a late-'60s hit as a head film. In fact, it backed
away from its view of man the savage by conveniently having Keir
Dullea's astronaut be reborn as an angel. Kubrick reverted to form
in the pessimistic ``A Clockwork Orange,'' taken from Anthony
Burgess's novel about a violent, amoral futureworld. But it
sentimentalizes and glamorizes Malcolm McDowell's sadistic thug by
making his traditional violence seem somehow more human than the
government-ordered lobotomies in place to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   In ``2001'' and ``A Clockwork Orange'' Kubrick seemed to
surrender to technical indulgence and sophomoric philosophizing at
the expense of narrative drive and flesh-and-blood characters. His
films seemed more and more engineering projects populated by the
very robots whose ever-increasing presence he thought he was
decrying. In ``A Clockwork Orange,'' Kubrick seemed to pass from
moral outrage, from engagement with the world, to reactionary
retreat from it. This chilly detachment lent itself perfectly,
however, to the icy madness simmering away and finally exploding in
his ``The Shining.''
</P>
<P>
   It represents a perfect fusion of novelist and filmmaker.
Stephen King, veteran of long house-bound winters in Maine, took a
wickedly funny look at the perils of being married to a writer and
cooped up too long with him. Kubrick, riding a brilliant
performance by Jack Nicholson as a satanic loose cannon, turned the
ancient burial ground into a minefield of primal rage, climaxing in
an orgy of would-be infanticide in a mythic maze. Nicholson's
monster, recycling his own baggage of violence in a labyrinth,
stands as Kubrick's ultimate personification of man locked into a
kill-crazy pattern beneath the reach of anything so tame as reason.
</P>
<P>
   Pessimism, detachment, cerebral distancing. Each became more
pronounced as Kubrick's literal retreat into his own English
fortress progressed. It was as if he had seen ``A Clockwork
Orange'' too many times and been scared by it into a prison of his
own making. In the end, Kubrick's films seemed as alienated and
detached as their protagonists. Just as ``Saving Private Ryan'' is
now inevitably being pitted against ``The Thin Red Line, so ``Full
Metal Jacket'' was pitted in its time against the far more popular
``Platoon.'' There are parallels.
</P>
<P>
   The visceral ``Platoon'' convinced us it was grounded in
authentic Vietnam experience. ``Full Metal Jacket'' seemed grounded
in nothing more than an idea in Kubrick's head. For this it paid a
price in power and moral force, even though no film more
unforgettably evokes the nightmarish pulping of human volition as
the recruits are pounded into ambulatory conditioned reflexes in
the first half of ``Full Metal Jacket.'' You can't help remembering
the way the recruits allow themselves to be terrorized and
brutalized just to avoid detonating their maniac drill sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   But the main structural failing of ``Full Metal Jacket'' lies in
its ushering us to the edge of nightmare, then drawing back to the
much less compelling level of mere irony. Instead of sending the
boot-camp sequences into a more intense orbit, the second half
deflates by never summoning a truly reverberant, visceral kind of
horror. One of the big film questions of 1999 will be whether
``Eyes Wide Shut'' can muster a sense of fateful moral entrapment,
whether it will represent a renewal of the venturesomeness that
made Kubrick able to fail at big, ambitious films worth failing at,
or whether it will revert, as so many of his more recent films
have, to a case of humanity in retreat. Did he evolve from social
critic to despairing misanthrope? Or is there yet another Kubrick
to be revealed? Perhaps ``Eyes Wide Shut'' will point to an answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
