<HEADLINE>
BOOKS RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Single &AMP; Single'' by John le Carre (Scribner, $26). Drugs,
family, and business collide in the latest by the British dean of
foreign intrigue. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreamland'' by Kevin Baker (HarperCollins, $26). A fictional
wild ride through the New York of the turn of the century. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``November 1916'' by Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $35). The second installment of the Russian writer's
monumental fiction cycle, meant to recast his country's
revolutionary history. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crime of Sheila McGough'' by Janet Malcolm (Knopf, $22). A
unique reporter recounts the trials of an innocent found guilty of
14 felonies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diary of Vaslav Nijinsky,'' edited by Joan Acocella
(Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $30). The soaring dancer's tragic mental
collapse, in his own words. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler: 1889-1936: Hubris'' by Ian Kershaw (Norton, $35). A
massive and highly readable account of the rise of the tyrant.
</P>
