<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES RECENTLY REVIEWED IN THE BOSTON GLOBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ?????  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
!!! ``The Corruptor'' In a pulp-fiction Chinatown, an inexperienced
white cop is paired with a veteran Chinese cop with ties to the
neighborhood mob. Chow Yun-fat is riveting as the charming,
enigmatic rogue. Mark Wahlberg, as the newcomer, has good chemistry
with Chow as the two forge a friendship. Ric Young is a
scene-stealer as an elegant mobster. The movie's strength is its
depiction of the pressure-cooker mix of cops, feds, old-style
mobsters, and ruthless gang members. (R) (Betsy Sherman) 
 
!! 1/2 ``Deep End of the Ocean'' Nice gnarly take on the dynamics
of a family whose young son is kidnapped, then returned nine years
later. Michelle Pfeiffer is outstanding as the guilt-ridden
anguished mom. Stephen Schiff's intelligent screenplay mostly
avoids conventional Hollywood responses, though there are
compromises in this jaggedly paced and tonally uneven film. 
 
!!! ``God Said Ha!'' Julia Sweeney turns her own family's nightmare
into art, transforming her brother's cancer and her own into a
stageful of black humor that begins with their parents, whom both
kids had fled, descending upon them in LA for the duration. There's
more sweet, poignant absurdity than actual gallows humor in
Sweeney's spunky and very funny one-woman show.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
!!! ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' Entertainingly
propulsive crime caper set in London's East End, where the
theatrical side of criminality is savored and celebrated as four
Cockney wiseguys work their way up and down the criminal food
chain, trying to get out from under a crushing debt incurred at a
crooked card game. &QL; 
 &QL; 
! ``The Rage: Carrie 2'' Lots of red paint here. You wonder if this
silly attempt to update and replicate Brian De Palma's original
shouldn't be called ``The Rouge.'' Emily Bergl, making her film
debut as the successor to Sissy Spacek's dispenser of telekinetic
fireworks, seems promising, but this film is too focused on blood
and not enough on the characterizations that made the original. &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``Tango'' Nobody has put dance on film more often or more
masterfully than Spain's Carlos Saura. But he stumbles a bit here
in framing _ and freighting _ Argentina's national dance with a
balletic distillation of the tango rather than the tango itself,
and sinking his movie with a clumsily melodramatic and
anticlimactic plot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! ``Telling You'' This story of recent college grads working in
their hometown pizza parlor could have been ``The Little Chill''
for twentysomethings discovering adulthood isn't always all it's
cracked up to be. But the screenwriters don't know what story they
want to tell; in the end, they don't say a whole lot about
anything. (R) (Renee Graham) &QL; 
 &QL; 
!! 1/2 ``20 Dates'' Myles Berkowitz combines his professional and
personal failures into an occasionally funny, sometimes
mean-spirited film about a would-be filmmaker's quest for love.
Where he should be sympathetic, he often comes across as cruel and
manipulative as he secretly videotapes his dates. (R) (Renee
Graham) &QL; 
 &QL; 
! 1/2 ``Wing Commander'' One shouldn't expect much from a movie
based on a video game. This trifle certainly manages to be
everything we expect it to be, and less. Freddie Prinze Jr. does
nothing to forward his film career in this boring exercise in
cynical cross-marketing. (PG-13) (Renee Graham)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
