<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, March 16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ Kosovo talks resume, with ethnic
Albanians expected to sign the accord, paving the way to more
Allied threats against Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav president.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Dateline to kum) _ Yugoslav forces backed by tanks shell
villages in northern Kosovo. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the leftist
mayor of Mexico City, appears to be readying a campaign for the
Mexican presidency. By Dam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR-ECON (Quito) _ Ecuador's banks open for the first time
in 10 days amid chaos as taxi drivers block main roads in the
capital to protest a sharp rise in fuel prices imposed by the
government last week. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ZHU (Beijing) _ Prime Minister Zhu Rongji holds a news
conference; among other things, he denies recent accusations that
China spied to obtain U.S. nuclear technology. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-JAYARAM (New Delhi) _ Jayalalitha Jayaram, the former
movie star who is one of India's most politically powerful and
dependably outlandish figures, faces charges that she thrashed her
former accountant with high-heeled shoes, beating him black and
blue during an hourlong ordeal that left him bed-ridden with a
bandaged right eye. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (Washington) _ Developments: Attacks in both the north
and south no-flight zones. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLPOX-VIRUS (Undated) _ The National Institute of Medicine
weighs in on an American-Russian debate over whether to destroy the
last two remaining repositories of deadly smallpox virus, shifting
the decision to likely retention. By Judith Miller. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Des Moines, Iowa) _ In Al Gore's first trip paid
for by his political fund, the vice president captures the
endorsement of Richard Gephardt, the House minority leader, and
hold rallies in New Hampshire and Iowa. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-LA (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles is officially picked as site
for the Democratic Party's 2000 convention. By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   NC-ABORTION-BOMB (Atlanta) _ Developments in the FBI
investigation of the Saturday bombing of an abortion clinic near
Asheville, N.C. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-POLL (New York) _ The results of a N.Y. Times poll on
public attitudes toward the police and Mayor Giuliani. By Dan
Barry.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING (New York) _ Rep. Charles Rangel and former
Mayor David Dinkins facing arrest as protests continue in the
shooting death of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant,
at the hands of the police here. By Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-UNIVERSITY (Washington) _ The mayor of the District of
Columbia proposes to sell the University of D.C., much to the
consternation of its largely black student population. By Michael
Janofsky. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2 p.m., the industrial average was up 41
points, and the Nasdaq index was up 29. Elsewhere, prices rose 1.9
percent in Tokyo and 0.3 percent in Hong Kong. They were up 3.4
percent in Frankfurt and down 1.2 percent in London. On the
American debt market at midday, the long bond was down 3/32 point,
with the yield at 5.53 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   CHANCELLOR-LIN (Undated) _ Chancellor Media ends its agreement
to acquire Lin Television, saying investors are opposed to the
deal. Also, Chancellor's chief executive, Jeffrey Marcus, resigns
and is succeeded by Thomas O. Hicks. Hicks, Muse, which controls
Chancellor, will invest as much as $500 million in Chancellor. By
Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FLEET-BANKBOSTON (New York) _ More about Fleet's acquisition of
BankBoston for $16 billion in stock. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   DUPONT-PIONEER (Undated) _ DuPont buys the 80 percent of Pioneer
Hi-Bred International that it does not already own for about $7.6
billion. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-EXCHANGE (Undated) _ Canada's four major stock exchanges
are talking about a drastic restructuring that would turn Montreal
exclusively into an options market, consolidate big stock trading
in Toronto and combine the two scandal-ridden small-cap exchanges,
Vancouver and Alberta. By Diana Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   THERMO-SYRON (New York) _ Richard F. Syron, head of the American
Stock Exchange, will become chief executive of Thermo Electron, a
collection of companies that make equipment for various industries.
Syron had spent his whole career as a regulator before taking the
job at the Amex. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DEBT (London) _ Developments on Russian debt. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-RENAULT (Tokyo) _ Nissan shares rise 13 percent as
expectations of a Renault alliance grow. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
