<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1008 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-POLITICS-031     03-15 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICS-0316-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET PLAYS WHISTLE-STOP ROLE IN CAMPAIGN 2000
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) political categories
 &HT;    With COX-FORBES
 &HT;    With COX-INTERNET-SITE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON ``Jesse Ventura for president (in) 2000?'' the
maverick Minnesota governor's official political Web site asks --
before dispensing the answer: ``Sorry folks, it's not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time, other candidates seeking the presidency
in 2000 -- ranging from heavyweights to virtual unknowns -- plan
large-scale campaign efforts on the Internet. In doing so, they are
responding to the lessons learned from Ventura's surprisingly
successful bid for office in 1998. ``Through his site, while not
dynamic, Ventura activated and energized people to become involved
and vote. And in politics, that's the bottom line,'' says Phillip
Noble, who hosts a Web site that examines online politics.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Ventura campaign, political handlers and
scholars say, the Internet is finally emerging as a potent mass
market arena. Its appeal to politicians is heightened because
voters tend to be cyber-savvy and because the cost of reaching them
is far lower than by such traditional methods as TV ads. Some
experts predict the Internet could do much to level the political
playing field now tilted in favor of the best financed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Says Gary Selnow, a professor of computing systems at San
Francisco State University and a leading scholar on the advent of
political activity on the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ``Some 50 years ago, the political whistle-stop tour was so
named because trains blew their whistles twice when making
unscheduled stops in backwater towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like its distant cousin, the electronic whistle-stop brings
the candidate's message directly to the people, but with one
outstanding difference: the new whistle-stop offers politicians an
accuracy, efficiency, and success at voter persuasion unimaginable
to earlier whistle-stoppers such as (President) Harry Truman.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates who learn how to ``successfully inform,
persuade, enlighten, and even confuse voters will win votes,''
Selnow concludes. To do so, he says, they need to sponsor
state-of-the-art ``home pages'' while also offering extensive
electronic bulletin boards and access to their data libraries.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear to Selnow and others that presidential-level
politicians can no longer ignore cyberspace. That, in turn,
requires them to hire Internet advisers to show the candidates how
to appeal to the ever-larger numbers of voters who go online. But
just how this process will evolve remains uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim ends)
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually everything of consequence in the political sphere
that has occurred on the Internet has been unintended and
unexpected,'' says Carl Wagner, a Washington-based consultant who
has managed several presidential campaigns for Democratic hopefuls,
including Sen. Edward Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   A prime example: In counter-point to traditional 30-second TV
spots, cyber-ready candidates offer voters direct access to
detailed issue papers.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates also have discovered the Ventura-style political
rewards of using e-mail to build lists of volunteers and
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   These electronic political lists can spark spirited two-way
messages and even one-on-one chat room ``debates'' with the
candidate that others are able to monitor. (In the Ventura
campaign, supporters would log on, chat, and then regularly turn
out at campaign events.)
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim ends)
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1998, about one-half of the voters were regular Internet
users,'' Wagner notes. ``Next year, that's expected to climb to 75
percent. Consequently, I think you'll see in 2000, information
technology for the first time bring interactive communication fully
into the political process, all in real time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even non-candidate Ventura, whose techniques are serving as a
model for 2000, has gotten into the act. A blurb on Ventura's site
spells out what's afoot:
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse is providing national organizing assistance to help draw
a viable Reform Party candidate into the year-2000 presidential
race. Using his Web site, Jesse is providing a place where citizens
can register to demonstrate their willingness to support such a
candidate. By building a large national list, and making it
available for presidential campaign use, Jesse is providing a
strong incentive for a viable candidate to rise and run for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   Most of the current crop of 2000 presidential political Web
sites offer fast access, good navigation tools, thumbnail
biographies, photos of candidates and their families, and a heavy
diet of issues-based content.
</P>
<P>
   As surfers drill into these contents, they are often invited to
volunteer their time or contribute money, usually via a printed
form that must be mailed in.
</P>
<P>
   (end optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   While the complexity of the federal election laws discourages
candidates from seeking funds directly online, programming experts
report that compliant software, featuring individualized ``bank
accounts,'' will soon be widely available. That will protect
candidates from co-mingling funds and potentially violating donor
caps.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hockaday, a Republican consultant who worked for New York's
Gov. George Pataki re-election effort last year, has pioneered the
use of political ``banner'' ads that he buys for candidates ``at a
very attractive cost'' on Internet portals or news-oriented Web
sites. ``Visitors can click through, get more information or even
become instant volunteers,'' Hockaday notes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hockaday feels that full political promise of the
Internet has yet to be achieved. ``It's still emerging,'' he says.
``There are lot of politicians below the presidential level who
still haven't quite got it. When it comes to the effective use of
the Internet, the political world is still two to five years behind
the business world.''
</P>
<P>
   In citing a recent study of 20 GOP 1998 campaigns, underwritten
by GOPAC and his own firm, Campaign Solutions Inc., Hockaday
concludes that ``any future Republican candidate, anywhere, is
going to have to integrate the Internet into their campaign
strategy to reach the increasingly active 'netizens.'''
</P>
<P>
   Among the study's key findings: More than 90 percent of Internet
volunteers signed up to help without being recruited by a campaign.
And some 55 percent said they never had volunteered for a political
campaign before they found a chance to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Users that went to political Web sites stayed online 4 to 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine someone watching a four-minute television spot
or listening to a four-minute telemarketing call?'' says Martin
Edlund, who supervised the research project.
</P>
<P>
   ``This technology offers voters direct access to candidates at
virtually no cost to either voters or candidates,'' says the
Democrats' Wagner. ``It's a sure winner. And it's time has finally
come.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
