<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN SITES
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) political categories
</P>
<P>
   W/ COX-INTERNET-POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   W/COX-FORBES
</P>
<P>
   Campaign sites
</P>
<P>
   Here's a rundown on the presidential scene in cyberspace for
campaign 2000:
</P>
<P>
   Democratic sites:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley - Easy to navigate, low-key entry offers overview
of Vice President Al Gore's sole current primary rival.
(http://www.billbradley.com/).
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore - He's not there yet, but campaign spokesman says he'll
go online in week or so. (http://www.gore2000.org/). Until then,
you can find official Gore information via Bill Clinton's site.
(http://www.whitehouse.gov/).
</P>
<P>
   Republican sites:
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Alexander - Well-crafted Web site covers all bases,
including online volunteer forms. (http://www.lamaralexander.com/).
(CQ) Site also illustrates perils of online campaigning: many
search engines fail to find it, directing surfers instead to
nautical supplies store in Ohio. (http://www.lamaralexander.org/).
(CQ)
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer - Features only rundown of Bauer's campaign issues.
(http://www.campaignforfamilies.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan - Finely tuned online menus link to stands on
issues, upcoming events and instructions on how to join his
Internet ''brigade''. (http://gopatgo2000.com/).
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush - Official placeholder for promised site to come.
Offers no links to already extensive Bush Jr. online network.
(http://www.georgewbush.com/).
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole - Features video clip of this month's Iowa
announcement. Such clips are likely to become widely used when
high-speed Internet services are widely available.
(http://www.edole2000.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes - Latest online presidential campaign site, one
marking first time White House candidate turns to Internet to make
official announcement. (http://www.forbes2000.com/).
</P>
<P>
   John Kasich - With short and snappy domain name, Ohio
congressman urges supporters to get involved and shows them how.
(http://k2k.com/).
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes - Packed with speech texts and schedules.
(http://www.keyes2000.org/).
</P>
<P>
   John McCain - Slick site highlights toll-free number and ``get
involved'' page to process volunteers and would-be donors online.
(http://www.mccainforpresident.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle - No misspelled words here: Highly polished site,
replete with thumbnails of vice-presidential years.
(http://www.quayle.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Bob Smith - Visitors bidden to buy Smith's $50 ``share'' in
America's future but aren't shown how.
(http://www.smithforpresident.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Other Sites:
</P>
<P>
   Bush Watch - Often updated by retired teacher Jerry Barrett of
Austin. Features skeptical, liberal viewpoint with many links to
related sites.
(http://www.geocities.com/CapitolHill/3750/bush.htm/).
</P>
<P>
   Ross Perot - He's still ticking, hoping not to take another
licking. (http://www.perot.org/).
</P>
<P>
   Purely Politics - ``Politics1'' offers fine Web starting point
to examine would-be presidential players.
(http://www.politics1.com/p2000.htm/). For basic up-to-date news,
political junkies also often turn to ``All Politics''
(http://cnn.com/allpolitics/). For links to potential presidential
candidates in 2000, including third party hopefuls, try
http://www.politicsonline.com/ or ``Elections U.S.A.''
(http://www.geocities.com/CapitolHill/6228/index.html0/).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
