<HEADER>
A1041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-COWBOY16-COX     03-15 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-COWBOY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHEN EAST MET WEST AND FELL IN LOVE
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By the time she fell in love with the cowboy, Sara
Davidson had completed an Ivy League education, written four books,
borne two children, survived two failed marriages and was a
producer and screenwriter on the CBS-TV series ``Dr. Quinn:
Medicine Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   On a fateful night of fiddles and guitars, she was struck by the
cowboy's ``intense green'' eyes _ not to mention his baby blue
boots _ when he asked her to two-step across a dance floor in Elko,
Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson had flown in from Los Angeles to research a piece for
the New York Times Magazine on cowboy poetry. It eventually ran
under the headline, ``Git Along Little Doggerel.''
</P>
<P>
   The cowboy had driven up from Arizona to sell bridles and reins
and gewgaws that he braided from rawhide. He tried unsuccessfully
to sell a $200 flyswatter with hair from the tails of three horses
_ sorrel, palomino, and black _ to the tall woman with a blondish
mane and a badge that said, ``New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Their chance meeting came in 1993 and rather quickly led to an
unlikely but steamy affair that still continues. The relationship
is the centerpiece of Davidson's fifth book, ``Cowboy: A Love
Story'' (Harper-Collins, $24), published Monday (March 15).
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's fool, the cowboy asked right off _ on page 14, even
before the first sexual encounter _ ``Is this research, ma'am?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No sir,'' declared Davidson _ both then, and in an interview
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he got very used to my taking notes,'' she conceded.
``We'd be riding in the car or sitting in the house and he'd say
something that was so amazing and bizarre and unexpected that I'd
say, 'I have to write this down,' and I always keep a notebook with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   She soon realized a book would emerge from this sexy yarn of a
writer with degrees from the University of California at Berkeley
and Columbia University and a cowpoke who barely finished high
school and had never heard of Anne Frank. Practically every other
word in his love letters was misspelled. But he had ``magic
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often that God drops material like this into your
life,'' said Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   The cowboy is called ``Zack'' in the book, although that is not
his real name, and the episodes involving her now teen-aged
children and her ex-husbands are fictionalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writer in me simply wanted to tell the truth. But as a
mother, I felt an obligation to the kids,'' she explained. ``They
were just growing up _ not expecting to find some of their most
painful moments or embarrassing moments in a book that anyone could
read.''
</P>
<P>
   The family conflicts described in the book are real, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Omigod, just imagine a couple of upper-middle-class,
trying-to-be-cool California kids who are already troubled by their
parents' divorce. Then mom brings home this cowboy who smokes and
wears a belt buckle the size of a Frisbee and won't leave the house
without a huge Stetson. And mom, like, brings him to your soccer
games.
</P>
<P>
   The 50ish Davidson is about a decade older than the cowboy. Her
previous books include ``Loose Change,'' a semi-autobiographical
novel about three women growing up in the Sixties. Writing for
``Dr. Quinn,'' she again noticed her life and craft co-habitating.
</P>
<P>
   On the television series, Dr. Quinn is a well-educated woman who
goes west and ends up in a relationship with Sully, an uneducated
mountain man reared by Cheyenne Indians. Both Sully and Zack have
an innate backwoods wisdom and a steady moral compass, said
Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hit me until two or three years into the
relationship that I was actually having the same experience
off-camera as the one I was writing for the screen,'' she said.
``Then comes the question: Is my life imitating what I'm writing,
or am I writing from my life? ... There are lot of things from my
life that ended up on the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Once when Zack had come to visit, she was in a bad mood, so the
cowboy massaged her feet. Sully did the same thing for a tired and
troubled Dr. Quinn in one episode.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the screenwriter's cowboy boyfriend had moved to
California was riding horses as an extra on the series. So both
were hit hard when the show was canceled. In addition to promoting
her book, Davidson is working on a Lifetime cable movie _ ``kind of
a female 'Deliverance'.'' Zack has taken a course in shiatsu
massage to try to cash in on his talents.
</P>
<P>
   The live near each other but not together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of us wants to get married,'' she said. ``We both
crave solitude. I love being alone in my house one or two nights a
week, when the kids are with their dad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in this wonderful place where we look forward to getting
together,'' she said. ``I don't think I would have had this
relationship when I was looking for a husband and a father of
children, because Zack doesn't have the means to support them. ...
``We often joke that if we had met at different points in our
lives, we wouldn't have had anything to do with each other. Our
needs were different.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone understands their relationship now.
</P>
<P>
   Some women say, `` 'How could you? I could never have a
relationship with such a person. It's too big of a gap,' `` said
Davidson. ``I've had men who are intellectuals who feel very
offended by it. They say 'You're romanticizing the blue-collar guy
_ (writing) that he has a more primal and elemental and powerful
sexuality than the intellectual'.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``a friend of mine who works at the New Yorker loved
it,'' she said. ``He said that as a young boy, he wanted to be a
cowboy,'' and the book touched those memories.
</P>
<P>
   While admitting that the Marlboro Man always turned her on a
bit, Davidson said she loves the cowboy for a deeper reason: ``Zack
was the first man who said, 'I'll take you just the way you are.'
``
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
