<HEADLINE>
SENATORS LEAN ON OLYMPICS TO REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a, i and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF AND JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the International Olympic Committee gathers this week in
Switzerland to expel wrongdoers and repair its reputation, it will
do so under threat of action by members of Congress poised to force
fundamental changes in how the Olympics does business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a significant (IOC) dependency on the United States
that gives the United States significant interests,'' said Senator
John McCain, an Arizona Republican with presidential ambitions.
``We're not asking for the United States to control the Olympics.
But I think American interests should beneficially impress upon
them the need to clean up the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   That dependency, as McCain sees it, results from simple
economics: 60 percent of the money that fuels the Olympics comes
from US sources. IOC officials called that figure exaggerated but
would not elaborate. United States Olympic Committee officials,
however, said the amount is closer to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC jealously guards its finances _ a source of irritation
among investigators examining vote-selling allegations _ but there
is general agreement that the Olympics would essentially cease to
function without the roughly $450 million paid every four years by
US-based corporations that are nine of the IOC's 11 chief sponsors,
and the $3.5 billion in television rights fees paid by NBC to
broadcast the Games through 2008.
</P>
<P>
   New concerns about where that money goes, and what the United
States gets in return, have arisen as an outgrowth of the scandal
involving alleged bribery of IOC members by Salt Lake City
organizers and other would-be Olympic hosts. In response, McCain,
as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, has scheduled an
April 14 hearing on the Olympics and plans to invite IOC President
Juan Antonio Samaranch to testify.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the question he wants answered is whether the IOC
has proven itself so inept at controlling itself and the Games that
Congress should seek to redirect some portion of the American
money, most likely away from the IOC and toward its US affiliate,
the USOC.
</P>
<P>
   So McCain and Senator Ted Stevens, an Alaska Republican who is
the chief author of federal laws governing amateur athletics, are
insisting that the IOC _ starting with its meeting this week _ take
what McCain called ``appropriate steps'' toward reform.
</P>
<P>
   By their definition, that means adopting the proposals outlined
in a report two weeks ago by former Maine senator George Mitchell,
which include major changes in the way IOC members are chosen, term
limits, greater financial accountability, and strict enforcement of
rules on gift-giving and travel expenses.
</P>
<P>
   This week, at least, Mitchell's report is not on the IOC's
agenda, which focuses primarily on dealing with six IOC members
facing expulsion, changing the way host cities are chosen, and
creating a commission to consider ethical and other reform issues,
possibly including Henry Kissinger as a panel member.
</P>
<P>
   McCain used diplomatic language to warn of consequences if the
Mitchell report is not addressed. ``I would deeply regret that, and
I would urge them to seriously consider every recommendation of the
(Mitchell) commission,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain declined to limit his options, but the Senate committee's
staff director, Mark Buse, said failure by the IOC to act
decisively might prompt the senators to consider legislation that
would remove the IOC's tax-exempt status in the United States,
depriving it of millions of dollars in tax breaks on the
sponsorship deals with US-based corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to do anything that would damage or hurt the
Olympic movement,'' Buse said last week. ``We're trying to use our
leverage to force them to clean up their act so the Olympics will
survive and continue to prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   Another potential move by Congress would be to redirect the
money paid by NBC for Olympic television rights. Rather than have
that money paid to the IOC, the US Amateur Sports Act could be
amended to put that money under the control of the USOC, which now
receives 10 percent. If Congress altered that balance of power, the
USOC would be in a position to determine how much to give to the
IOC, how much to keep for American athletes, and how much to share
with other national Olympic committees.
</P>
<P>
   In the broadest sense, that would greatly diminish the IOC's
power by putting the USOC on almost equal financial footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their image has been badly tarnished by this scandal,'' McCain
said. ``They should understand that the United States, because of
our funding, might not be more equal to others, but they shouldn't
do anything that would put that funding in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's comments underscore an undisputed fact of life for the
Olympics: While no nation is supposed to have preference over any
other _ nationalism is anathema to what the IOC calls ``Olympism''
_ the United States is first among equals, particularly where
finances are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   IOC officials grudgingly acknowledge that fact, but also
maintain there is widespread misunderstanding about what the IOC
does with the money it receives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly do recognize the special nature of the United
States in the Olympic movement,'' said IOC vice president Richard
Pound. ``But if it's perceived as a US creature you lose the
international flavor and possibly the universality.''
</P>
<P>
   Added IOC marketing director Michael Payne: ``Without question,
America is the single most important market of the 200 countries''
that participate in the Olympics. However, he stressed, ``The IOC
and the Olympic Games are not supported by one dollar of taxpayer
money. It is totally privately funded. It is not like any other
international organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Payne said, the IOC keeps only about 10 percent of the
money in takes in, redistributing the rest to the cities that host
the Games and to national Olympic committees, with the biggest
share already going to the USOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``This money is going to all of the countries to support their
teams,'' Payne said. ``If somebody is wanting to cut that back,
quite simply the Games won't take place because there won't be the
financial mechanisms to support it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said no other Olympic committee gets a direct share of the
television rights, while the USOC gets 10 percent, rising to 12.5
percent in 2004, as well as millions more in IOC support. In 1988,
the USOC's share of the US television rights was $37.5 million;
that is expected to rise to $112 million in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress delves into the IOC's finances, it will find an
organization that during the current four-year period probably will
collect more than $3.6 billion in revenues. Of that, about 10
percent will remain with the IOC, and the USOC gets by far the
biggest cut of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   First, the USOC receives its 10 percent share of the US
television rights. It also receives 20 percent of the estimated
$500 million in revenue from the 11 chief corporate sponsors. By
some estimates, the combination should give the USOC about $200
million during the current four-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Other national Olympic committees complain that the United
States already gets more than its share, but from the USOC's
perspective it does not get enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're resented. . . . But 70 percent of the IOC's revenue
comes from the US,'' said Richard Schultz, USOC executive director.
</P>
<P>
   It also rankles the USOC that the United States, with two IOC
representatives, has the same number of seats as countries such as
Belgium, Sweden, and Morocco, and is outgunned by Italy with four
and Switzerland with three.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy financial reliance on US-based corporations and
broadcasters can be traced to the early 1980s, the dawn of
Samaranch's reign as IOC president, when the Olympics were nearly
broke.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing the worst, Samaranch turned to his old friend, Adidas
heir Horst Dassler. Dassler had a deceptively simple solution,
translated roughly as: Go West, young man. ``To get at the big
money nowadays, one has to go international, to the big
multinationals,'' Dassler said at a 1982 meeting of an Olympic
finance committee.
</P>
<P>
   It was sound fiscal advice, and Samaranch followed it
religiously and successfully through the 1980s and '90s, selling
sponsorships and television rights that attracted billions of
dollars, which turned the International Olympic Committee into a
financial juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic historian John Lucas, a retired Penn State professor,
cautioned that any change in the financial balance between the IOC
and national Olympic committees, including the USOC, could have a
dangerous ripple effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things the IOC does with its vast fortune is to
subsidize athletes. The people that would suffer the most would not
be the IOC, but the 3,500 to 4,500 male and female Olympic athletes
from the poorest countries in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The corporate sponsors, meanwhile, are hoping that the IOC does
whatever is necessary to protect their mutual interest: restoring
the luster on the Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what anyone is expecting from this week, but the
last thing we're expecting and the last thing we need is any more
drama,'' said Susan Rosenberg, spokeswoman for UPS, one of the
chief Olympic sponsors. ``The Olympics has been a very valuable
program for us. Whatever the IOC does, whatever Congress does, we
just don't want to see that change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
