<HEADLINE>
WHOSE LIFETIME WARRANTY ARE WE TALKING ABOUT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting 18 years of life out of a backpack would be enough for
most people, but not David Chalfin.
</P>
<P>
   The Framingham, Mass. man loves his Jansport backpack, which he
thinks he purchased in 1981. So, when a seam started to split
recently, he decided to take advantage of the company's lifetime
warranty. In the process, he learned that a lifetime warranty isn't
what he thought it was.
</P>
<P>
   Chalfin shipped his backpack to Jansport's warranty center in
Everett, Wash. The company fixed the seam and returned the pack,
adding a notation, ``The product has seen its lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   While pleased that his pack was repaired, Chalfin was puzzled by
the message. He called Jansport and was told that the life of the
pack had expired and that the warranty would no longer be valid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is defining what the lifetime is, and I don't
think that's a lifetime warranty,'' Chalfin said. ``That means that
if a product lasts just two days, the company could say its
lifetime is over.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Delorey, the president of Jansport in Appleton, Wis., said
there is a lot of confusion about lifetime warranties. Most
consumers mistakenly think the lifetime warranty applies to their
life, not the product's life, Delorey said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of such confusion, he said, most European countries
don't allow lifetime warranties and instead require companies to
specify warranty length in years.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts advertising regulations aren't that specific, but
they do require that the meaning of lifetime be explained if a
product is represented as having a lifetime guarantee or warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Jansport's warranty doesn't do that. The warranty states:
``Jansport equipment is warranted to be free from defects in
materials and workmanship for the life of the product. Our warranty
applies when the product is used for the purpose intended under
normal conditions and does not apply to damages caused by typical
wear and tear, unreasonable use, or neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. offers a stronger lifetime warranty on its
Craftsman hand tools. The warranty allows return of a defective
tool at any time for repair or replacement, said Jan Drummond, a
Sears spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a lifetime warranty, mail-order giant L. L. Bean
offers a satisfaction guarantee. It states: ``Our products are
guaranteed to give 100 percent satisfaction in every way. Return
anything purchased from us at any time if it proves otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Chalfin acknowledged that his pack's seam probably started to
split because of wear and tear, but he said his pack still has a
lot of life in it. The quality of his pack and the lifetime
warranty were two reasons he bought another Jansport pack last fall
for his 9-year-old nephew Sam, who lives in Natick, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Delorey said Jansport tries to honor warranty requests because
they are a direct link to customers and allow the company to assess
a product's weaknesses and how it is being used. Last year,
Jansport sold more than 10 million packs and processed 200,000
warranty claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to use our best judgment on warranty work,'' Delorey
said, ``but eventually a pack is going to wear out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The case of the double label
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Brookline, Mass. woman said she's not a fanatic about apparel
brand names, but she did notice that a $22 wool blazer she bought
recently from Marshall's had a ``Larry Levine'' label.
</P>
<P>
   After a closer look, she realized that the ``Larry Levine''
label was glued over an ``Eddie Bauer'' label. What is the blazer's
true name? She wanted our help to solve the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   After phone calls to Larry Levine apparel company in New York,
and Eddie Bauer in Redmond, Wash., we learned how garments can
collect different identities as they're recycled by the same
company.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Levine is a division of S. Rothchild, a Manhattan apparel
maker. Rothchild has other ``private label'' divisions that produce
special garments for a particular company, such as a line of Eddie
Bauer wool blazers, said Elizabeth Ferraro, executive vice
president for sales at Larry Levine.
</P>
<P>
   She said that if Eddie Bauer rejects any shipment for whatever
reason, S. Rothchild is allowed to resell the garments as long as
they don't use the Eddie Bauer label. She said her company can
remove the old label or cross out the name. She said nothing stops
the company from adding the Larry Levine label, though ``it's not
our practice'' to stick a new label over an old one.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro asked us not to rule out the chance that this one jacket
got two labels as part of a bizarre sewing mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Lurma Rackley, spokeswoman for Eddie Bauer, wasn't happy to hear
about the blazer. She said manufacturers who take back Eddie Bauer
garments must ``physically remove'' the old tag. Eddie Bauer has
contracts with hundreds of factories in 50 countries to make its
brand-name products, and they all agree to remove the Eddie Bauer
tag before reselling the garments, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the agreements, Larry Levine's sales staff doesn't
think consumers should get worked up over the double labels.
Ferraro insisted the two brands are of ``equal quality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we sold a Kmart jacket that had the Larry Levine
label,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Delivery confirmations. Starting March 14, anyone who uses the
US Postal Service can pay a little extra to verify that their
priority mail or parcel post packages were received. The retail
rate is 35 cents for priority mail and 60 cents for parcel post.
Customers will get a confirmation number which they can use to
track their package through an 800 phone number or the postal
service's Web site (www.usps.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
