<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOGRAPHERS-TRENDS-B     03-15 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOGRAPHERS-TRENDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOGRAPHERS CAUGHT LOOKING ON U.S. TRENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When World War II ended and Americans refocused on
home life, the nation's population experts failed to predict that
they would have so many babies for so many years. When women
started streaming into the work force, the experts took decades to
understand the magnitude of the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Now, having bungled the two most important demographic changes
in postwar America _ the baby boom and the rise of working women _
population specialists are making crucial forecasts that will shape
the debate over how to shore up Social Security and Medicare. And
this time, even they say that they are not sure they can produce
the accurate numbers lawmakers need.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering major changes to the two massive
programs for the elderly. Some lawmakers have called for cuts in
benefits, others for tax increases. President Clinton has proposed
diverting $3.4 trillion in additional cash to the programs during
the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   These proposals are driven by demography, the study of
population. The nation's 76 million baby boomers will hit
retirement age early in the next century, forcing huge payouts by
Social Security and Medicare. But no one knows how many retirees
there will be, how many workers will pay taxes to support them, or
how badly the programs will be squeezed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anyone who can challenge economists for making bad
predictions, it's demographers,'' said Patrick Burns, a population
expert at the National Council of Senior Citizens. ``I believe in
my profession. I believe they'll be right for the next few years.
But beyond that? They've never been right before.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Census Bureau, looking ahead 50 years, cannot even give a
firm population estimate. Its highest- and lowest-case guesses
differ by 236 million people. Put another way, its margin of error
is almost equal to the population of the United States today (about
272 million).
</P>
<P>
   And yet Congess must look beyond 50 years in attempting to
repair the financial problems facing Social Security. The program's
nonpartisan actuaries, who evaluate proposed solutions, are seeking
one that works for at least 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   Looking that far ahead with accuracy is almost impossible,
demographers say, because human behavior is too unpredictable. But
forecasters have also missed important signs that could have
improved their chances of accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, for example, demographers expected a baby
boom as servicemen returned home. But they said it wouldn't last.
Fertility rates had been declining for many decades as America
became urbanized and less reliant on agriculture. Experts such as
P.K. Whelpton, who made projections for the Census Bureau, said the
falling fertility rates would resume.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the baby boom lasted for two decades and became one of
the defining events of postwar America. ``Whelpton's projections
were abysmally low,'' said Gregory Spencer, who makes projections
for the Census Bureau today. ``This man was one of the trailblazers
of my profession. If a man as great as that can make mistakes, then
it can happen to any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Miscalculating another change in behavior, demographers in the
late 1970s saw that the number of high school graduates was falling
sharply. In well-publicized predictions, many concluded that
colleges would soon run short of students, forcing as many as 30
percent of them to close or merge. That would have been a
catastrophe for New England, home to a large cluster of schools.
</P>
<P>
   What actually happened? As predicted, a ``baby bust'' cut the
number of high school graduates. But the fraction of them going on
to college skyrocketed. The demographers failed to see that with
blue-collar wages falling, a college education became far more
important, said Paul Harrington of Northeastern University's Center
for Labor Market Studies. ``You couldn't have gotten this story
more wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, demographers were slow to understand the movement of
women into the work force. From the 1950s through the 1980s, they
constantly understated the number of working women and the big
increases in their hours on the job. As a result, government
forecasts for the size of the US work force were too low, said
Andrew Sum of Northeastern's labor studies center.
</P>
<P>
   No one says that these mistakes should dissuade politicians from
trying to fix Medicare, which is projected to see its trust fund
run dry in 2008, or Social Security, which in 2013 is expected to
start paying out more in benefits than it raises each year in
taxes. Lawmakers do not need dead-on figures in order to strengthen
the programs.
</P>
<P>
   But the picture that demographers draw of the future can have a
major effect on politics today.
</P>
<P>
   That is because people who favor radical changes to Social
Security and Medicare tend to portray the programs as facing a
demographic nightmare _ a crisis even greater than government
officials expect. Those who want only modest changes say the
programs face only modest challenges.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Cato Institute, an influential libertarian
think tank in Washington, says that tinkering cannot fix the Social
Security program. It wants wholesale change. Instead of paying
taxes to the government, it says, workers should put money into
their own stock and bond accounts and retire on the nest egg.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster its argument, Cato says that Social Security is in
more trouble than it acknowledges. The reason: People will live
longer than forecasters at the Social Security Administration
predict, so future costs will be higher than estimated. And worker
paychecks will rise more slowly than Social Security forecasts, so
its future tax revenues will be lower than estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Making the opposite argument for Medicare, Senator Edward M.
Kennedy says the future will be kinder to the health-care program
than most people expect. Scientific advances will bring new medical
treatments that save Medicare millions of dollars. It would be
imprudent to make radical changes to Medicare today, he says,
because we don't know what the future will hold.
</P>
<P>
   To paint a vision of the future, demographers make assumptions
about three key factors: life span, birthrates, and immigration.
Small changes in each one can have a big effect on government
finances.
</P>
<P>
   Consider life span. The Social Security Administration says that
by 2075, Americans on average might live as few as 78 years or as
many as 85, up from about 76 today. Longer lives might be
desirable, but they also mean more Americans will draw more Social
Security checks.
</P>
<P>
   If life span rises to 78 years, a payroll tax increase of 1.6
percentage points, or equivalent program cuts, would be needed to
fix Social Security for the next 75 years. That would bring the
current 12.4 percent Social Security tax to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But if Americans live to age 85, Social Security would need a
far larger tax increase of 3 percentage points today to remain
stable.
</P>
<P>
   It might cost even more. Many demographers think that advances
in medicine, better diets, and other factors will allow people to
live into their 90s and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Birthrates are even trickier to predict. They have risen and
fallen in recent years among American women, and nobody is sure
why.
</P>
<P>
   In their worst-case scenario, Social Security actuaries say US
birthrates could fall to 1.6 children per woman, down from a little
above 2 children today. At that rate, it would take an immediate
tax increase of nearly 2.6 percentage points _ or program changes
worth an equal amount of money _ to fix Social Security for the
next 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor _ immigration _ is highly dependent on political
changes. And all manner of economic trends, from wages to
productivity, could have a big effect on government finances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1503EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
