<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LATTES, GIVE US SOMETHING CALLED JOE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How has San Francisco changed since Joe, Dom and
Vince DiMaggio were lads? There are too many ways to count, but one
street scene tells the tale.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while the press, old-timers and younger people with
souls were saying goodbye to Joe, the block in front of his boyhood
home on Taylor Street was blocked off for a film crew.
</P>
<P>
   What were they shooting? No, not a film about Joe. It was a
Peugeot commercial.
</P>
<P>
   The house that was home to 11 DiMaggios is now a ritzy backdrop
for a yuppie French car, pronounced ``Pooh Joe,'' as the carmaker
once said in its ads.
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm not sorry I restarted the old San Francisco Rename Game
by doing the hackneyed column on what to name for Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, you hear a lot of obvious stuff like putting DiMaggio's
name on the new Giants ballpark, the airport, various schools or
the Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants may not want to be disconnected from the Pac Bell
stadium and the $50 million it paid for naming rights. Besides,
DiMaggio played for the Yankees, as many Giants fans and Yankee
fans pointed out _ Yankee fans with characteristic rudeness.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the San Francisco International Airport becoming
SFJoe is alluring, but I have a feeling that Mayor Willie Brown has
that one staked out for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Putting Joe's name on a school doesn't seem appropriate. He
didn't spend much of his time in that kind of building.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Bay Bridge, it would be nice to have DiMaggio's name
on something that's completed within our lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   I did get some cute ideas. John Schutz said that DiMaggio's
church in North Beach should be renamed SS Peter, Paul &AMP; Joe
Church. Just a joke, fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dodds, who lives on Clipper Street, suggested renaming
it Yankee Clipper Street. Just add street-sign extender.
</P>
<P>
   Serious ideas include renaming the North Beach Playground,
Funston Playground, Big Rec in Golden Gate Park, or the field near
the site of the old Seals Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Stephans, of El Granada, has an idea that could help
DiMaggio's sport. He'd like to see an annual baseball award to
``the player that best represents the spirit of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa would have won the Joe DiMaggio Award hands down last
year.
</P>
<P>
   People take their DiMaggio and their San Francisco very
seriously. That's the wonderful thing I learned from their letters,
faxes and e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   City Supervisor Gavin Newsom is reviewing all the proposals that
have poured into his office, and enjoys reading them so much he
carries them wherever he goes.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous ``captive in Colorado Springs'' argues against
renaming anything: ``I was born and raised in the Mission District
and San Francisco still and always is my home, and let it be as it
has been.''
</P>
<P>
   That gets to the heart of the issue. It's impossible to let San
Francisco be as it has been. The city is changing faster than
usual, and in some ways for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   However, there is one fitting tribute to Joe DiMaggio that would
make San Francisco a better place, and not just a place with one
more plaque on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Rik Myslewski writes to say that his baseball-loving son says,
``How can you learn to play when all the baseball fields suck?
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you been to any of the fields that San Francisco Youth
Baseball leagues are forced to play on in this city?'' Myslewski
says. ``Outfields full of potholes and `extract of dog,' torn-up
infields _ and don't even get me started on the condition of the
base paths.''
</P>
<P>
   A fitting memorial to Joe DiMaggio, he says, would be fields for
kids to learn to play ball without fear of torn ligaments or ``bad
hops so ludicrous that they at best turn a game into a farce, and
at worst can break a jaw.''
</P>
<P>
   Fixing an existing field would be a great way to start, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Several other readers echoed Myslewski's thoughts. Dr. Glenn Lew
suggests building new ballparks for kids, too.
</P>
<P>
   Lew says the Little League of San Francisco is small but
growing, and needs a new home. ``San Francisco has no room for
these teams of kids 8 to 14 years of age to play, so they must play
a number of their games in Sausalito.''
</P>
<P>
   That's shameful. When San Francisco kids go out of town to play
in tournaments, they realize they are growing up as second-class
citizens in sports.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio brought America together. There could be no better
tribute than to make his city sparkle with neighborhood Joe
DiMaggio Diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
