<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-CORPORATIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH WORLD TWEAKS CORPORATE TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Traditional corporations should emulate the
informality, flat organizational structures and quick
decision-making prowess of Silicon Valley companies if they plan to
succeed in the future.
</P>
<P>
   So says Karen Southwick in her book, ``Silicon Gold Rush: The
Next Generation of High-Tech Stars Rewrites the Rules of Business''
(John Wiley &AMP; Sons Inc., March 1999).
</P>
<P>
   Southwick, who is managing editor of Forbes ASAP, the business
magazine's bimonthly technology supplement, spoke recently about
the pros (mostly) and cons of valley corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   Question: How are tech firms rewriting the rules of business?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: They are totally different from traditional companies in
their structure and the way they deal with people.
</P>
<P>
   They empower people. They share knowledge instead of hoarding
knowledge. They move very quickly. They'd rather move and make a
mistake than not move at all. The industries they're competing in
are moving so quickly, they'd rather just refine things later.
</P>
<P>
   Another main difference is that at (high-tech) companies, the
boundaries are very blurred. They interact with customers and
suppliers in different ways. Customers help design products. These
are small companies, at least initially, so they out-source a lot
of things and have to work very closely with their vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can old-guard corporate America actually apply high-tech
business methods?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think they're going to have to to survive. The fundamental
business model is changing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is part of that. It's sped up the pace of change so
much. It's also the globalization of business. The companies that
don't adapt are going to be left behind.
</P>
<P>
   I still think there's quite a bit traditional industry has to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they've embraced the technology, but my impression is that
they haven't changed their underlying culture. Stock options are
still reserved at the executive level in traditional companies.
They still hoard information. But if everyone has e-mail, it's
going to make it hard to keep secrets anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there examples of traditional companies that have
incorporated aspects of high-tech corporate culture or used
technology to make their businesses run more smoothly?
</P>
<P>
   A: Certainly, traditional companies are moving to become less
hierarchical. They've gotten rid of a lot of middle management.
</P>
<P>
   A good example would be Fed Ex. You can on-line track your
packages now, so it becomes more of an information services
company.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is going to be an increasingly important influence in
the way we do business. Even mom-and-pop retail ventures have a Web
site. Eventually, they're going to do e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since there are now some very mature Silicon Valley
companies, such as Hewlett-Packard, is there a fear these
businesses will become more traditional?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's true, as companies grow they have to put more structure
in place. On the other hand, these companies have to keep an
entrepreneurial edge and empower people. It's too expected now. If
your company doesn't offer stock options, you just go down the
street to a company that does.
</P>
<P>
   I think H-P, which is probably the biggest company in the
valley, has shown you can get big but still have a lot of these
ideals in place.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that they just split up (into two companies), says they
know they had to make big changes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the downside of Silicon Valley's business model?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think technology is definitely creating a two-tier society.
It's making the haves and have-nots divide bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's kind of a frat-boy atmosphere for women and some
minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear Asians have prospered, but other minority groups,
like African-Americans and Hispanics, have been left out. Some of
that's education. They don't take enough math and science courses.
Really, the way to move to the top of these companies is to be an
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   It would behoove the technology industry to take more of an
interest in our educational system.
</P>
<P>
   From what I've observed of these companies, they're also
obsessed with youth. If you're over 40, you're washed up.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do you see Silicon Valley in 10 or 20 years? Can it
keep soaring ahead?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't see Silicon Valley losing its leadership role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
