 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, March
16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HUMAN-DNA (Undated) _ Analyzing the DNA of people living
now, biologists exploring the history of the earliest human
populations say they have evidence of a genetic split in human
ancestors some 200,000 years ago. This date, 70,000 years before
the oldest known fossils of modern man, is much earlier than
previous estimates based on other genetic samples. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SINKING-FREIGHTERS (Undated) _ Over the years, the sinking
in 1980 of the Derbyshire, a British bulk carrier three football
fields long, has turned into an epic of scientific debate and
sleuthing, a high-stakes detective story that is still unfolding.
The goal is to stem widespread tragedy. Since the Derbyshire went
down, the sea has claimed 180 ships of similar design and 1,465
lives, according to Lloyd's Register of Shipping. The vessels go at
a rate of nearly one a month, often mysteriously, like a fleet of
Titanics quietly disappearing from view. By William J. Broad. (2300
words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TREATING-SYNDROMES (Undated) _ For syndromes like Gulf War
and chronic fatigue, the professional debate is not over whether
the symptoms are real. Those affected are definitely sick, experts
say. Instead, it focuses on whether there is any point in
continuing a thus far fruitless search for specific causes. A more
productive approach, they say, would be to treat these syndromes as
one and the same and provide effective treatment regardless of the
cause. By Jane E. Brody. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANGIOGENESIS-CANCER (Undated) _ Researchers are reporting
new insights into understanding angiogenesis, the body's process of
forming new blood vessels, and how it might be blocked as a therapy
against cancer. One team of biologists says it has isolated a new
kind of angiogenesis inhibitor from human cartilage. The powerful
inhibitor may explain why cartilage is a tissue that has no blood
vessels. As with other angiogenesis inhibitors, biologists hope
that it can be used to cut off the blood supply on which tumors
depend. By Nicholas Wade. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FOAM-TERRORISTS (Undated) _ By combining ingredients of
hair-conditioning creams and toothpaste, government chemists have
created a foam they say could neutralize many of the chemical
poisons and disease-causing microbes that might be spread by
terrorists in confined spaces. By Malcolm W. Browne. (580 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEEP-SEA (Undated) _ Human explorers of the eternal darkness
surrounding deep sea hot springs may inadvertently be blinding
swarms of shrimp whose eyes are exquisitely adapted for life in a
world of eternal darkness. By William J. Broad. (550 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-APE-RIGHTS (Undated) _ Animal activists in New Zealand, in a
largely symbolic gesture, are pushing a plan that would give basic
human rights to apes. By Allan Coukell. (475 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXTINCTION (Undated) _ Scientists now are virtually helpless
as they observe and record the final days of a variety of species
that becoming extinct, particularly in the isolated Mascarene
Islands. By Carol K. Yoon. (826 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WRIGHT-FLIGHT (Undated) _ In a giant NASA wind tunnel used
to test components of advanced airplanes and spacecraft sits a
fragile looking biplane of wood and cloth: a replica of the Wright
brothers' aircraft that began the age of powered flight. Experts
now are trying to figure out just how it did fly and then to
restage the events for the centennial of the first flight, which
occurred in 1903. By Warren E. Leary. (890 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short items on science: cooking oil for
diesel engines, supercharged rice and carbon dioxide in the ice
ages. (750 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: A
practical guide to deciding the issue of circumcision, in the face
of little guidance from scientific studies. While there are no
clear-cut answers, there are clear issues. A parent's guide. By
Jane E. Brody. (1220 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RABIES (Undated) _ Worldwide, some 30,000 people a year die
from rabies, mostly in developing countries where dogs are not
vaccinated and treatment is not available for people who are
bitten. In the United States, the disease has become extremely rare
in humans, but recent examples show people can be bitten by rabid
bats and not even know it. By Denise Grady. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SLEEP-CAFFEINE (Undated) _ Sleep researchers now believe the
best way to remain alert through the night is to nap in the
afternoon, drink coffee around midnight _ and avoid any catnapping.
By John O'Neil. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NURSING (Undated) _ An essay: Nurses are alarmed that in
medical cost-cutting nursing staffs were cut. And now, they say,
patient care is suffering. By Claire M. Fagin. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FITNESS-MINIPOOLS (Undated) _ Swimming pools as small as
sport utility vehicles are now the rage in at-home fitness. Current
keep the swimmer in place, like the tread on a treadmill. But the
mini-pools also are playing an increasingly important role in
training world class athletes, whose performance can be closely
monitored in the tanks. By Alex Frankel. (580 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ Shorts on health and fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Can a supplement that promises to reduce cellulite actually
work? (365 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ A study shows that pregnant women who also have cancer can
successfully be treated with chemotherapy during the final two
trimesters, with no apparent harm to their babies. (330 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Engaging in high-impact exercise or strenuous weight lifting
while taking fluoroquinolone antibiotics, commonly used to treat
urinary tract, bronchopulmonary or intestinal infections, may lead
to tendon ruptures, injuries that can require surgery and months of
rehabilitation. (440 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Is there a fungus that helps trees absorb
water? Yes, it is called mycorrhizae. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FASHION &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-FASHION-I (Paris) _ Review of Paris fashion collections:
Cerruti, Galliano, Chanel, Vivienne Westwood and Christian LaCroix.
By Constance C.L. White.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-FASHION-II (Paris) _ Review of Paris fashion collections:
Celine, Jean-Paul Gaultier, Valentino and Loewe. By Cathy Horyn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS-FASHION (Undated) _ Short items on fashion. By
Constance C.L. White.
