<SLUG> BC-SCI-APE-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALANDERS PRESS PLAN FOR APES' RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALLAN COUKELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ A group of activists here is pushing a
plan that could make the nation the first in the world to grant
basic ``human'' rights to apes.
</P>
<P>
   The activist group, the Great Ape Project of New Zealand,
advocates that animal welfare legislation currently under review be
amended to guarantee basic rights to chimpanzees, bonobos, gorillas
and orang-utans.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed guarantees include the right not to be deprived of
life, the right not to be subjected to torture or cruel treatment
and the right not to be used in medical or scientific
experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   The group, representing 38 New Zealand scientists,
conservationists and academics, is affiliated with the Great Ape
Project International, which was formed in 1993 to campaign for a
United Nations charter on Great Apes.
</P>
<P>
   In a submission to a parliamentary committee, the New Zealand
group argued that great apes shared many human emotional and
psychological characteristics, including self-awareness, the
ability to reason and the ability to imagine what others are
thinking and feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would have little direct effect in New Zealand,
because primates are not used in research here, and the country has
fewer than 50 chimpanzees and orangutans in total.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it is important for New Zealand to take the lead
on this issue, said David Penny, scientific spokesman for GAP New
Zealand and professor of theoretical biology at Massey University
in Palmerston North. People from overseas ``are almost begging us
`please, if you go and do it, then we can follow. We need someone
to take the lead,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments can be powerful in New Zealand, where many people
are proud of the country's bold anti-nuclear stance and its past
trailblazing approach to women's suffrage, whaling and other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue has yet to catch fire in public opinion and the
proposal does have its opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Professor David Mellor, also of Massey University, presented a
submission to the parliamentary committee opposing the suggested
changes. Mellor is an animal ethicist who is respected for his work
in improving animal welfare in New Zealand. He argues that the bill
as written is adequate to protect New Zealand's few great apes.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would be inappropriate to introduce major changes of
this kind without further public consultation. He also expressed
concern that in the long term these changes could affect the
nation's legal and moral relationships with other animals.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it may be arguments about process, rather than
ethics, that prevent the proposed changes from going through. But
even Mellor acknowledged that changes in attitudes toward the great
apes and other ``higher'' animals were coming, in New Zealand and
elsewhere: ``The necessary thinking is wide ranging and
multidimensional. It will take time. It will occur. We will be
affected by it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
