<SLUG> BC-WINE-INSTITUTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE INDUSTRY MOVES FROM TASTINGS TO HARDBALL LOBBYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In 1934, the Wine Institute was a fledgling
nonprofit organization founded by 48 California wineries to help
the battered wine industry regroup after 14 years under
Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   No longer a sedate trade group sponsoring wine tastings and
endorsing cookbooks, the Wine Institute today is a sophisticated
public policy and lobbying organization.
</P>
<P>
   Some 430 dues-paying commercial wineries _ out of 740 in
California _ belong to the Wine Institute. It has become the
leading organizational voice of the $11 billion wine industry in
California, where 90 percent of American wines are made.
</P>
<P>
   The makeover began in 1992, according to Wine Institute
president and chief executive John A. De Luca, when the
organization decided to counter moves by government and
anti-alcohol groups to increasingly tax and control wine.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was to promote and lobby for research on the health
benefits of moderate consumption and position wine as the
time-honored drink of civilized life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were being defined by our adversaries as a gateway drug, as
a sin tax industry,'' De Luca said. ``In order to redefine the
debate and get it back to the roots of the Mediterranean diet and
lifestyle, we had bring it to the public policy arena.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we redefined ourselves, we would have (had) incredible
restrictions on us, like tobacco,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has staked out positions on the health effects
of drinking wine and on governmental regulation of wine sales.
Moreover, it secured congressional approval of laws encouraging the
Departments of Agriculture and Health and Human Services to study
the benefits of moderate wine and alcohol consumption. Some 15
independent, taxpayer-funded studies with a price tag of about $10
million have resulted, the institute says.
</P>
<P>
   All this activity keeps De Luca on the move. ``I go to
Washington once a month,'' said De Luca, who became president of
the institute in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca, a former aide to Sen. Frank Church, D-Idaho, recently
testified at a Senate Judiciary Committee hearing about state laws
on the direct shipment of wines from wineries to consumers. The
Wine Institute favors liberalization of regulations that restrict
interstate sales, so that ``the hundreds of small wineries that
don't have access to store shelves can circulate their products,''
De Luca said.
</P>
<P>
   Wine Institute critics such as George Hacker, director of the
alcohol policies project for the Washington, D.C.-based Center for
Science in the Public Interest _ a nonprofit public policy think
tank _ concede that the organization is a serious player in the
hardball politics of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're able to maneuver on Capitol Hill quite well,'' Hacker
said, ``and they're well-connected.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Koch, the institute's vice president for federal
government regulations, used to be chief of staff for House
Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., and is married to
former President George Bush's daughter Dorothy.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca emphasizes the economic importance of wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The components of our state economy are agriculture and
tourism,'' De Luca said. Wineries are ``central components of both,
as well as a component in the hospitality industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Major wine producers such as Gallo, Canandaigua and Seagram's
Chateau and Estate Wines belong to the Wine Institute, which
operates with a staff of 41. Thirty-one staffers work in the San
Francisco headquarters, and there are seven U.S. regional offices
and eight offices abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The institute declines to disclose its budget. ``We don't want
our opponents to know what kind of resources we have,'' said
communications manager Gladys Horiuchi.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute retains some features of a traditional trade
association, such as promoting California wines abroad. These
efforts appear to be bearing fruit: In 1998, U.S. wineries racked
up export sales of $532 million, a 28 percent jump from 1997. That
year, California exported $425 million worth of wine, up from just
$25 million in 1987, according to the Wine Institute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is for political savvy, though, that the Wine Institute has
become known.
</P>
<P>
   When the current version of Dietary Guidelines for Americans was
issued in 1995, the revamped guidelines _ seen as Washington's
nutritional seal of approval _ were heralded in the media as a
triumph for the wine lobby. The reason? For the first time,
``moderate'' consumption of wine was accepted as part of a healthy
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Wine industry consultant Ed Everett, president of New World
Wines, a San Francisco wholesaler and importer, attributes much of
the institute's political success to De Luca.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is a very, very bright guy,'' Everett said. ``He
understands the big forces. He's experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the federally funded studies of wine drinking,
Everett added, ``He's good at getting Big Uncle to cough up.''
</P>
<P>
   De Luca said that labeling regulations, the dietary guidelines
(due for a five-year update in 2000) and interstate commerce laws
will continue to occupy the institute's political agenda in the
short term. Long term, he said flatly, ``We're deciding who's going
to define the state of wine in America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
