<SLUG> BC-REDWOOD-RESERVE-513&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC ACCESS TO HEADWATERS RESERVE BRINGS CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By MIKE GENIELLA   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Beginning Monday the first wave of eager
visitors entered the Headwaters forest to see the nation's newest
redwood reserve. The access is being opened even though there are
no marked trails.
</P>
<P>
   When state and federal officials tramped into Headwaters forest
last week, they were enthralled by its unspoiled beauty and careful
to acknowledge a groundswell of public interest in opening the
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But by tour's end, broken branches, sagging ferns and deep and
muddy imprints stomped in the soggy forest floor raised new
questions about just how much public access should be allowed into
a place that until now has been largely untouched by humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legitimate issue. We're going to have to look at it
very closely as the state works with federal agencies to develop a
long-term management plan for Headwaters,'' said Steven Glazer, an
aide to state Resources Secretary Mary Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols and Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt entered Headwaters
near Fortuna. Targeted to be the primary access for visitors and
their vehicles, the site isn't scheduled to open until June. The
access site that opened Monday is about 6 miles southeast of
Eureka.
</P>
<P>
   Government representatives say they're acting in response to
strong public interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been getting lots and lots of calls. I guess it's
because Head-waters has been in the public eye for so long,'' said
Lynda Roush, field manager for the Arcata office of the federal
Bureau of Land Management.
</P>
<P>
   After years of negotiations that were completed only minutes
before a March 1 deadline, the federal government agreed to pay
$250 million and California $242 million to acquire the 10,000
acres of ancient redwoods from the Pacific Lumber Co. The company
also agreed to forgo logging for at least 50 years on 7,900 acres
in a dozen other old-growth groves.
</P>
<P>
   Because some key federal lawmakers in 1996 feared rugged and
remote Headwaters would remain isolated and inaccessible to
taxpayers, a provision mandating public access was written into a
1996 congressional authorization of $250 million toward the
forest's purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The present push to open a remnant of ancient redwood forest
before a comprehensive management plan can be developed is raising
serious questions among environmentalists, government biologists,
botanists and fishery experts, who worry about the impacts on a
fragile ancient redwood environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to ensure that Headwaters remains wild,'' said Kevin
Bundy of the Environmental Protection Information Center, a group
based in Northern California that has waged a decade-long battle to
permanently protect what was then the last large tract of old
redwoods remaining in private ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau of Land Management botanist Jennifer Wheeler is among
state and federal scientists who agree too many visitors could
destroy the very redwood environment that government leaders seek
to protect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Headwaters provides an opportunity for important scientific
research, but that's hard to do if overrun by visitors,'' Wheeler
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to the scientific concerns, Pacific Lumber Co.,
which owns 200,000 acres of industrial timberlands surrounding
Headwaters, has raised safety issues related to the easement it has
granted to allow public access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The access roads are narrow and will still be used by large
trucks and other equipment. We can't have Winnebagos lined up along
the roadway,'' said Pacific Lumber President John Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   After his hike into Headwaters last Tuesday, Babbitt said he was
in awe of the wild state of the 3,000-acre core. Babbitt pledged to
work to protect Headwaters' integrity, and he vowed not to let the
ecological wonder be turned into a ``Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   But scientists say even with limited access, it won't take much
to jeopardize the untouched nature of Headwaters. Larger and older
groves of ancient redwoods exist in nearly 200,000 acres already
protected in state and federal parks. But in general, few protected
areas match the primitive state of Headwaters.
</P>
<P>
   Roush said the Bureau of Land Management will work with state
agencies to develop a long-range management plan for Headwaters.
Despite the quick decision to open the preserve to hikers,
government agencies intend to go slow on allowing broader uses, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The process, anticipated to take up to a year and including
public hearings, will begin this fall. Roush said the likely result
would be a trail system within Headwaters and to points that
overlook the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Bailey, the Sierra Club's statewide forestry
representative, said she's in favor of placing limits on the number
of people that will be allowed to tramp through Headwaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening up Headwaters is going to have to be very carefully
done, or we're going to lose what we set out to protect,'' Bailey
said.
</P>
<P>
   ( Mike Geniella writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
