<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-ANGIOGENESIS-CANC     03-15 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANGIOGENESIS-CANCER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOOD VESSEL STUDY MAY HAVE LINK TO CANCER THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.C., Mass.)   (af)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers are reporting new insights into understanding
angiogenesis, the body's process of forming new blood vessels, and
how it might be blocked as a therapy against cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's issue of the Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences, one team of biologists says it has isolated a new kind of
angiogenesis inhibitor from human cartilage. The powerful inhibitor
may explain why cartilage is a tissue that has no blood vessels. As
with other angiogenesis inhibitors, biologists hope that it can be
used to cut off the blood supply on which tumors depend.
</P>
<P>
   Another group of researchers describes a revealing discovery
about angiostatin, a powerful angiogenesis inhibitor discovered
recently in the laboratory of Dr. Judah Folkman, the pioneer of the
field. Like other chemical signaling systems in the body,
angiostatin seeks out special receptors that stud the surface of
its targets, in this case the cells that form the blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   After five year's work, Dr. Tammy L. Moser and other biologists
at Duke University have now identified binding sites on blood
vessel cells that are probably the angiostatin receptors.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Salvatore Pizzo, the head of Moser's laboratory, said that
now that the binding site is known it may be possible to design a
small molecule that will home in on it as accurately as angiostatin
does. That would improve chances of developing an anti-cancer
treatment because angiostatin itself is very hard to manufacture in
active form.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical company Bristol Myers recently halted its
work on angiostatin, saying it doubted enough could be made to
support clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the angiostatin was inactive because its structure is so
hard to duplicate. Proteins like angiostatin are made by cells in
the form of a long chain that naturally folds itself up into the
right shape. Sometimes the shape is reinforced with internal
cross-links. Proteins with cross-links are hard to make
artificially because, outside of the human cell, the cross-links
often don't form correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Angiostatin has three or four regions (depending on how it is
prepared) in which its chain is looped in a characteristic pretzel
shape called a kringle after the Danish cookie of the same name.
Each kringle has three internal cross-links. Because of these 9 to
12 cross-links, preparations of angiostatin are typically only 10
percent active.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been skeptical for quite a while that angiostatin could
be used as a drug candidate. Our yields were terrible,'' Pizzo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman, who works at Children's Hospital in Boston, said that
people are slowly learning how to make angiostatin but that ``if
someone could bypass it and make a small molecule that's effective,
that would be a major step, that would be wonderful.'' Discovery of
the angiostatin binding site by the Duke University scientists
``provides a glimpse that you could do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another important aspect of the Duke biologists' work lies in
the nature of the angiostatin receptor they have identified. The
molecule to which angiostatin binds is a large protein enzyme which
generates energy for the cell.
</P>
<P>
   ATP synthase, as it is called, is usually an interior protein
and has never before been found on the outside membrane of a cell.
</P>
<P>
   Its presence on the outside of blood vessel cells could explain
how the cells manage to survive in tumors where there is often very
little oxygen. Presumably the ATP synthase can generate energy from
a substance common in the surrounding fluid, and pump the energy
into the blood vessel cells.
</P>
<P>
   That insight, if true, would immediately explain why angiostatin
has the effect it does. By binding to ATP synthase, it closes down
the cell's energy supply and continued viability.
</P>
<P>
   The odd ability of blood vessel cells to survive in low-oxygen
conditions has been described by Dr. Harrison Farber of Boston
University, who has studied the phenomenon in deep sea turtles. The
Duke finding links the field of angiogenesis to Farber's work,
Folkman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The new angiogenesis inhibitor from human cartilage was found by
Marsha A. Moses of Children's Hospital and colleagues. Dr. Moses
said she was following up an observation made by Folkman in the
1980s, that when pieces of raw cartilage were dropped into a
chicken embryo, the blood vessels would move away as if repelled by
some factor in the cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the pursuit of the factor with new methods, Dr.
Moses and her colleagues discovered a substance in the cartilage of
cow shoulder bones that powerfully inhibited blood-vessel growth.
The substance turned out to be a protein well known in another
context.
</P>
<P>
   It is called troponin I, and is a subunit of the protein complex
that controls muscle contraction. The equivalent human protein was
then isolated from rib cartilage and also found also to inhibit
angiogenesis.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Moses' research was funded by Boston Life Sciences, a
biotechnology company, which is testing troponin I's usefulness in
treating the spread of melanoma. The company is conducting animal
tests to calculate the best dose to use in future clinical trials,
which will be on head and neck cancer and on preventing cancer
spread in sarcoma patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc E. Lanser, the company's chief scientific officer, said
that in a standard laboratory test troponin I proved to be
considerably more potent than either angiostatin or endostatin.
</P>
<P>
   Could troponin I have anything to do with claims about the
effectiveness of shark cartilage for treating cancer? Probably not.
If there is any troponin I in shark cartilage, it would be
destroyed by stomach acid, could not in any case cross the wall of
the gut, and even if it did so would not reach any tumors in
meaningful doses, Folkman said.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman remarked that the new finding may also prove of interest
to arthritis specialists. ``At a certain stage, blood vessels
invade and destroy the cartilage and you have the severe pain in
the joint of bone scraping on bone. Arthritis specialists will
probably start to ask if troponin is lost or destroyed in some way
before the blood vessels come in,'' Folkman said.
</P>
<P>
   A curious feature of angiogenesis is the way it is controlled.
The generation of new blood vessels, such as in wound healing or
menstruation, is not a casual matter for the body; the vessels need
to be switched on and off with the same precision as blood
clotting. Yet instead of having a dedicated set of signals to close
down new blood vessels, the body scavenges pieces from other
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Angiostatin is a part of a larger protein called plasminogen,
which plays a vital role in blood clotting. The angiogenesis
inhibitor is generated when certain enzymes cleave it out of its
parent plasminogen molecule.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly endostatin, another angiogenesis inhibitor found in
Folkman's laboratory, is cleaved out of collagen, the main
structural protein of skin. Troponin I is not generated by cleavage
but its angiogenesis effect seems secondary to its other duties.
</P>
<P>
   Several angiogenesis inhibitors are being tested as tumor
suppressors in clinical trials, although angiostatin and endostatin
are not among them. Folkman hopes some will prove effective but
does not expect any dramatic advance in treatment. He believes
physicians will start to use the various inhibitors in conjunction
with conventional treatments like chemotherapy and radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The particular promise of anti-angiogenesis lies in the fact
that the blood vessel cells it targets are normal cells and thus
not expected to develop resistance to agents directed against them.
Cancer cells, by contrast, are genetically unstable and quickly
develop resistance to chemicals and radiation, which is why cancer
is such an intractable disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
