<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; With the Millennium in mind, The Boston Globe has collected a
series of essays that ponder who we are, where we've been, and
where we are going. The package offers Globe staff writers'
reflections, forecasts and fantasies on the nation, millennial
angst, community, language, war, race, culture and sports.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-MILLENNIUM (Undated) _ After Monica and OJ and the media
exploding in all directions and elections too numerous to mention
and the enuii of it all, we're wiped out. &UR;  &LR; So maybe we are just
alienated enough, just distracted enough _ yes, just tired enough _
to need the Millennium. By David M. Shribman. 1670 words.
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-WE (Undated) _ Most of human history has been driven by
the desire for self-determination, for individuals and for peoples.
But at the end of the millennium, in a technologically
sophisticated consumer culture, those honorable impulses have been
trivialized into a kind of ``do your own thing'' narcisism. By
Renee Loth. 1480 words.
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-JONESES (Undated) _ Following one family, the Joneses,
while tracking the nation's changing demographics, moves, and
rampant consumerism through the last century and predicting their
course in the 21st. By John Yemma. 1800 words.
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-LANGUAGE (Undated) _ What's with all the fussing these
days about words and usage? Will the obsession continue? And, hey,
will anyone be speaking English in 600 years? By Jan Freeman. 1760
words.
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-WORLD (Undated) _ One might think technology has made
the world shrink. But that's not the case. Sure you can watch a war
start on CNN, but travel elsewhere, in war or peace, and the world
is as ancient weird, spooky, unpredictable as ever. By John Yemma.
(2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-RACE (Undated) _ Exploring W.E.B DuBois' prophetic
missile shot across the bow of American thought: The problem of the
20th century will be the color line. And we advance this by asking:
Will the problem of the 21st century be the color line? By Wil
Haygood. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-CULTURE (Undated) _ At the end of the 19th century,
romanticism had played itself out, giving way to modernism. The
same thing is happening today: people and artists think that
modernism and postmodernism have gone too far and that we have to
reconnect with the past without becoming reactionary about it. By
Ed Siegel. 1780 words.
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-SPORTS (Undated) _ What a wild ride the 20th century in
sports has been: The dollars, the scandals, the sponsorships, the
talent, the gender and age barriers, the trades, the humongous
players, the records. What does the future look like? By Michael
Holley. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   VISIONS-CHILDREN (Undated) _ Some things never change. A
mother's letter to her children -- and future generations -- about
justice, compassion, and that thing called love. By Eileen
McNamara. 1270 words.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the General National (a) category code.
</P>
