<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1218 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT &LR;      03-15 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL HEALTH: A GUIDE FOR PERPLEXED PARENTS WEIGHING
CIRCUMCISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JANE E. BRODY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Circumcision of infant boys has alternately been called ``the
unkindest cut'' and the key to good penile health and hygiene.
Which is correct, and how does a parent with a newborn son make the
decision?
</P>
<P>
   Those who have looked to the nation's pediatric authorities for
guidance are no doubt thoroughly confused by now. The American
Academy of Pediatrics has revised its policy on infant circumcision
four times in three decades, with the latest word coming this month
in an eight-page statement published in Pediatrics, the academy's
journal.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with its manual on the care of newborns in 1971 and in
revisions published in 1975 and 1983, the academy stated clearly
that there was ``no absolute medical indication for routine
circumcision.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1989, new research suggested that neonatal circumcision
reduced the risk of certain infections, mainly urinary tract
infections in childhood and sexually transmitted diseases later in
life. That finding prompted the academy to conclude that ``newborn
male circumcision has potential medical benefits and advantages as
well as disadvantages and risks'' and to recommend that these
benefits and risks be clearly explained to parents before they
consented to having the foreskin surgically sliced from their
newborn sons.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the rare physician who has the time and knowledge
needed to fulfill this mission and, unless parents consider all the
pros and cons of circumcision before childbirth, those with
newborns are rarely able to weigh these factors rationally at a
time of such heightened emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, parents hear frightening facts about the risks of
circumcision or of being uncircumcised without realizing how rare
these hazards are. And they are often misinformed about how to care
for an uncircumcised child. The United States has one of the
world's highest rates of newborn circumcision, but that rate has
dropped considerably in recent decades, from about 90 percent in
the mid-1960s to about 65 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   While the academy's 1971 statement was no doubt a factor in the
decline, other influences included the back-to-nature movement and
widespread publicity about unnecessary surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the removal of a boy's foreskin should not impair
his later sexual ability and enjoyment. Therefore, no authoritative
source has condemned male circumcision that is done for religious
reasons, primarily by Jews and Muslims. But for those making a
secular decision about male circumcision, there are distinct
advantages and disadvantages to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Benefits and Risks
</P>
<P>
   In considering the following facts, it is important to keep in
mind that some of the statistics reflect decades-old hygienic and
sexual practices that have since changed considerably. Thus, the
data may not always be relevant today.
</P>
<P>
   PENILE CANCER: The most clear-cut benefit of circumcision is a
major reduction in the risk of eventually developing cancer of the
penis. Since 1930 about 50,000 cases of penile cancer and 10,000
deaths from this disease have been reported in this country, with
only 10 of those cases among circumcised men.
</P>
<P>
   But, as the academy has pointed out, this is a rare disease, and
the risk to an uncircumcised man is low. This cancer is most
strongly linked to having a nonretractable foreskin. Other risk
factors include contracting genital warts, having more than 30
sexual partners and smoking cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   INFECTIONS: Remaining uncircumcised unquestionably raises a
boy's risk of developing a urinary tract infection during the first
five years of life, with the greatest risk, a three-fold to
seven-fold increase, occurring during infancy. Breast-feeding has
been shown to protect against these infections in uncircumcised
infants, and the absolute risk of an uncircumcised infant's
developing a urinary tract infection is low, at most about 1
percent, the academy stated.
</P>
<P>
   As for sexually transmitted diseases, uncircumcised men may be
more susceptible to developing syphilis, and several studies have
found higher rates of infection by HIV, the virus that causes AIDS,
among men who are not circumcised. However, the academy noted,
``behavioral factors appear to be far more important risk factors
in the acquisition of HIV infection than circumcision status.''
</P>
<P>
   PENILE PROBLEMS: The overall risk of penile problems to
uncircumcised boys is unclear. The academy cited a New Zealand
study of 500 boys that found higher rates of penile problems in
infants who were circumcised but higher rates in older boys who
were not circumcised.
</P>
<P>
   RISKS OF CIRCUMCISION: No surgery, however minor, is free of
hazards. The risks of newborn circumcision are very low when the
procedure is performed by experienced physicians or mohels, who do
Jewish ritual circumcisions. The most common complications,
occurring in 2 percent of cases, are infections and excessive
bleeding and, less often, improper or excessive cutting of the
foreskin, which impairs penile function. In a few recorded
instances, circumcision has resulted in loss of the penis or death
of the infant.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that circumcision hurts, and every infant who
undergoes it should be given local anesthesia and, if needed,
postoperative pain killers. Those circumcised without anesthesia
often remain hypersensitive to pain.
</P>
<P>
   Care of the Uncircumcised Baby
</P>
<P>
   Last month in an article published in Contemporary Pediatrics,
Dr. Jane E. Anderson, a pediatrician, and Dr. Karl A. Anderson, a
urologist, both of whom practice in San Francisco, emphasized that
``parents of uncircumcised infants should be instructed not to
attempt to retract the foreskin or use cotton swabs to clean
underneath it.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreskin does an excellent job of keeping the penis clean.
The doctors point out that very few newborns have retractable
foreskins, and by age 1 only half of boys have partially
retractable foreskins. Not until age 3 is the foreskin retractable
in 80 percent of boys and not until age 17 in 99 percent of boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normal bathing maintains cleanliness until the foreskin
becomes easily retractable,'' the doctors wrote. ``Once it does,
the parent, and later the child, can gently pull it back, wash the
glans and replace the foreskin over the glans.'' After age 1, the
doctors suggested that during the baby bath, his caretaker could
gently try to pull back the foreskin, but if this could not be
done, to wait three months before trying again.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors warn against allowing physicians or anyone else to
attempt to free the adhesions between the penile glans and foreskin
that normally occur in infants and small boys. This practice can
cause pain, bleeding and worse adhesions that may ultimately render
the foreskin nonretractable.
</P>
<P>
   Their final word: Having a boy circumcised is a decision made by
parents who should be fully informed about the benefits and risks
of the operation before they sign a consent form.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
