<SLUG> BC-COSMETIC-SURGEON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITY PLASTIC SURGEON PLACED ON PROBATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dr. Alan Gaynor, a San Francisco dermatologist
nationally known for his glib guest appearances on talk shows, has
been placed on five years probation by the Medical Board of
California, in part for the half-blinding of a woman who suffered a
needle stab to the eye in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Under a settlement with the state licensing agency, Gaynor is
prohibited from practicing cosmetic surgery until he completes a
yearlong surgical training program. He also promised to enroll in
an ethics course, to limit his cosmetic surgery to certain
procedures, to have another doctor monitor his practice and to
perform at least 96 hours of free community service for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco lawyer Anglia Benjamin, who represented one of
Gaynor's former patients in a lawsuit against the doctor, blasted
the medical board settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very rarely do we, as medical malpractice attorneys, consider
doctors as bad doctors. Gaynor is one of them,'' she said. ``The
Medical Board is not policing them. That's what they are supposed
to do, but they aren't. You want to stand on a mountain top and
shout, `How many does he have to maim before he's stopped?'''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin represented Lisa Santoro, a former fashion consultant
who wanted permanent eyeliner tattooed on her eyelids.
</P>
<P>
   She was left half-blinded when her eye was punctured by a
syringe during a 1992 procedure. Santoro ended up settling her
lawsuit against Gaynor, but her complaint became part of the
state's case against the physician alleging gross negligence,
incompetence and dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   According to the board decision, which took effect in November,
Gaynor admitted he had failed to properly monitor the
administration of Valium in Santoro's procedure and that ``he was
responsible for (her) eye injury even if it was caused by a
cosmetologist working in his office, as he contends it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The cosmetologist denied Gaynor's allegation that she had caused
the eye injury.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding another patient, Gaynor admitted that he had ``failed
to fully appreciate or assess the possible need to have (the
patient) go to an emergency room sooner than actually occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor, who gained fame in several television talk show
appearances, once performed a face lift live on Geraldo Rivera's
show, transferring fat from Rivera's buttocks to his face.
</P>
<P>
   An energetic promoter who dubbed himself ``the best known
cosmetic surgeon in the United States,'' Gaynor has said he's
appeared on more than 400 TV shows, including Larry King and
``Regis and Kathie Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Gaynor has apparently discontinued his medical
practice; he worked in a California Street clinic. In an interview
last year with the San Francisco Examiner, he said his practice was
``in hibernation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor's 1998 consumer book, ``Everything You Ever Wanted to
Known About Cosmetic Surgery But Couldn't Afford to Ask,'' has sold
out the first printing in hardback edition, said Nancy Clare
Morgan, a publicist with Gaynor's publisher, Broadway Books. Next
month, it is being released nationally in paperback, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
