<HEADLINE>
TOO FEW JOURNALISTS OF COLOR, SEMINAR TOLD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CARLOS BYARS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Newsroom staffing and sensitivity to people of color
got intense scrutiny at a recent seminar on race conducted by
Houston's journalism associations.
</P>
<P>
   The seminar, ``Straight Talk About Race,'' brought together the
heads of national organizations representing Hispanic,
African-American, Asian-American and Native American journalists.
</P>
<P>
   News directors of five local news organizations, the four major
television stations and the Houston Chronicle also took part in a
question-and-answer session Saturday moderated by independent
producer Ed Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   The four organizations represent about 7,000 journalists in the
United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   All members of the panel, representing newspapers in
Albuquerque, N.M.; Dallas; Seattle; and Washington, D.C., agreed
that there are too few journalists of color and their
representation in upper management is too small.
</P>
<P>
   There also was agreement that media organizations tend to
pigeonhole minority reporters, often assigning them to stories
particularly related to the minority community and failing to
obtain minority input on stories of general interest.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities, especially the Asian-American community, generally
are thought of as homogeneous and monolithic, said Catalina Camia,
president of the Asian American Journalists Association.
</P>
<P>
   Camia, a member of the Dallas Morning News' Washington bureau,
said ``Asian-Americans tend to be the invisible minority.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted the organization's 1,900 members make up only 2.5
percent of the newspaper work force, and one-fifth are students or
reporters with less than three years' experience.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Baca, assistant features editor at the Albuquerque News
Journal, said she believes Hispanic journalists suffer from an
image problem and that Hispanic professionals need more
representation in mainstream stories.
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Williams, who covers city hall for The Washington Post,
said she expects to see gradual changes over the coming decades as
a result of the country's growing diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Williams noted that if there were more tutoring and mentoring of
minorities by people in management, there would be more minorities
moving upward in news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   She also said managers fear that they might make a mistake by
taking a chance and promoting a minority. ``(The candidate) has to
be virtually foolproof before they will make that investment,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
