<SLUG> BC-SCI-SLEEP-CAFFEINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T GO SLEEPLESS WITHOUT THIS ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By JOHN O'NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is going to be a rough night. The beeper is bound to go off
once or twice or the baby will howl on and off until dawn. What's
the best way to make it through the night?
</P>
<P>
   Here is advice gleaned from research focused on two of the most
sleep-stressed professions, soldier and doctor: Take a nap this
afternoon, drink two cups of coffee around midnight and after that,
if you need a clear head, tough it out _ no catnapping!
</P>
<P>
   To those studying an increasingly weary populace, sleep itself
is ``without a doubt, hands down, the best countermeasure to sleep
deprivation,'' said Dr. James Wyatt of Harvard Medical School, one
of a number of researchers who addressed a recent National Academy
of Sciences conference reported last week in The Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Bonnet of Wright State University in Dayton, Ohio,
suggests thinking of limited doses of sleep _ that is, a nap _ as a
medication superior in almost every way to the most common
fatigue-fighting drug, caffeine. But every medicine can be misused.
He found in experiments replicating a medical resident's night on
call that taking short naps between tasks can actually lower
alertness levels.
</P>
<P>
   Tired people fall quickly into deep sleep, Dr. Bonnet said, and
waking from that state produces sleep inertia, that terrible,
groggy feeling that can impair responses for up to half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Naps are most effective when the sleeper is not tired, and can
be used to prevent fatigue, a practice researchers call
prophylactic napping.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David F. Dingess, chief of the division of sleep and
chronobiology at the University of Pennsylvania Medical Center,
said the body recovers from sleep deprivation most rapidly during
the first hour of slumber. ``That's why naps work,'' he said. ``Now
that I'm approaching 50, I'm amazed at how much of a difference 10
minutes makes.''
</P>
<P>
   This miracle cure, however, has a real-world limitation _ the
time it takes to administer. Bonnet recommended two-hour naps for
residents before a night on call, an idea that startled the
director of the medical/pediatrics residency program at his school.
``Two hours?'' Dr. Gary Onady remarked. ``Wow. That's not going to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   But when there are no naps, there is caffeine. And the armed
forces, worried about the increasingly common combination of
high-tech weapons, night operations and rapid deployment across
time zones, has become a major sponsor of research in the field.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent conference, psychologists from the Army's Walter
Reed Institute of Research described what happened when soldiers
were kept awake for 48 hours and then given 600 milligrams of
caffeine, the equivalent of six cups of coffee. The drug's effect
on postponing sleep was fleeting, said Col. Greg Belenky. ``But the
effect on performance was more enduring, lasting 10 to 12 hours,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The practical challenge is making caffeine available in combat.
During the 100 hours of ground combat in the Persian Gulf War,
``there was no coffee to be had for love nor money,'' Belenky
recalled. ``Guys had brought little packets of Taster's Choice and
were ripping them open and pouring it in their mouths.''
</P>
<P>
   Food technologists at the Department of Defense Soldier Center
of Excellence in Natick, Mass., are working on a heavily
caffeinated ``Hoo-ah'' food bar _ ``as in `Let's take that hill!
Hoo-ah!''' Belenky said. But the Walter Reed team prefers Stay
Alert chewing gum, a commercial product that gets 80 percent of its
caffeine into the bloodstream within five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   For civilians, the emphasis should be on making the most
effective use of coffee and naps, Dingess said. Nerve cells develop
tolerance to caffeine, so consider going without it for a week
occasionally to restore its punch. And when there is a tough
stretch ahead, he said, avoid alcohol, use coffee strictly as a
``wake promoter _ why do people drink it first thing in the
morning, if they've had a good night's sleep?'' _ and nap
strategically to head off weariness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
