<SLUG> BC-SCI-DEEP-SEA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERS' FLOODLIGHTS MAY BLIND SHRIMP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Great Britain)  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In spots, the depths of the sea teem with shrimp whose eyes are
exquisitely adapted for life in a world of eternal darkness.
Extraordinarily sensitive, the eyes can apparently see a diffuse
light given off by hot volcanic springs, around which the creatures
feed by the millions.
</P>
<P>
   The light of the hot vents is far too faint to be detected by
human eyes. But very sensitive cameras on occasion have captured
its eerie glow.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it turns out, human explorers of these dark ecosystems,
working in submersibles equipped with banks of strong floodlights,
may inadvertently be blinding swarms of the shrimps.
</P>
<P>
   A team of three oceanographers in the March 11 issue of the
journal Nature report evidence of blinding among deep-sea shrimp of
two types, Rimicaris exoculata and Mirocaris fortunata. Diving in
the French submersible Nautile, the team collected the shrimp from
two vent sites in the deep Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Close examination of the creatures showed eye damage, at times
severe, and at times with a complete breakdown of eye-pigment
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shrimp swarm over the vent chimneys and are illuminated by
any vehicle working at the active region,'' the team said. ``There
is at present no means of working at the vents without causing this
damage, so every vent population visited will already have been
exposed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The team added that eyes were spared only among ``juvenile
specimens taken by trawling in midwater well above the vents.''
These shrimp would have escaped the floodlights down below.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists reporting the findings are Peter Herring of the
Southampton Oceanography Center in Britain, and Edward Gaten and
Peter Shelton of the University of Leicester.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Lee Van Dover, a deep-sea biologist at the College of
William and Mary in Williamsburg, Va., who has studied the shrimp
and documented the vent glow, said in an interview that such damage
had long been suspected and was worth confirming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know that the shrimp use their eyes,'' she added.
``We've never shown they have a visual response to light. But we
think that they're looking at ambient light from the vents,
probably to keep away from very hot water that would cook them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Van Dover said that submersibles with floodlights and
scientific observers had been diving regularly on the Atlantic
vents since 1985, and that the divers had never found any lessening
of the shrimp populations, despite the repeated illuminations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shrimp are always there,'' she said. ``So the sense is
that the lights haven't blinded them to the point that it's
affecting the population density. Individuals may be having their
eyes damaged, but in terms of the behavior and ecology of the
system, we don't see any effects. If they had all disappeared, we
would have wondered.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the apparent lack of population damage, Dr. Van Dover
said, a move is afoot among deep-sea scientists to protect some
parts of the seabed from further exploration and potential damage
by setting up deep sanctuaries that are off-limits to most
research.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the scientists, she added, have a favorite place that
they are eager to protect and preserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1649EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
