<HEADER>
A1235 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-NURSING-NYT &LR;      03-15 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NURSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOLL OF ILL-CONSIDERED NURSING CUTBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By CLAIRE M. FAGIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When hospitals and other health care agencies started worrying
about pressures from managed care organizations, they brought in
highly paid consultants to help them restructure. Though they
recommended cutbacks in a number of areas, the quick, cookie-cutter
solution for which many firms earned millions was to cut
direct-care nursing staff.
</P>
<P>
   Patients, families and nurses are alarmed about what these cuts
have meant to quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when the American Nurses Association surveyed its
members, 70 percent of all respondents said their employers were
cutting back on staffing by leaving vacant positions unfilled, 66
percent said hospitals had already laid off nurses or were planning
to do so, and 67 percent of registered nurses said the number of
patients assigned to them had increased.
</P>
<P>
   My colleagues and I are hearing from nurses who tell us they are
dealing with ratios of 1 RN to 10 patients on the day shift, 1 to
15 or even 1 to 20 on some shifts. Although designing safe
nurse-patient ratios is complex, these caseloads are unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Restructuring plans have also led to substituting lesser-trained
aides for registered nurses. Training these RN replacements is not
regulated by state licensing boards. There are no minimum
requirements governing the amount of training aides or ``cross
trained'' workers must have before they can be reassigned to do
nursing work.
</P>
<P>
   Training periods generally range from a few hours to perhaps six
weeks. One study cited by the Institute of Medicine report found
that 99 percent of hospitals in California reported less than 120
hours of on-the-job training for newly hired ancillary nursing
personnel. Only 20 percent of the hospitals required a high school
diploma.
</P>
<P>
   What some are calling a race to the bottom of hospital staffing
patterns is occurring in the face of vastly reduced lengths of
hospital stays and increases in the severity of conditions for
which patients are hospitalized. These changes call for a higher
intensity of nursing care, not a lower one.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many consultants do not understand the
complexities involved in caring for the sick and the role nurses
play.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I met a man who had worked for one of the major
consulting companies and who had been involved in a great deal of
hospital restructuring. When he heard I was a nurse, he confessed
sheepishly, ``I am one of the bad guys.'' We talked a bit about the
recommendations he had made in what he described as his ``naive and
dangerous period.'' Then he told me he now felt extremely guilty
because of those recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife had a baby, born prematurely with severe
congenital problems. They spent weeks at the hospital, watching
expert nurses monitoring and responding to the subtle shifts that
occurred in the infant's condition.
</P>
<P>
   The baby survived. But the father told me he now thought back on
his professional interventions in restructuring with horror and
shame.
</P>
<P>
   I do not wish that personal experience on anyone. But it
highlights the fact that health care consultants, policy experts
and administrators ought to get close to those who are close to the
patient before they interfere in a relationship that patients
identify as key to hospital care and quality.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas of the country, managed care has left nurses
unable to find jobs, but other areas are experiencing cyclical
nursing shortages. An aging and retiring nurse work force,
ill-considered cutbacks in staffing and increased needs for
specialized nurses are some of the reasons cited.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news about employment opportunities and working conditions
in hospitals contributed to a drop in enrollment of bachelor's
degree students in the nation's nursing schools of 5.5 percent in
1998. This problem will be exacerbated if expert nursing becomes
even more invisible and women and men are encouraged to abandon
caring roles in favor of more powerful and economically rewarding
roles.
</P>
<P>
   We all have to ask ourselves if the technological assembly line
of care that market-driven health care is creating can provide the
nuances and safeguards that patients need.
</P>
<P>
   Can physicians expect the treatments they prescribe _ often
complex drug regimens, with serious side effects and potential
adverse interactions _ to be successful without nurses to
administer them and monitor patients responses? Can they expect
unskilled caregivers to provide the care their hospitalized
patients require and on which they have come to depend, often
without awareness?
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Baer, a nurse and historian of nursing; Suzanne Gordon, a
journalist, and I have been studying the increasing burden of care
on nurses, patients and family members that has resulted from the
cutbacks of the 1990s. We've concluded that caregiving by
professionals and by families contains within it the possibility of
immense richness and human connection but also the potential for
crushing burdens.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to eliminate the core of responsibility and
obligation that is embedded within the caregiving relationship. If
the caregiver is not morally, emotionally and educationally
prepared, then caregiving becomes an experience of frustration, and
perhaps an act of control.
</P>
<P>
   When even professional caregivers are stressed by impossible
demands and unable to give the care they believe patients need,
their frustrations are inevitably communicated to patients and
families.
</P>
<P>
   Caregiving is defeated when society views care as an individual
obligation that does not require institutional or societal support,
or as an unaffordable luxury, rather than as a vital social
relationship that demands skill, social support, and education.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the scientific knowledge, professional judgment, and
interpersonal and technical skills integral to nurses' clinical
expertise can lead to dangerous outcomes for patients. The health
of our health care system depends on nurses. To demean, diminish,
or eliminate them puts the entire system in jeopardy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
