<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGETABLE OIL FOR DIESEL ENGINES: FROM FRIES TO FUEL  
 FROM JAPAN, SUPERCHARGED RICE  
 GLOBAL TEMPERATURES OR GREENHOUSE GAS: WHICH CAME FIRST? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Idaho, Calif.)  (fb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FROM FRIES TO FUEL
</P>
<P>
   Diesel engines are hardly picky eaters. In addition to
petroleum-based fuel, they will run, relatively cleanly, on just
about any kind of vegetable oil. But a driver cannot simply pour a
bottle of Mazola into the tank. A bit of chemistry has to take
place first.
</P>
<P>
   And there, alas, is the rub. Converting vegetable oil into
diesel fuel takes time, can be done only in batches and creates a
waste water problem.
</P>
<P>
   Now, researchers at the Idaho National Engineering and
Environmental Laboratory, part of the Energy Department, have
developed a technique that streamlines the process and results in
less waste and what should be less expensive fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Like the older technique, it uses an acid or a base to catalyze
the reaction of the oil and an alcohol, producing the diesel fuel
and a byproduct, glycerol. But the acid or base in the new process
is solid, not liquid, remaining separate from the reaction products
and easy to recover. The new process can also run continuously, and
the high quality glycerol produced is valuable in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   For the researchers, who tested the technique on used vegetable
oil from a local producer of french fried potatoes (this being
Idaho, after all), the next step is to create a pilot project. They
foresee a day when a food producer is able to convert its waste oil
into diesel fuel for its trucks.
</P>
<P>
   FROM JAPAN, SUPERCHARGED RICE
</P>
<P>
   It won't power an engine, but a way to give rice more of a kick
for humans in the form of increased iron content has been figured
out by researchers in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Iron deficiency is a serious problem worldwide, particularly for
people whose diet consists mostly of vegetables and grains.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, reporting in the journal Nature Biotechnology,
re-engineered the rice, transplanting a soybean gene responsible
for producing ferritin, a complex compound that stores thousands of
iron atoms in a central cavity. They also found a way to control
production of the ferritin so that it ended up in the endosperm,
the starchy part of the rice grain. The new rice contains up to
three times the iron of ordinary rice, and a meal-sized portion may
provide 30 to 50 percent of the adult daily requirement.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL TEMPERATURES OR GREENHOUSE GAS: WHICH CAME FIRST?
</P>
<P>
   The transition period at the end of an ice age is something of a
dance, where a rise in world temperatures fox-trots with an
increase in the greenhouse gas, carbon dioxide. The question has
always been, which of the partners is leading?
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Scripps Institution of Oceanography at the
University of California at San Diego think they know. Analyzing
the carbon dioxide content in tiny air bubbles trapped in ancient
Antarctic ice, and comparing the results with a temperature record,
they have determined that the warming begins first.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, reporting in the journal Science, studied
transition periods of about 10,000 years at the end of the last
three ice ages, 18,000, 135,000 and 240,000 years ago. They found
that during the ice ages, carbon dioxide concentrations were about
180 to 200 parts per million. As the Earth warmed, the
concentrations increased to 280 parts per million, but lagged
behind the temperature rise by about 400 to 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   The warming, scientists believe, was touched off by changes in
the earth's position relative to the sun. As the warming proceeded,
organisms flourished, producing carbon dioxide through respiration
and decay. The carbon dioxide trapped more heat in the atmosphere
and amplified what would otherwise have been a relatively small
warming.
</P>
<P>
   When the warmer periods ended and temperatures started cooling
again, higher carbon dioxide levels persisted for a shorter or
longer time, depending on the length of the warmer period.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the warm period, the scientists suggest, the more
organisms flourish, and thus the more carbon dioxide there is to
keep the levels high even as temperatures begin dropping again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
