<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER, TWO TEENS REMAIN MISSING IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MODESTO, Calif. _ After exhaustive searches and investigations
in the vicinity of the Yosemite National Park, FBI officials said
they have no hard evidence of what happened to a trio of sightseers
trio or the red Pontiac they were driving.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities believe Carole Sund, 42, her daughter, Julie,
15, and Silvina Pelosso, 16, a friend from Cordoba, Argentina, were
the victims of a violent crime and probably are dead.
</P>
<P>
   The only trace they appear to have left behind is Carole Sund's
wallet, which was found on a street in Modesto, about 80 miles west
of the Yosemite National Park, with the cash missing but credit
cards still inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI said only a miracle could bring them back,'' said
Raquel Pelosso, 43, the mother of Silvina. ``OK, then, I believe in
miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   Carole Sund and the two girls vanished Feb. 15 from the Cedar
Lodge, a restaurant and motel in El Portal on the western edge of
the park.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, dozens of family members and volunteers in
Modesto worked to keep the search efforts alive, organizing a
Sunday vigil to call attention to the many families who have loved
ones who have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the perplexing case of the missing trio has
generated a flood of sympathy and concern from the public in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ``People there are very upset,'' said Raul Guastavino, the
deputy Argentine consul in Los Angeles. ``This is a middle-class
family who sent a teen-age daughter to the United States, a place
we in Argentina perceive as being very safe. Now she's disappeared
under mysterious circumstances. It's a big story.''
</P>
<P>
   Jens Sund, the husband of the missing woman, caused a media
frenzy on Wednesday, when he said the FBI had told him something
that left him ``devastated.'' Despite speculation about a big break
in the case, FBI agents have said they have no suspects in custody
and have not found the victims' bodies or their car.
</P>
<P>
   The families have offered a $250,000 reward for information
leading to their loved ones' safe return and a $50,000 reward for
information leading to the discovery of the car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
