<HEADER>
A1264 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENCEPHALITIS-HNS &LR;      03-15 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCEPHALITIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS TRY TO CRACK MYSTERIES OF ENCEPHALITIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dozens of cases of encephalitis are being
examined in depth at the California Department of Health Services,
where a project funded in part by the federal Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention is trying to find causes for the many cases
of encephalitis that defy explanation.
</P>
<P>
   There are few effective treatments for most cases of
encephalitis, and attempts to control it depend on knowing the
cause, said Jordan Tappero, epidemiological section chief for the
meningitis and special pathogens branch of the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Tappero is among the researchers seeking the causes of
unexplained deaths and serious illness that appear to be
infectious. A significant number of those cases are encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're ever going to develop prevention strategies, we're
going to need to know where these are coming from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Glaser, the doctor who runs the state-CDC encephalitis
project, hopes to construct a clearer picture of the puzzling
syndrome, which strikes about 20,000 Americans each year.
</P>
<P>
   Some patients will respond to drugs, and there are more
medications in development that could help future cases _ once
doctors figure how to diagnose them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't know, you don't know if you're missing something
that is treatable,'' Glaser said.
</P>
<P>
   Encephalitis isn't a disease, but a syndrome triggered by brain
inflammation that can lead to headaches and seizures, personality
changes and the destruction of brain cells. It usually strikes
otherwise healthy people, making it especially heartbreaking in
many instances.
</P>
<P>
   While some people recover completely, many end up with permanent
brain damage, and some die.
</P>
<P>
   Some cases are linked to occasional insect-borne outbreaks, but
most are isolated. With few clues to go on, patients are sometimes
thought to be suffering from epilepsy, having a psychotic break or
overdosing on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Even once encephalitis is diagnosed, doctors usually won't be
able to say why someone lapsed into a coma or began having
seizures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rarely make a definitive diagnosis,'' said James Homans, a
Los Angeles pediatrician specializing in infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The potential culprits are many, including the herpes virus,
which causes cold sores, genital lesions and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Either by direct infection or by setting off the immune system,
it can trigger one of the most destructive forms of encephalitis
that, untreated, kills 70 percent of its victims.
</P>
<P>
   Encephalitis also can be brought on by bacteria, a fungus,
parasite or toxic chemical; a reaction to a vaccine; or even a
delayed immune response to an early childhood sickness.
</P>
<P>
   The patients featured in the film ``Awakenings'' were victims of
an epidemic in the 1920s of encephalitis lethargica, which left
tens of thousands of people with permanent brain damage. Its cause
was never definitively identified, and it was thought to have died
out. But a handful of potential new cases have cropped up in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a flu or other kind of virus already has left the body
when the immune system gears up to attack it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it ends up going after the fatty protective sheath
around the nerves and brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   That is apparently what happened to Debra Caires' son, Jonathan,
four years ago. Two weeks after a bout with the flu, Jonathan, then
5, fell into a deep sleep and later lapsed into a coma. Once a
tidy, disciplined child, he came home from the hospital full of
uncontrolled impulsiveness. He also lost his ability to control his
bowels, and became the object of teasing at school.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Caires was a hospital employee and aspiring medical
student. She begged doctors for medical journal articles she could
read on encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Debra, there is nothing,''' Caires recalled. ``I
said, `You've got to be kidding.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her response was to form the National Encephalitis Foundation in
San Jose, Calif. The organization gets nearly 50,000 visitors a
month on its Web site from frustrated families worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times I just sit on the phone and cry with them. It's
such a horrible thing to go through,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
