<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMOR COLUMNIST FOR THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, March 17)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I trust that you will give more weight to my words now that I
have designated myself the Official Humor Columnist of the New
Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   I am not absolutely sure that some other grasping, covetous,
opportunistic humor columnist in some other dismal backwater (I am
thinking specifically of certain disreputable individuals in
Honolulu and Kansas City) has not already proclaimed himself or
herself Official Humor Columnist of the New Millennium, but as is
the case with most things having to do with the millennium,
ignorance is bliss, so I am claiming the title for myself.
</P>
<P>
   As the Official Humor Columnist of the New Millennium, I'll have
lots of responsibilities, the specific nature of which I presume
will become apparent as time goes on. I'm imagining the job as
being something like Dan Quayle's when he was vice president: You
eat fancy dinners, play a lot of golf, give occasional speeches to
trade groups like the Velcro Manufacturers of Samoa or the
Cranberry League and say as many dumb things as you think are
necessary to preserve the indignity of the office.
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing about being the Official Humor Columnist of the
New Millennium is that it's not an elected office so you can kick
me out and replace me with someone more qualified, like, say, Dan
Quayle. The bad thing about it is that it doesn't come with a big,
fat salary, a fancy house or even Secret Service agents to clear
the road for me when I drive to the 7-Eleven for beer and lottery
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   But what the position lacks in perks I trust it will make up for
in endorsements. Manufacturers of whoopee cushions and rubber
chickens will be among those hurling wads of cash in my direction
in exchange for a 15-second infomercial or perhaps a brief
appearance at a novelty store. It's more than an Ed McMahon
fantasy; imagine if Ed had named himself Official Sidekick of the
New Millennium. That's where I see this thing heading.
</P>
<P>
   I hear what you're saying. You're saying, ``Dave, how can I give
myself an absurd millennium-related trademark and subsequently
asphyxiate under the weight of a mountain of cash?''
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is you'd better get with it, and quick. Thousands
of lazy, greedy individuals such as ourselves have already sought
or received registered trademarks containing the word
``Millennium,'' and ``Year 2000'' and every combination and/or
derivation imaginable for a range of products and services that is
unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy, for example, has already been trademarked as the
Official World Wide Brand of the Millennium. One might think that
would be enough, but Hugh Hefner was never one to think small, so
Playboy is also The Official Entertainment of the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   (I have no idea how Hustler magazine publisher Larry Flynt
missed out on this. Perhaps he was too busy ratting out
congressional philanderers to think that far ahead.)
</P>
<P>
   You can ponder this, if your taste buds have atrophied, by
sipping the Official Beer of the Millennium (Miller), not to be
confused with the Official Beer of Y2K (Coors). I'm not sure what
the Coors people were thinking here, but if I'm in an airplane
flying at 35,000 feet when the Y2K bug strikes at midnight, Dec.
31, I'm going to want something stronger than beer; perhaps some
Beefeater gin, the Official Martini of the Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dechert Price &AMP; Rhoads (Official Humongous Law Firm
of the New Millennium), trademarks have been awarded for the Air
Freshener of the Millennium, the Die-Cast Collectibles of the New
Millennium, Fishing Tackle of the New Millennium and Food for the
New Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Also be on the lookout for Microwave Popcorn for the New
Millennium, Self-Storage for the Millennium, Family TV for the New
Millennium, the Bedliner of the New Millennium, the Toothbrush for
the New Millennium and, of course, the Personal Injury Law Firm of
the New Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be the Official Snorer of the New Millennium or
designate your lawn the Crabgrass Capital of the New Millennium,
the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office (Official Lunatic Federal
Bureaucracy of the New Millennium) is the place you want to
contact.
</P>
<P>
   It costs only $245 to apply for a trademark and spelling doesn't
count. (Nearly 90 people or companies have applied for
``millenium'' with only one ``n.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't even think of trying to become Official Humor
Columnist of the New Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   That baby is mine.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and by the way: If you folks at the U.S. Patent and
Trademark Office haven't gotten my $245 yet, don't worry. My
Official Rubber Check of the New Millennium is in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. This story was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
