<HEADER>
A1266 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-CERVICAL-CANCER-N     03-15 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-CERVICAL-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOW-TECH SCREENING METHOD FOR CERVICAL CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(lh) 
 By NANCY BETH JACKSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cervical cancer, curable if detected early, kills more women in
the developing world than any other cancer for the lack of a
simple, inexpensive and effective screening method. But researchers
in Zimbabwe believe they have found just that, in vinegar, a
trained eye and a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting in the current issue of The Lancet, researchers said
they simply swabbed a woman's cervix with acetic acid (vinegar) and
a minute later looked to see if some cells had turned white, an
indication of the presence of precancerous lesions caused by the
human papilloma virus.
</P>
<P>
   The technique itself is not new. Doctors used it before _ and
sometimes even after _ more sophisticated testing became widely
used in industrialized nations. In those countries, screening for
cervical cancer is done by examination of the cells of the cervix
after a Pap smear has been taken.
</P>
<P>
   But in less developed countries, this kind of screening may not
be available. Researchers estimate that only 5 percent of women in
developing countries are routinely screened for cervical cancer,
compared with 70 percent in industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes the screening program really successful is not the
test itself but the ability to cover a lot of people with the
test,'' Dr. Paul D. Blumenthal, an author of the Lancet paper and
an associate professor of gynecology and obstetrics at Johns
Hopkins University. ``It provides immediate results in
hard-to-reach populations whether in a developing country or in
rural or center-city settings in the industrial world.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, cervical cancer kills 200,000 women each year, mainly
in Africa, Asia and Latin America, said the researchers. In the
United States, the disease led to 4,900 deaths last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the two-phase, cross-sectional study by the University of
Zimbabwe and a nonprofit reproductive health center affiliated with
Johns Hopkins, 10,934 women were screened by nurse-midwives in 15
primary-care clinics around Harare, the capital. Visual assessments
and Pap smears were done in both phases. In the first phase, if the
visual assessment suggested an abnormal condition, the woman
received a colposcopy (a microscopic examination). In the second
phase, all women had the colposcopy. The acetic acid test detected
more than 75 percent of potential cancers, although false-positives
in visual assessments were high in the second phase.
</P>
<P>
   American researchers see little application for the simpler
screenings here, though there are pockets of women who may not be
screened.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Diane Solomon, senior investigator at the National Cancer
Institute, said, ``Most people who advocate the low-tech approach,
advocate it in areas where there is not the infrastructure of
cervical cytology. But I would not like to see a two-tiered
cervical screening system here with low-tech for people who can't
afford high-tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Carr Wright Jr., director of gynecological pathology
at Columbia Presbyterian Hospital, who is working with a similar
project in South Africa, regards the study ``as another test to put
in our packet'' but believes the emphasis in the United States
should be on reducing the cost of the more sophisticated type of
screening.
</P>
<P>
   The human papilloma virus is sexually transmitted and is
sometimes associated with HIV infections. The Zimbabwe researchers
note that cervical cancer is developing at increasingly younger
ages and at a greater rate as the HIV virus damages immunity. The
papilloma virus grows slowly and may appear as warty lesions long
after exposure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1729EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORBES-0316-COX     03-15 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-0316-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FORBES TO SCORE POLITICAL FIRST VIA INTERNET
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) political
 &HT;    with COX-INTERNET-POLITICS
 &HT;    with COX-INTERNET-SITE
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Steve Forbes planned an unprecedented leap into
political cyberspace today by becoming the first presidential
candidate in U.S. history to formally announce his intentions via
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a new, information-age campaign about
great ideas and enduring values,'' Forbes says in a statement to be
delivered live this morning (8:30 a.m. EST) on his campaign
website, http://www.forbes2000.com/.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to run the first full-scale presidential campaign in
American history on the Internet _ because I want you to be
involved every step of the way,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   The closest any other candidate has come to Forbes' Internet
appearance occurred last month when Rep. John Kasich of Ohio
announced the formation of a committee to explore whether he should
run for the GOP nomination. C-SPAN, which provides coverage of
Congress and other public affairs events to cable TV systems around
the country, put Kasich's announcement on its website.
</P>
<P>
   Following his Internet appearance, Forbes planned to travel to
Concord, N.H., for a more traditional announcement of his candidacy
and an interview on America Online, the nation's largest Internet
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' choice of the Internet as his forum underscored the
``Washington outsider'' theme he intends to use in this, his
second, attempt to win the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and I are entering the information age _ and the
Washington politicians are stuck in the Stone Age,'' he says in his
statement. ``The problem is the Washington politicians don't get
it. They're wholly-owned subsidiaries of the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, 52, the multimillionaire head of his family's magazine
publishing business, is feared by some of the other GOP
presidential candidates, largely because of his personal wealth. In
1996, he poured millions into his campaign against Bob Dole for the
party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes is a very serious player because of his money,'' said
Charles Black, an informal adviser to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
the frontrunner for the 2000 GOP nomination. ``He's like a loose
cannon on the deck ... and he's got more cannon balls than anybody
in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes's statement announcing his candidacy for the 2000
nomination invokes the name of former President Ronald Reagan, the
GOP's icon. ``Today marks the beginning of a national crusade to
restore Ronald Reagan's vision of hope and prosperity for all
Americans,'' Forbes says.
</P>
<P>
   But the statement also contrasts slightly with the rhetoric of
his 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Where Forbes pushed a flat tax four years ago, in his statement
today he is a bit more vague, calling simply for ``an honest,
simple tax code for a new century _ one that will put real money
back into the pockets of working families.''
</P>
<P>
   And where he largely avoided the issue of abortion in 1996, he
suggests today that ``the establishment politicians'' should not be
trusted to ``protect the first and most important freedom of every
child - the freedom to be born.''
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding any mention of his Republican opponents by name, Forbes
takes a couple of jabs at President Clinton and Vice President Al
Gore, the frontrunner for the 2000 Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He says the Clinton-Gore administration is ``raiding'' Social
Security funds ``to pay for more big government spending.'' And he
vows that as president he would ``clean out the corruption and
sleaze'' of the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   He also promises more parental control of schools, more freedom
to choose doctors and medical specialists and more economic
opportunity. ``It's time to give every American the freedom to
participate in this new era of prosperity,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes adds that he also would seek to ``confront the atrocities
in China, end Saddam Hussein's reign of terror and deploy a
realistic missile defense system'' for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Although he offers no specific proposals, Forbes also says
America's foreign policy must address the global economic crisis
and its affect on American farmers and steel producers. ``America
cannot afford to be an island of prosperity in an ocean of
poverty,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
