<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, March 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow fell in the mountains east of Los Angeles early Monday at
elevations as low as 1,500 feet as a cold upper-level low-pressure
system came slowly ashore from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated thunderstorms will develop Tuesday across parts of
Arizona and New Mexico as the lofty low drifts overhead. Isolated
thunderstorms are also possible across the high deserts of
southeast California. Snow will accumulate above 5,000 feet in
parts of the northern Arizona Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   East of the lethargic low, unseasonably warm weather will
embrace much of the Plains as a warm ridge of high pressure builds
northward from Texas. Temperatures may reach 70 degrees as far
north as Nebraska Tuesday afternoon, save for parts of Oklahoma,
Kansas and Missouri, where vestiges of snow left in the wake of the
storm that struck last week reflect and deplete warming rays of the
sun. The warm spell will be short-lived across the Plains, however,
as a cold front arrives Wednesday. In response, the seat of warmth
will shift to the Gulf Coast and Southeast states.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the heavy snow that blanketed parts of northern
New England Monday, a few areas of light snow will gradually
diminish over northern Maine as the culprit low-pressure system
moves over the Canadian Maritimes. Gusty winds from the northwest
averaging 20 to 30 miles per hour along the New England Seaboard,
will start to ease from Cape Cod northward. As the low over the
Canadian Maritimes lifts northeast Wednesday, milder air from the
south will begin to arrive in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Snail's Pace
</P>
<P>
   Up to 10 inches of snow fell in the mountains of Santa Barbara
and Ventura counties of Southern California early Monday. Snow
continued into the afternoon as a cold, upper-level low-pressure
system pressed sluggishly eastward. Slow-moving upper-level lows
are a hallmark of spring weather patterns over the southern-tier
states. With the main branch of the steering winds of the jet
stream having typically retreated toward Canada, potent
disturbances, which might otherwise dislodge floundering
upper-level lows, pass by far to the north, allowing the low's
snail's pace to continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1733EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
