<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-STATES-HNS &LR;      03-15 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-STATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES SEEK TO PROTECT TOBACCO SETTLEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Pennsylvania, Kentucky, Texas)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Attorney General John Cornyn joined officials
from other states Monday in protesting a federal proposal to recoup
Medicaid costs from the $246 billion in settlements the tobacco
industry has reached with the states.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said federal claims on Texas' $17.3 billion settlement
should be dismissed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair, it's not the law, and this committee should
reject it,'' Cornyn told the Senate Appropriations subcommittee on
health and human services.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, a Republican, joined Kentucky Gov. Paul Patton, a
Democrat, and attorneys general from Iowa and Pennsylvania in
supporting an amendment by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, that
would block federal attempts to take a portion of the tobacco
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment could be heard as early as this week when the
Senate takes up a supplemental spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   The states have reached out-of-court settlements with tobacco
companies in an effort to recover the costs of tobacco-related
illnesses paid through Medicaid, the federal-state health insurance
program for the need, disabled and low-income families with
children.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said a majority in the Senate favor
an administration compromise that would drop reimbursement of
Medicaid expenses if the states agree to spending 25 percent of
their settlements on anti-smoking and cessation programs aimed at
young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not for turning over all the money, carte blanche, to the
states,'' said Specter, the subcommittee chairman, who wants ``some
assurances'' that states spend a significant portion to curb
smoking among teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchison argued that the states have negotiated the
settlements without help from the administration or Congress, and
should now be free to spend the funds as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the states' money, and I don't think they need strings on
it,'' said Hutchison, whose bill has attracted 44 co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the nation's governors said one of their priorities
this year would be to protect the tobacco settlements from the
Health Care Financing Administration, the federal agency seeking
Medicaid reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton proposed waiving the federal government's
reimbursement claim, if the states agreed to spend a portion of the
money on various anti-smoking programs.
</P>
<P>
   The issue could come before the entire Senate later this week
when it considers a supplemental spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison expects to move forward with her bill to block the
federal government from taking a 57-percent cut of the settlement _
its share of federal-state Medicaid payment formulas _ or imposing
regulations on how the states can spend their funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep from dictating to the states what they can
do with the money that they won fair and square,'' Hutchison told
Mike Hash, deputy administrator for the Health Care Financing
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Texas settled last year with the tobacco companies for $17.3
billion, to be paid over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the state would set aside $2.3 billion to compensate
counties and rural hospital districts for unreimbursed health care
costs. In addition, the state plans to spend $881 million for a
number of health-related programs, including the creation of a $200
million children's cancer ward at the University of Texas Health
Science Center in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the money the state has received so far has been
earmarked for health-related expenditure,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
