<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OLY-IOC-MEETING _ LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ Coverage of IOC
meetings, where the future of implicated IOC members in the Salt
Lake scandal _ and possibly the future of the committee itself and
its president _ are at stake. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/OLY-IOC-GANGA _ Jean Claude Ganga says Atlanta did not buy his
vote for the '96 Games, saying he made up his mind before the gifts
from Andy Young came. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both stories moving in the (i) International categories and
(s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-MISSING _ MIAMI _ A United Nations helicopter with 13
people on board was missing in Haiti Monday. The helicopter,
missing since Sunday night, comes in the wake of last week's
statement by the head of the U.S. Southern Command that he is
considering pulling 500-member U.S. support team out of the poor
island nation. Developing. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   FORBES _ WASHINGTON _ Steve Forbes plans to announce his
candidacy for the Republican presidential nomination Tuesday on the
Internet, becoming the first candidate to do so in cyberspace. A
story on the substance of the Forbes announcement, based on text of
his statement. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   w/INTERNET-POLITICS _ WASHINGTON _ The Internet, barely a factor
in '96, has now become a major tool for the presidential campaigns.
(Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SITE _WASHINGTON _ List of major political Internet
sites. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO _ WASHINGTON _ Attorneys general from Texas and other
states testify before a Senate Appropriations subcommittee in
support of legislation that would protect state tobacco settlement
money from being recovered from the federal government. (Malone,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-COWBOY _ WASHINGTON _ Sara Davidson, graduate of Berkeley
and Columbia and author of the best-selling novel ``Loose Change,''
was a screenwriter for the TV show ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman''
when she fell in love with a cowboy. She was writing a piece on
cowboy poetry for the New York Times Magazine (''Git Along Little
Doggerel'') when a lanky cowpoke in a tan stetson and baby-blue
boots two-stepped off with her heart. She's 50, the divorced mother
of two teen-agers, and he's more than 10 years younger and earns a
meager living braiding rawhide doo-dads, but they're still together
five years later. Now she's written a book, ``Cowboy: A Love
Story,'' about the experience. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLELAND _ WASHINGTON _ For 31 years, Max Cleland has believed
his own mistake caused the grenade explosion that cost him both
legs an arm in Vietnam. But now, a former Marine corporal claims he
treated another soldier that day who was sobbing uncontrollably:
``It was my grenade, it was my grenade.'' (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE _ ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ Investigators have not rejected a
possible connection between the weekend bombing at an abortion
clinic here and serial bombing suspect Eric Rudolph. But U.S.
Attorney Mark Calloway also said today they have not pointed to
Rudolph as a primary suspect. (Burritt, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-KIDSINSURANCE _ AUSTIN, Texas _Gov. George W. Bush, who
earned accolades from Mexican-American groups for extending food
stamps to elderly immigrants, even if they're illegal, says he
won't support health insurance for children who entered the U.S.
illegally after 1996. This is sure to cause people to question the
governor's ``conservative compassion.'' (Greenberger, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MINISTRY _ Following up on last year's pastoral letter, the
Archdiocese of Cincinnati announces three gay ministries. (Lyles,
Dayton Daily News). 8-10.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MILITARY _ According to the Servicemen legal defense group,
30 people were discharged from Georgia's military bases over the
last year for being homosexual. Since the don't ask, don't tell
policy took effect five years ago, Fort Benning alone has dismissed
50 people for being gay, making it one of the least tolerant bases
in the country. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CONNERLY _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A Q&AMP;A with Ward Connerly, who brought
his anti-affirmative action push to Texas. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
