<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-Y2K-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS CONSIDERS Y2K LIABILITY LEGISLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., S.C. )  (fb) 
 BY SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the millennium just a few pages of the
calendar away, lawmakers have caught the Y2K bug, looking for ways
to help businesses stave off potential computer problems and also
limit what could be a wave of costly litigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, House members and senators stand to benefit from
a windfall of campaign contributions as computer companies, trial
lawyers, high-tech firms and small-business owners step up their
presence on Capitol Hill and battle over who is to blame should
computers crash when 2000 rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there's a lot at stake with Y2K legislation and
everybody wants to get an edge,'' said Holly Bailey, a researcher
at the Center for Responsive Politics, which tracks the flow of
money on Capitol Hill and in campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The potential millennium problem stems from the fact that most
computer programs read the last two digits of a year to register
the date. That means that 2000 could be read as 1900, throwing
various time-sensitive data banks into disarray.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, lawmakers have rallied around efforts to give
small-business owners low-interest loans so they can find solutions
to the feared computer bug. One bill even calls for a one-time
national holiday on Monday, Jan. 3, 2000, so corporate America
would have one more day to work on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of liability has emerged as the most
contentious issue of the Y2K debate. Big business wants Congress to
pass a bill that limits the amount of damages anyone could collect
because of a Y2K glitch.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, John McCain, R-Ariz., is pushing the Y2K Act, a
bill, strongly supported by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, that does
just that. The Commerce Committee, which he chairs, recently
approved his bill on a party-line vote. Other bills would limit the
amount of money attorneys could collect in any lawsuits stemming
from the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Trial Lawyers of America opposes such legal
limits, and a nasty battle is brewing.
</P>
<P>
   Each side accuses the other of greed and selfishness. Corporate
executives describe lawyers as opportunists looking to cash in on a
costly problem, while trial attorneys say big business is just
trying to avoid responsibility for a problem it could have avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wooten, executive director of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce's
Institute for Legal Reform, predicted that there would be a
``litigation explosion'' with businesses suing each other, and
consumers dragging companies into court unless Congress acts to put
some limits in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race to the courthouse will begin,'' Wooten predicted.
</P>
<P>
   To which, Mark Mandell, president of the Association of Trial
Lawyers of America, said, in effect, so what.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely astounding that these people can create a
crisis out of their own wrongdoing,'' Mandell said, noting that the
potential of a Y2K glitch has been known for years. ``And instead
of fixing it, they're trying to deny people their rights ... Why
should they be immune from lawsuits?''
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers did not help their image, however, at a recent
annual convention of the American Bar Association where some
members spoke enthusiastically about the business opportunities the
Y2K problem could provide.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Clinton administration and many Democrats opposed the
idea of providing any sort of immunity to the business community.
They argue it would set a bad precedent and discourage companies
from fixing potential computer problems.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., the top Democrat on the Commerce
Committee, described McCain's bill as ``little more than an effort
to protect big businesses from their responsibility to ensure that
their products work on Jan. 1, 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   In this legislative fight, attorneys and businesses will not
weigh in only with words, however. Through political action
committees and individuals, business interests and the legal
community have long contributed to congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, trial attorneys and high-tech companies have
favored Democrats, while corporate America has long been a strong
donor base for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Responsive Politics, computer
companies donated $8.8 million to political parties and candidates
during the 1997-98 election cycle, more than doubling what they
gave in the last midterm elections. The Association of Trial
Lawyers of America donated $2.4 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   If past is prologue, both sides are expected to increase their
donations as Congress considers legislation with costly
implications for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is a correspondent in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
