<HEADLINE>
DON'T MISS OUT ON CHILD TAX CREDIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internal Revenue Service has been getting the word out that
many taxpayers are missing a tax break _ the new child tax credit _
that could sharply cut their tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   That's good advice. If you qualify for this break, which applies
if you support a child, grandchild, stepchild, adopted child or
foster child who is under age 17, it can mean a credit of up to
$400 per child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very straightforward for the vast majority of
taxpayers,'' said Henry Holmes, spokesman for the Internal Revenue
Service in Houston. ``It's when you get to the higher income and
lower income levels where the confusion sets in.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that the IRS is changing a number of returns where
taxpayers failed to claim this tax break shows there is a lot of
confusion. A lot of people may be missing this new break because
they confuse it with the child and dependent care credit.
</P>
<P>
   The child and dependent care credit applies to expenses you
incur in caring for your child, such as day care. The new child tax
credit doesn't require any spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child tax credit is something you're entitled to, simply
by virtue of having the child,'' said Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   To get the child tax credit, you must file a 1040 or 1040A tax
form.
</P>
<P>
   You should indicate on the front of the 1040 or 1040A form that
you have a dependent who was under age 17 at the end of 1998. You
enter that information on line 6c of both the 1040 and 1040A forms.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to include the Social Security number of each
qualifying child on the return. You need this because the break
only applies if the child is a U.S. citizen or resident.
</P>
<P>
   The credit begins to phase out when your income is $75,000 for a
single taxpayer, or $110,000 for couples filing a joint return. To
calculate the credit, use the Child Tax Credit worksheet. You don't
have to submit this form with your tax return, but keep it for your
records.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the credit amount on line 43 of the 1040 form or line 28
of the 1040A form.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LAW HAS SOME TWISTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As always, this new tax law comes with some twists.
</P>
<P>
   If you have two children or fewer, you won't be able to claim
the child tax credit if you don't owe any tax for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if the credit is larger than your annual tax liability,
your credit is limited to your total tax unless you have more than
two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most taxpayers are going to multiply the number of qualifying
children they have and get the full credit for that amount,''
Holmes said. ``Where the wrinkles come in is if your income exceeds
a certain amount. Then you have to do some additional computation
to figure out the reduction of your credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is a tax credit, which is better than a tax
deduction because it reduces your tax liability on a
dollar-for-dollar basis. A deduction reduces the amount of income
that is subject to taxation. That means if you're in the 28 percent
tax bracket, for every $100 you can deduct, you're saving $28 in
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit can't be larger than your total tax bill for the
year. ``A taxpayer with two children and a tax liability of $500
would only qualify for a $500 child tax credit,'' Holmes said. ``If
this same taxpayer had no tax liability, he would not qualify for
any child tax credit.''
</P>
<P>
   This limit does not apply if you have more than two children.
Then, your tax credit can exceed your tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress figures if you've got families out there who are
low-income and they've got three children, they need extra relief,
more so than that family with just two children,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DO YOU QUALIFY? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To determine whether you can get the additional credit, you must
complete child tax credit worksheets in the instruction packet that
came with the 1040 and 1040A forms. You also must complete form
8812, called Additional Child Tax Credit, and attach it to your
1040 or 1040A form.
</P>
<P>
   If you have an additional credit on line 11 of form 8812, carry
it to line 60 of the 1040 form or line 38 of the 1040A form.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Social Security (tax) payments will increase the amount
of child tax credit, but high earned-income tax credit will
decrease the amount of child tax credit,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, the IRS really wants you to get this credit
if you qualify.
</P>
<P>
   If the IRS can verify the ages of your children through their
Social Security numbers, it will calculate the credit for you and
send you a refund check.
</P>
<P>
   But if the IRS can't verify the ages of your children, it will
send you a notice telling you that you may qualify for the child
tax credit and to file an amended return to claim the tax break.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
