<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ZHU-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE LEADER PREDICTS CONTINUED COOPERATION WITH U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Less than a month before he leaves for a state visit
to the United States, China's blunt-speaking prime minister, Zhu
Rongji, laid out his agenda Monday for what promises to be a
turbulent trip, saying the two nations would continue to cooperate
despite renewed friction on issues ranging from human rights to
charges that China stole nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it will not be easy for me to go to the United
States in such an atmosphere,'' Zhu said at a news conference. But
he quickly added: ``My goal is to let you vent your anger and
complaints and to tell you the truth. And to regain the momentum of
building a strategic partnership between China and the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   In an unscripted 90-minute meeting with reporters after the
adjournment of China's Parliament, Zhu covered a range of topics
including his country's plans to further open its markets, the
arrest of pro-democracy advocates, and China's unyielding
opposition to a proposed regional missile-defense system that could
potentially include Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   None of the positions presented by Zhu were entirely new,
although some fresh tidbits were offered, like China's willingness
to relax restrictions on foreign investment in its banking sector.
More important, the news conference was the first time that many
positions had been stated directly by one of China's top leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And Zhu's matter-of-fact style made the many serious conflicts
percolating between the two nations seem more like spats between
old friends.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six weeks, the U.S. Congress has accused China of
stealing American nuclear secrets, trying to smuggle military
hardware out of the United States and violating a U.N. Human Rights
Covenant it signed just last year.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu acknowledged that relations between Beijing and Washington
had lost ``momentum'' since President Clinton's ebullient state
visit to China last summer.
</P>
<P>
   But his underlying theme, that the two nations could cooperate
despite their considerable differences, echoed that of Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright when she visited Beijing last month. And
in general, Zhu's statements were more measured than recent Chinese
government pronouncements, which have lambasted the United States
as ``hypocritical'' on human rights and denounced spying charges as
fabrications by enemies of China.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference was broadcast live, just after China's
Parliament approved a host of reports and constitutional amendments
sponsored by the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   While Parliament inevitably passes such motions by huge margins,
debates at committee meetings have become increasingly lively. And
this year's meeting provided some unusual excitement as two
government reports on China's legal system presented a frank
picture of widespread abuse and corruption. A constitutional
amendment that elevated the status of the private sector was at
least a symbolic victory for China's emerging business class.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Zhu's meeting with reporters that carried the day.
Zhu is regarded here as the chief sponsor of China's most recent
wave of economic reforms. But Monday's session provided a glimpse
of how he handles foreign relations, less familiar waters that he
will have to navigate in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu scoffed at the spying charges that have riveted both the
U.S. Congress and media: that a Taiwan-born scientist passed on
secret information enabling China to modernize its nuclear arsenal.
The charges both underestimate the American government's ability to
keep secrets and Chinese scientists' ability to make discoveries,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is fully capable of developing any military
technology,'' he said. ``It's only a matter of time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said the charges had grown out of ``internal struggles in the
United States.'' Evoking the McCarthy era in the United States and
China's Cultural Revolution, he added that both countries had known
``periods where everyone was afraid of being accused by everyone
else, and we should never forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's mood turned more serious as he discussed proposals for the
United States and Japan to build a missile defense system for East
Asia that might eventually include Taiwan. He dismissed American
news reports that China has 600 missiles trained on Taiwan. ``How
could they know that?'' he said. ``Even I don't know that!''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years after Chinese Nationalist forces fled to Taiwan,
Beijing still regards the island as a renegade province and
American military aid there as interference in China's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu also rehearsed answers to the human rights questions that
will certainly come up during next month's trip. Although Chinese
officials have long insisted that human rights policies are
strictly internal affairs, Zhu expressed what appears to be at
least a superficial willingness to hear opposing views.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome foreign friends to criticize us in our work, but
don't be impatient,'' he said, noting that he has grown accustomed
to ``friends from abroad pulling out lists'' of pro-democracy
activists whom they want released from jail.
</P>
<P>
   But as Zhu briefly lit into such activists Monday, it was clear
that the two sides shared little common ground.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu was clearly most at home when the talk returned to economic
policy, where he reiterated that the government would not devalue
its currency and would no longer prop up insolvent companies.
</P>
<P>
   He talked of China's renewed eagerness to get into the World
Trade Organization this year. American and Chinese officials are
now negotiating furiously to this end, in the hopes that even a
embryonic deal will provide a happy note to what many expect could
be a dissonant visit to America.
</P>
<P>
   To this end, Zhu suggested that China would now be willing to
open its telecommunications and banking sectors somewhat to gain
admission _ a tantalizing prospect for foreign investors _ though
he refused to go into details.
</P>
<P>
   He said that after years of discussion, the two sides had
recently made substantial progress, although differences remained.
``The black hair has turned gray, and it's time to conclude these
negotiations,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
