<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-IRISH-REVIEW-ART-N     03-15 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-IRISH-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IRISH EYES ARE SMILING AND NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, with St. Patrick's Day on Wednesday you may be yearning to
make some wee connection, searching the closet for that Kelly green
necktie or trying to remember the lyrics to ``Did Your Mother Come
From Ireland?'' But even if your mother (italics)did(end italics)
come from Ireland, your authenticity credentials may pale beside
those of the McCourt brothers, New York's reigning jacks of
heartstrings.
</P>
<P>
   Frank McCourt laid out his family's moving story in the Pulitzer
Prize-winning memoir ``Angela's Ashes.'' His brother Malachy had
his own tale to tell in ``A Monk Swimming.'' A revival of the
brothers' autobiographical theater piece, ``A Couple of
Blaguards,'' is currently running in Manhattan. And Tuesday night
brings two opportunities to visit the melancholy McCourts via
television.
</P>
<P>
   Cinemax is presenting a documentary, ``The McCourts of New
York,'' directed by Malachy's son Conor. Public television
stations, including WNET in New York, are showing ``The Irish ...
and How They Got That Way,'' Frank's hybrid of revue and history
lesson that ran and ran at the Irish Repertory Theater in Chelsea.
Both have an amateur quality that may tax the viewer's patience.
But both come wrapped in the earnest McCourt charm.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have not read the books or seen ``The McCourts of
Limerick,'' Conor McCourt's earlier film about the brothers' youth,
the documentary will introduce these sons of the long-suffering
Angela McCourt, a woman burdened by a heartless husband and haunted
by the death of an infant daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, born in New York but reared in his parents' native
Ireland, returned to America alone at 19 and became a teacher and
writer. Malachy came next, becoming, among other things, an actor
and the host at a Manhattan bar. In their shadow dwelt two more
brothers, Mike, who once tended bar for Malachy, and Alphie, who
came over with their mother in 1959. She died in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   All four men, whose weathered faces define the phrase ``sadder
but wiser,'' share their memories in scenes that sound like
psychotherapy sessions and look like home video, shot in the United
States, Ireland and India, where Malachy gleefully retraces the
steps of a gold smuggling caper he survived between careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we're doing this,'' Frank says of
re-exploring the past, ``when most people are content to let it
be.'' They go back anyway, with occasional glimpses of snapshots to
prove that the brothers once were younger and slimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Their lives were all tinged with pain, much of it associated
with alcohol, one of the demons that gripped their detested father,
also named Malachy. ``The booze got in the way,'' says Mike, who
lost his job behind the bar when ``I began to be too much of a good
customer.''
</P>
<P>
   One piece of family history does unfold movingly before the
camera. The four brothers, along with members of the family's later
generations, make a pilgrimage to the pauper's grave in Queens
where baby Mary Margaret McCourt was buried in the 1930s. The four
white-haired men place a marker with her name and slip a shard of
their mother's bone into the soil, reuniting mother and daughter, a
sad duty of these survivors, battered but standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering what we came from,'' Frank says about his family,
``we haven't done so badly at all.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have been talking about all his countrymen in America,
which is what he did in ``The Irish ... and How They Got That
Way.'' But while his book elevated life's daily trials to the level
of the historic, his stage show reduces the sweep of history to the
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   The show is an often angry history lecture with songs, delivered
by an attractive, energetic cast of six. The anger is well earned.
The Irish, so badly treated by the English, were hardly welcomed to
their new country:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Irish came to America, one 19th-century immigrant
observed, because they thought that the streets were paved with
gold. But when we got here, we found out that not only weren't they
paved with gold, they weren't paved at all. Furthermore we were
expected to pave them, which we did.''
</P>
<P>
   All this is leavened with a little humor (an Irishman's marriage
proposal: ``Mary, how'd you like to be buried with my people?'')
and lots of familiar music, including the tenor Ciaran Sheehan's
lovely if inevitable performance of ``Danny Boy.'' But the glib
message that the Irish suffered and died so the world could have
George M. Cohan, James Cagney and John F. Kennedy doesn't do
justice to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The production was videotaped at the Irish Rep with its original
cast. The camera cannot capture the live show's intimacy; the stage
lighting and stagey gestures and speeches do not translate well to
video. Still, there is plenty of heart here, and it does come
through. And if Frank McCourt remains more teacher than showman, he
does support his show's thesis, ``It's not easy being Irish.''
Nothing worth being ever is. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE McCOURTS OF NEW YORK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cinemax, Tuesday night at 6:30 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chris Vroom, executive producer; Conor McCourt and Laurie Gwen
Shapiro, producers; Conor McCourt, director. For Romeo and Juliet
productions: Juliet McCourt, executive producer. For Cinemax:
Sheila Nevins, executive producer; Jacqueline Glover, producer.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE IRISH ... AND HOW THEY GOT THAT WAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 8) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Macken, producer and director. For the Irish Repertory
Theatre: Charlotte Moore, director; Shawn Lewis, set designer; Dan
Walker, lighting designer; David Toser, costume designer; Axexia
Hess Sheehan, choreographer; Bob Green and Rusty Magee, music. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
