<SLUG> BC-INDIA-JAYARAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN POLITICIAN CHARGED WITH ATTACK ON ACCOUNTANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By BARRY BEARAK    c. 1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Jayalalitha Jayaram, the former movie star
who is one of India's most politically powerful and dependably
outlandish figures, faced charges Monday that she had thrashed her
former accountant with high-heel shoes, beating him black and blue
during an hourlong ordeal and leaving him bedridden with a bandaged
right eye.
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha, as she is known here, denies that any such attack
took place. ``I am too cultured to indulge in such an uncivilized
act,'' she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   She sent flowers to the hospitalized auditor, R. Rajasekaran,
who refused the bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials say they are investigating the incident, said
to have occurred in Jayalalitha's elegant residence in Madras on
March 13.
</P>
<P>
   True or not, Rajasekaran's bizarre story was front-page news
Monday in India _ a grand entertainment for some and an acute
embarrassment for others.
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha heads the All India Anna Dravida Munetra Kazhagam,
the political party that is the largest coalition partner of the
Hindu nationalists who lead the government.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the government have frequently had to mollify
Jayalalitha during her many threats to abandon the coalition. They,
in turn, have come under severe criticism for what some here view
as improper efforts to help her escape from numerous criminal
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the government transferred various corruption cases
against the former actress away from the special state courts that
had been handling them.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from the early 1990s, when Jayalalitha was
chief minister of the state of Tamil Nadu. During that time she
reportedly accumulated a fortune through kickback schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Usually clad in a flowing cape, Jayalalitha is known for
ostentatious displays of wealth and a large appetite for fealty.
Followers often bow when greeting her. Campaign posters have
portrayed her as a Hindu goddess. She is feared.
</P>
<P>
   And Rajasekaran is among the fearful. ``They threatened to kill
me if I spoke up,'' the injured man anxiously told reporters at his
bedside.
</P>
<P>
   He had been Jayalalitha's accountant for 10 years until they had
a falling-out in 1997, he explained. He said he was surprised to be
summoned to her residence on Saturday, where the former chief
minister met him along with her long-time companion, Sasikala
Natarajan, and Ms. Natarajan's nephew, M. Mahadevan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Sasikala came into the room, she bolted the door from
inside and took two shoes with high heels from a plastic bag,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The women hammered at him with the spiked shoes while Mahadevan
used a stick. ``Unable to bear the pain, I cried for mercy,'' the
accountant said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeling from the assault, with hands swollen from the blows,
Rajasekaran was then made to write and sign statements that
admitted his responsibility for lapses in the two women's tax
returns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In her statement, Jayalalitha called the allegations a complete
lie intended to disparage her. She said she suspects that her
political arch-rival, Tamil Nadu's current chief minister, Muthuvel
Karunanidhi, was behind this ``sinister conspiracy''
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha's supporters Monday demanded the right to stage a
protest in the Lok Sabha, the lower house of India's Parliament.
When refused the floor, they angrily walked out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
