A1284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-15 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CAN DO MORE TO FIGHT DRUNKEN DRIVING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ One of the most emotional issues in any
legislative session is the fight against drunken driving, and this
year's chapter started unfolding last week.
</P>
<P>
   Photos of four teen-age girls, who died Dec. 19 after a pickup
crashed into their car in North Texas, lined a table at the front
of the Senate chamber.
</P>
<P>
   So did their grieving parents and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, all
making a strong pitch for legislation to lower the legal
intoxication limit for drivers from .10 percent to .08 percent
blood alcohol content.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, a Senate committee unanimously approved the
bill, which also is strongly supported by Gov. George W. Bush and
will likely become law this session.
</P>
<P>
   Would the proposed law have saved the four girls' lives? Nobody
knows for sure, but an argument can be made _ and opponents of the
bill certainly are making it _ that it probably wouldn't have.
That's because the driver of the pickup, who faces charges of
intoxication manslaughter, allegedly had a blood alcohol content
exceeding the more permissible .10 percent when the wreck occurred.
</P>
<P>
   But that argument misses the point. The point is that drunken
driving still produces multiple tragedies in Texas, and the
Legislature can do more to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Lowering the intoxication limit is an important step. So is a
proposal to ban open containers of alcohol from motor vehicles, a
perennial bill that also may have a reasonable shot at winning
lawmakers' approval this year.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the tougher laws may argue that it is unrealistic
or just flat wrong for the Legislature to try to regulate personal
behavior. But no one has an unfettered right to operate a motor
vehicle on public streets and highways. If people did, the courts
would have thrown out driver's license and insurance requirements _
and even speed limits _ a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   Government has a responsibility, within constitutional limits,
to safeguard the public safety, and laws against driving while
intoxicated are part of that responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol-related auto deaths have generally been decreasing in
recent years, in part because of tougher penalties imposed by
lawmakers and public awareness campaigns by groups such as Mothers
Against Drunk Driving, or MADD. Improved safety features in cars
and on highways also may have contributed.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas remains a problem state. Some 1,748 people were killed
in alcohol-related crashes in Texas in 1997, the last year for
which complete data are available. Not all those accidents were
actually caused by drunken drivers, but many were.
</P>
<P>
   Helping lead the fight against the lower intoxication limit is
the American Beverage Institute, a trade association of the
restaurant industry, whose members fear that they will sell fewer
drinks and lose money wherever the .08 limit is imposed.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement distributed in Austin, Rick Berman, a
lawyer for the institute, said .08 laws, which 16 other states
already have, don't work because they merely punish ``responsible
social drinkers'' who usually aren't involved in fatal auto
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that most alcohol-related fatalities involve drivers
with blood alcohol contents of .10 or higher. But a scientific
study of traffic deaths in California, Maine, Oregon, Utah and
Vermont _ the first five states to lower their intoxication limit
to .08 _ showed that the law does work.
</P>
<P>
   According to that study, those five states had an overall
reduction of 16 percent in the proportion of crashes with a fatally
injured driver whose blood alcohol content was .08 or higher and an
18 percent reduction in crashes with a fatally injured driver whose
blood alcohol content was .15 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Tougher DWI laws won't keep problem drinkers and irresponsible
drivers from getting behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   But, despite the restaurant industry's protest, ``responsible''
people don't knowingly violate the law. And if a .08 limit would
make a motorist think twice before ordering that extra drink, so
much the better for that person and everyone else he or she may
encounter on the road while driving home.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, the Legislature enacted a law to ban drinking
while driving in Texas. But it is extremely difficult to enforce
because a police officer actually has to observe a driver drinking
alcohol. And their jobs haven't been made any easier by convenience
stores that provide a brown paper bag to customers who purchase a
single can of beer.
</P>
<P>
   A law banning open containers of alcohol from the entire
passenger compartment of a vehicle, which also is pending before
lawmakers, may or may not reduce traffic deaths, but it is worth a
try.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a popular misperception to the contrary, a motorist
doesn't have a constitutional right to drink a beer on the way home
from work, and neither does his or her passengers.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to crack down on drunken drivers after they have
killed people, but it is more important to try to prevent tragedies
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
