</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN'S FILMMAKERS ON THE VERGE OF A CIVILITY BREAKDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 BY AL GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ When ``The Grandfather'' won an Oscar nomination
last month as best foreign-language film, there was a sense of
vindication for its director, Jose Luis Garci, who has been locked
in a nasty credibility battle with Spain's film establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Garci, who won a foreign-film Oscar in 1983 for ``Begin the
Beguine,'' has attacked the leaders of the Spanish film academy as
``fascist'' for not fully clearing his name after allegations of a
vote-buying scheme for Spain's top film awards, the Goyas.
</P>
<P>
   An anonymous letter was sent in December to most of the 771
voting members of the Spanish Academy of Cinematic Arts and
Sciences saying that Garci's aides would personally collect the
ballots, which are supposed to be mailed directly to a Madrid
notary. Garci has denied any connection to the letter.
</P>
<P>
   It is the biggest scandal ever for Garci and for the 13-year-old
Spanish academy, which some industry veterans regard as a clubby
institution whose members have more than once snubbed
internationally known Spanish directors like Pedro Almodovar.
</P>
<P>
   The academy insisted in two communiques in January that the
matter was settled when no proof emerged of vote buying or improper
back-room pressure to win votes. The academy dropped the matter,
although its president agreed to consider a stricter code of ethics
on voting.
</P>
<P>
   But for Garci that was not enough, and he abruptly quit the
academy before its Jan. 23 awards ceremony here. ``The
Grandfather'' won just one Goya statuette, for best actor, after
being nominated in 13 categories, including best picture and best
director.
</P>
<P>
   Garci said the results demonstrated that he did not buy votes.
His lawyers are seeking a more definitive statement from the
academy absolving him of any misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can play with a person's honor,'' said
Garci, 55, a compact, dark-haired man. ``I want a full reparation
of the damage, and I hope to get it soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Garci and others said that fierce commercial pressures, and
perhaps pure envy, may have inspired the anonymous letter.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal arose after the Spanish film industry had reached
cruising speed, with high-quality movies and wide popularity after
years of hard work. In 1997, Spanish moviegoers bought some 13
million tickets to domestic films, accounting for $52 million in
box-office receipts, roughly double the numbers from a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Grandfather,'' the story of an aristocrat's search to
discover which of his two putative granddaughters resulted from an
extramarital affair by his daughter-in-law, got off to a good start
in October when Spain's academy designated it for a foreign Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   It then became one of the American academy's foreign finalists,
an honor that Garci has now achieved with four of his films, more
than any other Spanish director.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in December, the Spanish academy announced the finalists
for its Goyas, and ``The Grandfather'' was second in nominations
behind ``The Girl of Your Dreams,'' by Fernando Trueba. He is the
only Spanish director besides Garci to have won a foreign Oscar,
for ``Belle Epoque,'' in 1994. (The Spanish director Luis Bunuel
won in 1972 for ``The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie,'' but as a
nominee from France, where he lived in exile.)
</P>
<P>
   The anonymous letter appeared soon after the announcement of the
Goya finalists and, Trueba said, it cast a ``shadow of doubt'' over
all of the competitors. ``I would have preferred not to have been
in competition this year,'' Trueba said. ``It wasn't fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Trueba's film won the Goya as best picture and six other
prizes, and the film's producer, Andres Vicente Gomez, called Garci
a coward for not attending the awards ceremony, although Garci
apologized the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Gomez strongly criticized the anonymous letter, but he
said Garci may have contributed to the controversy by ``taking the
role of the victim and trying to promote his film.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The epilogue to the story is that `The Grandfather' got the
Oscar nomination,'' Vicente Gomez said. ``This compensates
everything. I wish him luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery remains over who sent the letter to the academy
members. ``We'd need Philip Marlowe to find out,'' said Garci,
referring to the Raymond Chandler's fictional Los Angeles
detective. Various rumors have swept Madrid about the letter's
author.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Garci may have been singled out as a target for having
been perceived as cuddling up to the conservative government But he
pointed out that some of his earlier films had anti-Franco themes,
like ``Begin the Beguine,'' the story of a Spaniard in exile after
the Civil War who wins the Nobel Prize in literature.
</P>
<P>
   While the harsh words have waned, the wounds do not appear to be
fully healed.
</P>
<P>
   After ``The Grandfather'' became an Oscar finalist, the film's
leading actress, Cayetana Guillen Cuervo, who is Garci's romantic
off-screen partner, told the Spanish daily El Pais: ``Now some
people will have to shut up. Or did we buy the American academy,
too?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
