<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1286 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-15 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If President Clinton had heeded former White House
press secretary George Reedy's advice, he would not have let George
Stephanopoulos into his inner circle to invade his privacy and
betray his trust.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusted by the competing egos and circular intrigues of Lyndon
Johnson's chaotic White House, Reedy concluded that no one should
be permitted to work for a president until he or she was at least
40 years old and well-seasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Young folks, the middle-aged Reedy felt, were not yet adequately
equipped with experience and maturity to serve responsibly and
dispassionately in the heady, high-pressure environment that
inevitably surrounds a president. Stephanopoulos was only 30 when
he went to work for Clinton, where he eventually became living
confirmation of the soundness of Reedy's theory.
</P>
<P>
   In his self-serving, harshly judgmental book ``All Too Human'',
Stephanopoulos concedes that Clinton finally figured this out for
himself, regretting the hiring of too many wide-eyed young
assistants who were ``smart but not wise.'' Of course no staffer
brought such disgrace on the institution as Clinton himself, but
several public embarrassments could have been avoided had he been
given better advice.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, as Reedy knew, is no place for idealism and
selfless devotion, qualities Stephanopoulos claims to have
initially held before he realized Clinton's flaws.
</P>
<P>
   It is inevitably a hotbed of seething staff ambition, in which
pandering to the chief occupant in pursuit of reflected glory
becomes more important than thoughtful decision-making or
commitment to principle. And its intimate institutional nature
exposes a president and first lady _ ANY president and first lady _
to the kind of close-up scrutiny that allows little privacy and
room for imperfection.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos was an eager player in the inner game, elbowing
his way to Clinton's side and clinging like a limpet until Clinton
became disenchanted with his aide's loose tongue and political
miscalculations. Stephanopoulos fled his mentor before he could be
shoved out the door, capitalizing on his White House credentials in
a new role as television commentator and author of a $2.75 million
tell-all book.
</P>
<P>
   Now he makes money pontificating as the insider he no longer is
_ or ever will be again unless some other big league politician is
foolish enough to want a smart-aleck blabbermouth at his side.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, beyond a few anecdotes, Stephanopoulos doesn't tell us
much that we didn't already know or guess about White House
infighting and presidential bumbling. He has no particular sense of
the sweep of history and the implications of the events he
witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   He is carefully discreet about still-powerful presidential
friends like Erskine Bowles while he has a good time detailing his
feud with outside strategist Dick Morris, an easy target since
Morris' disgraceful adventures with a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos is candid about the mental and emotional toll
levied by his constant desire to please Clinton amid all the White
House tensions and conspiracies. He developed insomnia and slid
into clinical depression, which a psychiatrist finally treated with
the prescription drug Zoloft.
</P>
<P>
   Reedy could have predicted that, too.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1970 book ``Twilight of the Presidency,'' Reedy notes,
``The inner life of the White House is essentially the life of
chickens in the barnyard. ... It is a question of who has the right
to peck whom and who must submit to being pecked.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stephanopoulos was riding high and doing the pecking, he
was okay. But when he fell from favor and saw himself as low on the
pecking order, he was consumed by hives and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The institution provides camouflage for all that is petty and
nasty in human beings and enables a clown or a knave to pose as
Galahad and be treated with deference,'' Reedy observes.
</P>
<P>
   Reedy wasn't referring merely to the Johnson White House that he
knew best. He quoted a former aide to Franklin Roosevelt, a fellow
known for what FDR called a ``passion for anonymity,'' as
explaining that insecurity and duplicity were eternal at the seat
of ultimate governmental power. ``That's the way it has always been
and that's the way it will always be,'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Insider stories from the subsequent administrations of Richard
Nixon, Ronald Reagan and George Bush reinforce the truth of that
pessimistic but realistic view. Despite the tawdry behavior of its
president, the internal Clinton White House is not a horrible
aberration but part of a traditional pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos pretends he never anticipated any of that. His
insistence on his own honorable political principles and naivete
about Clinton's womanizing are a typical author's trick. You get to
write the book; you get to cast yourself as hero.
</P>
<P>
   But he comes across as a far less intriguing personality in his
own book than Hillary Clinton, whom he has trouble understanding
and whose character is as complex and puzzling as that of the
president. On one page, she is bullying her husband. On another,
she is vulnerable and crying. On a third page, she is compassionate
and considerate.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos can't make up his mind whether to like her or
not. It doesn't matter. On the basis of his premature literary
squealing we can easily decide not to like him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
