<HEADER>
A1293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAASTRICHT-FAIR-400&AMP;A     03-15 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAASTRICHT-FAIR-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIR HAS LOCATION, LOCATION, LOCATION ... AND ART 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAASTRICHT, Netherlands _ Thirty-three private planes flew into
the tiny airport here during the first 24 hours of the opening of
the European Fine Art Fair over the weekend, with others rerouted
to nearby Liege, Belgium. Hotel rooms were sold out nearly a year
in advance. On Friday afternoon and all day Saturday, cars were
backed up for miles on local roads, and the best restaurants within
50 miles were fully booked all weekend. These are the trappings of
art buying on a scale never seen in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem strange that the world's largest art fair is held in
this small Dutch city, especially to Americans who are used to
visiting big cities to see great art. But for Europeans,
Maastricht's proximity to France, Belgium, Germany and Luxembourg
makes it convenient. Over the years, as word has spread that this
was the place where all the major European collectors buy great
art, Americans have followed.
</P>
<P>
   Now museum curators, auction house experts and collectors from
all over the world make the pilgrimage to Maastricht every March.
As a result the fair has grown to a degree that staggers first-time
visitors and seasoned dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago I never would have imagined this fair would draw
such crowds,'' said Konrad O. Bernheimer, a London dealer. ``The
fact that it's in the middle of nowhere is the secret to its
success. People come here for days, and they come here to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its beginning 25 years ago as primarily a showcase for
paintings, particularly 17th-century Dutch works, the fair has
significantly broadened its scope, and it now includes outstanding
examples of every collecting category from Old Masters and
antiquities to textiles, jewelry and contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   In the Maastricht Convention Center, a stark space that seems
more appropriate for a cattle auction than an art fair, nearly 200
dealers (13 more than last year) from 12 countries exhibit their
best finds. The scope of these offerings is enormous. Some of this
year's highlights include a 1740 English garden pavilion with its
original pine paneling, priced at $235,000; an $11 million emerald
and diamond snake necklace, and a $1.3 million illuminated
manuscript made for an abbey near Antwerp, Belgium, in 1524.
</P>
<P>
   Last year more than 68,000 people came to the fair. This year
the organizers have conservatively estimated that a total of more
than 72,000 will have attended by the time the fair ends on Sunday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The fair is physically larger this year. A 7,000-square-foot
hall has been added to the convention center, and the aisles have
been enlarged as have many of the booths. To transform this
cavernous space into an elegant art fair is not easy. The dealers'
stands are covered in colored felt, and the show's central plazas
are decorated with enormous flats of tulips and hyacinths.
</P>
<P>
   There are curators here from the National Gallery in London, the
Louvre, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Solomon R. Guggenheim
Museum, the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and the Wadsworth
Atheneum in Hartford. Christie's auction house dispatched nearly 40
of its employees here to chat up clients. Major collectors in
attendance include Sir Graham Kirkham, a British financier; Mica
Ertegun, a New York City decorator and collector, and Linda J.
Wachner, the chief executive of Warnaco.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fair's inception, this has been known as the most
comprehensive place to see Old Master paintings. It still is. This
year, however, many of the dealers are grumbling that there are not
enough masterpieces on view because business has been so brisk in
recent months that they haven't been able to replenish their stock.
Even so, Rob Smeets, a Milan, Italy, dealer, offered ``The Mocking
of Christ'' (circa 1615), a luminous candlelight painting by
Honthorst.
</P>
<P>
   At an auction in Paris three months ago, Jean-Luc Baroni, the
director of Colnaghi, a London gallery, bought ``The Scourging of
Christ'' by a medieval painter known only as the Master of the
Karlsruhe Passion. It is one of six panels painted between 1435-65
for a church in the Strasbourg area. The other five panels are all
in European museums.
</P>
<P>
   Some dealers have purposely hidden their best artworks, saving
them for special clients. ``Let me show you my finest painting,''
said Simon Dickinson, a dealer in London and New York, leading a
visitor into a tiny room tucked in the back of his booth to see
``Rest on the Flight into Egypt, with St. Jerome'' (1530), by Paris
Bordone. Dickinson was also offering some of the fair's only
top-quality Impressionist paintings, including Pissaro's ``Campagne
aux Environs de Conflans-Ste.-Honorine'' (1874).
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Waddington, a London dealer, has been appointed chairman
of the paintings department at the fair and has worked to improve
its quality. His own stand featured a sampling of works by Picasso,
Warhol, Josef Albers and Henry Moore. This year he persuaded Annely
Juda of London, a leading dealer in contemporary art, to exhibit at
Maastricht. Ms. Juda is displaying works by Christo, Anthony Caro
and David Hockney, as well as a 1927 Mondrian, ``Composition with
Red, Yellow and Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the fine arts tend to get most of the attention at the
fair, there are also rare examples of silver, furniture, porcelain
and jewelry. One of the choicest pieces is a rock crystal and
silver gilt 16th-century double cup that the London dealers S.J.
Phillips have had hidden away since they bought it at a sale of
objects from Victor Rothschild at Sotheby's in London in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dealers in Oriental art have deserted Maastricht
this year for the Asian Art Fair to be held in New York later this
month. One holdout is Ben Janssens, a London dealer whose booth
here displays a rare Tang dynasty group of 10 horses with riders,
some of whom are holding musical instruments. He found the pieces
in an English private collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``At specialized fairs you only meet people interested in
Oriental art,'' Janssens said. ``But here I meet new people who are
interested in all fields of collecting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
