A1322 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINES-Y2K-HNS &LR;      03-15 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SAY AIR TRAVEL COMPUTERS WILL BE FIXED BEFORE JAN. 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government investigators said Monday they are
confident that the computers operating the nation's air traffic
control system will be updated with new programs before Jan. 1,
ensuring that it will be safe to fly on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, the agency that manages the
nation's air traffic controls, is installing new computer programs
at about 3,700 air traffic facilities so that the computers will
correctly read dates after Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the government's computers, as well as those in private
industry, use two digits to read the year. Unless this is fixed,
computers and embedded microchips could read ``00'' as 1900 rather
than 2000 and malfunction. The potential problem is known as Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Government investigators such as the General Accounting Office
warned last year that the FAA might not have its systems fixed by
Jan. 1. The agency did not begin fixing its computers until last
year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Congress heard good news Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a much higher level of confidence today than we did a
year ago that the Department of Transportation's mission-critical
systems, such as air traffic control, will be Year-2000 complaint
before October, 1999,'' Kenneth Mead, the DOT's Inspector General,
told the House Government Reform and House Science Committees.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Willemssn, the General Accounting Office's director of
civil agencies information systems, agreed. ``Looking back to where
the agency was only a year ago, FAA has made tremendous progress,''
he said. ``But much remains to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Garvey, head of the FAA, said the agency is scheduled to
have its computer systems fixed and installed by June 30. That
deadline, however, is behind the Clinton administration's plan to
have all government computer systems upgraded and tested by the end
of this month.
</P>
<P>
   But Garvey, as well as the inspector general, noted that the FAA
has been able to meet its self-imposed deadlines during the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA will also conduct its first major test next month when
FAA air traffic control systems in Colorado will be turned ahead to
April 10, 2000. The test will be conducted on a flight from
Colorado Springs to Grand Junction to Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey said the test is designed to determine whether individual
system fixes will be able to work together in an actual operational
environment. So far the only testing that has been completed has
been with simulations.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA is also in the process of developing contingency plans
in case any of its computer systems fail on or after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey said it includes such things as increasing the amount of
distance between planes that are landing and taking off. It also
includes having another air traffic control tower take over for one
that is experiencing problems.
</P>
<P>
   This, for example, could mean that air traffic controllers at
Dulles Airport in suburban Washington, D.C., would help controllers
at Ronald Reagan Washington National airport if a problem arises
there.
</P>
<P>
   Willemssn said such a plan would not work, however, in the event
of widespread power outages.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey said the FAA is continuing to work with airports to
ensure that all of its systems including airport lighting and
baggage systems, are upgraded. She also said the agency is working
with international aviation officials to ensure that their air
traffic control systems will be fixed by Jan. 1. The FAA plans to
conduct tests with several countries by Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the GAO reported mixed results in airports'
Year-2000 readiness. One third of 413 airports surveyed said they
would be ready by June 30 while the rest planned on a later
completion date.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those airports are small, but the GAO said 26 of the
nation's largest 50 airports' computer systems would not be ready
by June 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
