<HEADER>
A1334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     03-15 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MADISON SAID IT: ARM YOURSELF WITH KNOWLEDGE OR LOSE FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.1999 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   March 16, James Madison's birthday, is the occasion for a
national celebration _ Freedom of Information Day. It's a day to
remember the significance of requiring open government and open
records.
</P>
<P>
   Madison expressed this thought powerfully in his 1798 report to
the Virginia House of Delegates, ``Knowledge will forever govern
ignorance: And a people who mean to be their own Governors, must
arm themselves with the power which knowledge gives.''
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is there are bureaucrats at every level of government
who hide their mistakes as officials from the public, who hide
government maneuvering that exceeds legislative intent, who wish to
deny agency errors, who want to blind the public to the expansion
of their power.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is there are presidents and governors and members of
city and town councils who cherish power more than they cherish the
tradition of democracy and representative government. And there are
state and federal legislators who would join these would-be
tyrants.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is the term ``national security'' is used to conceal
despicable acts and contemptible policies. Agents of the government
used citizens without their knowledge in radiation experiments, to
test diseases, to see if psychedelics could be used to control the
mind. And hid it all behind the old rubric of ``national
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential national security decision directives are used to
create foreign policies without the knowledge of the public and
often without the knowledge or advice of Congress. President Reagan
wasn't the only president to issue such directives, although he may
have issued more of them than any preceeding president,
approximately 300. One NSDD authorized the use of the National
Security Council to conduct covert operations _ a clear violation
of its mandate. The secrecy of NSDDs destroy the checks and
balances built into our system of government. Not even our elected
member of Congress can stop a policy of which they are ignorant.
</P>
<P>
   ``A serious violation of national security'' was the
government's cry when the Pentagon Papers were first published in
The New York Times and the Washington Post. After examining the
papers, a majority of the justices of the U.S. Supreme Court
thought otherwise. Indeed, what the report clearly showed was how
the United States politically blundered into the Vietnam War
without a clear foreign policy goal and without cogent military
leadership. It also showed that secrecy was the handmaiden of this
nation's bungling.
</P>
<P>
   According to Arthur Schlesinger Jr., President Kennedy later
regretted that The New York Times had not played up its story on
the exile invasion of Cuba. ``If you had printed more about the
operation, you would have saved us from a colossal mistake,'' he
told a Times editor.
</P>
<P>
   When California closed its prisons to journalists a few years
ago so that interviews with inmates were either forbidden or
greatly restricted _ on the phony rationale that criminals
shouldn't be treated as media stars _ newspapers were kept at a
distance and their role as government watchdogs severely
diminished. Any wonder then, that last year the Los Angeles Times
was finally able to break a series of stories about prisoners being
used as gladiators in fights to the death in prison yards? When
there is no public oversight, power is rawly abused.
</P>
<P>
   Madison, again from that 1798 report, said: ``To the press
alone, checkered as it is with abuses, the world is indebted for
all the triumphs which have been obtained by reason and humanity
over error and oppression.'' The press is the only private,
commercial enterprise mentioned in the Bill of Rights or in the
Constitution, for that matter _ for good reason, the Founding
Fathers understood the significant role that newspapers play in
informing the people about public issues. At root, that is one
reason we, the people, manage to hold tight to our democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom of Information Act was passed in 1966. It grants all
citizens and journalists the legal right to inspect records kept by
federal agencies except those specifically exempt as classified or
records that reveal commercial trade secrets. Presidents have
attempted to limit the scope of the FOIA _ Reagan, and Gerald Ford,
for instance.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress has stood firm in bipartisan support of the FOIA
and in 1974 passed important amendments to the act, over the veto
of President Ford. In 1996, the act was again strengthened with the
passage of key amendments regarding electronic media.
</P>
<P>
   But there are new problems in this electronic information age.
</P>
<P>
   Government agencies remove Web pages without storing them or
copying them to files that can be accessed by the public at some
later date. In other words, an agency can alter the history of its
actions _ not unlike George Orwell's prophetic novel ``1984.''
Federal agencies are also failing to make public information
available on their Web sites or withdrawing the information for
so-called security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has begun to be understood to be one of the most
powerful communication tools the world has ever known. A citizen
can know as much about an issue as his senator or representative in
Congress _ sometimes a lot more. Knowledge gives the people
leverage in Congress and in state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups understand the enormous power of the
Internet to defeat misinformation circulated by agricultural or
mining interests.
</P>
<P>
   The hog farm industry spends millions of dollars to convince
legislators that hog farm waste isn't a danger to surrounding
communities and well water. Ask a North Carolina resident who lives
anywhere near the 10 million hogs produced in that state.
</P>
<P>
   The government, as the Founding Fathers understood it, has an
obligation to provide public access to any information created or
compiled by government employees at taxpayer expense. It has an
obligation to preserve that information and guarantee its
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Madison understood there is no democracy when the citizenry is
ignorant.
</P>
<P>
   We need more than one day a year to keep vigilant on these
issues, but one day is a good start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
