<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAYES-AUCTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once-mighty Hayes to auction what remains
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is how it ends: with the bark of an auctioneer,
the call for bids and the carting away of what's left.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day auction of assets at Hayes Corp., the company that
once dominated the analog modem market, begins Wednesday at 10 a.m.
in the Norcross building that once housed its corporate
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Emerald Assets Management, Nuri Otus, will take
the microphone as he has at hundreds of auctions and invite the
bidding to start. For item number one, he has promised a surprise
_something bidders will not be expecting.
</P>
<P>
   But everything else is on display until the end of the day
today.
</P>
<P>
   Emerald workers have gone through the four-building, 178,000
square-foot spread and tagged every for-sale item with a number to
make bidding easy.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses might be interested in the more common devices,
or perhaps office furniture, Otus said.
</P>
<P>
   Some huge corporations have checked out the now-idled Hayes
assembly lines, which include a number of large, complex machines
that cost tens of thousands of dollars new.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something for everyone,'' Otus said. ``In terms of
buying one modem, no. But for buying a computer or fax machine,
yes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Hayes factory are circuit board inserters, ovens to bake
parts into place, wave soldering machines, in-circuit testers, a
bar code printer, oscilloscopes from Tektronix and something called
a Vectorscope from NTSC.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the floor sits a Hewlett Packard 3070 Series II
in-circuit board tester, the kind of machine that _ unlike personal
computers _ does not become obsolete every four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a current product that sells for about $400,000 new,''
Otus said. ``We will probably take in half to two-thirds of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction takes place at Hayes corporate headquarters, on
Peachtree Corners East, just off Peachtree Industrial Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   The event is open to the public and is intended to raise money
toward paying off the debt Hayes amassed as it went under.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
