<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDSPAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worldspan chief exec to quit post for new job
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The top executive at Atlanta-based Worldspan is
leaving the travel reservations company to take a job with an
Internet real estate firm in California.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Buckman, Worldspan's chief executive officer since 1995,
will depart at the end of the month. Worldspan said a search for a
successor has begun, and an interim CEO soon will be named.
</P>
<P>
   Buckman, who will be president and chief operating officer of
Real Select, is the second top Worldspan official to leave in
recent weeks. Jeffrey Hoffman, vice president for distribution
planning and development, left for a job at the Internet travel
service priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coincidence that they both went with Internet
companies,'' said Patricia Cooledge Forsyth, a Worldspan
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Worldspan, based at the Cobb Galleria, is one of a handful of
computer reservations systems that sell booking information and
tools to travel agencies. It also provides computer support to
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Worldspan is jointly owned by Delta, Northwest and TWA and has
about 3,100 employees, just over half of them based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The company is the fourth-largest global reservations system,
behind Galileo, Sabre and Amadeus, which also are partly owned by
various domestic and foreign airlines.
</P>
<P>
   A merger between Worldspan and Europe-based Amadeus was widely
expected last year, but Amadeus reportedly hoped to combine the
move with an initial public offering and shelved the plan when the
market cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about the deal has quieted, but not died, since
then.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
