<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAMASCUS-BOOK-REVIEW-     03-15 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAMASCUS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAY AFTER A NIGHT OF HAPPINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hazel is sated, happy and confident after their first night of
making love. Finally the mists of growing up and casting about to
find out who she is have lifted, and she is ready to set a course
out into life.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer is sated, happy and in deep doubt. Mists were a comfort,
and a sunlit course is scary. After Hazel brushes a languorous
morning-after hand across his chest, he reflects: ``That was nice,
he couldn't deny it but then uninterrupted niceness had been part
of the problem the first time around.'' Poets apart, it is in
happiness, not dreams, that responsibilities begin. For Spencer,
seeking is much lighter than finding: it imposes neither choice nor
its constricting consequence. Being knocked off his donkey by
divine choice was not the big thing for Saul/St. Paul. Rather, it
was choosing that choice and submitting to go on by foot to
Damascus and the other towns that would more and more painfully
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Damascus is title and metaphor for Richard Beard's blithe jaunt
around the uncertain peaks and yawning hollows of his
contemporaries' efforts to engage the task of living. The
transfiguring event that is supposed to bring commitment is also a
perpetually receding alibi.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, that tumble from the donkey wasn't such an event, only a
matter of an inconvenient pebble. Nor, surely, could it be a night
of astonishing happiness with a long-sought-for woman. (Hazel and
Spencer had been courting and evading each other since childhood.)
</P>
<P>
   Beard takes us through the day that follows the couple's night,
to the unsurprising conclusion that this pretty much has to be it.
That is the only unsurprising thing about ``Damascus.'' The novel
is a tipsy game, part of whose fun consists in figuring out rules
that alter as you go along, like the flamingo mallets in Alice's
Wonderland croquet.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nick Hornby and Jonathan Coe, two other young British
writers, Beard comically unhinges style, character and point of
view to tell us that indeed we are in the chaos of the contemporary
world. Then they introduce an oddly straightforward tenderness to
suggest that we may indeed survive it.
</P>
<P>
   The joining of such opposites is not always convincing _ it can
excessively manipulate plot and emotions _ but what results is
witty, original and sometimes transporting.
</P>
<P>
   In ``X20,'' his first book, Beard used a dizzying set of
variations on the subject of smoking and not smoking to construct a
graceful novel about the frontier between ego and intimacy, a
frontier that contemporary culture has armed to the point of
outright warfare.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Damascus'' he uses two other drolly disorienting devices to
chart Hazel's and Spencer's struggles to burn clear in an era of
quenching becloudment.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, a series of brief retrospective chapters about
their growing up are all announced as taking place on Nov. 1, 1993
_ the night and day of the story's present action. This bewilders
for a while and sometimes irritates, but it works oddly well.
</P>
<P>
   Beard's wackiness has a shrewd precision that makes it
infectious. Furthermore, there is a point. Memory takes place in
the present, clarifying or befuddling it. Everything that Hazel and
Spencer remember crowds into the same forcing-chamber with their
efforts to decide who they are and who they will be.
</P>
<P>
   A related device consists of blurring circumstances so that each
retrospective chapter is described as occurring in half a dozen
different spots in Britain (seven or eight dozen of them, by the
time we're through, a veritable travel guide).
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly loony and certainly reiterative; yet again, there is a
point. It is like one of those old stage effects in which the
background moves by while the characters stand still: instead of
dispersing emotion, the effect is to focus it on them.
</P>
<P>
   Devices aside, the best scenes in ``Damascus'' come in glimpses
of Hazel and Spencer from birth to that first bedding. At 12 they
meet at the beach where their families have gone for chilly (and
cheap) off-season holidays. It is a lovely portrait of
shy-but-longing boy and shy-but-assured girl. (It will be years
before they are reunited, though they keep in touch by illegally
activated pay phone.)
</P>
<P>
   Later there will be Hazel's promiscuous adolescent rebellion
against a smothering mother who has no doubt that anxiety is the
right response to life. ``Her timidity is therefore very assured,
almost aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   As for adolescent Spencer, he is convinced that he is the only
male of his age who doesn't have ``nonstop all-action sex all of
the time.'' At his school dance he prepares pickup lines, each more
absurd than the other, and tries them on three girls. They ``heave
with laughter, as if together they comprise a single organism which
feeds off the embarrassment of 15-year-old boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Beard writes these chapters with comic ardor and telling
silences: the blackouts and uncanny touches that characterize
memory as opposed to narrative. As for the narrative _ the 24 hours
in a dilapidated London mansion where a series of extravagant
incidents propel Hazel and Spencer into something approaching a
happy ending _ it is less successful, though it contains much that
is engaging.
</P>
<P>
   There is William, the wobbly brother of the mansion's wealthy
owner, and under Spencer's hired care. Shrewd and kindly, William
suffers from a state of indecisiveness so extreme that he is unable
to leave the house. Everything he sees _ pedestrians, buses,
garbage cans _ seems equally in need of his attention, making him
forget why he went out in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   True, the outdoors is unsettling in Beard's faintly absurdist
contemporary London. Britain is about to join the European
Community, the local library is putting on a shouting session for a
festival titled ``Most Noise Ever Heard in a Library,'' and a
vagrant who haunts a nearby doorway is the former director of the
National Economic Development Office.
</P>
<P>
   What disrupts all this is a McGuffin so gnarled and elaborate as
to throw the novel out of whack, even as it propels the plot. An
insane Japanese student armed with a poisonous powder invades the
house convinced that he is in love with Hazel. What follows is
frequently comic and appropriately absurd, but it is also terribly
forced.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, so is the Hazel-Spencer resolution it engenders.
After bringing us a witty, original and sometimes enchanting novel,
Beard has tried too hard to bring it off. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `DAMASCUS'
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Beard
</P>
<P>
   310 pages. Arcade Publishing. $23.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
