<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Masters field the largest in 33 years
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angel Miguel Jimenez of Spain and Patrik Sjoland of Sweden were
added to the 1999 Masters field on Monday through invitations from
Augusta National chairman Hootie Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The starting field of 95 is the largest since 103 golfers
competed in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Three more opportunities are available, for winners in the Bay
Hill Invitational, The Players Championship and Atlanta's BellSouth
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first Masters appearance for Sjoland, 27, who
finished fifth in the 1998 European Tour Order of Merit, and the
second for Jimenez, 35, who on Sunday won his second Turespana Open
in a row. Jimenez, fourth on the Order of Merit last year, missed
the cut at the Masters in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think both men are very talented players,'' Johnson said.
``Both golfers finished among the top five last year 
European Tour's Order or Merit and have competed successfully
against the best players in the world. We are very happy to have
them in our field.''
</P>
<P>
   The total number of Masters invitations is 104, but nine have
gone to non-competing players. The Masters, the first major
championship of the season, will be played April 8-11.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
