u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-NOTES16-COX     03-15 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    International soccer: Will Real Madrid survive?
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most storied club in European soccer is in grave danger of
missing out on the continent's most lucrative competition next
season. And for defending European Cup holders Real Madrid, that's
far from being good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Real, which travels to the Ukraine on Wednesday to play
dangerous Dynamo Kyiv (4:45 p.m., ESPN2), must win the second leg
of its Champions League quarterfinal matchup in order to move on.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish giant is hanging on by a thread, as it was last
season. Real won a spot only by virtue of its European Cup
championship, a record seventh. Its current seventh-place status in
the Primera Division won't be enough by itself, even with the
Champions League expanding from 24 to 32 teams next year.
</P>
<P>
   Kyiv got a crucial road goal in a 1-1 draw at Madrid's Bernabeu
Stadium two weeks ago. The good news for Real, which has given up a
Primera-high 42 goals, is that the injured Fernando Hierro and
Manuel Sanchis are back, and defender Christian Panucci and
midfielder Clarence Seedorf are coming off suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Europe: Cup crazy
</P>
<P>
   Other Champions' League matches Wednesday feature Manchester
United at Inter Milan; Juventus at Olympiakos and Bayern Munich at
Kaiserslautern, with the visitors all having the upper hand. . . .
The second leg of the UEFA Cup quarterfinals will be played
tonight: Olympique Marseille at Celta Vigo; Bologna at Olympique
Lyon; Girondins Bordeaux at Parma; and Atletico Madrid at AS Roma.
. . . On Thursday, the same stage of the Cup Winners' Cup will be
held: holdersChelsea at Valerenga of Norway; Lokomotiv Moscow at
Maccabi Haifa of Israel; Varteks of Croatia at Mallorca; and Lazio
at Panionios of Athens.
</P>
<P>
   England: Wembley bought
</P>
<P>
   The Football Association will purchase Wembley Stadium in London
and spend $380 million for a complete overhaul to help England's
bid for the 2006 World Cup. Wembley, which opened in 1923, will be
demolished and rebuilt to seat 80,000, with modern facilities and
improved sight lines. . . . Premier League chief executive Peter
Leaver resigned last week after board members expressed dismay that
he hired two executives of BSkyB, Rupert Murdoch's cable outlet, as
media advisers. . . . After getting his third red card of the
season Sunday, Arsenal's French midfielder, Emmanuel Petit, says he
wants to leave England. Petit will be suspended for Arsenal's
upcoming FA Cup semifinal match with Manchester United.
</P>
<P>
   France: Buying Bordeaux
</P>
<P>
   Although leading the first division, financially troubled
Girondins Bordeaux has attracted the interest of an English
investment firm and a French television station. The club also has
been clouded by decade-old allegations of fraud and bribery. A
players' agent has testified in an ongoing trial that he offered
gifts and women to referees to help Bordeaux officials fix
Champions' League matches in 1985. . . . Artur Jorge has left as
manager of Paris St-Germain, the richest club in France but
currently in 12th place in the first division.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Juninho no given
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian midfielding whiz Juninho has been told by interim
Atletico Madrid manager Carlos Aguiar that his spot in the lineup
is not guaranteed. Juninho, who passed up a chance to return to
England after being promised a starting role by former manager
Arrigo Sacchi, has played little since Aguiar came on board last
month. . . . Rivaldo scored twice in the first half Saturday,
pushing his total to 15 for the season, as Barcelona built a
four-point lead in the Primera with a 3-0 win over city rivals
Espanyol.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America: Pan-Am no go
</P>
<P>
   The South American federation will not send men's or women's
teams to the Pan American Games this summer. Organizers in Winnipeg
balked at being asked to spend $3 million for CONMEBOL to
participate. . . . The Argentina Clasura season got under way over
the weekend after a three-week players' strike, and Racing Club of
Buenos Aires also got into the act. The club, a favorite of former
dictator Juan Peron, was declared part of the country's national
heritage by current president Carlos Menem, himself a Peronist.
Cash-strapped Racing, which nearly went bankrupt, now will get
government protection from creditors for at least another year.
</P>
<P>
   Around the globe
</P>
<P>
   FIFA boss Sepp Blatter has proposed a global calendar to be
played annually between February and November to help meet his goal
of holding the World Cup every two years. He also proposes that
domestic leagues cut down to 16 teams, an idea being blasted in
Europe. . . . Tokyo will be the site for the 2002 World Cup
qualifying draw on Dec. 7. The Asian federation is threatening to
withdraw all 40 nations under its umbrella if it doesn't get more
slots in the finals. Asia has only two other teams in the 32-team
event besides co-hosts Japan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
