<HEADER>
A1351 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-URUGUAY-2TAKES     03-15 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-URUGUAY-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN URUGUAY, THE SIGHTS AND SMELLS ARE COMPELLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LINDA TRISCHITTA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALTO, Uruguay _ Eucalyptus trees and jasmine vines perfume the
daytime air of Uruguay, until the cool and sweet scents are
overtaken by the smell of burning pine, fuel for the evening
barbecue ritual in a country where grass-fed beef is exported to
Argentina and costs less than chicken in the supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   The Monday before Ash Wednesday, our route winds north along
Route 3 and Rio Uruguay to the Salto province to visit my hosts'
relatives and soak in roadside hot springs at sunset. After bathing
we drive into the capital city of the state, also called Salto, and
are greeted by the sounds of drummers practicing on side streets
for the evening's four-hour-long desfile, or Carnaval parade.
</P>
<P>
   Salto is laid out in a grid with a mix of architectural styles
19th-century neo-classical, stone-columned municipal buildings and
boxy flat-roofed stores and houses from the 1950s and '60s. We
inhale the aroma of grilled freshly slaughtered beef and lamb as we
drive toward our hotel on Plaza Artigas. Every city has a similarly
named memorial designated for Jose Gervasio Artigas, a leader in
Uruguay's 1811 revolution against Spain. The banks of the Rio
Uruguay and the Argentine border are a 15-minute drive east, and
all roads lead to the river, which floods waterside neighborhoods
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   The party would not begin until 10:30 p.m., and a mass of
spectators senior citizens and teen-agers aboard buzzing scooters,
horse-drawn wooden carts driven by children and groups of walking
families head toward Calle Uruguay, the evening's byway for bands,
clowns, beauty queens and floats.
</P>
<P>
   Multicolored wands of lights provided by commercial sponsors are
strung across the parade route. The celebration begins with a
summons of cymbals and drums accented by firecrackers that pass
beneath our hotel balcony. The costume colors and rhythms are so
alluring I cannot wait to get to the street, but we do not want to
leave our perch for fear of missing any of the show. Our lodgings,
the Gran Hotel Salto, cost about $50 per night for suites, which my
hosts think is pricey.
</P>
<P>
   It is the tallest structure in the city, a five-story Art Deco
building with a 1950s interior in a neighborhood of embassies, a
historic church and retail storefronts. When we return to the
street, the crowd is six deep on both sides, choked with chairs and
tables that were set up hours earlier. But the curb-side seated
spectators are friendly and we squeeze in and do not miss a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Marchers dressed as witches, monsters and giants loom over
children who run along the sidelines near their families' spots.
The kids sneak up on the performers, who feign surprise and turn to
frighten them. The brave ones retaliate with foam sprayed from
narrow cans or throw water to melt the threat away, before running
back to their folks, shrieking. It is a great way to wear out the
little ones who are excited by the colors and the noise.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers, their faces covered with fabric or masks bought at
bodegas, join the scary monsters in the ruse.
</P>
<P>
   Women shimmy atop floats to the musical vibrations of
unamplified but powerful bands whose sounds shake the curb-side
trees. Throngs of dancers appear wearing smiles, sequined tangas
(thongs) and brief bras, dancing to an escola do samba beat, a
Brazilian influence from the neighbor to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Hourglass is not a dirty word in Uruguay, and the female form is
celebrated, especially the posterior portion. Since this is not
Brazil, breasts are restrained. The parade is simulcast live on
televisions in city restaurants and bars, and shown in slow-motion
when cameras focus on costume beads that bounce off of undulating
hips.
</P>
<P>
   A 120-member band featuring a line of 30 drummers precedes a
spangled white float with an almost life-size model of an SST jet,
pulled by a proud farmer driving a tractor. The band rocks back and
forth, taking baby steps down the calle while playing a samba
serenade, allowing spectators an eyeful of the woman deemed most
beautiful in all of Salto, the parade queen who stands at the
plane's tail.
</P>
<P>
   The brunette monarch wears a white beaded mini shift and high
white boots; on her shoulders rests a harness of 12 2-foot-long
white feathers that nuzzle her face and long dark hair in the soft
breeze like nurturing angels' wings. The float carries her court, a
corps of young girls who wear tangas and bras with less dramatic
yellow feather headdresses. It takes a half-hour for the queen's
group to pass the block, and the pulse of the music never wavers
during the sustained applause for the sight.
</P>
<P>
   Bystanders, unable to keep still, join the swirling dancers that
keep coming down the parade route. If the crowd really claps, the
performers will come close and dance just before them. Radio
station vans are joined by a Santa Claus float, a huge dove with
luminescent eyes and adolescent girls in evening dresses who are
targets of the sprayed foam, which they smilingly wipe away.
</P>
<P>
   Uruguay is one of South America's smallest countries with only
3.2 million people. It sits on the Atlantic coast, to the right of
Argentina, just beneath Brazil. The warmth of the climate permeates
the culture, where a handshake is an insult and introductions are
made with a kiss. Or two.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling to the Southern Hemisphere to escape the cold of North
America may seem extreme, but an invitation from three generations
of Uruguayans (who are friends and naturalized Americans) to join a
Carnaval Week road trip around their homeland was too enticing to
resist.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   The Carnaval in Uruguay is a blend of traditions: the Llamadas,
which are candombe drum rhythms played by black musicians and
whites in blackface who summon residents to their Montevideo street
party; religious celebrations of the cross and also of the farmer's
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Every desfile also contains performances by groups called
Murgas.
</P>
<P>
   The word means a band of street musicians, and there are about
20 groups that come from some of the poorest sections of the
country. Murgas perform nightly in cities and villages during the
month of February for prizes and to earn money for their art. A
century-old theatrical tradition, the groups specialize in drum
sounds derived from the Canary Islands and incorporate humor,
political parody, skits or a combination of all those forms in
their shows.
</P>
<P>
   A national election will be held in November, and posters of
smiling candidates were glued to the walls of shantytown shacks on
the outer rings of cities. Graffiti and murals touted members of
the red, green and other political parties, saturating the
landscape and informing the themes of the murgas, who as comedians
and actors perform behind masks in ornate rainbow-colored satin
costumes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Salto desfile, some of the murga's headpieces completely
covered their faces, sometimes they relied on paint. Always they
carried political banners bearing their group's name in one case
``Faltan Papas'' (not enough potatoes, or food; that is, people are
hungry), and careened around the calle like the Marx Brothers while
singing sardonically about corruption, poverty and unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   When we returned to Montevideo, the country's capital, we spent
Friday night at Club Atletico Tabare in the Buceo barrio to see the
famed murga group ``Reina de La Teja,'' or Queen of the
Neighborhood, which has toured in parts of New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   While a desfile attracts everyone, murgas used to draw only the
poorer people to performances and have become a chic entertainment
attended by the upper classes. In this small neighborhood where it
seemed every resident turned out for a show on the other side of
the planet from the United States, a skit about President Bill
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky was prominent as the second act and
received uproarious applause.
</P>
<P>
   The song was a bizarre North American intrusion on my escapist
reverie that was Uruguay. Otherwise my journey was an exotic and
sunny escapade, and the Carnaval was just one highlight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Days began with Parisian-style breakfasts of bizcocho
(croissants), followed by a climb into the navy blue Hyundai van
that held eight (grandparents, my friends and their teen-age sons)
and took us on a c-shaped tour of the western and southern sections
of the country. We enjoyed luxurious beach living on the
southeastern coast (the Uruguayan Riviera) and bounced along in the
dark on our way to Tacuarembo on a 40-mile rocky path that maps
described as a highway.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling with native speakers is the best way to learn about
subtle aspects of a culture, things like the rivalries between
Uruguayans and the superior mind-set of the Argentines;
understanding the jokes during a rapid-fire theatrical performance
on a bus ride around the old section of Montevideo; which pastas
contain sesos, or cows' brains, considered a delicacy, and that
tipping more than 10 percent is considered a week's wages for some.
</P>
<P>
   During the 10-day trip my hosts took me to pueblos in the
northern Artigas state that are not in any guidebook ... places
where there is not even a plaza, police station or church, only a
school and general store, where gasoline is sold from a glass jar.
</P>
<P>
   Often we were the only game in those dusty towns, and our
late-model vehicle stood out among the decades-old cars and trucks
that appeared well maintained and were painted far more brightly
than their original colors.
</P>
<P>
   Though education is mandatory through only the sixth grade, the
country claims a 98 percent literacy rate. ``Even gauchos need to
count,'' my friends said. Speaking of South American cowboys, some
were more handsome than Antonio Banderas, and adhered to a unique
sartorial style of bloused pants, ponchos and three-cornered or
flat-brim hats.
</P>
<P>
   When not on horseback they wore fabric espadrilles and because
they eat even more beef than the average Uruguayan, their huge
carving knives, strapped to the small of their backs on wide
leather belts, were often visible ... a fierce aspect that belied
their friendly demeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days was too brief, despite my host's efforts to present the
variety of Uruguay, and I feel compelled to return, an indication
of a successful and soul-nourishing trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
