<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Tuesday, March 16. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONUMENT-ARIZONA (Flagstaff, Ariz.) - A new national monument
proposed for northwest of the Grand Canyon should be twice as large
as originally envisioned by Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, the
head of a prominent Flagstaff environmental group said Monday. The
Grand Canyon Trust wants to make the proposed Shivwits National
Monument nearly 1 million acres, almost the size of Grand Canyon
National Park. Opponents call the monument ``Land Grab II.''
Ranchers, miners and others _ still steaming over the 1996
designation of a national monument in southern Utah _ protested the
proposal at a town hall meeting in Flagstaff on Monday night. By
STEVE YOZWIAK. Storyr will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PARK-ARIZONA (Ajo, Ariz.) - Most small-town residents in
southwestern Arizona can appreciate the pristine Sonoran Desert's
natural beauty. To a point, they even want to preserve it. The
desire to preserve stops short of depriving personal freedoms, some
Ajo and Gila Bend residents declare. They're speaking of a group of
40 mainly Tucsonians and Phoenicians who want to convert more than
3 million acres of sonoran desert into a national park. ``If they
get through with this (national park) it's going to destroy the
community,'' said Ajo resident and activist Bud Klinefelter. By
SETH LANDAU. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BABBITT-GRANDJURY (Washington) - The independent counsel
investigating Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt has convened a grand
jury and is looking inside the White House to determine whether
politics influenced a decision on an Indian casino, The Republic
has learned. The existence of the grand jury has not previously
been reported. One of the witnesses who has been called is Loretta
Avent of Phoenix, a former deputy assistant for Indian Affairs to
President Clinton. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HAGGARD-MUSIC (Phoenix) - It comes as a surprise to hear Merle
Haggard, one of America's most gifted songwriters, proclaim,
``There's nothing I hate worse than perfect music.'' After all,
what could be more perfect than the heartfelt lyrics of the
country-music standards penned by Haggard over four decades. But
there he is, on the phone from his home in northern California,
expressing concern that country music in the '90s has had its roots
polished right out of it. By LARRY RODGERS. Story moved in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COMPUTER-COLUMN (Phoenix) - Ack! I've been attacked by a killer
Trojan worm! Yes, you read that right. We consumers would call it a
virus. But experts in Computing Land say the correct term is either
``Trojan'' or ``worm.'' (I added the ``killer'' part for fun!). By
DAVID HOYE. Story moved in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FUENTES (Phoenix, Ariz.) - Mexican writer Carlos Fuentes now wears
the literary mantle he inherited last year after the death of
Octavio Paz. But although acclaimed as the grand old man of Mexican
letters, Fuentes, 70, is still as productive and in demand as ever,
having just produced a new novel, ``The Years of Laura Diaz.'' By
BARBARA YOST. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
