<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0316-COX     03-15 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOC-SCANDAL-0316-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACCUSED IOC MEMBER BASHES INTERNAL INVESTIGATION, INVESTIGATOR
 &HT;    EDs: With optional add at 600 words.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The most prominent IOC member targeted
for expulsion in the Salt Lake City bidding scandal went on the
offensive Monday saying the investigation that implicated him was
fatally flawed and motivated by internal politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is fighting about the succession after (IOC President
Juan Antonio) Samaranch retires,'' said Jean-Claude Ganga, the
member from Congo and president of the association of African
Olympic committees. ``Maybe it's because I have a little influence
with the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga's aggressive stand could preview what the IOC's leadership
will face Thursday when it pushes the full membership to expel six
members on allegations that they accepted bribes or improper gifts
during Salt Lake's successful campaign for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   With 91 IOC members attending the emergency session called to
respond to the Salt Lake crisis, it will take 61 votes to expel.
While many IOC members say they expect the full committee to follow
the lead of the executive board, there is the chance that Ganga and
others of the accused could muster the 31 votes needed to block
their ouster. This would be interpreted as a disaster for Samaranch
and the IOC leadership, which is under extreme pressure from
sponsors and the public to take substantial steps in response to
the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, speaking to reporters in the lobby of the Lausanne Palace
hotel, refused to name the orchestrators of the campaign against
him but implied strongly that he suspects Dick Pound, the Canadian
IOC member who chaired the inquiry commission that recommended
Ganga's expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga denied he did anything improper and said he has documents
to support his case. He said the Pound commission's investigation
was done hastily and overlooked facts that would exonerate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the things they say I have done wrong, they cannot
prove,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He implied that Pound was out to get him because of Pound's own
ambitions to become IOC president, which Ganga would oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the members of the Pound commission -- Pound, Jacques
Rogge of Belgium and Pal Schmitt of Hungary -- have long been
considered successors to Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   One of the members implicated in the Salt Lake scandal is Kim Un
Yong, the South Korean member who also has been mentioned as a
candidate to replace Samaranch, whose term expires in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, whom Ganga supports, was issued a strong warning by Pound's
commission, which stopped just short of seeking to expel him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim did nothing wrong,'' Ganga said. ``They want to kill him
because he is a candidate for IOC president.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga also suggested that Pound's enmity may date back to the
1976 Montreal Olympics when Ganga orchestrated a damaging boycott
by African countries. Pound was a member of the Montreal organizing
committee.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Pound denied that he had any ulterior
motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking as a lawyer, if you have a case with bad facts, you
attack the law,'' Pound said. ``If you have a case with bad law,
you attack the facts. If you have a case that has bad facts and law
you attack the prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound rejected the argument that the IOC could have avoided such
complaints by appointing an outside investigator to review the
allegations rather than relying on an internal committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied both personally and as chair of this ad hoc
commission that the work that was done was thorough, impartial and
independent,'' he said. ``The ability to self-govern has been
conclusively demonstrated as far as we're concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound added that his commission heard Ganga's assertions and
still voted to expel him.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, an independent auditor in Sydney said the city's
successful bid for the 2000 Olympics involved numerous breaches of
IOC guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But the auditor, Tom Sheridan, criticized the IOC rules
governing bids, saying the guidelines are unclear and ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan found Danish IOC delegate Niels Holst-Sorensen and his
wife traveled from Copenhagen to Paris to watch the 1993 French
Open tennis final at the invitation of Australian IOC member Phil
Coles, who also worked with the bid committee. Their air travel and
associated expenses were paid for by Sydney's bid.
</P>
<P>
   The bid also paid for Irish IOC member Kevin O'Flanagan and his
brother to travel from Dublin to London for the 1992 Wimbledon
final. Sydney paid their air travel, accommodation, theater tickets
and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan named a number of other IOC members who received
special treatment or gifts from the bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan said breaches of the IOC guidelines included the value
of gifts given to IOC members, the duration of visits, the number
of overseas trips made by Sydney bid members to lobby IOC officials
and assistance in finding jobs for members' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0369 </DOCNO>
