<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1364 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINES-GAYS-HNS &LR;      03-15 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINES-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE'S DESERT BASE DISCHARGED HIGH NUMBER OF HOMOSEXUAL TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Marine Corps base at Twentynine Palms in
California's Mojave Desert had the highest number of Marines
discharged for homosexuality last year, according to figures
released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines fired 76 homosexual troops in 1998 throughout the
force; 12 male and four female Marines were discharged at
Twentynine Palms.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Pendleton, Calif., the Marines fired 10 male and two
female troops for homosexuality during the same period. At Camp
Lejeune, N.C., seven male troops and five female troops were
dismissed for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon figures on specific military installations were
provided by the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network, a leading gay
rights legal organization based here. The group obtained them from
Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
   Marine Corps spokeswoman Capt. Aisha Bakkar-Poe said the service
couldn't explain the relatively high number of homosexual
discharges at the desert facility. ``We'd be speculating to say
why,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bakkar-Poe said the Marine Corps considers sexual orientation
``a personal and private matter (that) is not a bar to continued
service unless manifested by homosexual statements or conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Twentynine Palms, which occupies about 900 square miles of
desert, hosts large-scale infantry, artillery and armor exercises
to test the military preparedness of Marine Corps units.
</P>
<P>
   Located an hour's drive from Palm Springs and near the 500,000
acre Joshua Tree National Monument, the base, known as the Marine
Corps Air-Ground Combat Center, is home to the service's
communications and electronics school and about 9,600 military
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's current policy of ``don't ask, don't tell, don't
pursue'' means that homosexual activity is banned in the military,
but that gays and lesbians may serve as long as they keep quiet
about their sexual orientation and aren't caught engaged in
homosexual acts.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders may not inquire of a service member's sexual
orientation, according to the rules. However, they may do so if
they have ``credible information'' that a service member engages in
homosexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Pentagon efforts to clarify the policy, homosexual
rights organizations maintain that gays and lesbians in the ranks
who conceal their sexuality are routinely drummed out.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the armed forces discharged homosexual personnel in
record numbers last year despite the Clinton administration's
controversial policy aimed at allowing gays and lesbians to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the military, there were 1,145 personnel discharged
in 1998 for homosexuality, compared with 997 personnel the previous
year. The 1998 total was the highest level since 1987 when 1,380
men and women were released, according to Pentagon data.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the Air Force let go 414 gay and lesbian personnel. The
Army discharged 310 personnel, while the Navy released 345 sailors.
</P>
<P>
   The figures represent the largest number of homosexuals
discharged from the military since President Clinton's
controversial ``don't ask, don't tell, don't pursue'' policy went
into effect in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Servicemembers Legal Defense Network believes contends that
the increase is due to an increase in anti-gay harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The group documented 400 cases of anti-gay harassment in the
military last year, including death threats, compared with 182
violations in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   C. Dixon Osburn, co-executive director of the legal group, said
Monday that homosexual personnel ``are forced between hiding under
this blanket of fear and anxiety from harassment every day or
coming out and being fired for who they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
