<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EINSTEIN-RECALLED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WORLD NEEDS MORE EINSTEINS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REA LUBAR DUNCAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was April 1954, and I had gone to see Albert
Einstein at his home in Princeton, N.J., to ask if he would accept
an achievement award from Lord &AMP; Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a Lord &AMP; Taylor?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   And would he make an acceptance address at a luncheon at the
Waldorf?
</P>
<P>
   This was during the tyrannical reign of Sen. Joseph McCarthy,
the Wisconsin Republican who was trying, all too successfully, to
destroy the careers and ruin the lives of non-conformist thinkers
he stigmatized as communists.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with bravery that the late Dorothy Shaver, then
president of Lord &AMP; Taylor, dared to present the store's awards
that year to ``intellectual adventurers whose non-conformist
thinking had opened new worlds of thought and accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   I presented to her my suggested winners, among them newsman
Edward R. Murrow whose rambunctious adventuring on television
helped topple McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've left out the greatest intellectual adventurer of our
time,'' she snapped. ``Einstein. Get him.''
</P>
<P>
   George Bernard Shaw called Einstein, who died April 18, 1955,
``a maker of universes,'' ranking him with Pythagorus, Ptolemy,
Kepler, Copernicus, Aristotle, Galileo and Newton. The atom bomb,
as we called it then, was, of course, his brainchild. And, in the
10 years he lived after the first bomb shattered Hiroshima, he was
sickened from self-torment that perhaps he had been a destroyer,
not a maker of universes.
</P>
<P>
   I saw him as neither, but rather as a gentle host of astonishing
modesty, roguish humor and insatiable curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was arranged. But the question remained, would
Einstein accept such a ``commercial'' award?
</P>
<P>
   Entering Einstein's house, I trembled with fright. Downstairs
all was darkly somber, the parlor furnished with brown mohair
furniture and tall, heavy, carved, German-style wooden chairs.
</P>
<P>
   But upstairs, in the professor's study, all was sunshine and
bright from a great picture window. It looked out on the garden,
where a dogwood tree was in full snowy bloom and daffodils were
golden.
</P>
<P>
   The professor greeted me from a well-worn brownish upholstered
arm chair. He looked _ well, like Einstein. Wispy white hair, a
threadbare jacket the color of rotten spinach over a gray
sweatshirt. Shoes but no socks.
</P>
<P>
   I was so nervous, I had to smoke. Would the professor mind?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, no, I will take one from you.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't smoke it. Instead, he unrolled the cigarette and
carefully poured every grain of tobacco into a battered cold pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The professor is not allowed to smoke,'' said his housekeeper,
Miss Dukas. ``It's bad for him.''
</P>
<P>
   When she left to make tea, he whispered, ``If you send some
tobacco to this address, I will get it.'' It was the house next
door.
</P>
<P>
   I never sent any. How could I risk shortening by even a moment
the earthly stay of this rare human being who, although he well
knew his self-worth, had no self-illusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years ago I thought I was very important,'' he said,
``but I long ago grew out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, talking about scholars who risked their careers to pursue
unpopular ideas, he said, ``I do not deserve this award. I take no
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the risk of pursuing a theory for years and having
it lead nowhere?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is no risk,'' he said giggling. ``That is the fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally I got up the nerve to ask: Would he accept the award?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But no, he would not attend the luncheon. He was in poor health
and made few public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   I was devastated. My job was to get him there. Sensing my
plight, he said, his blue eyes twinkling, ``Make me a
proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought fast. Would he record his acceptance remarks to be
played at the luncheon? He would. I still have the recording.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that five awards be given instead of the customary
four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some young non-conformist must not lose recognition because of
an old one like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now picture me, a person who barely scraped through college
physics, having to describe Einstein's achievements for the
presentation speech _ including, my God, the theory of relativity.
</P>
<P>
   With dread, I phoned him and read him the segment for approval.
</P>
<P>
   There was an ominous silence, then came his wondrous giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let it stand,'' he said. ``No one will know any better.''
</P>
<P>
   With typical humor, his acceptance remarks began, ``It gives me
great pleasure, indeed, to see the stubbornness of an incorrigible
non-conformist warmly acclaimed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, professor, the world has need of you now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
