<HEADER>
A1369 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUENTES-AZR &LR;      03-15 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUENTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARLOS FUENTES HAS MADE MARK AS WRITER, DIPLOMAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - From his home in the south of Mexico City, Carlos
Fuentes can see the volcanoes of the Ajusco Mountains spewing
plumes of white steam.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, craters like Popocatepetl have been
``rumbling fiercely,'' the venerable writer says, a phenomenon that
disturbs him not in the least.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico itself has been rumbling since the revolution of 1910,
providing Fuentes with the themes of political and social turmoil
that permeate his acclaimed novels, including ``The Death of
Artemio Cruz'' and ``Where the Air Is Clear.''
</P>
<P>
   At 70, he takes rumbling in stride. Comfortable wearing the
literary mantle passed to him after the death last year of Octavio
Paz, the graceful and erudite Fuentes now is considered the grand
old man of Mexican letters, though he shudders a little at the
label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not old!'' he protests with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he has just published a new novel, ``The Years of Laura
Diaz,'' which looks at Mexican history through the eyes of women.
It is a companion piece, he says, to ``Artemio Cruz.'' Sales have
been brisk.
</P>
<P>
   Could this work finally earn him the Nobel Prize, which has
continued to elude him despite his winning nearly every other
literary prize in Latin America?
</P>
<P>
   He dismisses such notions.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever thinks about winning a Nobel Prize,'' Fuentes says
by telephone in the flawless English he learned while being
educated in the United States. ``One doesn't write to win prizes
but for the pleasure of writing.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 45 years, Fuentes has had the pleasure of writing
as one of the luminaries of the ``El Boom'' generation of Latin
American authors who came to prominence in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of his colleagues have passed on, Fuentes endures,
bridging the gap to what he calls the ``Boomerang'' of
up-and-coming poets and novelists.
</P>
<P>
   The new generation includes such writers as Alberto Rios, 46, a
regents professor at Arizona State University in Tempe who teaches
creative writing and Latin American literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love his poetry,'' Fuentes says of Rios.
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fuentes' ideas are big ideas,'' Rios says. ``He is urbane and
persuasive. He is a charming man. When he comes into a room, you
know it. He has a lot of energy, a lot of poise, a good sense of
humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Rios hopes to reacquaint himself with Fuentes when the elder
writer appears at ASU in Tempe on Monday, March 22, to deliver the
Centennial Lecture.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Fuentes was the first guest of the Centennial
Lecture series, sponsored by the Flinn Foundation. Fuentes says he
has ``warm memories'' of Tempe and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a trip to Arizona inspired his writing of ``The Old
Gringo,'' a story in which American author Ambrose Bierce finds
himself in the midst of the Mexican revolution confronting Pancho
Villa. The story is based partly on history. Bierce, indeed, did
disappear into Mexico around the turn of the century and never was
heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Gringo'' became the 1989 American film of the same name,
starring Gregory Peck as Bierce and Jimmy Smits as Villa.
</P>
<P>
   Do not ask Fuentes his opinion of the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not speak of that,'' he says sternly.
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes easily can afford one bad movie treatment of one fine
novel. His status is secure not only as a writer of fiction but
also as a journalist and diplomat as well.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, he served as Mexico's ambassador to France and
consistently has shouldered the responsibility of interpreting the
culture and politics of Mexico for the world outside its borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been an articulate spokesman for the cultural,
political and social relations between the U.S. and Mexico,'' says
David Foster, regents professor of Spanish and chairman of ASU's
languages and literatures department.
</P>
<P>
   Foster says Fuentes has devoted his career to expounding on the
``vast panorama of Mexico,'' which Foster characterizes as a
diverse people who do not always share even the same language.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done that brilliantly,'' Foster says.
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes agrees that his beloved Mexico is a complex society. It
is a mix of Indian, Iberian, Greek, Roman and mestizo heritage.
Fuentes' own great-great-grandparents came from Spain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   He prides himself on being one of the first Mexican writers to
be in touch with an American audience, which long has embraced his
intellectual writings.
</P>
<P>
   But Fuentes warns that the United States has become more
isolationist since the end of the Cold War, concerned mostly with
``itself, its scandals and with entertainment . . . Madonna and
Bruce Willis.''
</P>
<P>
   Though America and Mexico share a common border, they also share
misconceptions about each other.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, Mexicans view Americans as vulgar and loud,
Fuentes says. Up north, Americans see Mexicans as shiftless, lazy
and unruly. He says neither stereotype is true.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans ultimately admire the culture of the United States, but
they have been frequent victims of its lumbering foreign policies
and trade practices, he believes, especially during the War of
1848.
</P>
<P>
   Two incendiary issues, illicit drugs and illegal immigration,
continue to divide the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes remains optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``These problems can be solved with diplomacy and goodwill,'' he
insists.
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes' penchant for promoting diplomacy and goodwill is his
personal choice, not a professional mandate. He believes a writer's
duty is only to tell a story.
</P>
<P>
   ``A writer's obligation is to language and imagination, to
create a new realism in the imagination,'' he says. ``The purpose
of a novel is to extend the consciousness of your reader.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Fuentes is fluent in English, French, Italian and
Portuguese, he writes only in Spanish. Though a rich language for
literature, English is not the tongue of his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dream in English. I don't make love in English. I
don't get mad in English. That's why I don't write in English.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, he executes most of his writing in the most
English-speaking of countries. With homes in Mexico and England, he
spends six months of the year on the speaking circuit in Mexico and
then retreats to London for six months.
</P>
<P>
   That storied land of bad food and worse climate, he says,
provides a solitude that nurtures his creativity. In a city with no
distractions beyond the odd trip to the theater, the grand old man
of Mexican letters gets down to business.
</P>
<P>
   England swings, but it does not rumble. In London, Fuentes is
the only volcano. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
