<HEADER>
A1375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO16-COX     03-15 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMPROMISE URGED IN STATE-FEDERAL FEUD OVER TOBACCO FUNDS
 &HT;    500&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Attorney General John Cornyn drew on a
childhood fable Monday as he asked Congress to keep the federal
government's hands off the money the states won by suing tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who joined officials of three other states before a
Senate Appropriations subcommittee, said the dispute over $206
billion reminded him of ``The Little Red Hen,'' who tried in vain
to get the Cat, the Rat and the Pig to help plant the grain,
harvest it and bake the bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``They refused,'' Cornyn said, but the three were more than
willing to help eat the loaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government is like the Cat, the Rat and the Pig,''
the Texas attorney general said of the Clinton administration's
effort to claim 57 percent of money yielded by a 46-state effort to
recover health-care expenses from tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won, and that money is theirs,'' agreed Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, who is sponsoring a measure with Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla., to keep all of the money in the states. The
provision has been added to an emergency supplemental spending
bill.
</P>
<P>
   However, U.S. Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala
voiced ``strong opposition'' to the Bailey-Hutchison proposal
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal share of Medicaid expenses ranges from 50 percent
to 77 percent,'' she said in a letter to the Senate Appropriations
Committee. She added that the federal government is entitled to
recover its share of the expenses, or at least to direct how the
states spend the proceeds of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has told the state governors that they could
control the money, if they would spend 25 percent of it for
anti-smoking campaigns and follow his priorities, including helping
tobacco farmers, assisting children and promoting public health.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's hearing, an administration official testified that
the federal government is legally entitled to 57 percent of the
lawsuit proceeds. ``Existing federal law clearly requires states to
share all Medicaid recoveries with federal taxpayers,'' said Mike
Hash, deputy administrator for the Health Care Financing
Administration. ``Nothing in the law creates an exception for
tobacco settlements, regardless of their size.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks drew a vow from Hutchison, whose state of Texas won
$17.3 billion in the tobacco settlements. ``I'm going to try to
keep you from dictating to the states what they do with money
they've won fair and square,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the subcommittee chairman, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.,
indicated that a compromise could be in the works. ``It may be that
we can reach an accommodation,'' he said. He predicted that a
majority of the Senate will favor ``some sort of guidance'' for the
states that does not set up restrictive regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison told reporters later that she would go along with a
``sense of the Congress'' measure that would make general
recommendations to the states. ``But a set-aside would be a very
difficult hurdle for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   She said spending one-quarter of the funds for anti-smoking
campaigns could be excessive amount in large states. In Texas, that
amounts to more than $4 billion over 25 years. ``I don't think you
could spend it responsibly for smoking cessation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The state officials urged a quick resolution of the dispute so
that they could begin spending their tobacco payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until this issue is settled, I would not recommend spending
any of these funds,'' Gov. Paul E. Patton of Kentucky told the
Senate panel. Iowa attorney general Tom Miller said that his state
was ``paralyzed'' until the issue is settled.
</P>
<P>
   Some states are proceeding with plans for spending the funds,
even with the final control in doubt. Texas is proposing to spend
$881 million over the next two years for a variety of health care
and anti-smoking programs. Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida has proposed
using some of that state's $13 million settlement for tax cuts as
well as for anti-smoking efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
