<HEADLINE>
CALIF. REGENTS TO VOTE ON PLAN TO MAKE UNIVERSITY MORE ACCESSIBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They get nearly perfect grades, take honors
classes, hold student body offices and outside jobs. But for some
of the highest-achieving students in the state's inner city and
rural school districts, University of California appears hopelessly
out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't attract my attention,'' said Claudia Pompa, one of
the top seniors at Fresno's Central High School this year. ``It's
too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the list of her accomplishments is long _ a 4.0 grade
point average, honors classes, membership in numerous student clubs
_ she hasn't requested a UC application and plans to go Cal State
Fresno, where she can live at home.
</P>
<P>
   This week the UC Regents are set to vote on a plan to make the
top 4 percent at every California high school eligible for the
university in an effort to draw more students from rural and
inner-city areas. But some counselors, administrators and students
say while they welcome the plan, it will take extra financial aid,
outreach and preparation to get them there.
</P>
<P>
   The barriers to UC are complex and costly. Many students from
poor families cannot afford the yearly $13,000 price tag to attend
UC and live on campus. Some fear, despite their own high grades,
that they are poorly prepared to compete with the state's best
students. And others simply do not have what's dubbed the ``UC
mind-set'': They may be the first in their family to attend college
of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is that general lack of confidence and lack of feeling
they will do well,'' said Marigrace Cohen, head counselor at
Mission High School here, where several top students said they
believe UC is ``too much of a jump'' for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go from here to there,'' said Arlene Mitri, a
Mission High senior with a 3.85 grade point average, who has taken
honors classes and works outside school 25 hours a week. ``It's not
possible for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The 4 percent plan, backed by Gov. Gray Davis, is being hailed
by UC President Richard Atkinson as ``historic,'' and is expected
to be approved by regents Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Through it, the university would identify the top 4 percent of
students in their junior year, then advise them on what courses to
take and what financial aid to seek in order to attend one of nine
campuses in the prestigious UC system.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is one of three suggested changes to make the top 12.5
percent of students statewide eligible for UC, a state goal.
</P>
<P>
   Currently 11.1 percent of students statewide are eligible, but
that figure hovers between 5 and 6 percent in some inner cities and
rural areas like the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The other two major changes would alter the weight of SAT scores
and reduce by half the extra point given to students who take
Advanced Placement courses, which are not available at all high
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The 4 percent plan is not expected to change the racial
diversity at UC, where affirmative action was banned four years
ago. But it is an attempt to boost access among students who attend
high schools in disadvantaged regions.
</P>
<P>
   About 240 of the state's 858 high schools send few students to
UC and about 50 send none.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving what school administrators call the UC mind-set,
however, will not be simple. Even UC-Riverside Professor Keith
Widaman, who heads the faculty committee that drew up the
recommendations for regents, said he didn't consider UC as a young
student growing up in the Central Valley because of its size, cost
and distance from his home.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest obstacle to UC cited by students and counselors is
lack of money. Indeed, even Regent Ward Connerly, the architect of
the ban on affirmative action at UC, said he worries that without a
commitment to provide financial aid for needy students, the
proposal won't help broaden access to universities.
</P>
</TEXT>
