<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEPHARDT BACKS GORE FOR PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H _ Armed with the endorsement of a former rival,
Vice President Al Gore dropped by two key primary states Monday to
promote an array of domestic initiatives and ignite his
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Gore received the endorsement of House
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who opted last month to
sit out the 2000 presidential race and instead concentrate on
winning back the House for Democrats and becoming the chamber's
next speaker.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore and Gephardt faced each other in the 1988
presidential primary and have differed in the past on a number of
issues, particularly on trade policy, the House leader lavished
praise on the almost-certain candidate at a rally of Democratic
supporters at the New Hampshire Institute of the Arts and Science.
</P>
<P>
   Countering the stereotype of Gore as a stiff policy wonk,
Gephardt said he had seen the vice president ``react as a father
and a husband'' when his son was seriously injured by an automobile
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that Gore ``cares most deeply about what happens to all
of the people,'' Gephardt said, ``I am here today to say that I
will make my fight putting Al Gore into the presidency of the
United States.``
</P>
<P>
   While Gore acknowledged that the two men occasionally fought, he
said they were ``almost always on the same side.``
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt later flew with Gore to Iowa, where Gephardt has a
strong political organization, and then to the congressman's
hometown of St. Louis, where the two were scheduled to dine at one
of Gephardt's favorite Italian restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   In Des Moines, Gore picked up 67 endorsements of state
politicians and Democratic activists.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's support for Gore was a setback to former Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, the only Democrat who is currently
challenging Gore for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   And aides said the endorsement was meant to show a unified
Democratic Party in contrast to the Republicans, who face a bitter
primary fight that, at the moment, features a dozen high-profile
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But two of those Republican candidates who announced exploratory
committees last week, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Elizabeth
Hanford Dole, have received an unusual amount of publicity so early
in the campaign cycle and, at this early stage, polls show they
appear to hold more appeal with voters than the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest Fox News poll, taken March 10-11 among 900
registered voters nationwide, Bush led Gore 59 percent to 30
percent. Dole led Gore 50 percent to 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In a Zogby International survey of 908 likely voters conducted
March 4-7, Bush bested Gore 55 percent to 38 percent. The Zogby
poll did not test a Dole-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not officially announced his intentions to run
for president, Gore's trip to New Hampshire and later to Iowa
appeared a concerted effort to focus attention on his upcoming
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Urging supporters to ``stand with me,'' Gore laid out a domestic
plan heavy with Clinton administration proposals, such as hiring
new teachers and protecting Medicare and Social Security. He also
offered a handful of new proposals, the most prominent being the
promise to provide preschool education for all children.
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to core Democratic constituencies, Gore stressed equal
pay regardless of gender, more progress on racial harmony, and
attention to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Long known for his environmental activism, Gore briefly touched
on proposals to reduce global warming and curb urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   But criticized by Republicans for what they consider
environmental extremism, Gore justified some of these plans as an
extension of solid family values. He said curbing growth would
allow people ``to spend more time with friends and families than
stuck on the road.``
</P>
<P>
   Eager to carve out his own political identity, Gore largely
avoided mention of Clinton. But at the same time he made it clear
he hoped to benefit from the economic prosperity that has kept
Clinton's approval ratings astronomically high.
</P>
<P>
   In a theme that advisers said would be a mainstay of his
campaign, the vice president indirectly warned of the economic
downturn that could occur if the White House was turned over to the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not slow down our economy. Let's not go back to some
failed prescription of the past,'' he told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sidestepped any talk of two areas that could prove
troublesome, the recent impeachment of Clinton and foreign affairs,
where the administration is currently embroiled in controversies
over China and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters asked if impeachment would factor into the
campaign, the vice president responded,``The American people want
to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point supporters who had been listening burst into
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Gore adviser Bob Squier said he believed the economic message
would be powerful in the 2000 campaign and would help propel Gore
past Republicans such as Bush and Dole. Early polls show both
potential candidates leading Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Squier dismissed these early polls arguing that Bush and Dole
are ``two big brand names.``
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic consultant said voters currently do not see Gore
as presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They see him right now as part of Clinton Gore. ... He is not
thought of in presidential terms,'' Squier said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he was unconcerned about his current underdog standing
in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suits me fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
