<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER PRESSURE, ALBANIANS ACCEPT KOSOVO ACCORD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(wg) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Ethnic Albanians said Monday that they were ready to
sign the Kosovo peace accord, but the signing was delayed while
mediators consulted the Serbs to see whether they would accept the
agreement with some minor changes, French officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to the ethnic Albanian delegation said that if the
international sponsors of the talks began proposing changes to the
plan to end the violence in the Serbian province, the ethnic
Albanian promise could be nullified.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to a document that has already been completed,''
said Veton Surroi, a leader of the Kosovo Albanian delegation.
``It's up to the mediators now to get Serb agreement to the
document.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord taken up when Kosovo peace talks resumed Monday in
Paris would grant the ethnic Albanians autonomy, disband their
guerrilla army and enforce the settlement with 28,000 NATO
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian side has accepted most of the political provisions
of the agreement but has refused to consider NATO peacekeepers to
enforce it, even though the alliance has threatened President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia with heavy bombing of Serbian
military targets if he does not agree.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanian delegation took more than two weeks to
discuss the terms of the agreement, settled in talks at
Rambouillet, France, with representatives of their people, who
account for 90 percent of the population of Kosovo. They announced
their acceptance of the package only under considerable pressure
from the United States as fighting in Kosovo continued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you propose changes to the agreement the Kosovars have
accepted, you will take what had been a victory for British and
American diplomacy and turn it on its head,'' said Paul Williams, a
legal adviser to the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The French foreign minister, Hubert Vedrine, and the British
foreign secretary, Robin Cook, co-chairmen of the peace conference,
which is also sponsored by the United States, Russia, Germany and
Italy, hailed the long-awaited acceptance of the terms by the
Kosovo Albanians as a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav delegates are now up against the wall,'' Vedrine
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must now act quickly to make up for lost time,'' Cook
agreed at a news conference in the French Foreign Ministry, on the
other side of the Seine from the talks.
</P>
<P>
   At the news session, the two officials portrayed the Serbs as
the main obstacle to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton praised the decision by the
ethnic Albanians and renewed the NATO threat to carry out air
strikes if Milosevic did not agree to the accord or if attacks on
civilians continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he shows intransigence and aggression,'' Clinton said, ``I
think that from my point of view we would have little option'' but
to use force against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike President Clinton, Vedrine seemed almost to play down any
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NATO decisions remain in force,'' he said, ``and everyone
knows it. We have not as yet fixed a deadline. If there was one, it
would be very short.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in answer to a question, he added: ``There is a
finalization of the negotiations, which were quite far advanced in
Rambouillet, on the political side of the agreement. And that is
taking place between the Yugoslav delegation and the mediators.
Obviously, there is very little leeway.''
</P>
<P>
   French officials said the mediators were not discussing changes
in the agreement with the Serbs but only trying to sound them out
about what changes they wanted and try to persuade them to accept
the agreement in principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know nothing basic or really important can be changed,''
one official said. ``But if they would agree, for example, to an
`international military force,' if not yet to a NATO force, then it
would be difficult to justify bombing them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
