<HEADER>
A1385 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-NYT &LR;      03-15 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 PARIS: bombing them.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Underlying the differences is the fragility of agreement in the
six-nation ``Contact Group'' that is sponsoring the talks. The
allies would like Russia to participate in the eventual
peacekeeping force, but it is adamantly opposed to bombing the
Serbs to get them to agree to it. The United States is more ready
to use the threat of bombing than France is, but would leave most
of the peacekeeping to 14,000 French and British troops. Germany
and Italy are somewhere between France and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   And the Kosovo Albanians proved far less willing to accept
allied guarantees of their security than the United States thought.
Even Secretary of State Madeleine Albright failed to persuade them
in Rambouillet last month to sign the agreement when it was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Williams said, ``The Kosovar Albanians have given an
unequivocal yes to the document.'' But, he added, ``The Kosovar
delegation was informed by the U.S. National Security Council last
week that there would be no changes to the agreement absent their
consent,'' and none had been discussed with them yet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their acceptance Monday came in a letter to the co-chairmen from
Hashim Thaci, chairman of the Albanian delegation. ``This
delegation and I personally say `yes' to this agreement,'' he
wrote. ``We would be honored to sign this agreement in your
presence at a time and place of your choosing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with the Albanians Monday afternoon, Vedrine and
Cook said, they sought and got reassurances that this meant
acceptance of both the peace terms and the NATO peacekeepers to
enforce them.
</P>
<P>
   European officials said they did not ask the Albanians to sign
right away because they wanted flexibility in dealing with the
Serbs to get them to accept the peace plan, an 82-page document
with provisions for a constitution, an ethnically representative
legislature, an independent police force and a multinational
NATO-led military force that would disarm the Kosovo Liberation
Army and oversee the withdrawal of all but 1,500 Serbian border
troops from the province within 180 days.
</P>
<P>
   After three years, it says, an international meeting would be
convened to discuss a final settlement for Kosovo, taking into
account ``the will of the people'' and the ``opinions of relevant
authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's special envoy, the Serbian President Milan
Milutinovic, said after Monday's talks ended, ``We are still
working on the political agreement. All those stories that the
agreement is finished are fake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unilateral signing does not mean anything,'' he said of
Albanian acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   And he and other Serbian delegates to the talks told
international mediators they would not accept foreign peacekeeping
forces on Serbian territory.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and the United States have emphasized that any agreement
must include NATO peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   About 26,000 soldiers, largely European, would oversee the
disengagement of Albanian and Serbian military and police forces in
Kosovo and supervise the withdrawal of all but 12,000 Serbian
Interior Ministry Police to withdraw within a year.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers would be commanded by a British general with a
rear base of 2,000 support troops in Macedonia. Some 10,000 allied
soldiers and others are already gathering there now, ready to go in
within a week of a possible accord. The force is to include 4,000
U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   If the mediators conclude that Serbian refusal of the accord is
the main obstacle to ending a year of violence that has killed more
than 2,000 people and driven 200,000 from their homes, then the
alliance's secretary-general, Javier Solana, has been authorized to
send hundreds of warplanes against Serbian targets.
</P>
<P>
   Solana, visiting Washington Monday, said: ``If an agreement is
not reached and President Milosevic doesn't sign, the risk of a
catastrophe will be very likely, and we have to prevent that from
happening. And NATO will prevent that from happening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
