<HEADLINE>
RESOLUTE TRAVELERS FIND THRILL IN TAKING A RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Helga Hahneiser vacationed in Cambodia while the
murderous Khmer Rouge still roamed the country, went sightseeing in
Lebanon near the Hezbollah guerrilla headquarters and visited Zaire
while leader Mobutu Sese Seko was railing against whites.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Hahneiser is heading to Libya, which the United
States considers a rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   Hahneiser, 57, is one of a growing number of people seeking rare
sights and unusual experiences on their vacations.
</P>
<P>
   In the tourism business, it is known as ``adventure travel.''
</P>
<P>
   While some vacationers crave physical thrills, such as glacier
skiing, others seek the excitement of mingling with unfamiliar
cultures, and exotic flora and fauna.
</P>
<P>
   Hahneiser is drawn to Libya _ and other countries deemed unsafe
by the U.S. government _ for their ancient archaeological sites,
which have not yet been overrun with busloads of
video-camera-toting tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I arrived at the temple of Baalbek in Lebanon last year,
there were five Japanese tourists roaming through who left after an
hour,'' said Hahneiser, who lives near Los Angeles. ``After that I
had a splendid, incredible archaeological site all to myself. For
me, those are moments to accept a little bit of danger for.''
</P>
<P>
   A desire to travel to remote lands can lead to dangerous, even
deadly experiences _ as in Uganda recently when rebels killed eight
foreign tourists who were on a safari to see mountain gorillas in a
national park.
</P>
<P>
   The area had long been considered safe; 4,000 permits are issued
each year to visitors hoping for a glimpse of the elusive primates
portrayed in the movie ``Gorillas in the Mist.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the massacre, a London newspaper reported that rebels
had warned Ugandan officials in advance that they planned to target
British and American tourists. The threats were not passed along to
tour operators or diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Young Pelton, author of ``The World's Most Dangerous
Places,'' said adventure-seeking travelers court disaster when they
travel to places without a political road map.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although statistically it's safe in Uganda, people are
entering into areas where there isn't much security or control,''
he said. ``There are three wars going on in Uganda _ on its
northern, southern and western borders. Islamic fundamentalists are
seeking to destabilize the government, and they're using tourists
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, two British men and an American woman died when Yemeni
troops stormed a terrorist hideout to rescue 16 foreign tourists
who had been abducted by Islamic fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
   If the tourists had been familiar with the political situation
in that Middle Eastern country, they would never have chosen to
sightsee in that part of Yemen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started their trip four days after the United States
starting bombing Iraq,'' Pelton said. ``They went into the south of
Yemen, which is a hotbed of terrorists, after a fatwa (Islamic
edict) had been issued against British and Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   But they wouldn't have found that out from a popular guidebook
that described Yemen as an exotic place that had calmed down and
was ready for tourists, Pelton said, noting that 160 foreigners
have been kidnapped in Yemen since the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell tourists they are being parachuted in behind enemy
lines in a country, they would think twice about taking a bus tour
there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelton, whose new book, ``Come Back Alive,'' will be released in
June, has become a magnet for accounts of tourists caught in a
country's political cross hairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These incidents happen on a regular basis now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Sano, president of Geographic Expeditions of San Francisco,
said his travel company takes special security precautions when
sending people to risky areas.
</P>
<P>
   The company hired armed escorts to go to Cambodia with a group
of wealthy people who had donated money to preserve Angkor Wat, an
ancient temple complex.
</P>
<P>
   Sano said the company outlines travel risks to clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We attach all the latest State Department information to our
predeparture materials,'' he said. ``When somebody signs up for a
trip with us, we also give them medical information and general
security information, like pickpocketing in capital cities, which
is a big deal in Mexico City right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sano said the company also relies on its partners in foreign
countries for up-to-date information on changing political
situations. Sometimes, the State Department calls Geographic
Expeditions for information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company cancels trips when the danger becomes too great.
</P>
<P>
   Sano said risk is part of all travel _ wherever vacationers go.
And their tolerance for risk varies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started going to Iran in 1993, the individuals who
signed up for those trips were in their 50s and 60s,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't fit the typical profile of people who were willing
to take what was perceived as a risky trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The travel company does put some countries _ such as war-ravaged
Afghanistan _ off limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we don't have partners on the ground there, and
we don't feel comfortable taking those kinds of risks,'' Sano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really the Wild West there in terms of security concerns.
We could not guarantee anybody's safety.''
</P>
</TEXT>
