<HEADLINE>
INSTITUTE TO SHARE IN DEVELOPING HUMAN GENOME BLUEPRINT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Scientists at the Whitehead Institute will be major
players in a new, accelerated phase of the drive to decode all the
genetic blueprints of man, creating a foundation for a new era of
biology and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitehead/MIT Center for Genome Research was notified Monday
it will receive $35 million from the federal government as one of
three US genetics facilities that aim to create a ``working draft''
of the human genome by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Human cells each contain about 70,000 genes that serve as
blueprints for making the proteins that build and operate the body.
Those genes, altogether, contain about 3 billion chemical units of
four types that spell out all the information that's inherited
through generations.
</P>
<P>
   By next spring, said Eric Lander, the director of the Whitehead
genome facility in Cambridge, Mass., scientists hope to have
deciphered, or ``read out,'' the code for 90 percent of the human
genome (all the genes in a human cell). At present, only about 15
percent of the complete sequence has been deciphered, in a ``pilot
phase'' of the project that concluded at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot phase has been about developing the methods of
sequencing the genome accurately and efficiently,'' said Lander in
an interview. ``Costs have dropped from about $2 per base (chemical
unit of code) to about 20 cents a base,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sequencing'' is the process of determining the order of the
chemical units _ represented by the letters a,c,t and g _ that,
through long combinations of thousands of letters, spell out the
gene's ``message'' for how to make a given protein.
</P>
<P>
   The genome project began in 1990 as scientists first made maps,
by locating distinctive pieces of DNA that served as landmarks on
the 23 pairs of chromosomes that carry the 70,000 genes.
Researchers could locate certain genes with respect to these
landmarks, thereby putting the genes on a map.
</P>
<P>
   But to learn what information the genes contain, it's necessary
to read all the chemical letters in order. This task used to be
done by hand in the laboratory, but now there are robot-like
computerized machines that can do the reading at a rapid pace,
which accounts for the drop in the cost of doing it.
</P>
<P>
   The ``working draft'' will contain missing stretches of genetic
code in the genes' messages, said Lander, but a finished and
accurate version of the ``book of life,'' as it's been called,
should be completed in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Whitehead, scientists at Washington University
School of Medicine in St. Louis and Baylor College of Medicine in
Houston received funding for the next phase of sequencing. The
Sanger Centre in England is the fourth facility receiving the
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The speeded-up sequencing drive by the federal government comes
partly in response to a challenge by a private company, Celera
Genomics, of Rockville, Md., whose scientists say they can sequence
the genome faster and cheaper. However, Lander and other
researchers funded by the National Institutes of Health and the US
Department of Energy say the sequences deciphered by Celera's
methods may not be as accurate.
</P>
<P>
   With the human genetic blueprints in hand, researchers believe
they will be able to unlock many secrets of how the human being
develops and how genetic variations and adverse changes affect
health and illness. Pharmaceutical companies are eager for the
sequence data so they can design new and better drugs. The genome
project also aims to decipher the genes of organisms like mice,
rats and harmful micro-organisms to compare with the blueprints of
humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
