<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BUTLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOROTHY BUTLER, 84; STORIED WEDDING MADE HEADLINES IN WWII 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dorothy (West) Butler of Holderness, N.H., whose whirlwind
romance and storybook wedding to a captain in the Royal Welch
Fusiliers made international headlines in the early days of World
War II, died of heart failure March 4 in Speare Memorial Hospital
in Plymouth, N.H. She was 84.
</P>
<P>
   A niece of the late US Senator Leverett Saltonstall, Mrs. Butler
was born in Chestnut Hill, Mass. She attended Beaver School in
Brookline and Foxhollow School in Lenox.
</P>
<P>
   ``She met my father, who was in the British Army, in Ireland. It
was 1937. A fox hunting party,'' her son George, the author of the
book ``Pumping Iron,'' and director of the movie of the same name,
said in a story published in the Globe on Feb. 2, 1984. ``My father
had to immediately report to his regiment in Nigeria. So he
proposed to my mother by post, by sea mail, and he didn't get an
answer from her for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``When his letter arrived in Boston, it kicked up a big family
storm,'' he said. ``My mother was terrific, the oldest daughter of
a formidable man, George Saltonstall West. He was a powerful
presence, a man who looked like God and had played football at
Harvard. But she was enormously self-confident. She used to say to
me often: `If you can do something you want to do, something
outrageous, and not worry about what other people think, you can do
anything.' But at that time what she said to her father was: I'm
going to marry Capt. Butler.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, German forces were driving the British back in
North Africa and the English military was operating in great
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   A story in the London Daily Mirror on Nov. 6, 1940, said ``A
Guards officer's American fiancee has been sworn to silence about
her wedding plans by British Authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her lover is overseas and an indiscreet word about where he is
stationed might imperil him and his men. She is on her word of
honor not to reveal, even to her relatives the date and place of
the wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Mirror, ``She herself is at present unaware of
her fiance's whereabouts, because the authorities refuse to reveal
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother got in a ship and went to Africa. She landed in Cape
Town,'' said her son. ``There was no Capt. Butler waiting for her
at the wharf. She went incognito to Nairobi, thinking he was there.
But her trip had made all the newspapers. All of Kenya was looking
for him. And anybody named Butler was stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother arrived at the New Stanley Hotel in Nairobi three
days before she had to leave the country. A runner arrived from
Nkuru with the message that my father was on his way to Nairobi. He
arrived and they got married.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Butler married Desmond Butler in Nairobi Cathedral. They
remained together until his death in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves two sons, George of Holderness and Richard of
Gardiner, N.Y.; a sister, Mary Barnes of Concord, Mass.; and a
brother, Eric West of Lyme, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
