<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1396 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-HUTCHISON-HNS     03-15 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-HUTCHISON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUTCHISON CALLS CLINTON'S PLAN A `FEDERAL GRAB' FOR SHARE OF
TOBACCO MONEY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison and Texas Attorney
General John Cornyn on Monday assailed President Clinton's proposal
that Texas and other states give the federal government at least 25
percent of the billions of dollars from out-of-court settlements
with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, R-Texas, speaking at a Senate Appropriations
subcommittee hearing, derided Clinton's plan as ``a federal grab''
for a percentage of the $17.6 billion Texas wrestled from tobacco
companies after lengthy and expensive negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, a subcommittee member, has introduced legislation to
ensure that states remain free to spend their settlement money as
they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who testified at the hearing, mockingly compared the
president's effort to the tale ``The Little Red Hen,'' in which
farm animals reject a hen's request for help in the kitchen but
then have the gall to ask for her bread after it is baked.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, through its Health and Human
Services Department, has told the states that federal law requires
that they pay 57 percent of the settlement money to Medicaid, the
federal government's health care program for the poor. But under
strong opposition from Texas and other states, Clinton last month
proposed that states earmark 25 percent of the settlement money for
public education campaigns targeted at discouraging teen-agers from
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hash of HHS defended the administration's call for 57
percent, telling the subcommittee Monday that the federal
government is a ``third-party'' beneficiary to the states'
settlements with tobacco companies and is entitled to that
percentage under the Medicaid law. But Hash said the president is
willing to work with the states to reach an agreement that would
require them to put a portion of the settlement money toward
programs to reduce teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal taxpayers are entitled to their fair share,'' said
Hash, deputy administrator of HHS' Health Care Financing
Administration. ``We should work together.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchison and Cornyn rejected Hash's reading of the law and
said the federal government has no claim to the settlement money.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who chairs the subcommittee, said he
rejects the administration's specific demand that states either
surrender money to the federal government or set aside a percentage
for specific programs. Specter, however, said he would not object
to the federal government setting general guidelines for how states
should spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   But Hutchison said she would reject any proposal that would
interfere with a state's independent spending decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to keep you from dictating to the states (how
they spend) money they have earned fair and square,'' Hutchison
told Hash. ``Let's look for another funding source.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn told the subcommittee that the federal government's claim
to the settlement money under the Medicaid law is irrelevant
because neither Texas nor most of the other states sued the tobacco
industry to recover Medicaid funds they had paid to Washington. The
federal government also has no other claim to the settlement money
because it did not participate in the states' lawsuits, Cornyn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies in January 1998 agreed to pay Texas $17.3
billion over 25 years to settle the state's claims that cigarette
companies violated the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations Act, also knows as the RICO law; federal and state
antitrust and personal-injury laws; and Texas product-liability
law. The industry also agreed to pay another $3.3 billion in
attorney's fees.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas settlement is separate from the $206 billion
out-of-court agreement the tobacco industry reached with 36 other
states in November. That agreement was reached after Congress last
year failed to enact a $368 billion settlement, as the out-of-court
deal called on federal lawmakers to do.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Attorney General Mike Fisher and Tom Miller,
attorney general of Iowa, echoed Cornyn's opposition to the federal
government in their testimony before the Subcommittee on Labor,
HHS, Education and Related Agencies
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the $17.3 billion Texas settlement, $2.3 billion has been set
aside for counties and hospital districts to compensate them for
unreimbursed health-care costs. Under a proposal before the Texas
Legislature, $881 million of the settlement money would go toward a
children's health insurance program; a statewide anti-smoking pilot
program directed at children; and the creation of 11 research
endowments to benefit public health to create and operate a
children's cancer center and an institute for border health.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
