<SLUG> BC-COWGIRL-FASHION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN COWGIRL LOOK RETURNS, SANS BOOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Yeee ... haw! Cowgirl couture is back in town.
</P>
<P>
   As fashion turns its heel on '60s geek chic, start looking for
prairie panache. The details? Deep, dark denim skirts and cuffed
jeans; peasant blouses, bandanna prints and dresses with other Wild
West motifs that we haven't seen since the late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   The look is a citified version (no rhinestones), that's taken
root in the music industry, and Levi's Jeans is leading the fashion
posse. The original blue jeans company not only is sponsoring
Grammy Award winner Lauryn Hill's worldwide Miseducation Tour but
is also dressing her. According to Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. spokeswoman
Kim Sobel, ``Lauryn liked several pieces from our current
collection, including the cargo pants, dark denim jeans and denim
jacket ... and her input helped inspire the special 10-piece
collection she'll be wearing on her tour.'' Sobel added that the
youthful line reflects Hill's distinct style that's reminiscent of
the '70s, and it may be available in stores at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she says, take note that denim jackets are back, but
the latest trend is to wear them short and form-fitting in the
darkest blue possible.
</P>
<P>
   While other denim designers are bringing back red and pink jeans
to be worn with white cotton peasant blouses (remember puff
sleeves?), L.A. designers are thinking of what to wear to the next
barn dance.
</P>
<P>
   Mica's design director Judy Rabineau, is celebrating the
company's 10th anniversary with a variety of saucy country-girl
dresses, featuring empire waists and ruffled hems, in red and blue
bandanna prints and gingham checks. The dresses are priced under
$200 at Macy's and Bloomingdale's.
</P>
<P>
   Too citified?
</P>
<P>
   Try the Trail Blazer. It's a photographic image of the West at
its wildest, printed on a strapless tube dress. Designed by Hot
Kiss, the desert-themed dress is available at junior fashion
outposts such as Wet Seal and Contempo Casuals for $49.
</P>
<P>
   Now, before the dust settles and the fashionistas move on to new
territory, rethink prairie skirts with ruffled flounces and white
petticoats. Or embroidered and/or top-stitched jeans and overalls,
denim bikini tops worn with skirts or pants (very '70s), and top it
off with a colorful cowboy hat like the big 10-gallon model favored
on the head of MTV host Ananda Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   But resist the urge to pull on western boots. Dainty mules are
the shoes that separate the haute from the hayseed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1910EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
