<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1402 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-PROTEIN-BOS &LR;      03-15 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-PROTEIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTILAGE PROTEIN SHRINKS MOUSE TUMORS, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Scientists say a potent tumor-starving protein found
in cartilage has sharply curbed the spread of cancer in mouse
experiments, and could be ready for initial human tests later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the protein, troponin I, is the latest installment
in the closely-watched drama of anti-angiogenesis therapy _ the
development of non-toxic drugs to treat cancer by destroying the
life-support system of blood vessels a tumor needs to survive and
grow.
</P>
<P>
   Like glamour drugs endostatin and angiostatin that have produced
stunning anti-tumor results in mice, the new substance, called
suppresses the formation of tiny blood vessels _ angiogenesis _ and
thereby starves the tumor of nourishment from blood.
</P>
<P>
   Troponin I, isolated several years ago from animal and human
cartilage, is ``one of the most potent inhibitors'' of angiogenesis
yet discovered, said Robert Langer, an author of the paper
appearing in the current Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The PNAS issue contains a related paper in which scientists from
Duke University Medical Center say they have found the exact
structure on blood vessel cells that angiostatin binds to,
revealing how angiostatin blocks blood vessel growth.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the most potent angiogenesis inhibitors have been
angiostatin and endostatin, discovered in the Children's Hospital
laboratory of Dr. Judah Folkman. A combination of the two drugs
dramatically shrank cancers in mice.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity about the drugs has stirred enormous interest and
desperate pleas from cancer patients, even though scientists stress
the fact that they have worked only in mice and may not be
effective _ or as effective _ in humans.
</P>
<P>
   A biotechnology company and the National Cancer Institute plan
to conduct the first human tests of endostatin and angiostatin in
late 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Troponin I, first purified from veal cartilage, is a protein
that is also found in smooth muscle of the heart. It is the most
recently found of seven or eight natural angiogenesis inhibitors
discovered in the body.
</P>
<P>
   The protein was identified in the laboratories of Langer, who
has laboratories at Children's Hospital and the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, and Marsha A. Moses, who heads a
laboratory affiliated with Folkman's at Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The research was supported by Boston Life Sciences Inc., which
licensed the rights to the protein from Children's.
</P>
<P>
   It was Folkman who, 25 or 30 years ago, first proposed that
cancers must recruit new blood vessels from surrounding tissues to
survive, and that biological weapons targeted to those blood
vessels could destroy them and cause the tumor to become dormant or
shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Cartilage, because it contains no blood vessels, has seemed a
natural place to look for angiogenesis inhibitors. Langer and Moses
several years ago made an extract from cartilage that inhibited
angiogenesis, but they didn't immediately identify it.
</P>
<P>
   More recently they purified the active ingredient in the extract
and discovered that it had the same structure as troponin I, which
had been discovered earlier in muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Using laboratory animals, they showed the troponin I could block
the formation of new blood vessels. Then they injected it into mice
that one day earlier had been injected with skin cancer cells that
quickly and aggressively metastasize, or spread, to the lungs. The
drug reduced the number of lung metastases by more than half,
compared with untreated animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When compared with other angiogenesis inhibitors tested in
this same model, (troponin I) is among the most inhibitory,'' the
scientists said in their report.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman, in an interview, agreed that the new inhibitor is
``very potent.'' And, he added, ``whenever a new one (inhibitor) is
found, the message is that the body has a whole family of these
proteins whose job it is to keep blood vessels from growing'' in
certain circumstances, ``so that must be important.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marc E. Lanser, founder and chief scientific officer of
Boston Life Sciences, said his goal was to apply for and receive a
permit from the US Food and Drug Administration and begin human
trials later this year. The first patients to receive troponin I
will probably be those with sarcomas, cancers of soft tissues that
tend to metastasize quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, enthusiastic publicity about the animal results with
endostatin and angiostatin stirred premature hopes among cancer
patients who ignored warnings that cancer drugs that work in mice
may not be effective in people.
</P>
<P>
   Lanser said he wasn't concerned about such a reaction, because
``the data speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The companion scientific report in PNAS helps clarify a
longstanding question about how blood vessels are able to grow in
the hostile environment of a tumor. The center of a growing tumor
is filled with dead and dying cells because oxygen is in short
supply _ there are no blood vessels nearby to supply it.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do the tiny, new blood vessels that grow during
angiogenesis manage to survive as they form new endothelial cells
(the lining of blood vessels) to reach the tumor?
</P>
<P>
   Duke researchers Sal Pizzo and Tammy Moser answered the question
by looking at the flip side of the question: not how do the vessels
grow, but how does angiostatin, an inhibitor of angiogenesis, stop
the vessels' growth?
</P>
<P>
   They report in their paper that angiostatin binds to a molecule
on endothelial cells that scientists hadn't know was there. The
molecule -- ATP synthase _ is a kind of biochemical power pack that
provides energy to growing blood vessel cells so they can overcome
the lack of oxygen in a tumor. When angiostatin seizes the ATP
synthase molecules, it deprives the blood vessels of their crucial
power, and they die.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
