<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1403 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PLEDGE-BOS &LR;      03-15 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PLEDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC ALBANIANS SAY THEY'LL SIGN PEACE PLEDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Ethnic Albanian leaders gave a written pledge Monday
that they would sign a proposal to end months of ethnic strife in
Kosovo. This put pressure on the Yugoslav Republic's president,
Slobodan Milosevic, to do the same or face possible NATO air raids.
</P>
<P>
   But the Western allies brokering the deal set no deadline, and
it remained unclear how long Milosevic could continue to defy the
West without suffering consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The pledge was signed by Hashim Thaci, the Kosovo Liberation
Army commander who leads the ethnic Albanian delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the six-nation Contact Group on the Balkans, who
convened the Kosovo peace talks, took heart from the written pledge
because it came from Thaci. The KLA had initially balked at the
settlement that would return political automony to Kosovo because
it did not guarantee an independence referendum and called for the
KLA to disarm. Kosovo had been largely self-governing until 1989,
when Milosevic revoked its autonomy and brought the province under
the political control of Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, when the peace talks reconvened after a
three-week hiatus, Thaci handed a copy of the pledge to Christopher
Hill, the US envoy to Kosovo, asking that it be sent to US
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright. According to Hill's
spokesman, Philip Reeker, the pledge said, ``This delegation and I
personally say yes to this agreement. We would be honored to sign
at a time and place of your choosing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the logistics for having the ethnic Albanians sign the
81-page settlement had not been worked out Monday night, the
diplomatic pressure shifted to the Serbs. The initial session with
the Serb delegation was not encouraging, according to US and
European diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs say they are willing to accept the political component
of the agreement, which allows the ethnic Albanians, who make up 90
percent of the 2 million people in Kosovo _ a province in Serbia,
the dominant republic in Yugoslavia _ to run their own affairs. But
the Serbs refuse to accept the provision that calls for 28,000 NATO
troops, including 4,000 Americans, to police the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Vedrine, the French foreign minister, and his British
counterpart, Robin Cook, who are hosting the talks, said they would
meet regularly with the Serbs this week to try to persuade them to
sign.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine said the Contact Group _ the United States, Britain,
France, Germany, Italy, and Russia _ had not set a deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if there was one,'' he said, ``it would be a very brief
delay.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, Albright and Defense Secretary William S.
Cohen met with NATO general secretary Javier Solana at the White
House Monday and gently turned up the heat on Milosevic. Clinton
said afterward that bombing Serb military installations remained a
real possibility, but he sounded more conciliatory than in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to give everyone time to assess the situation,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's caution reflects a rift within the Contact Group
over the wisdom of using air strikes. While NATO's credibility is
on the line, and the prospect of backing down just a month before
NATO celebrates its 50th anniversary is galling to many NATO
members, there is no consensus for bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, who are sympathetic to the Serbs, are vehemently
opposed to using force to settle what they see as a domestic
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Europeans, the French are the most skeptical about the
wisdom of bombing. But Vedrine asserted that the Contact Group's
resolve remained strong and warned Milosevic not to test it.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, meanwhile, gave the strongest hint yet that Russian
troops, who are not part of NATO, would be part of the peacekeeping
force if the Serbs relent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would welcome them,'' Cook said he told the Russian prime
minister and foreign minister last week.
</P>
<P>
   The chief mediators, including Hill, the US ambassador to
Macedonia, are trying to sell that compromise to the skeptical
Serbs, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian negotiators had tried the patience of the Contact
Group ever since the initial round of peace talks ended
inconclusively last month at Rambouillet, 35 miles southwest of
Paris. The Albanian delegation said then that they accepted the
agreement in principle but could not sign it until they consulted
with their supporters in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there were still no formal signing, US and European
diplomats seemed assured that it was a done deal Monday, if only
because the Albanians would lose all credibility if they reversed
course again.
</P>
<P>
   While the mood among US and European diplomats was upbeat for
the first time in more than a month, the situation on the ground in
Kosovo remained unstable. Serb forces are digging in around the
southern border between Kosovo and Macedonia, shelling ethnic
Albanian villages and creating more refugees. Some 2,000
international observers inside Kosovo remain potential hostages.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the unpredictability of the situation, a
sign behind Cook and Vedrine fell down as they talked to reporters
in an opulent, chandeliered room at the French foreign ministry.
The reporters laughed. Cook and Vedrine did not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
