<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC MEMBER GANGA SAYS HE'LL FIGHT EXPULSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ A defiant Jean-Claude Ganga, insisting
he has done nothing wrong, claimed Monday that he was being
railroaded and vowed to fight his expulsion from the International
Olympic Committee before the full membership here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I am condemned, then they ask for proof,'' said Ganga,
the member from the Republic of Congo who was forced out by the
executive board in January after allegedly taking more than a
quarter of a million dollars in payoffs and gifts from the Salt
Lake City bidders for the 2002 Winter Games. ``I'm guilty until
proven innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, who was portrayed as the worst offender among the nearly
two dozen IOC members implicated in the scandal, said he was being
singled out because he led the African boycott of the 1976 Summer
Olympics in Montreal and because the IOC wanted to reduce his
continent's influence in the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true I was excluded, but I don't think it was because I
have done something wrong,'' said Ganga. ``Some heads had to be
sacrificed to save the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Four members already have resigned amid the worst scandal in
modern Olympic history, and Ganga and five others are expected to
be expelled by two-thirds of the 91 voting members.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ganga was accused of taking $70,000 in payoffs from Salt
Lake plus free medical services, lavish trips to Utah, and
expensive gifts for his family, he said he was being punished for
trifles while colleagues guilty of graver offenses have escaped
notice. He specifically mentioned vice president Richard Pound of
Canada, who chairs the inquiry panel that recommended Ganga's
expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga noted that Pound had accepted a family genealogy from the
Church of Latter Day Saints worth at least $40,000 and suggested
that Pound also had profited while acting as the IOC's TV rights
negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think this person is qualified to head the (inquiry)
commission?'' Ganga said.
</P>
<P>
   Pound flatly denied both charges Monday. The genealogy was a
``spontaneous gift'' made two years after Salt Lake was awarded the
Games, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, Canada had a candidate for 2002 (Quebec City),''
Pound said. ``It was quite clear I would not be voting for Salt
Lake in any event.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV contracts, Pound said, are approved by the 11-member
executive board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not negotiated in one dark corner of the world by one
person,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pound denied that Ganga was being singled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of these investigations are politically motivated,'' he
said. ``The facts were all divulged to us by Salt Lake City and by
their ethics report. They weren't generated by the IOC. Mr. Ganga
has been confronted with the evidence that exists and has been
given an opportunity to refute it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, who heads Africa's association of national Olympic
committees, said the $70,000 was merely being kept in his personal
bank account before being distributed to other countries. He said
he assumed there was no fee for the medical services because of a
sponsorship agreement between the Salt Lake bidders and the Utah
hospital. And Ganga insisted that he had paid for the shopping
trips himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We paid for every single item that was bought in Salt Lake
City,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga will be given 30 minutes to make his case before the full
membership, but IOC sources say privately that he is all but
certain to be expelled, along with Agustin Arroyo of Ecuador, Zein
El Abdin Ahmed Abdel Gadir of Sudan, Lamine Keita of Mali, Sergio
Santander Fantini of Chile, and Seiuli Paul Wallwork of Western
Samoa.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to recognize that the Olympic movement is organized
by human beings,'' Ganga said. ``They are not angels, they are not
saints. If you want angels and saints, go to heaven to organize the
Olympic Games. But if you organize them on this earth, you have to
organize them with human beings who have good sides and bad
sides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
