<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Tuesday, March 16. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-MISSILES (Washington) _ Seeking to contain the
political fallout from the Clinton administration's response to
suspicions that China stole nuclear secrets, two Cabinet members
explain to senators steps taken to prevent a repeat of the thefts.
By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CORRUPTION (Washington) _ Tale of a Mexican Drug Case
That Might Have Been: Early last year, as undercover U.S. Customs
agents neared the end of the biggest investigation ever conducted
into the illegal movement of drug money, money men working with
Mexico's most powerful cocaine cartel said they had clients,
including Mexico's powerful defense minister, who needed to launder
$1.15 billion. But rather than continue the undercover operation,
Clinton administration officials ordered it shut down. Senior
administration officials denied that foreign policy influenced
their decision, saying they were moved primarily by concerns for
its security. By Tim Golden. With graphic. 2,896 words. (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-POLL (New York) _ In the aftermath of the shooting
death of Amadou Diallo, fewer than a quarter of all New Yorkers
believe that the police treat blacks and whites evenly, with blacks
in particular viewing the police with fear and distrust, according
to a New York Times poll. By Dan Barry. With graphic and photo.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-INTERNET (Riyadh, Saudia Arabia) _ Ever so gingerly, the
Internet is being allowed across some final frontiers, into
restrictive parts of the Islamic world, under the wary eye of
governments used to playing Big Brother. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-RESORTS (Bernalillo, N.M.) _ After using casino gambling
over the past several years to help reverse their fortunes,
Native-American tribes are now beginning to build an entire leisure
industry on their reservations. But as the easy-money aura of
vacation resorts, gambling, golf and shopping spreads across the
land that these people have for centuries defended, worshipped and
fervently protected from outside intrusion, concern is growing
among tribal members that their religion, culture and sovereignty
are being pushed aside. By Brett Pulley. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Prugovac, Yugoslavia) _ The activity in Prugovac is a
typical operation for the Yugoslav army and police forces: A sniper
shot and wounded an army officer driving his jeep down the main
road at mid-morning, and the security forces reacted swiftly and
with full force. A few miles west, a group of ethnic Albanian
villagers stood waiting for a bus outside the village of Stanovac.
As they talked beside the road, gunfire crackled behind them. No
one even flinched. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map and KOSOVO-TALKS.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-NAVIGATOR (Washington) _ The Marine Corps drops
manslaughter and homicide charges against the navigator of the
EA-6b Prowler that hit a gondola cable in the Italian alps last
year, saying it would be ``unreasonable'' to proceed after the
pilot was acquitted of the same charges. But they said both
officers will be court-martialed on charges of obstruction of
justice. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-REPORT (Washington) _ The chairman of Medicare
commission releases final details of its reform plan, which is
intended to win enough votes on 17-member panel that disbands on
Tuesday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLPOX-VIRUS (United Nations) _ In a development likely to
have a significant impact on President Clinton's decision on
whether to support plans to destroy the world's last known samples
of smallpox virus, a new scientific report concludes that
preserving the deadly virus may provide important scientific and
medical opportunities that would be lost if the virus were
destroyed. By Judith Miller.
</P>
