<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-THEATER-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE THEATERS GROW QUICKLY AND COMPETE AMIABLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036.) 
 (fb) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ ``The Sisters Matsumoto,'' a play by Philip Kan
Gotanda about Japanese-Americans emerging from internment camps
after World War II, was ending its well-received world premiere run
at the Seattle Repertory Theater's new 286-seat house when the
theater opened a new show on its main stage: the Northwest premiere
of Martin McDonagh's Broadway hit, ``The Beauty Queen of Leenane.''
For several nights in a row the lobby of the theater at the Seattle
Center, this city's sprawling arts campus was thick with the hushed
fervor of engaged playgoers.
</P>
<P>
   It was an impressive week for the Rep, this city's flagship
theater, and for its new artistic director, Sharon Ott, who arrived
a year and a half ago from the Berkeley Repertory Theater. Her
predecessor, Daniel Sullivan, a gifted director who led the theater
to national prominence by developing new, largely mainstream plays
(Wendy Wasserstein's ``Heidi Chronicles'' and ``Sisters
Rosenzweig,'' for example) had left to pursue his own work as a
director. It has been Ms. Ott's mandate to root the theater more
firmly in the city and to reclaim its stature as a local
institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an artistic director because I'm interested in what
theaters do in a community,'' said Ms. Ott, 49. ``If I wasn't, I'd
just be a director.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, she has expanded the theater's multicultural
programming and started collaborations with local institutions like
the Seattle Asian Art Museum (where admission to the current ``Year
of Japan'' exhibition is free with a ``Sisters Matsumoto'' ticket
stub) and the Wing Luke Asian Museum, which remounted its exhibit
on the internment camps in the lobby of the Rep during the
``Sisters'' run.
</P>
<P>
   This season the theater has produced ``Play On,'' the show
created by Sheldon Epps from the music of Duke Ellington, the first
musical the Rep has put on in years. In the spring, it will stage
``Radio Mambo,'' by the Hispanic performance group Culture Clash,
the theater's first gesture in the direction of the region's Latin
population. ``We've had Asian audiences here occasionally,'' Ms.
Ott said. ``But the Hispanic population is tougher to reach.
They've probably never been here.''
</P>
<P>
   The new agenda at the Seattle Rep, which was founded in 1963, is
at the forefront of a reconfiguring of the theatrical landscape in
this city of 600,000 (about 1.8 million including the surrounding
counties). Seattle has blossomed steadily as an arts town in
general and a theater town in particular since the World's Fair of
1962, but now competition among the larger theaters has begun to
eat into the audiences for the fringe groups that have proliferated
here for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that there are three major nonprofit theaters in
Seattle, including A Contemporary Theater (known as ACT) and the
Intiman Theater, each with more than 10,000 subscribers and budgets
exceeding $3 million, is extraordinary in a city this size. All
three have had successful capital fund drives in the 1990s and
significantly improved their physical plants.
</P>
<P>
   This is in addition to the Seattle Children's Theater, perhaps
the most prominent niche theater on the West Coast, and a range of
smaller professional and nonprofessional companies (the number
ranges from 60 to 75, depending on who is estimating) sprinkled
throughout the area. And in the last decade, two nonprofit groups
have begun operating downtown theaters as houses for road show
musicals, adding 6,000 theater seats to an already swarming arena.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recently published survey by the Corporate
Council of the Arts, a Seattle-area fund-raising body that annually
makes about $2.5 million in operating grants to local arts groups,
theatergoers account for 35 percent of audiences for arts events
here, excluding for-profit enterprises like movies and pop
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably there has been a downside. On the same day that
``Beauty Queen'' opened at the Rep to laudatory reviews, there was
a bit of bad news as well. The Bathhouse Theater, a small but
locally renowned company that had survived for 20 years on spit and
gumption, finally succumbed to financial pressures and closed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
