<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1427 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-THEATER-ART-2     03-15 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
SEATTLE: and closed. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was another reminder of the growing pains the theater here
has been going through. Seattle has long been a place where eager
young companies, fed by the University of Washington's theater
program, have found a place to produce their work and people who
want to see it. Seattle is also a place where arts institutions are
famously cooperative; in 1965, when ACT opened for business as a
home for new plays, the Rep shared its subscriber list, essentially
fueling the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That set a pattern that survives today,'' said Peter Donnelly,
the former managing director of the Rep and now the president of
the Corporate Council. ``As a result the arts have had a collective
face in the city that you don't get when you're squabbling all over
each other. The arts are at the table in every important community
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, audience-building has become more competitive than ever
with the recent expansions of the Rep, the Intiman, across the
alley at the Seattle Center, and ACT, on the other side of downtown
in the former national headquarters of the Fraternal Order of
Eagles and with corporate money from the young computer industry
beginning to find its way to the arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more and more theater happening here,'' said Susan
Trapnell, managing director of ACT. ``At a certain point you can't
keep growing new theaters in a city this size.'' Indeed, in
addition to the Bathhouse, the city has lost several other small
theaters in the last year, including its only company devoted to
multicultural programming, the Group Theater, and its only gay and
lesbian theater, Alice B.
</P>
<P>
   The Langston Hughes Cultural Center, a neighborhood arts center
housed in a former synagogue, is, with city support, in its second
year of producing work with largely African-American themes, but
aside from that there is no black theater in the city either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community used to be smaller and more niched,'' said
Melissa Hines, the managing director of Empty Space, an
experimental theater that was founded in 1970 and is the city's
third oldest. ``The growth that has taken place has also introduced
fascinating problems.''
</P>
<P>
   All the lost theaters had specific difficulties to combat. The
Group, for example, was forced from its home on the university
campus to a more expensive space in the Seattle Center just when it
suffered a withdrawal of foundation support. But part of the
problem is also the expansion of programming in the three large
houses, which gobbled up audiences and financial support.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening in the theater ecology is the larger houses
are becoming more stable and doing strong work,'' said Tim Bond,
the former artistic director of the Group. ``And the small to
midsize theaters are losing their funding and audience support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Group led the way in diversity programming here, but as
the other theaters began to make headway in that direction, we had
funders tell us, `We've given our multicultural dollars for the
year.'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Big Three, which were founded with distinct
missions (the Rep as a standard repertory house, ACT focusing on
new plays and the Intiman, which opened in 1972, devoted to
classics, with an emphasis on Ibsen and Strindberg), have all begun
in the last decade to pursue a similarly broad agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In one way, the theaters complement one another; ACT and the
Intiman both run spring to fall schedules, minimizing their
head-to-head competition with the Rep and allowing multiple
subscribers the chance to pursue their theatergoing year round. But
of course they compete with each other, and all three wage regular
battles for the rights to put on shows like ``Beauty Queen,''
``Three Tall Women'' (Intiman) and ``Side Man'' (ACT).
</P>
<P>
   One might expect ``Sisters Matsumoto'' to be a natural for ACT;
by the same token, ``Death of a Salesman'' and ``The Crucible''
should fit most easily at the Rep, but ACT did the former in 1997
and will do the latter this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time has gone on, we've become more and more alike,'' said
Benjamin Moore, the Rep's managing director since 1985. ``Some
people think we should all merge and become one big theater.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, won't happen, though Ms. Ott raised the idea of
the Rep, the Intiman and ACT's combining resources to sponsor a
theater festival. What is more certain is that the three theaters
will use their new facilities to distinguish themselves in ways
that have yet to be determined. The Rep is unusual in that it has
two proscenium houses, ACT's main stage is a theater in the round,
and the Intiman features a semi-thrust stage.
</P>
<P>
   Their programming is bound to be informed by the ascent of new
leaders. Gordon Edelstein, formerly an associate artistic director
at the Long Wharf Theater in Connecticut, took over the artistic
reins at ACT in September 1997. Shook, who has presided for seven
years over a resurgence of the Intiman, has announced that this
year would be his last. A search for his replacement has begun.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is general agreement among institutional
administrators that both corporate and individual arts philanthropy
is a seriously undertapped resource. Several older corporations
with headquarters here _ Boeing, Weyerhauser and Safeco Insurance,
three of the largest _ have been steady arts contributors. Now a
new generation of givers flush with high-tech profits has begun to
emerge, and arts groups have begun to focus on them in hopes of
establishing a serious habit of arts support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this town could be much more of an intellectual and
international center for the arts than it has been,'' Ms. Ott said.
``It's located well, on the Pacific Rim, in a vibrant part of the
world. There is money here and the potential for patronage. All the
businesses here have global interests, and I don't think it's too
much to think that the performing arts will share in that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
