<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1430 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      03-15 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WARNS OF NATO ATTACK IF SERBS REJECT PEACE PROCESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Kosovo's ethnic Albanians agreeing to a
cease-fire, President Clinton and NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana threatened airstrikes Monday if the Yugoslavs show any
``intransigence or aggression'' against the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders warned during a meeting at the White House that
they would have little choice but to use military force against
Serbian troops if Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic does not
agree to the cease-fire and the posting of NATO troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Milosevic) shows intransigence and aggression, from my
point of view we would have little option,'' Clinton told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Solana agreed. ``If an agreement is not reached and President
Milosevic doesn't sign, the risk of a catastrophe will be very
likely, and we have to prevent that from happening,'' said Solana,
who heads the 19-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Milosevic has balked at allowing NATO to station about
28,000 peacekeeping troops in Kosovo, likening it to a foreign
invasion of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, ethnic Albanians refused to go along with the
peace accord, which requires Serbian forces to withdraw from Kosovo
and calls for the Kosovo Liberation Army to disarm. The army has
been fighting to free the largely Albanian region from Serb
control.
</P>
<P>
   Even as peace talks continued in Paris, however, both the
Yugoslav army and the KLA bombarded villages with tanks and rocket
and rifle fire, setting houses ablaze and wounding at least eight
Yugoslav soldiers. The army said it also ``inflicted losses'' on
the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   During the last year, fighting between the Kosovo rebels and
Serbian security forces has killed 2,000 people. More than 300,000
people have lost their homes. U.S. officials say Serbia has
recently posted more troops in the province, has begun mining
routes they expect NATO troops to take from Macedonia into the
province, and over the weekend has shelled three rebel-held
villages in northern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright received a
letter in which Hashim Thaqi, chief negotiator for the Kosovo
Albanians, promised to sign the cease-fire accord. The agreement
calls for three years of autonomy for Kosovo, a period in which
NATO troops _ including 4,000 U.S. soldiers _ are to maintain peace
between the warring ethnic groups. The letter also was sent to the
foreign ministers of Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
   ``This delegation and I personally say `Yes' to this
agreement,'' Thaqi wrote. ``We would be honored to sign this
agreement in your presence at a time and place of your choosing.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbian President Milan Milutnovic played down the significance
of the Kosovo Albanians' agreement to sign the peace deal, saying
that ``unilateral signing does not mean anything.'' He also
dismissed threats of airstrikes. ``This is not out of the question,
but we are not afraid of that,'' Milutnovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen and German Defense Minister
Rudolf Scharping cautioned the Serbs to go along with the deal,
noting that U.S. and other NATO forces in Europe are still on alert
to launch immediate strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope (Milosevic) will see the handwriting is very much on
the wall for him to observe, and will take peaceful action as
opposed to seeking greater conflict,'' Cohen said at a news
conference with Scharping.
</P>
<P>
   The German defense minister said Milosevic is mistaken if he
believes NATO might be unwilling to act if necessary. ``Mr.
Milosevic must be clear that NATO is ready and decided to act if
necessary,'' Scharping said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO currently has more than 400 attack and support aircraft
within striking distance of Serb targets, a contingent assigned to
the region five weeks ago when Milosevic refused to participate in
the peace deal. The aircraft include U.S. B-52 bombers and
radar-avoiding F-117A ``stealth'' fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Although the peace talks resumed Monday in Paris, State
Department officials said Albright currently is not planning to
participate and has no immediate plans to travel to Europe for
Thaqi's signing of the accord.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, officials indicated they would not wait for
Thaqi's signature to put military heat on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the pressure is indeed shifted, and I think the spotlight
is going to shine very brightly on the Serb side to agree,'' said
State Department spokesman James Rubin. ``They are still not
engaging seriously on the fundamental question'' of allowing NATO
peacekeepers into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton indicated no strike was imminent and
that negotiators should be given time to bring Milosevic and his
allies around to signing the agreement. At the same time, he said,
stalling will not be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ought to be able to talk this through a little bit,'' the
president said. ``But, obviously, they can't go on indefinitely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would encourage Mr. Milosevic to agree to the terms as well
so that we can avoid further conflict and bloodshed,'' Clinton
said. ``From his point of view, I think it's the best chance to
preserve the integrity of Serbia and avoid economic and other
adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
