<HEADLINE>
LINCOLN CENTER TO REVIVE OPERA THWARTED BY CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.) (fb) 
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lincoln Center announced Monday that it would present
a complete 20-hour production of the classic Chinese opera ``The
Peony Pavilion'' similar to the one that was canceled last summer
after cultural officials in Shanghai refused to allow the
performers to leave China.
</P>
<P>
   The work, staged by the New York-based director of last summer's
aborted production and featuring the same charismatic Chinese
performer as its female lead, is to be presented throughout Lincoln
Center Festival '99, which runs from July 7 to 25.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of the production has been envisioned virtually
since it was called off last year. But the production has become
much more expensive, partly because it is being produced in the
United States. Substantial donations and a crucial financial gift
recently from Bloomberg News are making the production possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came at a good moment,'' Beverly Sills, the chairwoman of
the board of Lincoln Center, said of the contribution. It was
described only as being ``in the mid-six figures'' and was
announced by Michael R. Bloomberg, the founder of Bloomberg News
and a member of the board, at a meeting of the board's executive
committee on Feb. 23. ``It takes away an enormous burden,'' Sills
said.
</P>
<P>
   The staging, by Chen Shi-Zheng, a New York director and
performer, is closely modeled after his innovative production with
performers of the Shanghai Kunqu Opera Company, which was to have
been the centerpiece of the Lincoln Center Festival last year.
Shanghai cultural officials intervened just as sets and costumes
were to have been shipped from the Shanghai International Airport
last summer, jeopardizing the festival schedule. The shipment was
freed after several days of negotiation, but the company was denied
permission to leave, forcing cancellation of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent presentations in Paris, Sydney and Hong Kong were
also canceled. The Festival d'Automne in France has again joined
forces with Lincoln Center and is to present the work in Caen and
Paris in November. Presentations elsewhere are being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Chen recently began rehearsals with a mostly new troupe at an
undisclosed location on the East Coast. The only holdovers from the
Shanghai company are Qian Yi, a gifted young performer who plays
the heroine in the romantic epic, and Zhou Ming, a flutist who
leads the little orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve other performers have come or are coming from Beijing and
elsewhere in China. The rest of the 21 cast members and 12
instrumentalists are Chinese citizens living in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether any derring-do had been required to enlist
performers from Shanghai and China in light of the diplomatic furor
that arose last summer, Nigel Redden, the festival director, said
only, ``They all got out legally.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any of the performers, many of them young, would have
difficulty returning to China and resuming their careers there,
Redden said: ``We went to great lengths to talk to people who know
about such matters, and everyone encouraged us to go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that ultimately the individuals and their families
were the best judges of that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Chen, who left China in 1987 and has often returned there to
work, said: ``It's a fast-changing society in many ways. The
performers are confident that they will be able to work both in
America and in China.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When the Lincoln Center production was canceled last summer, the
sets and costumes, all painstakingly handmade in China, were
shipped to France for a scheduled presentation in November. They
have arrived back in New York unused.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the sets, which are made of fitted wood, without nails,
will need minor rebuilding, Redden said, but the 800 pieces of
clothing that make up the more than 500 embroidered costumes are in
good shape and need little attention other than refitting for
different performers.
</P>
<P>
   Redden traveled to Shanghai last summer to join Chen in
last-ditch negotiations with Ma Bomin, the director of the Shanghai
Municipal Bureau of Culture and the central figure in the dispute.
The bureau, which considers itself the guardian of the ancient
regional tradition of Kunqu opera, judged the production
pornographic, feudal and superstitious, and therefore a
misrepresentation of Kunqu tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau was seconded in that opinion by some Kunqu adherents
elsewhere, including the New York Kunqu Society, which recently
presented a three-hour condensed version of ``The Peony Pavilion''
as a lesson in proper performance style. Another condensation of
similar length but pointedly untraditional style, directed by Peter
Sellars and with new music by Tan Dun, had its American premiere
this month in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Peony Pavilion,'' written by Tang Xianzu in 1598, has come
down as a canonic work in the tradition of Kunqu, one of the most
venerable and refined forms of Chinese opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we're not going to call it Kunqu,'' Chen said of his
production. ``It uses the Kunqu music, but we're just going to call
it my interpretation of Tang Xianzu's work and not refer to any
particular tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival also plans to present a symposium in collaboration
with the New School University exploring the topic ``Who owns
tradition?'' and related issues surrounding the cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always hoped we could revive the production,'' said Nathan
Leventhal, the president of Lincoln Center. ``The forces that tend
to prevent freedom of expression can't win. We can't let them
win.''
</P>
<P>
   The same issues evidently led to the Bloomberg News
contribution. ``We are a communication company,'' Bloomberg said.
``We feel strongly about freedom of the press, freedom of
expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen, who had spent eight months in intensive rehearsals with
the Shanghai troupe for the production last year, was initially
skeptical about starting again.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought I should just put it away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has only four months to duplicate what he achieved in
twice that time last year: a production that the French newspaper
Le Monde called ``one of the major cultural events of the end of
the 20th century'' on the basis of the dress rehearsal in Shanghai.
As in Shanghai, Chen has older, more experienced performers working
with the younger ones.
</P>
<P>
   The ill-fated production last year cost about half a million
dollars, with Lincoln Center covering two-fifths of the budget and
its co-commissioners in Paris, Hong Kong and Sydney, Australia,
covering the rest. For the current production, Lincoln Center
expects to invest $1.1 million and $300,000 in donated goods or
services. Additional costs will be incurred by the Festival
d'Automne and other partners that may pick up the production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing a more difficult prospect than last year,''
Redden said. ``This has not been a producing festival but a
presenting festival. Now we have to come up with rehearsal space
and a supporting staff for a large company.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Center Festival is to include 10 other events, some
consisting of several parts. They are to be announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Each presentation of ``The Peony Pavilion'' is to consist of six
segments. Three complete cycles are to be presented at the 800-seat
La Guardia Concert Hall, near Lincoln Center. The first cycle
comprises one installment each on July 7 and 8, and two on July 9
and 10. The other presentations take place July 16-18 and July
23-25, with two segments staged each day.
</P>
</TEXT>
