<HEADLINE>
NO GUARANTEES NEW BANKING ENTITY CAN FEND OFF ACQUIRERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston Corp. tout their
proposed merger as a way to ensure that Boston will always have a
hometown bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important day for these two companies, and we hope
an important day for New England,'' Fleet's chief executive,
Terrence Murray, crowed at a press conference Monday to announce
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that there will be no guarantees in the next
millennium for bankers wishing to maintain independence _ not even
for the chief executives of the two biggest banks in New England,
Murray and his counterpart at BankBoston, Charles Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   Today's financial world is being transformed so rapidly and so
dramatically that big never seems to be big enough, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, globalization and cross-industry mergers in the
financial industry wiped out all boundaries to doing business _
witness Germany's largest bank, Deutsche Bank AG, cutting a deal in
November to purchase Manhattan-based Bankers Trust Corp. And
cross-country mergers became vogue with the matchup of BankAmerica
Corp. in San Francisco and NationsBank Corp. in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In heady talk hours after the Fleet-BankBoston merger
announcement, there was talk that Fleet Boston Corp. might one day
pair up with Boston's biggest insurer, John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this company, Fleet Boston, if it wants to compete
with the big banks in this country, will need to grow to $300
billion in assets in the next five years,'' said Gerard Cassidy,
banking analyst for Tucker Anthony Inc.
</P>
<P>
   If a banking company is big enough, the theory goes, then it is
too big to take over. As a bank grows in size, there are fewer
banks with enough market capitalization to buy them out.
</P>
<P>
   A Fleet-BankBoston merger, if approved by regulators, would
create the nation's eight-largest bank with $178 billion in assets.
``When you get near $200 billion, you're only going to be bought if
you want to be bought,'' said Nancy Bush, senior vice president of
Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co., a Livingston, N.J., investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure to merge would intensify, other analysts said, if the
newly merged Boston institution isn't profitable enough to keep its
share price high. That's what happened to BankBoston _ its stock
price dropped from a 52-week high of 58 11/16 partly because of
financial disaster in emerging financial markets that rocked the
company's substantial operations in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston closed Monday at 47 1/16, up 1/8, in reaction to the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, where investment banking fees are commensurate
with the size of the deal, deal makers scoff and say Fleet Boston
is not immune. ``They're not too big to be gobbled up,'' said one
New York investment banker who asked not to be named. ``There are
still much bigger players out there.''
</P>
<P>
   There is Citigroup, a $669 billion institution formed in the
unprecedented merger of the nation's largest bank, Citicorp, and
insurance behemoth Travelers Corp. And there is BankAmerica, which
has $618 billion in assets _ three times more than Fleet Boston
would have.
</P>
<P>
   James Moynihan, senior vice president of Advest Inc., said
Fleet's ownership of BankBoston's premier franchise in Brazil would
make Fleet Boston attractive _ and vulnerable _ to a whole new
league of international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these New York banks would dearly love to have some of
Latin America,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of such megamergers is highly speculative at a time when
the merger has not been approved by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, analysts said, there are two likely routes for
Murray. One is to continue on his well-worn path, acquiring small
and large banking companies and nonbanking companies. Murray has a
history of aggressive acquisitions, including virtually every major
bank in the region as well as Quick &AMP; Reilly, the discount
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Boston is limited in how much it could expand inside the
region through acquisitions of smaller banks. With its heavy
concentration in urban markets _ namely Boston, Hartford, and
Providence _ it would quickly run into problems with regulators.
The banks said Monday that they would be required to divest some
$13 billion in deposits and sell branches and ATMs to comply with
regulatory antitrust hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Edward J. Kane, professor of finance at Boston College, said
Fleet may one day seek merger partners among banking companies
outside the region in a bid to extend its geographic reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they say is plausible _ it's big enough for the time
being and it may want to make some out-of-region takeovers to
become a truly national enterprise,'' Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors swirled Monday that Boston insurer John Hancock might be
Fleet's next merger game. ``It's ridiculous,'' said Stephen Burgay,
a Hancock spokesman, about the rumor. The company's plan to sell
public stock ``is our priority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
