<HEADLINE>
ECUADORAN BANKS REOPEN, BUT TENSIONS PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ Banks here reopened Monday for the first time
in more than a week after a government decree closed them because
of a worsening financial crisis. But tensions remained high, the
result of a strike by taxi drivers that blocked roads and brought
commerce and transport to a near halt throughout this Andean
country.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Ecuador's cities, irate cab drivers blocked key
intersections with their yellow vehicles, built barricades and set
tires and tree trunks on fire. They were protesting increases of
nearly 200 percent in the price of gasoline, to more than $3 a
gallon, announced Thursday by President Jamil Mahuad as part of a
broader austerity package that unions have vowed to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about politics,'' said Alberto Carrillo, a
64-year-old taxi driver, as he and colleagues stood near a burning
barricade. ``This is about being able to make a living, and we are
not backing down until the government rescinds these measures that
are crippling the middle class and the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The only signs of real activity Monday were outside bank
branches, where depositors began lining up at dawn in hopes of
retrieving money from accounts that have been blocked to them all
of last week.
</P>
<P>
   The bank reopening was regarded as an important test for
Ecuador, one of Latin America's most impoverished countries, which
has been battling what the government is calling the worst
financial crisis since the Great Depression. A combination of low
prices for oil exports, damage from El Nino, pressing government
debts and the broader economic problems that have hurt Ecuador's
giant neighbor, Brazil, have sent the economy into a tailspin.
Ecuador has been negotiating with the International Monetary Fund
for a rescue package.
</P>
<P>
   A pent-up demand for the currency, the sucre, and speculation by
some banks helped the sucre surge in value when the banks reopened
Monday. The sucre was trading at 9,050 to the dollar in late
Monday, 30 percent higher than its level of 12,500 to the dollar
after the banks were closed March 5.
</P>
<P>
   President Jamil Mahuad had ordered the banks to close in hopes
of preventing a run on deposits that had seized the country amid
signs that several large banks are on the verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I took everything out, every last cent,'' Juan Caicedo, a
31-year-old mechanic, said Monday morning after closing an account
that had less than $200 in it and therefore was not subject to
restrictions on withdrawals Mahuad decreed Thursday. ``I have no
confidence in any of the banks, and since no one can guarantee to
me they won't collapse, I'm going to invest this in something else
until I feel that it is safe to return.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Mahuad, a 49-year-old Harvard-educated lawyer,
declared a 60-day state of national emergency. Though army and
police units have been patrolling the streets ever since, they have
been sparing in their use of force, apparently fearful of fanning
popular discontent.
</P>
<P>
   Many bus drivers joined in Monday's taxi strike, and the lack of
public transportation paralyzed much of daily life. Most stores and
businesses did not open Monday morning. Those that did seemed to be
operating with a skeleton staff, their employees unable to get to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Molina, a secretary for a fruit juice bottler, was one of
those who was forced to stay home. Six months pregnant, she felt
she should not walk to work, and was worried because she is running
out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no buses, no trucks, no transport at all,'' she
said. ``My paycheck was deposited directly in the bank, and I
couldn't get at it all of last week. This economy is really fatal,
and I don't know what is going to become of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Ecuador's 12 million people had hoped the situation here
would calm down after a two-day general strike last week, but
Monday's work stoppage contributed to a sense that things are only
getting worse. ``The country finds itself on the verge of
anarchy,'' the daily newspaper ``Hoy'' warned Monday in a front
page editorial, blaming what it called the ``blindness of political
leaders and the intransigence of unions.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders have promised further strikes this week, with some
even threatening to occupy banks. In addition, the leader of the
country's main coalition of American Indian organizations, Antonio
Vargas, has called for a ``popular uprising'' to defeat the
president's austerity package, which has been widely criticized by
members of the opposition-dominated Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot go on like this,'' Carlos Torres, a 29-year-old
X-ray technician, said Monday, despair in his voice. ``The country
has been paralyzed for a week, and nobody is producing anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
