<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-LAWYER-SLAIN-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER WHO REPRESENTED BELFAST CATHOLICS KILLED IN CAR BOMB 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A well-known human rights lawyer who had received death
threats for her work representing Catholics in one of Northern
Ireland's most volatile communities was killed Monday when a bomb
blew up her car as she drove from her home.
</P>
<P>
   A renegade Protestant guerrilla group, the Red Hand Defenders,
claimed responsibility for the blast in a telephone call Monday
night to the BBC in Belfast that used an authenticating code word.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Nelson, 40, suffered fatal stomach injuries in the
explosion, which occurred 50 yards from the primary school in
Lurgan, where her sister is a teacher and her 8-year-old daughter
was on lunch break. Two sons, 11 and 13, were away in France on a
school ski trip.
</P>
<P>
   Her car had been parked outside her house while she was in the
Irish Republic with her husband, Paul, an accountant. Police on
Monday night appealed for information from witnesses who might have
seen any activity in her driveway over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nelson had represented the residents of the Catholic
housing projects lining the Garvaghy Road in nearby Portadown that
has repeatedly been a flash point in Northern Ireland's sectarian
conflict. It is the thoroughfare from Drumcree Church that
uniformed men of the Orange Order have tried to walk at the
beginning of the Protestant ``marching season'' each July,
provoking province-wide violence.
</P>
<P>
   The main paramilitary groups in Northern Ireland have been
maintaining cease-fires while their political representatives took
part in the negotiations that led to the peace settlement that
faces an April 2 deadline to be put into effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Hand Defenders are a small band of dissidents dedicated
to upsetting the accord, and Mrs. Nelson's death is the third they
have claimed since they began a campaign of pipe bomb attacks on
Catholic families and of arson attacks on churches last May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sole aim of the murderers is to remove any chance of
reconciliation,'' said British Prime Minister Tony Blair in London.
``They will not be allowed to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nelson had gone with a group from Garvaghy Road to 10
Downing Street last month to discuss the Drumcree standoff with
Blair. She was quoted in Monday morning's Irish News saying the
confrontation had left community relations in the town in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing occurred as the political leaders of Northern
Ireland were gathering in Washington, where they hoped to resolve
remaining disagreements with the help of President Clinton, who was
a major force behind the peace accord signed last year on April 10.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart opened his daily news
briefing Monday with a statement from the president calling the
bombing a ``despicable and cowardly act.''
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists and First Minister
of the new Northern Ireland Assembly, called the murder ``an
appalling act'' and said ``at the end of the day it is going to be
counter-productive and it is not going to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, called Mrs. Nelson a beacon
for truth and justice whose killing put an onus on the signatories
to the pact to overcome obstacles to putting it into effect.
</P>
<P>
   The accord was endorsed in referendums in the Irish Republic and
British-ruled Ulster.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has set Good Friday, April 2, as the deadline for
transferring home rule to Belfast from London, but politicians in
Northern Ireland are at an impasse over the issue of paramilitary
disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Adams insists that leaders of Sinn Fein, the political wing of
the Irish Republican Army, must be able to take up all the seats
they are entitled to in the new assembly cabinet. Trimble says he
will not admit them until the IRA signals a willingness to start
dismantling its arsenal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Nelson visited New York last April to inform U.N. and U.S.
officials about the intimidation of lawyers in Northern Ireland.
Martin McGuinness, the chief Sinn Fein negotiator, said it was ``a
well-known fact'' that her life had been threatened repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nelson disclosed last week that she had prepared 200
compensation claims against the Royal Ulster Constabulary from
Catholics injured in the Drumcree confrontations. A group of
demonstrators marched to police headquarters in Lurgan Monday night
with black flags and spray painted ``Disband the RUC'' slogans on
the barracks walls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
