u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLPOX-VIRUS-1     03-15 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLPOX-VIRUS-1,000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE PANEL SAYS PRESERVING LETHAL VIRUS COULD YIELD BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ An independent scientific panel has concluded
that preserving the world's last known samples of deadly smallpox
virus in Russia and the United States may provide important
scientific and medical opportunities that would be lost if the
virus is destroyed later this year as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The report issued Monday by a 19-member committee of the
prestigious National Academy of Sciences' Institute of Medicine is
likely to influence significantly President Clinton's thinking
about this politically and scientifically contentious issue.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The New York Times in January, Clinton said
he would rely heavily on guidance provided by the Institute of
Medicine report in formulating his administration's position on
whether the stocks should be retained or destroyed. Clinton said he
would rely on the report's recommendations to ensure that the
United States would have ``whatever it takes to buy us a response
[to a potential smallpox outbreak) as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The 100-page report did not express an opinion whether the
stocks should, or should not be destroyed, since the panel of
experts was asked to examine only the potential value that such a
stock provides.
</P>
<P>
   But its main conclusion that retaining the virus could lead to
``new and important discoveries with real potential for improving
human health'' _ including the development of new antiviral drugs
to protect citizens against a future smallpox outbreak _ is likely
to strengthen the hand of those within the administration who want
the United States to join Russia in opposing the destruction of the
highly infectious, lethal virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt the report will have a major impact,'' said a
senior White House official who has closely followed the explosive
debate both within American scientific circles and at the United
Nations. ``Science is science, and the science that has now spoken
will dramatically affect the decision-making process here.''
</P>
<P>
   Prominent American scientists, such as Donald A. Henderson, a
former deputy White House science adviser and dean emeritus of
Johns Hopkins School of Public Health, helped lead the campaign for
eradication and then the destruction of all smallpox stocks soon
after the World Health Organization, a Geneva-based agency of the
United Nations, certified in 1980 that smallpox had, in fact, been
eradicated. In 1996, the WHO recommended that the remaining stocks
of the dangerous virus be destroyed, a decision then supported by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the WHO also decided, again with Washington's
agreement, to recommend that destruction be deferred til June 30 of
this year so that, among other things, the scientific consequences
of destruction could be more fully evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the 190-member group are scheduled to meet in
Geneva to review the issue in May, and many poorer nations that
suffered the worst smallpox epidemics are expected to press hard
for the virus' destruction as scheduled. Officially, the world's
only remaining collections of live virus are now kept only by the
federal Centers for Disease Control, in Atlanta, and at the State
Research Center of Virology and Biotechnology, known as Vector, a
leading Russian research institute in Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   But many American experts now agree that smallpox samples may
have already been secured by rogue states or terrorist groups
seeking to wreak havoc or settle grudges.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview late last year, Lev. S. Sandakhchiev, Vector's
director, denied allegations that Russia had given samples to
suspect nations, such as North Korea. He also spoke passionately
against destruction of the virus, arguing, as he has in scientific
papers, that infectious diseases like smallpox cannot ever be
considered completely eradicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Infectious disease eradicated can return anytime,'' he said,
sometimes in even more virulent form. Sandakhchiev has proposed
that international research teams work together at Vector to devise
new antiviral drugs and more effective vaccines against smallpox
and other viruses.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine report issued Monday concluded that
the most ``compelling'' reason for long-term retention of smallpox,
or live variola virus stocks, was ``their essential role in the
identification and development of antiviral agents for use in
anticipation of a large outbreak of smallpox.'' Supplies of the
existing vaccine ``have dwindled and may be deteriorating,'' the
report warned.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the current vaccine is a live virus that ``cannot be
used safely with immunocompromised individuals,'' such as those
infected with HIV or who have had organ transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the report notes, ``much scientific information,
particularly concerning the human immune system, could be learned
through experimentation'' with the smallpox virus. Smallpox, the
report notes, ``was eradicated before the development of many
modern techniques of microbiology.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, the leading advocate of destruction, expressed
``disappointment'' in the report's conclusions, saying he wished
the panel's findings had been ``more balanced.'' Destroying the
stocks, he argues, would effectively criminalize the use of the
disease as a weapon and send a powerful moral signal that even
rogue states or terrorists could ill ignore.
</P>
<P>
   He maintained that new antiviral drugs could theoretically be
developed without the live smallpox collections, and said he
doubted that drug companies or even the government would invest the
$200-400 million required to produce such new drugs from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The developing world has been been very unhappy that Big
Brother and Russia have retained these stocks. They have worked
very hard to get rid of this terrible scourge, and yet those who
argue that the strains must be kept for research are not doing
research on them,'' Henderson said. ``So I understand when they
ask: What right do you have to retain these strains? What if some
of them escape, why should we have to fight this fight all over
again?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the past year, the Clinton administration has debated
whether the United States should formally oppose destruction at
this time, as Russia did last year. An interagency group is
scheduled to meet at the week's end to consider the issue again,
now in light of the Institute of Medicine report, and come to a
formal decision by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine report, however, appears to strengthen
considerably the retention camp in its strong endorsement of the
potential value of stock retention.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in the interview in January, said that while the United
States had supported destruction of the live virus stocks in 1996,
``we're concerned about having adequate stocks of the vaccine,''
and, he added, ``we want to have some way of conducting research
because smallpox, or any kind of virus, can be wrinkled, if you
will, twisted, turned a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   While he knew that much of the world favored destruction, he
said the United States would be the most likely country ``rushing
in'' to a poor country to help it contain a future outbreak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
