<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE TROUBLE SEEN ON DEFAULTED RUSSIAN DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A group of 19 Western banks holding $15 billion in
defaulted short-term Russian government debt headed for deeper
division on Monday after the largest creditor, Credit Suisse First
Boston, broke the group's already fractured ranks to announce a new
ruble-based investment fund aimed at recovering the bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by Credit Suisse First Boston represented the
second time in recent weeks that the lender banks had been divided
over the best way to recover at least some of a debt that no one
expects to be repaid in full.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting in London on Monday, participants said at least
one other major bank in the group felt that Credit Suisse First
Boston had, in the words of a banker who spoke in return for
anonymity, ``cut a side deal'' with the Russians without the
knowledge of the other members of the creditors' committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew Ipkendanz, appointed by Credit Suisse First Boston to
head the fund, disputed that, saying, ``The fund is open to all
banks and their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The same charges of separate dealing were leveled last month at
Deutsche Bank and Chase Manhattan, which accepted Russian terms for
debt restructuring _ said to be worth no more than 5 cents on the
dollar and possibly less _ when the others did not and before
Russian authorities had disclosed the full terms of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston, a unit of the Credit Suisse Group,
said Monday that its Nikitsky Recovery Fund, which will last at
least seven years, would provide an alternative to the Russian
terms, enabling creditors to invest in infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
   Participants at Monday's meeting said officials of Credit Suisse
First Boston had been reluctant to say whether the Russian central
bank had agreed to the terms of the new fund.
</P>
<P>
   But Ipkendanz, appointed as head of the fund, and who previously
led the Emerging Markets Fixed Income Group of Credit Suisse First
Boston, said in a telephone interview: ``We have been in a dialogue
at the highest level with the Russian government, and they have
approved in principle the creation of the fund. We are working on
the details and expect an announcement soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse said it would provide management and a $15 million
loan to the fund. But other bankers complained that the deal also
involved a management fee of 2 percent of the net asset value,
payable to Baiame Strategic Advisers Ltd., to be headed by
Ipkendanz.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank had been acting as the leader of the creditor
banks in negotiations with the Russians until it broke with the
group a few weeks ago and cut its own deal. The other banks decided
to proceed without a leader, which raised questions over the
group's future.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's development deepened that uncertainty by leaving the
creditor banks facing two clear options _ to accept Russia's terms
by a deadline of April 15, or to sign up for the Credit Suisse
First Boston fund by March 31. But bankers said that both
alternatives were risky and that one could undermine the other.
</P>
<P>
   The debt involves GKO Treasury bills and OFZ Finance Ministry
bonds held by foreign institutions when Russia defaulted on
billions in Treasury debt last August, setting off wide financial
trouble. Roughly a third of the debt was held by foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   In tortuous negotiations since then, Russian authorities offered
to refinance the debt in the form of new bonds and ruble payments
but they did not provide full details of the vaguely worded
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Deutsche Bank and Chase Manhattan accepted the deal
last month. Chase said it agreed to exchange its own holdings,
though not those of clients, while Deutsche Bank agreed to swap
part of its own holdings and some client holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston said it would contribute most of its
proprietary holdings to the new fund, adding in as statement that
it believed ``investors must be offered a real alternative to the
restructuring terms presently proposed by the Russians.'' It argued
that the 19-bank committee ``is not an effective forum to pursue
that alternative approach.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the statement said that Credit Suisse
First Boston would remain as a member of the committee ``in order
to obtain the best solution possible for those GKO and OFZ holders
who wish to participate in the Russians' restructuring.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, said that the new fund's existence could
weaken Russia's commitment to its existing repayment terms. And,
said an opponent who spoke in return for anonymity, ``it shows the
Russians that now the ranks of the creditors are truly divided.''
</P>
</TEXT>
