<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-COMMISSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE COMMISSION TO WEIGH PLAN WITH DRUG BENEFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The leaders of the bipartisan commission struggling
to resuscitate Medicare unveiled a compromise plan Monday that
would for the first time cover the cost of prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The plan ``represents both good policy as well as good
politics,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La., co-author of the proposal
and chairman of the 17-member National Bipartisan Commission on the
Future of Medicare. It ``does what the people of this country want
us to do, that is to save Medicare (and) guarantee it will be there
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux and Rep. William Thomas, R-Calif., will present the plan
up at the commission's final meeting Tuesday in a gamble that it
will win the 11 votes required by law for a formal recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   But Breaux and Thomas, the co-chairman of the panel, made clear
that even if their plan does not win 11 votes, they intend to take
it to the floor of Congress for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal that we will present is the only reasonable way
to go,'' Thomas said. ``The work product of this commission will
become law.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan is a new version of one introduced in January by Breaux
but retains the central feature of Breaux's original proposal: A
new government subsidy that would partly fund the purchase of
private health insurance tailored to the needs and income of
elderly people. Beneficiaries also would pay a premium averaging 12
percent of the total cost.
</P>
<P>
   But beneficiaries also could elect to stay in the existing
``fee-for-service'' system, in which the government pays set
amounts for medical bills and beneficiaries pay the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The plan unveiled Monday differs from the January version
because it adds coverage for prescription drugs. Under the new
proposal, health plans would be required to offer prescription
coverage for which beneficiaries would be expected to pay higher
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income beneficiaries _ a yearly income of up to $10,568 for
individuals and $13,334 for couples _ would be eligible for full
government coverage of prescriptions under the federal Medicaid
program.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had been deadlocked on what kind of fix is needed
for the 34-year-old program of government-paid medical assistance
to the elderly. Seven of the committee's nine Democratic members
want the prescription benefit but oppose the Breaux concept of
subsidies for the purchase of private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's eight Republican nominees support the Breaux
plan, but many say the drug benefit as unaffordable.
</P>
<P>
   With a drug benefit now included, it remains to be seen whether
the revamped Breaux plan will win 11 votes. ``Stay tuned,'' Breaux
told reporters in a late-afternoon briefing.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made a pitch in his State of the Union message
for prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also has proposed pumping 15 percent of projected budget
surpluses _ about $350 billion _ into Medicare. The money would
extend Medicare's lifespan from 2010 _ when it would become
insolvent if nothing is done _ to 2020.
</P>
<P>
   But the president has been silent on Breaux's subsidy idea,
leading Republicans to criticize him for not helping to drum up the
necessary votes among Democrats to make it an official commission
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only group that hasn't given us one vote is the
president's appointees,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of prescription drugs has skyrocketed in recent years,
rising 14 percent in 1997 alone. At the same time, drugs have
become integral elements of treating chronic illnesses. Often
doctors prescribe medications for conditions that might have
required hospitalization a decade or two ago.
</P>
<P>
   Senior-citizen advocates argue prescription drug coverage is
indispensable to any Medicare overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without coverage of prescription drugs, you don't have
anything responsive to where medicine is going in the 21st
century,'' said John Rother, legislative director of the American
Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives are skeptical. Greg Scandlen, health policy fellow
at the conservative Cato Institute, said that 65 percent of
Medicare beneficiaries get prescription coverage through private
``Medigap'' health insurance that covers what Medicare does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``To turn that into a free-for-all program doesn't make sense
when Medicare already is on shaky financial ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Established by Congress in 1965, Medicare now provides health
insurance to nearly 40 million elderly Americans. Medicare's ``Part
A'' hospital insurance program, which pays hospital bills, is
financed through a 2.9 percent payroll tax split between employers
and employees.
</P>
<P>
   Its ``Part B'' supplementary medical insurance program, which
pays for care by doctors and other health professionals, is funded
through beneficiary-paid premiums and general tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The government will spend about $207 billion on Medicare this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Like Social Security, Medicare faces the impending retirement of
a rising pool of beneficiaries _ the 70 million baby boomers born
between 1946 and 1964. Without changes, it will be up to the
less-populous ``Generation X'' _ 40 million people born between
1965 and 1980 _ to finance the government programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
