<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDANGERED-WHALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW STUDY CITES EXTINCTION DANGER TO RIGHT WHALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Already teetering on the brink of extinction, the Northern right
whale population has been shrinking since the early 1990s,
according to a disturbing new study, putting the animals on a path
to oblivion if more is not done to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by researchers at Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution and the University of Massachusetts at Boston, shatters
the widely held belief that the world's 300 remaining right whales
were slowly gaining numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the population has been declining as female right
whales have fewer calves while more whales die from collisions with
ships, entanglement with fishing gear, and perhaps pollution, the
researchers found.
</P>
<P>
   ``The picture is not good at all,'' said Hal Caswell, a
mathematical biologist at Woods Hole who calculated the whales
could become extinct in less than 200 years if current trends
continue.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, published in the current Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences, are sure to heighten debate over
whether the federal government and other agencies are doing enough
to protect the right whale, already known as the most endangered of
the world's large whale species. For example, there are no
mandatory speed limits or other restrictions on ships when they
enter known right whale areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clear change in the fate and fortune of right whales
in the last eight to 10 years that we don't fully understand, but
we had better begin to do something about it,'' warned Scott Kraus,
director of the New England Aquarium's Edgerton Research Laboratory
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Right whales, known for their distinctive V-shaped spouts,
white-speckled heads and the large filters through which they feed,
were hunted nearly to extinction by the early 20th century because
their slow speed and near-shore visits made them easy targets.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other whale species such as the humpback, Northern right
whales have not rebounded strongly since the end of whaling.
Despite more than 60 years of federal protection, their numbers
remain so small that even a single death is viewed as a setback by
conservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Their exact numbers are not easy to count because the animals'
habitat ranges from the Bay of Fundy in the north to the Florida
coast in the south. Caswell and the other researchers used
extensive photographic records from the New England Aquarium,
identifying each whale by unique marks such as the white growths on
their heads, called callosities.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that the number of whale offspring remained
stagnant while the death rate rose significantly. As a result,
instead of a gain of 5 to 10 whales per year that had been
estimated in the 1980s, the researchers found the population was
shrinking by a few whales annually.
</P>
<P>
   At that pace, Caswell gave the whales less than 200 years until
extinction, and even fewer years if the death rate continues to
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why right whales have fared so poorly is highly debated,
but Kraus's research, which was conducted separately from the
study, shows that part of the problem is that females are taking
longer to produce each calf, now waiting five years between each
offspring. He said the slowdown may reflect the long-term effects
of pollution, genetic inbreeding or natural changes in their food
supply.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Kraus and other researchers point out that
relatively little has been done to reduce collisions with ships. He
said that a coalition of fishermen, shipping companies, and
conservationists has begun pressing Congress to provide more money
for measures such as acoustic signals that could warn whales when
ships are near.
</P>
<P>
   However, Caswell said the news may not be all bad. His analysis
does not include the impact of several new measures to prevent
fishing gear entanglements and to educate shipping companies that
could reduce whale deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Thounhurst, a marine mammal specialist at the National
Marine Fisheries Service, said that voluntary efforts to work with
mariners seem to be helping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much the entire fishing community knows about right
whales now. That's a lot of eyes on the water that we didn't have''
a few years ago, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kraus said right whale protections have failed in part
because the National Marine Fisheries Service has had too few
resources and too little direction. ``There is no overarching
vision for right whales in the Fisheries Service as far as I can
tell,'' said Kraus. ``That has really hurt them. They're trying to
do everything at once.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
