<SLUG> BC-WENDYS-AD-COLUMN-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WENDY'S FOUNDER WASN'T A HIT _ EXCEPT WITH CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Basile and Jim McKennan thought their advertising careers
were over.
</P>
<P>
   The Bates USA creative team had just broadcast their first
commercial for Wendy's International using its founder, R. David
Thomas, as the spokesman, and the press skewered it. They picked on
Thomas unmercifully, criticizing his flat Middle American delivery,
his open-faced expression and his pudgy physique. One critic even
called him ``a steer in a short-sleeved shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was rough,'' recalled McKennan, a copywriter and group
creative director at Bates USA in New York, part of the Bates
Worldwide unit of Cordiant Communications Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   That was 10 years ago. Since then, Wendy's has broadcast more
than 640 television commercials using Thomas, making it the
longest-running campaign featuring a company founder as spokesman,
according to the Guinness Book of World Records.
</P>
<P>
   Turned out that as rudimentary as the early spots were, a funny
thing happened after they ran on TV: consumers believed them. To
television viewers, Thomas resonated as a man who looks like what
he portrays _ the Horatio Alger-like inventor of the Wendy's
hamburger chain who enjoys a hearty meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is what you get,'' said Thomas, 66, speaking
recently in a phone interview from Miami where Bates was shooting a
series of commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The Bates ad team concedes that Thomas' early performance _ in
which he guaranteed Wendy's quality or he ``wouldn't have named the
company'' after his daughter _ was ``awful,'' said Basile, an art
director and group creative director at Bates.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speech, pacing and rhythm were way off,'' Basile said.
``But he has a believability, an honesty and a sweetness that is so
far away from the glib spokesman that people were intrigued. People
said this is a real guy.''
</P>
<P>
   And Wendy's crucial franchise system _ which pays a portion of
the advertising _ embraced the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy's says the advertising works because ``it's not about
Dave; it's about Wendy's'' quality, and Thomas is the likable
messenger who is recognized by the public, said Don Calhoun,
Wendy's senior vice president for marketing in Dublin, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said each of the 65 commercials Bates created annually
started with the product. The creative team then decides how Thomas
can promote it, often in a humorous way.
</P>
<P>
   Bates has also learned how best to use Thomas. The senior
chairman of Wendy's board _ whose aphorisms such as ``be nice'' are
called ``Dave-speak'' inside the company _ is often seen poking fun
at his own simplistic Dale Carnegie-like philosophy and his love of
the food he invented. One commercial showed Thomas at a chic
restaurant where the entrees are artistic creations the size of
peas; another had him writing to the blues great B.B. King, who
confesses a love for Wendy's food, with a letter extolling the
musician to ``Keep smiling, you'll beat those blues yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Wendy's is a mass-market business, the commercials are
designed to appeal more to a consumer attitude than to a
demographic segment of the population, said Gary Steele, managing
director of Bates Retail, a unit that oversees retail accounts. But
he said Wendy's did appeal slightly more to adults and women
because of its chili and salad menu offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The company spokesman genre was a favorite in the 1980s when it
was common to see Lee Iacocca pitching Chrysler, Frank Perdue
selling Perdue chicken and Orville Redenbacher for the popcorn with
the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is not as popular, partly because companies realize
that not many chief executives have the kind of history and
business knowledge of, say, a Thomas, that would lead an agency to
use them as a representative, said Gary Stibel, principal of New
England Consulting Group in Westport, Conn. He said a notable
exception today is the use of August Busch III and his son, August
Busch IV, in advertising for the beer giant Anheuser-Busch.
</P>
<P>
   While Wendy's has had a good run, Stibel said he believed the
campaign was ``getting a little stale,'' and that the Wendy's adult
slant missed the all-important children's market, which is a
battlefield of advertising and toy giveaways between the hamburger
leader, the McDonald's Corp., and the second-ranked Burger King, a
unit of Diageo PLC; Wendy's is ranked third.
</P>
<P>
   Others say Wendy's adult concept is well positioned for the long
term because of the aging population.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is going to drive growth in the future is the
adult-oriented convenience situation,'' said Bob O'Brien of NPD
Food Service Information Group in Rosemont, Ill., a research
concern. ``And Wendy's has the oldest skew to its buyer profile.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bates won the huge Wendy's account in 1987 while the chain was
suffering a malaise after the famous ``Where's the beef?'' campaign
created by its previous agency. That campaign's signature line was
picked up in the 1984 presidential campaign, and became part of the
American vernacular.
</P>
<P>
   Although the account had billings of more than $100 million,
Bates found itself stymied because nothing the agency did excited
Wendy's. Calhoun recalled: ``The advertising wasn't incorrect.
There just wasn't a spark.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Charles Rath, the former Wendy's marketing director, who
suggested using Thomas _ an idea that was not exactly embraced by
the urbane Bates ad team. Using a company spokesman is often
considered trite _ and an obvious move to massage a chief
executive's ego.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not so with Thomas, who did not even want to be in
the advertising and said he was nervous about how his name and
likeness would be depicted.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Thomas said, it is like ``a reunion'' to go on a
Wendy's shoot. In an advertising rarity, Bates has used virtually
the same 50 or so people over the last decade to create Wendy's
commercials, from the director, Billy Hudson, to extras.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Wendy's plans to continue the campaign, which Calhoun
said had contributed to Wendy's decade of growth and profits. In
1998, Wendy's systemwide sales of company and franchise-owned
stores increased 7 percent, to $6.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the minute sales turn soft,'' Steele said, the Thomas
campaign would be history.
</P>
<P>
   And that would be fine with Thomas, who said, ``If we don't have
the sales, I'm gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
