<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FOCUS ON EVEN-STRENGTH WEAKNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Bruins spent Monday's hour-plus practice working
on what has become their Achilles' heel of late: their play at even
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns put his club through several one-on-one drills
with an eye toward correcting some of the errors that led to a 3-1
loss in Buffalo Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play's not killing us,'' said Burns. ``We're ninth
in the league, it's not the (penalty killing), that's rated No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's killing us is the five-on-five goals. We're getting
beat one-on-one, we're getting guys walking out of the corners on
us. It's a lack of concentration. We talked about that. We've got
to be a lot better in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said it was incumbent upon both the defensemen and
forwards to be more diligent in following through on their
assignments. On the Sabres' third goal, which came off the stick of
Brian Holzinger at 9:19 of the third period, Burns said it was just
a colossal breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's four different errors on one play,'' he said.
``(Mattias) Timander gives the puck up, (Cameron) Mann and (Ken)
Belanger don't pressure the guy. (Dave) Ellett goes and takes the
wide guy and then Kenny comes in and doesn't know who to take and
then Ray (Bourque) is in front of the net. That's four major errors
right there on one goal. It might be (the result) of two games in
two nights and your concentration goes down, but it just can't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuse for it now. You can't get beat one-on-one,
not this time of year. We have a tough schedule compared to
everybody else. Everybody else has three games at home and three on
the road. In our next six games, we've got two at home and four on
the road plus we've got to play the No. 1 team _ Ottawa _ and in
Toronto twice. We can't go to sleep. We've got to be sharp in all
those areas. Every single game is so important.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 16 games left, and this is the time of year when
players talk about the pressure of keeping mentally prepared and on
top of things with so much on the line. For Burns, it's a 24-hour,
seven-day-a-week obsession. Burns, who has said he loses sleep many
nights by getting up to look at videotape or address some other
concern, said his concentration is different from that of his
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know as coaches we do more than players do,'' he said. ``I
sit there and watch games and try to figure out things. I go back
and look at a tape once in a while or look at a goal. As coaches,
we have to do that because if we don't, we get our asses fired.
That's the difference between coaches and players. We get
unemployed and they just go to another team.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns empathized with Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy, who
reportedly was going to lose his job if New York didn't beat
Charlotte Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 24 hours a day in all sports,'' he said. ``Look at Van
Gundy, he doesn't win the basketball game, he's fired. That's a lot
of pressure to go out there, and you don't hold your destiny. The
Knicks went out and won the game and if they don't win, he goes
home. That's the nature of the beast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about being fired. It's happened before, it's
going to happen again. But we want the owners to be happy, we want
management to be happy. We want everybody to be happy. But when it
comes down, the pressure comes down on one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The objective during Monday's workout in Wilmington, and
today's, too, is to help players cut down on even-strength miscues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's no goals in a hockey game, there's no errors,''
said Burns. ``Mistakes are going to happen and that's part of the
game. If there were no errors, there would be no fun for anyone to
watch a hockey game or any sporting event. But when errors are
repeated and repeated, then they become mistakes and we wonder if
it's willingly or if it's just that maybe he can't do it anymore or
you can't do it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Byron Dafoe, who enters Wednesday night's game in Toronto
with a 2.16 goals-against average and .923 save percentage,
considered the loss to the Sabres a missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that was a great chance for us to get right
on their tails,'' Dafoe said. ``If you look at `The Week,' as Pat
called it, if we were going to go .500, we won the two games we
needed to win. It was a pretty good week. We played two on the road
and two at home and we split. I don't think it's tragic at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's positives in the way we played the games. I mean,
Buffalo didn't outplay us by any means. It was just a matter of
mistakes starting to add up. We dodged a couple late in the second
to hang in there. We addressed the issue but it was more talk than
action when we came out for the third. We did the same thing and
they capitalized.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Landon Wilson skated with the club and said he's
feeling much better after a few days off to recover from a mild
concussion. If he feels all right Tuesday, he'll skate again and
could play against the Maple Leafs.
</P>
</TEXT>
