<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1477 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIA-KAZAN-HNS &LR;      03-15 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIA-KAZAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR FACES OLD RESENTMENTS AT OSCAR CEREMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NANCY SCOTT  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On Sunday, Elia Kazan, famous worldwide as a
distinguished director of theater and film, will walk to the podium
at Dorothy Chandler Pavilion in Los Angeles to receive an honorary
Oscar, and if, God forbid, there is an ovation, the sound will be
drowned for some of us by a clamor and a screaming from long-gone
ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first award for Kazan; he has had Oscars before
now, most famously for 1954's ``On the Waterfront.''
</P>
<P>
   But news of the special honor has provoked contradictory and
impassioned emotions for hundreds, probably thousands, and the
upcoming ceremony may turn out to be the most divisive and
troublesome moment in the Academy's history because Kazan, 89, is
also known worldwide as the stool pigeon who sold out his
colleagues before the House Committee on Un-American Activities in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide is no exaggeration. Bernard Gordon, the 79-year-old
blacklisted screenwriter who has begun a protest against Kazan's
award, has received calls from journalists in Brazil, South Africa,
Spain and Colombia; he has heard from the New York Times and from
more than two dozen other newspapers. The first major evidence of
protest will be an ad scheduled to appear in Variety asking the
Oscar audience ``to sit silent'' when Kazan receives his award. A
civilized concept, this one _ no boos or hisses or walking out,
just silence.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Sekler of the Los Angeles Alternative Media Network, who is
preparing the ad, hopes to muster 100 names.
</P>
<P>
   Sekler has ``a handful of famous names,'' although she preferred
not to say who they are just yet (shades of the old days).
</P>
<P>
   Famous names aside, Sekler has signed children of the
blacklisted _ Chris Trumbo, son of the late Dalton Trumbo, who went
to jail for refusing to name names, and Becca Wilson, daughter of
the late Michael Wilson, who wrote ``Bridge on the River Kwai''
(with blacklisted writer Carl Foreman) and received no public
recognition for the Oscar-winning script until 20 years after the
fact.
</P>
<P>
   While the audience inside will _ perhaps _ sitting silent,
Gordon will be wearing a tuxedo and standing in silent vigil
outside the Chandler Pavilion on Oscar Night with as many of his
generation as are willing and able to join him. They are calling
themselves the Committee for Silence, and if they appear on TV _
and I surely hope they will; it's not 1952, I keep telling myself _
I expect that some viewers who were not even born when these elder
citizens were cast out of Hollywood will find the whole spectacle
as mysterious and puzzling as the Wars of the Roses.
</P>
<P>
   They'll probably find it amusing, too _ a bunch of tuxedoed
geezers protesting something that happened 47 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it's not the number of names Kazan named to the
House committee, or the nature of those he named; it was his
distinguished reputation that counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He validated the committee,'' says Bernard Gordon. ``It meant
they could continue the blacklist.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Kazan named names and shut up about it, resentment might
have dwindled, but he chose to take out a lengthy ad in the New
York Times excoriating communism.
</P>
<P>
   Even that might have faded from memory, but there were also
rumors that he had made a big- money deal with a major film
producer contingent on naming names.
</P>
<P>
   And there is this: Unlike many informers, Kazan has never
apologized. Add it all up, and as Victor Navasky, publisher of The
Nation magazine puts it, ``Kazan emerged in the folklore of the
left as the quintessential informer.''
</P>
<P>
   Navasky has this to say about Kazan's award. ``He's obviously a
great director, and I do believe that he ought to be honored for
his art. On the other hand, if he is receiving a lifetime
achievement award, he ought to be reminded of his entire
contribution, and that includes keeping other people from
working.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does Kazan deserve to be called great? Absolutely. His triumphs
would fill a page. Among the high points: In 1949, he directed the
celebrated premiere of Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman,'' and
Miller (a witness before the House committee who refused to name
names) has written in his autobiography that he believed Kazan
``was a genius of the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Kazan directed ``Gentleman's Agreement,'' a breakthrough film on
anti-Semitism in 1947, and won an Oscar for it; in 1949, with John
Ford, he directed ``Pinky,'' a film on racism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947 and '50, he directed ``Boomerang'' and ``Panic in the
Streets,'' films of conscience. ``It was because he took social
content so much to heart,'' writes Navasky, ``that his appearance
caused such astonished dismay.''
</P>
<P>
   Kazan directed ``On the Waterfront'' two years after his
testimony before the House committee, and his hero was a stool
pigeon. His later films include ``Viva Zapata,'' ``East of Eden''
and ``America, America,'' a rich and gorgeously photographed story
of the immigrant experience based on Kazan's own novel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
