<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASHEVILLE-COX     03-15 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASHEVILLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duffel bag may have hidden clinic bomb
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ Federal agents investigating whether fugitive
Eric Robert Rudolph was involved in Saturday's early-morning blast
at a downtown abortion clinic are looking for a suspect who might
have concealed the bomb in a duffel-type bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to know if I saw anybody carrying a bag,''
neighbor Ronald Jones, 37, said Monday, after being questioned by
the FBI on Sunday. ``They asked whether I saw any strangers or any
unusual cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph is wanted in the Jan. 29, 1998, bombing of a Birmingham
abortion clinic, in which a nail bomb was planted in a plastic tool
box, and in three Atlanta bombings, including an explosion in
Centennial Olympic Park during the 1996 Olympics in which a bomb
was concealed in a small military-style backpack.
</P>
<P>
   In a news briefing in Asheville on Monday, officials of the FBI,
the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, and the U.S.
Marshal Service reiterated that they have no suspects and no
evidence linking Rudolph to the Femcare clinic explosion that
startled residents in the working-class neighborhood shortly after
7 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors of Femcare said the clinic has been the target of
increasing protests in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extremists are really hurting my business,'' said Ronda
Hensley, 38, owner of Accents, a beauty salon next door to Femcare.
``I am getting tired of this _ the protesting, the bomb threats,
now the bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Femcare was one of numerous clinics that last month received
packages said to contain potentially deadly anthrax bacteria.
Agents descended on the Femcare building, and one entered wearing a
protective suit and mask, but the scare turned out to be a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence gathered from Saturday's blast is being examined at
ATF's laboratory in Atlanta. ``A good bit of comparison was
accomplished,'' said ATF special agent Richard Fox, but he released
few of the findings aside from the bomb's potential power.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the bomb partly detonated, causing no injuries
and no evident damage to the clinic. If the bomb had exploded as
officials think it was intended to, it could ``have devastated the
entire end of the building and gone into the building approximately
40 to 60 feet,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that this bomb was intended to go off and . . . to
kill, maim or hurt people,'' Fox said. Authorities said no one has
reported receiving any warning that the bomb had been planted.
</P>
<P>
   The Asheville bombing drew more than 30 investigators, including
members of the Southeast Bomb Task Force, who have been searching
for Rudolph for almost a year in the rugged mountains around
Andrews, N.C., about 75 miles west of Asheville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no evidence, at this time, that this bomb is the work
of Eric Rudolph,'' U.S. Attorney Mark Calloway said at the Monday
news briefing. ``It is too early, of course, to draw any
conclusions. . . . It is early in the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who lives about 100 yards behind Femcare, said he saw
nothing suspicious in the hours before the explosion. Later
Saturday, shortly after noon and then around 8:30 p.m., he said he
heard two more blasts, presumably caused by agents detonating parts
of the bomb that had not gone off in the original explosion. Darryl
Unruh, a 61-year-old businessman who owns the building housing the
Accents salon, said police in recent months have photographed the
anti-abortion protesters from his building.
</P>
<P>
   Assembling along Orange Street two or three days a week, the
protesters have numbered from one or two to as many as 15, Unruh
said. One has used an amplified sound system to urge women arriving
at the clinic not to go inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly do not appear violent,'' Unruh said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
