<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1479 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLELAND-COX     03-15 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLELAND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former marine claims Cleland's injuries not a result of own
grenade
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For 31 years, Sen. Max Cleland has blamed his loss
of three limbs on his carelessness with a grenade on a hilltop in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Cleland learned that the grenade, and thus the fault,
may not have been his.
</P>
<P>
   The news in no way undoes the terrible damage Cleland, then an
Army captain, suffered on Hill 440 near Khe Sanh on April 8, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia's Democratic senator said Monday that it will
``provide some emotional healing.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lloyd, a former Marine, said he was on the same hill when
a grenade ripped off Cleland's legs and right arm.
</P>
<P>
   After he wrapped a tourniquet around Cleland's thigh, he tended
to another soldier who had been slightly wounded by fragments from
the M-26 grenade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was crying and saying, 'It was my grenade, it was my
grenade,' `` Lloyd recalled in a telephone interview Monday from
his home in Annapolis, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd's version of the horror and confusion that followed the
explosion on Hill 440 near Khe Sanh might never have been shared
with Cleland if Lloyd had not been watching a History Channel
program on medics and corpsmen a few weeks back.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland was describing his experience and crediting a Navy
corpsman, attached to a Marine unit, with saving his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just took it for granted that it was his grenade,'' Lloyd
said of Cleland. ``That's when I realized he didn't know. He was
living with it for years and feeling bad about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd, a retired Delta Air Lines employee, contacted Cleland's
office. The two men eventually spoke by telephone, and last week
they shared lunch on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost been like a second emotional grenade,'' Cleland
said.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the story has never been about Cleland's wounds,
but his remarkable recovery. His inspirational rehabilitation
undergirds his political career.
</P>
<P>
   No one will ever be able to say conclusively how a live grenade
came to rest on the helicopter pad atop the hill. Cleland noticed
it, he has said innumerable times, only after the helicopter that
deposited him there had lifted off. ``I did not know it was live,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The M-26 fragmentation grenade was standard issue for American
servicemen in Vietnam. It typically had a five-second fuse, which
was ignited when a soldier pulled the grenade's pin and let go of
the ``spoon,'' or handle.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's accounts of the accident have shifted, but in an
April 30, 1968, report, Army Capt. Charles E. Steuer wrote, ``The
source of the grenade, and how it became armed ... could not be
determined.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cleland said he has always been haunted by the idea that he
was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The story Lloyd told him, of a newly arrived private who
straightened the pins on his grenades to make them easier to
activate in combat, ``meshes with the bits and pieces of
information that I have,'' Cleland said.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd, a corporal in a mortar squad, said he never knew the
private's name. But he said the soldier was on his feet and covered
with blood when Lloyd approached him.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd took away the soldier's other grenades to avoid another
mishap, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Dave told me this I didn't get much sleep the next
night, because it opened up all the old wounds, all the old
thoughts that I had tried to lay aside to get on with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine the terrible thing of living with something
like this ... living with the mystery, not the knowledge, but the
mystery that somehow or another you might have screwed up
somehow?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the senator believes that particular burden has been lifted
from his shoulders. But he is not about to place it on someone
else's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ever came across that individual,'' Cleland said, ``I
would give him a big hug and say, 'Don't worry, don't feel guilty.
A thousand things could have happened to us out there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 1956EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
