<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-MERGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    El Paso-Sonat deal stirs interest in metro utilities
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Monday's announcement that Texas-based El Paso Energy
Corp. is acquiring Birmingham-based Sonat Inc. and forming the
largest U.S. interstate natural gas pipeline company may have
implications for Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies operate gas pipelines that connect to Atlanta Gas
Light Co.'s network. Sonat also is a partner with AGL Resources
Inc., parent of the Georgia utility, in the wholesale gas and
electricity marketing business.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a combined company could emerge as a competitor to
Atlanta-based Southern Co. as it moves into the electricity
business. And the new company could become an acquisition target
for Southern, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of announcing his company was acquiring Sonat for
$6 billion in stock and assumed debt, El Paso Chairman William Wise
placed a courtesy call to Walter Higgins, chief executive officer
of AGL Resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he thought the merger created some very interesting
possibilities for our company and Georgia,'' Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   AGL announced last month it would review its 35 percent stake in
a natural gas marketing venture with Sonat after $4.1 million in
losses during the first fiscal quarter. (El Paso has a similar
business of its own.) Higgins said the merger had created a ``new
set of alternatives'' for the joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   The merger could also have an impact on interstate pipeline
links to Atlanta Gas Light's 30,000-mile pipeline system that
supplies 1.5 million homes and businesses in Georgia and part of
Tennessee. The utility currently gets about 85 percent of its gas
supplies from Sonat pipelines, 15 percent from Transco and 5
percent from El Paso's East Tennessee pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   AGL has filed plans to drop the East Tennessee pipeline in favor
of a new interstate pipeline it plans for North Georgia in a 50-50
partnership with Transco, a subsidiary of the Tulsa, Okla.-based
Williams Cos.
</P>
<P>
   PSC Chairman Stan Wise said he does not view the merger as
anticompetitive in Georgia because interstate pipeline charges are
regulated by the federal government. But the merger may give AGL
and Transco more ammunition when the PSC opens hearings April 12.
</P>
<P>
   A Southern acquisition of Sonat could face antitrust barriers
because of the Alabama company's concentration of assets in
Southern's Southeastern service territory.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this year, Southern held unsuccessful negotiations
to acquire El Paso. The talks reportedly collapsed over what role
El Paso Chairman William Wise would have played in a combined
company.
</P>
<P>
   Under Monday's merger plans, Wise will be the CEO of the merged
company, the corporate headquarters will be in Houston, and the
name will be El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   According to Barry M. Abramson, utilities industry analyst at
PaineWebber, El Paso will now be positioned to compete against
Southern in the fast-growing gas-and-electric national wholesale
business. He also said Southern, the largest U.S. power generator,
could end up acquiring the combined company. ``It's big enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Revenue of the combined company would be $9.5 billion, with $15
billion in assets. Southern's revenue last year was $11.4 billion,
with assets of $36.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wise told The Wall Street Journal his company does not need to
``inhale a slow-growth utility'' to grow. But El Paso said it will
expand into the unregulated wholesale electricity business with the
expanded company.
</P>
<P>
   Sonat announced plans last week to build an electric power plant
in Upson County, its third Georgia power plant project. El Paso
already has stakes in 17 U.S. power plants, though it is still
primarily a gas company.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Tirello, an analyst at BT Alex. Brown, said El Paso will
``not be a big threat'' to Southern unless or until it greatly
expands its electricity holdings.
</P>
<P>
   But once Wise consolidates the two companies, El Paso will be
attractive as an acquisition for any number of big electric
companies that want to become full-service energy providers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tirello predicted a new owner during the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fits into a lot of big strategies,'' he said. ``In time,
this could be the next acquisition of the Southern Co.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew C. Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
