A1485 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS-DOW-COX     03-15 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-DOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Milestone not touched, but close a record
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market roared skyward like a jet through
clouds Monday but failed again to break through the magical barrier
of 10,000 on the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   In a rally that began at the opening bell and lasted all day,
the Dow rose three times within striking distance, once coming as
close as 30 points before settling back to close at a new high of
9,958.77.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Dow's fourth high in seven trading sessions. Broader
market indexes also advanced.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 12.67 to 1,307.26, also a
record. The Nasdaq, driven by technology issues, rose 49.91 to
close at 2,431.44.
</P>
<P>
   There was a clear consensus _ from clerks on up to top members
of the New York Stock Exchange _ that 10,000 will be surpassed
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even bearish experts said they don't think the Dow can be
stopped for more than another day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Many, however, expressed alarm at the Dow's recent rise, calling
it unjustified and reflecting a speculative mania in which
investors are buying simply because it seems like everyone else is.
Stocks are overpriced by any historical standard, and many analysts
believe the market is at least 20 percent overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is dangerous,'' said Robert W. Seijas of Fleet
Specialists, who holds one of the most important positions on the
exchange floor. He is a specialist who deals in high-quality stocks
such as Atlanta-based Coca-Cola and AGL Resources, parent of
Atlanta Gas Light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public investors tend to chase strength. They buy stocks that
are going up, and that's fine _ until the end. They (stock prices)
won't go up forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Seijas said the danger is that naive investors are throwing
money at highly speculative stocks of Internet companies that are
actually losing money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is that folly must be paid, '' he said. ``Quality
is smart investing, stocks like Coke and Procter &AMP; Gamble. They
make things. Internet stocks make noise.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Buying some of these Internet stocks is like paying
$150,000 for a Cadillac. It may be a great car, but it's certainly
not worth that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, hundreds of tourists in lower Manhattan braved the snow
and sub-freezing temperatures to visit the New York Stock Exchange
in hopes of catching a glimpse of history from the visitors gallery
25 feet above the trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   The din was constant among the traders _ but not as much as it
was during the crash of Oct. 19, 1987, or the Friday the 13th
mini-crash in October 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Many floor brokers were almost nonchalant going about their
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a number,'' said trader Frank Schultz, 52. ``It'll
hit 10,000 and then go higher. The public is fascinated with
numbers. We'll hit it this week, easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Brahams, 49, of Los Angeles, was one of the spectators
crowding the visitors gallery, gawking at the swirl of red, green,
blue and black jackets below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm positive it'll hit 10,000,'' said Brahams. ``People may be
a little skittish, but we're still positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
