<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-HOMEDEPOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot seeks to authorize more shares
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot shareholders are voting on the company's
proposal to double the number of authorized shares of common stock
from 2.5 billion shares to 5 billion, according to a preliminary
proxy filed last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based home improvement retailer said the additional
shares would be used for potential stock splits and dividends, as
well as to ``meet future business and financial obligations,''
according to the filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``This opens the door for a stock split, but I wouldn't read too
much into it,'' said analyst Stephen Long of Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot shares recently have been trading in the mid-$60s,
Long noted. ``They like to split more in the $70 to $80 range.''
</P>
<P>
   The proxy also noted an increase in base salaries for Chairman
Bernard Marcus and Chief Executive Arthur Blank. In 1998, both
salaries rose roughly 12.5 percent to $900,000, from about $800,000
in the previous year. Marcus and Blank each received bonuses of $2
million.
</P>
<P>
   Blank's base salary will increase to $1 million effective in
April. The preliminary proxy didn't reveal Marcus' 1999 salary.
Marcus and Blank do not receive annual stock option grants.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's annual meeting is scheduled May 26 at the Cobb
Galleria. The company may broadcast the meeting over the Internet
through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
