<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS-MANIA-COX     03-15 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-MANIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Craziness' of market attracting spectators, speculators
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Financial manias have been occurring ever since ''Peg
Leg'' Peter Stuyvesant hobbled down what's now Wall Street before
the British kicked out his Dutch settlers and changed the Big
Apple's name from New Amsterdam to New York.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening on Wall Street now represents the latest, and
many experts fear it will end the same way as all the others: A
bust.
</P>
<P>
   No one, though, seems to doubt that the Dow Jones industrial
average will break through the 10,000 mark this week, and possibly
today, culminating a gigantic rally from 5,000 only four years ago.
The runup has made thousands of investors rich, and at least as
many far richer.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is craziness,'' says Barton Biggs of Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter and one of the Street's most respected analysts. ''It's like
the Super Bowl, this fascination with 10,000. I think it's a good
time to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggs is a big bear, but he's outnumbered by raging bulls even
though by historical standards, stocks are way overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   The speculative frenzy that has lifted the prices of many
Internet stocks to astronomical levels has drawn in countless
investors, many of whom have never experienced a bear market and
whose brokers were still in college when the Dow crashed in 1987,
Seijas said Monday as the world watched to see if the Dow would hit
10,000.
</P>
<P>
   But for every expert who's cautious, there seems to be two or
three who're still raging bulls, like Ralph Acampora of Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love what's going on,'' he said. ''All the people who're
concerned because they say it's only the Dow that's rising, I
disagree. We are going to cross the bar and keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Acuff, equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney, says
he's worried, too, but not about a major decline.
</P>
<P>
   It's simply time, he said, to be careful. ''Forget the forest,''
Acuff said. ''Look at the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   But many famous economists, such as Harvard's John Kenneth
Galbraith, who has written books detailing previous manias in
history, aren't as upbeat. He compares what's happening on Wall
Street now to the Dutch tulip mania of 1637, when the people of
Holland went wild trading tulip bulbs, many of which had been
infected with viruses that made them not only beautiful, but
unique.
</P>
<P>
   That ''bubble'' burst, bankrupting thousands in Europe who had
paid the equivalent of $50,000 in today's money for a single tulip
bulb.
</P>
<P>
   ''All this goes back more than 300 years,'' Gailbraith said
Monday in an interview from his Boston home. ''What we know for
sure is, what goes up eventually comes down, and extravagantly.
Everyone should be warned by what has happened throughout
history.''
</P>
<P>
   The tulip mania, he said, was the first recorded in history.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobles, citizens, farmers, mechanics, seamen, footmen,
maid-servants, even chimney-sweeps and old clotheswomen dabbled in
tulips,'' Galbraith said in his 1990 book, ''A Short History of
Financial Euphoria.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what made people come to their senses, he said, but
thousands were reduced to ''beggary.''
</P>
<P>
   Next came the Mississippi Bubble in 1720. A Scotsman named John
Law concocted a scheme to pay off the French national debt by
establishing a bank and selling stock in it. Trouble was, Galbraith
said, people thought they were investing in a company that would
search for gold in the New World.
</P>
<P>
   The bubble burst when investors realized their money went to pay
the French debt and line the pockets of Law and a handful of French
nobles.
</P>
<P>
   Law fled for his life back to England, where another bubble was
ballooning. Investors there formed the South Sea Co., which agreed
to pay off England's national debt for the exclusive right to trade
in the Pacific. Shares were in great demand until one day people
realized that Spain controlled the area, and that there were few
people in the area to enslave _ a major part of the South Sea Co.'s
business plan.
</P>
<P>
   Though there were other bubbles in between, another blew up in
the United States after the formation of America's first central
bank. It floated loans for speculative ventures, which didn't pan
out, causing that bubble to burst in 1837.
</P>
<P>
   America plunged into a depression in 1873 and again 20 years
later. The first burst, experts of the day said, because the U.S.
was trying to retire Civil War debt and move to a gold standard.
The collapse in the 1890s was loosely blamed on a railroad boom
characterized by corruption and thievery.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few others afterward, but the classic example came
in 1929, when the stock market crashed after a years-long
speculative frenzy similar to what's happening now in the Internet
sector, Galbraith said. A contributing factor was that people could
buy stock with only a 10 percent down payment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, after the Dow had rallied from 777 in 1982 to over
2,700, Wall Street crashed again, and no one has, as yet, figured
out quite why, Galbraith said, though many reasons have been
offered.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is not to say another crash is in the offing, but
''people should be warned by history,'' Galbraith. ''It does repeat
itself. And economic predictions should always be regarded with
skepticism, now as then.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two kinds of economists: those who don't know, and
those who don't know they don't know.'' Stuyvesant, incidentally,
was the last Dutch governor of New Amsterdam. The wall for which
Wall Street was named was constructed on his orders.
</P>
<P>
   And it was built by a pirate.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
