<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta won't get 2003 Super Bowl
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ In a mixed-bag day for Atlanta, National Football
League officials said Monday that the Georgia Dome will be the site
of a Monday Night Football game in 1999 but not the 2003 Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   While the NFL is not expected to make a formal announcement on
the fate of the 2003 title game during this week's owners'
meetings, the decision to remove it from San Francisco already has
been made.
</P>
<P>
   The game was awarded to San Francisco contingent upon the city's
ability to complete a new stadium. That project, though, remains
uncertain and the NFL could wait no longer for a resolution to the
political and economic issues jeopardizing it.
</P>
<P>
   Executive director of special events Jim Steeg, the league's
point man on Super Bowls, and commissioner Paul Tagliabue declined
comment on the 2003 game. However, the game is expected to be moved
to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will have at least one, and more likely two, Monday
Night games this season. Although the regular-season schedule will
not be released until early April, the Falcons probably will face
either Minnesota or San Francisco at home. The Falcons have not
played in a Monday night game since '93. They have not won on
Monday night since 1981, the longest such drought in the NFL, and
have lost seven in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion stalled
</P>
<P>
   Just three hours after Tagliabue assured the media Monday
afternoon the expansion committee would have a recommendation on
Los Angeles or Houston by the end of the day, the process stalled
again and none was forthcoming. It now appears there is some chance
the meetings will adjourn without a recommendation. Clearly some
owners are enamored of the package presented by Houston businessman
Bob McNair. ``Right now we don't even have the 24 votes (necessary)
for expansion,'' said Carolina Panthers owner Jerry Richardson,
chairman of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Talking turkey
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is expected to discuss today a proposal by owners Lamar
Hunt of the Kansas City Chiefs and Thomas Benson of the New Orleans
Saints to rotate the Thanksgiving Day games currently held in
Detroit and Dallas. The resolution will not receive enough support.
</P>
<P>
   Suspension, fine for DeBartolo
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue is expected to announce today that San Francisco 49ers
owner Ed DeBartolo Jr. will be suspended for one year and fined $1
million. DeBartolo stepped down from the team to fight federal
racketeering charges in Louisiana, then agreed to a deal in which
he'll testify against former Gov. Edwin Edwards. The club has been
run by his sister, Denise DeBartolo York, and former coach Bill
Walsh recently was installed as team president. Most owners agree
DeBartolo should not be able to regain the 49ers until they
evaluate his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Footing the Bills
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Bills reached a three-year contract extension with
quarterback Doug Flutie. The extension created a four-year deal
worth $22 million and included a signing bonus of $6 million.
Counting the five-year contract the Bills negotiated with Rob
Johnson in July, the team has spent $14.5 million in signing
bonuses for quarterbacks over the past eight months. Owner Ralph
Wilson and general manager John Butler said there are no plans to
trade Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens to get Mitchell
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens agreed in principle to a deal to acquire
Lions quarterback Scott Mitchell for a third-round choice this year
and a late-round pick in 2000. The Ravens will trade quarterback
Jim Harbaugh to San Diego for a fifth-rounder. . . . The Falcons
were awarded a compensatory seventh-round pick in this year's draft
for free-agency losses last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
