<HEADLINE>
NATION'S TOP CHEESE AND THE CHEESIEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Wisconsin brick cheese described as ``sturdy'' and made under
the Country Cheese brand by the Klondike Cheese Co. of Monroe,
Wis., has been chosen winner of the U.S. Championship Cheese
Contest.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Milfred Severson &LR; , head cheesemaker at Klondike Cheese, said
he'd been working to win the contest for 30 years. ``I can't
describe it. I'm excited and worked up. I can hardly sit still.''
The champ beat out a baby Havarti from Muskegon, Mich., and a
cheddar made in Cabot, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gene Wieber &LR;  forwards a report from the Bakersfield
Californian on groundbreaking ceremonies for the Grand Canal Port,
a shopping mall modeled after Venice. Plans include a canal,
gondoliers, Linens N' Things, Ross Dress for Less, &LR;  and,
appropriately enough, Old Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The groundbreaking, which took place Friday, ``featured a
27-foot model gondola with three tiara-topped beauty queens aboard
towed by a pickup through the dry canal channel. A dust devil
briefly struck the speaking platform, popping balloons and sending
others skyward, and a confetti-bearing plane made three unfruitful
circles over the crowd before flying away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAVEAT PIE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   March 14, was the Exploratorium's annual Pi Day, in keeping with
which someone left a message on a friend's answering machine that
said something like, ``Pi Day's today. Meet you at the
Exploratorium.'' The message, however, was left on a wrong number;
its recipient, thinking the caller was a member of the Biotic
Baking Brigade, called the police.
</P>
<P>
   Officers rushed to the scene of a Buddhist event at the Palace
of Fine Arts, which shares the site with the Exploratorium, looking
for a VIP who might be a likely target. When one cop stopped next
door, saw the Pi Day signs and 1,600 slices ready to be served, the
mystery was solved and the case closed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WRITERS' DAUGHTER KVETCHES IN PUBLIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An essay by 20-year-old  &UR; Molly Jong-Fast &LR;  in the latest issue of
Marie Claire is in the  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR;  mode:
</P>
<P>
   She was a chubby kid; there was pressure to conform; in
desperation, she tried all kinds of things (in Jong-Fast's case,
beauty treatments, not romances) to overcome her low self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Jong-Fast describes the ``large lonely purple townhouse'' in
which she grew up, her mother dragging her early on for weekly
manicures; getting drugs, at 13, from a diet doctor to cure ``not
only parental disapproval but also social isolation''; finally
becoming ``thin enough to be seen in public with my Jewish,
quasi-socialite family.''
</P>
<P>
   Such self-loathing, she writes, was inherited from her
self-loathing mother. ``In my house,'' she writes, `` `food' was a
four-letter word, cookies were guarded by a padlock, devil's food
cake really was. Gluttony became my rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jong-Fast is, like most 20-year-olds, eager to blame
everything on her parents, she's at least polite enough not to name
them. Her mother, it doesn't say anywhere in the essay, is feminist
novelist  &UR; Erica Jong &LR; . Her father is writer  &UR; Jonathan &LR; 
 &UR; Fast &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Hillary Rodham Clinton &LR;  goes on America Online at 7:45
tonight tues &LR;   &LR; t &LR; o answer questions about ``Dear Socks, Dear Buddy:
Kids' Letters to the First Pets,'' which Amazon.com puts at 9,574th
on its best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Bard is so hot that the online service
culturefinder.comcq &LR;  is offering a new 1999 Shakespeare Performance
Finder. The most-performed Shakespeare play in the country right
now _ with 10 productions _ is ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Education Secretary  &UR; Richard Riley &LR;  announced last
week that the makers of ``Shakespeare in Love'' are producing
``Shakespeare in the Classroom,'' a teaching kit that includes a
video starring  &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow &LR;  and directed by  &UR; John Madden &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``There couldn't be a Joe DiMaggio today. Today, they'd destroy,
or at least impair, DiMaggio and Ted Williams and Joe Louis by
telling stories about their tax returns and their temper tantrums.
And the Drudge Report would come up with an old girlfriend who said
she went out with all three of them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Former New York Governor Mario Cuomo in the Los Angeles Times.
Roger Angell writes in this week's New Yorker that DiMaggio was
invited to meet Queen Elizabeth and Prince Philip aboard the royal
yacht in San Francisco in 1983. When DiMaggio ``was announced and
stepped forward, the prince appeared to pause before they shook
hands. `THE Joe DiMaggio?' he asked.''
</P>
