<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-875&AMP;ADD     03-15 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE, STILL UNANNOUNCED, MAKES FIRST OFFICIAL CAMPAIGN TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.H., Ariz., N.J., Md.) (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore began laying a
platform Monday for his all-but-announced presidential candidacy,
appealing to both harried suburbanites and more traditional
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gore offered a continuation of President Clinton's policies,
with only minor tinkering. He said, for example, that he wanted to
hire enough teachers to reduce the size of classes in all grades
through high school, not just through eighth grade as Clinton has
proposed. And he wants to make preschool education available in all
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But he did little to separate himself from his political
benefactor as he took one more step in his long slow march toward a
presidential candidacy by taking his first official campaign trip,
paid for by his election committee. He is not expected to announce
his candidacy officially until later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to build on the wisdom that we've all gained in the
last several years,'' he said at a rally in snow-bound New
Hampshire before flying here, paying homage to the two states that
vote the earliest in the primary process.
</P>
<P>
   Gore put special emphasis on what he calls ``quality-of-life''
issues _ easing traffic congestion, for example _ that some have
ridiculed as unpresidential because they are local issues, but that
Gore defends as integral to strengthening families by creating more
free time. They are also aimed squarely at an important block of
swing voters, especially frazzled parents, who live in the suburbs
and could decide the next election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who deserves to be our next president is the one
who understands how tired working parents are,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the daily commutes get longer and longer,'' he
said. ``And for people who don't think that it's a problem that
parents are caught in traffic jams that are lengthening each day,
I'll tell you, they haven't been in traffic jams and they don't
know what it does to the desire to balance work and family.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of Gore's identification with the Clinton
administration, particularly the nation's economic prosperity, he
seemed quite ambiguous about how strongly to associate himself with
it. He did not mention Clinton by name, and he seemed to want to
create distance by describing not a policy divide but an epochal
divide _ a natural break in the calendar in the year 2000 that
would leave Clinton in the past and put Gore in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only the beginning of a new century and a new
millennium,'' Gore said. ``It's the beginning of a whole new era in
human history.'' And that, he added, posed a new set of challenges
with ``new approaches for the new century.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has spent years building up an extensive financial,
political and policy network across the country, and that in-place
apparatus has gone a long way toward clearing the field of primary
challengers. He was accompanied Monday by Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, the House Democratic leader, who formally endorsed him in
what the two billed as a strong sign of party unity.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, the former senator from New Jersey, is the only
Democrat who has entered the race, and the polls strongly favor
Gore for the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But the polls are less encouraging for Gore in hypothetical
match-ups against various Republicans, suggesting serious
vulnerabilities in the Gore candidacy. The latest NBC/Wall Street
Journal poll showed him 18 points behind Texas Gov. George Bush and
15 points behind Elizabeth Dole, the two leading Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   And Judith Hope, the Democratic chairman in New York, last week
openly questioned whether Gore would be the party's best nominee,
noting that Democratic vice presidents who have sought the
presidency have tended to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's media consultant, Bob Squier, said that Gore was flagging
in the polls because he was still being perceived as vice
president. ``He is not thought of in presidential terms,'' Squier
said, suggesting that campaign forays like Monday's, which drew the
biggest press contingent of Gore's tenure a vice president, would
start to change that perception.
</P>
<P>
   Gore sidestepped questions about whether he was too closely
linked with the impeached president. He said the campaign would be
about ideas, not polls.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore aides admit that he is using a series of narrowly
focused, poll-tested initiatives reminiscent of some of Clinton's
micro-proposals in 1996 to appeal to voters.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton off in Central America last week, the vice
president used the empty stage of the White House almost every day
to discuss topics ranging from traffic jams and drug labels to lost
bags at airports.
</P>
<P>
   Aides even imitated the Clinton strategy of targeting their
announcements to certain media venues to insure maximum _ and
sympathetic _ exposure. For example, at last week's announcement on
ways to ease traffic congestion, they invited traffic reporters,
those who ride the choppers and describe road conditions. This
guaranteed the vice president media coverage in local markets
across the country and on drive-time radio, much as Clinton in 1997
insured heavy attention to his conference on global warming by
inviting more than 100 local weather forecasters to cover it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Republicans have poked fun at Gore for directing a presidential
campaign to such seemingly small issues as lost bags at airports
and such seemingly local issues as traffic congestion. Jim
Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee, has been
particularly scathing, accusing Gore of trying to ``do away with
the internal combustion engine, the automobile,'' and calling him
``an apologist for the president; he's a wasteful dreamer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even an airline passenger, Jim Corsetty, of Rockville, Md.,
whose plane was stranded on a runway and who found himself on stage
with the vice president last week, expressed his astonishment that
he had become an anecdote in the presidential campaign. He
introduced the vice president as ``my own personal consumer
advocate.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Republicans think Gore might be on to something.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McInturff, a Republican pollster who is working for the
presidential campaign of Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said that even
if Gore was talking about ``microscopic'' issues and sounded as if
he were running for town manager rather than president, he was
still controlling the policy debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's working,'' McInturff said with some exasperation.
``You're writing a story about Gore talking about lots of popular
issues. But have we really so dumbed down the office that he can be
talking about traffic?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
