<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO (Washington) _ Armed with an agreement from
Kosovo's ethnic Albanians to sign a peace accord for the troubled
region, President Clinton turns up the heat on the Yugoslavs to
drop their objections. If Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
does not quickly agree to the cease-fire, Clinton says the only
option left for NATO is an aerial bombardment. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-COMMISSION (Washington) _ The leaders of the bipartisan
commission struggling to resuscitate Medicare unveil a compromise
plan that would for the first time cover the cost of prescription
drugs. The plan ``represents both good policy as well as good
politics,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La., co-author of the proposal
and chairman of the 17-member Medicare commission. By DAN FREEDMAN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-Y2K (Washington) _ Government investigators now say
they are confident the nation's air traffic control system will
work on Jan. 1. A year ago the Federal Aviation Administration
hadn't started fixing its computers to ensure that they won't
malfunction on or after Jan. 1. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MARINES-GAYS (Washington) _ The Marine Corps' base at Twentynine
Palms in California's Mojave Desert had the highest number of
troops discharged for homosexuality in the Marine Corps last year,
the government says. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-STATES (Washington) _ Texas Attorney General John Cornyn
and officials from other states protest a federal proposal to
recoup the Medicaid costs from the more than $200 billion in
settlements reached between the states and the tobacco industry. By
GARY MARTIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
