   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-2000 (Manchester, N.H.)_ Armed with the endorsement of a
former rival, Vice President Al Gore drops by two key primary
states to promote an array of domestic initiatives and ignite his
presidential campaign. Gore picks up the support of House Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., once considered a contender for the
Democratic presidential nomination. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   RACE-MEDIA (Houston) _ Newsroom staffing and sensitivity to
people of color get intense scrutiny at a recent seminar on race
conducted by Houston's journalism associations. By CARLOS BYARS.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In his tattletale book, George
Stephanopoulos says President Clinton regrets surrounding himself
with too many young people who were ``smart but not wise.'' Clinton
should have remembered the warning by LBJ Press Secretary George
Reedy against allowing people to work for a president until they
are at least 40 and well-seasoned. If he had, Clinton never would
have made the mistake of hiring the gossipy Stephanopoulos. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ One of the most emotional
issues in any legislative session is the fight against drunken
driving, and this year's chapter started unfolding last week in the
Texas Legislature. Lawmakers are all making a strong pitch for a
bill to lower the legal intoxication limit for drivers from .10
percent to .08 percent blood alcohol content. By CLAY ROBISON.
(Already filed.)
</P>
