<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-SURPRISES-CO     03-15 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-SURPRISES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCAA Tournament: The year of the party crashers
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cinderella isn't making just a token appearance at this week's
NCAA
</P>
<P>
   Sweet 16. She has kicked the door in and taken over the place.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the tournament field was expanded to 64
teams in 1985, five double-digit seeds _ No. 10 seeds or lower _
have advanced to the regional semifinals. Never before had more
than three gone so far.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny Gonzaga, the 10th seed in the West Regional, had the
tournament's Cinderella crown all to itself on Saturday when it
knocked off second-seeded Stanford 82-74. But on Sunday, two No. 2
seeds (Utah, Miami of Florida), and a No. 4 (Tennesee)
</P>
<P>
   were beaten to fill this week's dance card with some new faces.
</P>
<P>
   What we are left with this week are three No. 10s (Gonzaga,
Miami of Ohio, Purdue), a No. 12 (Southwest Missouri State), and a
No. 13 (Oklahoma). It was one of the bracket-busting weekends of
all time.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri coach Steve Alford, whose team destroyed
fourth-seeded Tennessee 81-51 on Sunday in the East Regional and is
in the Sweet 16 for the first time in school history, spoke for
Cinderellas everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the fun things about this tournament,'' Alford
said. ``I don't believe a lot of brackets out there had us in the
Sweet 16. Suddenly, people out there are scrambing to find out who
we are and wondering if we're really any good. We like that.''
</P>
<P>
   History, however, says that the clock will strike midnight soon
for the Cinderellas. Since 1985, 25 double-digit seeds have
advanced to the Sweet 16 but only four have won their next game in
the regional semifinals. Of those four, only one (LSU, 1986) won a
regional championship and advanced to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   But until then, each of these surprising teams has a story to
tell about how it beat the odds:
</P>
<P>
   _ GONZAGA (27-6): Until last weekend, the Spokane, Wash., school
was best known as the alma mater of John Stockton, point guard of
the Utah Jazz, and the late Bing Crosby.
</P>
<P>
   When the Zags beat Minnesota in the first round, the media wrote
it off to the absence of four Gopher players suspended on charges
of academic fraud. When they outrebounded Stanford 47-33 and won on
Saturday, the whole country took another look.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga had played exactly one NCAA Tournament game in its
history until
</P>
<P>
   Thurday, but coach Don Monson says his team is no fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our kids believed we were going to win that game (against
Stanford),''
</P>
<P>
   said Monson, in his 11th season at the school. ``We haven't gone
into a game this season
</P>
<P>
   where our kids didn't think they were going to win. And that's a
hard mentality to get in
</P>
<P>
   when it says Gonzaga on your jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Quentin Hall, born in the Bahamas, is the man who
makes the
</P>
<P>
   Zags zig. He'll have to do it again on Thursday against the
Flordia Gators.
</P>
<P>
   _ OKLAHOMA (22-10): With a No. 13, the Sooners were the
highest-seeded
</P>
<P>
   at-large team in the field, which means they were the 64th and
final team to
</P>
<P>
   make the tournament. Now, OU is in the Sweet 16 after beating
fourth-seeded Arizona and
</P>
<P>
   fifth-seeded UNC Charlotte. Oklahoma is just the third No. 13
seed to advance
</P>
<P>
   from the first weekend of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kelvin Sampson thought his team should have gotten a lower
seed
</P>
<P>
   after finishing second in the Big 12 and posting road wins at
Oklahoma State,
</P>
<P>
   Missouri and Texas, all of which got lower seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what? Sweet 16 gives our program that credit,''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson said. ``It's validation. It gives you credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners, who have a group of hot three-point shooters led by
Eric
</P>
<P>
   Martin, are in the round of 16 for the first time since 1989 and
will meet top-seeded
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State on Friday in the Midwest Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   _ SW MISSOURI ST. (22-10): The Bears never have been to the
Sweet 16 but advanced thanks to a withering defense that held No. 5
Wisconsin and No. 4 Tennessee to a combined 30 of 108 shooting
(27.7 percent).
</P>
<P>
   SMS has a pair of solid guards in William Fontleroy and Kevin
Ault and a vastly under-rated post player in Danny Moore, who had
37 points and 21 rebounds in two games. The Bears also have a good
forward in Ken Stringer, a native of Lithonia.
</P>
<P>
   For its efforts, Southwest Missouri State gets to play No. 1
Duke Friday night in
</P>
<P>
   East Rutherford, N.J. Duke has won its last 11 games by an
average of 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Alford is realistic. ``We'll prepare, show up and play hard,''
said Alford, who might be headed
</P>
<P>
   to Iowa after that game. ``People certainly never thought we'd
get this far.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MIAMI OF OHIO (24-7): As one scribe said, it's Wally's World
and we're just living in it.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Wally Szczerbiak, who had 43 points in the
first-round upset
</P>
<P>
   of Washington and 24 on Sunday when the Red Hawks knocked off
second-seeded Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in my game and our team's playing our game, then
we're a team to
</P>
<P>
   contend with,'' the 6-8 forward said.
</P>
<P>
   After losing in the MAC Tournament, the Redhawks weren't
positive that they were going to get a bid. When they got a No. 10
seed, many poeple figured that Wally and the boys
</P>
<P>
   wouldn't be hanging around too long.
</P>
<P>
   Now Miami, in its first Sweet 16, takes on Kentucky, the
defending national champion,
</P>
<P>
   Friday in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   _ PURDUE (21-12): After losing five of its last six games going
into the tournament, the Boilermakers were one of the least likely
teams to make the Sweet 16. But
</P>
<P>
   Gene Keady and company, known for so many early exits as a low
seed, turned the
</P>
<P>
   tables, knocking off seventh-seeded Texas in overtime and
second-seeded Miami of
</P>
<P>
   Florida by 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people didn't even think we belonged in this
tournament,'' said
</P>
<P>
   forward Brian Cardinal, who had 20 points against Miami. ``It's
kind of fun to shock people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers, who finished 7-9 in the Big Ten, will play
sixth-seeded
</P>
<P>
   Temple in East Rutherford, N.J., on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
