<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN STOCK EXCHANGE CHIEF TO LEAVE FOR THERMO ELECTRON 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard Syron, who spent four years buffing up the
image of the often-beleaguered American Stock Exchange before
executing a surprising merger with the rival Nasdaq Stock Market
last year, will leave the exchange on June 1 to become chief
executive of Thermo Electron Corp.
</P>
<P>
   A conglomerate with subsidiaries in the instrumentation systems,
medical equipment and industrial machinery industries, Thermo
Electron has been one of the largest sources of new listings for
the American exchange in recent years, with 23 publicly traded
subsidiaries now traded on it.
</P>
<P>
   Syron, who has served on the board of Thermo Electron since
September 1997, will replace the company's 72-year-old founder,
George Hatsopoulos, who will remain as a non-executive chairman.
Hatsopoulos guided the company's unusual strategy of forming dozens
of subsidiaries around new technologies and then offering minority
stakes in the new companies to the public.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy, combined with growth that was often fueled by
acquisitions, led to big gains for Thermo Electron shareholders in
the first half of the 1990s, when the company's share price
quadrupled, to more than $44. But over the last three years, the
company has struggled, particularly since the Asian financial
crisis has slowed many of the cyclical industries, like paper and
pulp, where the company operates.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in addition to announcing Syron's appointment, Thermo
Electron said that a continued slowdown in its biomedical products
business would cause earnings in the first quarter to fall below
expectations. Thermo Electron shares, which are traded on the New
York Stock Exchange, fell 18.75 cents, to $14.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of Thermo Electron's board, Syron, 55, is already
familiar with the company and its unwieldy array of subsidiaries.
In fact, Syron said in an interview that the company's strategy has
created such a complex corporate structure that one of his first
jobs will be to decide which subsidiaries should be reincorporated
into the parent and which should be sold.
</P>
<P>
   The new position will represent a significant departure for
Syron, who has spent most of his career as a regulator, first
within the Federal Reserve System and then on Wall Street at the
American exchange.
</P>
<P>
   From those comparatively staid, tradition-bound institutions,
Syron will move to a company with an embedded entrepreneurial
culture, where for the first time he will answer to public
shareholders who, in effect, vote on the company's stock price
every day.
</P>
<P>
   His departure also marks the end of a sometimes rocky
relationship with members of the American Stock Exchange.
Seventy-five percent of the American exchange's members voted in
favor of the merger last June, but many of those were won over to
favoring the merger only in the final days of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Liang, a managing member of PBL Partners, a Chicago
investment firm, who initially opposed the merger, said he came to
have a good working relationship with Syron. ``He is a very
progressive thinker,'' Liang said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, said that if Syron had done more to promote the
exchange's growth, perhaps the institution could have remained
independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left the exchange in the position where the Nasdaq merger
was the best of the alternatives it had at that time,'' said Lewis
Lowenfels, a former member of the board of governors of the
American exchange, and a prominent New York securities lawyer who
represented the floor brokers in the Nasdaq-American Stock Exchange
merger. ``Perhaps he didn't build up the number of listed companies
to the extent that he could have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Syron came to the American Stock Exchange in 1994 from the
Federal Reserve Bank of Boston, where he served as president and
chief executive beginning in 1989. For the three previous years, he
was president of the Federal Home Loan Bank of Boston.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When he arrived, the American exchange was beset with problems
that went far beyond a poor image. The exchange was unable to
attract the most desirable technology companies, which favored the
Nasdaq market, and often lost listings of growing companies to the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   One of his first moves was to shut down the Amex's Emerging
Company Market, a small-cap market that was originated by Syron's
predecessor, James Jones, a former congressman who left the
exchange to become ambassador to Mexico. Soon after the new market
began operations, the exchange was embarrassed to find among its
listings a company whose largest shareholder had previously been
barred by the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Syron said he recognized that some exchange members did not
favor the merger with Nasdaq, or wanted him to recruit more company
listings. But he points out that during his tenure the exchange has
listed several highly successful unit trusts, each a sort of
publicly traded index fund that tracks a popular market index.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the exchange has lost several high-profile listings,
most recently Viacom Inc., which will begin trading on the Big
Board next month. But Syron points out that since he took over, the
value of seats on the American exchange has grown markedly, to a
record $660,000 last month from about $100,000 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Thermo Electron shareholders are likely to expect similar
results from Syron after seeing the value of their shares fall by
63 percent in the last year. Syron said he will initially put his
emphasis on continuing a restructuring that began last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues and challenges for Thermo Electron are not in its
product markets,'' Syron said. ``The company has become, perhaps
inevitably, quite complex, and that complexity is in danger of
deflecting the focus of the company's managers away from what they
need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   There are benefits to the company's structure, Syron said,
including giving the smaller subsidiaries access to the corporate
infrastructure of the parent and allowing them to borrow money at
lower rates than they would otherwise be able to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the complexity has made it difficult for many investors
and many institutions to understand the company,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The company will still consider potential acquisitions, he said,
but the more immediate focus will be either to bring companies that
are not sufficiently large to stand on their own back into the
parent's fold, or to sell those that do not fit with its long-term
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Further details about Syron's plans will be revealed on May 27
at the company's annual meeting in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Syron said he did not see any conflict in holding a seat on
Thermo Electron's board and, at the same time, overseeing the
exchange where its subsidiaries listed their shares. He noted that
he is not a member of the boards of any of the subsidiaries, and he
said he recused himself from any listing decisions. In addition, he
said, no exceptions to listing requirements were made for
Thermo-related companies while he was at the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Syron is not the only stock exchange chairman to serve on a
corporate board. Richard Grasso, chairman of the New York Stock
Exchange, has served on the board of Computer Associates
International since 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
