<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-RENAULT-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN SHARES, AND HOPES, RISE SHARPLY ON TALK OF RENAULT DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Shares of the ailing Nissan Motor Co. rose 13 percent in
heavy trading Monday as investors increased their bets that Renault
SA would seek to preserve its future in the rapidly consolidating
global auto industry by taking a stake in Japan's second-largest
car maker.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan said in a statement that it had received no formal offer
from Renault and could not comment on any discussions. But Kaoru
Yosano, the minister of international trade and industry, said
Nissan had become more confident that it would complete a deal.
Yosano said he believed that the two companies were close to
reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the ministry were similarly confident just two
weeks ago that Nissan would sell a stake to DaimlerChrysler AG.
Those negotiations broke off abruptly last week, apparently over
issues of management control and DaimlerChrysler's concerns about
its integration of the former Daimler Benz and Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshikazu Hanawa, Nissan's president, would say only that a
whirlwind 32-hour trip to Paris and back over the weekend to hold a
meeting with Renault's head, Louis Schweitzer, was very amicable.
Twenty-five of those hours were spent in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers would normally construe the trip's brevity as a sign of
rebuff, but Hanawa's trip was interpreted on Monday as an effort to
demonstrate good faith and personally negotiate the final issues
relating to a potential deal.
</P>
<P>
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, Nissan shares rose 53 yen, to 454
yen, or $3.85, in trading of 21.3 million shares, about five times
the average. Renault shares fell 0.43 euro, or 1.2 percent, to
35.40 euros, or $38.59, on the Paris Bourse.
</P>
<P>
   Renault's board is to meet on Tuesday to discuss the offer. The
French government owns 44 percent of Renault's shares, and it has
already expressed enthusiasm for an investment in Nissan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Without French government support, Renault might face difficulty
raising enough money to purchase a big enough stake to have board
representation and limited veto power. The company has $2.1 billion
in cash at its disposal, but a 33.4 percent stake would cost it 500
billion yen, or about $4.3 billion at current exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a stretch for them, yes,'' said Steven Usher, an
auto analyst at Jardine Fleming Securities in Tokyo. ``But if they
get the backing of the French government, which implies they will
have the full faith and credit of the French government behind
them, it won't be a stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the deal makes sense for Renault. An alliance with
Nissan would offer opportunities for sharing car designs and
utilizing surplus capacity in Nissan's factories in Japan and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It would also greatly expand Renault's global reach. Usher said
the company currently gets 84 percent of its revenues from Europe,
where it will face increased competition at the end of the year
because of deregulation. Only 4 percent of its revenues come from
Asia, and although the bulk of Nissan's Asian sales come from
Japan, its factories here would give Renault a springboard to the
rest of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's board was to discuss the terms Hanawa brought back with
him at a meeting on Monday. The most contentious issue was likely
the question of how much control Nissan was willing to cede to its
French suitor; many of Nissan's board members are worried about
signing away the company's autonomy, according to former
executives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
