<HEADER>
A1516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAFEE-RETIRE-BOS &LR;      03-15 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAFEE-RETIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHODE ISLAND'S CHAFEE TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senator John H. Chafee, the Rhode Island Republican who over
four terms in office became a champion of moderate conservatism,
announced Monday he will not run for reelection in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee, 76, a descendant of one of Rhode Island's founding
families, said the decision was based neither on fear of losing nor
frustration with the conservative wing of his party.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Chafee said simply: ``I want to come home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen senators hang around too long,'' he said in a
telephone interview. ``There are not enough Michael Jordans,
leaving at the peak of their game.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came on the heels of similar retirement
announcements by four other powerful senators, prompting new
speculation about whether the balance of power in the Senate might
shift in the next election. It also renewed questions about whether
another member of the Kennedy clan, Representative Patrick Kennedy,
Democrat of Rhode Island, might run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   And the decision left a gaping hole in the so-called New England
``mod squad,'' the group of four moderate Republicans who often
share opinions, and who, at Chafee's urging, meet for lunch in
Washington every Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But the most significant effect, in the eyes of officials in
both parties, was the loss of a powerful personality who for
decades stood as a symbol of New England independent-mindedness,
repeatedly _ and stubbornly _ bucking his own party to defend his
position on issues such as health care and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the announcement, President Bill Clinton phoned
Chafee in his Rhode Island office to praise his service in the
Senate, saying he was a ``darned good poker player'' for keeping
the decision secret for several weeks. Prodding Chafee to keep up
his good work during the remainder of his term, Clinton spoke to
the senator as an ally, saying he was ``interested in getting
things done with people who want to get things done,'' according to
a Chafee aide.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Jack Reed, the junior senator from Rhode Island and a
Democrat, described the affable war veteran as a role model of
sorts, saying ``everyone in Rhode Island will measure their careers
against the standards that he set.'' And throughout New England,
other moderates lamented the departure of a senator who staunchly
defended centrism even when the GOP made it politically dangerous
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept saying to him, `Oh, John, don't do this to us,''' said
Senator Olympia Snowe, a moderate Republican from Maine. ``I just
wanted to cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about a successor immediately swept Rhode Island and
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had earlier toyed with the idea of running for Senate,
then pledged to remain in the House, where he was recently
appointed by Minority Leader Richard Gephardt as chairman of the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee _ a powerful position
that controls the party's congressional bids.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, many Democrats wondered aloud whether Kennedy would run
anyway. Representative Joseph Moakley, dean of the Massachusetts
congressional delegation, said he would be in favor of a Kennedy
run but said voters ``would probably see another broken promise.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy, 31, who has shot up through the leadership ranks
since his arrival in 1994, renewed his promise to stay put. Any
hints of laying political groundwork _ such as Kennedy's brutal
attacks on Chafee for his role during the president's impeachment
trial _ should be taken at face value, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on the precipice of the House going back Democratic and
my mentor and friend, Dick Gephardt, being speaker, I think it's a
very big deal for me,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate is the Senate, but it's got one Senator Kennedy
there already,'' he said, referring to his father, Senator Edward
M. Kennedy. ``The only Kennedy on the ballot in 2000 is going to be
my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, attention turned to a wide range of candidates from
both the Democratic and Republican parties. Among the potential
candidates was another political son: Lincoln Chafee, son of the
senator, who is the Republican mayor of Warwick, just outside
Providence.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Chafee deflected attention away from a possible bid
Monday, saying of his father, ``Today is his day.'' But an aide
hinted his campaign was likely, even as a host of other politicians
threw their hats into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Robert Weygand, the state's junior Democratic
congressman, was widely viewed as a contender. So, too, were
Providence Mayor Buddy Cianci, an Independent; Richard Licht, a
former lieutenant governor and a Democrat; William Lynch, chair of
the state's Democratic Party; former lieutenant governor Bernard
Jackvony, a Republican; and Rhode Island Secretary of State James
Langevin, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, strategists at the national level wondered
what impact Chafee's retirement would have on the Senate, where
Republicans are in the majority, 55 to 45. Three Democrats _
Senators Richard H. Bryan of Nevada, Frank R. Lautenberg of New
Jersey, and Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York _ have said they
will not run again. One Republican, Senator Connie Mack of Florida,
has made similar plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears there's going to be a lot of change in the Senate
next time,'' said Senator Susan M. Collins, another moderate
Republican from Maine. ``Certainly, Senator Chafee's retirement
puts Rhode Island in the toss-up category.''
</P>
<P>
   Chafee, a Marine veteran of World War II and the Korean War,
came to elected office in 1956, as a legislator in the Rhode Island
Statehouse. He made his first astounding victory over a Democrat in
1962, beating an incumbent to become governor. After facing defeat
in 1968, he served as Secretary of the Navy to President Nixon. In
1976, after a failed Senate bid against Democrat Claiborne Pell,
Chafee was elected to the Senate _ the first Republican to do so in
six decades.
</P>
<P>
   He now sits as head of the Environmental and Public Works
Committee, in a powerful slot that handles conservation and
environmental issues. On the environment, he has sided with
Democrats more than once: In 1987, he supported a water projects
act opposed by President Reagan, and in 1990, he helped push the
Clean Water Act through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been a prominent voice on health care, chairing a
Republican task force on the issue in 1990 and later, in the early
1990s, working on proposals that, although never adopted, were at
the time deemed potentially bipartisan deals.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Chafee has been a true conservative, supporting
Republican initiatives such as NAFTA. Collins described this
independent quality as his ``substantial contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents a well-respected voice of reason on so many
issues,'' said Collins, who considers Chafee a mentor and friend.
``It's a loss for the Senate, and the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Chafee said: ``I'm saddened to leave them, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
