<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-MILITARY-COX     03-15 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MILITARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report claimBy Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For nearly 12 years, former Army Maj. Jeff Cleghorn
felt like a hunted man.
</P>
<P>
   Every bookstore he entered, every dinner with friends, every
time he looked at another man, Cleghorn, a Griffin native, feared
his fellow servicemen would detect the truth.
</P>
<P>
   And if they found out that he was gay, Cleghorn feared he would
be thrown out of the Army, an institution that had given him a
college education at North Georgia College and a passport to places
like Munich, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day of my life I was concerned about being found out,''
Cleghorn said. ``You are forced to submit to a pattern of deceit,
which runs against every core value taught in the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleghorn's experience is not uncommon. In fact, a new report
released Monday from the Servicemembers Legal Defense Network
asserts that discrimination against gays in the military is far too
common and on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after President Clinton adopted its ``don't ask,
don't tell, don't pursue'' policy, the group has found that
homosexual men and women are ferreted out, harassed and discharged
from the military against their will.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, reports of anti-gay harassment more than
doubled. Reports of military commanders asking and pursuing
suspected homosexuals increased by 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department reported 1,145 gay discharges from all
service branches in 1998, up from 997 in 1997. In 1994, the year
the last year, the Pentagon reported in January. In 1997, the total
was 997, the highest number since 1987. The number hit a low of 617
in 1994, the year the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy took effect,
there were 617 such discharges.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Fort Benning has one of the highest discharge rates
for homosexuality, scoring sixth among the nation's 44 major Army
bases, according to the group.
</P>
<P>
   And that has Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D-Ga.), a member of the
House Armed Services Committee, concerned that Fort Benning is
mistreating homosexuals and thumbing its nose at the president's
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to be allowing persecution at Fort Benning,'' McKinney
said. ``That's quite disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney plans to write a letter to Clinton urging him to
reconsider his policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any report of failure of a policy that was implemented to make
life easier for gays and lesbians is disappointing,'' McKinney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Army Lt. Col. Tom Begines said the Defense Department conducted
an extensive review of the policy last year and found that the
president's wishes were being applied and enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our policy that harassment of individuals will not be
tolerated,'' Begines said. ``If a service member is harassed or
threatened because of perceived sexual orientation, it is the
department's policy that commanders hold fully accountable those
persons who did the harassing.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's policy was adopted in 1994 after the killing of
a sailor in Japan. The policy allows gay men and lesbians to serve
in the armed services, but it prohibits them from declaring their
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Benning, Army spokesman Richard McDowell said he was
surprised at the base's ranking for discharging homosexuals. One
reason for the high number of discharges could be the high number
of trainees at the camp who don't make it through the rigors of
training. The president's policy is closely followed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never heard the charge that someone is being pursed,''
McDowell said. ``Our policy is the president's policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The denials carry little weight for Michelle Benecke and C.
Dixon Osburn, co-authors of the group's 230-page report documenting
cases of abuse and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lesbian, gay and bisexual service members are caught in a
deadly Catch-22,'' Osburn said. ``If they come out to try to dispel
the myths and stereotypes, they will be fired. Silence in the face
of anti-gay harassment only fuels the fires of hate.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do gay service members still endure physical attacks and
verbal comments such as ``You better not be gay, because in the
Navy we kill our fags?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of leadership,'' said Benecke, a former Army captain and
battery commander. ``Senior military leaders have been AWOL when it
comes to stopping anti-gay harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
