<P>
   THREATENED-CHINOOK (Seattle) _ Few area residents will feel it
Tuesday, when the chinook salmon is declared a threatened species
in Puget Sound. But over the next five years, the region is
expected to get a lot more green. Trees will be planted along
denuded rivers where salmon currently get baked by the sun.
Streamside forests and wetlands will be preserved. The salmon
listing is going to force people to think more green, too, from the
way they build roads, sewers and homes to the way they regulate
logging, fishing and even lawn fertilizing. The goal: to restore
chinook salmon runs, down about one-third from their peak.
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Taylor. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KARL-FINED (Seattle) _ The National Basketball Association
fined the Milwaukee Bucks $25,000 because George Karl made
disparaging comments about the management of his former Sonics
team. Karl, who was fired by Seattle after last season, was quoted
last week as saying that SuperSonics President Wally Walker was
``incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ For the Milwaukee Bucks, that
$25,000 fine is just their down payment on life with the mercurial
George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
