<SLUG> BC-ALZHEIMERS-STUDIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIES AIMED AT ALZHEIMER'S LIKE MALADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mild memory lapses without other thinking difficulties may
signal early Alzheimer's disease _ but they may not, according to
new studies that are focusing attention on an in-between disorder
called mild cognitive impairment.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists' ability to distinguish people with mild cognitive
impairment from those with early Alzheimer's disease led Monday to
the launching of two large studies to see if drugs or daily vitamin
E pills can keep the memory lapses from worsening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly exciting that we're beginning to identify this
new class of people'' with mild cognitive impairment, said Marcelle
Morrison-Bogorad of the National Institute on Aging. ``We know a
lot about the late stages of Alzheimer's disease, with its
multitude of disastrous cognitive problems. Now we must try to go
earlier in time.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is sponsoring one of the first prevention
trials, and the other is under the aegis of Novartis
Pharmaceuticals Corp. A third company-sponsored study is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The two studies unveiled Monday will monitor a total of 1,620
patients around the world for three years. They will compare the
effects of drugs used for Alzheimer's, high-dose vitamin E, and
placebo pills.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, scientists have no way to predict which
individuals with mild cognitive impairment will go on to develop
Alzheimer's. The new studies will try to determine if magnetic
resonance imaging scans will help identify those at risk.
</P>
<P>
   A new Mayo Clinic study of mild cognitive impairment, published
Monday, should help researchers and doctors distinguish patients
with mild cognitive disorder from those with mild Alzheimer's or
the normal effects of aging.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has not been a clear method of evaluating people with
memory loss,'' said Dr. Ronald C. Peterson, a Mayo Clinic
neurologist who led the study. ``We can now differentiate people
who meet the criteria for mild cognitive impairment from healthy
people and from those with mild Alzheimer's disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the Archives of Neurology, found that
patients with mild cognitive impairment have memory loss but no
difficulty with language, attention, or orientation in time or
space. The study involved 76 patients with mild cognitive
impairment, 234 healthy subjects, and 106 with mild Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   It also found that about 1 percent of healthy elders developed
Alzheimer's each year, compared to 12 percent of people with mild
cognitive impairment.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison-Bogorad said the memory changes seen in individuals
with mild cognitive impairment are different from the common
experience of misplacing car keys or groping for a word. ``It's
more like beginning to forget things you normally don't, like
important appointments,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal study will recruit 720 men and women between the
ages of 55 and 90 in up to 80 centers in Canada and the United
States, including Boston. Some will take the approved Alzheimer's
drug donepezil, others will take 2,000 units of vitamin E daily,
and a third group will take a placebo, or dummy drug.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers may call 1-888-455-0655 or go the project's web site
at www.memorystudy.org, Morrison-Bogorad said.
</P>
<P>
   The Novartis study will compare an experimental Alzheimer's drug
called rivastigmine to a placebo. Volunteers may call
1-877-554-HOPE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
