</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE PANEL CHIEF STRUGGLES TO FIND SUPPORT FOR CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of a bipartisan commission studying
the future of Medicare made a last-ditch effort on Monday night to
salvage his proposal for radical changes in the health insurance
program for the elderly. However, he said he did not know if he
could round up the necessary votes in time for the panel's final
meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the chairman, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., said President
Clinton had given him no assistance in trying to get those votes.
Breaux needs support from at least one of the president's four
appointees on the 17-member commission, but Breaux said he has not
secured support from any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I wish the president had come out and endorsed this
proposition?'' Breaux asked. ``The answer is yes. Am I disappointed
if he doesn't? The answer is obviously yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Breaux's proposal, the government, instead of paying
separately for each medical service, would offer a fixed amount of
money to each beneficiary. The beneficiary could use the money to
buy private health insurance, through a managed care plan, or to
enroll in the traditional fee-for-service Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which was created by a 1997 law, plans to vote
Tuesday on its final recommendations to insure the long-term
solvency of Medicare. The program is expected to run short of money
just as the first of 76 million baby boomers turn 65, in 2011.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and liberal Democrats in Congress
predict that the commission will end its work with 10 members
supporting the Breaux plan and seven opposed. Under the law that
created it, the commission needs 11 votes for any recommendation to
be sent to the president and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   To win support from Democrats, including Clinton's appointees,
Breaux is proposing to offer Medicare coverage of prescription
drugs as a new benefit. The government would pay all the costs of
such drugs for people with incomes up to 35 percent above the
official poverty level (incomes up to $10,568 a year for an
individual and $13,334 for a couple).
</P>
<P>
   Health maintenance organizations and other private health plans
would have to offer drug coverage to Medicare beneficiaries, but
they could charge extra. The original fee-for-service Medicare
program would also offer prescription drug coverage, through
arrangements with private insurers, but the government would not
subsidize the cost.
</P>
<P>
   In purchasing drugs for millions of Medicare beneficiaries,
Breaux said, the government would pay ``prices commonly available
in the market, without recourse to price controls.'' Drug companies
adamantly oppose price controls, saying they would choke off the
revenues needed to finance research and reward investors.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Clinton's appointees _ Stuart H. Altman, a professor of
health policy at Brandeis University, and Laura D'Andrea Tyson,
former chairwoman of the President's Council of Economic Advisers _
have praised some features of Breaux's proposal, including its
potential to save money by stimulating competition in the Medicare
market. But they have also insisted that Breaux clarify many
details of his plan.
</P>
<P>
   One of Clinton's appointees, Bruce C. Vladeck, the federal
official in charge of Medicare from 1993 to 1997, has led
opposition to Breaux's proposal, saying it would shred the
guarantee of health benefits for some of the sickest, most
vulnerable people in America.
</P>
<P>
   Rep.e Bill Thomas, R-Calif., who is co-chairman of the
commission, said he was disappointed that Clinton had stayed aloof
from the panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Republicans, we have Democrats,'' Thomas said. ``We
have members of the House, we have members of the Senate. We have
members of the public, and we have members of the private sector
all in support of this plan. The only group that hasn't given us
one vote is the president's appointees.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials responded on Monday that while they had
often consulted with the president's appointees, the commission
members were free to vote as they chose on the proposals. And, the
officials said, the White House will not comment until Clinton
reviews the panel's final report.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux and Thomas said they would translate the Breaux plan into
legislation and try to push it through Congress this year,
regardless of whether it is formally endorsed by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is supported by all 8 Republican members of the
commission and by 2 Democrats, Breaux and Sen. Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux's plan would gradually raise the eligibility age for
Medicare, to 67 from 65, over 24 years, from 2003 to 2027. People
age 65 or 66 who could not obtain private insurance would be
allowed to purchase Medicare coverage under rules to be specified
in the future, Breaux said.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal would also extend provisions of the Balanced Budget
Act of 1997 that curbed the growth of Medicare payments to doctors,
hospitals, home health agencies and nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of the commission estimated that Breaux's plan would
not produce significant savings in the first five years, but would
save a total of $100 billion from 2005 to 2009. Then, it said, the
savings would gradually increase, so that in 2030, Medicare
spending would be $600 billion less than now anticipated: $1.6
trillion, rather than the $2.2 trillion envisioned under current
law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2023EST &QL; 
