<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-AIRLINES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airline stocks up on fare increase
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite concerns of rebounding fuel prices, Delta Air
Lines' (DAL) and other carriers' stocks soared Monday on news the
industry raised fares for the second time this year.
</P>
<P>
   The ascent also was propelled by United Airlines' announcement
that first-quarter profits will exceed expectations. Parent UAL
Corp. said it foresees profits of about $1.35 a share, 24 percent
higher than the previous consensus. The world's biggest carrier
cited strong domestic business that, so far, has defied predictions
of a downturn this year.
</P>
<P>
   United initiated the fare increase last week, and by Monday
other big carriers had gone along, including Atlanta-based Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Delta closed up $5 at $69. The stock is up nearly 33 percent
year to date.
</P>
<P>
   The increase raises short-notice fares used by business
travelers by 1 percent, while more restricted leisure-oriented
fares rise 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows a boost of 2 percent on business-type fares and
4 percent on others imposed in January. Prior to that, there had
been no generalized fare increases in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst said the industry's willingness to go along with the
latest boost _ fare hikes usually fall apart if even one big
carrier balks _ reflects concern about rising fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think one of the primary motivators that caused the
airlines to fall into line was the fact that fuel prices appear to
have bottomed and are creeping back up,'' said Susan Donofrio, an
analyst with BT Alex. Brown Inc.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC last week announced crude oil production cuts that could
lead to a rebound in oil prices, which fell to a 12-year low at the
end of last year. It remains to be seen, however, whether the
planned cuts take full effect and how much they affect prices.
</P>
<P>
   Low jet fuel prices have been a major contributor to the airline
industry's profit run since 1996. Delta, for instance, spent $280
million less on fuel in 1998 than it did the prior year.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Dow Jones News Service contriibuted to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
