<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Different takes on DiMaggio, Kubrick farewells
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week the newsstand sings a chorus of goodbyes to film
auteur Stanley Kubrick and baseball great Joe DiMaggio, some
bidding adieu with a chuckle, others with a tear. In Newsweek
($3.50) Richard Ben Cramer paints DiMaggio as ``the loneliest hero
we have ever had,'' a man who walled himself away from his public,
friends and family. He died as he lived, writes Cramer, ``without
intimates of any sort.'' On the other hand, Roger Angell hymns
DiMaggio in the New Yorker ($3) by writing strictly about his
on-field style. Elsewhere in the New Yorker we learn of Ian
Watson's years-long effort to write a script for a Kubrick project
called ``A.I.'' and his visits to the reclusive filmmaker's manor
house in St. Albans, England. Among Kubrick's idiosyncrasies: Each
day the chauffeur would bring in a tray of fresh grass for one of
Kubrick's pampered indoor cats to roll in.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Yo, don't bumrush the bondsman: Ten years ago Richard
``Professor Griff'' Griffin, one-time ``minister of information''
for the rap group Public Enemy, precipitated a quick separation
from the group after he told a Washington Times reporter that Jews
were ``responsible for the majority of wickedness that goes on
around the globe.'' Today Griffin is a bail bondsman in Atlanta,
and he tells Vibe ($2.99) about his preferred handgun, his methods
of capturing bail jumpers, and his longing for a different line of
work that doesn't ``profit on someone else's misery.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  God, and Private Ryan: James Hampton Jr., an Elloree, S.C.
native, worked as a janitor in Washington D.C. from 1948-1964,
creating, in his offhours, a staggering work of devotional art that
he called ``The Throne of the Third Heaven of the Nations Millenium
General Assembly.'' ``St. James'' is profiled in the current Gadfly
($2.95). Also in Gadfly is a relentlessly corrosive review of
Steven Spielberg's cinematic career, printed just in time to take
the shine off Spielberg's upcoming Oscar statuettes. Writes Daniel
Kraus, ``Now Spielberg is merely so talented that he can cover up
the fact that he has almost nothing to say.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The wood man: Chuck Leavell, keyboard player for the Rolling
Stones, is listed among the Forbes ($4.95) Celebrity 100, partly,
we assume, because of his prudent financial planning. When the
aging Glimmer Twins decide to stop touring, Leavell will retire to
his 2,000-acre tree farm in Dry Branch, Ga. Called Charlane, the
spread generated $350,000 last year from sales of pulp wood and
from quail hunters paying to shoot birds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Funny papers: Despite the success of cartoonists such as Matt
Groening (''The Simpsons'') and Mike Judge (''King of the Hill'')
the comics subculture still lacks regular coverage in the mass
media. To right that wrong comes Hogan's Alley ($5.95), a thick,
and entertaining semi-annual (created by Atlantan Tom Heintjes)
that offers deep detail in the world of comics. The current issue
includes interviews with Tom Batiuk (creator of Funky Winkerbean
and Crankshaft) and an account of Popeye's transformation from a
newspaper comic strip to a Max Fleischer animated cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Early to the massacre: ``Few places can rival the primal
allure of Africa, or the continent's troubles,'' begins the account
of a safari in the current Conde Nast Traveller ($3.95). Writer Ted
Botha takes a trip to the Bwinde Impenetrable Forest in Uganda to
goggle at one of the last surviving enclaves of mountain gorillas.
Shortly after Botha thrilled to a close encounter with a Silverback
male, Rwandan rebels would hack to death eight gorilla-watching
tourists, including two rebels, in the very same national park.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
