<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MAGAZINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE BILL INTENSIFIES US-CANADA TRADE TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Setting the stage for an ugly trade war with the
United States, Canada has moved forward on a controversial bill
meant to protect its domestic magazine industry from American
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Despite US warnings of retaliation that could do billions of
dollars of damage to the Canadian economy, Parliament's House of
Commons Monday passed a bill banning Canadian companies from
advertising in so-called ``split run'' editions of US magazines
marketed in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the bill won approval, however, Canadian and US trade
officials continued to negotiate in Washington, raising the
possibility of a compromise before the bill becomes law and a clash
becomes inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, passage of the legislation by Commons, the most
powerful of Parliament's two chambers, represented an escalation of
what has already become one of the most rancorous disputes in
decades between the neighbors, with Washington threatening
sanctions that could put thousands of workers north of the border
out of work by imposing punishing tariffs on Canadian steel,
textiles and plastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Canadian magazine market means very little to the US, but
the US has decided to make a test case, as it has with the European
Union on bananas,'' said Toronto-based trade consultant Lawrence
Herman.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is being followed closely in Europe, especially
France, where there is sentiment in favor of restricting some US
``cultural imports,'' especially movies, in order to nurture
homegrown talent. No other country except Canada, however, has been
willing to risk American trade wrath by pressing one of the
trickest of trade issues _ should expressions of culture, whether
high art or low skin mags, be exempt from the rules governing
trade?
</P>
<P>
   For some Canadians the issue carries considerable moral
resonance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We either fight for this country, or we blink and let the
Americans take over,'' author June Callwood told a news conference
in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of the bill is to block American mass market
publications from taking an even larger bite of the Canadian
magazine market. But US officials say the measure violates free
trade treaties between the two countries, and Washington has
pledged to launch massive sanctions against the Canadian steel,
textile and plastic industries if the bill becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian nationalists say the drastic step is necessary to
defend Canada from the cultural Juggernaut of the US. Magazines,
they argue, are a vital form of cultural expression, not just a
commodity covered by trade law.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do nothing would be to lie down to the schoolyard bully,''
said Canadian Heritage Minister Sheila Copps, chief architect of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the nationalists were crowing victory in Parliament,
Canadian diplomats were negotiating feverishly with American trade
officials in hopes of striking a compromise that would head off a
trade row. There is still time for a deal as the bill heads to
Canada's Senate, a usually rubber stamp body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US and Canada will end up cutting a deal, and all this
will have been for naught,'' said former US Ambassador James J.
Blanchard, who stepped down in 1996 as Washington's top diplomat to
America's most important trading partner. More than $1 billion in
goods and services crosses the US-Canada border every day, the
world's largest trade relationship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
