<HEADLINE>
DOW, S&AMP;P CLIMB TO RECORD HIGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices rose sharply Monday, swept higher by a
couple of big merger announcements, enthusiastic buying of
technology shares and an optimistic earnings forecast from UAL, the
nation's biggest commercial airline company.
</P>
<P>
   The advance pushed two major market measures _ the Dow Jones
industrial average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index _ to
new records. The Nasdaq composite index failed to set a new high
but was the session's best-performing index. Even small stocks,
which have done dismally this year, had a good day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what has been happening in the U.S. economy, you have to
be very positive on the market,'' said Jack Shaughnessy, the chief
investment strategist at Advest Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 82.42 points, or 0.8
percent, at 9,958.77. Despite the run-up, the Dow never seriously
challenged the 10,000 mark. In the session, it rose as high as
9,970.15. Still, it was the first time the blue-chip index had
closed above 9,900, eclipsing its previous high of 9,897.44, set on
March 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, the 10,000 level for the Dow is largely an
irrelevancy,'' said Peter Canelo, a U.S. investment strategist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``The key drivers for the market are a
tremendous economy without any inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the S&AMP;P 500 rose 12.67, or 1 percent, to 1,307.26.
That gain passed the previous record of 1,297.68, which was also
established on March 11.
</P>
<P>
   Strong buying of technology and Internet shares powered the
Nasdaq index to a gain of 49.91, or 2.1 percent, to 2,431.44. And
the Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks gained 2.46, or 0.6
percent, to 400.84.
</P>
<P>
   Two big merger deals _ Fleet Financial's acquisition of
BankBoston and DuPont's takeover of Pioneer Hi-Bred International _
were important positives.
</P>
<P>
   The Fleet deal refocused attention on consolidation in the
financial services industry and pushed up prices of a number of big
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch gained 4 7/16, to 91 11/16, on rumors that Chase
Manhattan might be looking to acquire the nation's biggest
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, a Dow component and a company that in the past was
mentioned as a possible takeover candidate, was the best performing
part of the blue-chip index Monday, rising 3 3/8, to 125 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston gained 1/8, to 47 1/8; Fleet lost 2 9/16, to 42 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pioneer Hi-Bred, the world's largest seed-corn
company, rose 4 1/16, to 38 3/8, after it was announced that DuPont
had agreed to buy the 80 percent of the company it does not already
own for about $40 a share in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont was the worst-performing component of the Dow, falling 1
1/2, to 56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings announcement from UAL, which said it expected
first-quarter earnings to exceed expectations by 24 percent because
of strong domestic business, powered the entire airline sector
higher.
</P>
<P>
   UAL, the parent of United Airlines, gained 6 11/16, to 73 3/4;
US Airways rose 2 7/8, to 55 3/8; AMR, the parent of American
Airlines, jumped 3 3/4, to 61 3/4, and Delta Air Lines rose 5, to
69.
</P>
<P>
   The gains helped to push the Dow Jones transportation average up
4.2 percent. Even with the big rise, that index is still trading
almost 8 percent below the peak it set in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Given the strength in the economy, Canelo from Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter said that first-quarter earnings could well be strong
across a wide swath of industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel the consumer is slowing down at all,'' he said.
``That should be a positive for the overall economy and should lead
to strong earnings across-the-board, with the exception of some
basic industries and energy, which will suffer due to tough
comparisons from a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In technology, Netscape Communications rose 6 1/8, to 91. It was
announced on Friday that America Online had won antitrust clearance
from federal regulators to complete the $8.98 billion acquisition
of the top maker of Internet software. America Online rose 5 7/8,
to 102.
</P>
<P>
   Among large-capitalization technology companies, Microsoft
gained 5 11/16, to 165 7/8; Dell Computer rose 1 9/16, to 43 3/4,
and EMC jumped 4 1/16, to 116 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   TheStreet.com's Internet sector index rose 36.83, or 6.5
percent, to a new high of 604.83.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stocks look expensive, but they have looked that way
since they were trading at half of what they are now,'' said
Michael Molnar, a managing director in retail sales and trading at
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
