<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREATENED-CHINOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITIES FORCED TO PLAN FUTURE AROUND SALMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB TAYLOR  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Few area residents will feel it Tuesday, when the
chinook salmon is declared a threatened species in Puget Sound. But
over the next five years, the region is expected to get a lot more
green.
</P>
<P>
   Trees will be planted along denuded rivers, including the
Sammamish River, where salmon currently get baked by the sun.
Streamside forests and wetlands will be preserved by acquisition
and easements.
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, the salmon listing is going to force
people to think more green, too, from the way they build roads,
sewers and homes to the way they regulate logging, fishing and even
lawn fertilizing.
</P>
<P>
   Government, business and homeowners ``are going to have to think
far more about their impacts on fish than ever before,'' says King
County Executive Ron Sims.
</P>
<P>
   The goal: to restore chinook salmon runs, down about one-third
from their peak.
</P>
<P>
   Only the general outline of those changes has been framed in
recent months by cities, counties and the state. The details will
be penciled in over the next three years by a plethora of agencies
and watershed groups, perhaps with additions from federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   What won't happen, according to Sims, is economic paralysis. By
taking strong actions to protect and restore salmon habitat, King,
Pierce and Snohomish counties in Western Washington expect to avoid
being tied in knots by Endangered Species Act lawsuits, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have the flexibility to continue much of what
we do today in terms of growth and development _ and still be able
to conserve the salmon.'' Sims said in an interview. ``We're not
going to have a lot of litigation in our county stopping things.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen. Environmental-group lawyers are waiting
to see what stream safeguards are applied. And though Sims and
other local leaders hope to get a broad federal exemption from
citizen lawsuits, federal officials are leaning toward narrow
exemptions. In any event, these will take months to hash out.
</P>
<P>
   What will change immediately is anything that involves federal
authority or money. As soon as the fish is formally protected by
the Endangered Species Act, all federal activity in the region will
be subject to review by biologists to ensure it doesn't harm the
fish. Hundreds of road projects will face review, as will decisions
to fill wetlands, dredge waterways or even build federally
subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, nothing else will change right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could drive a bulldozer down a stream on private land now
and it would be stupid, but it wouldn't be illegal,'' at least
under the species law, says Brian Gorman, a spokesman for the
National Marine Fisheries Service.
</P>
<P>
   Still, local governments face strong pressure to show progress
toward a more salmon-friendly environment. Federal prohibitions
against hurting salmon habitat will kick in as soon as federal
officials write a rule on what is banned. Federal officials want a
Puget Sound chinook rule in place by fall, and another against
harming bull trout in June.
</P>
<P>
   Those rules are crucial to the region. If they are written as
simple, sweeping prohibitions, they could paralyze economic growth
by exposing all kinds of actions to citizen lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, King, Pierce and Snohomish counties and their component
cities want rules that would exempt them from citizen lawsuits. In
effect, they want federal declarations that they are doing enough
to recover the listed fish.
</P>
<P>
   To win such a broad shield, the counties are touting what they
have done in the past, together with promises to do more over the
next three years. Because promises alone aren't enough to satisfy
federal courts or agencies, their strategy to demonstrate
commitment includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Laundry lists of all they have done to preserve and protect
salmon habitat in the past.
</P>
<P>
   _ Early actions that include additional environmental reviews
and better enforcement of existing rules.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pledges to review all relevent ordinances for salmon impacts.
</P>
<P>
   _ A list of research and habitat protection or restoration
projects they will propose for funding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Support for watershed groups that will draft detailed recovery
plans over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest challenges for local government is the need
to show quick improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, salmon habitat protection comes from a tangle of
ordinances that have accumulated over decades: on grading,
clearing, building codes, shorelines, drainage, sensitive areas and
comprehensive plans. Each was a product of years of debate and
compromise, so quickly revising them was not an option. Instead,
the counties pledged to consider tightening each of those
ordinances over the coming year or two.
</P>
<P>
   So far, King County is saying its rules look pretty good, but
need much better enforcement. Pierce and Snohomish Counties are
expected to need more tightening of their rules. And smaller cities
are further behind.
</P>
<P>
   To show quick improvement, the counties have already moved to
hire more staff to enforce environmental rules, and additional
requests for inspectors are coming.
</P>
<P>
   They also have proposed to expand reviews of new construction
near streams, wetlands and shorelines. This scrutiny, conducted
under the State Environmental Policy Act, is likely to push new
buildings farther back from these sensitive areas, while requiring
better runoff control, less pavement and other adjustments. To
builders' distress, it also could expand permit delays.
</P>
<P>
   Major new habitat acqusitions, restoration projects and
construction projects are expected. King County will build new
sewage treatment plants to recycle treated ``grey'' water for use
by golf courses, industries and farms. That will enable those users
to leave more water in streams for fish.
</P>
<P>
   Construction and maintenance of roads will change across the
region, with an eye to reducing the flow of pollution and sediment
into streams. Culverts will be fixed to allow fish passage.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pressure on homeowners and businesses will mount to
use less water and protect stream quality by using fewer pesticides
and fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the counties hope to win these changes through major
public education efforts like newsletters, advertising and public
meetings. But new forms of regulation will be considered.
</P>
<P>
   King County, the only Washington government to require control
of livestock around streams, says it will consider imposing rules
on commercial use of pesticides and fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   All this talk and planning, however, will pay off only when it
is reflected in what government actually does. Even while hatching
these plans, local agencies have dredged Adare Creek near Duvall
and polluted it with diesel fuel and sediment from an industrial
storage area, says Kurt Beardslee, director of Washington Trout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talk is great,'' he said, ``but it doesn't yet match the
reality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
