<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE PANEL VOTE SHY OF REVAMP AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM AND AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hopes of a bipartisan agreement in Washington on a
plan to revamp Medicare faded Monday as a blue-ribbon panel charged
by Congress with recommending changes to the financially troubled
program appears to be one vote shy of reaching a consensus on a
broad proposal.
</P>
<P>
   As the popular health insurance program for 39 million elderly
and disabled Americans veers toward bankruptcy, the 17-member panel
has been grappling for more than a year to craft a broad plan to
avert Medicare's financial collapse, which is predicted to occur as
early as 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, scheduled to meet a final time Tuesday, has been
unable to agree on a broad range of issues, from finding new ways
to pay for Medicare to adding prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the panel's co-chairmen, Sen. John Breaux, Democrat of
Louisiana, and Rep. John Thomas, a California Republican, unveiled
a revised final proposal and said they would be making a last ditch
effort to garner the 11 votes needed to reach a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux and Thomas have 10 votes, but have so far been unable to
come to agreement with swing voters Stuart Altman, professor at
Brandeis University, and Laura D'Andrea Tyson, dean of the
University of California at Berkeley Haas School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   Altman and Tyson have insisted that the proposal be more
specific about ways to finance Medicare, including adopting
President Clinton's suggestion to devote 15 percent of the
projected federal budget surplus to Medicare. They have also called
for broad prescription drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The final proposal contains neither request, setting up a
scenario in which it is unlikely to muster the necessary votes to
win the bipartisan imprimatur of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux Monday declined to predict the outcome of Tuesday's vote.
He did, however, say he would propose the plan as legislation,
regardless of whether the panel gives its approval. Breaux further
stated he was confident he had enough votes in the Senate to pass
such legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the end of the process. This is just the
beginning,'' Breaux said.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux's proposal calls for raising the eligibility age for
Medicare beneficiaries from 65 to 67, adding prescription drug
coverage for beneficiaries whose annual incomes are at or less than
135 percent of federal poverty guidelines, requiring Medicare
supplemental insurance policies to cover prescription drugs, and
removing graduate medical education subsidies from Medicare's
budget. It also proposes to create a market for private health
insurers to care for beneficiaries, who would be required to pay 12
percent of the insurance premium.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, Breaux said, would result in $102 billion in reduced
Medicare spending between 2003 and 2009, with savings reaching $700
billion a year by 2030. The proposal would keep Medicare solvent
for five additional years beyond 2008, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's panel debate is likely to be politically charged.
Republicans on the panel have charged Clinton with obstructing
their work, using his influence with Altman and Tyson to hold up a
consensus. Altman Monday vigorously denied the claim, saying he has
always pushed for expanded drug coverage and an effort to identify
explicit financing for the $210 billion-a-year program.
</P>
<P>
   White House deputy for health policy, Chris Jennings, Monday
said Clinton ``made a decision that he wouldn't tell people to vote
for something they think is flawed or against something they think
is strong. The idea that we could direct members cannot be held up
for credible argument. They all have their own views.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
