u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-LA-NYT     03-15 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-LA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES REVELS IN DESIGNATION AS SITE OF DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Evoking the glories and the ghost of John F.
Kennedy, the Democratic National Committee announced on Monday that
it will hold its national convention here in the summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In coming to Los Angeles for the first time in 40 years, the
Democrats are hoping that history will repeat itself. In 1960, John
F. Kennedy, then a U.S. senator from Massachusetts, won the
presidential nomination here and went on to become a cherished
icon.
</P>
<P>
   The city's selection had been widely known since last week, so
Monday's official announcement was a time for the people who
brought the Democrats to town to take a bow.
</P>
<P>
   The newly elected Democratic governor of California, Gray Davis,
said the convention and the state's new earlier primary will help
give California ``unrivaled clout'' and show that ``Los Angeles is
back, having weathered riots and recession, floods and fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The billionaire businessman, Eli Broad, said the convention will
create jobs and pour $150 million into the city's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican mayor of Los Angeles, Richard J. Riordan, was
beaming about the prospect of so many Democrats coming to town.
``Democrats are almost as good as Republicans,'' the mayor said
after the news conference. ``Right now, I'm in love with the
Democrats for picking Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, the national chair-designate of the Democratic
National Committee, said that Los Angeles was selected for several
reasons, including the ``vibrancy and diversity of the people'' and
the election of Davis, the first Democratic governor elected in
California in 16 years. He added that Riordan, ``a man who has
reached across the divide of partisan politics,'' had also played a
key role.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Andrew said Los Angeles was selected because of a
partnership between business, politicians and civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   According to convention organizers, the private sector is
committed to providing $28.1 million of the $35.3 million cost of
the convention. ``The citizens of California,'' Andrew said, ``will
get the benefit and not the burden.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention will be held at the new 900,000-square-foot
Staples Center, which is scheduled to be completed this fall. The
center is in downtown Los Angeles, a few blocks from the city's
Skid Row, which was crowded with homeless people on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Erlenbusch, executive director of the Los Angeles Coalition
to End Hunger and Homelessness, said he did not expect the
convention to have much economic impact on the people who live so
close to the Staples Center. During the Olympics of 1984 and the
pope's visit four years later, Erlenbusch said, there were
countless ``horror stories'' of homeless people being swept off the
streets by the police.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James M. Lawson Jr., a leader of the civil rights
movement and now the pastor of the Holman Methodist Church, a few
miles from the convention site, said there is no doubt that some
ordinary people will get jobs because of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the convention will not effect any long-term change in Los
Angeles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Joel Kotkin, a senior fellow at the Pepperdine Institute for
Public Policy, said the coalition that helped bring the convention
to Los Angeles is an example of a new direction for the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
