<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-RAPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPE CASE ILLUMINATES PROBLEM IN MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ A young female soldier is assigned to work for the
commander of an Israeli military training base in the Negev Desert.
One day, the two start a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it does not sound like a surprising story, in a country
where high-ranking officers are feted like movie stars and where
young female conscripts are assigned to be their secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   But this relationship has moved out of the backroom and into the
courtroom. The woman, who was 19 years old when the affair began
with her 40-year-old married commanding officer, said the
relationship started as consensual but, several weeks later,
culminated in rape in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the military sided with Brigadier General Nir
Galili, who denied raping the woman, although he admitted to a
sexual affair. He was reprimanded for ``inappropriate behavior''
with a subordinate, and his promotion was delayed two years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Galili's two years are up, and the military wants to make
him a major general, the second highest rank in the Israeli
military. But the woman, whose name has not been made public, has
gone to the high court to demand it stop the promotion or order
that Galili be tried for raping her.
</P>
<P>
   The military's decision to promote Galili, which the court is
expected to rule on Tuesday, is being cited by women's activists as
proof that Israeli society in general, and the military in
particular, is still unwilling to treat rape allegations seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military says it was consensual, but we think you can't
talk about consent between a 40-year-old man and a 19-year-old girl
under his command,'' said Yaron Keidar, a lawyer for the woman.
</P>
<P>
   The case has come up at a time when reported rapes and other
sexual abuses are on the rise here. Some activists say that the
army, as the protector of the country, needs to show that it is as
serious about protecting those who fill its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, over the past few years, there has been
growing consciousness about violence and sexual abuse of woman, but
where is the army in all this? Is it blind?'' asked Orit
Sulitzeanu, spokeswoman for the Israel Women's Network, an activist
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of sexual harassment and abuse is one that all
countries with mixed-sex armies must grapple with, but in Israel
the issue may reverberate more deeply because the compulsory army
service applies to young Jewish women as well as men.
</P>
<P>
   While the military's rules forbid sexual relationships between
officers and soldiers under their command, activists say women
often feel powerless to say no. Some say the military should revoke
Galili's promotion, to make it clear to all soldiers and officers
that any sexual relationship that smacks of harassment or abuse
will not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What message is the army broadcasting when it declares its
commitment to fight sexual harassment while, at the same time,
promoting a senior officer who had sex with a female soldier under
his command in gross violation of the general staff's order
forbidding such relationships?'' wrote the defense correspondent
for the respected daily newspaper Ha'aretz.
</P>
<P>
   The same newspaper reported that some officers say Galili has
been punished enough, arguing that his promotion should not be held
up any longer over a three-year-old rape allegation.
</P>
<P>
   The military itself said in a court filing that the woman's
petition should be dismissed because, among other things, she could
have responded three years ago if she did not like the punishment
meted out to Galili. Noting that she refused to testify at the time
_ making a trial impossible _ it also suggested that her claim was
not credible because she did not immediately leave the room after
the alleged assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the opinion of the chief of staff, he is one of
the best fighters and commanders we have,'' the military's court
filing said of Galili. The filing was provided by Keidar, the
woman's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Keidar added that his client did not testify at the time because
she was traumatized and did not want to face the ordeal of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt ashamed and humiliated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   News of the promotion jolted her and rekindled her anger, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't think he would be promoted and only after she heard
the announcement did she decide to start legal action,'' Keidar
said.
</P>
<P>
   The military's stance outrages many women's activists. They say
the military's position is a sign that despite its campaigns to
stop sexual harassment and abuse, the male-dominated institution
still does not understand how difficult it can be for a young,
female conscript.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the structure of the military itself.
With rare exceptions women do not serve in combat units and instead
are often consigned to secretarial work.
</P>
<P>
   The commanding officer, usually a man, has almost full control
over the woman's life. He decides whether the young woman goes home
for the weekend, whether she gets a task she enjoys, what time she
can leave for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to understand the all-encompassing power he has over
her. She's serving him, he has complete authority over her and I
don't think she has the ability to say no,'' said Anat Hoffman, a
Jerusalem city councilor and a member of the Israel Women's
Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people on the outside understand what sort of
price she would have to pay,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
