<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-HATTEBERG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATTEBERG CATCHES THE SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Honest, it really happened this way. Monday,
Red Sox catcher Scott Hatteberg learned he no longer has to catch
the knuckleballs of Tim Wakefield. His response was a wide smile
and pair of three-run homers against the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't have written a script to top what the third-year
catcher did in the Red Sox' 13-2 exhibition victory. In addition to
his offensive outburst, he was solid behind the plate in his
handling of Pedro Martinez, who struck out seven in four innings
and three times pitched out of danger by changing speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg is no Carlton Fisk. He's not even a Rich Gedman,
although he does wear uniform No. 10. He was the Sox' third pick in
the 1991 draft who has worked himself up through the system and now
splits the major league catching duties with Jason Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg caught 112 games last year, and even with Varitek
assigned to be Wakefield's caddie, Hatteberg will get a lot of
action again this season. He will be looking to hone his skills,
too, because there will be serious competition from some current
farmhands soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the lefthanded-hitting Hatteberg was used mostly
against righthanders, and Varitek, a switch hitter, against
lefties. But even if a righthander is opposing Wakefield, Hatteberg
will take a seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to catch both of them every day,'' said Sox manager
Jimy Williams, ``but I can't. Will this take some at-bats away from
Hatteberg? Probably. But it won't matter because these two kids
pull for each other. They really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg's first homer Monday came in the first inning off
Pittsburgh's Chris Peters, a lefthander who gave up seven runs. In
the fourth, Hatteberg went deep off Johan Lopez, a righthander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've gotten a little stronger,'' said Hatteberg.
``It's not a case of me trying to hit more home runs. I think I'm
just making better contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatteberg had no problem with the decision to use Varitek with
Wakefield. There are four other starters in the rotation and a
bullpen to work with. It's a much better situation than a year ago,
when Jim Leyritz, since traded to San Diego, was also in the
catching mix and Hatteberg was battling to make the roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had Leyritz, and it looked like a situation where neither
of us would be catching a lot,'' said Hatteberg. ``But it worked
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This spring training, I can use it for what it was intended _
get ready for the year. That's nice. You come in and maybe push
each other. Before, you worried if you had a bad at-bat it was do
or die because you want to impress so much. Now you come in and you
feel better _ not that you want to screw up. There's just not that
constant pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot in the last two years. In the case of
pitchers, there are quite a few of them back and it's easier to
work with guys you knew in the past. Last year, it worked out great
offensively. You combine our numbers and it's the kind of
production we'd like to have every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, hitting is always been a matter of adjustments. My
first year I got a lot of fastballs, my second I saw fewer of them
in fastball situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Williams said, decisions to platoon young players
backfire. Varitek has a slight edge on defense. Hatteberg's bat is
making him a valuable asset. And he can catch, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can Scotty handle Wakefield?'' said Williams. ``Yes, he did
for two years. But this is just a decision we made. One catcher for
Wake. Maybe this will help him. As for Hatteberg, I know he feels
better about himself. He looks good out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
