<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THERMO-SYRON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMEX CHIEF SYRON TO HEAD THERMO ELECTRON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 43 years at the helm of Thermo Electron Corp., George N.
Hatsopoulos Monday said he is stepping down as chief executive and
turning over the reins on June 1 to board member Richard F. Syron,
chief executive of the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Syron, a former president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston,
will return to Massachusetts to become president and chief
executive of Thermo Electron during a difficult period for the
Waltham, Mass. instruments and equipment company. Thermo Electron
is undergoing a restructuring after a slump in profits. Monday, it
warned Wall Street analysts that first-quarter earnings would be
lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Hatsopoulos, 72, will remain Thermo Electron
chairman, his departure from active management ends one of the
longest reigns in corporate history.
</P>
<P>
   Hatsopoulos, a Greek immmigrant who did graduate work at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, founded Thermo Electron in
1956. He and his brother John built the company, a pioneer on Route
128, into a diversified company with $3.9 billion in revenue last
year.
</P>
<P>
   John Hatsopoulos, 64, retired in January as president and will
remain as vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Currentl president Arvin Smith will remain with the company in
an advisory role.
</P>
<P>
   Thermo Electron's stock has fallen from a high of 44 at the end
of 1997 to 13 5/8 earlier this month. Monday, Thermo Electron
shares closed at 14, down 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``In December, the board (of directors) and I decided that we
had to addresss the issue of who will succeed me,'' said
Hatsopoulos. ``My health is very good, but I got tired of working
70 hours a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Syron is ``an organization person, a manager of talent and
someone who also has a vision,'' said George Hatsopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   The board tapped Syron after the company hired a search firm and
interviewed nearly three dozen inside and outside candidates,
Hatsopoulos added.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was personal contact that cemented the appointment.
Both men have known each other for 17 years. Hatsopoulos, once a
board member of the Boston Fed, had recruited Syron away from
Federal Home Loan Bank of Boston, where was chief executive, to
become Boston Fed president in 1989. Earlier in his career, Syron
had served as an aide to then-Federal Reserve Board chairman Paul
Volcker.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Syron left Boston for New York to head the American
Stock Exchange. Last year, he helped engineer its absorption into
the Nasdaq Stock Market and its parent, the National Association of
Securities Dealers. That in effect left Syron without a job.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, in a phone interview, the 55-year-old Syron said he
plans to complete Thermo Electron's previously announced
reorganization. The company is known for its unusual strategy of
forming companies around technologies it develops and selling a
minority interest in them to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The reorganization calls for reducing the number of spinout
companies from 23 today to 16 by the end of this year. Last
December, the company said it would fold some spinouts into a
single company, transfer some operations and take some
publicly-held subsidiaries private.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these spinouts _ which are 60 percent to 90 percent
owned by Thermo Electron _ have not been as profitable as expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a parent company with 23 subsidiaries, you have
the danger of just the complexity of working on the interactions
between the companies and the managers, which is very
time-consuming, and you have to simplify the organizational
structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the core, the strategy of having all these spinout
companies was a good, but we may have stayed with it too long,''
Syron said.
</P>
<P>
   Syron, a Boston native, said future products developed by Thermo
Electron may become part of existing spinout companies that address
specific industries.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came just before the company warned that
first-quarter profit would be around 15 cents a share, down from
analysts' consensus forecast of 19 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thermo Electron has some underperforming businesses and I
think having Syron on board will be viewed positively. He has both
an understanding for the company and a background of leading large
organizations,'' said Michael Hutchison of Barrington Capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
