<SLUG> BC-FLEET-LATIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATIN AMERICA WATCHING FLEET-BANKBOSTON DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ News of Fleet Financial Group's acquisition of
BankBoston Corp. made headlines from Mexico City to Buenos Aires
Monday, as observers in Latin America's major business centers
wondered whether Fleet would maintain BankBoston's decades-long
commitment to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder what they're going to do now in Latin America,'' said
one Mexico-based foreign banker with extensive experience in the
region. ``Fleet has no expertise in this field.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger was front-page news in Sao Paulo, Brazil's financial
capital and one of the major hubs of BankBoston's Latin American
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston's international experience could not be
more different. Fleet has no recognizable presence overseas, having
concentrated on building up its domestic and regional operations.
BankBoston, on the other hand, has built an extensive and
well-respected Latin American unit over almost a century.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it may have been the bank's exposure in Latin America,
coupled with the economic crisis that has hit the region, that
ultimately led BankBoston to accept Fleet's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like the stars were aligned this time,'' said
BankBoston chairman Charles Gifford, who will become chief
executive officer of the new entity at the end of 2001. ``The
volatility of our business was making it increasingly difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, officials said Monday, the Latin American
operations of the combined Fleet Boston Corp. will keep the
BankBoston name.
</P>
<P>
   The unit will be managed by Henrique C. Meirelles, BankBoston's
Brazilian-born president, who will oversee much of the new
institution's international businesses.
</P>
<P>
   And despite a continued economic crisis that has hampered the
bank's recent performance in Brazil and Argentina, there are no
immediate plans to scale back an aggressive $100 million expansion
program that BankBoston began in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done business in Latin America for over 80 years, and
we expect to continue that tradition while pursuing opportunities
in other global markets,'' Meirelles said in a statement issued by
both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts and banking industry leaders in Latin America
wonder whether the merger will mean a diminished role for
BankBoston in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this will give them more ways to cushion the blow of
what's happened in Latin America,'' said the president of a bank in
Buenos Aires who requested anonymity. ``But in situations like
this, what we usually see is layoffs and loan portfolios which are
cut back because they're considered to be too risky.''
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston established its first Latin American office in
Argentina in 1917 to assist Massachusetts textile companies. Thirty
years later, it set up shop in Brazil, and now has offices in eight
countries, where it provides corporate lending and consumer
services such as checking accounts, credit cards, and mutual funds,
primarily for affluent clients.
</P>
<P>
   The business has contributed as much as 19 percent to the bank's
annual revenue in recent years. But it also has accounted for some
costly failures.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, poor decisions by the bank's emerging-markets
operation resulted in a $52 million third-quarter loss.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, the head of BankBoston's private banking
operation in New York was charged with embezzling $66 million in
fraudulent loans to an Argentine businessman, exposing the bank's
loose financial controls. Officials insist those controls have
since been reviewed and tightened.
</P>
<P>
   Once the merger is complete, officials said, Latin American
operations will make up about 9 percent of annual revenue.
Officials said the larger bank will be better insulated from sudden
and explosive swings in international markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a bigger balance sheet, we can better exploit the
strengths and better withstand the perceived volatility,'' Gifford
said. ``With the new company, there's a lot more we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, competitors and bank employees alike preferred to
withhold judgment about the merger until they had more evidence _
one way or the other _ that Fleet Boston will continue to view
Latin America as an important market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is uncertainty here, but I wouldn't call it panic,''
said one BankBoston employee in Argentina. ``Things are changing,
but none of us are sure yet where we fit in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
