<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHANCELLOR-LIN-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCELLOR MEDIA CANCELS DEAL FOR LIN TV; CHANCELLOR CHIEF OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, R.I.)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chancellor Media Corp., the big radio and outdoor-advertising
company in Dallas, called off its $900 million deal to buy Lin
Television Corp. on Monday and said that its chief executive had
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor, which has been under pressure from shareholders
unhappy with its lagging stock price and its plans to expand into
television, said it would remain independent after a review that
included merger talks with Clear Channel Communications Inc.,
according to people involved in the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Chancellor, Jeffrey Marcus, resigned and
was replaced by Thomas Hicks, the chairman of the Dallas buyout
firm Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst, which owns 12 percent of
Chancellor. Hicks was already chairman of Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus, a longtime acquaintance of Hicks, took over the top spot
at Chancellor after its former chief executive, Scott Ginsburg, and
Hicks had a falling-out over the company's future. Marcus will join
the board of Lin, which is three-quarters owned by Hicks, Muse, and
will remain a Chancellor director.
</P>
<P>
   He said the reshuffling was not acrimonious, adding that now
that Chancellor would no longer be making a lot of big
acquisitions, ``We no longer had a need for someone who does what I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, Muse will spend $500 million over the next two weeks to
buy Chancellor shares on the open market, giving it a 29 percent
stake in the company once Chancellor completes its pending
acquisition of Capstar Broadcasting Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, Muse, which built Chancellor through acquisitions, also
said Monday that it would stop charging Chancellor oversight and
advisory fees, a practice that had been criticized by some
Chancellor shareholders. The change was made, Hicks said, ``to
eliminate any perceived impediment the fees might otherwise
represent to the maximization of value for all Chancellor
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many shareholders hoped Chancellor would receive an
acquisition offer over the weekend, Hicks, speaking during a
conference call with investors, said: ``We never received an offer
for any of our assets. We had lots of constructive conversations
with people. We concluded that the right thing to do for this
company is to stay independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Chancellor, which initially fell 11 percent Monday
morning, recovered strongly and rose $1.1875, to $45.5625, on heavy
volume. Some analysts said that after arbitragers and other
investors hoping for a quick sale to Clear Channel, a media company
based in San Antonio, sold the stock, investors bid shares up on
hopes that a deal with Clear Channel might still occur, and that
Chancellor shares would eventually be awarded the same high
multiple as other big radio companies.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor said in January that it had hired an investment bank
to examine potential mergers and other transactions. Since then,
the company has had talks with Clear Channel about a possible
merger, but did not have discussions of that scope with other
companies, according to a person involved in the discussions. Clear
Channel officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chancellor did, however, discuss other transactions, like
strategic partnerships and equity investments, with several
companies, said the person involved in the discussions. The
companies, that person said, included Outdoor Systems Inc., the Fox
Entertainment Group of News Corp., the NBC unit of General Electric
Co., Walt Disney Corp., Liberty Media Group and America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of a deal with Clear Channel, Chancellor was hoping to
find a company that would invest $1.5 billion to $2 billion _ cash
that could be used to pay down some of Chancellor's debt _ in
exchange for a stake in the company. But Chancellor was unable to
attract much interest from potential partners or investors, the
person said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for Outdoor Systems, Fox, America Online, Disney
and Liberty declined to comment. Representatives of NBC were
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   During the conference call, Chancellor officials that they
expected to save at least $15 million a year in overhead expenses,
in part by getting rid of the company's Gulfstream jet and by
largely disbanding its internal mergers and acquisitions staff. The
executives also said they hoped to have the company's debt upgraded
to investment grade within a year.
</P>
<P>
   And the company will, within a few weeks, outline an Internet
strategy that Hicks said ``will integrate local Web portals
maintained for each of Chancellor's radio stations with various
e-commerce and marketing opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of the acquisition of Lin Television, which is
based in Providence, R.I., came as several analysts and large
Chancellor investors said it appeared increasingly likely that
Chancellor shareholders would reject the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Asset Management, which owns more than 4 million
Chancellor shares, had already voted against the deal. ``The No. 1
concern was: I bought Chancellor for radio, and radio is a better
business than television; why do I want to vote for something that
dilutes my interest in radio?'' said Thomas Maguire, manager of the
Safeco Growth fund.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and large shareholders said that a sale to Clear
Channel remained a possibility, noting that Chancellor executives
disclosed that some companies they had talked to had ``indicated
they may want to propose a strategic transaction in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts said that Chancellor remained a good value in
its own right, given how its stock is priced in comparison with
others in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   William Meyers, an analyst at BancBoston Robertson Stephens,
said that Chancellor traded at about 15 times estimated 1999
earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization,
while Clear Channel and Infinity Broadcasting Corp., another big
radio company, both traded at about 20 to 22 times 1999 earnings,
Meyers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
