<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLAMEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS ALREADY START ON NEXT SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One season is over, another just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   It's the season of skill development and lonely hours in the
gym, practicing jumpers, honing footwork and improving
ballhandling. UCLA's diligence this spring and summer will help
determine its performance next March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players are made over the summer,'' Bruins forward Sean
Farnham said. ``We all have to get better individually. Everybody
needs to work on their jump shots, their strength and certain
aspects of their game.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches will provide each player with a daily workout
designed to improve weaknesses. Ray Young will concentrate on
dribbling with his left hand, for instance, and Ryan Bailey will
work on his defensive footwork. Jerome Moiso must get stronger and
tougher. Earl Watson must improve his ballhandling and decisions in
the open court.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also will participate in pickup games with NBA
players at the Men's Gym. The games are an invaluable experience if
they avoid the bad habits that typically form in ragged settings _
habits that are not broken when the season arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Watson threw wild passes last summer, wild passes in December
and wild passes last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the pickup games) are just a huge positive,'' coach
Steve Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ How good in 2000?: If sophomore guard Baron Davis returns,
the Bruins will be favored to win the Pac-10 and be a popular pick
for the Final Four. Even if he doesn't, they'll have eight of their
top nine scorers back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be a different team,'' Lavin said. ``We won't be the
prohibitive favorite. People will look at us like a top-15 team.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Performance review: Asked to assess the season and the
coaching staff's performance, Lavin said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it was a successful season with a disappointing
finish. It would have been nice to have beaten Detroit and gotten a
game against Ohio State, where the tempo would have been more
favorable. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``What we wanted to put in place this year was that the players
understand the importance of working hard. If they did one thing
well, it was that they competed very hard. There were times we
didn't play smart, times we didn't hit free throws or 3-pointers,
but we played extremely hard. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better than I did at this time last year. Even though
we had gone to the Sweet 16, I didn't feel as successful as I do
now. You're supposed to be depressed after you lose in the first
round. But because there are so many things I like about this team
and so many reasons to be excited about the future, that's why this
feels different than (after first-round losses to) Princeton, Penn
State or Tulsa.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More roulette?: As for his chaotic rotation _ caused in part
by injuries and disciplinary issues _ Lavin said he plans to use as
many players as possible next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be similar to Duke, something like Kentucky with
(two units of five players),'' he said. ``They've shown when you
have 10 guys who can really play, you can wear opponents down. If
we have 10 capable of playing, we'll use 10. If we have six, like
last year, we'll go with six.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruiting update: UCLA lost one of its top recruits last
week when Alameda power forward Justin Davis committed to Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are actively pursuing JaRon Rush's brother, Kareem, a
shooting guard from Kansas City, and Carlos Boozer, a forward from
Juneau, Alaska, considered the best senior prospect in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Rush has narrowed his choices to UCLA and Missouri. Boozer is
considering UCLA, Duke and St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Davis departs, the Bruins will have 12 players
returning and four scholarships available.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't sign anybody, it would still be OK,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gadzuric update: Freshman center Dan Gadzuric is recovering
steadily from February knee surgery and hopes to return to the
court by early summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start rehab in a couple weeks,'' he said. ``I think I'll be
ready by June or July.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
