</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAFEE-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAFEE BECOMES 2ND GOP SENATOR TO RULE OUT RE-ELECTION BID
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla., R.I., N.Y., Nev., N.J.) (fb)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island, the courtly
Republican who is one of his party's dwindling band of Senate
moderates, announced on Monday that he would not seek a fifth term.
His decision put another Senate seat up for grabs in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this 44 years and that's a pretty good run,''
said Chafee, 76, a Marine veteran of Guadalcanal who began his
career in public office in the Rhode Island House of
Representatives in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it clear that I'm not going away mad or
disillusioned or upset with the Senate,'' he said in a telephone
interview. ``I think it's a great place.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold a 55-45 seat edge in the Senate. But they will
be defending 19 seats next year compared with only 14 for the
Democrats. Chafee is the second Republican to announce retirement
plans in recent weeks, but his party is expected to have a much
harder time holding his seat than that of the other Republican,
Sen. Connie Mack of Florida, who set off a political free-for-all
with his announcement earlier this month that he would step down in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rhode Island has a Republican governor, the state is
overwhelmingly Democratic, with just 8 percent of its voters
registered as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a competitive state politically,'' said Sen.
Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who is chairman of the Democratic
Senatorial Campaign Committee. ``I think people are starting to
recognize what many of us in the Democratic caucus have understood
for some time. There's a real chance that there will be a
Democratic majority in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Senate Democrats _ Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York,
Frank Lautenberg of New Jersey and Richard Bryan of Nevada _ have
also announced that they will not seek re-election in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The scion of a prominent Rhode Island family, Chafee has been a
steadfast moderate in a party whose ranks in the Senate have become
increasingly conservative. He has played a major role in drafting a
generation of environmental laws as the ranking Republican on the
Environment and Public Works Committee and then as the committee's
chairman. He has also put his stamp on health care policy. On
Monday he mentioned a raft of environmental measures and ``the
extension of Medicaid for low income children'' as his proudest
achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Chafee won a Senate leadership post as Republican conference
chairman in 1984 but lost it six years later, in part because of
his breaks with party orthodoxy. He favors abortion rights, and he
was one of the Republicans who voted last month against convicting
President Clinton on impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me,'' he said Monday, ``it was perfectly justifiable, the
vote I took. I didn't have second thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was among many political figures who called Chafee on
Monday to wish him well.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said he did have some regrets about leaving behind
the small group of moderate Republicans like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of hate to leave them high and dry,'' he said. ``I
just think these things will go in cycles. Others will come
along.''
</P>
<P>
   Chafee's son, Lincoln, the mayor of Warwick, is considered a
possible Republican contender for his father's seat. The list of
possible Democratic candidates includes James Langevin, the Rhode
Island secretary of state; Rep. Bob Weygand; Myrth York, who has
lost two governor's races to Lincoln C. Almond, and Richard Licht,
a former lieutenant governor who lost to Chafee in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patrick J. Kennedy, who recently became the chairman of the
House Democrats' re-election effort, will not seek the seat, said a
spokesman, Larry Berman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
