<SLUG> BC-MARINE-NAVIGATOR-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINES DROP HOMICIDE CHARGE AGAINST NAVIGATOR IN FATAL GONDOLA
ACCIDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Marine Corps dropped manslaughter and homicide
charges Monday against the navigator of the EA-6b Prowler that hit
a gondola cable in the Italian Alps last year, saying it would be
``unreasonable'' to proceed after the pilot was acquitted of the
same charges. But the Corps said both officers will be
court-martialed on charges of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, testified at his
court-martial that he lent his home video camera to his navigator,
Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, who used it to tape an early portion of
the flight, before the accident that killed 20 people in the
gondola car at Mount Cermis.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby testified that after he piloted the damaged plane back to
an air base in Aviano, he removed the tape from the camera and
replaced it with a blank tape and left the camera in the cockpit.
He later gave the tape to Schweitzer, Ashby testified.
</P>
<P>
   Schweitzer has not said what he did with the tape. His civilian
lawyer, David Beck, would not discuss that Monday afternoon, but
said, ``If there's no underlying crime, what are you obstructing?''
</P>
<P>
   The case against Schweitzer, 30, of Westbury, N.Y., will be
heard by a different judge and a new jury, which is supposed to be
selected beginning on Thursday. Beck said he would ask for a delay
to prepare his case.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissal of the more serious charges against Schweitzer was
widely expected after Ashby was acquitted on March 4. But lawyers
for both men had hoped for an adjudication of the obstruction
charges in a less formal setting, possibly involving a fine or loss
of rank.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction charge, which carries a sentence of up to one
year, is the last remaining count that could result in punishment
for any Marine officer involved in the accident. The squadron
commander has been relieved of command and the squadron director of
safety standardization has had a letter of reprimand inserted in
his record.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction charge was filed after one crew member in the
rear cockpit of the plane, who was granted immunity, told
prosecutors about the tape.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ashby said at his trial that Schweitzer had tried to use the
camera only at the beginning of the flight, before it began its
low-level training route, and that he was not sure that it had
taped anything at all, because Schweitzer was unfamiliar with the
camera and complained that he could not find the catch to push the
trigger and start recording.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby testified that while they were still in Italy, they looked
for another 8-millimeter camera after his was impounded by Italian
authorities, but could not find one and thus could not see what was
on their tape.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had put the tape in the pocket of his flight suit
as other crew members, fearful of an explosion, scrambled from the
crippled jet, Ashby testified, ``I can't say exactly why we did it.
We were wrong, and I admit we were wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's announcement, the Corps said that Lt. Gen. Peter
Pace, commanding general of Marine Corps Forces, Atlantic, had
``determined that the seriousness of the charges and the
availability of the evidence warrant that Captain Schweitzer face
charges of obstruction of justice and conspiracy to obstruct
justice at a general court-martial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
