A1555 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERRANK-ATLANTA-COX     03-15 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERRANK-ATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New report at AEA show sheds light on technical jobs in Georgia
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia's growth in technology industries has pushed
it into the top 10 states in high-tech employment, new reports by
the American Electronics Association show.
</P>
<P>
   But the state still lags in the number of students it produces
with high-tech degrees. It ranks 19th in that category, according
to the association, the nation's largest trade group representing
electronics and information technology industries.
</P>
<P>
   The rankings confirm Georgia has reached a new plateau in its
quest to create high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Georgia of 1990. You've come a long way,''
said AEA president William Archey, who disclosed the rankings
Monday in a speech before the Georgia Economic Developers
Association. ``This is a state with a lot of strength in high
tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Archey pulled the information from reports the electronics
association plans to release over the next two months. California
ranks first in high-tech employment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech jobs in Georgia grew 54 percent from 1990 through
1997, to 132,524. That's 46,405 new high-tech jobs in the state
since 1990, when the state ranked 16th, Archey said. The numbers
are based on U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics data.
</P>
<P>
   Another report shows Atlanta in the nation's top 10 metro areas
in the number of high-tech jobs, Archey said. He didn't have other
details about that top 10 listing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dramatic growth in Georgia's high-tech industry, there's
a wide gap between first and tenth. No. 1 California has about six
times as many high-tech jobs as Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Industry recruiters consider high-tech jobs a plum. In 1997, the
average wage for a high-tech job nationally was $53,145, or 77
percent higher than the average for the rest of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia relies heavily on high-tech workers from other states to
fill jobs here. It is one of only two states in the top 10 of
high-tech employment that was not in the top 10 for producing
high-tech graduates.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia is addressing the discrepancy. While the nation
produced 5 percent fewer high-tech degrees in 1996 than it did in
1990, Georgia did the opposite. It awarded about 6 percent more,
according to Archey.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech research grants have doubled to nearly $1 billion at
major universities in Georgia in the past decade, according to the
Georgia Research Alliance. Venture capital invested in young
companies in the state has tripled.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia seems determined to increase its investment in high-tech
education. Legislation backed by Gov. Roy Barnes would add faculty
at state universities with the aim of delivering more graduates
specializing in design of microchips for the telecommunications
industry, a niche believed to be particularly fast growing and high
paying.
</P>
<P>
   The job rankings will find their way into presentations Georgia
makes to high-tech companies, industry recruiters say. Archey said
some companies look at the rankings when considering where they may
grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry that tends to want to be with itself,''
Archey said. ``It feeds on itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Todd, president of the Georgia Research Alliance, said the
rankings give state and business leaders something tangible to aim
for. ``It's a good scorecard,'' he said. ``We do well in a
competitive environment. . . . Moving from middle of the pack to
top 10 and eventually to the top five.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kempner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
