<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SCANDAL-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICAN EXPELLED FROM IOC LOBBIES FOR HIS REINSTATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ The clubbiness of the International
Olympic Committee was evident Monday when the delegate accused of
receiving the most illicit favors from Salt Lake City Olympic
organizers checked into the same hotel as the members who will vote
on his expulsion and sauntered through the lobby, shaking their
hands and kissing them on the cheek.
</P>
<P>
   But the delegate, Jean-Claude Ganga of Congo Republic, was not
in such an accommodating mood toward the IOC's internal
investigation, which ousted him for receiving more than $250,000 in
travel, medical benefits and extravagant gifts. Ganga denied any
wrongdoing and said that if he broke any rules, the rules should be
changed.
</P>
<P>
   He contended that his ouster was politically motivated by
investigators who, like Ganga, would like to succeed Juan Antonio
Samaranch as president of the IOC. Ganga said he was also facing
retribution because he organized the African boycott of the 1976
Summer Olympics after a New Zealand rugby team toured South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga also questioned the integrity of the leader of the IOC's
investigation, accused the committee of a double standard in
ousting only Third World delegates and of trying to ``exclude
Africa from the center of decision-making in world sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch's future may rest on Ganga's future. If Ganga's
expulsion in January is not ratified by two-thirds of the entire
IOC assembly on Wednesday, many believe that Samaranch will have
essentially received a vote of no confidence and that he will have
no choice but to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Another IOC member who could face the same fate as Ganga is Kim
Un Yong of South Korea, the highest-ranking delegate to be
implicated in the Salt Lake City scandal. Kim has been accused of
arranging jobs for his daughter and son through the Salt Lake City
bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   When he was given a warning instead of expulsion last week, the
IOC was accused of having a double standard in disciplining
members. The investigation of Kim continues, however, and he may
face a vote of expulsion on Wednesday, IOC officials said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga defended Kim, saying that his only mistake was in aspiring
to succeed Samaranch and that Kim's scrutiny was also politically
motivated. ``They are looking for lice even though his head is
clean shaven,'' Ganga said.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC received further embarrassment Monday when an
independent audit sought by Sydney, Australia, on its bid for the
2000 Summer Games alleged that 16 delegates had received improper
gifts, benefits or trips, including 11 who were not previously
mentioned in investigations of Salt Lake City's successful bid on
the 2002 Winter Games. The audit came six weeks after the IOC
cleared the Sydney bid without sending anyone to Australia to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five delegates _ nearly one-third of the IOC assembly _
have been linked by investigators to improprieties in Salt Lake
City and Sydney. Tom Sheridan, who conducted the independent audit
of Sydney's bid, said the IOC guidelines governing the bidding
process were ambiguous, unworkable and ``had fallen into
disrepute.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Phil Coles, an IOC member from Australia, was the only delegate
accused of both offering and receiving improper favors. He has been
accused by a Salt Lake City ethics panel of repeatedly violating
travel guidelines. The independent Sydney audit accused him of
improperly paying the travel expenses of a Danish delegate and his
wife to the 1993 French Open.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has struggled to explain why Coles merited a warning
instead of expulsion, and Richard W. Pound, who heads the
committee's investigations, was criticized for excessive chumminess
when he had dinner with Coles while investigating his behavior.
There is growing pressure in Australia on Coles to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one more than Ganga epitomizes the ethical blurriness
that exists in the IOC Ganga denied accusations that he and his
family had run up huge bid committee credit card bills and said he
had offered to pay for medical care for hepatitis, even producing a
letter from a Utah doctor that seemed to support his claim.
</P>
<P>
   But Ganga did admit that his wife, Eugenie, had received free
cosmetic surgery and that his mother-in-law had received a free
knee replacement, flying from Paris to Salt Lake City on a ticket
provided by the bid committee. Asked if that was proper, Ganga
said: ``The laws are made by man. It is not the laws that make the
man. If you make the laws and cannot adapt them to different
situations, the laws are bad and must be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga questioned whether Pound should lead the Salt Lake City
investigation, given that he received a genealogy study from the
Mormon Church, which is based in Utah; such a study might cost
$40,000 for an average person. Pound defended himself, saying the
study was presented two years after Salt Lake City won the Games.
Ganga's expulsion was based on facts, not politics, Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a case with bad facts, you attack the law,'' Pound
said of Ganga. ``If you have a case with bad law, you attack the
facts. If you have a case with bad facts and bad law, you attack
the prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganga was known by staffers in Utah for continually asking for
favors.
</P>
<P>
   Support for him among African delegates has been lukewarm. ``I
don't support people who are guilty,'' said Sam Ramsamy of South
Africa. Even Ganga's longtime friends, like LeRoy T. Walker, former
president of the U.S. Olympic Committee, have distanced themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed the handshake from palms together to palms up _
what's in it for me,'' Walker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
