<HEADER>
A1565 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     03-15 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW APPROACHES 10,000 AS STOCKS SET RECORDS
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices rose sharply, swept higher by a couple of big
merger announcements, enthusiastic buying of technology shares and
an optimistic earnings forecast from UAL, the company that operates
United Airlines. The advance pushed two major market measures _ the
Dow Jones industrial average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index _ to records. The Dow closed at 9,958.77, up 82.42 points,
and the S.&AMP;P. closed up 12.67 at 1,307.26. The Nasdaq composite
index failed to set a new high but was the session's
best-performing index.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds rose for a second day, as investors bet that economic
reports this week will point to subdued inflation and slowing
growth.
</P>
<P>
   UAL FORECASTS STRONG EARNINGS
</P>
<P>
   UAL, the parent of United Airlines, said that strong domestic
sales and the spillover from last month's sickout by pilots at
rival American Airlines would help lift its earnings above Wall
Street estimates. The announcement, which came on the heels of the
industry's second broad fare increase this year, sent airline
stocks soaring. UAL rose $6.6875, or nearly 10 percent, to $73.75.
</P>
<P>
   $3.5 MILLION BONUS AT PHILIP MORRIS
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Bible, chairman and chief executive of Philip Morris,
received a $3.5 million bonus from his company's compensation
committee for his participation in talks that led to the $206
billion settlement between cigarette makers and 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   BANK SPLITS OVER RUSSIAN DEBT
</P>
<P>
   A group of 19 Western banks holding $15 billion in defaulted
short-term Russian Government debt faces new problems after the
largest creditor, Credit Suisse First Boston, broke the group's
already fractured ranks to announce a new ruble-based investment
fund aimed at recovering the bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTORS BET ON NISSAN DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Shares of ailing Nissan Motor rose 13 percent in heavy trading
as investors increased their bets that Renault would seek to
preserve its future in the rapidly consolidating global auto
industry by taking a stake in Japan's second-largest automaker.
</P>
<P>
   DuPONT TO ACQUIRE SEED COMPANY
</P>
<P>
   DuPont, seeking to create an agricultural powerhouse to match
its giant chemical business, agreed to pay more than $7.7 billion
in cash and stock to buy the remaining 80 percent of Pioneer
Hi-Bred International, the world's largest producer of seed corn.
The deal is part of DuPont's effort to push into the life sciences
arena, where it will compete in the race to create and develop
genetically engineered seeds and crops, according to Charles O.
Holliday Jr., the chief executive of DuPont.
</P>
<P>
   EL PASO ENERGY IN DEAL FOR SONAT
</P>
<P>
   In an expected deal, El Paso Energy agreed to buy rival Sonat
for $3.9 billion in stock and $1.9 billion in assumed debt,
creating the largest interstate natural gas pipeline company in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   NBC NAMES ENTERTAINMENT CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   NBC named Garth Ancier, the former president for entertainment
at the WB network, as its president for entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab Predicts 30% Gain in ProfitCharles Schwab, the discount
and on-line brokerage firm, said that its first-quarter earnings
would exceed analyst estimates by as much as 30 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
