A1566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UGA-NEEDS-COX     03-15 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-NEEDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulldogs seeking backup at quarterback for Carter
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ As Georgia begins spring practice today, perhaps
no position on the Bulldogs' roster is more solid than quarterback,
where Quincy Carter returns after becoming conference and national
freshman of the year last season.
</P>
<P>
   Because of offseason developments, however, the position
suddenly has become one of great focus this spring. Georgia has had
three quarterbacks transfer after Carter's tremendous success _
redshirt freshmen Nate Hybl and Daniel Cobb, and junior Mike Usry.
As a result, developing depth is of paramount importance.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs know that fifth-year senior Jon England will be
available, giving them an experienced backup who knows the system
and can fill in if Carter is injured. But Jan. 5 shoulder surgery
will cause England to miss spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves freshman Regan Torbert as the only quarterback in
camp. The Bulldogs may also try freshman Terrence Edwards and
sophomore flanker Labrone Mitchell as backup candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Here are four other questions the Bulldogs hope to answer during
spring drills:
</P>
<P>
   1. Is there a tailback in the house?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Donnan never found a star tailback last year,
depending instead on the solid, no-nonsense work of now-graduated
senior Olandis Gary.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that they have plenty of candidates in camp in
Robert Arnaud, Patrick Pass and Jasper Sanks, none of whom
distinguished themselves last season despite ample opportunities.
Georgia will look for one to emerge this spring, before the arrival
of the freshmen in August.
</P>
<P>
   2. Who will replace offensive tackles?
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs were hurt by the loss of Matt Stinchomb and Chris
Terry, both of whom are expected to be high NFL draft choices in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the other five offensive line starters return, along
with part-time starter Reggie Stargill. The Bulldogs need senior
Kelvin Williams or one of five redshirt freshmen to emerge at
tackle, but some reshuffling could be in order.
</P>
<P>
   3. What about the logjam at linebacker?
</P>
<P>
   In his boldest position change of the offseason, Donnan moved
Adrian Hollingshed and Dustin Luckie, last year's starters at
middle linebacker, to defensive end.
</P>
<P>
   The move says that the Bulldogs are desperate to improve their
pass rush and that they have a lot of confidence in the abilities
of Champ's brother, sophomore Boss Bailey, and Will Witherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the team expects contributions from junior college
transfer Kendra Bell, and redshirt freshmen Tony Gilbert and Kawika
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   4. Can anyone fill Champ Bailey's cleats?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not, but the Bulldogs think they can recover from his
loss, at least on defense.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, Georgia lost its top four receivers in wideouts
Bailey and Tony Small, and tight ends Larry Brown and Jermaine
Wiggins. Juniors Michael Green and Thad Parker will move up, and
Edwards will get a good look. But the real answers will come his
summer, in freshmen Reggie Brown and Durrell Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
