A1572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENOME-MAP-NYT &LR;      03-15 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE OF THE TEAMS IN GENOME-MAP RACE SETS EARLIER DEADLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (sw) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The date for completing the first draft of the human genome, the
three billion units of DNA held in every human cell, has been moved
up to the spring of 2000, the publicly financed consortium
sponsoring the work announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If met, the new date set by the consortium _ the National
Institutes of Health, the Energy Department and the Wellcome Trust
of London _ could allow the public venture to claim some measure of
victory over its commercial rival, Celera Corp. of Rockville, Md.
Celera, headed by Dr. J. Craig Venter, has said it will produce a
substantially complete, accurate human genome sequence by the end
of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Venter said in response to Monday's development that he had not
changed his goals and that the public consortium's announcement had
``nothing to do with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is projected cost, projected timetables,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until the formation of Celera last May by Perkin-Elmer Corp., an
instrument-making company based in Norwalk, Conn., the public
consortium had aimed to finish the complete genome by 2005. Then,
in the fall, the consortium said it could crank out a first draft
of the genome by December 2001. The new target cuts even that
ambitious goal by some 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The genome sequence is expected to become the nucleus of
medicine, because it represents the programming for the human
organism. Most diseases are caused to varying extents by bugs in
this programming, which are the mutations that affect each
individual's genetic endowment.
</P>
<P>
   Participants on both the public and private teams believe that
the intense competition between them has forced faster progress
than if either team were working by itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we lose that pressure, we wouldn't be seeing such good
reciprocity between the public and private efforts,'' said Dr.
Richard Gibbs, head of the sequencing center at the Baylor College
of Medicine in Houston, who works with the consortium's team.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the pressure that Celera's mere existence has
created for the genome efforts of the National Institutes of
Health, Dr. Norton Zinder, biologist at Rockefeller University and
a member of Celera's board, said, ``The Venter-Hunkapiller
initiative will cause the DNA of the human genome to be made
available from the NIH, without Celera's having to do a line of
sequence.'' Dr. Michael W. Hunkapiller is the Perkin-Elmer
executive responsible for design of the company's widely used DNA
sequencing machines.
</P>
<P>
   The draft that the consortium says it can complete by the spring
of next year is intended to reflect all human genes, estimated to
number about 100,000, and most of the long intervening stretches of
DNA that lie between them. Much of the genome is in the form of
repetitive sequences that are hard to decipher and have no known
functional significance because they are not part of the genes.
Such regions that are not completed now will be done later.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 60 percent of the genome will be sequenced by the
national institutes' university-based centers, 10 percent by the
Energy Department's laboratories, and 33 percent by the Sanger
Center near Cambridge, England.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's share of the human genome project was
intended to cost $3 billion over 15 years. But Dr. Francis Collins,
director of the institutes' part of the project, said the actual
amount spent on production-scale sequencing would be much less. He
expects the international consortium's cost of preparing the draft
sequence to be $280 million or less, comparable with Celera's
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the national institutes have financed eight
university-based centers to generate human DNA data. But Collins
announced on Monday that new money would be focused on the three
most productive centers, those headed by Dr. Robert Waterston at
the Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis, Dr. Eric
Lander at the Whitehead Institute in Cambridge, Mass., and Gibbs at
the Baylor College of Medicine in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The new focus may give the institutes' decentralized system a
helpful edge in competing with the monolithic but nimble Celera.
Lander said economies of scale were readily apparent in centers
that had 100 of the latest-model DNA sequencing machines, a
capacity that is to be reached soon by the Sanger Center,
Washington University's and his own.
</P>
<P>
   An early test of strength may come with Celera's pilot project,
that of sequencing the entire genome of the Drosophila fruit fly, a
standard laboratory organism. Venter, Celera's chief, said he hoped
to complete the sequence in three to six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
