A1576 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-AR     03-15 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINKINS, RANGEL ARRESTED IN PROTEST OVER POLICE SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
 (With NY-POLICE-POLL) 
(ART ADV: Photo of Dinkins and Rangel is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Former Mayor David Dinkins, Rep. Charles Rangel and a
dozen others were arrested Monday as they staged a protest at
Police Headquarters in lower Manhattan over the police killing last
month of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed immigrant from Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations, along with acts of civil disobedience
intended to provoke arrests, have become weekday ritual at One
Police Plaza since last Tuesday, when the Rev. Al Sharpton led the
first group of 12 protesters in a sit-in that ended with their
arrests. Sharpton, who was also arrested Monday, has vowed to
continue the protests each day until the four officers involved in
the Diallo shooting are arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gregory W. Meeks, a Democrat from Queens, and two City
Council members, Margarita Lopez and Bill Perkins, both of
Manhattan, were also among those arrested Monday and charged with
criminal trespassing after they entered Police Headquarters and
refused a request to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the police appeared reluctant to arrest Dinkins and
the others. The protesters at first knelt in front of the entrance
to Police Headquarters, an act that had led to the arrest of
earlier protesters on charges of disorderly conduct. But officers
declined to intervene, prompting Monday's protesters to go a step
further and enter the building.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood in the lobby waiting to be arrested, Dinkins
criticized the Giuliani administration, saying it tolerated acts of
police misconduct as the price for lowering the crime rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this administration is dangerously close to
having adopted a philosophy that the ends justify the means,'' he
said. ``I think that if the street unit were to shake down 10
people and find one dirty, they would think that the other nine
whose civil and human rights were violated, that that was OK, that
that justified it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinkins was referring to the street crimes unit whose officers
were hunting for a rapist on Feb. 4 when they shot and killed
Diallo, an unarmed street peddler with no criminal record, in the
lobby of his Bronx apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   After Dinkins stood in a circle with the other protesters and
joined arms, a police officer, Lt. Kevin Mullen, addressed the
crowd through a megaphone, telling the people that they faced
arrest if they did not leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You now have an opportunity to leave,'' he said, waiting a
minute. When nothing happened, he said, ``Now that you have refused
to leave, I'm ordering that you be placed under arrest.''
</P>
<P>
   The protesters were charged with trespassing, a misdemeanor that
can carry a more severe penalty than disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   One by one they were asked to put their hands behind their
backs, and they were put in plastic handcuffs known as flex-cuffs.
A brief discussion followed among police officials, who considered
taking the protesters out a back door, away from the photographers
waiting outside the front door. The officials decided not to, and
Dinkins and the other handcuffed protesters were led out the front
door.
</P>
<P>
   Inspector Michael Collins, a police spokesman, said that police
procedure requires officers to handcuff the people they arrest with
their hands behind their backs, except in extraordinary
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani denounced the protests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
