<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOSTON-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK DEAL UNLIKELY TO SPUR OTHER MERGERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass., Calif.) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036.) 
 (fb) 
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again, two large banks have merged. Once again, speculation
is rampant about which banks will rush to the altar next.
</P>
<P>
   But Fleet Financial Group's proposed $16 billion acquisition of
the BankBoston Corp., while creating a powerhouse in New England,
would not likely spur a new round of megamergers similar to the
gargantuan deals of last year, bank advisers and analysts said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, even with a market capitalization of about $40 billion
and $180 billion in assets, the new bank _ to be named the Fleet
Boston Corp. _ would still lack the size needed to ensure that
Boston will remain home to a major bank in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   A historic round of mergers during the last few years has split
the banking industry into two camps, with a handful of big banks _
Citigroup, BankAmerica, Chase Manhattan, Bank One, First Union and
Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. _ in one and thousands of small community banks
in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Left out of both are scores of midsized banks that missed
joining the ranks of the titans but are too big to offer the
specialized handholding that community banks provide clients.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry executives say that the future of those
midsized banks _ including Keycorp, PNC Bank, USBancorp, National
City, Wachovia and SunTrust Banks _ will be as acquisition targets
or as participants in smaller mergers that merely delay their
eventual acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there's been major consolidation and the top 10 banks
will have the majority of the assets,'' said Terrence Murray,
Fleet's chief executive, in a telephone interview on Monday. ``And
the nature of services and demands on the upper tier of banks
continues to get more sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray is to be Fleet Boston's chief executive for the first two
years, to be succeeded by Charles K. Gifford, the chairman and
chief executive of BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even among the handful of giants atop the banking industry,
analysts say, there will be another eventual winnowing. Bank One,
First Union, Wells Fargo and Fleet all have at least one more deal
ahead of them involving the changing of names, location and
management, either as acquirers or acquirees.
</P>
<P>
   The banks that survive the last hurrah of banking mergers within
the upper echelon will be those that execute their current mergers
successfully _ no small feat given that successful mergers are as
much an art as a science.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo, once regarded as among the most skillfully managed
banks in the nation, botched its acquisition of First Interstate a
few years ago, setting up the bank for a takeover by the Norwest
Corp. last year. Wells kept its name but its senior management
largely stepped aside.
</P>
<P>
   First Union, until recently considered one of the industry's
most adept acquirers, is slashing as many as 7,000 jobs to meet
expense goals tied to overly rich takeovers, at the same time that
some of its business lines are slowing. The bank has recently
disclosed an inability to meet both first-quarter and
second-quarter earnings estimates; its stock now suffers from these
merger-related woes, trading well below its 52-week high of
$65.9375. It closed at $52 on Monday, down $1.125.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan, still one of the top banks in the country, has been
awash in merger speculation because it has yet to deliver on the
financial promises it made when it began transforming itself into
an investment bank in the late 1980s. Its stock has also been weak.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Chase has quietly pulled off two of the
biggest mergers in banking and its stock has soared, leaving it
well set for a shopping spree.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chase, which had serious merger discussions with the Credit
Suisse Group last year, is hungry for an equity operation and has
courted such brokerage firms as Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Bank advisers
say Chase may now try to achieve its goals by snapping up the Paine
Webber Group and Lehman Brothers Holdings in quick succession.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston plan to cut as many as 5,000 of about
60,000 jobs at the combined bank and a substantial number of those
cuts will involve layoffs. The banks said that cuts are required
for Fleet Boston to reach financial goals and overcome regulatory
hurdles. But a demoralized work force, or understaffed service
operations, could undermine the merger's potential success.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, investors showed a lack of enthusiasm for the
deal on Monday. In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Fleet's
shares sank $2.5625, or 5.7 percent, to $42.1875, while
BankBoston's shares rose only 12.5 cents, to $47.0625, less than
the $53 a share Fleet has offered to pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The architecture of these deals is pretty clear now,'' said
Don Kerr, a senior vice president with Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton, a
consulting firm. ``Who wins and who loses within the top tier will
ultimately be determined by which banks trip up or make mistakes
and then get punished by the stock market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
