<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: It's Probably Better to Pay the Taxes
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Last year, I earned some income in a private transaction
that was perfectly legal, but the government doesn't know about it
because nobody sent the Internal Revenue Service any information
about it. There also are deductible expenses involved, so I thought
I might ask my accountant to calculate the net tax burden. If I
then decide that it's more than I care to pay, and leave this item
off my tax return, is the accountant required to squeal on me if
questioned by the IRS? Or am I protected by the kind of
confidentiality that exists between lawyers and clients, or priests
and their flocks?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  I'm tempted to lecture you on morality, but I won't,
because I think you know everything I might say.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that you probably can't count on your
accountant to keep your secret. Your conversations with the
accountant qualify as privileged communications only if the IRS
socks you with a civil suit _ not in a criminal action. And if the
agency thinks you deliberately evaded taxes, it may very well bring
a criminal action.
</P>
<P>
   You may think you can play it safe by using a lawyer as an
intermediary in dealing with your accountant _ or by simply dealing
with a tax lawyer. But that won't work either, because there is no
lawyer/client protection in a criminal case when it comes to
working papers or conversations that go into preparing a tax
return. They must be disclosed if the IRS requests them.
</P>
<P>
   You also must bear in mind that whoever paid you the money
already knows about your hidden income.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't mention how much money is involved _ but is your
potential saving from tax evasion worth the burden on your
conscience? How much is peace of mind worth to you?
</P>
<P>
   Oops, I promised not to lecture.
</P>
<P>
   My bottom line advice is borrowed from a famous vaudeville
routine: ``Pay the $2.''
</P>
<P>
   Market, Limit Orders
</P>
<P>
   Q: What exactly do discount brokers do once you ask them to sell
your stock? Do they watch the prices go up and down until they
think they have the best possible price? Or do they just sell it
willy-nilly?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: It all depends on you. If you ask a discount broker _ or
any other broker _ to sell stock for you, you are expected to make
one of two basic choices.
</P>
<P>
   You can enter a ``market order,'' in which case your broker will
sell the stock immediately at the best available price.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you can enter a ``limit order,'' in which you specify the
lowest price you will accept for your shares. For example, if the
market currently prices the stock at $50 per share, you might tell
your broker to sell your shares for $52 per share or more. However,
in that case you might not sell the shares quickly.
</P>
<P>
   You also can place limit orders on the buy side, specifying the
highest price at which you will buy a stock.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MONEYBAG (72753 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Limit orders can be placed for one day only, or you can instruct
your broker that the order is ``good until canceled.'' If the trade
isn't transacted on the day you place the order, the order will
carry over from day to day until a trade is made on your terms, or
until you cancel it.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``good until canceled'' is slightly misleading, because
most brokers expect you to refresh your GTC orders, typically every
month or two. You should keep close tabs on this and renew your
broker-canceled GTC orders promptly if you still want to buy or
sell the stock at the price you specified.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing Lost Shares
</P>
<P>
   Q: I own 16 shares of a blue-chip stock, but I only can find a
certificate for eight shares. Evidently the company split the stock
two shares for one, but I misplaced one of the certificates. How do
I go about getting my other shares? Also, once I get my shares, I
want to sell them. Do I need a broker for that? I don't have one.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Telephone your company's headquarters and ask for the
investor relations department. Explain your plight and the people
in that department will explain how to replace your missing
certificate. You may have to pay a fee.
</P>
<P>
   While you have them on the line, ask whether the company buys
back stock from shareholders. Many do, and you might be able to
sell the shares that way, with little or no commission.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, you should get a broker to sell your stock.
</P>
<P>
   If you only plan to make this one transaction, you might as well
open an account with one of the deep-discount online brokers. A few
charge $10 or less per trade. However, some require you to deposit
substantial amounts of stock or cash before you can open the
account. They spell out their ground rules on their Internet Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to moneybag(at
sign)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
