r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXES-SFCHRON &LR;      03-15 1727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Federal, state surpluses yield tax breaks for investors,  students,
parents, renters 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Arthur M. Louis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
If you are one of the 80 million Americans who haven't yet filed an
income-tax return for 1998, you may find the normally
nerve-jangling task less costly than you expected.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Congress and the California Legislature passed
laws last year that offer many taxpayers substantial tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   In most years, the legislators take away at least as much as
they give in tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a rare exception, thanks to the federal and state
budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   If those surpluses are sustained in the future, we could soon
see another wave of benign tax legislation, predicts Ali Farhat, a
certified public accountant with Coopers &AMP; Lybrand in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The principal beneficiaries of the new federal tax rules include
parents of children younger than 17, people who realized capital
gains on sales of securities or other assets, people who paid
tuition to colleges and graduate schools, people who have student
loans outstanding and people with Individual Retirement Accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Many taxpayers will be surprised to learn that they now can
deduct interest paid on their student loans and can buy precious
metals for their IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   The state legislators helped large families last year by greatly
increasing the tax credit for dependents. They also aided renters
by restoring the renter's credit.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the major changes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CHILD TAX CREDIT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  For 1998, you are entitled to a $400 credit on your federal
return for each child under age 17 that you claim as a dependent.
The new credit reduces your income tax dollar for dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Someone with two dependents younger than 17 _ which might
include children, grandchildren, step-children and foster children
_ would get an $800 benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, the credit rises to $500 per child starting this
year.
</P>
<P>
   If you have one or two qualifying dependents, your child tax
credit cannot exceed your tax liability. If you have three or more,
you may be able to claim credits exceeding your tax liability,
entitling you to a refund. You can determine this by filling out a
complicated worksheet that comes with your tax forms.
</P>
<P>
   There are income caps on the child tax credit: $110,000 of
adjusted gross income for married couples filing jointly, $55,000
for married people filing separately, and $75,000 for single
people. For every $1,000 of income above that, you lose $50 in
credits.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of TAXES16 (13603 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  (The new credit does not affect the $2,700-per-person exemption
for each member of your household.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CAPITAL GAINS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  The holding period required to qualify for long-term
capital-gains tax rates was reduced, across the board, to 12
months. Previously, assets sold after July 29, 1997, had to be held
at least 18 months to qualify as long term.
</P>
<P>
   That's a significant improvement, because the maximum tax rate
on long-term capital gains for people in the 28 percent income
bracket and higher is only 20 percent. Their maximum rate on
short-term capital gains is 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For every $10,000 worth of capital gains, the difference between
long-term and short-term treatment amounts to $800 in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   For people in the 15 percent bracket _ those with adjusted gross
income no greater than $42,350 on joint returns and $25,350 on
single returns _ the maximum capital-gains tax is 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For short-term capital gains, those taxpayers must pay 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, sales of collectibles _ such as antiques, coins and
sports memorabilia _ do not qualify for the lowest tax rates no
matter how long you hold them, notes Bill Schulte, a certified
public accountant with Burr Pilger &AMP; Mayer in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Both long-term and short-term gains on such sales will continue
to be taxed at a maximum of either 28 percent or your regular tax
rate, whichever is less.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; EDUCATION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Many people pursuing post-secondary education can choose from two
new tax credits _ the Hope credit and the Lifetime Learning credit
_ that can be used to offset part of their tuition and fees.
</P>
<P>
   Because these are credits rather than deductions, they are
subtracted directly from your tax obligation. (Deductions are less
valuable because they are merely used to reduce the amount of your
taxable income.)
</P>
<P>
   With the Hope credit, taxpayers can reduce their tax bills by up
to $1,500 apiece for themselves and for each eligible dependent.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of TAXES16 (13603 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  To be eligible for this credit, students must be a college
freshman or sophomore working on a degree or other academic
credential and must be free of any felony convictions for
possessing or distributing controlled substances. (People convicted
of other types of felonies presumably can claim the credit.)
</P>
<P>
   The maximum credit is equal to 100 percent of the first $1,000
in tuition and fees, plus 50 percent of the next $1,000 _ for each
student.
</P>
<P>
   This benefit is not available to married taxpayers filing
separately.
</P>
<P>
   It is available in full to married taxpayers filing jointly
whose income does not exceed $80,000 and to single taxpayers whose
income does not exceed $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The amount you can deduct decreases in stages as your income
rises above those levels, with the deduction eliminated entirely
for joint filers with $100,000 in income and single filers who earn
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   All expenses paid or incurred in 1998 are eligible for the Hope
credit.
</P>
<P>
   The Lifetime Learning credit has the same income limits as the
Hope credit.
</P>
<P>
   It can be used for expenses up to $1,000 per year paid by all
students in your family after June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Hope credit, it is available to students in any year
of study at college or graduate school _ and there is no drug test.
</P>
<P>
   The Lifetime Learning credit is calculated by taking 20 percent
of the total amount of tuition the taxpayer shells out _ up to a
maximum expense of $5,000 for all family members.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the maximum credit for a family in any given year is
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   You can't use both the Hope and Lifetime Learning credits in the
same year for the same student. But you can use the Hope for one
student and the Lifetime for another.
</P>
<P>
   Students or their parents also can get tax relief by opening an
Education IRA _ another legal innovation that took effect last
year.
</P>
<P>
   You can make nondeductible contributions of $500 per year to an
Education IRA for a child under age 18, provided your income is no
greater than $150,000 filing jointly or $95,000 for singles.
</P>
<P>
   The permissible contribution is reduced as your income exceeds
those levels and phases out completely at $160,000 and $110,000
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of TAXES16 (13603 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The investment gains in an Education IRA accumulate tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   Money can be withdrawn from an Education IRA without tax or
penalty to pay for the child's tuition, fees, books, supplies and
equipment at a college or graduate school. However, the withdrawal
must not exceed the expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Warning: You cannot withdraw money from an Education IRA to pay
a student's expenses in the same year that the student uses either
the Hope or Lifetime Learning credit.
</P>
<P>
   Another warning: Any amount you contribute to an Education IRA
counts against your $2,000 maximum annual IRA contributions for
that year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you contribute the full $500 to an Education
IRA, you cannot contribute more than a total of $1,500 to other
IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   Congress also looked kindly upon students who already have
graduated. Many of them now are allowed to deduct from their 1998
income part of the interest they paid &UR;  &LR; last year on their student
loans.
</P>
<P>
   An especially appealing thing about this new rule is that you
can deduct your interest even if you don't itemize your other
deductions. You can add the student-loan deduction to your standard
deduction.
</P>
<P>
   The student-loan deduction can be used only for interest paid
during the first five years in which interest payments are
required.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum deduction for the 1998 tax year is $1,000, but it
moves up to $1,500 for this year and increases $500 more in each of
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   You can take the full deduction if your adjusted gross income is
no greater than $60,000 for married people filing jointly and
$40,000 for singles. The deduction phases out completely at $75,000
and $55,000 respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; RETIREMENT ACCOUNTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  Starting with the 1998 tax year, IRA holders were permitted to
take money out of their accounts penalty-free before age 591/2 to
pay for a first home or for higher-education expenses.
</P>
<P>
   However, all the money withdrawn from a deductible account, and
earnings withdrawn from a nondeductible account, will be taxed at
the taxpayer's regular rate.
</P>
<P>
   As of last year, IRAs are permitted to invest in gold, silver,
platinum and palladium bullion, and in platinum coins. All those
investments previously were off limits.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STATE TAXES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  On state returns, people who rent rather than own their homes
will save some money, thanks to the restoration of the renter's
credit.
</P>
<P>
   The credit _ subtracted directly from your tax obligation _
amounts to $120 for married couples filing jointly, and $60 for
singles, provided you lived in California during the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   If you lived in California for less than a full year, you can
claim a credit equal to one-12th the maximum amount for each month
of your residency.
</P>
<P>
   The credit cannot be used on joint returns if your adjusted
gross income is $50,000 or more or on single returns if your income
is $25,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayers with multiple dependents will save big money because
of a substantial boost in an existing state tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   If your adjusted gross income is less than $233,556 (for joint
returns) or $116,777 (for singles), you can reduce your tax
obligation by $253 per dependent on your 1998 return _ up from $68
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a taxpayer with three dependents who is below the
income thresholds would save an additional $555.
</P>
<P>
   However, for every $2,500 by which your income exceeds those
thresholds, your credit for each dependent will be reduced by $12
on joint returns and $6 on single returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
