<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1583 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-3D-SFCHRON &LR;      03-15 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-3D-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Video Card Firm Bets on Voodoo
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By David Einstein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
3dfx Interactive, whose Voodoo brand has become synonymous with
high-performance 3-D graphics cards, today is unleashing an all-out
effort to turn its technology into a de facto standard for
mainstream PCs.
</P>
<P>
   At the Game Developers Conference in San Jose, 3dfx will
announce a $20 million campaign aimed at bolstering its already
strong retail sales while persuading big PC-makers to put its
technology in their computers.
</P>
<P>
   3dfx's goal is to challenge Canada's ATI Technologies, the
leading seller of graphics cards _ circuit boards that go inside
PCs and provide enhanced video for games, the Internet and
graphics-intensive software.
</P>
<P>
   In girding for the battle, 3dfx of San Jose is changing its
logo, redesigning its Web site and launching a worldwide
advertising blitz using the tag line ``So powerful, it's kind of
ridiculous.'' The campaign will include three television ads
devised by Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners, the agency known for its
``Got Milk'' commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing push will be accompanied by the introduction of
three new video cards based on Voodoo3, the third generation of the
Voodoo chip technology.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the first time, 3dfx will make its own cards, using
manufacturing capabilities gained in its pending acquisition of STB
Systems, a maker of video cards. Until now, Voodoo cards were made
under license by other companies, among them Creative Labs and
Diamond Multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging in price from $130 to $250, the new cards will offer
both 2-D and 3-D graphics enhancements _ an improvement over
previous high-end Voodoo cards, which were 3-D only.
</P>
<P>
   The new cards could give 3dfx a boost in selling directly to
PC-makers, something it's had trouble doing with its 3-D-only
cards. 3dfx sells to just a few PC-makers, while ATI, whose cards
are both 2-D and 3-D, has contracts with nearly the entire top 20.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ATI controls some 35 percent of the total PC
graphics market, compared to just 6 percent for 3dfx.
</P>
<P>
   In the much smaller retail market _ selling directly to PC
owners _ 3dfx dominates. According to PC Data, 73 percent of
high-performance cards sold in the fourth quarter of last year were
powered by Voodoo chips. And last month, three of the five
top-selling cards were Voodoo-based.
</P>
<P>
   By increasing sales to PC-makers, 3dfx hopes to raise awareness
of its technology _ generally considered the best in the business _
to the point where game developers will routinely optimize new
games to work best on Voodoo.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of 3D16 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  That could help establish the technology as a standard. Moreover,
if one or two hot games were written exclusively for Voodoo, ``3dfx
could really have a stranglehold on the market,'' said analyst
Charles Boucher of Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers called 3dfx's moves bold but also risky, with
no guarantee of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``ATI is going to be tough to crack in the PC market,'' said
Mike Feibus of Mercury Research. ``Even if 3dfx gets some design
wins from PC-makers, it's going to pale by comparison to what ATI
is shipping.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is some concern that PC-makers already tired of
having to put ``Intel Inside'' on their systems may balk at the
prospect of promoting the Voodoo brand as well.
</P>
<P>
   Feibus also noted that Creative Labs and Diamond Multimedia plan
to bring out new video cards with non-Voodoo technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diamond and Creative aren't going to curl up and die,'' he
said. ``3dfx is going to have competition from two big guys who
used to be its allies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
