 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scope out the course beforehand, says Ilene Sokoloff, who used
to run a business-golf seminar and now writes about golf. If you
don't know soft spikes are required, you could end up having to buy
your client nd yourself new shoes _ and you'll look unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   If you bring a female client to play during men-only hours, or
vice versa, you'll embarrass everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Get to know course employees so you're treated like a regular in
front of your client, adds Rhame, who's the co-author along with
James A. McNulty of ``Pat Summerall's Business Golf: The Art of
Developing Relationships Through Golf'' (Birch Lane Press, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   On game day, says Rhame, arrive early. Have your golf bag put on
the driver's side, especially if you're a woman, says Sokoloff. It
creates equal footing. Greet the client as he drives in. Pay in
advance so the client understands he's your guest. Have a gift
waiting, ideally a golf shirt with your company logo.
</P>
<P>
   Don't scrimp on anything. If the client needs golf balls, don't
buy her three _ buy her a dozen. Pay for the cart, too. Exception:
If the client wants to walk, you walk.
</P>
<P>
   Make it a foursome. Invite two other people who will interest or
be of help to your client and who will help keep the conversation
moving, says Rhame. Or let the client bring someone, says Bill
Storer, who runs Business Golf Strategies in Basking Ridge, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Sal Pulitano, CEO of Computing Concepts, a computer integrating
company, played with a client who was a purchasing agent, and the
client brought his father, who was a purchasing agent for another
company. ``We picked up another account,'' says Pulitano, who pays
for his employees to attend Storer's seminars.
</P>
<P>
   Establish the format in advance. One of the most conducive for
business is best ball, with two-person teams. After you both tee
off, each of you plays from the spot where the better drive landed
and so forth for the rest of the hole. That makes you and your
client a team, calling each other partner and working off each
other's success, says Rhame. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 225 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1200) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember _ during the game, you're being watched as closely as
you are watching. Storer tells the recent story of a salesman who
made the mistake of drinking during a round and tipped the cart on
a sharp turn. His client fell out and was knocked unconscious.
After recovering, the client didn't stick around to do more
business. The salesman was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Woo, who runs Golf 101, encourages women to play off the
middle tees, where men usually start, instead of the forward tees,
which used to be called the ladies' tees but are now less
chauvinistically referred to as the beginners' tees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're out there trying to build a relationship, you don't
want to be coming in and out of the conversation,'' she says. If
the more difficult drive holds a woman's game back, she should tell
the other players she'll move her ball from where it lands to where
theirs land, to keep the game moving.
</P>
<P>
   If you're playing with someone who plays from the forward tees,
don't sit in the cart and wait for her to tee off, says Rhame.
``Give her the courtesy to get out of the cart, and go stand with
her like she stood with you.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, send a thank-you note, maybe even an article about an
interest that your client casually mentioned. Follow up with a
phone call to set up an appointment to do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``People take my calls more frequently after we've played a
round of golf,'' says Dave Lakhani, director of sales at Cougar
Mountain Software in Boise, Idaho. And that's what it's all about. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Reshma Memon Yaqub is a staff writer at WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SIDEBAR FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
