<HEADER>
A1589 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN-(SLA     03-15 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENCH COULD FIT RICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ One of the top 3-point shooters in NBA history is
playing in long relief off the Lakers' bench and that could be
where Glen Rice remains for a while.
</P>
<P>
   In two games since joining the Lakers, Rice has struggled to
regain his magic touch. He's hit 12 of 33 shots from the field
(36.4 percent) and just 1 of 8 attempts from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   It's not entirely unexpected considering Rice hadn't played in
10 months, following the NBA lockout and arthroscopic elbow
surgery. But even once he regains his shooting stroke, Rice won't
necessarily become the starting small forward. Coach Kurt Rambis
might keep starting Robert Horry and let Rice come off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about that (Sunday),'' Rambis said. ``It
depends on if he likes coming off the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept has merit. The Lakers' starting lineup already has
the scoring punch of Shaquille O'Neal (26.9 points per game) and
Kobe Bryant (19.5), but they have few reserves who can sustain a
scoring run when those two take a breather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like punches off the bench,'' Rambis said. ``Teams have a
tendency to put all their other guns out there on the floor. . . .
It's something I was thinking about, but I don't know what
direction I'm going.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, meanwhile, is confident his shots will start to fall soon,
as he regains his game legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting good shots, I'm just not getting the lift that I'm
capable of getting,'' he said. ``Those shots are gonna be there all
year, so I've just gotta keep stepping up and taking them. . . . I
know for sure everything's going to fall into place perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Unguarded: The absence off Derek Harper (sprained ankle) on
Sunday underlined the Lakers' suddenly shaky backcourt situation.
When they traded Eddie Jones for Rice, the Lakers were left with
only one proven shooting guard, starter Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   When Bryant needs a breather, the Lakers turn to small forwards
Rick Fox and rookie Ruben Patterson, or the 37-year-old Harper,
whose minutes are usually consumed by his duties as starting point
guard.
</P>
<P>
   With Harper out, matters were worse. Derek Fisher, who's
struggled this season, started at point guard. That left only
Bryant, already starting at off guard, available to back him up.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers last week waived veteran guard B.J. Armstrong, a
throw-in in the Rice trade, who could have provided some
flexibility and depth. Instead, look for one of two scenarios:
increased minutes for defensive specialist Patterson at shooting
guard, or the activation of rookie point guard Tyronn Lue from the
injured list.
</P>
<P>
   Harper, meanwhile, participated fully in Monday's practice and
is probable for tonight's game against the Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   __ Worm watch: ESPN reported that Dennis Rodman, who left the
team to attend to ``personal business,'' was seen Sunday night
playing blackjack at Caesars Palace in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers executive vice president Jerry West wouldn't comment on
the report, saying he had no direct knowledge of Rodman's
whereabouts. He reiterated that the team would deal with Rodman's
absence, excused or unexcused, internally.
</P>
<P>
   The team remains uncertain when Rodman will return to action.
Rodman's agents did not return phone calls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quote me: After Friday's game, in which Rice tried to shake
off the rust by shooting as often as possible, 21 times in all, he
told reporters, ``When you've got just about everyone on the team
telling you to shoot, you've got to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis, responding Sunday: ``I wasn't telling him to !ital!shoot
it, I was telling him to !ital!make it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
