<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1590 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-POLL-ART-2TAKE     03-15 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-POLL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL FINDS MOST NEW YORKERS THINK POLICE TREAT BLACKS AND WHITES
UNEVENLY 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 DAN BARRY with MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the aftermath of the shooting death of Amadou
Diallo, fewer than a quarter of all New Yorkers believe that the
police treat blacks and whites evenly, with blacks in particular
viewing the police with fear and distrust, according to a New York
Times poll.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 9 out of 10 black residents questioned in the survey said
they thought that the police often engage in brutality against
blacks, and almost two-thirds said that police brutality against
members of minority groups in general is widespread. Also, more
than two-thirds of blacks said the policies of the Giuliani
administration have cause an increase in police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   The survey suggests that police matters and race relations _
along with a growing dislike for the assertive style of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani _ have combined to give him the lowest
job-approval rating of his five-year tenure, 42 percent, reflecting
a sudden, precipitous drop in his popularity. Just five months ago,
a New York Times/CBS News poll found that 63 percent of city
residents approved of Giuliani's performance.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, one issue overshadowed all others: the death of
Diallo. The 22-year-old African immigrant was hit with 19 bullets
during a 41-shot fusillade fired by four white police officers as
he stood in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment building in early
February. Diallo was unarmed, and had no criminal history.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting has since become the focus of a grand jury
investigation and has prompted protests and rallies that continue
to this day. The protests are organized by black leaders who charge
that the shooting reflects a persistent and dangerous distrust of
minorities by white police officers. It has also led to sustained
criticism of Giuliani's tough-on-crime policies and perceived
failure to establish working relationships with many of the city's
elected black officials.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who is considering a run for the United States Senate
next year, has countered that the city's sharp reduction in crime
and its improved economy have benefited the city's black and
Hispanic populations and that his critics are engaging in
race-baiting. Although he has defended the Police Department in
general, he has repeatedly expressed his regrets over Diallo's
death. On Sunday, he and Police Commissioner Howard Safir attended
a prayer service in Brooklyn that was held in his memory.
</P>
<P>
   But the results of the latest survey suggest that the city's
black and Hispanic residents do not think the mayor has done enough
to control the police or improve the city's tenuous race relations.
Sixty percent of those surveyed said that in his public responses
to the Diallo shooting, Giuliani had made matters worse. That
figure includes 47 percent of white residents, 61 percent of
Hispanic residents and 79 percent of black residents.
</P>
<P>
   The results point to a sharp disparity between blacks and whites
over how the police have affected their sense of personal safety. A
third of blacks said they had been in situations where they feared
a police officer, while only 11 percent of whites said they had
felt that way. In contrast, 62 percent of whites said they had been
in situations where they felt safer in the presence of a police
officer, while 57 percent of blacks said they had never felt that
way.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for Giuliani, his press secretary, Colleen Roche,
suggested that the poll results exaggerated the reality of
attitudes in the city. ``The poll numbers seem to be driven by
false perceptions about police brutality, due in large measure to
the intense media and public scrutiny of the Amadou Diallo case,''
she said. ``The fact remains that the New York City Police
Department is among the most restrained in the nation. As times
passes and perspective returns, the poll numbers will once again
reflect reality.''
</P>
<P>
   But James Taylor, 59, a black man from Brooklyn who participated
in the survey, disagreed when contacted after the poll was
completed. The police ``don't give the minority neighborhoods a
chance to explain themselves,'' Mr. Taylor, a food-production
worker, said. ``They will stop you for no reason and ask for
identification. Giuliani may not be responsible for this kind of
behavior on the part of the police, but he can certainly do
something about it. He could start by not always taking the side of
the police.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times poll was conducted by telephone last Monday
through Sunday and surveyed 915 adult residents of New York City.
The margin of sampling error for all New Yorkers is plus or minus
three percentage points; for white residents it is five percentage
points, and for black or Hispanic residents it is six points.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
