<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1592 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-POLL-ART-2NDTA     03-15 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-POLL-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: six points. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The poll included some encouraging indicators for Giuliani. Half
of those questioned said that life in the city had improved in the
last four years, a figure that was nine points lower than five
months ago, but still significantly better than the 34 percent
reflected in a March 1997 poll. Residents also overwhelmingly
approve of the mayor's handling of crime, although that support
dropped 20 points in five months, from 82 percent to 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cares about the welfare of the people,'' said Linda Glaze,
39, white housewife from Staten Island. ``He's more than a
politician. He's looking out for the people in terms of the
economy, jobs, education.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked to cite the worst thing that Giuliani had done as
mayor, 22 percent cited his handling of the police; 15 percent of
whites and 28 percent of blacks cited that issue. The only other
category to receive a double-digit response, 11 percent, was Mr.
Giuliani's outspoken personality; 15 percent and 10 of blacks felt
that way.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also conveyed a concern among residents about the
behavior of the city's police officers that is more pronounced than
the reaction that followed another police encounter: the alleged
brutalization of Abner Louima, a Haitian immigrant, by police
officers in a Brooklyn precinct station house in the summer of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-seven percent of those surveyed last week said that the
policies of the Giuliani administration had caused police brutality
to increase, compared with 31 percent who answered the same
question in October 1997, shortly after the Louima case became
public and just before Giuliani was overwhelmingly re-elected to a
second term.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 70 percent of those polled recently said that the
police ``often engage in brutality'' against blacks, compared with
53 percent who felt that way in October 1997. And two-thirds said
that the police also brutalize Hispanics; a similar question was
not posed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, only 12 percent said they believe that the police
brutalize whites.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, more than half of those recently surveyed said they
believe that the police use excessive force, rather than necessary
force. But once again, their attitudes seem shaped by race. A third
of whites say the police use excessive force, compared to
three-quarters of blacks, and two-thirds of Hispanic people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 43 percent said they believe that police brutality
directed against minorities is widespread. But only 24 percent of
the white residents felt that way, compared with 63 percent of the
black residents and 55 percent of the Hispanic residents.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also demonstrated the inextricable link between the
mayor and law enforcement, a link that he has nurtured for most of
his public career. While the survey reflected public's interest in
reducing crime, with 20 percent saying it should be the mayor's top
priority, 19 percent said that police behavior should be his main
concern instead. That represents a sharp spike from the 4 percent
who answered the same way in October 1997, in the wake of the
Louima case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the police are compassionate enough, especially
towards minorities,'' said Robert Altym, 48, a white hardware
technician from Queens. ``They don't hear them when they ask them a
question. I don't think the police are as familiar or comfortable
with the ethnic diversity of the city as much as they should be.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``I think the mayor has to insure that the police
are trained more with this in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Young, a securities salesman from Coney Island, said
he sympathized with the challenges faced by the police. ``In terms
of brutality, I think some of it is exaggerated,'' he said. ``When
your life is on the line, you have to be extremely cautious. I'm
not condoning brutality, but in many cases the criminals are better
armed than the police themselves. Sometimes being over-cautious
makes you do things you don't intend to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
