A1593 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERSONALIZED-TV-CHANN     03-15 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONALIZED-TV-CHANNELS-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH REPLAYTV, YOU CAN SET UP YOUR OWN CHANNELS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 450-word ``separate buy'' story is from ``WORTH'' magazine.
To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``a''
domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
  
 By JASON ADAMS  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We, a nation of TV enthusiasts, have placed our faith in the
idea of the little black set-top box, an accoutrement that, as a
cable box, turned out feeble network options into a viewing
Shangri-la.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from TV, some Internet providers soon spawned the
notion of content personalization through ``channels.'' Then came
the idea that we could reap television-like enjoyment from
``viewing'' these Internet channels on our TV. When we signed on,
we envisioned a web of TV; what we got was WebTV.
</P>
<P>
   But now we have reached convergence: ReplayTV. A step beyond
WebTV, ReplayTV has taken the personalization features of Internet
portals like Yahoo! and Excite and adapted them to what we want to
see emanating from our tubes _ namely, television programs.
</P>
<P>
   A small, sleek black box with the savvy of a PC yet commanded by
the familiar click of a remote control, ReplayTV lets us believe
again in the idea of personalized channels.
</P>
<P>
   Its Replay Channels _ tailored by show, entertainer, or theme,
be it ``The Simpsons,'' ``Jeff Gordon,'' or ``fishing'' _ act like
a set of earmarked mailboxes (you've got ``Friends''!), where
specific types of programs of your predetermined choosing are found
and recorded.
</P>
<P>
   A Yankees fan could set up a ``Yankees Channel'' and, whenever
he wanted, check for Yankees games and related programming on the
on-screen program guide. Just punch up that channel when it's time
for marathon viewing.
</P>
<P>
   There's more: Let's say that during ``Frasier'' we decide we'd
love to have a permanent record of David Hyde Pierce's future work.
Just press the ``Record This Show'' button on the Replay remote.
</P>
<P>
   The TV will ask, ``Record just this episode or record all
episodes?'' If you decide on the latter, the most recent show will
always be in the on-deck circle, ready and waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Because its hard-drive storage (anywhere from 6 to 20 hours) is
random-access, ReplayTV can record and play a show at the same
time, allowing you to pause, rewind, and fast-forward during
currently airing programs.
</P>
<P>
   Each night ReplayTV dials into the free Replay Network Services
to update itself with the latest channel-guide info.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the top-of-the-line ``enthusiast version'' is available
from Replay Networks for $995. But various manufacturers have
licensed this technology, so coming down the pike will likely be
$500 versions with an emphasis on simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Bells and whistles are one thing, but as Replay Networks
director of marketing Jim Plant explains, the core of the issue is
always that ``the number-one problem people have is missing their
favorite television show.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 450-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
