<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-N     03-15 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-LEWIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCOMFORTABLE SPOTLIGHT IS ON JUDGES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jean Williams has attended fights for as long as she can recall
and trained to box as a teen-ager before women were accepted in the
sport. A referee introduced her to judging amateur fights, and by
1989 she was licensed by New Jersey and sanctioned by the
International Boxing Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing's in my blood,'' she said Monday by telephone from her
job at City Hall in Atlantic City, N.J., where she works as an
accounts clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday night, Williams' name was no more famous than a
typical civil court judge's. And if her scoring during the Evander
Holyfield-Lennox Lewis heavyweight unification fight had not
ignited a public uproar, she might have collected her $5,150 fee,
left Madison Square Garden and gone home to Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   But her 115-113 score for Holyfield _ combined with another
judge's 116-113 decision for Lewis and the third judge's 115-115
verdict _ turned the fight into a draw, and Williams was labeled
inept by critics who wondered what she was watching.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' scorecard is more than fodder for sports talk radio.
Her decision is calling into question the qualifications of judges,
the procedures for approving them by states and sanctioning bodies
and the sometimes incestuous relationships of promoters,
sanctioning bodies and judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I did something wrong, I'd be upset,'' Williams said
Monday. ``I know I didn't. And I don't want people to think I did
anything illegal. I'm offended by the idea that people think I
didn't know what I was doing, but everyone's entitled to their
opinion. I'm not worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Added to the questioning of Williams' scoring was an admission
by the British judge for the fight, Larry O'Connell, that he erred
by scoring the bout a draw. ``Judged on the weight of public
opinion, I would say I was wrong,'' he said in Monday's London
Evening Standard.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lee, the IBF president, said, ``That's a hell of a time to
admit you're wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The vehement reaction to the draw provoked the New York State
Athletic Commission to launch a weeklong investigation Monday.
Eliot L. Spitzer, the state attorney general, and state Sen. Roy
Goodman also scheduled hearings Thursday in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if what happened Saturday night was an honest error,
there is a perception by the public that there won't be an honest
evaluation of a fight,'' said Spitzer, who is working with U.S.
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., on federal boxing legislation. ``At
minimum, the sport is tainted by the appearance of corruption, and
a reality of impropriety at the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said, ``We're going to explore the connections between
the promoters and sanctioning bodies with a great deal of
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of what they will discover is that promoters pay the
judges' fees, airfare and lodging and that written tests are not
always required to become judges. The New York and New Jersey
athletic commissions require a background in amateur judging, but
do not mandate a written test for a license. Nevada judges must
have extensive amateur experience and pass a written test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't license anyone without five years in the amateur
ranks,'' said Larry Hazzard, the New Jersey athletic commissioner,
``and that includes recommendations from amateur officials.''
</P>
<P>
   To become licensed in New York, applicants practice scoring at
bouts, and their scores are compared with those of the official
judges' cards. If their credibility is established, they get more
individual experience, said Scott Trent, a spokesman for the
athletic commission. In Nevada, judges move steadily higher from
scoring four-round fights up to 12-rounders.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, commissions require that judges attend annual seminars
to review films and be updated on anything that may affect their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   With a license, judges can apply to the alphabet soup of
sanctioning bodies from best-known ones like IBF, the World Boxing
Council and World Boxing Association to lesser lights like the
North American Boxing Federation.
</P>
<P>
   There is no licensing procedure for the sanctioning organization
to accept the judges into their fold. ``We rely on what their
commission sends us, and they must attend a seminar,'' said Lee, of
the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   Lee had 90 judges to choose from for the Holyfield-Lewis fight
and selected Williams. ``She met the criteria,'' he said. ``She
gave me a list of 27 fights, including nine IBF title fights. I
have the utmost confidence in her.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``If Jean put down a score for Holyfield, that's what
she saw. I wouldn't tell her what to do. Whatever happens,
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, the state athletic commission chooses judges from a
list submitted by the sanctioning bodies. ``We don't let them say
who they want,'' said Marc Ratner, the commission's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner said that while he believed that promoters' paying for
the judges is a conflict, ``I don't know how to get around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to how a judge scores fights is how he or she applies
the rules to his or her scoring. Harold Lederman, the on-air judge
for HBO and TVKO, which carried the fight, said judges should score
four elements equally: clean punching, effective aggressiveness,
ring generalship and defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to give them all equal weight, but in
professional boxing, most judges go 95 percent for clean
punching,'' said Lederman, who scored Lewis the winner of the
fight, 117-111.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, the judges at the Holyfield-Lewis fight _
Williams, O'Connell and Stanley Christodoulou _ were in different
places around the ring. Williams said she was farther from the ring
than she preferred, unable to lean on the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I couldn't see,'' she said. And during
the fifth round, which Williams scored for Holyfield and the other
judges scored for Lewis, she had a view of Lewis' back.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when he moved to the side, Holyfield took over in the
later part of the round,'' she said. ``I couldn't judge what I
couldn't see. The other judges may have seen what I couldn't see. I
couldn't go to the other side. I even hit my head on a camera when
I tried to get closer.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I didn't do anything wrong. I made a judgment
call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
