<HEADER>
A1596 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITI-MALTA-FREIGHTER     03-15 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-MALTA-FREIGHTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Questions arise over freighter crew's involvement in Hatian
immigrant disaster
 &HT;    By Larry Hobbs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Coast Guard officals wonder if the crew
of a Maltese freighter could have done more to rescue the victims
of a deadly Haitian immigrant smuggling disaster offshore from West
Palm Beach last week.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Adm. Norman T. Saunders is asking for an
investigation by the government of Malta, the country where the
ship Tomis Faith is registered, petty officer Scott Carr said. The
Coast Guard rescued three men and confirmed four women dead after
Tomis Faith crew members contacted it at about 1 a.m. on March 6
and said they heard screams coming from the water.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Border Patrol officials believe anywhere from 15 to 43
people drowned when at least one, and possibly two boats sank 26
miles offshore. Details remain sketchy because of conflicting
accounts from the survivors, Border Patrol agents said.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing screams, the crew of the Tomis Faith shined a
light into the water, but saw nothing, Scott said. They continued
on and later reported the incident to the Coast Guard via telex,
Scott said. The telex went to the Coast Guard's communications
center in Virginia, and was then passed on to the Coast Guard
station in Miami, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Saunders wonders if the crew violated international
maritime laws by not remaining in the area until a search and
rescue crew arrived, or by not calling the Coast Guard immediately
on its radio, Carr said. Because the incident took place in
international waters, it is up to the ship's registered country to
conduct an investigation, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   About three weeks ago, Tomis Faith left its port in New Orleans
against orders to remain because of problems with the boat, Scott
said. The ship is en route to Spain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hobbs writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
