<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS &LR;      03-15 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET TO GET LION'S SHARE OF EXECUTIVE JOBS IN NEW BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Fleet Financial Group Inc. moved quickly to put its
stamp on the proposed $178 billion banking powerhouse formed by its
acquisition of archrival BankBoston Corp., despite official
descriptions of the deal Monday as a marriage of equals.
</P>
<P>
   Six of nine top executive slots at the new institution, Fleet
Boston Corp., are slotted for Fleet managers, the companies said in
a press conference to announce the deal. Fleet chief executive
Terrence Murray will head the new institution, and ``most staff
positions will report to me,'' Murray said. BankBoston chief
executive Chad Gifford will become chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, Gifford would take over as chief
executive at the end of 2001 when Murray said he hopes to retire.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston's Gifford and Fleet's Murray _ known as bitter rivals
with nearly opposite personalities and management philosophies _
took pains Monday to portray the deal as a partnership employing a
``sprinkling of talent from both companies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lopsided management appointments are part of a pattern,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can talk all they want about this being a merger of
equals, but let's make no bones about it: This is Fleet's deal,''
said Gerard Cassidy, an analyst at Tucker Anthony Inc. in Boston.
``Take a look at all the deals Fleet has done over the years. Fleet
people are always the ones who survive.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Monday's announcement Fleet's Eugene McQuade will
become chief financial officer; Jay Sarles will be chief
administrative officer; David Eyles will be chief risk officer,
Michael Zucchini will head technology and operations; and Robert
Higgins will head commercial and retail banking.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BankBoston's Henrique Meirelles will head
international banking, corporate investment banking, and investment
services. Joseph Smialowski, also of BankBoston, will help lead
technology and operations.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed $16 billion stock-for-stock transaction shocked the
local banking world when word of an impending deal began to spread
Sunday. In creating the nation's eighth largest financial
institution, by far the largest in New England, it seeks to combine
radically different cultures. Despite its recent merger with
BayBanks, BankBoston retains an air of patrician old Boston, while
Fleet Fleet arrived in town at the beginning of the decade as an
aggressive, acquisition-hungry upstart.
</P>
<P>
   The deal received an unenthusiastic reception on Wall Street,
where Fleet shares fell 5.7 percent, or 2 9/16, to 42 3/16 a share
on the New York Stock Exchange. BankBoston nudged up less than 1
percent, or 1/8 cents, to 47 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Both banks, however, sought the deal in part because each was
vulnerable to an acquisition from outside the region, possibly from
a suitor such as North Carolina's First Union Corp., said Cassidy,
the analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of these guys are very proud of their New England
heritage,'' he said. ``Neither of them wanted to be the one to let
a Confederate flag fly over their insititution.''
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's announcement, the executives said joining the two
institutions will take at least a year. Ultimately, about 5,000
positions are expected to be eliminated as the new institution
slashes jobs and looks for ways to cut costs, officials said. About
3,000 slots should be taken care of through an immediate hiring
freeze and attrition, they said. In all, 60,000 people now work for
the two banks worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The bank is likely to shutter neighboring branches, especially
in southern New England where BankBoston and Fleet branches often
overlap, officials said. In addition, the bank will close 24
branches and sell an as-yet-unspecified number of its automatic
teller machines and branch offices to a competing bank to satisfy
antitrust regulators concerned with preserving competition in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said Fleet is currently negotiating with regulators to
determine the ``size and type'' of the banks who would be offered
the branches.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet will keep BankBoston's extensive operations in Latin
America, where political and economic instability have contributed
to BankBoston's recent weak stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a bigger balance sheet, we can better exploit the
strengths and better withstand the perceived volatility,'' Gifford
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new bank also plans to greatly expand its base of some
500,000 customers who bank on line with personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the Internet age is a tremendous springboard and
something we're going to take advantage of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have spoken out against the merger, saying its
sheer size leaves Fleet with a virtual monopoly and the power to
charge higher fees for banking services.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's press conference, Fleet's Murray said consumers can
expect some higher fees but also improved services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average household today is probably not consciously aware
of the fact that banking services are better,'' he said. ``What
they probably are aware of is that they're paying for them. The
fact is the world is demanding these services, and we intend to
provide them while reflecting those costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials Monday sought to allay criticism from community groups
that have worried BankBoston's practice of lending liberally in
poorer communities could be swallowed by Fleet's historically more
reluctant approach to community lending.
</P>
<P>
   ``BankBoston will take the lead on that,'' Gifford said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, US Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts
Democrat who serves on the House Banking Committee, said he expects
to meet with community leaders in New Bedford and Fall River, the
poorest urban areas that Frank represents.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said he wanted to be sure the merged bank conforms with
federal regulations meant to ensure loans and bank services in poor
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no reason to doubt it, but no reason to take it for
granted, either,'' said Frank, who is the senior Democrat on a
House Banking subcommittee on community development.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said the merger presented ``a tradeoff'' for the region. A
deal between two banks from the same area probably produces more
layoffs than if one of the banks was not based in New England, he
said. But merging two in-region banks also keeps the business under
local control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your main goal is to preserve the absolutely largest number
of jobs in our region, you want one or both of the banks to be
bought from outside'' the Boston area, he said. ``The tradeoff is
that versus lack of local control. But that's not up to the
government to decide. That's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   There were moments of levity at Monday's press conference
between Murray and Gifford, whose differing backgrounds have often
pitted each against the other.
</P>
<P>
   Fielding a question on the possible location of the new
institution's headquarters, Murray said his rival's downtown
building is ``by far is the most attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford blurted out, ``I think we've just made a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murray, speaking over him, added: ``From the outside it's
more attractive. From the inside, ours is much better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
