<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1599 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-INVESTOR-SANIT     03-15 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-INVESTOR-SANITY-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO FIND INTELLIGENT LIFE ON THE ONLINE-INVESTING PLANET  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Financial Editors)   (This 950-word ``separate buy'' personal-finance story is from
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial news, and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
  
 By BRONWYN FRYER  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nineteenth-century French novelist Gustave Flaubert loathed that
newfangled contraption, the steam locomotive. When there was talk
of laying track in his peaceful hometown of Croisset, he scoffed,
``What's the point? It will only bring in more people to be stupid
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing Flaubert never wandered into an Internet chat room.
Online chat rooms _ basically, the real-time, typed equivalent of a
telephone conversation _ are open forums haunted by an assortment
of people with time on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   In the typical chat room, Monsieur and Mademoiselle Lonelyhearts
pretend to have sex while pretending they're someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Most investment chat rooms aren't much of an improvement. (To
find these places, do a quick search on the keywords ``Stock+Chat''
using an engine like Yahoo!)
</P>
<P>
   I've visited several of them, usually to discover that I'm the
only one to show up. The only time I encountered another virtual
creature, it dropped a hint about some suspiciously cheap,
unheard-of stock, then darted off. No wonder sites such as
InvestorExchange.com have closed their chat areas in favor of
bulletin boards, where investors don't converse but post and read
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior is par for the course. As one Silicon Valley
investor points out, ``If the people who inhabit these places and
give advice on stocks were taking their own advice, they'd have
better things to do than hang out in chat rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   An exception to the dismal run of chat rooms is the scheduled
variety hosted by legitimate Web sites, where investment movers and
shakers take real-time questions from participants.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Network's Investor.com, for example, regularly sets up
scheduled chats with Wall Street stars, such as the recent seminar
``Investing for Growth and Income,'' sponsored by Charles Schwab &AMP;
Co. and featuring Robert Natale, a managing director at Bears
Stearns Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   Also higher on the evolutionary scale are the newsgroups and
other threaded discussion forums _ bulletin boards focused on a
fairly narrow topic _ offered by the big online services and
portals, such as America Online, Microsoft Network, Compuserve,
Netscape, and Yahoo!
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's Business and Finance message board
(http://messages.yahoo.com/yahoo/business_and_finance/index.html)
is typical of the genre, with discussions on such topics as
brokerage firms, upcoming initial public offerings, fund-trading
strategies, and overvalued stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The boards aren't without their share of hype and nonsense, but
practiced participants learn to separate the signal from the noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take time to read with an unbiased eye, you can find
employees and insiders posting good information,'' says Michael
Burry, a physician in Palo Alto, Calif., who also writes an online
investment newsletter, ``Valuestocks.net.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring he joined a Yahoo! group focused on the titanium
industry. ``There was a guy named Acroti, who said he was an
insider in the titanium business,'' Burry recalls. ``He told us
where the trends in titanium were going and that it would soon be
in a downturn.''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent events showed Acroti to be ``dead on,'' says Burry,
and he now looks for postings that, like Acroti's, are delivered
with authority but without an apparent ax to grind. ``He posted
what he needed to post and didn't get involved in arguments,'' says
Burry.
</P>
<P>
   Fee-based or monitored Web sites are also good for weeding out
the riffraff. Burry's favorite site, Silicon Investor, charges a
$10 monthly fee, but he says the price is worth it. ``It's really
amazing to see the time and thought that some people put into their
posts, '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Such sites tend to do a better job of shooing away the hucksters
than the open forums on sites such as Yahoo!
</P>
<P>
   In open discussion groups where users can create multiple
identifiers for themselves, stock pushers can create what looks
like a group discussion, usually around a small stock, when in fact
the entire conversation is the fabrication of a single person with
an interest in hyping the stock.
</P>
<P>
   When inspecting discussion groups, look for sites that post
clear ground rules and for discussions that stay on-topic. Don't
become embroiled in passionate debate right from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, study the posted messages in various areas. If the site
appears to lack serious, concentrated discouse, lists several
postings by the same person (identified by a nickname), or allows
users to carry multiple nicknames, keep several grains of salt
handy.
</P>
<P>
   The following are some of the better sites:
</P>
<P>
   SILICON INVESTOR (www.siliconinvestor.com) is a members-only
club for investors in high tech. The $10-per-month price tag (or
$200 or a lifetime membership) discourages the weirdos and phonies.
More than 300,000 messages are posted monthly, some of them,
admittedly, of the amuse-and-schmooze variety but many of them
serious analyses of market events. There's also private E-mail for
members.
</P>
<P>
   THESTREET.COM (www.thestreet.com) also charges a $10 monthly fee
($100 a year), which buys access to the site's rather uneven news
coverage as well as to a portfolio tracker, a useful SEC Filings
feature, and plenty of intelligent debate. The Talk section offers
threaded discussions on travel and culture as well as investing.
</P>
<P>
   THE MOTLEY FOOL'S (http://boards.fool.com/) discussion boards,
which are free, let participants post questions on message boards
and receive replies. There are plenty of instructive tales as well
as a weekly roundup of the best postings.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian firm StockGroup Interactive Media posts a free
forum, INVESTOR EXCHANGE (www.investorexchange.com). The monitored
discussions cover all aspects of investing, with a focus on
Canadian firms.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT NETWORK INVESTOR (http://investor.msn.com), which
offers free and pay services, features forums plus scheduled and
open chats. A section called MoneyCentral
(http://moneycentral.msn.com) provides discussion groups on such
topics as retirement, credit, taxes, and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   CBS MarketWatch's STOCKCHAT (www.stockchat.com) is a free,
wide-ranging forum. You can search for discussion threads
alphabetically or by stock ticker symbol. The discussions are
monitored for obscenity and other breaches of netiquette.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the INVESTMENT FAQ (www.invest.faq.com) culls some of
the best postings from investment newsgroups, compiles the combined
wisdom into straightforward articles, and provides links to outside
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Even Flaubert would probably consider it a vast improvement over
live chat rooms. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Bronwyn Fryer profiled a Merrill Lynch financial
planner in the November 1998 issue of WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
