<HEADER>
A1601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-I-ART-525(2TA     03-15 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-I-ART-525(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAGERFELD'S LESSON FOR YOUNGER DESIGNERS: STAY RELEVANT 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036.) 
(fb) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ He has been in fashion long enough for his thick black
hair to gleam white _ with some artful help from powder dusting. He
has seen bell-bottoms come and go and come back. He has lost his
label, been abandoned by Chloe for a younger woman, and that outre
business of posing with a fan has gone on a little too long.
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, Karl Lagerfeld should be working somewhere
stress-free, proposing pearls and navy sweaters as the look of the
new season. But on the contrary, with his latest collection for
Chanel, Lagerfeld showed that he is more than capable of keeping up
with Tom Ford at Gucci, Miuccia Prada, the Americans and the young
Belgians who are redefining style.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another important bit of news that emerged as the
Paris shows for fall 1999 ended on Monday: the bid by American
designers to gain more creative credibility by showing first,
rather than last, on the international calendar, has worked. From
the perspective of a month's runway shows in New York, London,
Milan and Paris, American design looks incredibly strong.
</P>
<P>
   It is now a startling reality that, while France is
unquestionably a center of world fashion, it will take the French
years to reclaim the kind of hegemony they enjoyed just five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The situation isn't improving. French designers continue to be
marginalized in their own country. Nicolas Ghesquiere at Balenciaga
is one of the few French talents who still matter. At Nina Ricci, a
French woman, Myriam Schaeffer, has been replaced by Nathalie
Gervais, a Canadian who worked at Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Alber Elbaz moved in at Yves Saint Laurent this season, and
Thierry Mugler, who ended Paris fashion week Monday with a series
of small shows in his ceiling-to-floor powder-blue work space, is
now an afterthought in some fashion circles.
</P>
<P>
   Mugler's twin as a guru of 1980s power fashion, Claude Montana,
is embroiled in business troubles and did not show at all. The
French can't quite figure out what's happening.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Lagerfeld to spell it out: D-R-E-S-S D-O-W-N. Before
Bernard Arnault of LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton installed
Alexander McQueen of Britain at Givenchy, before Tom Ford revived
Gucci, there was Lagerfeld, the German expatriate making Chanel
incandescent. Chanel is no longer white-hot, but thanks to
Lagerfeld, it remains relevant and prestigious.
</P>
<P>
   The designer put Chanel into a dangerous but necessary
metamorphosis last year, which made some retailers and editors
nervous. This season, Lagerfeld cannily blended the house's legacy
and the future. The young can keep wearing Chanel, and the mature
customer can feel comfortable in feather-light jackets with
ruffles, leather vests and knee-length skirts, easy cardigan coats
and Goth-style Chanel dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the metal belts big enough to chain a gate. I liked
the flat, soft leather boots, which brought to mind the astronaut
footwear in ``2001: A Space Odyssey.'' The death during show week
of Stanley Kubrick, the director of that film, made vivid the
influences of designers who are looking forward to the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness someone is thinking about the future. John
Galliano certainly is not. He made his runway into a construction
site, and left one observer wondering what on earth shards of
glass, rubble, a demolished car and police barricades had to do
with a grand 1920s Poiret-style coat, sweeping skirts inspired by a
trench coat and 1940s bias gowns.
</P>
<P>
   The effect was as if Cate Blanchett playing Elizabeth had lost
her way and wandered onto the set of ``Cruel Intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   You would not have been surprised if a police officer had
appeared from behind a barricade and ticketed Galliano for failure
to heed a new century.
</P>
<P>
   Galliano knows how to make a woman look seductive, as he did in
claret-colored bias dresses slit up the leg, or a peacoat etched in
white appliqued tribal markings. But there were conceptual
stumbling blocks in this collection.
</P>
<P>
   Little was new or exciting. The preponderance of wools looked
heavy, the huge proportions retrograde. A spectator could feel
positively embarrassed for models with too much eye shadow like
Stella Tennant as she preened as if in a burlesque show.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions of fashion and beauty are changing, and those who
viewed Galliano's show, it seems, have changed more than he has.
When the audience is ahead of a designer, that's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Galliano needs to refresh his vision. He could take notes from
Lagerfeld _ or he could just hang out with Dave, the proprietor of
one of this city's restaurants, a favorite with the fashion pack.
</P>
<P>
   Like taxi drivers and hair stylists, it is the restaurateurs,
particularly ones as well connected and fashionably astute as Dave,
who have their own way of calibrating shifts in the spirit of the
times.
</P>
<P>
   As he surveyed his clientele the other night, Dave observed in
Franco-Asian tones, ``In six months, the people at companies have
completely changed.''
</P>
<P>
   He's exaggerating a bit _ it is, after all, Dave who tells
patrons he's reserving a table for them, and there isn't actually
one available when they arrive. That's because Stella McCartney is
occupying a table; Robert Forrest, creative director of Ungaro, is
in another corner with Bonnie Pressman, now at Ralph Lauren, James
King, the model, is near the fish tank, and Joe Boitano of Bergdorf
Goodman is tucked in with the English designer Eskendar.
</P>
<P>
   But the kernel of truth is there. The look and names that are of
interest in France have switched, seemingly overnight.
</P>
<P>
   A textbook case: Christian Lacroix, who continues to struggle to
look current. He's having some success as he pares down his shapes
and denudes some fabrics of his trademark pattern mixes and
festoons.
</P>
<P>
   A few pretty pieces surfaced in his collection: a coral quilted
coat in taffeta, jersey T-shirts printed with fanciful themes, a
black skirt trimmed with colorful sequins.
</P>
<P>
   To Lacroix, the phrase ``a little goes a long way'' means
nothing. But Gilles Dufour, Balmain's new designer and Lagerfeld's
former design associate at Chanel, appreciates it completely.
</P>
<P>
   To the hem of a pair of loose trousers, Dufour appliqued a
charming spray of felt flowers; and to a small purple tweed jacket,
he added discreet touches of embroidery and sequins. The collection
lacked a strong statement, but it must have made Georgina
Brandolini, the creative director who hired Dufour, happy. It was
not fusty old Balmain. Immediately, a consistency has been
established between the ready-to-wear and Balmain couture designed
by Oscar de la Renta.
</P>
<P>
   Brandolini, scion of the powerful Agnelli family of Italy, can
wear these clothes, and so can Catherine Deneuve and Lee Radziwill,
both of whom sat in the front row to cheer Dufour.
</P>
<P>
   In a cathedral setting with soaring ceilings and cavernous
rooms, Dries van Noten's solemn collection was unveiled: flowing
skirts peeking out beneath flowing rough-hewn coats, and sparkling
velvet rustling beneath a brown flannel dress. The designs were
ethereal and monastic, a mood that was the polar opposite of
Veronique Leroy's.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy was at her wry best with split trousers that look like
skirts, swooping black coats and a carnation adorning a white
shirt. There was a new version of the ponchos that she showed for
spring. She is early out of the gate with a lot of ideas. The
late-1970s and '80s Mugler-Montana power look that designers like
Jeremy Scott are doing now and that Alexander McQueen at Givenchy
plumbed two seasons ago Leroy did first.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be we're heading toward a Mugler moment? Foxy Brown in
a leather and chrome bikini in the ``Hot Spot'' video from her hit
CD looks as if she'd been channeling old Mugler shows. And Scott's
pink collection this season was reminiscent of Mugler. But the
problem with doing Mugler is that no one can do the dangerous-woman
look better than the designer who invented it.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after Scott's show, Mugler himself showed seriously
tailored pink suits and candy-pink dresses. It's a good idea to
wait until the designer is no longer in business before the homages
begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered if it gives someone the opportunity to go a step
further,'' Mugler said on Monday. ``If it's a copy or a cheap
imitation of what I did, then I think it's very negative. It's not
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, what goes around comes around. But as we see the
last of the first collections for the next century, designers must
understand that not everything from the 20th century should come
around again so soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
