A1605 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-STOCKS-BIG-LETD     03-15 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-STOCKS-BIG-LETDOWN-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-COMPANY STOCKS: HIT OR MYTH?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Financial Editors)   (This 1,150-word ``separate buy'' financial story is from ``WORTH''
magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news files.)  
  
 By SCOTT BURNS  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is a truth universally acknowledged that the road to real
money and mind-boggling returns is small-company stocks. But just
try following the path.
</P>
<P>
   Why have small stocks been so disappointing?
</P>
<P>
   Why have so many investors searched so hard to find so little?
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that only one small-stock fund beat the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 Stock Index over the past 15 years _ and then by less
than one-tenth of one percentage point?
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that more than 600 managers, scouring the most obscure
nooks and crannies of the known stock universe, seem to be falling
further and further behind, Internet fever notwithstanding?
</P>
<P>
   The time has come to examine a deep belief _ the idea that
small-company stocks will, in the long run, provide a higher return
than large-company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It has a remarkably diverse array of adherents. Mavericks
believe because there is a romance attached to finding a small
company that will transform an industry _ or create one.
</P>
<P>
   Quantitative types believe because the largest and most revered
database, the virtual bible of modern portfolio theory, says small
stocks provide higher returns than big stocks.
</P>
<P>
   And commonsense types believe because it seems so logical: At
some point, a big company's ability to grow should be constrained
by its already massive size.
</P>
<P>
   Actual events, however, don't support the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of the small-company stock creed are to be found in
the aforementioned bible: ``Stocks, Bonds, Bills, and Inflation,''
the Ibbotson Associates yearbook that provides data on asset
returns from 1926 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 yearbook shows that large-company stocks _ as
represented by the S&AMP;P 500 _ have delivered a compound annual
return of 11 percent while small-company stocks have returned 12.7
percent. That extra return isn't free, however.
</P>
<P>
   Small-stock prices are more volatile than large-stock prices _
investors have to live with greater price risk while waiting for
their higher return.
</P>
<P>
   But the payoff is substantial. Put $1,000 into large stocks, and
the Ibbotson data say it will grow to $184,565 over 50 years. Make
the same investment in small stocks, and it will grow to $394,635
over the same period. Twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   The problem starts with the actual results of the professional
investors who are paid to capture that extra return.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1981, just months before the start of the stock
market's long rise, there were only 17 small-company funds. FPA
Capital, which Robert Rodriguez has run for 14 years, is the
best-performing fund in that group.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 years that ended October 31, the fund provided a
compound annual return of 17.20 percent, enough to edge out the S&AMP;P
500's 17.11 percent return.
</P>
<P>
   Acorn Fund, managed by Ralph Wanger and Ralph McQuaid, was
second-best, returning 15.56 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, both funds beat the Russell 2000 _ a broad index
of small companies _ by a wide margin. Indeed, the two funds
performed so well that they lifted the 15-year average for the
entire small-stock category above the Russell index.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1981, the number of small-company funds has burgeoned to
682. Their track record, measured against the Russell 2000 index,
hasn't been bad. On average, they beat their index in three of five
measuring periods. What they haven't done is come close to the
returns on large-company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the persistent faith in small stocks is that over
the past 15 years some companies have grown from tiny, struggling
start-ups into industry leaders, while some large companies that
were once seen as invincible have suffered devastating declines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, to cite just one example, Eastman Kodak had the
seventh-highest market value among U.S. stocks. Today it ranks
117th.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Microsoft had yet to go public in 1977, and neither
Dell Computer nor Compaq Computer had even been founded. Today,
Microsoft has the largest market capitalization of all U.S. stocks;
Dell and Compaq rank 31st and 45th, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the divergent fates of Microsoft and Kodak represent the
general triumph of the small and entrepreneurial over the large and
bureaucratic.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Two respected observers offer different, but related,
reasons. In ``Stocks for the Long Run,'' finance professor Jeremy
Siegel points out that small stocks' edge over large stocks
virtually disappears if the 1975-83 period is excluded from the
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   While some might object to simply removing a block of years from
a time series, it happens that small stocks lost 31 percent of
their value in 1973 and an additional 20 percent of their value in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that small stocks did relatively well from
1975 to 1983. They were recovering from virtual obliteration.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the price volatility of small stocks means that
market makers increase their bid/ask spreads _ that is, to
compensate for the added risk, they charge a higher markup when
buying or selling small stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel cites a study showing that even in modern times the
spread on small stocks has been 2.65 percent, compared with 0.40
percent for large stocks. That wider spread wipes out the entire
long-term advantage of small stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation comes from value manager David Dreman. An
asterisk in the 1998 ``SBBI'' yearbook notes that the 12.7 percent
annual return of small-company stocks includes 1933, when their
total return was a stunning 142.9 percent. Large stocks have never
enjoyed a comparable one-year jump.
</P>
<P>
   Dreman found that trading in the 1931-35 period was very light,
with some 58 percent of the small-stock group not trading at all on
any given day. Not surprisingly, bid/ask spreads were enormous,
averaging 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   We'll let the academics worry about the fine details. The
practical message is that market realities may hinder any investor
from reaping the benefits of small-stock investing _ if those
benefits exist at all.
</P>
<P>
   So what's an investor to do? Forget size _ it's just too
limiting.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the median company on the Russell 2000 list has a
market capitalization of $220 million. If and when its market value
exceeds $1 billion, it will cease, by most conventional
definitions, to be a small stock.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who stick strictly to small stocks, then, are
voluntarily limiting their potential gains to what Peter Lynch
would call a ``five-bagger.'' That's giving up a lot of potential
upside.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most doctrinaire small-stock investor would probably
regret selling the likes of Cisco Systems ($125 billion in market
capitalization as of Dec. 8), Dell ($85 billion), or Oracle ($34
billion) when they became ``too big.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's anything to be learned from following the contrails
of these highfliers, it's that size doesn't matter. Good stocks
do. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Scott Burns is the
personal-finance columnist for the Dallas Morning News. His E-mail
address is scott(at)scottburns.com, and his Web-site address is
www.scottburns.com.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 1,150-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0516 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMART-KITCHENS-COX     03-15 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMART-KITCHENS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motorola, MIT seek to improve consumers' home environment
 &HT;    (EDS: Was previously sent out as MOTOROLA-MIT-COX.)
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Motorola Inc. is hoping a marriage between high
tech and higher education will create tools to make your home more
user friendly.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the communications company announced a $5 million
grant to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology to create a lab
focused on a new line of ``smart'' products for the home. Examples
are clothing with computerized labels that can tell a washing
machine which cycle to use and dishwashers that communicate with
other household appliances about noise levels and energy use.
</P>
<P>
   The Motorola DigitalDNA Laboratory at MIT's Media Lab will be
completed in 2003 as a new 5,000-square-foot building next to the
current lab. It will develop products to complement Motorola's
semiconductor division, headquartered in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The Schaumburg, Ill., company, which has about 10,000 employees
in Austin, said the technology to create smart products already
exists, but isn't geared toward consumers. The hope in creating
smart products would be that they could be linked together in the
home to make a more efficient, more responsive environment.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Ruiz, president of Motorola's Semiconductor Products
Sector, said the devices will make life easier by simplifying tools
like remote controls. Instead of using several remotes or a
universal remote, a home entertainment center might be controlled
by a central device that could control not only electronic devices,
but air conditioning and home security.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership, Motorola and MIT said, was born after market
surveys found consumers think many technological advances are
useless to the average person, and that many products are hard to
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should people have to read a 2-inch-thick manual to do
something simple?'' Ruiz asked. ``These are things at the low end
of the (technology's) application, things that make the consumer
happier.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Motorola heralded the new devices as revolutionary,
Motorola is one of many companies racing to get network devices
into the home as bandwidth improves. While phone and cable
companies introduce new technologies to bring faster Internet
access into the home, companies including Microsoft Corp., Intel
Corp. and Cisco Systems Inc. have announced initiatives to get
homes wired.
</P>
<P>
   At a demonstration at the Consumer Electronics Show in January,
Cisco Systems Inc. showed a prototype of a networked home in which
air conditioning, music and lighting could be monitored and changed
on a Web page, even from outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, however, is betting that its investment into the
400-person MIT lab will pay off in low-cost products that will
enable people to customize their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front door can open as it sees you coming with a load of
groceries,'' said Nicholas Negroponte, MIT Media Lab director, who
also serves on Motorola's board of directors. ``Or it can let the
dog out but not let 10 dogs back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola has recently been billing itself as a solution provider
for the growing convergence of technologies in the home. At the
Consumer Electronics Show, the company introduced Streamaster, a
platform for companies to create set-top boxes that could handle
cable, video games, video-on-demand and home theater.
</P>
<P>
   Omar L. Gallaga writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas. This article contains information from the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
