<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/15/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- March 15, 1999 -- DEECEE-UNIVERSITY, 3-15
-- Two University of the District of Columbia students working in
the school's library. Mayor Anthony A. Williams proposed moving the
university from its current location in northwest Washington near
embassies and expensive homes, to Anacostia, the poorest section of
the city. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) ARLINGTON, Texas -- March 15, 1999 -- CHANCELLOR-LIN,
3-15 -- Thomas O. Hicks, the chairman of Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst,
will be taking on more responsibility. Chancellor Media Corp., the
big radio and outdoor-advertising company in Dallas, called off its
$900 million deal to buy Lin Television Corp. on Monday and said
that its chief executive, Jeffrey Marcus, had resigned and would be
replaced by Hicks. (Mark Graham/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) BERNALILLO, N.M. -- March 15, 1999 -- INDIANS-RESORTS-2,
3-15 -- Tribal members at the Santa Ana Pueblo reservation are
increasingly concerned over the projected expansion of their
casino. ``There are so many attacks on Indian casinos,'' says Roy
Montoya, who as chief administrator of the 690-member tribe is in
charge of all business development. ``What the new resort
represents is another step towards self-sufficiency.'' (Cary
Herz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) BERNALILLO, N.M. -- March 15, 1999 -- INDIANS-RESORTS-1,
3-15 -- The ``Star Casino'' on the Santa Ana Pueblo reservation
boasts a 27-hole championship course, and it plans to expand. After
using casino gambling over the past several years to help reverse
their fortunes, Native-American tribes are beginning to build
entire leisure industries on their reservations. But concern has
been growing among tribal members that culture and sovereignty are
being pushed aside. (Cary Herz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- March 15, 1999 -- NY-RANGEL-PROFILE, 3-15 --
Rep. Charles B. Rangel was arrested with former Mayor David N.
Dinkins on Monday for disorderly conduct at a demonstration outside
police headquarters in lower Manhattan. ``One officer gave me a
cough drop when I was handcuffed,'' says Rangel, whose publicity
stunt was just another firecracker in the noisy spectacle of his
life in recent months. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- March 15, 1999 -- NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING, 3-15
-- Former Mayor David Dinkins being taken in a van to police
headquarters Monday. Dinkins was one of several high-profile
protesters - including Reps. Charles Rangel and Gregory Meeks and
two members of the City Council - arrested for decrying the fatal
police shooting of Amadou Diallo. (Angel Franco/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) PRUGOVAC, Yugoslavia -- March 15, 1999 -- KOSOVO-3, 3-15
-- Yugoslav army tanks and vehicles close off the main road during
an attack of Prugovac after a Serb convoy received sniper fire. The
Serb infantry swept through the area with house-to-house searchs
and automatic weapons fire. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BIJALIC, Yugoslavia -- March 15, 1999 -- KOSOVO-2, 3-15
-- The village of Bijalic burns during a Yugoslav army attack at
twilight involving artillery, mortars, and automatic weapons. Serb
forces have burned several villages in this area in recent days.
(Alan Chin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) STANOVAC, Yugoslavia -- March 15, 1999 -- KOSOVO-1, 3-15
-- Two women wait on the side of the main road for a bus after
fleeing Stanovac with several other women. Small arms fire could be
heard coming from the direction of the village. (Alan Chin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MIAMI -- March 15, 1999 -- MEXICO-CORRUPTION, 3-15 --
Bill Gately, a former senior customs agent who led an undercover
probe into Colombian money laundering, feels the U.S. government
dropped the ball. ``Why are we sitting on this kind of
information?'' he wonders. ``It's either because we're lazy, we're
stupid, or the political will doesn't exist to engage in the kind
of investigation where our law-enforcement efforts might damage our
foreign policy.'' (Laura Kleinhenz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SAN FRANCISCO -- March 15, 1999 -- ETRADE-MARKETPLACE,
3-15 -- Christos M. Cotsakos, E-Trade's chief executive. A computer
glitch halted trading for three days in February, but E-Trade,
while acknowledging that it had to prevent such problems from
recurring, is unashamed. ``The degree to which we have been
recognized as a leader in this space is unequaled,'' says Cotsakos.
``And that is something we should be very proud of.'' (Ann
Dowie/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) PARIS -- March 15, 1999 -- PARIS-FASHION-II-2, 03-15 --
Black leather zip front jacket with a mesh knit sweater and black
beaded skirt by Narcisco Rodriguez for Loewe, right; Tweed sweater
and tweed skirt in guinea feathers designed by Michael Kors for
Celine. (Jean-Luce Hure/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) PARIS -- March 15, 1999 -- PARIS-FASHION-II-1, 03-15 --
Gold halter top with flannel trousers and animal print belt bag,
right; pale-pink skirt with ruffled-edge and sleeveless knit top.
Both are from Valentino. (Jean-Luce Hure/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PARIS -- March 15, 1999 -- PARIS-FASHION-I-3, 03-15 --
The preponderance of wools etched in white appliqued tribal
markings looks heavy over highly slit skirts in John Galliano's
fall collection. Galliano knows how to make a woman look seductive,
but there are some obvious conceptual stumbling blocks with this
collection. (Jean-Luce Hure/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PARIS -- March 15, 1999 -- PARIS-FASHION-I-2, 03-15 --
Karl Lagerfeld's molded leather vest and ruffled suit for Chanel,
left; his welted shearling jacket and wide-legged tweed pants.
Chanel, while no longer white-hot, remains relevant and prestigious
thanks to Lagerfeld. (Jean-Luce Hure/New York Times Photos) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PARIS -- March 15, 1999 -- PARIS-FASHION-I-1, 03-15 --
Jeremy Scott is reviving the Mugler-Montana power look. This tutu
skirt in rolled fabric from his pink collection. (Jean-Luce
Hure/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SEATTLE -- March 15, 1999 -- SEATTLE-THEATER-3, 3-15 --
The Seattle Repertory Theater's new 286-seat house. The Seattle Rep
has expanded its multicultural programming and started
collaborations with local institutions like the Seattle Asian Art
Museum and the Wing Luke Asian Museum. (Dan Lamont/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SEATTLE -- March 15, 1999 -- SEATTLE-THEATER-2, 3-15 --
Sharon Ott, artistic director of Seattle Rep, who arrived a year
and a half ago from the Berkeley Repertory Theater. ``I'm an
artistic director because I'm interested in what theaters do in a
community,'' says Ms. Ott, 49. ``If I wasn't, I'd just be a
director.'' (Dan Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SEATTLE -- March 15, 1999 -- SEATTLE-THEATER-1, 3-15 --
A Contemporary Theater has offered a home to new plays since 1965.
It is one of three major nonprofit theaters in Seattle, each with
more than 10,000 subscribers and budgets exceeding $3 million. (Rex
Rystedt/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BAYSHORE, N.Y. -- March 15, 1999 -- TV-IRISH-REVIEW,
3-15 -- Frank McCourt is featured on ``The McCourts of New York.''
For those who have not read the books or seen ``The McCourts of
Limerick,'' Conor McCourt's earlier film about the brothers' youth,
the documentary will introduce these sons of the long-suffering
Angela McCourt, a woman burdened by a heartless husband and haunted
by the death of an infant daughter. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 15, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-TORRE, 3-15 --
At Legends Field in Tampa, Yankees manager Joe Torre talks about
his ordeal with cancer at a press conference Monday in the
visitor's clubhouse. Torre says he doesn't know how long he will be
out of action, but that being around in the future for his
3-year-old daughter is what counts most. (Jon Adams/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- March 15, 1999 -- GUNS-SAFETY, 3-15 -- For
decades, the nation's biggest gun maker, Smith &AMP; Wesson, has
incorporated a magazine safety in virtually every semiautomatic
pistol it sold to the public. Other companies have never used one.
(Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- March 15, 1999 -- BOOKS-COWBOY16-COX, -3-15
-- Sara Davidson, author of the best-selling novel, ``Loose
Change,'' poses with her new book, ``Cowboy: A Love Story.'' The
book is based on her experience falling in love with a cowboy she
calls ``Zach'' while writing a piece for the New York Times
Magazine on cowboy poetry. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- March 15, 1999 -- SCI-OLDER-COLUMN-BOS, 3-15 --
Nursing homes are required by law to discard down a toilet all
unused medication, even if it is sealed in foil, when a patient is
taken off medication, is transfered or dies. Legislators around the
country are considering proposals to cut back on the wasteful
policy. (Joanne Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HAMPTON, Va. -- March 15, 1999 -- MCKINNEY-SPEAKS-BOS,
3-15 -- Twin brothers Gene Mckinney, left, and James Mckinney, at
James' home in Hampton; they are both former sergeant majors in the
army. Gene faced court martial charges in 1998 for sexual
harrassment, and was aquitted on all charges but one. (John
Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- March 15, 1999 -- SCI-DEEP-SEA, 3-15 -- Shrimp
illuminated by the soft glow an undersea chimney in the
Mid-Atlantic Ridge hydrothermic vent field. Human explorers of
these dark ecosystems, working in submersibles equipped with banks
of strong floodlights, may inadvertently be blinding the shrimp.
(Woods Hole Oceanographic Institute/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MOFFET FIELD, Calif. -- March 15, 1999 --
SCI-WRIGHT-FLIGHT-2, 3-15 -- A full-scale replica of the Wright
Flyer undergoing tests in a NASA wind tunnel at the Ames Research
Center in Moffet Field. Engineers here are trying to learn why this
plane succeeded after so many others had failed, while assisting a
group of airplane buffs who want to build and fly a replica of the
Wright Flyer in four years to commemorate the 100th anniversary of
the historic event. (NASA Ames Research Center/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MOFFET FIELD, Calif. -- March 15, 1999 --
SCI-WRIGHT-FLIGHT, 3-15 -- Workers preparing a full-scale replica
of the Wright Flyer, which is undergoing tests in a NASA wind
tunnel at the Ames Research Center to learn why this plane
succeeded after so many others had failed. The original aircraft
made history in 1903 at Kitty Hawk, N.C. (NASA Ames Research
Center/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. -- March 15, 1999 --
SCI-FITNESS-MINIPOOLS, 3-15 -- Flumes, like this one used to train
Olympic swimmers in Colorado Springs, create a steady current that
allows the athlete, patient or exercise enthusiast to swim in
place. Mini-pools are playing an increasingly important role in the
training world of class athletes, whose performance can be closely
monitored in the tanks. (USOC/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
