</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MINISTRY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Catholics reach out to gays
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Archdiocese of Cincinnati is starting a
ministry that will reach out to gays and lesbians, their families
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry will ``offer compassionate love and concern of
Jesus Christ and the teachings of the church,'' said Dan Andriacco,
archdiocese spokesman. ``It will be faithful to those teachings and
embrace the universal call to holiness in seeking to include all in
the community of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop Daniel E. Pilarczyk will inaugurate the pastoral care
initiative in the Miami Valley at a prayer service April 14 at St.
Peter Church in Huber Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry may consist of prayer groups, days of prayer and
reflection, providing resources or other support. It also will work
to remedy discrimination against gays and lesbians. The archdiocese
has no data on the number of gay and lesbian Catholics registered
at Miami Valley churches.
</P>
<P>
   The head of one gay and lesbian advocacy group expressed concern
that the ministry might be an attempt to convert homosexuals to a
heterosexual lifestyle, similar to some controversial Protestant
ministries. The Catholic Church does not view homosexuality as a
choice, according to the 1997 U.S. Catholic Bishops pastoral letter
Always Our Children.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as this being a conversion effort, I have talked to
</P>
<P>
   the archdiocese and that approach would fly in the face of the
pastoral letter, which says that homosexuality is not a choice,''
said Ann Wilger, regional director of Parents, Families and Friends
of Lesbians and Gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a group within the Catholic Church called Courage
which feels that people can be converted, but I have talked with
the archdiocese and I've been told that it has not modeled this
ministry after Courage,'' Wilger said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Margaret Black, director of the Archdiocese Family Life
Office, which would oversee the Catholic Ministry with Gays and
Lesbians, ``I've been on the telephone all morning talking to
people who are asking tough questions: 'Is the ministry going to
try to convert people?' 'Do we have a hidden political agenda?' ``
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the purpose,'' Black said. ``We're here to nurture
them and to help them from a spiritual sense to understand what is
God's will for them, and to help them to fulfill that will.''
</P>
<P>
   Andriacco said the ministry was formed in response to sessions
that the archdiocese sponsored in 1998, in which Auxiliary Bishop
Carl K. Moeddel met with parents of gays and lesbians to hear their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Those sessions followed the 1997 pastoral letter which
reconfirmed the church's teaching that homosexual acts are a sin,
but urged the church to treat gays and lesbians with compassion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ministry is not outside the teaching of the church about
homosexual acts, but that's not its purpose,'' Andriacco said
Monday. ``Its purpose is the other area of church teaching, which
is that they have to be accepted and respected with sensitivity and
love.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlise Lyles writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: charliselyles(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
