</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-PROTECTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE RESIDENTS FACE ECONOMIC CONSEQUENCES OF SAVING THREATENED
SALMON
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: 2nd take is scheduled to move by 10:15 p.m. ET) 
(sw) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Federal officials will formally declare on Tuesday
that nine wild salmon species in the Pacific Northwest are
threatened with extinction, the first listing under the 26-year-old
Endangered Species Act that affects an entire urban region,
</P>
<P>
   But while that stark announcement deals with fish, it is people
_ especially the three million of them who live in the greater
Seattle area _ who will have to face the consequences of halting
the decline of these once mighty salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   They will almost surely pay more in taxes, to acquire land
around waterways and to buy out floodplains so that rivers can
reclaim areas where the salmon once spawned. They are already being
urged by their local leaders to stop using fertilizers and
pesticides, voluntary efforts that may eventually become mandatory,
county officials said on Monday. They will likely face sharp new
restrictions on building, especially near streams and other
waterways.
</P>
<P>
   And at the heart of all these measures will be these questions:
Will people decide that these are all steps toward a better quality
of life in a region already consumed with worry that its lavish
natural splendor is under attack? Will they find, as Mayor Paul
Schell of Seattle likes to put it, that ``in working together to
save the salmon, it may turn out that the salmon saves us''? Or
will the listing, which in many ways dwarfs the impact of the 1990
listing of the northern spotted owl that set off its own
environmental controversy, spawn an angry backlash against the
Endangered Species Act?
</P>
<P>
   The salmon listing on Tuesday is a bombshell, though not an
unexpected one. Officials from Gov. Gary Locke on down have been
formulating plans for months in anticipation of the announcement,
and now they will be forthcoming. Under the Act, governments and
even private citizens can face criminal penalties unless steps are
taken to protect the affected species. But so far, unlike the
spotted-owl fight, in which many leaders in logging and timber
towns bitterly opposed the listing and even mocked the owl, there
has been little opposition to the proposed listing. And no one is
belittling the salmon, a revered icon of the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is recovery of the salmon,'' said Ron Sims, the King
County executive, who oversees an area that includes the city of
Seattle and who has repeatedly said that he believes residents here
are willing to pay more in taxes and take other steps to protect
the fish. ``However, our ultimate purpose is to restore our
environment so that we may provide for the co-existence of people
and fish in the Pacific Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials on Monday said they believed that salmon
restoration could amount to ``life by a thousand stitches instead
of death by a thousand cuts.'' But the devil will be in the
details, and some political and business leaders have already said
that some of the contemplated steps are far too Draconian to pass
public muster.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
