<HEADER>
A1621 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CALIPARI-BOS &LR;      03-15 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CALIPARI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIPARI FIRED AS NETS COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The whole scene was like something out of Mario Puzo. The Nets
team bus, with its players and assistant coaches, went one way.
John Calipari and his boss went the other way in a limo, the
luggage in the trunk, his future in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   That was Sunday, shortly after the Nets had lost for the 17th
time in 20 games, a depressing, humiliating 102-76 loss to Miami
aired for all to see on NBC and for the Nets' suits to see in
person at Miami Arena. It turned out to be Calipari's last game as
New Jersey head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Nets were ready to leave for practice at the
University of Toronto, still not knowing for sure who would be
calling the shots for Tuesday's game with the Raptors. They soon
found out. Calipari, who had flown in earlier in the day, addressed
the players and wished them well. It was over.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Cal's 2 1/2-year stewardship of the Nets is finished. He
compiled a 72-112 record. Former Celtics assistant Don Casey, who's
been at Cal's side through good and (mostly) bad in New Jersey,
will run the club on an interim basis.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after meeting with the players, Calipari, team owner
Lewis Katz, and team president Michael Rowe met reporters in an
atmosphere of almost gallows humor. While Rowe noted that Calipari
has accepted full responsibility, Calipari quickly quipped, ``I'd
like to share some of it.'' Rowe added, ``(Calipari) has been a man
of his word and his character throughout has not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz all but called the decision a mercy killing in the meeting,
saying, ``I kept hoping against hope something would change. But I
watched every game and saw the pain and the misery and realized it
was not the fair thing to keep the train rolling. It didn't look to
me like it was going to turn around. I'm not talking about winning.
I'm talking about being competitive. When do you say, `Enough is
enough'?''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari has been told he can stick around in some sort of
advisory capacity and said he would help in any way. But he's a
coach, and expect him to look to those ranks for future employment.
He said Monday that he came in with a five-year plan and ``I felt
we could move this thing to where we needed to be in five years. In
a selfish way, I want them to turn it around and win and show they
can be what I believe they can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper reports out of New York and New Jersey had the Nets
interested in Phil Jackson, a former Jersey player, assistant
coach, and radiohead. He also had some success with the Bulls.
Jackson's agent, Todd Musberger, did not return a phone call
Monday. The Nets said they have not contacted Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Calipari's dismissal does not qualify as a stunner.
When you have promise and hope and start out 3-17, someone, usually
the coach, has to pay. The players were passive, almost waiting for
the ax to fall. Newcomer Stephon Marbury ripped into the club's
defensive schemes after the Miami fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has lost seven straight and 12 of 13, the sole
victory being its last-second win over the Celtics eight days ago.
Since then, they were embarrassed at home by Charlotte and
bludgeoned on the road by the Bulls. As the losses continued,
Calipari's firing soon became a question of `when' rather than
`if.' The conspicuous presence of New Jersey's management team on
Sunday in Miami only added to the sense of doom.
</P>
<P>
   Big things were expected from the Nets this season. They
finished strong last year, making the playoffs, and playing three
tough games with the Bulls. Michael Jordan, for one, urged Calipari
to keep the team intact because good times were around the corner.
ESPN predicted a Pacers-Nets Eastern Conference final. No one
envisioned a total collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But injuries, mainly a sprained ankle to point guard Sam
Cassell, crippled the team. Its shooting touch disappeared.
Calipari seemed to turn inwards as the losses piled up. Cassell,
widely seen as Calipari's pet, eventually was traded in the deal
for Marbury and once the deal went down, there were reports that
Calipari soon would be dismissed. But ownership waited four more
days before pulling the plug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new beginning,'' said Nets general manager John Nash.
``Hopefully, we can turn it around and get some wins. This has been
a very tough four days for all of us, from the trading deadline, to
the re-signing of (Kerry) Kittles to the decision to replace Cal.
We're all exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Calipari had two years and $6 million remaining on his
five-year, $15 million contract. There are some attractive college
vacancies: Notre Dame, Georgia, San Diego State, and Iowa come to
mind. He made his name, of course, in the college ranks at
Massachusetts, but left in June 1996 as reports of improprieties
started to surface. The school eventually returned its share from
the 1996 Final Four after Marcus Camby admitted to taking money
from an agent while still on the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
