<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-II-ART-NYT &LR;      03-15 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-II-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAULTIER AND A MISSOURIAN ARE OVER THE TOP
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036.) 
(fb) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The question of why people come here for fashion, rather
than mere clothes, was answered this weekend by two starkly
different shows, one by Jean Paul Gaultier, who sent his audience
screaming ``Ooh-la-la'' toward the new millennium, and the other by
Jeremy Scott, whose all-pink revue literally sent his howling into
the night, but wondering, What if he is right? What if this
funny-looking youngster from Missouri is talented after all?
</P>
<P>
   Gaultier's show, played out on a long runway with an digital
millennium clock blinking in the background, was wildly inventive.
This is Gaultier's year, what with his strong haute couture showing
in January and Friday night's reverent ready-to-wear ode to the
power of love. That was his message for fall as a Noah's ark of
couples came trooping down the runway _ now dressed in Eskimo
regalia, now in swanky his-and-her glittery knits and tartan kilts.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that there were no futuristic cliches made Gaultier's
show all the more potent. Male couples came out in pinstriped suits
with the trouser legs creased four ways, as if to form a box, while
women wore jumpsuits that could be transformed into long dresses
with the pull of a zipper. ``Ingenious'' describes this collection,
particularly Gaultier's hilarious take on motocross leathers
(superwide). The show ended with a traditional bridal couple: old
and gray, but still in love.
</P>
<P>
   What can one say about Scott's pink farce except that it brought
to mind a scene from that Hollywood romp ``What a Way to Go,''
starring Shirley MacLaine, in which a guy named Pinky spends every
last dime to paint everything pink? Scott, whose previous
collections have also been devoted to one color, must be of the
same mind. There were shorts and trouser suits with enormous
``Dynasty''-era shoulder pads, and some evening ensembles, if one
can call them that, with skirts that looked as if they had been
blown up to float in a children's pool.
</P>
<P>
   With his buzzed hair and sly smile full of gold-capped teeth,
Scott, who is 24, seriously bugs people, but in a world easily
intimidated by raw talent, nobody can write him off just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The theme at Michael Kors' Celine show on Friday was ``disco
lodge'' _ as in luxe ski sweaters, racy white satin chinos, rabbit
fur and leather trench coats of the '60s French film-star genre,
all warmed by T-shirts encrusted with ruby-red stones. It was
Charlotte Rampling meets Ursula Andress, with Diana Ross belting
out the high notes. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being impeccably styled with a casual elegance that
fulfills some people's idea of modern taste, Kors' collection was
invariably practical. No space-age hokum or divinely trashy rocker
gear for him. He avoided all the high-tech futuristic business by
sticking to the classic fabrics he knows best, like double-faced
cashmere and good old cotton duck, all simply executed as narrow
pants and duffel coats. A hooded zip-front jumper, a kind of
dawn-patrol dress in tan cotton, evoked some of fashion's
utilitarian madness, but without its muffled sex appeal, while a
coat doused with tiny gray and brown feathers looked as if the
model had been blown through a henhouse, except that the feathers
were all arranged in an understated tweed pattern. Marvelous.
</P>
<P>
   While almost anyone can understand this kind of jet-set allure,
there is a built-in problem when European houses like Celine and
Loewe hire American designers to modernize their images: no matter
how far they spread the glamour, the clothes still look like
American sportswear. This was the case at Narciso Rodriguez's show
for Loewe on Saturday. Rodriguez started out impressively enough
with minimalist black leather separates _ sleeveless tops, sheaths
and so forth _ all cut gloriously close to the body. There were
sheared raccoon jackets and pullovers worn with trousers and
sequined tops and colored a garnet hue that looked almost brown;
suede camisoles with filigreed cutouts, and other separates
lathered with stones in semiprecious shades of amethyst and rose
quartz.
</P>
<P>
   But any way Rodriguez sliced it, the underlying message of this
slick collection was still American sportswear basics. Of course,
one could say that Rodriguez, a former Calvin Klein assistant who
went on to distinguish himself at Cerruti, was providing a
venerable Spanish leather goods house with some of his commercial
know-how. But in a season of strong individual separates, that
logic doesn't wash. Anyway, it's not why one comes to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Herve Leger cuts a mean dress, as everyone knows, but apart from
a bondage-wrapped bustier that looked like giddy censor bars
dancing over the bosom, there was little new here. Cerruti, by
contrast, drew a firm line for modern clothes without futuristic or
arty effects. The designer, Peter Speliopoulos, presented one of
the smartest collections of the week, with glossy nylon shifts
embroidered in a grid of squares, pony skin coats and colors in
corrosive tones of orange and green.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one Valentino, the perennially tanned Roman
designer who caters to the world's rich and titled. Yet this season
the ever-chic Valentino seemed to abandon the sense of hidden
luxury that had made his January haute couture collection look so
modern for a style that was almost ... well, '80s over-the-top
passe would not be putting too fine a point on it. Out came
skintight jeans with flaming red stitching, animal-print pouches
dangling from belts and metallic halter tops. There were some
graceful Valentino touches, like gowns in gray and cloud pink
chiffon, but one had the impression that Donatella Versace had
sneaked into the designer's workrooms, played around with the
clothes, and, what the heck, someone at Valentino actually liked
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0532 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1633 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-DEAL &LR;      03-15 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-DEAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET BOSTON CORP.: HOW THE DEAL GOT DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was a negotiation conducted over secret breakfast
meetings and cheeseburger dinners with California pinot noir at
Terry Murray's tony but understated Four Seasons apartment across
from the Public Garden.
</P>
<P>
   For five months, starting last November, Murray, the head of
Fleet Financial Group, and Chad Gifford, his counterpart at
BankBoston, met often in private to see if they could agree on a
deal that had eluded them before: the merger of their banks.
</P>
<P>
   The breakfasts and dinners at Murray's apartment opened the door
to dozens of other face-to-face sessions between the two executives
and key lieutenants. They met at Florida resorts and a Waltham
hotel and, finally, at a New York law office on Sunday where they
ironed out sticking points, including a provision that would make
it difficult for the new bank to remove Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 p.m., Murray and Gifford shook hands, agreeing that Fleet
would acquire its longtime rival BankBoston for $16 billion. Then
they telephoned the news to Gifford's ailing, 87-year-old father, a
Rhode Island banker who, according to legend, once turned the young
Murray down for a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point,'' said a senior executive close to the
negotiations, ``we were absolutely married.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's moves to buy BankBoston began last November at the
Marriot Copley Place in Boston, where Gifford chaired a
million-dollar fundraiser for the American Ireland Fund, a favorite
local cause, according to sources who provided a detailed account
of the meetings leading up to a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Murray waded through 1,500 guests to approach Gifford to suggest
the two meet soon for an informal lunch. It was a difficult time
for Gifford, whose patrician, 215-year-old bank had been battered
by a downturn in emerging markets, especially in Latin America,
where the bank has extensive operations.
</P>
<P>
   A week after the event, Gifford had lunch at Murray's
antique-filled apartment. The two men could not risk being seen
together even in their corporate dining rooms.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, the two rivals, who had discussed merging with
each other as far back as late 1994 and as recently as last April,
spoke only about broad industry issues like consolidation and
deregulation. Murray made no proposal to buy BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   The New Year came and went. BankBoston disappointed investors by
reporting more quarterly losses, while Fleet charged ahead, earning
plaudits from Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-January, Gifford and seven top BankBoston executives
traveled to Vanderbilt Hall in Newport, R.I. to discuss the
company's strategic alternatives. Soon Murray began making the kind
of aggressive, masterful moves he is known for.
</P>
<P>
   First he invited Gifford back over to his apartment for a
one-on-one dinner of cheeseburgers, French fries, and two bottles
of wine from Murray's cellar. It was the first time the two men had
met since their brief lunch two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, sources said, Gifford was interested in at least
exploring the possibility of merging with his rival.
</P>
<P>
   Discussions intensified, with in-house acquisition specialists
at both banks producing reams of charts and graphs showing what a
deal might mean for both companies. In early February, key
strategists _ Peter Manning of BankBoston and Jay Sarles of Fleet _
signed a confidentiality agreement. The document stipulated that
both banks would keep strategic corporate information confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Then Murray began playing the host again.
</P>
<P>
   During the first two weeks of February, over four breakfasts at
his apartment, the Fleet chief served Gifford and a handful of key
executives from both banks croissants, coffee and juice, along with
a hefty dose of rhetoric on why the two companies should merge. The
gatherings, which began around 8:30 a.m., lasted until lunch time.
At one meeting, Sarles and Manning joined Gifford and Murray, and
the four men, all golfers, agreed to play a round soon at Augusta
National, the site of the Masters golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Over a three-day weekend in late February, BankBoston's
executives, as well as 16 board directors and spouses, convened at
Fisher Island, an exclusive _ and reclusive _ Florida resort.
BankBoston executives from Argentina and Brazil were also present.
In meetings lasting five hours a day, according to a person who
attended the sessions, executives and directors pondered
BankBoston's future. During breaks, some executives played golf at
the Indian Creek and Deering Bay country clubs, while others toured
local mansions.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, ``the BankBoston board was still thinking it
could remain independent,'' one participant said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The executives would soon find themselves in less plush
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   On March 3, at the Wyndham Hotel in Waltham, top executives from
BankBoston _ including president Henrique Meirelles, regional bank
head Brad Warner, corporate bank head Paul Hogan, and chief
financial officer Susannah Swihart _ met with their Fleet
counterparts. The Fleet team included president Bob Higgins, chief
financial officer Gene McQuade, vice chairman Jay Sarles and
strategic planning head Brian Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a Motel-6,'' said one source who attended the
meeting. ``It was the last place anybody would expect us to be. And
that's why we went there.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Wyndham, Murray and Gifford were absent _ and for a
reason. ``We wanted to see if we liked each other and could work
together, and we decided we did and could,'' one source said.
</P>
<P>
   From March 7-9, Fleet's board and key executives met in Palm
Beach, Fla. Unlike BankBoston's board, which still had qualms about
losing independence, Fleet's was keen to do a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, BankBoston decided to step up talks with Fleet and
sent a team of 50 executives, in-house acquisitions specialists and
lawyers to New York, where Fleet's lawyers were ready to begin
crafting a deal. BankBoston also sent its corporate jet to Palm
Beach to pick up four Fleet executives and fly them to South
America, where they spent two days touring the bank's offices in
Brazil and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   With BankBoston's jet in service, Fleet offered its own jet to
fly Gifford and other BankBoston executives to New York on March
11. The team checked into the Four Seasons Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   That day, for the first time, Murray and Gifford called in their
investment bankers _ Goldman, Sachs and Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette for Fleet, and Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter for BankBoston. A deal seemed imminent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the next several days, teams from the two banks met in
all-night sessions to iron out several key sticking points before
drafting a formal agreement.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gifford was worried about what had happened to
David Coulter, the BankAmerica chief who sold his company to
NationsBank but was eventually pushed aside. Gifford, worried about
such a scenario, insisted on a guarantee that he would take over
the reins of combined Fleet-BankBoston when Murray retired in 2001.
In an unsual move, Murray agreed to amend Fleet's charter so that
any attempt by the board of directors to remove Gifford would
require an 80 percent supermajority.
</P>
<P>
   Murray and Gifford also agreed to a board structure that would
make it dificult to attain that majority. The board of the merged
company has 22 members _ 12 from Fleet and 10 from BankBoston. Even
if all 12 Fleet members against Gifford, it would still take around
5 BankBoston members to remove him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hard-wired Chad into the contract,'' one source said.
``He can't be Coulterized.
</P>
<P>
   Late on March 12, Murray and Gifford, along with an army of
lawyers and accountants, began discussing price for the deal,
finally agreeing on $53 per BankBoston share. That amount
represented a 13 percent premium over the closing price of the
bank's stock that day. Both sides met in the law offices of Fleet's
law firm, Wachtell Lipton Rosen &AMP; Katz, to begin drafting a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   By 6 a.m Sunday morning, after lawyers for both sides had
settled 13 key issues, including executive compensation, a copy of
the merger agreement was delivered to each Fleet and BankBoston
executive's hotel room. Several BankBoston executives read the
draft and headed to St Patrick's for an early Mass, but were turned
away after a bomb scare at the famed New York cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 p.m., in the Wachtell Lipton offices, Gifford and Murray
shook hands on a final deal. Two hours later, Gifford and his team
flew to Boston for a meeting with the BankBoston board, which
approved the deal on Sunday night. Fleet's board also back the
acquisiton that night.
</P>
<P>
   By late Sunday night, Gifford was back in New York, where he met
Murray again at the law offices. The two formally signed the
agreement and then called Gifford's father.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet Boston Corp. was born.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
