<HEADER>
A1635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEECEE-UNIVERSITY-ART     03-15 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-UNIVERSITY-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON MAYOR CREATES FUROR WITH PLAN TO RELOCATE UNIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Taking on an issue that has always exposed the gulf
between haves and have-nots in the nation's capital, Mayor Anthony
Williams on Monday proposed moving the University of the District
of Columbia from its current location in northwest Washington, near
embassies and expensive homes, to Anacostia, the poorest section of
the city.
</P>
<P>
   While Williams suggested that the move would spur economic
development in both locations, the idea sparked instant and
widespread outrage from people who claimed that it reflected an
overwhelming insensitivity to the needs of low-income blacks, who
regard the university as a way out of neighborhoods that have been
ravaged by crime and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is upset about this. It's awful,'' said Lawanda
Johnson, a senior at the school who attended Williams' news
conference Monday to protest the plan. ``People are fighting to get
away from places like Anacostia. Where we go now is a way out. We
don't want to go back to look at crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Many said the proposal would primarily benefit real estate
developers who might buy the current property. Williams disputed
that contention, saying he was committed to keeping the university
open and thriving.
</P>
<P>
   The University of the District of Columbia was created 22 years
ago as the city's version of a state university, and as an
alternative for high school graduates who cannot afford more
expensive private institutions and older students who have
full-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In its early years, the university's curricula expanded to
accommodate almost any subject imaginable, from aviation to gospel
singing, in an effort to help students earn a college degree. But
the city's financial troubles in the early 1990s forced a scaling
back that not only reduced course offerings but fueled speculation
that city leaders would prefer to close the school.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, defenders of the university have contended that
the need for a low-cost institution of higher learning, similar to
those available to state residents, offers city residents the best
chance to overcome generations of poverty. They also say the
university's location has reflected a symbolic assurance that city
leaders regard its students with the same respect accorded those
attending private universities in the city, like George Washington,
Georgetown, American, Catholic and Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning here for mayor last year, his first bid for elective
office after several years as the district's chief financial
officer, Williams supported those perceptions and promised to keep
the University of the District of Columbia as a four-year
institution, even though the undergraduate population fell by
nearly half, to 5,029 this year from 9,179 in 1996, because of
budget cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams' idea of moving the university caught the city by
surprise, angering many who said the proposal reflected a larger
scheme: to marginalize the university for the benefit of real
estate tycoons who could make a fortune developing the property.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Williams said he was committed to
helping the school thrive. But as part of his first budget, he
proposed selling the school and using tax revenues from new
businesses at the current location to support a new campus in
Anacostia, which in turn would spur economic development in a
region of the city that needs it most.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We have to think outside the box,'' Williams said. ``We have
to boost UDC up to a higher level of performance. We have to think
how we can do that in the overall concept of better government.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams brushed aside questions that suggested that his
proposal reflected a political naivete on his part, for wading into
an issue that touched raw nerves involving class and race.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that many district residents had questioned his
political instincts even when he was a mayoral candidate.
Nonetheless, he easily won the Democratic primary last September
and carried every precinct in the city in the November general
election, something his popular predecessor, Marion Barry Jr.,
never did in four terms as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get elected to adjust the air-conditioning,''
Williams said. ``I was elected to make some changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams took a swipe at Barry. ``I think it's important to send
a signal that this administration is ready to wade into areas where
others have feared to tread,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While many other proposals in his budget suggested that other
city agencies face changes, few packed the emotional wallop of the
one concerning the university.
</P>
<P>
   On campus Monday, many students said they were angered by the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, this is nothing more than another attempt to shut us
down,'' said Diallo Sumbry, president of the senior class. ``If you
look at our history, we had our budget cut by 50 percent, then they
wanted to sell the school,''
</P>
<P>
   Lenox Yearwood Jr., the university's director of student life, a
1994 graduate and a former student government president, said: ``It
is racist at the core. They systematically dismantled our budget,
faculty and morale. This is back-door politics at its best.
</P>
<P>
   ``How would Georgetown students feel if we told them to leave
their home?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The same view was shared by university leaders, past and
present. Roger Wilkens, a history professor at George Mason
University in Fairfax, Va., was a member of the University of the
District of Columbia's board of trustees from 1986 to 1991. He
lives in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was disappointed by Williams' proposal, arguing that
young people who have grown up with crime, drugs and shabby housing
need a beacon of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you create a first-rate institution in a city, then you
give parents and teachers the opportunity to say to little kids,
`Look up there on Connecticut Ave. Look at where you can go in
life,''' he said. ``It's a terrific place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
