<HEADER>
A1636 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-HASEGAW-LADN-(SLA     03-15 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HASEGAW-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAYING THE GROUNDWORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Shigetoshi Hasegawa is a major-leaguer now, his
lifelong dream fulfilled. But it took some clever planning for the
onetime Japanese League player to make the jump across the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa, about to begin his third season with the Angels,
didn't want to be the first Japanese League player to attempt to
make the move. If he failed, it might close the door on others who
wanted to try.
</P>
<P>
   So Hasegawa sought out Hideo Nomo, at the time one of Japan's
best pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to come here before he did,'' said Hasegawa. ``I
talked to him and gave him the idea. I thought if he came here and
had success, I could try. Of course, he was the best pitcher in
Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa's plan worked. Nomo was the National League Rookie of
the Year in 1995 with the Dodgers. After Hasegawa pitched his sixth
season with the Orix Blue Wave in 1996, he signed with the Angels
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels don't regret it it all. The right-hander has become a
vital part of their bullpen. With Rich DeLucia, he'll be relied on
to set up closer Troy Percival. Last season, Hasegawa led all
American League relievers with 971/3 innings pitched and eight
victories. His durability has been a big plus, but he's anything
but a power pitcher. He's slight of build, listed at 5-foot-11 and
171 pounds, though he's probably closer to 160. He relies on good
control and outguessing the hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But it took time. Hasegawa struggled in his first year with the
Angels as he learned the hitters and the major-league game in
general. Hasegawa pitched in 50 games in 1997, including seven
starts, and went 3-7 with a 3.93 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first year, he kept pitching down-and-in to left-handed
hitters, because it's a good pitch in Japan,'' Percival said. ``I
asked him about it and he said `Down and in . . good pitch.' I said
`No, lefties here kill that pitch.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Hasegawa made the necessary adjustments. On top of
that, he had hit the weights hard, something Japanese players don't
believe in as strongly as player in the U.S. The result was an
increase in velocity on his fastball from about 87 mph to 91.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand, Shige is very special,'' Percival
said. ``He's very strong mentally. Japanese players have a
reputation for that, but look at the problems (Hideki) Irabu had.
(Hasegawa) doesn't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   The transformation Hasegawa made last year _ becoming one of the
Angels' most reliable relievers _ meant many more opportunities to
pitch. Maybe too many.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' starters completed only three games all season,
fewest in the American League. The bullpen was overworked at times
and Hasegawa was often in the middle of it. Angels manager Terry
Collins said he isn't worried about a carry-over effect on his
bullpen this year, except for possibly Hasegawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one guy we're going to have to wait and see about,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Last season alone probably would not have a negative effect on
Hasegawa, but Collins knows Hasegawa pitched six years in Japan,
all as a starter, compiling 903 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa, though, says he feels fine. And he's well-adjusted to
life not only in the majors but in the U.S. He bought a home in
Newport Beach and lives there year-round with his wife, Erie, and
2-year-old son, Kohto, who goes to preschool and is learning to
speak English.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa also has become just one of the guys in the clubhouse,
which means he gets ribbed as anyone might. And he can dish it out
as well.
</P>
<P>
   In his first season, the movie ``Midway'' was being shown in the
Angels clubhouse one day after Nomo and the Dodgers had beaten the
Angels. During the movie _ about one of the World War II battles
between the U.S. and Japan _ one Angel yelled at Hasegawa, ``How
about that, Shige?'' as U.S. planes bombed a Japanese ship.
</P>
<P>
   To which Hasegawa replied: ``Too bad you couldn't do that to
Nomo yesterday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
