<SLUG> BC-NBC-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC NAMES A NEW PRESIDENT FOR ITS ENTERTAINMENT DIVISION
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ NBC on Monday named Garth Ancier, the former
president for entertainment at the WB network, as its president for
entertainment. The appointment, which had been expected, completes
NBC's plans to reshape its entertainment division under Scott
Sassa, as president of NBC's West Coast division, and Ancier.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa will replace Don Ohlmeyer in that position starting May
10, when Ancier joins NBC. Ohlmeyer, who led NBC to a dominant
position in prime-time ratings over the last five years, will move
into a new role starting in June, Sassa said. Ohlmeyer is expected
to stay at NBC, which is owned by General Electric, through the end
of this year, fulfilling his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ancier and Sassa said Monday that they intended to maintain
NBC's leadership position in television entertainment by focusing
on the identity the network has built over the last two decades.
Ancier called that identity ``the smart network.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancier has deep roots at NBC, where he started his career in
1979. He left NBC in 1986 to become the first programmer for the
Fox network. He worked there until 1989, when he joined Walt Disney
as its top television production executive. After that, he served
for a time as an independent producer, creating the Ricki Lake talk
show for syndication.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa said he and Ancier were longtime friends. ``For a lot of
reasons, he was an easy choice for this job,'' Sassa said.
</P>
<P>
   Ancier said he looked forward to the opportunity to return to
NBC not only because of his previous association with the network
but also because it meant a return to ``a full-service network
after helping start up two niche networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ancier said NBC would remain a broad network, even in the face
of increasing competition, sticking generally with its appeal to
adult viewers younger than 50. ``It certainly will never be as
narrow as the WB or Fox, but in the future it will be impossible
for a network to be all things to all people,'' Ancier said.
</P>
<P>
   Sassa said in January that he hoped to move NBC toward more
family shows and fewer shows set in New York City. Sassa said he
interpreted that directive as meaning NBC needed shows with ``more
nuclear families'' in them. ``Right now virtually every show takes
place in the workplace arena,'' he said. But he argued that NBC did
not necessarily need to be less urban.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have smart writing in a show even if it's not set in
an advertising agency,'' he said. ``Look at `Cheers.' That was set
in Boston, but it was more of a blue-collar show. My sense of NBC
is that they've tried to keep the network a cut above. They give
the audience more credit.''
</P>
<P>
   As for why he would leave WB, which he helped put on the
television map during the last three years with teen-age-oriented
hits like ``Seventh Heaven,'' ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and
``Dawson's Creek,'' Anicer said: ``I just think there's a
difference between a full-service network and a niche network. NBC
has the most powerful distribution system in the business. It's
great to be a broadcaster and have that kind of broad cultural
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, NBC executives on Monday played down an article in
The New Yorker this week that pointed at a possible deal with the
Sony Corp. that would give NBC access to Sony's television studio
while providing Sony with a network outlet for its programs.
</P>
<P>
   Both NBC and Sony executives said that top executives of both
companies met last month in Tokyo but that no deals, or even the
framework for future deals, emerged from that meeting. No talks are
taking place now, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2203EST &QL; 
