<HEADER>
A1642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-PROTECTION-2ND     03-15 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-PROTECTION-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SEATTLE: public muster.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state agriculture commissioner, Jim Jesernig, said recently
that state officials were getting ``beaten up by all sides''
already _ by tribal leaders and environmental groups who believe
that the likely measures will not do enough to protect the fish,
and by irate homebuilders and farmers, some of whom, he said, were
already calling state officials ``jack-booted Nazis'' for trying to
impose new regulations on how they use their land.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon species, including the Puget Sound Chinook, or king,
salmon, have been hurt in all kinds of ways by human development in
recent decades, by pollution and runoff that includes sewage and
chemicals from fertilizers, and by construction that in many cases
has simply closed off ancient waterways. Further inland, their runs
have been dramatically reduced by the huge dams that provide the
region's famously cheap and abundant hydroelectric power, and yet
another looming battle in the whole salmon-restoration issue will
be whether those dams should be modified or even taken down
someday.
</P>
<P>
   For now, many local officials here said they are convinced that
there is a way to help the salmon and help people at the same time,
especially since many people here list ``runaway growth'' or
``sprawl'' as one of their dominant concerns. And they think there
is a way to do it without the kind of legal rancor that has
attended endangered-species listings elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked very hard at many of those cases,'' Tim Ceis,
director of the Endangered Species Act policy coordination office
for King County, said in a briefing on Monday. ``The lawyers were
the ones making the money. Nobody was spending any money on the
fish.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawsuits may be inevitable, from both sides. Washington
state's Building Industry Association, representing developers,
says that the salmon issue is being used to stop growth and that
the likely proposals for building restrictions show that local
regulators have ``lost all common sense.'' With the Seattle
metropolitan area projected to add as many as one million people to
its population total in the next 25 years, some skeptics say the
fish do not stand a chance, no matter what regulations are put in
place now.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups, on the other hand, say that the issue can
be a win-win for the both salmon and human beings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special-interest defenders of the status quo who oppose real
action to save salmon would have you believe the listings will
produce a shattered economy, a Cuba-on-the-Sound,'' said Tim
Stearns, executive director of Save our Wild Salmon, an
environmental group. ``That kind of thinking is laughable, and in
fact, the opposite is true. If our governor and state legislature
get serious about salmon restoration, we would see enormous gains
in our quality of life and real economic benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on Tuesday, by the National Marine Fisheries
Service, will extend Endangered Species Act protections to wild
salmon found in nearly every watershed in Washington state, as well
as in parts of Oregon's Willamette Valley. The endangered fish
include the Puget Sound chinook, the Lower Columbia River chinook,
Upper Columbia spring chinook, Lake Ozette sockeye, Hood Canal
summer chum, Lower Columbia chum and the Mid-Columbia steelhead.
Decisions were delayed for six months on four other salmon runs in
California and Oregon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
