<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHERS STAGE A WALKOUT AT THE GAULTIER SHOW  
 THE NATURAL LOOK  
 GLOVES WITH HEELS 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOTOGRAPHERS PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hundreds of photographers who swooped down on Paris
from around the world to cover the fall 1999 fashion shows left
without film from Jean Paul Gaultier. At Gaultier's show Friday
night, a number of photographers blocked the entrance and shouted
to protest their difficult working conditions. Others refused to
cross the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions had begun building earlier in the week at the Chloe
show, where photographers were made to stand in a sweltering room
on a platform that several of them said was dangerous. The
situation boiled over when the Gaultier house issued credentials to
80 photographers but had room for only 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just glad everyone stuck together,'' said one American
photographer, who insisted that his name not be used for fear of
retaliation, underlining the uneasy relationship between designers
and the photographers who disseminate their work. ``We're
professionals who travel around the world to work, and they make us
wait in the rain and stand for hours without water.''
</P>
<P>
   After the show, Gaultier said backstage: ``I think it's very
wrong when you have worked months and weeks, preparing the show.
They came three times this week to this same place to see other
shows. I'm a victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Journalists will have to make do with images provided by the
company, or they won't run any pictures, a loss to all parties.
</P>
<P>
   Elsa Klensch, a producer and the host of ``Style With Elsa
Klensch'' on CNN, said the situation had changed drastically since
she began covering for the cable news service in 1980. ``When I
first started, there were about three cameras in Milan and 20 at
most in Paris,'' she said. ``There's been an enormous change in the
way fashion's covered, and I don't think the fashion industry has
kept up.''
</P>
<P>
   NATURAL MAKEUP
</P>
<P>
   Women will be happy to hear that the trend toward natural
makeup, which took off for spring, will continue for fall. Loewe,
Chanel, Valentino, Gaultier and Celine all showed little makeup but
for dark ruby or deep red lips and a pale face, perhaps influenced
by all the Elizabethan films.
</P>
<P>
   Blow-dry looks, lightly crimped hair and braids, a mix of the
homey and the exotic, were also popular. ``It's more CBGB than
Studio 54,'' said Narciso Rodriguez, the designer for Loewe. Dick
Page, who did the makeup for Loewe and Celine and for Calvin Klein
in New York, said he achieved the look using Rouge Baiser No. 117,
an old French lipstick found in Paris drugstores. ``The rest of the
face is very smooth and clean,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ONE GLOVE CLAPPING
</P>
<P>
   A passionate advocate for shoes as the root of all fashion,
Benoit Meleard, is the new designer for the Loewe shoe collection.
During show week, Meleard staged a show with his shoes, which can
only be described as weird. They are certainly provocative with
their square box shape and, often, no heel.
</P>
<P>
   His black leather shoes with red buttons down the side are an
ode to Patrick Kelly. His red and black glove _ Meleard does
gloves, too _ with a heel where one of the fingers should be, is a
homage to Michael Jackson in his ``Thriller'' days.
</P>
<P>
   Thrilling though the glove may be, even Isabella Blow, the
fashion editor of the Sunday Times of London magazine and an
epicure of the avante-garde, refused to wear it. She has supported
the talented Meleard by wearing his box shoes, which she swears are
comfortable, and was at his showroom on Sunday to be fitted for
another pair. Meleard was impatient with Blow about the glove. But
it was he against her and Andre Leon Talley, the imposing Vogue
editor, who had also dropped by. ``It's a bit too kitsch for me,''
Blow said, pushing her short blue hair off her face.
</P>
<P>
   At that, all eyebrows in the room shot up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
