<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0539 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1647 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      03-15 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Common Sense to Reign in Choosing a Name for
Robertson  Stephens 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
One of the various and sundry things that annoy me about bank
mergers is having to traffic in their balkanized monikers.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Fleet Financial's $15 billion buyout of Beantown
rival BankBoston yesterday, what in the devil are they going to
call what's left of the former Robertson Stephens? 
Fleet-Financial-BankBoston-Not-Quite-Nations-Bank-Almost-BankAmerica
-Once-Upon-a-Time-Robertson-Stephens Corp.?
</P>
<P>
   Gratefully not.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, cooler chowderheads may prevail. In what might be
construed as an ample dose of old fashioned New England
sensibility, Fleet's brass is expected to call its newly acquired
investment banking boutique ``Robertson Stephens.''
</P>
<P>
   Catchy, eh? How much do you suppose Fleet needed to fork over to
corporate identity titan Landor Associates to come up with that
one?
</P>
<P>
   As much as I applaud this return to simpler times, I think Fleet
shouldn't be so hasty. I respectfully submit that they borrow some
branding moxie from a multimillion-dollar one-man music corporation
in Minneapolis and call their new division ``the San Francisco
investment banking boutique formerly known as Robertson Stephens.''
</P>
<P>
   Just one warped person's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   You have to admit that the firm that Sandy and Paul built has
been through its fair share of deals. Starting with the original
buyout by the old BankAmerica in 1997, Robbie Stephens now will
have been subjected to four takeovers in less than two years. That
kind of frenetic pace is enough to make Gordon Gekko break for
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the 225 people employed by BancBoston
Robertson seemed unfazed by the news, employees at the firm say. As
one would expect, the firm has experienced employee and client
turnover as a result of the distracting mergers.
</P>
<P>
   But Robbie Stephens hasn't fallen victim to churning to the same
extent that the former Montgomery Securities has seen under
NationsBank, investment bankers say. What's more, most of the
bankers and analysts who were unhappy with the mergers have already
left for greener pastures by this point, investment banking sources
say. ``I've been here for every one of these mergers and I'm pretty
numb to it,'' says one BancBoston Robertson Stephens employee.
</P>
<P>
   While BancBoston Robertson Stephens chief executive Michael
McCaffery admits that his firm has suffered from employee turnover,
he was not willing to quantify how much. However, McCaffery says it
is ``less than the industry average.''
</P>
<P>
   ```The transaction is an awesome opportunity for our firm ...
and is an excellent deal for shareholders and for the New England
region,'' McCaffery says.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a good deal for Robbie Stephens employees who have
stuck around, especially top executives. While some of the firm's
equity partners have been bought out twice, the Fleet deal does not
make for a triple-dip. Robbie was a unit of BankBoston and not an
independent entity this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Robbie employees make out OK. A retention pool of
BankBoston stock options worth $100 million is now worth about $150
million. The premium paid by Fleet for BankBoston's shares accounts
for the bump. What's more, those stock options become vested
immediately after Fleet closes its buyout of BankBoston, which is
slated for later this year, says a person familiar with the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in short, Robbie employees get paid more for their
options, plus they get to cash them out sooner, as most shares were
previously slated to become vested in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; REBUTTAL: &LR;  Occasionally, we at Street Smarts hear from subjects of
the column who, well, putting it mildly, have a different
perspective than ours.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, such disparity of opinion and analysis is espoused
with venom and spite. Other times, it is conveyed in a more civil
and constructive tone.
</P>
<P>
   A recent response by Dr. Neil Gesundheit, vice president and
chief medical officer at Vivus, falls under the latter category. In
a thoughtful yet pointed retort, Gesundheit raises two issues with
last week's column that warned investors about the volatility
surrounding Vivus' shares. (Vivus is a Mountain View maker of male
impotence treatments that last week announced it won a patent that
could lead to a treatment for female sexual dysfunction.)
</P>
<P>
   Gesundheit articulated two basic beefs. The first involved a
financial analyst's view that Vivus' patent was ``broad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When a patent protection is described as `broad,' it typically
means that it encompasses a significant amount of intellectual
property. Thus, a `broad' patent is powerful, whereas a `narrow'
patent provides little protection. I believe that you
misinterpreted the word `broad' in your article by implying that it
was easy to circumvent a broad patent. The opposite is true: A
broad patent implies that the inventor has been granted significant
protection under patent law,'' Geshundheit argues.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, the analyst we spoke to, Sergio Traversa of
Mehta Partners in New York, says he meant what he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In broad, I meant it covered a big product area. Not that it
brought broad protection,'' emphasizes Traversa.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, I meant it differently than (Geshundheit),'' Traversa
says. ``I see the patent as vulnerable to attack by large amount of
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The second issue Geshundheit raises has to do with my comment
about Vivus' staying power in the face of Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viagra clearly is, as you have described it, a pop-culture
phenomenon. But the less glamorous story about Viagra is that its
use has been associated with the death of more than 200 patients.
The FDA has documented these events in their numerous safety
updates,'' Geshundheit says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The safety record of Muse (Vivus' rival treatment to Pfizer's
Viagra) is pristine, and what motivates us at our small company is
to make the public aware of the dramatic discrepancy between the
safety records of the two drugs. If your father had impotence,
there is no question about which drug you would want him to take.
We are motivated at Vivus to be true to the Hippocratic oath of
`primum non nocere' (above all, do no harm). That is what drives us
to keep slugging away at the Viagra Goliath,'' Geshundheit states.
</P>
<P>
   Got me there. Perhaps, the reported dangers and health risks of
Viagra should be a bigger drag on Pfizer's shares or should give
Muse a competitive boost. Unfortunately for Vivus shareholders,
that hasn't always been the case. Vivus closed yesterday at $3.75,
up 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
