<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER PEN PAL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ For better or worse, the Dodgers are
trumpeting the pitching of left-handed reliever Onan Masaoka. He
struck out three Houston Astros in two innings Monday afternoon,
including Ken Caminiti and Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Masaoka, that part of the game could be a possible role
for him,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``I wanted to see
how he takes to situations. So far he's scored well. He's passed
some tests. I figured he might get his lunch (Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   That Masaoka is making a serious run for the left-hander's job
in the bullpen is both good and bad news for the Dodgers. It means
someone is finally beginning to distinguish himself in that role,
but it also means the Dodgers might have to count on a 21-year-old
with nothing more than Double-A experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the organization wants him to start in Double-A,''
Johnson said. ``But there's discussion on whether his best role
will be in starting or relieving.''
</P>
<P>
   When spring training began, Masaoka was the least-likely
candidate for the left-hander's job. Instead, the Dodgers brought
in veterans Greg Cadaret, Chris Haney and Pedro Borbon. Cadaret
(five innings, five runs, two earned) hasn't been sharp and Borbon
(four innings, two runs) has been erratic. Haney has allowed one
run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   But Masaoka hasn't allowed a run in three appearances and
opponents are hitting .053 against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's really dominating so it's still up in the air,''
Dodgers pitching coach Charlie Hough said. ``Right now, for me,
Masaoka has the best stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Masaoka is also new to the bullpen, converted from a starter
late last season in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer relieving, just going (to a game) and knowing I have
a chance to pitch,'' Masaoka said. ``I know they're looking for a
left-handed reliever. I like coming out of the bullpen, throwing
hard and going one or two innings.''
</P>
<P>
   This is also the week Johnson will begin setting up his bullpen.
He said he was sure about Jeff Shaw closing and Alan Mills setting
up, but Hough voiced concern over Mel Rojas, struggling with his
mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   __ Starting slow: Dodgers right-hander Darren Dreifort might be
the Dodgers' fifth starter, but he's not feeling good about it yet.
Dreifort threw 75 pitches, allowing two hits and three runs and
walking five in three innings against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he worries about his position, Dreifort said, ``All the
time. If you get complacent there's going to be someone younger
than you, doing better than you, working harder than you. There's
someone who will take your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort is 1-0 with a 5.63 ERA in three spring outings, but he
isn't completely comfortable with starting. A year in the rotation
doesn't offset a career's worth of relieving, and Dreifort is
struggling with how to pace himself in starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I'm still learning,'' he said. ``It's
something I don't really believe, but everyone talks about it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Balks, walks and chalk: Johnson said he'll wait until today
to decide whether catcher Todd Hundley will make his first
Grapefruit League appearance behind the plate. . . . Hough said
Shaw will make his spring debut either Thursday or Friday. Hough is
hoping to get Shaw into six or seven games before the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
