<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0544 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN16-COX     03-15 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Senate sounds like old House
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This year the Georgia Senate and House have undergone
a widely noted role reversal.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, where party hostilities used to crackle, bills
routinely pass with large bipartisan majorities and party leaders
rise, more often than they did before at least, to thank the other
party for its cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   It's the other side of the building, where members of the two
parties used to get along in such chummy fashion, that has become
the partisan arena.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans in the Senate had their first quarrel
over the disputed election last fall that Democrat Sonny Huggins
won in a recount over Republican Jeff Mullis, and have skirmished
throughout this session over issues ranging from committee
assignments to bill sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   This spells trouble for the legislative pay raise bill, which
passed the House last week on a comfortable 118-57 vote. About a
third of the House Republicans voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   In another year, passage by the Senate would only be a victory
lap for the bill, which follows a citizen panel's recommendation to
raise legislators' pay from $11,347 to $16,200 after the next
election. But Lt. Gov. Mark Taylor has warned the bill will have to
have bipartisan support to get anywhere in the Senate, and Minority
Leader Eric Johnson said Monday he can't give an accurate tally of
Republican support for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   With relations as strained as they are in the Senate, it's hard
to see how the bill could get the level of bipartisan support it
received in the House, although Taylor said he thought the part of
the bill granting pay raises to state constitutional officers might
be another story.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has not been shy about his intention to run the Senate in
a different way from his predecessor, Pierre Howard, who shared key
committee assignments with the GOP. ``Cry me a river,'' he said
recently after Republican Sen. Sonny Perdue complained he'd not
been properly recognized as sponsor of a bill.
</P>
<P>
   He said Monday, however, that he thinks he's being ``a very fair
presiding officer,'' and that Republican legislation and budget
projects are moving through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a split within their caucus between those who want to
be more partisan and others who want to be more bipartisan, and
that's for their caucus to work out. They're divided and we're
united,'' Taylor added.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, on the other hand, believes Taylor is unfairly
punishing Senate Republicans for his bitter race last year against
Mitch Skandalakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all defended Mark when specific constituents called us''
over allegations about drug use and other matters that came up in
the campaign, ``but he apparently feels like we should have called
a press conference and blasted our own nominee,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the House-Senate role reversal, House Minority Leader Bob
Irvin thinks it's really a matter of perception. Irvin did credit
new Chairman Calvin Smyre with opening up the Rules Committee
process, allowing more Republican-sponsored bills to get on the
calendar than in years past, but he was skeptical whether the House
had really become less partisan than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House is about like it always was, and the Senate has
become the House,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
