<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, MARCH 16
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NATO-POLAND-SCENE-NYT (moved on Friday, Mar. 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Mar. 12,
about the celebration in Poland on joining NATO misstated the date
of the Warsaw Ghetto uprising, an event commemorated on the Tomb of
the Unknown Soldier in Warsaw, where the NATO ceremony was held. It
was April 1943, not October 1944.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-STRAX-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Mar. 10)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Dr. Philip Strax, sent by the New York Times
News Service on Wednesday, Mar. 10, misstated the date of an
interview in which he explained that a good physical examination of
the breast included instruction in self-examination. It was in
1986, not 1966.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-MENUHIN-NYT (moved on Friday, Mar. 12)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Yehudi Menuhin sent by the New York Times News
Service on Friday, Mar. 12, omitted an honor he received from the
British throne and thus misstated his title. In addition to
granting him a knighthood in 1966, Queen Elizabeth II made him a
life peer in 1993. So he was Lord Menuhin, not Sir Yehudi.
</P>
<P>
   The obituary also misspelled the surname of his first wife. She
was Nola Ruby Nicholas, not Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-SAYAO-NYT (moved on Friday, Mar. 12)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Bidu Sayao sent by the New York Times News
Service on Friday, Mar. 12, misstated her age. She was 96, not 94.
The obituary also omitted Ms. Sayao's most celebrated recording.
The piece, ``Bachiana Brasileira No. 5,'' is a vocalise _ an aria
without words _ transcribed for her by the Brazilian composer
Heitor Villa-Lobos.
</P>
</TEXT>
