<HEADER>
A1657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ORGAN-TRANSPLANT-N     03-15 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ORGAN-TRANSPLANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CHARGES INVOLVING SALE OF BODY PARTS ARE DISMISSED
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal charges against two men accused of conspiring
to sell human organs taken from Chinese prisoners were dismissed on
Monday by a judge who sharply criticized the government for
building its case on an informant she denounced as ``a fraudulent
opportunist.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Deborah A. Batts of the U.S. District Court here said the
informant, Paul Risenhoover, had been seeking to overthrow the
Chinese government and might have entrapped the two defendants. She
said Risenhoover was now refusing to return from abroad to appear
at the trial, which denied the defendants their constitutional
right to cross-examine him.
</P>
<P>
   While Batts did not rule on the merits of the charges against
the defendants, Cheng Yong Wang and Xingqi Fu, she seemed to agree
that Risenhoover had orchestrated much of the illegal activity in
the case, and had pushed the defendants to join the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Risenhoover, Carlyle R. Hatfield, said his client
denied any wrongdoing and had refused to return to testify because
his wife is Chinese, and Risenhoover feared that Chinese officials
might retaliate against her extended family in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Risenhoover is one of the most patriotic people I know,''
Hatfield said. ``This is his country and he loves it very deeply.
His motivations are based on historical precedent and religious
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors in New York would not say Monday night
whether they would appeal the judge's decision, but they defended
their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government believes that its investigation and prosecution
of this case was responsible and well founded,'' said Herbert
Hadad, a spokesman for Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney. ``We
respectfully disagree with the judge's analysis and conclusion, and
we are reviewing her opinion and assessing our options.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution had been widely watched because the charges
appeared to confirm dissidents' allegations of a thriving trade in
China in which kidneys and other organs taken from executed
prisoners are sold for use in transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The case, which suggested that the activity had reached the
United States, had also received attention because it resulted from
a kind of private sting operation run by a prominent human rights
advocate, Harry Wu, who made his findings available to the Federal
Bureau of Investigation, which then conducted its own inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Wu declined to comment on the dismissal of the case because of
the possibility of an appeal, but he reiterated his view that the
organ trade ``is a violation of human rights, and you cannot
dismiss that.''
</P>
<P>
   In her 155-page opinion, Batts also attacked the government's
investigative work, charging that some records had been submitted
to the grand jury with pages missing and that a secretly taped
conversation of a meeting between Wang, an FBI agent and
Risenhoover had been mistranslated by Risenhoover. In what she
called ``the most egregious'' example, the judge quoted an
undercover FBI agent asking Wang whether unclaimed bodies of
Chinese prisoners are ``buried'' or ``sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang replies in Mandarin Chinese that they are buried, not sold,
the judge said. But Risenhoover translates as if Wang has indicated
that the bodies were sold.
</P>
<P>
   Wang has described himself as a former Chinese prosecutor on
Hainan Island, China, and Fu is a Chinese citizen who runs a
laundry in New York. Their lawyers praised the judge's ruling
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
