<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MAGAZINES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. MAGAZINE CURBS ADVANCE IN OTTAWA
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Canadian House of Commons passed legislation on
Monday intended to protect the country's magazine industry from
American competition for advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials from both countries are trying to negotiate a
compromise and prevent a trade war.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which essentially prohibits advertising in Canadian
editions of U.S.-owned magazines, can be amended before it is sent
to the Canadian Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect the bill as it stands now to become the law of
the land,'' said Richard W. Fisher, the deputy U.S. trade
representative, adding that talks with Canadian officials had been
friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The United States contends that the legislation in its current
form violates the North American and world trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the two countries, each other's largest trading
partner, are expected to meet again in Ottawa on March 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
