<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-COACH-575&AMP;AD     03-15 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-COACH-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS JETTISON CALIPARI
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Less than two months ago, John Calipari had every
reason to believe he was on the verge of leading the New Jersey
Nets to their best season in the National Basketball Association
and, in doing so, would solidify his image as a program builder who
could take teams from the bottom to the top.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, after losing the ear of his players somewhere
along the way to an almost unexplainable 3-17 record, it all came
crashing down, with Calipari being dismissed as the Nets' head
coach and executive vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   A drawn-out series of events that strongly hinted at Calipari's
demise came to a conclusion Monday when Lewis Katz, the Nets'
principal owner, officially relieved the third-year coach of his
duties. Calipari, 40, who joined the Nets amid praise and high
expectations on June 7, 1996, has more than two seasons and $6
million left on his contract. He will receive the remainder of the
money owed to him, and in a strange twist, was offered another job
by Katz in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have high regard for John Calipari as a friend and as
someone I have come to respect as a basketball professional,'' Katz
said in explaining the unexpected gesture. ``I offered him a
position as an adviser to myself with specific reference to
basketball-related issues. I hope he will consider this and remain
with the organization in some capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz's offer seemed to be an attempt to save some face for
Calipari, and while it seems unlikely that Calipari will remain
with the Nets in any capacity, he said he had not made a decision
one way or the other. For now, he was left to contemplate the utter
disaster his team became in only 20 games of a shortened NBA
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a part of coaching,'' said Calipari who had a 72-112
record with the Nets. ``When you're 3-17, that falls onto the
coach, and I understand that.'' Don Casey, who has been Calipari's
first assistant for the past two and a half seasons, was named the
Nets' coach on an interim basis. While there is at least a
possibility that Casey could eventually become the permanent head
coach, the club has been pursuing Phil Jackson, who coached the
Chicago Bulls to six championships this decade, for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Casey will coach his first game Tuesday at Toronto, but his
first move as the head man took place Monday night when, following
Katz's orders, he dismissed the remaining members of Calipari's
coaching staff _ the assistants Johnny Davis, Kenny Gattison and
Jack Haley _ as they were boarding the bus to go to a team practice
at the University of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   When the ax finally fell, Calipari and his three unemployed
assistants sat down in the lobby of the Four Seasons Hotel here on
Monday evening, looking battered and stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Calipari and Katz had flown in from New Jersey on the owner's
private jet only an hour earlier, with Calipari then meeting with
his former players in an apparently unemotional session that lasted
only about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal said, `Thank you,' and that's about it,'' said Jayson
Williams, the Nets' outspoken center who often clashed with
Calipari. ``I'm glad that he came up. It's never easy to see
anybody go. A lot of people are going to think that because of me
and Cal's relationship that I had something to do with it. But that
was the total opposite. I don't like to see anybody lose their
livelihood, lose something they love.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A few minutes later, Calipari sat between Katz and the Nets
president Michael Rowe and addressed reporters. It was an unusual
news conference in that Katz and Rowe spoke as if they had done
Calipari a favor by releasing him. They claimed that the constant
losing had dogged Calipari so much that he needed a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that there was any determining factor, but it was
pretty obvious that he was in his misery as he watched the season
slip away when there had been such high expectations when the
season started,'' Katz said. Rowe, whose relationship with Calipari
has been strained from the beginning, said he realized how much of
a toll the disappointing season was taking on Calipari when the
coach wondered out loud a few weeks ago why his players were not
performing better, why his plans were not being followed.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to be polite even as he was being fired, Calipari
accepted their statements of sympathy. But in his own remarks he
made it clear that he was not happy to be losing a chance at
finishing what he had started three seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe that they care about me,'' Calipari said of Katz
and Rowe. ``But I came in with a five-year plan and I have
two-and-a-half years left. We hit a bump in the road, but I wanted
to push forward and get over it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
