<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES LIKELY TO GET 32ND FRANCHISE
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ National Football League owners appear ready to select
Los Angeles as the site for the league's 32nd club, which would be
expected to begin play in 2002. But in a twist, the owners would
hold open bidding for new groups in Los Angeles to toss in their
hats for team ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, a group in Los Angeles led by the real estate
developer Ed Roski and the construction and insurance magnate Eli
Broad wants to obtain a team in Los Angeles to a refurbished Los
Angeles Coliseum. Another group, headed by the Hollywood mogul
Michael Ovitz, wants to put the team in Los Angeles and build a new
stadium in Carson, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But owners here say there are trouble spots in both plans. At
the Coliseum, owners are concerned about the project's being tied
into a mall, the area surrounding the Coliseum, parking and other
infrastructure issues. In Carson, roads and public support are the
chief concerns.
</P>
<P>
   So, the league might award Los Angeles a franchise, take control
of the franchise for six months to a year and then present the
opportunity to the current groups bidding and to any others
interested. According to several owners, there is more interest in
Los Angeles, parties who have arrived late in the game and need a
backdoor to enter. This would be it.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said that some owners were more
concerned with ``what kind of partner they will have,'' and others
think the discussion should end at which group ``makes the highest
bid.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the league also discussed these items on Monday:
the collective bargaining agreement, stadium projects including new
buildings in Denver, Pittsburgh and Philadelphia, NFL properties
and enterprises, and the Internet and its role in the future of the
league.
</P>
<P>
   The league meetings continue on Tuesday with more discussions on
expansion and on the proposed sale of the Washington Redskins to
Howard Milstein. The competition committee and the owners will
begin discussions on instant replay and a vote among the owners
will most likely follow on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Replay has gained another advocate in Bill Walsh, the former
49ers coach and Hall of Famer, who recently rejoined the 49ers'
front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistakes are so high, so costly, why not have a way to correct
it?'' Walsh asked. ``And its going to be easy to facilitate. I
think its going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue agreed, adding that the competition committee, led by
Coach Mike Holmgren of Seattle and General Manager Rich McKay of
Tampa Bay, had indicated to him that the votes ``appeared to be
there'' for instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   A decision could be made on Tuesday concerning the exiled 49ers
owner Eddie DeBartolo. Last year, DeBartolo pleaded guilty to a
felony charge of failing to report an alleged extortion attempt by
former Louisiana Gov. Edwin Edwards in connection with DeBartolo's
bid for a riverboat gambling license.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
