<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-GIRLS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GIRLS' FAMILIES CALL ORDEAL `FIVE WEEKS OF HELL' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTI MUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE JACKSON, Texas _ As police and prosecutors considered
charges against a trio of adults who drove two runaway teen-agers
to Mexico, the families of the girls described their time away as
``five weeks of hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The families of Harmony Olachia and Nicole Conrad, both 14, on
Monday declined to answer questions about the ordeal, citing ``the
sensitive nature of the traumatic experiences the young girls have
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston lawyer Guy Womack, asked to represent the teens and
offer support during their weekend interviews with law enforcement
authorities, said that the girls spent several days in a cave in
Mexico, eating whatever they could find and virtually living off
the land.
</P>
<P>
   The girls remained quiet during a Monday press conference as
Olachia's youth minister, Greg Pickering, read a statement from the
families, saying in part: ``Nicole and Harmony have been through
five weeks of hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls called home hungry and homesick Thursday from Parral,
Mexico. They were flown back to the Houston area Saturday, where
investigators began piecing together the story of what happened.
</P>
<P>
   The pair had left behind handwritten letters telling their
parents that God told them to leave, and their youth minister said
Olachia also told other members of her youth group that she was
going to Mexico. The friends, however, did not think she was
serious, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It all started after the arrival of a longtime family friend to
the Olachia home. Tara Burmeister, also known as Tara Nelson, was a
friend of Harmony Olachia's older sister and grew up in the Lake
Jackson area, the family said. She visited the family at Christmas
with James Paul Nelson, whom she introduced as her husband.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 5, the pair returned to visit unannounced.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the couple started talking to the teens about the
so-called ``Y2K'' computer problem and the potential for the end of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was talked about that the central part of Mexico was
a safe haven,'' said Lake Jackson police Sgt. Harold Haywood.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe James Nelson's uncle, Richard Eugene Brown, was
also staying in the Lake Jackson area that weekend and left with
the couple and the teens.
</P>
<P>
   According to Womack, the five left in a pickup with a camper
attachment, but abandoned the camper as they drove into Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Jackson police were talking with the Brazoria County
district attorney's office late Monday about filing charges of
enticing a child and harboring a runaway against all three adults.
</P>
<P>
   The whereabouts of Brown, 39, James Nelson, 27, and Tara
Burmeister, 21 _ all of whom had addresses in Milton, Fla. _ were
unknown Monday, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The girls' homecoming was a welcome development to authorities,
but the investigation about the initial disappearance as well as
the three adults' roles in that disappearance continued. Police
hope to talk more with the teens later this week.
</P>
<P>
   The families contend Brown escorted the teens to Parral last
week and encouraged them to call their parents after Nelson and
Burmeister said they were going for food and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   The teens also have been interviewed by FBI agents, who continue
to investigate the case to determine whether kidnapping charges
will be lodged.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, city workers Monday were taking down numerous yellow
ribbons tied to trees throughout the streets of Lake Jackson since
the girls' disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   The Brazoswood High freshmen are both soccer players, and their
good health when they left obviously served them well during days
with little or no food, said Womack.
</P>
<P>
   When they stopped Saturday for their first meal back in the
United States, Womack said they ate more pancakes than he had ever
seen consumed in one sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were extremely hungry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
