<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE GURU IS WAITING FOR A CALL
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greetings, basketball fans, from Woodstock, N.Y., sabbatical
retreat, where the snow is fresh and the air is clean, and on a
clear day, you can just about pick up the NBC signal coming out of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I have much use for television, given my meditations as
Big Chief Triangle, which is what the coach of the Knicks took to
calling me a few years ago. Clever little guy, that Gumby, though
he should have listened to the fellow in The New York Times, who
advised him to ease up on Ewing's minutes before he got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Now look at the mess he's in: Peter Vecsey reporting on the
halftime show the other day that a Knicks coaching change would
have been imminent had they lost that night to Charlotte. They
didn't, but, sure as Jerry Garcia's gone, I'm figuring that, as a
student of Knick history, Van Gundy's going unless the Knicks win
big. Which is sure nice to know before I've even agreed to succeed
John Calipari over in Jersey with the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   As a spiritual man, I don't want to come off the intellectual
snob but to quote Paul Valery, ``The best way to make your dreams
come true is to wake up.'' Gumby and Ernie Grunfeld and Dave
Checketts have been in snoozeland for the last two or three years.
Patrick Ewing, hardwood warrior that he is, couldn't lead his team
to the mountaintop five years ago, when we didn't have my man
Michael in Chicago, when Ewing was 31, when Charles Oakley was 30,
when John Starks and Derek Harper and Anthony Mason were all better
fits than the players they have now.
</P>
<P>
   What have those guys been smoking, bloating their team with
contracts like Chris Dudley's? Twenty-eight million for a backup
center? We gave Bill Wennington two pair of Air Jordans and free
family passes, and he was thrilled. Ernie's a great guy and all,
but if you really think about it, the three best players the Knicks
have had in the '90s _ Ewing, Oakley and Starks _ all came from the
'80s, from previous management teams.
</P>
<P>
   What am I saying here? Consider this a koan. (In other words,
figure it out for yourself.)
</P>
<P>
   I don't see these Knicks getting past the second round, if they
get that far, this season, or in any other season, but before
everyone tickets me for New Jersey, let's think out loud. Suppose
Minnesota can't sign Terrell Brandon next summer, and the Knicks
offer a package _ say Latrell Sprewell and Charlie Ward _ in a
sign-and-trade. There's your point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Now I haven't talked to Michael about this, but he always did
fancy the idea of playing in Madison Square Garden. For one year,
maybe two, who knows? Whatever the Knicks couldn't pay him under
the salary cap, Phil Knight could. I must have David Falk's number
somewhere around here. So now we _ I say ``we'' most hypothetically
_ move Allan Houston to the sixth-man role and bring in Dennis on a
one-year deal. He's already bolted the Lakers, proving once again
that I'm the only coach he'll play for.
</P>
<P>
   I admit, this whole scenario is unlikely, but then, maybe we
just start cleaning house, drop this championship-now pipe dream
and begin the heroic process of returning fluid basketball to the
Garden, the game I learned from the master, Red Holzman. Anyway,
leverage is leverage. I've got to consider the Knicks, if only for
the sake of dollars and Zen.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of me being intrigued by the Nets are accurate
because, let's face it, if you're going to be a savior, the
absolute bottom is the best place to begin. After Calipari, the
players will look at me and see Gandhi. Well, they probably don't
know Gandhi, so let's go with Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of commanding respect, I'm afraid Calipari was finished
the night Michael stared him down in front of his bench in our
playoff game in New Jersey last spring. Maybe I should feel guilty
about that, but, what the heck, to quote Thich Nhat Hanh, ``Our own
life is the instrument with which we experiment with the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Failed pro that he is, Calipari will get another college job
and, in all likelihood, I'll take his. This is a fine young
nucleus, though even with Sam Cassell playing his best ball last
season (his numbers, by the way, were better than Stephon
Marbury's), the Nets barely made the playoffs. But I like the idea
of philanthropic owners. I love Keith Van Horn. If Kerry Kittles
cut down on his jumpers, he could be a smaller Pippen. I know all
about the Nets' jinx but, what the heck, as Ursula K. LeGuin said,
``It is good to have an end to journey toward; but it is the
journey that matters, in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, start your bidding. I'm all ears. In the meantime,
the word up here in Woodstock is that Young is joining Crosby,
Stills and Nash on tour. Talk about a team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
