<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS HAVE BLUEPRINT FOR KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As they fight to salvage a dreary season, as they preach
patience to fans whose patience understandably is wearing thin, as
they wait for their recent draft choices to develop (they hope)
into top-flight NHL players, the Los Angeles Kings might gain
inspiration from the team they faced Monday night at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, as a much different Kings team was heading toward
the Stanley Cup finals, the Ottawa Senators were completing a
dismal expansion season.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, the Kings are waiting for a new generation of
prospects to develop, while the Senators are savoring the rewards
of their methodical building program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been very patient,'' Kings coach Larry Robinson said.
``They've stuck to their game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senators have also been smart. They have the second-best
record in the NHL (Dallas is first), but at $21 million they have
the third-lowest payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics are quick to say the Senators became good by being bad
and it is true that several of their players _ centers Alexei
Yashin and Radek Bonk, left wing Marian Hossa and defenseman Chris
Phillips _ are recent high first-round draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senators also have unearthed some gems, such as
third-leading scorer Andreas Dackell (the 136th player chosen in
the 1995 draft), fourth-leading scorer Magnus Arvedson (119th in
1997), free-agent signee Andreas Johansson (five goals in 95 NHL
games before this year but 19 this season), and star right wing
Daniel Alfredsson (133rd pick in 1994). Coach Jacques Martin has
done an outstanding job of molding this group of relative unknowns
into the NHL's most pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappily, Ottawa's success story could be in peril. The
Senators lost $7 million last season and are expected to lose more
than that this year. Owner Rod Bryden is facing a $7.2-million tax
assessment on the team's 3-year-old Corel Centre and had to pay $38
million for the highway off-ramp leading to the building.
</P>
<P>
   Bryden is making noises about selling the team or moving it if
he doesn't get some relief from the Canadian government, a case of
Senators asking for help from politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The Senators have their house in order on the ice. But the
financial realities of the NHL in the 1990s are threatening to
remove the Senators from Ottawa just as the fun is getting started.
</P>
<P>
   __ Too much too soon?: It remains to be seen whether
Philadelphia will regret trading 20-year-old winger Dainius Zubrus,
a former first-round draft choice, to Montreal for right wing Mark
Recchi, 31, who is anxious to sign with the Flyers this summer as
an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like Zubie,'' Flyers general manager Bob Clarke said
following last week's trade. ``You guys saw him in his first year.
He looked like he was going to be great. . . . I think the problem
with Zubie is that he was a young kid who had a pile of money
thrown at him and hockey became second (in his priorities). Only
the fast cars and women caught his attention.''
</P>
<P>
   As an 18-year-old rookie in 1996-97, Zubrus had eight goals and
21 points in 68 games. This season, the native of Russia has only
four goals and nine points. Clarke attributed Zubrus' decline to
laziness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him weigh in at training camp and the guy was 227
pounds,'' Clarke said of Zubrus, who stands 6-foot-3. ``That's 10
pounds heavier than he'd been (last season). I said, `You can't
play at 10 pounds heavier than you were,' and he started talking
about his mother being here now and making dinners. I said, `Push
yourself away from the (expletive) table.' ''
</P>
<P>
   __ Grounded Flyers: Speaking of the former Broad Street Bullies,
they have tied a club record with an 11-game winless streak, and
are 2-11-5 since going 16-1-7 between Dec. 12 and Feb. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 50 percent of the game at the pro level is mental,''
said Flyers chairman Ed Snider. ``And I think this team has had a
complete mental collapse. I don't think we've had a physical
collapse. . . . I've never seen anything like it. To see a team
play so well and then play so poorly _ the same team _ for such
long stretches, I've never seen this happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, on the road to the 1993 Stanley Cup finals, the Kings
enjoyed some amazing highs and endured some distressing lows. That
season, they were 20-8-3 in the first 31 games. They then went
4-17-4 in their next 25. But in the end, they righted themselves
and almost won the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers' questionable defense, however, will make it
difficult for them to match the Kings' turnaround in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   __ Loose pucks: Chicago general manager Bob Murray said his
Flyers counterpart, Bob Clarke, continues to pursue a trade for
defenseman Chris Chelios. But Chelios has a handshake no-trade
agreement with Blackhawks owner Bill Wirtz. . . . If Montreal
misses the playoffs, it will be just the second time since World
War II that the Maple Leafs have made the playoffs in a year when
the Canadiens missed. . . . Phoenix defenseman Teppo Numinen has
been playing with a fractured foot for nearly three weeks. . . .
Colorado goalie Patrick Roy missed scoring a goal last week when he
fired a rink-length shot into Philadelphia's empty net just after
time expired. ``I didn't know how much time I had, but I tried to
get rid of it as quick as I could,'' he said. ``I was very
disappointed to see there was no time left on the clock. I was
wishing they'd stop the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Show me the roster: Actor Cuba Gooding Jr. was leaving the
Forum last week after the Kings-Detroit game when he saw a Red Wing
standing outside the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``How you doing, man?'' Gooding said. ``Good to see you. Great
game out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooding didn't realize he was addressing defenseman Uwe Krupp,
who hasn't played since Christmas because of a back injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
