<HEADER>
A1677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BREAST-FEEDING-N     03-15 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BREAST-FEEDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAST-FEEDING AS MANSLAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Tuesday, March 16: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The death of two-month-old Tyler Walrond from malnutrition in
1997 has been made more tragic by the prosecution of his mother,
Tabitha Walrond, who goes on trial in the Bronx for manslaughter
Wednesday. If convicted, she could face up to 15 years in prison.
Ms. Walrond, who breast-fed her son, is charged with recklessly
causing her baby's death by failing to feed him sufficiently and to
seek medical care when he became sickly. No other signs of abuse
were found.
</P>
<P>
   One can sympathize with Tyler's father, who has urged
prosecutors to go forward in the belief that Ms. Walrond was
reckless in not heeding obvious signs that the baby was starving.
But expert testimony on how difficult it is for many nursing
mothers to recognize the danger signs by themselves and evidence
that the medical system let this young woman down suggest that this
is not a case that should be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucratic tangles and mistaken computer rejections made it
hard for Ms. Walrond, who was covered by Medicaid, to get medical
attention for her baby. Ms. Walrond tried to get the baby seen
through a Medicaid managed-care plan at the Health Insurance Plan
of New York, where she herself had received prenatal care. Although
the infant was entitled to Medicaid automatically at birth, Ms.
Walrond says she was led to believe that coverage would not start
until various documents were received and processed, and she was
turned back in efforts to make an appointment for the infant. Two
different Medicaid cards for Tyler eventually arrived in the mail
after he died.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's death could have been prevented by a more alert medical
care system. His mother should have had follow-up consultations
with lactation nurses, particularly since earlier breast-reduction
surgery and childbirth complications put her at risk for
insufficient breast milk. A routine checkup for the baby should
have been automatically scheduled before discharge from the
hospital but was not. Instead, an inexperienced young mother was
sent home with little advice about the sometimes tricky nature of
breast-feeding or about how to get her child plugged into the
medical system. Punishing that mother with prison is an
inappropriate response to a tragedy that arose out of ignorance
made deadly by fissures in the health care system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
