<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIP-MORRIS-BONUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$3.5 MILLION BONUS FOR CHIEF OF PHILIP MORRIS
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Geoffrey C. Bible, the chairman and chief executive
of Philip Morris, received a $3.5 million bonus from his company's
compensation committee for his participation in talks that led to
the $206 billion settlement between cigarette makers and 46 states,
according to a proxy statement released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said, ``A primary factor in determining the size
of the award was the committee's desire to reward Bible for his
leadership in helping to obtain a nationwide settlement of health
care cost recovery and other claims of the states against the
company's domestic tobacco subsidiary and other domestic tobacco
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The bonus, nearly twice the $1.9 million bonus Bible, 61, got
last year, came in addition to his $1.5 million salary. Yet, his
overall compensation appeared to decline, however, because last
year he was awarded $6 million in stock that is given to company
officers every three years, said a company spokesman, Bob Minkoff.
</P>
<P>
   Other officers of the company also received larger bonuses
because Philip Morris' worst fears were allayed when the settlement
became official last fall. They included Murray H. Bring, the
general counsel, who received a $2.1 million bonus, up from just
over $1 million last year; William H. Webb, the chief operating
officer, whose bonus rose to $1 million from $825,000 last year;
Louis Camilleri, the chief financial officer, whose bonus rose to
$1 million from $725,000 last year, and Michael E. Szymanczyk, the
president of Philip Morris' domestic tobacco company, whose bonus
rose to $750,000 from $525,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reasonable amount, given the alternative that could
have come out of these cases at trial,'' said Martin Feldman, a
tobacco analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, referring to Bible's
bonus. ``While important litigation remains, I think Bible deserves
the bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Philip Morris' compensation committee is John S.
Reed, himself well acquainted with the concept of a generous bonus.
As co-chairman of Citigroup, Reed pocketed a bonus of $7.8 million,
on top of his $1.7 million salary and took home stock options worth
more than $16.9 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
