<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ST.JOHN'S-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S AIMS TO KNOCK MARYLAND OFF ITS BEAT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Duke's Shane Battier knows what it will take for St. John's to
beat Maryland in Knoxville, Tenn., on Thursday in the South
Regional semifinal of the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever controls the tempo will win that game,'' said Battier,
whose Blue Devils beat St. John's in overtime earlier this season
and also gave the Terrapins two of their five losses. ``If it's
going to be up and down, racehorse style, it's Maryland's game. If
St. John's can execute their halfcourt offense, they'll win it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland (28-5), seeded second in the South Regional, St.
John's (27-8), seeded third, will face a team much like itself:
athletic and fast, not too big _ Maryland's tallest starter is the
6-foot-9 forward Terence Morris _ with a preference for running and
pressing.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland has averaged 85.2 points a game; St. John's has
averaged 79.3. Many of Maryland's points come off turnovers created
by a suffocating press. Maryland's opponents average 22 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Gary Williams of Maryland said: ``It's an interesting game
from the fans' point of view to see how much you can press a team
as quick as St. John's, or how much they can press us given our
quickness. A lot depends on how the game goes and how much courage
you have going in as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland, which has been to the Round of 16 in four of the last
six years but has not advanced since 1975, seldom deviates from its
plan. The Terrapins run and press, loft alley-oop passes with great
success and do not switch up the game plan. That presents an
opening for St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm is imbued with confidence that it can make the
adjustments in its game to win, as St. John's did against Samford
and Indiana last week. Although the Red Storm has not played much
half court this season, the team has played well in halfcourt
situations in beating Miami and Indiana and used a zone defense to
dismantle the Hoosiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can run with them,'' forward Ron Artest said
of Maryland. ``If I had to say who was more athletic, Steve Francis
or Erick Barkley, it's Francis. Terence Morris or me, Morris. You
don't want to get up and down with them because their legs are
stronger than ours. But I've never seen them play a solid halfcourt
game. I've seen us play a solid halfcourt game.''
</P>
<P>
   When St. John's Coach Mike Jarvis was at George Washington last
season, his Colonials beat Maryland. The Colonials took Maryland
out of its game by using point guard Shawnta Rogers to break the
press and get his teammates to score off it.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers scored 16 points in the first half and the Terrapins
called off their pressure. In the second half, George Washington
prevailed in a slowed-down, physical, halfcourt battle, and won,
70-66. George Washington had only 15 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   When Jarvis' St. John's squad opposes this season's Terrapins
the teams will be much different. For one, Maryland did not have
Francis, the explosive guard who averages 17.2 points. But for St.
John's, chunks of strategy can still be lifted from last season's
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You run when you can, like always,'' Jarvis said. ``Do you
turn it into a track meet? We're not going to win a track meet. I
feel this team will adjust when it has to.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's, which has not faced fullcourt pressure often this
season, averages 13 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   With George Washington, Jarvis expected Rogers to dribble
through the press, which the coach said was the ideal way of
breaking it. But Jarvis cannot do that this time.
</P>
<P>
   With his so-called two-headed point guard _ the freshman Barkley
and the sophomore Artest _ Jarvis will want his team to pass over
the press.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said the toughest press he faced this season was against
Providence. In two games against the Friars, Barkley had only one
turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erick really can see what's coming at him,'' Artest said.
``Against Connecticut, Richard Hamilton was faking the press and
most guards would have picked up the ball. He kept his dribble.
With me and Erick, it's hard to press us. We can bring it down.
We'll get the ball over, it may take a few seconds, but you've got
to be patient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
