<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UAL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAL SAYS EARNINGS EXCEED EXPECTATIONS OF ANALYSTS
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, said on Monday
that strong domestic sales and the spillover from last month's
sickout by pilots at rival American Airlines would help lift its
earnings above Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, which came on the heels of the industry's
second broad fare increase this year, sent airline stocks soaring.
UAL rose nearly 10 percent, or $6.6875, to $73.75, while the other
major carriers all posted substantial gains.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Dow Jones transportation average rose on UAL's
announcement, setting a new high of 3,404.65, after rising 137.14
points or 4.20%.
</P>
<P>
   UAL said in a government filing that its first-quarter earnings
would likely be $1.35 a share, 23 cents higher than $1.12 expected
by industry analysts surveyed by the First Call Corp. UAL also said
it expected to earn between $10 and $12 a share for the year, above
the First Call consensus of $9.12.
</P>
<P>
   Several Wall Street analysts raised their first-quarter
estimates Monday but some still remained cautious about the outlook
for United as well as for other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Donofrio, an analyst at BT Alex. Brown, said that UAL did
not disclose exactly how much of the first-quarter profit
improvement was the result of American having to cancel more than
6,600 flights in February. She and others have estimated that the
benefit will be equal to 15 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I do think it is a piece of positive news,'' she said,
referring to the company's higher estimate, ``I wouldn't assume
that the increase is solely from improving domestic revenue
trends.''
</P>
<P>
   The airlines have seen their sales decline in recent months
after four years of record profits. Analysts say that many carriers
have been having difficulty selling premium-priced tickets intended
for business travelers, which have gone up in price nearly 30
percent in the last three years. As a result, many companies are
either reducing travel or buying cheaper advance-purchase tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are also concerned that the introduction of new
airplanes by many airlines this year will lead to overcapacity and
erode profits. They say that broad fare increases can be easily
countered by more generous corporate discounts, fare sales and
other incentives. Finally, jet fuel, which is the industry's
second-largest expense after labor, appears to be moving up in
price from its current low level.
</P>
<P>
   But UAL said in a statement that United, which is the world's
largest airline, is seeing a ``reversal'' of the recent revenue
decline and that it ``is expecting strong domestic performance''
during the first quarter. The company also said that there has been
a modest improvement in its profits in Asia, where United gets
about 20 percent of its revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Donofrio was not impressed by that either, recalling assurances
made last year that passenger traffic in the Pacific was turning
the corner. ``While we are certainly encouraged with the way Asia
has been going,'' she said, ``we are going to wait for a few more
data points before we assume there is meaningful improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian A. Harris, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney in New
York, is more bullish on UAL. He said that United is ``the
strongest long-term fundamental story in the industry'' because of
its strong position at airports in Los Angeles, Chicago, Denver,
San Francisco and Washington's Dulles International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   UAL now trades at a discount compared with the other major
airline stocks but Harris believes that over time, as it grows its
hub airports, it should trade at a premium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
