<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-COLUMNIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-COLUMNIST FOR BOSTON GLOBE GETS A NEW OUTLET
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Barnicle, the columnist who resigned from The
Boston Globe last summer amid charges of plagiarism and slipshod
reporting, will begin writing a column for the opinion pages of The
Daily News' Sunday editions at the end of the month, according to
senior news executives at the New York paper.
</P>
<P>
   The executives, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said
Barnicle's first column has been scheduled to appear on March 28,
the day that the redesgned Sunday issue is launched. Reached at
his home in Lincoln, Mass., on Monday, Barnicle said ``no comment''
when asked about the new job.
</P>
<P>
   The news of Barnicle's appointment received mixed reviews within
the newsroom of The Daily News. ``The feeling is that they're
looking for somebody to make a splash and he's on Imus,'' one News
executive said. Don Imus, the acerbic radio and television
talk-show host, supported Barnicle during the columnist's final,
ragged days with The Globe last August and has featured his
commentary on the air several times since then.
</P>
<P>
   But, the executive continued, ``there is a large body of opinion
that worries that having an alleged plagiarist on the staff is not
the smartest thing for our paper to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kramer, the editor of the new five-page Sunday opinion
section, did not return messages left late Monday afternoon.
Mortimer B. Zuckerman, the newspaper's owner, was in Moscow and
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle, 54, who often wrote of the lives of police officers,
firefighters and poor families, developed a fiercely loyal
following in Boston, a city where some people still cling to the
old ethnic loyalties that once divided Irish immigrants from Yankee
Brahmins, and both from poor and middle-class blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's departure last August from The Globe, which is owned
by The New York Times Co., was the culmination of a wrenching
series of events that began when The Boston Herald, The Globe's
rival, reported that the columnist had plagiarized the jokes of the
comedian George Carlin in one of his columns.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle's resignation was requested by Matthew V. Storin, the
editor of The Globe, who was vacationing in Italy. Before Storin
returned, Barnicle had defied his request, and a wave of reader
support for the blunt-spoken storyteller overwhelmed The Globe's
switchboard. When Storin returned, he reversed himself.
</P>
<P>
   The reprieve was short-lived. Eight days later, Barnicle
tendered his resignation after he could not immediately provide
evidence that two young cancer victims he had described in a 1995
column actually existed. Some weeks later, The Globe published a
final column by Barnicle explaining that he had retold a story he
had heard from others.
</P>
<P>
   Richard P. Gulla, a spokesman for The Globe, said Monday
evening, ``We have said all along that Mike has been very good for
The Globe over two and a half decades, and The Globe has been good
to Mike over two and a half decades, and we parted over a
particular situation and we wish him well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0562 </DOCNO>
