<SLUG> BC-HASKEL-SALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASKEL SALE INFLATES STOCK TO HEAVYWEIGHT CLASS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pump up the volume indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Haskel International Inc. zoomed Monday after the
maker of industrial pumps announced it is being bought by
investors. More than 208,000 shares changed hands, about 30 times
the issue's 30-day average volume, lifting the price $3.0625 to
$12.125.
</P>
<P>
   Haskel officials said Monday that a group led by private
investment fund Tinicum Capital Partners LP will pay $72.8 million,
or $12.90 per share, to acquire all outstanding shares of the
Burbank firm. The price represents a 42 percent premium over the
stock's Monday opener of $9.0625 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Haskel makes high-pressure gas and liquid pumps used in
industrial and military applications. In October, the company
retained financial advisers Schroder &AMP; Co. to help evaluate options
to enhance growth opportunities. The Tinicum purchase has been
approved by both companies' boards of director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first concern was improving shareholder value, and I think
we've done that,'' said Malcolm Graves, Haskel's president and
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Haskel's share price had been in a slump since fiscal 1997, when
it wrote off $7.5 million from an underperforming electronics
division that it eventually sold. From a high of $16 in September
1997, Haskel shares fell as low as $6.625 last September.
</P>
<P>
   The Burbank-based company has 340 employees and annual sales of
about $50 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0563 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1684 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-OVERVIEW-HNS     03-15 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-OVERVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Admit it. You were warned.
</P>
<P>
   We touted Gonzaga. We told you about Stanford. We hinted that
this might not be another blue-chip season for Utah, and we pretty
much promised you that Kansas was a bad investment coming out of an
overvalued Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so we talked up Arizona and George Washington, too. And,
yes, we figured Ohio State wasn't up to its rating and that
Arkansas would foreclose on Iowa in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Southwest Missouri State never came up.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's perfect, particularly in these turbulent times. If
there is a moral to the story after the first weekend of this NCAA
Tournament, however, it may be this:
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to play the bracket market, you can't just bet
the blue chips. To win big, you have to diversify a little, too.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, a Duke or a Connecticut is nice to have in your portfolio.
Once in a while, though, you have to take a flyer on some guys
working out of gyms in places like Spokane, Wash.; Springfield,
Mo.; or Norman, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone saw this trend coming, of course. Some paid dearly
for loading up on some old, familiar brand names.
</P>
<P>
   Adios, Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   So long, Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   No Sweet 16 for you, either, North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In a maddening opening weekend, the offbeat outfits and small
investors had their way. Sure, the top four conglomerates _ Duke,
Connecticut, Michigan State and Auburn _ made money, too, but
consider the carnage below.
</P>
<P>
   Three No. 2 seeds _ Miami (Fla.), Stanford and Utah _ folded.
</P>
<P>
   Two No. 3s _ Cincinnati and North Carolina _ went bust.
</P>
<P>
   Three No. 4s _ Arizona, Arkansas and Tennessee _ lost their
seats on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   How unusual is all this?
</P>
<P>
   Since the Tournament expanded to 64 teams in 1985, no more than
three double-digit seeds previously had made it to the second
weekend. This year, three No. 10s (Gonzaga, Miami of Ohio and
Purdue) move on, joined by a No. 12 (Southwest Missouri State) and
a No. 13 (Oklahoma).
</P>
<P>
   Of the top 16 seeds, only eight survived, the lowest total since
1990. In four weird and wonderful (if your stock is on the rise,
that is) days, 19 teams defeated a higher seed, another record
since the field grew to its current size.
</P>
<P>
   Only the South, where the top four seeds all advanced, was
impervious to this fluctuation. Half of the West (No. 1 UConn and
No. 5 Iowa) played close to form, but the other (No. 6 Florida vs.
No. 10 Gonzaga) is a bit of a mess.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, things are even more unstable as No. 1 Duke gets
No. 12 Southwest Missouri State in the semifinals, while No. 6
Temple and No. 10 Purdue make up the other side of the skewed
bracket. And in the Midwest, No. 1 Michigan State is a little
surprised to see No. 13 OU coming, but not much more than No. 3
Kentucky is to be confronted with No. 10 Miami (Ohio).
</P>
<P>
   Some will advance while others decline as we move on to the
Round of 16. Before we do, a look back at those who went boom and
those who went bust after a volatile week on the floor:
</P>
<P>
   Winners
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma _ Who would have thought it when the Sooners barely
made the cut on Selection Sunday? Even Warren Buffett couldn't see
these guys coming.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Davis _ The Iowa coach, whose contract is not being renewed,
is cashing in that 401(k) with the feel-good story of the
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Alford _ Considered the favorite to take over Davis' job,
the Southwest Missouri coach may have upped his stock with two
wins, including a 30-point stunner over Tennessee. Everyone talks
defense, but the Bears play it, yielding just 83 points in two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Szczerbiak _ Where would Miami (Ohio) be without him?
Home, watching CNBC, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Big Ten _ Of the seven teams that opened play, four (Michigan
State, Ohio State, Purdue and Iowa) are still in the market. Only
Minnesota and Wisconsin heard the closing bell after the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Southeastern Conference _ Each of the six entries won at least
one game, and Auburn, Kentucky and Florida are still around. Only
the Big Ten can match the SEC's 9-3 record so far.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Valley _ Everybody had Southwest Missouri State in the
Sweet 16, right? Evansville lost in the first round to Kansas, but
Creighton's win over Louisville and respectable (75-63) loss to
Maryland didn't hurt the league's stock a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Mid-American Conference _ Miami (Ohio) is in the Sweet 16, and
Kent made a decent account of itself in a 61-54 first-round loss to
a Temple team that is still around.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed returns
</P>
<P>
   Big East _ UConn and St. John's moved on, but more was expected
from Miami (Fla.), a second-round loser to Purdue. Syracuse and
Villanova both lost openers as No. 8 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic Coast _ No big surprise that Duke and Maryland are
still on the big board, but North Carolina's first-round loss to
Weber State hurt the argument that the league deserved a better
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 _ Oklahoma, generally considered the last team selected
for the field of 64, has been a pleasant surprise, but Texas and
Missouri lost first-round games as higher seeds and Oklahoma
State's win over Syracuse is nothing to get excited about. Kansas
had a chance to take out Kentucky, but the Jayhawks go home early
again.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic 10 _ Temple lives, but Rhode Island and George
Washington declared no dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Losers
</P>
<P>
   Bob Knight _ Black Saturday _ a 25-point second-round humbling
by St. John's _ was his worst day ever in the Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Conference USA _ Of the four teams invited, only Cincinnati and
North Carolina Charlotte made it to the second round, and those two
have cashed out as well.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific-10 _ More trouble in the West Coast markets. As
expected, Stanford carried the banner the furthest, but that was
only into the second round. UCLA, Arizona and Washington all washed
out in their openers, and the Cardinal _ last year's hot commodity
_ was schooled in the second round by Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   Western Athletic Conference _ Utah went out in the second round
as a No. 2 seed. Tulsa and New Mexico won openers, but each was
embarrassed in second-round losses to Duke and Connecticut. Trading
is suspended as the league loses half its members.
</P>
<P>
   What's next
</P>
<P>
   East _ Cincinnati was the only team to beat Duke in the regular
season. The Bearcats are gone, and so is any chance that the Blue
Devils won't have a profitable weekend just across the river from
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri may slow Duke down but won't be able to stop
everyone. The Temple-Purdue winner will wrap up a nice season by
being able to say it didn't cash out until the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   Midwest _ Michigan State's slow starts may catch up to the
Spartans at some point. Is Oklahoma on a fluky run, or finally
playing up to decent talent? The Sooners shouldn't be a problem
here, but then again, they should be off the board by now, too.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (Ohio) has had fun, but Kentucky knows how to win at this
level. That could come into play in a Michigan State-Kentucky final
where the old money may prevail.
</P>
<P>
   South _ This might be the most interesting regional of all,
since the four blue chips all prospered. Auburn still has some
convincing to do and may not be able to do it against an Ohio State
team that mauled Detroit (75-44) in the second round. St. John's
embarrassed Indiana, jeopardizing the trendy pick of Maryland
emerging from this group.
</P>
<P>
   West _ If Jim Calhoun doesn't cash in on a Final Four trip this
year, he may lose his seat (on the exchange, not the bench). The
Huskies like to play up-tempo, and while Iowa managed to keep pace
with Arkansas, UConn has some inside muscle to go with the speed
and quickness elsewhere. The Florida-Gonzaga winner has the
potential to come down with a bad case of ``happy to be here,''
further lightening the Huskies' load.
</P>
<P>
   With only four issues sure to remain on the upswing by Sunday
night, the blue chips still could be the safe way to go.
</P>
<P>
   For those who like the safe route, Duke is as close to a
can't-miss commodity as this market has seen for a while.
Connecticut isn't far behind.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer a little risk, the big board is open, and
some bargains with potential remain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
