<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-STATEBUDGET-COX     03-15 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-STATEBUDGET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taft's budget proposal includes spending surplus on schools,
technology
 &HT;    By William Hershey and Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Gov. Bob Taft released a two-year budget Monday
that calls for record spending on primary and secondary education,
but ignores the potential impact of a court ruling that could force
Ohio to scrap how its pays for schools.
</P>
<P>
   The first-term Republican governor also called for increased
state spending for colleges and universities, prisons, economic
development and health care for the working poor and senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget reflects increased revenues from an expanding
economy,'' Taft told more than 100 reporters, lobbyists and state
employees who packed a hearing room in the downtown Riffe Office
Tower.
</P>
<P>
   His budget calls for spending nearly $40 billion in the state's
general fund during the next two years, up from the $36.4 billion
in the current two-year budget. The Legislature will immediately
begin committee hearings on the budget. The Ohio Constitution
requires it to be approved by July 1.
</P>
<P>
   State spending would increase by 6.1 percent in the first year
and 5.5 percent in the second.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also called for spending all of this year's budget
surplus, estimated at $415.7 million, for school construction and
technology, with $325.7 million going for construction and $90
million for school technology. Local districts would have to put up
a share of the money for construction to qualify for state aid.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed $13.2 billion for primary and secondary schools
would be the most ever spent on education. It would provide
``resources for an adequate education for every child,'' Taft said.
The total includes $10.6 billion from the general fund, as well as
money from the Ohio Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Taft crafted his basic school spending using the formula
developed last year by the Legislature _ a formula Perry County
Judge Linton D. Lewis threw out as unconstitutional on Feb. 26
because it did not overhaul the funding system as called for by the
Ohio Supreme Court in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   State leaders have said they will appeal the decision to the
Supreme Court, and the governor is confident the high court will
uphold the formula, Scott Milburn, Taft's spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Budget Director Tom Johnson acknowledged that the administration
did not take the pending Supreme Court's decision into
consideration, but said the budget helps poorer school districts
get more money, reduces the growth of state aid for affluent
districts and provides money for school buildings, ``all steps in
the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But state Sen. Rhine McLin, D-Dayton, was among those who
blasted the governor as being short-sighted for ignoring the
potential impact of Lewis' decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very arrogant of the governor,'' McLin said. ``No one
knows what may come out of the school funding case and the state
isn't prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   William Phillis, executive director of the school coalition that
brought the funding lawsuit, was disappointed but not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem is that at some point there's going to be
a day of reckoning,'' he said. ``Then they'll have to go to work
and overhaul the system. Just saying they overhauled the system
doesn't mean it's overhauled.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Jeff Jacobson, R-Phillipsburg, who helped design the
school funding formula, said Taft did the right thing by ignoring
Lewis' decision, and Rep. J. Donald Mottley, R-West Carrollton,
praised Taft's spending priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident that the formula will be upheld,'' Jacobson
said. ``The only way to take Judge Lewis into account is to hook up
an IV to the taxpayers' wallet and give Judge Lewis the button.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mottley: ``I think he correctly identified the state's
problem and opportunity _ the gap between what our public schools
do and what we need for them to do to make Ohio competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft said the budget fulfills his commitments to make schools
the state's top priority and provide them with adequate funding
without increasing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He highlighted his $25 million OhioReads program, which calls
for making sure all students can read by the fourth grade, using
the help of 20,000 volunteer tutors. Taft today will put his
emphasis on reading into action by reading to students from Xenia
while touring a dairy goat farm in Bellbrook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly no goal is more important than reading,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   While primary and secondary education constitute his top
priority, Taft said improving access to higher education also is
one of his major goals.
</P>
<P>
   His budget would increase direct financial aid to students and
also provide more money to two-year and four-year colleges in an
effort to keep down increases in tuition. His proposal would
increase general funding spending on higher education from $2.3
billion this year to $2.41 billion next year and $2.51 billion in
the second budget year.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also includes a 25.8 percent hike in the special
supplement for Central State University. The supplement would be
$9.7 million in each year, up from the current $7.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic State Rep. Dixie Allen of Dayton, a Central State
graduate, said the proposal was ``fantastic'' and a ``show of
confidence'' in Central State President John Garland who has worked
to restore the school to sound financial footing .
</P>
<P>
   Taft's proposal to provide health care to 27,000 additional
children from families of the working poor won praise from Mark
Real, director of the Childrens Defense Fund - Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest complaint in the past was that when people worked
they didn't get ahead. You had an incentive not to work. This is an
incentive to work. It's a significant number of kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was pleased with Taft's plans for increased
spending. The budget unfortunately conforms to the
State-of-the-State speech in which Taft called for increased
spending in 40 programs, said Richard C. Leonardi, president of the
Dayton-based Buckeye Institute for Public Policy Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's consistency in the wrong direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey and Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily
News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
