<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-OHIOSTATE-COX     03-15 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIOSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OSU freshmen the key to team's success
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ A month or so ago, Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien
wasn't sure how important freshman guards Brian Brown and Boban
Savovic would be in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The two had ``hit a wall,'' O'Brien said, and he wasn't sure how
soon they'd bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were in a kind of malaise,'' he said. ``They didn't seem
to be as aggressive, as physically strong, as physically fit. They
both seemed to be not as mentally fit or as aware as they were
earlier in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Buckeyes, Brown and Savovic have snapped out
of their freshman funk just in time to contribute to OSU's
postseason success. The two combined for 25 points and nine assists
in Ohio State's first and second round NCAA tournament victories in
Indianapolis last week. Their five 3-pointers vs. Detroit on
Saturday helped bury the Titans by 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian has played very well both offensively and defensively,''
O'Brien said. ``And Boban, with his instinct and intelligence,
seems to find himself in the right spot a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Brown, a 6-3, 190-pound guard from Bishop Loughlin
High in Brooklyn, N.Y., will be making just his third start of the
season when the No. 4 seed Buckeyes (25-8) face No. 1 seed Auburn
(29-3) in the NCAA Sweet 16. The game will tip off at approximately
9:55 p.m. at Thompson Boling Arena in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Savovic, a 6-6, 230-pound native of Yugoslavia, will be a key
player off the bench for Ohio State, especially with senior guard
Neshaun Coleman still recovering from strep throat. (After missing
last week's games, Coleman is expected to be available on
Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who averaged 17.4 minutes as a reserve during the regular
season, played for 28 and 30 minutes in OSU's first two NCAA games.
His tenacious defense and ball-handling skills makes it a
``no-brainer'' to start him again, even if it means a smaller
lineup, O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way that we've played with Brian,'' the OSU coach
said. ``When Brian's in the game, we can push (point guard) Scoonie
(Penn) off the ball, allowing him to be a little bit more tuned in
to scoring some points. Brian is the only guy on the team who
affords us that luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn said he likes the extra flexibility Brown's presence gives
him. He also thinks having another guard on the court, especially
one as quick as Brown, has helped the Buckeyes' transition game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the last two games we may have had more fast breaks
than we've had all season because I can just run the floor and
Brian can just run it and we can just pass (the ball) up,'' Penn
said. ``So having Brian, not only helps on the defensive end but
the offensive end, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he learned he would start in place of sophomore
forward Jon Sanderson a couple of days before OSU's first round
NCAA tournament game against Murray State. He said making his first
start in such an important game didn't intimidate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' he said. ``I have a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Savovic, who was slowed by tendinitis in his achilles tendon
earlier this season, has healed enough to provide the Bucks with a
consistent outside threat. His four 3-pointers in last week's NCAA
games helped compensate for the absence of Coleman, OSU's most
dangerous 3-point threat. The Bucks will look to Savovic again
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
