<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0568 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCONN-NYT &LR;      03-15 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIGHT ON UCONN: INEXPERIENCE, INCONSISTENCY, INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Connecticut captain, Amy Duran, put it best before the start
of the National Collegiate Athletic Association women's basketball
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really been immature at a time when you need to be most
mature, and our inexperience is starting to show,'' said Duran, who
should know since she is the only front-line senior on a Huskies
team that meets Iowa State in the Mideast Regional semifinals on
Saturday in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   That immaturity and inexperience on a team that starts two
freshmen, two sophomores and one junior _ Shea Ralph, who is
playing only her second season after missing last season because of
a knee injury _ showed Sunday night when Connecticut had to score
the last 8 points to overcome unheralded Xavier, 86-84.
</P>
<P>
   UConn Coach Geno Auriemma feels that ``something has been lost''
since his team won the Big East championship on March 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been having a tough time doing some things quickly and
changing from one task to another,'' he said recently, words that
proved prophetic when Connecticut's season nearly came to a
stunning end on its home court.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth remembering, of course, that Connecticut is 29-4 and
within one victory of winning 30 games for the sixth straight year.
But it's also true that injuries have left the Huskies without a
true point guard and center, and that has led to inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Sue Bird was the starter at point guard for the first
eight games but then was sidelined for the season with a knee
injury. Knee problems have also sidelined her freshman replacement,
Keirsten Walters, for three of the last four games and left her
availability in doubt for the rest of the tournament. As a result,
the Huskies have had to rely on sophomore Marci Glenney, who
averages 4 points a game and had only 1 field goal and 4 assists
against Xavier.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, UConn's two best players _ Svetlana
Abrosimova and Ralph _ have controlled the ball during fast breaks,
a team hallmark, along with a trapping defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Abrosimova, a sophomore who has a tendency to try to do too
much, has committed as many turnovers _ 125 _ as she has assists,
and leads the Huskies in both categories. Connecticut has been
turning the ball over at an alarming rate _ 22 times in routing St.
Francis of Pennsylvania by 51 points in the opening round last
Friday and 19 times (6 by Abrosimova) against Xavier.
</P>
<P>
   The team's post play has also been inconsistent, although
another freshman, Tamika Williams, filled in admirably against
Xavier with team highs of 19 points and 9 rebounds and sank two
tie-breaking free throws with seven seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 foot 2, Williams is supposed to be a power forward. But a
lack of production _ in part because of a sprained ankle and
bruised tailbone _ by the 6-5 junior Paige Sauer has forced
Auriemma to use Williams and yet another 6-2 freshman, Swin Cash,
at center from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ralph, an outstanding all-around player, can play the
point well _ she had a season-high 10 assists, along with 19
points, in the Big East championship game against Notre Dame _ her
main strength is as a scorer. She leads the Huskies with a 17.2
average, a notch ahead of Abrosimova, who is averaging 16.8 points.
</P>
<P>
   And Ralph became a starter only nine games ago. But then in the
scheme of things under Auriemma, it's not who starts, but who
finishes on a team with 12 players who average 11 minutes or more.
And Ralph, who may be the team's best player, is always there at
the end of a close game.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is Duran, who was a starting guard until she broke her
right hand on Jan. 20 in a game against Miami. Since her return on
Feb. 20 after missing eight games, the 5-11 swing player has been a
major contributor as the first one off the bench. In the first two
Mideast Regional games against St. Francis and Xavier, Duran,
playing 57 out of a possible 80 minutes, scored 22 points on
8-of-18 shooting, including 6 of 14 from 3-point range, while
distributing 10 assists.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa State, which is ranked 19th in the Associated Press
poll, Connecticut will be facing a 24-7 team that ranks second to
Xavier in 3-point-shooting percentage (39.6 percent) and in 3-point
field goals a game (7.6) and that has the nation's leading
perimeter shooter in junior guard Stacy Frese, who during the
regular season connected on 79 of 161 shots from 3-point range (49
percent). That is hardly good news for UConn considering how
Xavier's perimeter sharpshooters nailed 9 of 15 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inexperience sometimes shows, and we've been hurt by a lot
of injuries,'' Auriemma said. ``But we're a good team. In the
Xavier game, we played a great team, but our defense came up big at
the end and we made some big shots when we had to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
