<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIAMIOHIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Szczerbiak a Cinderella sensation
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Wally Szczerbiak isn't one to shy away from the
spotlight. Good thing, because there's no escaping it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked into my first class today I got a standing
ovation,'' Miami University's all-everything forward and likely NBA
lottery pick reported Monday in a conference call with the national
media.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a line of ticket-buyers cheered the sight of coach
Charlie Coles less than 24 hours after Miami played its way into
the Sweet 16 of the NCAA tournament, where Kentucky awaits Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was a standing 'O,' `` Coles said. ``But it
was an 'O' ``
</P>
<P>
   The adulation shows no sign of subsiding for the RedHawks, whose
triumphant weekend in New Orleans included upsets of Washington and
Utah, each a stunner. A throng of screaming fans greeted the team's
campus return late Sunday night, and when Szczerbiak got his first
look at Monday's USA Today, his own winsome smile flashed back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A CBS guy showed it to me,'' Szczerbiak said. ``I thought (a
picture) might be in the sports section, but it was on the front
page. Obviously, Miami is getting its name out there. I was pretty
excited for myself and my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three points against the University of Washington on
Friday went a long way toward establishing the 6-foot-8 Szczerbiak
as a household name, even if nine out of 10 households probably
couldn't spell it if you spotted them the z's. Basically playing
the role of decoy against Utah, he still managed 24 points Sunday,
meaning he was responsible for more than half of the RedHawks'
two-game total of 125.
</P>
<P>
   Living up to his ``Wally World'' nickname, Szczerbiak indeed has
been a world apart in two games, spearheading the RedHawks to their
most successful NCAA run ever. He's had help, but when the history
is written, no matter what happens next, upstart Miami will be
remembered as Szczerbiak's team, much like North Carolina-Charlotte
was Cedric Maxwell's team long ago and Navy belonged to David
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as getting here, this is what I've worked for my whole
career in college,'' Szczerbiak said. ``For it to be coming true
the way I dreamed is extra special and I'm just grateful for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky poses the biggest challenge yet, and the days of Miami
sneaking up on opponents have passed. Still, Szczerbiak can't wait
for Friday's tipoff in St. Louis and another chance to ``try on the
glass slipper,'' as he likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the challenge of playing against players who are well
known and have gotten a lot of respect,'' he said. ``I don't know
how we're going to match up, but I think we match up favorably at
every position, except they're bigger at center. We're just going
to have to find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles said he plans an exhaustive videotape study of Kentucky,
and if that doesn't yield enough clues, he might have to resort to
other tactics. Whatever plan emerges, you can bet Szczerbiak
figures prominently, whether physically or emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to come up with something, but I don't know what
we'll do,'' Coles said. ``We can't take (Kentucky's) experience or
great tradition away, but we can be spirited and work together as a
team. We'll try to win one for the Gipper and anyone who knows the
Gipper.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that doesn't strike a responsive chord with the team?
</P>
<P>
   Said Coles, ``Maybe I'll just get Wally mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean McClelland writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
