u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-TORRE-ART-N     03-15 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TORRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE REASSURES THE YANKEES AS HIS CANCER SURGERY LOOMS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Joe Torre moved from one end of the 80-foot
clubhouse to the other while he talked to the Yankee players
Monday, speaking confidently, mixing in jokes _ like an entertainer
working the room, one player said. In this manner, the manager
educated them about his prostate cancer and his impending
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Torre is scheduled for surgical removal of his cancer Thursday
at Barnes Jewish Hospital in St. Louis. Dr. William Catalona, with
whom Torre met Friday, will perform the operation. ``Basically, I
want to get this out of me,'' said Torre, who could have chosen
radiation treatments instead.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and club officials said Torre's recovery could take as
little as three weeks or as long as three months. Torre declined to
offer any time frame for his return to the dugout, acknowledging to
reporters that he really had no way of knowing how he would react
to the surgery and rehabilitation, or how he would feel about
managing.
</P>
<P>
   Torre offered no promises that he would continue with the
Yankees, though right now he said he had ``no doubt'' he would
return; in speaking to his players, Torre used the word ``soon''
repeatedly in reference to his return.
</P>
<P>
   Torre's 3-year-old daughter, Andrea Rae, sat on a couch in his
office, wearing a blue dress and pushing through a coloring book
with her tiny hands. Her father answered questions in a low voice
nearby. ``My concern is being around for her,'' he said, nodding
his head in her direction. ``And that's my goal. Getting back to
baseball is beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre's PSA test, which is used for the detection of prostate
cancer, registered at 2.6 last year, and when that increased to 4.6
in a physical examination last month, Torre assumed the worst; he
would rather have been pleasantly surprised, he said. Doctors
confirmed his cancer to him late in the afternoon last Tuesday. He
and Ali Torre, his wife, spoke late into the night. (``She is a
strong lady,'' he said Monday. ``If she is going to hang out with
an old guy, she's going to have to put up with this sort of
thing.'')
</P>
<P>
   Torre said his mind was like scrambled eggs. He stayed awake and
couldn't get his mind off the news. ``It was terrible,'' he said.
``It's like laying in bed and not being able to get comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Torre asked some of his veterans to
disseminate word of his cancer to other players. But they wondered
about his treatment, his long-term prognosis and when he might be
back. Torre knew they needed to hear from him directly, once he
made his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Torre entered the clubhouse at about 2:15 p.m., and for the next
15 minutes he told them in detail about his various examinations,
the diagnosis and the surgery he would have. Torre's tone was
optimistic and his delivery even, which was surprising to those who
had heard how subdued he had been last week.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams said Torre spoke to them in the same way he
always does; it was just like every other meeting, other than that
he was talking about his serious illness, rather than changing
base-running signs. Torre told them what he expected from them, how
they needed to approach the game the same way they did last year,
when they won a record 125 games.
</P>
<P>
   Torre walked over to Derek Jeter _ who has been joking about how
bench coach Don Zimmer, who will run the team in Torre's absence,
has forced him to make every road trip this spring _ and put his
hands on the shortstop's shoulders. ``Don't come to me and
complain,'' Torre told Jeter. ``Zim is the guy now.'' Everybody in
the room laughed.
</P>
<P>
   It was just like Torre to find a way to end the meeting in an
upbeat manner, David Cone said later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just so classy,'' Cone said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``He gave everyone a sense of confidence about this, and that
was good for everyone to hear,'' Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see him in good spirits,'' Scott Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry, who is coming back from colon cancer, stopped
Torre in the clubhouse and wished him well. ``He sounded good,''
Strawberry said. ``He knows the whole situation now.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre says he feels terrific, better than he has in a couple of
years, perhaps because he increased his workout regimen during the
off-season. The diagnosis, he said, ``is frightening, there's no
question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot better now than I was a week ago, and a lot better
now than I was last Friday,'' he said. ``I'm looking forward to it
at this point. I hope it's going to be all right, and I have
confidence in the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre will follow the Yankees closely; Zimmer has made a point
of calling Torre and keeping him informed daily. The staff and the
front office will make the final decisions regarding the roster,
Torre said, because they will have seen the players perform this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Torre has other matters to worry about now. You think that
baseball is your life, he said, and then something like this
happens. You have a 3-year-old daughter and now you are fully
dedicated to being around for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to feel like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Torre asked that those wishing to send flowers or cards instead
make a donation to their favorite charity or to the Starlight
Children's Foundation, c/o Joe Torre, 1560 Broadway, Suite 600, New
York, N.Y. 10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
