<HEADER>
A1831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLOONISTS-COX     03-15 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLOONISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ballooning duo still gunning for record
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. _ Long before earth's eyes were turned on
Bertrand Piccard, soaring now above continents and oceans in
pursuit of a world ballooning record, the Swiss adventurer had to
brave a much harsher scrutiny _ fellow 4th graders at Riviera Beach
Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   To the jeans-wearing, sneaker-scuffing kids of ``Ruh-vera''
Beach in 1968, a boy with a French accent, European clothes and
floppy blond hair was natural prey, no matter how famous his father
and grandfather were.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of tough for him,'' said Florida Power &AMP; Light
engineer Craig Terrana, who was 10 at the time and young Bertrand's
only connection to this odd new world. ``I was kind of his
ambassador at Riviera Beach Elementary. He spoke English enough to
get by, but he was obviously very, very different _ he showed up
for school in almost lederhosen.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bertrand Piccard is grabbing attention again _ the hard
way. He and British copilot Brian Jones are steering their balloon
across the Pacific Ocean and expect to reach the coast of Mexico
Wednesday. They hope to become the first to fly a balloon nonstop
around the globe. Already, they are closer to it than anyone has
been before.
</P>
<P>
   As boys, Piccard and Terrana were linked by the work of their
fathers, a multi-million dollar scientific mission that temporarily
put the Port of Palm Beach on the world oceanographic map.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Piccard was an internationally known scientist and
explorer who had a contract with Grumman Aircraft to design a
medium-depth submarine to drift the Gulf Stream from Florida to
Newfoundland. Piccard and another scientist had claimed the world
record _ 35,800 feet _ for ocean diving in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Terrana was Grumman's project engineer for the PX-15,
later christened the Ben Franklin submersible. The Terrana family
moved from New York to Lausanne, Switzerland, for two years while
the craft was being built. Then the project team moved from
Switzerland to Riviera Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite a dramatic culture change,'' Craig Terrana
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Month after month, the team tested the Franklin off Riviera
Beach, trying to solve the problem of electrical shorts in cables
connecting 378 batteries covering the outside of the hull.
Hurricane season was closing in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to do it or postpone it for a year, so we said
let's do it,'' said Donald Terrana, retired and living in Venice,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Franklin's crew of six finally locked the hatches and were
towed out to sea in July 1969. The Grumman-Piccard Gulf Stream
Drift Mission began July 14 and ended 30 days later and 1,440 miles
northward off the coast of Maine. It logged 5 million pieces of
oceanographic data, and provided NASA with 50,000 photos of crew
life in a confined area that were used in designing manned
spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Piccards returned to Switzerland in 1970, after which
Jacques Piccard used his knowledge and fame as an advocate for
protecting the ocean environment. Bertrand Piccard survived the
culture shock of Riviera Beach and grew up to be a psychiatrist and
adventurer in the mode of his forefathers _ most notably his
grandfather Auguste Piccard, who once held a world altitude record
for flying 55,000 feet high in a balloon.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bertrand Piccard's third try for the ultimate ballooning
record. He and Jones set off from the Swiss Alps on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   Rules of the International Aeronautical Federation govern how
the world record can be claimed. A balloon must:
</P>
<P>
   _ Not land during its flight.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reach or go beyond the longitude from which it took off.
</P>
<P>
   _ Travel a distance equal to two-thirds of the earth's
equatorial circumference _ in other words, stay within a zone
extending from the equator to about 40 degrees north.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, beermaker Anheuser-Busch announced it would award a cup
and $500,000 to the first team to succeed, plus $500,000 to a
charity chosen by the team. The prize is small, compared to the
millions of dollars that go into the balloon expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   To be first is the real goal and what keeps the handful of
world-class balloonists doggedly risking their lives and fortunes.
Bertrand Piccard's first attempt ended embarrassingly after only
six hours into the flight, so short that a local French newspaper
called it un saut de puce _ a flea's jump. He was not deterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it was only a dream, I don't care,'' he told The
Guardian newspaper afterward. ``People need dreams, they need
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have dreams that carry us forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary McLachlin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
