<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-OWNERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL OWNERS REMAIN UNDECIDED OVER EXPANSION IN HOUSTON, L.A. 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Though Los Angeles continues to have the look of a
champion for NFL expansion, team owners remained at odds between
that city and Houston on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said he
expected the Expansion Committee to reach a conclusion in the
afternoon, leading to speculation that Los Angeles would get the
nod.
</P>
<P>
   But because the 14-member committee remained split, NFL
officials put the matter before the entire ownership group for 1
1/2 hours without a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners argued for Los Angeles because it is an important
television market. But a forceful case was made for Houston because
it is a done deal, while the two Los Angeles bids are far from it.
</P>
<P>
   Under NFL rules, expansion must be approved by 24 of the 31 team
owners. The league hopes to have a decision when their annual
spring meeting ends Thursday at the Arizona Biltmore Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Houston businessman Bob McNair is proposing building a $310
million, retractable roof stadium using $195 million in public
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate developer Ed Roski and businessman Eli Broad would
spend $350 million in private funds to renovate the L.A. Coliseum.
Hollywood deal maker Michael Ovitz proposes spending roughly the
same amount of private funds to build a new stadium atop a waste
dump in nearby Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a challenge,'' said a visibly exasperated Jerry
Richardson, owner of the Carolina Panthers and committee
co-chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have 24 votes currently to go from 31 to 32
(teams),'' said Richardson. ``We don't have 24 votes for Houston.
We don't have 24 votes for Carson, nor do we have 24 votes for the
L.A. Coliseum. We don't have 24 votes for Bob McNair. We don't have
24 votes for Michael Ovitz. And we don't have 24 votes for Eli
Broad.''
</P>
<P>
   A strident bloc of owners that includes Tennessee Titans owner
Bud Adams opposes any expansion. The group includes owners with
stadium problems and those who don't want to risk sharing TV
revenues with a new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have is a difficult decision,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming owners agreed to expand this week, Richardson said he
could not yet envision a middle ground that would attract support
of 24 owners.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials have been pushing a plan to give Los Angeles up to
10 months to come up with a workable stadium deal and ownership
team. If the deadline passed, Houston would get the expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said that possibility was discussed Monday, ``but as
we stand here today, I would say we're not even close to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The delay was a pleasant surprise for McNair, who has said he
will seek to buy an existing franchise and move it to Houston
unless he gets some type of NFL arrangement giving Houston an
expanision team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our support hangs in with us, the (32nd) franchise won't go
anywhere _ it takes 24 votes,'' McNair said. ``I think they will
have to come out with some solution satisfactory to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said the league will neither expand to 33 teams nor
promise to move a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to expand to a 33rd (team), that's clear,'' he
said. ``Los Angeles ... is a large television market, but there are
still question marks. Houston is also a large television market,
though not as large. But it has a good stadium plan.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair said he will push a new scenario calling for Los Angeles
to get a shorter time frame than 10 months to put together a deal.
McNair said one NFL official told him that perhaps Los Angeles
would get only until September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be delighted if they would tell Los Angeles, `you've got
the deal, just come back at the May owners meeting and prove you
can do the deal,''' McNair said. ``I think I'd go put a shovel in
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Roski said he still believes that Los Angeles will get the
expansion team. ``We've been working on this three years,'' he
said. ``Waiting another day or two doesn't make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tagliabue said Roski's proposal has problems because a
renovated Coliseum would not have enough parking nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Roski later countered that the Coliseum currently has 25,000
parking spaces. However, many of those are up to one mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   One of Houston's biggest supporters Monday was Pittsburgh
Steelers owner Dan Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played there, we had a great rivalry with them (Houston
Oilers),'' Rooney said. ``(Former Oilers coach) Bum Phillips used
to say the Super Bowl goes through Pittsburgh and that he was
coming down to break down the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold out in both towns and I really enjoyed going to
Houston. I thought it was a great city for the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
