<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death of hosts' son cancels Clinton luncheon
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ President Clinton's visit to Sewall's
Point tonight will be subdued by the death during the weekend of
the 25-year-old son of Palm Beach County supporters Melvin and Bren
Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's luncheon in Manalapan was canceled Monday after Joshua
Jeremiah Simon died in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Bren Simon was told of her son's death while visiting the White
House to make plans for today's lunch at the oceanside estate,
according to friends.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will still visit Sewall's Point tonight for a $5,000 per
person dinner at the home of attorney Willie Gary. The money is
going to the Democratic National Committee for the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Details about Joshua Simon's death were sketchy Monday. The
family is in seclusion and a spokesman for the Simons declined to
comment. One family friend said the son, who would have been 26 on
April 30, died of natural causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd had no problems, nothing, this was just out of the
blue,'' said the family friend.
</P>
<P>
   The Simons are in Indianapolis, the family's hometown, preparing
for their son's funeral. Simon's company, which is run by his son,
David, owns shopping malls throughout America including the
Treasure Coast Square Mall in Jensen Beach, the Palm Beach and
Boynton Beach malls, and Town Center Mall near Boca Raton. He
recently signed a contract to operate malls in Europe. Simon 71,
also is the owner of the Ritz Carlton in Manalapan.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force One is expected to land at Palm Beach International
Airport at about 6:45 p.m. When Clinton steps off the plane, he
will be greeted by Palm Beach County Commission Chairman Maude Ford
Lee and Commissioner Carol Roberts as well as leaders of some of
the county's Democratic clubs. Also on hand will be Monte Friedkin,
chairman of the county Democratic Party and a major contributor to
the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after his arrival, Clinton will board Marine One for a
helicopter ride to Witham Field in Martin County. After dinner, he
will return to PBIA and take off about 10:20 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen supporters from the canceled Manalapan event are
expected at Gary's house, said his aide, Stacey Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   The mansion is getting a fresh coat of paint, and painters hope
to complete the rest of the home's exterior before Clinton touches
down in Stuart.
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley is The Palm Beach Post Political Editor. Staff
writers Sally Swartz and Angie Scharnhorst contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
