<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MOST LOCAL OF FISHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, March 16:
</P>
<P>
   When the blue pike began to disappear from Lake Erie in the
1950s, it took with it a major regional fishery and a cornerstone
of the Friday fish fry, a thriving culinary institution in the
heavily Catholic towns and cities that line the lake shore in Ohio,
Pennsylvania and New York. Other fish filled in once the blue pike
was gone _ it was declared extinct in 1975, when the Great Lakes
themselves seemed moribund _ but nothing really replaced it. It is
odd to think that no one under the age of 45 is likely to remember
tasting blue pike, though it was a staple of their parents' diet
and a vital element in their parents' religious observance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a long search, scientists have found a well-preserved
specimen of blue pike whose DNA will allow them to judge whether
the claims of blue pike sightings in other lakes are true. The
specimen was kept for decades in the freezer of Jim Anthony, a
barber in Conneaut, Ohio. Nearly every serious fisherman finds a
long-forgotten fish in the freezer now and then, but Anthony _ a
man as persistent as he is sentimental _ caught his blue pike in
1962 and has preserved it ever since. A frozen blue pike is even
rarer than a living coelacanth, a prehistoric fish once thought to
be extinct but which has been caught from time to time in the
Comoros archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   There has been talk, if blue pike still survive somewhere, of
reviving the blue pike fishery in Lake Erie. That will depend upon
the well-being of the blue pike's chief prey, the lake herring, and
the lake herring's chief prey, and the chief prey of the lake
herring's chief prey, and so on down to a microscopic level. But it
will take something else as well _ a renewed appetite for blue
pike.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the trend in this country was toward a
nationalizing of our foodstuffs, with the steady loss of locally
important foods. A good example is the general triumph of
chain-restaurant burgers over the ``beef on weck'' sandwich in
Buffalo, N.Y., which was once also a great blue-pike city. It
sounds remarkable to imagine eating local fish fresh from the water
in a shoreline restaurant overlooking the broad expanse of Lake
Erie. But there was a time, not that long ago, when it happened
every Friday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-15-99 2344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990315.0580 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-15 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
