<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPORTS-ON-THE-NET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND FOR BEST SPORTS WEB SITE ... ENVELOPE, PLEASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time for the first Sports on the Net awards for
sports-related Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Well, because the Academy Awards are less than a week away
... and some of us have already been eliminated from the March
Madness office pool.
</P>
<P>
   So, in no particular order, here is one Web surfer's winners
based on what's cool and functional:
</P>
<P>
   BEST MAINSTREAM SPORTS SITE: CBS SportsLine
(cbs.sportsline.com).
</P>
<P>
   CBS SportsLine, ESPN.com and CNN/SI have practically the same
format and features. The difference? CBS SportsLine's major
presence on America Online combined with its quick access to its
superstar sites, featuring Michael Jordan, Tiger Woods and
Shaquille O'Neal. CBS SportsLine also has a big international
section in cooperation with the London Daily Mail's Soccernet site,
which should delight soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   Other nominees: ESPN.com, CNN/SI.com, MSNBC.com.
</P>
<P>
   BEST FAN SITE: Andrew's Dallas Stars Page
(rampages.onramp.net/(tilde)markstep/stars.htm).
</P>
<P>
   Of the many thousands of fan pages out there, few compare to
this father-son creation. Mark and Andrew Stepneski of Plano keep
this site's content and design fresher than some official sites.
</P>
<P>
   Other nominees: Forty Niner Faithful (www.armanini.com/niners),
a clearinghouse of everything about the San Francisco 49ers; Packer
Palace (home.earthlink.net/(tilde)norbertn/packerpalace), with its
deco design, is the most entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   BEST OFFICIAL PRO TEAM SITE: San Jose Sharks
(www.sj-sharks.com).
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of official team sites have quicker load times, but
once the San Jose Sharks' official site gets in place, it's a
worthy visit. The non-frames site includes complete club
information, tons of interaction, submit-your-own-fan-site contests
(not something the holier-than-thou official sites usually do) and
multimedia connections. Of course, one would expect a team based
near Silicon Valley to produce a killer site.
</P>
<P>
   Other nominees: Yankees.com taps into its tradition effectively;
DenverBroncos.com pulls together its content and merchandising
nicely.
</P>
<P>
   BEST OFFICIAL SPORTS SITE FOR A SINGLE LEAGUE: NHL.com. The NHL
has great content and interactivity for the hardcore hockey fans,
along with features for young users (NHL4kids.com).
</P>
<P>
   BEST UNOFFICIAL SITE FOR A SINGLE SPORT: In The Crease
(www.inthecrease.com). In The Crease covers hockey from top to
bottom. It's a must-visit site for serious hockey fans, foreign and
domestic.
</P>
<P>
   BEST OFFICIAL COLLEGE SPORTS SITE FOR A SINGLE EVENT:
FinalFour.net (www.finalfour.net). If you're chained to the work
station, FinalFour.net offers an escape to March Madness, provided
your personal computer is powered with multimedia plug-ins.
</P>
<P>
   BEST UNOFFICIAL COLLEGE SPORTS SITE: Greatest College Football
Finishes (www.nd.edu/(tilde)tmandell/finishestable.html). Ted
Mandell of South Bend, Ind., has brought together descriptions of
fantastic finishes, several with original broadcast audio files.
</P>
<P>
   And now for the awards that's usually given backstage:
</P>
<P>
   BEST MULTIMEDIA SPORTS SITE: Broadcast.com
(www.broadcast.com/sports). Dallas-based company has the market
cornered on multimedia, from March Madness to live bull riding.
</P>
<P>
   BEST FANTASY SITE: Pure Sports (www.puresports.com). Top
resource for fantasy geeks.
</P>
<P>
   BEST USE OF GRAPHICS: Packer Palace
(home.earthlink.net/(tilde)norbertn/packerpalace). Discover the
many uses of Vince Lombardi's head as a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BEST OUTDOORS SITE: The Mountain Zone (www.mountainzone.com).
Not a resource for anglers or hunters, but for things to do while
careening off the sides of mountains.
</P>
<P>
   (Tommy Cummings writes about the Internet for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
dragon(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
